[StudyName "King's Gambit | Full Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "KGA: Fischer Defense 3...d6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ACmyH8gC/lLHwjwGS"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4PP2/8/PPPP2PP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.12.17"]
[UTCTime "12:56:29"]

2... exf4 3. Nf3 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gf3h4] } 3... d6! { The Fischer Defense, named after the 11th world champion: Robert Fischer.
This is also Stockfish's favorite option for black. Fischer called 3... d6 "a high-class waiting move." The idea of it is to free up the LSB and take away the e5 square for the white knight. } { [%csl Gc8] } 4. Bc4 { Developing and getting ready to castle. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 4... h6! { This move might look weird at first, but it actually makes a lot of sense, because it prepares for g5 on the next move. The most popular move for white is to castle, but black's going to get a very comfy position after g5. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Bg7g5,Rh6g5] } 5. h4! { This is an important move because g5 is no longer possible for black. } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Bh4g5] } 5... Nf6 { A developing move. } (5... Nc6 6. d4 { Taking the center } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4] } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 { Protecting e4. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc3e4] } 7... Nh5 { [%csl Gc3] } 8. d5! { Kicking away the knight and freeing up the d4 square for our f3 knight. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gd5c6] } 8... Ne7 (8... Ne5?? { The most popular move, but this simply loses a piece. } 9. Nxe5! { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gd1h5] } 9... dxe5 10. Qxh5 $18) (8... Nb8 9. Ne2 $13 { A very sharp position again. } { [%csl Gg3,Gf4][%cal Ge2g3,Gc1f4] }) 9. Nd4 $13 { A very sharp position. Stockfish likes black more slightly, but white is the one with an 80% winrate. } { [%csl Gd4] }) 6. Nc3! { The only good move, white protect e4. Now it's definitely not great to castle kingside, that would be suicide because black would do a massive pawnstorm. White should now focus on trying to castle queenside. } 6... Bg4 (6... Be7 { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 7. d4 { Taking the center. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gc3,Gc4] } 7... Nh5 { Black wants to hop a knight to g3. We have a nice counter: } { [%csl Rg3][%cal Rh5g3] } 8. Ne2! { Controlling g3 } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Ge2g3] } 8... O-O 9. Bxf4 Bg4 10. Qd2 Nd7 11. O-O-O $14 { Material is equal, white has a massive center, fully developed, and good piece placement. The engine-o-meter says it's equal, but I think most people prefer white here ;) } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4,Gf4,Gf3,Ge2,Gc4,Rh5,Re7] }) (6... Nc6 { [%csl Gd4] } 7. d4 { Taking the center } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4] } 7... Nh5 { [%csl Rg3][%cal Rh5g3] } 8. Nd5! Ng3 9. Bxf4 Nxh1 10. Qd2 Be7 11. O-O-O) 7. d4 { Dominating the center and attacking f4, there's no way to stop white from winning that pawn. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge5,Gf5,Rf4][%cal Gd4c5,Ge4d5,Gd4e5,Ge4f5] } 7... Be7 { Preparing to O-O } (7... Nh5? { The most popular move, but it's a mistake because of this brilliant sequence! :D } 8. Ne5!! { Sacrificing the QUEEEEEEN! } { [%csl Rd1] } 8... Bxd1?? (8... dxe5 9. Qxg4 { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gg4h5] } 9... Nf6 10. Qf5 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf5e5] } 10... Qxd4 (10... exd4 11. Nd5 Nc6 12. Bxf4 $16 { White's position is really great. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc4,Gf4,Gf5,Re8] }) 11. Qc8+ Qd8?? 12. Bxf7+! { Forcing the king away from the queen. If black takes the bishop, we just grab the free queen. } 12... Ke7 13. Qe6# { Checkmate! } { [%csl Ge8,Ge7,Gf7,Rf8,Rd8,Rf6,Gd7,Gd6][%cal Ge6e8,Ge6f7,Ge6d7,Ge6d6] }) 9. Bxf7+ { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gf7e8] } 9... Ke7 $7 10. Nd5# { A nice legal's mate! } { [%csl Ge7,Gf6,Yd7,Yf7,Be6,Be8,Rd8,Rf8,Rd6][%cal Gd5e7,Gd5f6,Ye5d7,Ye5f7,Bf7e6,Bf7e8] }) 8. Bxf4 O-O (8... Nh5 9. Be3 Ng3 10. Rg1 Bxh4 11. Bf2 { White's ok, just castle queenside. Mr. Fish gives +1 } { [%csl Gc4,Bd5,Bb5,Bc1][%cal Bc3d5,Bc3b5,Bd1d2,Be1c1] }) 9. Qd2 $14 { Next up is O-O-O and white gets a pretty comfortable position. } { [%csl Bc1,Rh6][%cal Be1c1] } *


