2... exf4 3. Nf3 d5!? { An interesting option from black. Black intends to immediately open up the position. } 4. exd5 Qxd5?! { This is the Modern Defense, although it ain't great because white gets tempo by kicking the queen around. A much better move would be 4...Nf6!: the Abbazia Defense, covered in the next chapter. } 5. Nc3! { Hitting the queen while developing. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 5... Qe6+ (5... Qd8 6. d4 Bd6 7. Bc4 Ne7?? { A common blunder. White has only one winning move. } (7... Nf6 8. Qe2+ Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 10. O-O $14 { White is ahead in development, also black's f4 pawn is very weak. Stockfish gives +0.5 for white. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc3,Gd4,Gf3,Rc8,Rb8] }) 8. Ng5! { double attacking f7. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7] } 8... O-O 9. Qh5 { A fork. } { [%csl Gf7,Gh7][%cal Gh5f7,Gh5h7] } 9... h6 10. Nxf7 Rxf7 11. Qxf7+ Kh8 12. Bxf4 Bxf4 13. Qxf4 $18 { White is up an exchange. }) 6. Be2 { Blocking the check but also preparing to castle kingside. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 6... Bd6 7. O-O { Bringing the king out of the center. } 7... Ne7 { Black prepares to castle too. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 8. d4 $14 { Giving the DSB some space to breathe. Stockfish gives +0.2. Black is a bit behind in development and the queen is awkwardly placed. } { [%csl Gc1,Rc8,Rb8] } *


