[Opening "King's Gambit Accepted: Cunningham Defense, Bertin Gambit"]
[StudyName "King's Gambit | Full Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "KGA: Cunningham Defense 3...Be7"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ACmyH8gC/t9A6aG5Y"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4PP2/8/PPPP2PP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.12.17"]
[UTCTime "12:56:29"]

2... exf4 3. Nf3 Be7 { This is the Cunningham Defense, it gets seen much more often at +1800 level. Black just wants to castle as fast as possible } { [%cal Bg8f6,Be8g8] } 4. Bc4! { Aiming at f7. } 4... Bh4+ { You will see this pretty much every time. Black forces white to move the king if he doesn't want to lose more pawns from his army. White has 2 options: Play Kf1 and you get an 'ok' game, or spice things up a bit with g3! } 5. g3!? { White's winrate immediately spikes up to 56%! This is the Bertin Gambit, one of the most craziest gambits in the King's Gambit. We'll sac 3 pawns! } 5... fxg3 6. O-O! { The absolute best move! } 6... gxh2+ 7. Kh1! { Black is up "3 pawns"! But we can take h2 anytime we want. For now we'll use it as an 'umbrella pawn'. } 7... d6? (7... d5 { The best move from black. Blocking white from getting any action on f7. But many players might miss this, and then white gets the advantage. } 8. exd5 Bg4 9. Qe2+ Ne7 10. d6 Qxd6 (10... cxd6?? 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7 (11... Kf8 12. Be6 $18) 12. Nxh4+ Kg8 13. Qxg4 $18) 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7?? (11... Kd8 12. Qg2 $13 { It's an unclear position, black is a bit better, but both sides get chances. }) 12. Nxh4+ Ke8 13. Qxg4 $16) (7... Nh6? 8. d4! { White has full compensation for the 3 pawns. Next we want to grab the knight on h6 (if it doesn't move away). } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4,Gc1] }) (7... Bg3? 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. d4! Nf6 (9... Ke8 10. Bg5 Nf6 (10... Ne7 11. Nh4 $16) 11. e5) 10. Ng5+ Kf8 11. e5) (7... Be7?? { this leads to checkmate. } 8. Bxf7+!! Kxf7 9. Ne5+! { Opening up the rook. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5f7] } 9... Ke8 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Nxg6 Nf6 12. Rxf6!! Bxf6 13. Ne5+! { Now just give checks. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5f7] } 13... Ke7 14. Qf7+ Kd6 15. Nc4+ Kc5 16. Qd5+ Kb4 17. a3+ Ka4 18. b3# { [%csl Ga4,Gb4,Ya5,Yb5][%cal Gb3a4,Ga3b4,Yd5a5] }) 8. Bxf7+! { Bringing the king to the f file. } 8... Kxf7 9. Ng5+! Kg6 (9... Ke8 10. Qh5+ { A fork. } { [%csl Gh4,Ge8][%cal Gh5h4,Gh5e8] } 10... g6 11. Qxh4 { Black's king is exposed, cannot castle, and completely not developed. } { [%csl Gh4,Gg5,Gf1,Re8,Rg8,Rh8,Rd8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8] } 11... h6?? { Another fun variation I want to show. } 12. Rf8+!! Kxf8 13. Ne6+ { White wins the queen!! } { [%csl Gf8,Gd8][%cal Ge6f8,Ge6d8,Yh4d8] }) 10. Nf7 { The best move from black is 10...Nh6! temporarily sacrificing the queen, but black wins it back later on. } { [%csl Gd8,Gh8][%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8] } 10... Qe7?? (10... Nh6!! 11. Nxd8 Bg4 12. Rf3 Rf8 13. Rxf8 Bxd1 14. Ne6 $10 { With perfect play, it's equal. But it's really easy for black to mess up. } { [%csl Rg6,Ra8,Rb8,Gf8] }) 11. Nxh8+! Kh6 12. d4+ g5 13. Nc3! { Black's king is way too weak. White has a +2 advantage. } { [%csl Rh6,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Gh8][%cal Bh8f7] } *


