2... exf4 3. Nf3 Ne7 { Preparing for a flexible development. The game takes a strategic turn. Black plans to reroute to g6. This is called the Bonsch-Osmolovsky Variation, It's pretty rare so you won't face it so often :) } { [%csl Bg6][%cal Be7g6] } 4. Nc3 Ng6 { Controlling e5 and supporting f4. } { [%csl Gf4,Ge5][%cal Gg6f4,Gg6e5] } 5. d4 Bb4 { The bishop enters the game, pinning the knight. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 6. h4! { White injects energy with a pawn storm. } { [%cal Bh4h5] } 6... d5 { Black opts for a solid central break. } (6... h5 { Stopping white from pushing further. } 7. Bc4 d6? { A common mistake. } 8. Ng5! { Double attacking f7. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7] } 8... Be6 { Castling doesn't work because it would leave the h pawn hanging. } 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. O-O $16 { [%csl Rf4,Re6,Re8] }) 7. h5 { Pushing further into black's territory. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gh5g6] } 7... Ne7 8. e5 $14 { White advances, clamping down on the center. White is slightly better. } *


