2... exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. h4 g4 5. Ne5 { This marks the beginning of the Kieseritzsky Gambit. } 5... Nf6 6. Nxg4 { White takes g4, but black can now grab e4. } 6... Nxe4 7. d3 { Kicking away the knight from the center. } 7... Ng3 { Attacking the rook, but white has a really brilliant response: } 8. Bxf4!! { The only good move! Rh3/Rg1 would be responded with with Qe7+!, which will be a nightmare for white. } 8... Qe7+ { The most popular move. } (8... Nxh1 { This line leads to a pretty drawish position. } 9. Qe2+!! Qe7 (9... Be7?? { A HUGE blunder! It blunders mate in 2! } 10. Nf6+ Kf8 $7 11. Bh6# { Checkmate! } { [%csl Bf8,Bg7,Yg8,Ye8,Rf7,Re7][%cal Bh6f8,Yf6g8,Yf6e8] }) 10. Nf6+! { The only move that doesn't lose! } 10... Kd8 11. Bxc7+!! { Forcing the king to come out. } 11... Kxc7 $7 12. Nd5+ { Forking the king and queen. } { [%csl Gc7,Ge7][%cal Gd5c7,Gd5e7] } 12... Kd8 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 $10 { Black's still up a bit of material, but it's still 0.0, although good to note that white has a 54% winrate :D }) 9. Be2 Nxh1?? { The most popular move, but it loses due to this brilliant sequence: } (9... Rg8! { The best move for black. } 10. Bxg3! Rxg4! { The queen is pinning the LSB, so black is able to pick up this piece. } 11. Bf2! Rxg2 12. Nc3 $13 { Stockfish says 0.0, but it's still dangerous for either side. This position has been reached a dozen of times in the masters database, most of them ended in a draw. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Bd1d2,Be1c1] }) 10. Bg5! { Controlling e7 and d8. White prepares for Nf6+ } 10... Qb4+ { The most popular move, it just postpones black's downfall. } (10... Qe6 11. Nf6+! { Forcing black's king to move to the dark squares, where he will meet with our monster dark-squared bishop. } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gf6e8] } 11... Kd8 12. Nd5+! { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gg5d8] } 12... f6 (12... Be7 13. Bxe7+ Ke8 14. Nxc7+ Kxe7 15. Nxe6 Kxe6 $18 { White's up material }) 13. Bxf6+ Ke8 14. Nxc7+ Kf7 15. Nxe6 Kxf6 16. Nxf8 Rxf8 $18 { White's up 3 points of material. Also, all black's pieces placement are really trash. Stockfish says +7 for white. } { [%csl Rh1,Rf8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8] }) (10... Qd6 11. Nf6+ Kd8 12. Ne4+ $18) 11. c3! { Kicking the queen. There really isn't anything black can do. the Nf6+ threat is still there. } 11... Qxb2 12. Nf6+! Kd8 (12... Ke7 13. Qa4!! { The queen is going to e4, the } 13... Qxa1 (13... Ng3 { Controlling the e4 square. } { [%csl Re4] } 14. Nd5+ Kd6 15. Qf4+ Kxd5 16. Bf3+ Kc5 17. Qd4+ Kb5 18. c4+ Ka6 19. Qxb2 $18 { White is totally winning, the king is really weak. }) 14. Qe4+ Kd6 15. Qd5+ Ke7 16. Qe5+ Kd8 17. Qe8# { [%csl Bc8,Bd8,Be7,Ye8,Rc7,Rd7][%cal Be8c8,Be8e7,Yf6e8] }) 13. Nd5+ Be7 (13... Ke8 14. Nxc7# { Checkmate! }) 14. Bxe7+ Ke8 15. Ba3! Qxa1 16. Bh5!! { An absolutely BRILLIANT move! Every other move loses! The LSB Prepares to sacrifice himself on f7 to bring the king out. } 16... Qxa2 (16... Kd8 17. Be7+ Ke8 18. Bxf7+ Kxf7 19. Qf3+ Ke6 20. Qf6+ Kxd5 21. c4#) 17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 18. Qf3+ { Now white just gives checks to lure the king forward. } 18... Ke6 19. Nxc7+ Ke5 20. d4# { An absolutely astonishing checkmate! White checkmates black while being down 10 points of material!! } { [%csl Ge5,Be6,Bd5,Yf6,Yf5,Yf4,Ye4,Rd6][%cal Gd4e5,Bc7e6,Bc7d5,Yf3f6,Yf3e4,Ra3d6] } *


