4... g4 5. O-O! { You have to play this move, trust me. Moving the knight away, would be responded with Qh4+, and you don't want to deal with that. Black didn't develop a single piece yet and he has made his kingside weaker. So, the sacrificed knight is justified for white. } 5... gxf3 6. Qxf3 Qf6 7. d3!? { Okay, I'm first showing this line, for people that are not a huge fan of sacrificing 7 points worth of material to be a show-off to their opponent. This is the safe line of the Muzio Gambit, it's not even close to the chaos of the Double Muzio Gambit. } 7... Bh6 { Protecting f4. } 8. Bxf4 { White willingly trades material for an attacking position. } 8... Bxf4 9. Qxf4 Qxf4 10. Rxf4 { A symphony of exchanges. The material count narrows, but White's rook looms ominously. } 10... Nh6 { Defending the f7 pawn. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rh6f7] } 11. Nc3 { [%csl Gd5,Gb5][%cal Gc3d5,Gc3b5] } 11... c6 { Preparing for a solid fortress. White's knight can no longer go to d5/b5. } { [%cal Rc6d5,Rc6b5] } 12. Raf1 $13 { Stockfish gives black a slight edge (0.5), considering that white is down a horse, that ain't bad! Also, white is the one with a whopping 55% winrate! :D } { [%csl Gc4,Gf4,Gf1,Gc3,Rb8,Ra8,Rc8,Re8,Rh8,Rh6,Rf7] } *


[Event "King's Gambit | Full Repertoire: KGA: Double Muzio Gambit"]
[Date "2023.12.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
