[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ACmyH8gC/Uqn6KF39"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppp1p1p/8/6p1/4Pp2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.12.17"]
[UTCTime "12:56:30"]

4. Bc4 { Now I'm going to show you the most INSANE, the most AGGRESSIVE, the most CHAOTIC gambit; presenting....The Double Muzio Gambit!! } 4... g4 5. O-O! { There goes the first piece! } 5... gxf3 6. Qxf3 Qf6 { You'll see this move pretty much every time, it's the Sarratt Defense. } 7. e5!? { We sacrifices the e5 pawn, bringing black into a labyrinth of threats! } 7... Qxe5 8. Bxf7+!! { A bishop sacrifice! The king is forced to dance amid the chaos! This is top engine btw. } 8... Kxf7 9. d4!! Qxd4+?! { The engine gives 1.8 in favor for black, but considering that white is down 7 points in material, that's not bad at all!! } (9... Qf5! { The top engine move! This will be the perfect line for black, if black plays this at the end black gets the advantage. } 10. Bxf4 Nf6! { All other moves lead the an equal position. } (10... d6?? 11. Qe3 Nf6 12. Bg5 { [%csl Rf6,Rf5][%cal Rf1f6] } 12... Qxf1+ 13. Kxf1 $16) 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. Qe3 $17 { Black has a 2.3 advantage, that's not that bad, the position is still very doubled-edged, but it's easy for white to make a mistake too. This is the drawback of the Double Muzio Gambit, if black's well prepared, they get the advantage. }) 10. Be3! { The only good move! The f pawn is pinned. } 10... Qf6? { By far the most popular move. It's crazy how black is up 7 points of material but the engine says 0.0! :D } (10... Qxb2? { Fails immediately: } 11. Qxf4+ Nf6 (11... Qf6 12. Qc4+ $18 { [%csl Rf7,Rf6][%cal Gc4f7,Rf1f7] } 12... d5 13. Qxc7+! $18 { [%csl Rf7,Rf6,Rc8][%cal Rf1f7] }) 12. Bd4 $18 { [%csl Ga1,Gb2,Yf6,Rf7][%cal Gd4a1,Gd4f6,Yf1f6,Bf1f7] }) (10... Qg7! { A much rarer move, but the only good move for black! } 11. Nc3 $13 { A very double edged position, black can go wrong very soon. I won't be covering more, because it's much too complex and in-dept, I recommend practicing this position a few times with a training bot. }) 11. Nc3 c6?? { A very natural looking move and also the most popular, black prevents white from bringing the knight to d5, but there's one problem...we can hop to e4. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6d5] } (11... fxe3?? { The second most popular move. White has a simple response: } 12. Qh5+! { We pick up the queen next, and because black's king is super weak, white is totally winning. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf6][%cal Rf1f7,Gh5f7] }) (11... Ne7 { This move leads to a draw. } 12. Nd5! Qf5 { The only good move. Every other move leads to a huge advantage for white. } 13. Rad1! $13 { The only good move for white. } 13... Na6 (13... d6 14. Bxf4! Na6 15. Ne3 Qf6 16. Nd5 Qf5 17. Ne3 $10) 14. Bxf4 d6 15. Ne3 Qf6 16. Nd5 Qf5 17. Ne3 { A draw by repetition. Any other move leads to the other side getting an advantage. }) 12. Ne4! { The only winning move. It's done for black now. } 12... Qf5 (12... Qg6 13. Qxf4+ Nf6 14. Nxf6 Kg7 15. Nh5+ Qxh5 16. Qf6+ Kg8 17. Qxf8# { [%csl Bh8,Bg8,Bg7,Rh7,Bf7][%cal Bf8h8,Bf8g7,Bf8f7] }) (12... Qh6 13. Bxf4! Qg6 14. Be5+ Nf6 15. Bxf6 $18) 13. g4! { Forcing the queen away. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gg4f5] } 13... Qg6 (13... Qe5 14. Bxf4! { The only winning move. } 14... Qd5 15. Bg5+ Ke6 16. Qf7+ Ke5 17. Bf6+ Kxe4 18. Rae1# { [%csl Be4,Be3,Yd4,Ye5,Gf5,Gf4,Gf3,Rd3,Rd5][%cal Be4e5,Be1e5,Yf6d4,Gf1f5,Rc2d3] }) 14. Qxf4+ $18 { There is nothing black can do, it's over, all white's pieces come flowing in. Also, notice how all black's pieces are still stuck on the backrank. It doesn't matter if you're up a bunch of material if you haven't developed yet. :) } { [%csl Yf6,Rf7,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8][%cal Gf1f7,Ye4f6] } *


