4. Bc4 Bg7 { Not always does black go into the Muzio lines, this is one of them. This is called the Traditional Variation. Black decides to just castle as soon as possible. Although it's still hard for black to castle because if the Knight goes to f6 or e7 we just grab g5. } 5. Nc3 { A developing move. } 5... h6 (5... d6 6. h4 { Striking the kingside. } 6... h6 7. d4 Bg4 8. Qd3 $13 { Next up is Bd2 and O-O-O. } { [%cal Bc1d2,Be1c1] }) 6. g3 fxg3 7. d4! { We grab the center. Developing comes first! } 7... gxh2 (7... d6 8. Be3! { Next up is Qe2 and O-O-O! } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Bd1d2,Be1c1] } 8... g4 { Something you have to be ready for. } 9. O-O! { Saving the knight would lead to black getting the advantage. } 9... gxf3 10. Qxf3! { We triple up on f7! } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf1f7,Gc4f7] } 10... gxh2+ 11. Kh1! { Using it as an umbrella pawn. } 11... Qd7! { The only surviving move. } (11... Nf6? 12. e5! { Every thing falls apart. }) 12. Rf2! { Getting ready to stack the next piece! White has more than enough compensation for the 5 points of material sacrificed. If you want you can dig deeper into this position, but I won't go to in-dept in this. }) 8. Rxh2 $14 { Stockfish gives a slight edge for white. } *


