3... e4!? { This is the most popular move. The idea of this move is to take away the f3 square from the knight, making it harder for white to develop. This is called the Staunton line. } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Re4f3] } 4. d3! { Trying to get rid of that annoying pawn. } 4... Nf6 (4... exd3 5. Bxd3 Nf6 6. Nf3 Bc5 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Nc3 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 O-O 10. Bd2 Re8 11. O-O-O $16 { White is up a clean pawn }) 5. dxe4! Nxe4 6. Nf3! { Controlling the h4 square. } { [%csl Rh4] } 6... Bc5 (6... Be7 7. c4 $14 { Next up is Bd3 and O-O. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc4][%cal Gc4d5,Bf1d3,Be1g1] }) 7. Qe2 Bf5 (7... O-O 8. Qxe4! Re8 9. Ne5 f6 10. Bd3 { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gd3h7] } 10... g6 11. Nc3 fxe5 12. fxe5 $16 { White is simply up 2 pawns } { [%csl Gd5,Ge5,Ge4,Gc3,Gd3] }) 8. Nc3 Qe7 9. Be3 Nxc3 10. Bxc5 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 Nxe2 12. Kxe2 $16 { White is up a clean pawn. The next step is to bring the h1 rook to e1 and get the king to f1. } { [%cal Bh1e1,Be2f1] } *


