[UTCTime "12:56:30"]

2... Nc6 { Black decides to simply protect the pawn. This is the Queen's Knight Defense, it's the second most popular move from black after 2. f4. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e5] } 3. Nf3 { [%csl Rh4,Gf3] } 3... d5 (3... d6 4. d3 { We have transposed to the same position as chapter 27. }) (3... g5!? { The Zilbermints Double Gambit, this is good for white, but often times white messes up. } 4. fxg5! { We can just grab it, it's free. } 4... h6 { Grabbing h6 would lose most of the advantage. } 5. Nc3 { A develoing move } 5... hxg5 6. d4 $16 { White gets a good game. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gc3,Rg5,Re5] }) 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6 (5... Qd8? { This hangs e5. } 6. fxe5! { White's up a clean pawn. Black got absolutely 0 compensation for that gambit. } { [%csl Ge5,Gf3,Gc3,Bb5,Bc4][%cal Bd2d4,Bf1c4,Bc4b5] }) (5... Qa5?! { The second most popular move. White has a nice response. } 6. Bb5! { Pinning the knight and obstructing the queen from defending e5. } { [%csl Rc6,Re5,Ra5] } 6... Bd7 { We can now go grab that juicy pawn. } (6... exf4 { Black grabs the f pawn in order not to lose the pawn. } 7. Ne5! { We start building up pressure on the c6 knight. } { [%csl Rc6] } 7... Ne7 8. Qf3! { Adding more pressure. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Yf3c6,Be5c6,Gb5c6] } 8... Bd7 (8... Qb6 9. d4! $16 { The queen is unable to take d4 because it would have to leave the knight. White gets a great game. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Be1g1,Bc1f4,Bd4d5] }) 9. Nxd7 Kxd7 10. d4! $16 { Next up is O-O, grab the f pawn, and white has a sweet advantage. } { [%csl Rd7,Rf4,Ra5,Rc6,Rf8,Re7][%cal Be1g1,Bc1f4,Bd4d5] }) 7. fxe5 O-O-O 8. O-O $14) 6. Bb5 exf4+ 7. Kf2 Bc5+?? { The most popular move for unknown reasons. \|'-'|/
This move is total trash, because of our very simple response: } (7... Be7?! { The second most popular move. Black avoids getting skewered on the e file with Re1. } { [%csl Ge7] } 8. Re1 Qd6 (8... Qf5 9. d4 $16 { [%csl Gd4,Gf3,Gd1,Ge1,Gc1,Gc3,Gb5,Rf4,Rf5][%cal Bf2g1] }) (8... Qh6 9. d4 $14 { White gets a good game! } { [%csl Ge1,Gd1,Rf4,Rh6,Gd4,Gb5,Gc3][%cal Bf2g1,Bd4d5] }) 9. Ne4! { d4 works too, but let's have some fun kicking the queen around :) } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge4d6] } 9... Qb4 (9... Qg6 10. Ne5 { [%csl Gg6,Gc6][%cal Ge5g6,Ge5c6] } 10... Qf5 11. d4 $14 { We got two horsies in the center. Stockfish gives + 0.6 } { [%csl Ge5,Ge4,Gb5,Ge1,Gd1][%cal Bf2g1,Bc2c3] }) (9... Qh6 10. d4 { everything's nicely placed. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gb5,Ge1,Gd1,Rf4][%cal Bc2c3,Bf2g1] }) 10. Qe2 { Black's been dancing the queen around for the past few moves. White's completely fine. The king has just artificially castled and is now safe. } { [%csl Gb5,Gf3,Gf2,Ge1,Ge2,Ge4,Rb4,Rf4][%cal Ge2b5,Bd2d4,Bc2c3,Bf2g1] }) (7... Bd7?? { The third mos popular move. It completely ignores our main threat. } 8. Re1! $18 { We pick up the queen on the next move. } { [%csl Ge8,Re6][%cal Ye1e8] }) (7... Qh6! { The best move, being played 2% of the time lol. } 8. d4! { The position is equal, you get a good game. }) (7... Ne7 8. d4! $14 { Threatening an immediate d5. You get a good game, white's slightly better. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Bd4d5,Bh1e1] }) 8. d4! { Black is in big trouble. White has 3 threats: 1. Re1, skewering the queen 2. simply taking the bishop on c5 3. d5, forking the queen and horse. So, white wins in all lines, it's gg. } { [%cal Bd4d5,Bh1e1,Bd4c5] } *


