2... Bc5 { The Classical Variation. Black develops his kingside bishop and already make it a bit harder for white to castle. Keep in mind that the e5 pawn ain't hanging, because of Qh4+, which completely wins for black. } { [%csl Rg1] } 3. Nf3 { Controlling the h4 square. } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gf3h4] } 3... d6 (3... exf4? 4. d4 $16 { Transposing to the same position as chapter 11. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rf4] }) 4. c3! { White plays c3, preparing for d4 and creating a pathway for the queen to come into play. This move strengthens the center and sets the stage for dynamic pawn play. } { [%cal Bd2d4,Bc3d4,Bd1b3] } 4... Nc6 (4... Qe7 { A fun trap arises from this move. } 5. d4! exd4 6. cxd4! Qxe4+?? 7. Kf2!! { the only winning move! } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Rd4c5] } 7... Bb6 8. Bb5+! Kd8 9. Re1! { [%csl Ge8,Ge4][%cal Ge1e8] } 9... Qf5 10. Re8# { Checkmate! } { [%csl Gc8,Gd8,Ye8,Yd7,Ge7][%cal Ge8c8,Yb5e8,Ge8e7] }) 5. d4 { White executes a central pawn advance, gaining space. Black responds by developing the bishop to b6, maintaining the tension in the center. } 5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb6 { Black retreats the bishop to b6, maintaining the tension in the center. } 7. Nc3 Bg4 (7... f5 8. exf5 Bxf5 9. Bb5 $13 { Make sure to play Kf2 after Qe7+! } { [%csl Bg1,Bc6][%cal Be1g1,Bb5c6] }) 8. Bb5 a6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Be3 $14 { White has a nice big center and is ready to castle. Black, on the other hand, has doubled c pawns, an isolated a pawn, and no real active piece. White has a 55% winrate! } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Rc7,Rc6,Ra6,Re8,Rg8,Gc3,Gf3,Ge3,Rb6,Bb3,Ba4][%cal Be1g1,Bd1a4,Bd1b3] } *


