[Event "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...Nc6: 🚀 == Introduction  == 🚀"]
[Date "2025.03.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B30"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Portsmouth Gambit"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...Nc6"]
[ChapterName "🚀 == Introduction  == 🚀"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/55CPbtmd/zstXXzmi"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.10"]
[UTCTime "11:04:23"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ ✨ Hello, I'm Bosburp! Welcome to my study! ✨

New study! CRUSH the Sicilian 2...d6: https://lichess.org/study/Vpb6r3Wq

In this study I'll share a rare, yet extremely powerful weapon against the Sicilian called the Portsmouth Gambit! 🏹

As some of you may know, I've created a study about this opening a long time ago ( https://lichess.org/study/ryfpxxYb ). It was well received, but it has a lot of room for improvement. So here's a better, expanded, much improved version of it! 😃

It will still contain the same lines, but hopefully this study will make your learning experience much smoother. 🎯

If you find this study helpful, please give it a heart 💓! It helps more players discover this study and adds it to the "favorites" list to help you find this study again easily.

If you have any questions about the study, feel free to DM me. 💬

Let’s get started! Play 1. e4! :) 🚀 }
1. e4 { "Best by test" } 1... c5 { Black plays the Sicilian Defense, the most popular response to 1.e4 at higher levels. It's known for its dynamic and counterattacking potential, it’s in the repertoire of every world-class player.
We'll be responding with 2. Nf3, nothing special yet. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gg1f3,Rc5d4] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { This is the Old Sicilian, Black's most popular option. In this study, we’ll cover how to crush this variation. However, if Black plays 2...d6, 2...e6, or another move, sadly, you won't be able to play the Portsmouth Gambit. I might create studies with weapons to handle those variations in the future. :)
Now we'll play a move that is most likely going to give Black a bit of a shock! Play 3. b4! } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gb2b4] } 3. b4! { This is the beginning of the Portsmouth Gambit! At fist glance, this might seem very dubious, but it's not. With perfect play (which is already a big challenge for Black), it's equal. Although, most of the time Black will mess up and you'll get a quick beautiful win. Even Former World Champion Magnus Carlsen has played this gambit multiple times. I've been playing the Portsmouth Gambit a lot, and my current stats from over 230 games is a whopping 60% winrate!
Black has 3 options here; take with the knight, take with the pawn, or ignore it. Most people will just take the free pawn, as declining it immediately allows us to play b5, kicking the knight away.
Feel free to use the engine and the Lichess database, and don't forget to explore the variations! 🕵️
Go to the next chapter :) } { [%cal Rc5b4,Rc6b4,Bb4b5] } *


