[UTCTime "11:04:23"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4! { We’re playing the Portsmouth Gambit! Important note: it doesn’t actually matter whether Black captures with the knight or the pawn, as both lines will transpose into the exact same position. Make sure to memorize how this transposition works, it’s covered in the variation below. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rb4b5] } 3... cxb4 { Black captures the pawn. This allows us to grab the center with d4 right away. } { [%cal Bd2d4,Rc5b4] } (3... Nxb4 { Black captures with the knight. We can’t play d4 immediately because Black's c-pawn will just capture it, so we first play 3. c3, kicking the knight away and it prepares the d4 pawn push. } { [%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d4] } 4. c3! { [%cal Rc3b4] } 4... Nc6 { Black retreats to the best square, Na6 wouldn’t make any sense. After all, a knight on the rim is grim! } { [%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4] } 5. d4 { Now we can play d4. } 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 { We're controlling the center and d5 is threat. Black will most times immediately challenge the center and avoid us pushing the d-pawn with d5. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4][%cal Rd4d5] } 6... d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3! { We've transposed to the exact same position! } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Rc3d5] }) 4. d4! { We're now threatening to play d5, kicking away the knight. This would be very unpleasant for Black. To avoid this, most players will respond with d5, blocking our d-pawn from advancing. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Bd4d5] } 4... d5 { You’ll reach this position most of the time, and it’s quite tricky. Many players have blundered in completely winning positions, so I highly recommend familiarizing yourself thoroughly with this section. The following sequence is rather forced. } { [%csl Rd5] } 5. exd5 { We take the d-pawn, luring the queen forward. } 5... Qxd5 { Black's queen is now placed in the center, where we can easily attack it. This allows us to develop while gaining tempi. } { [%csl Rd5] } 6. c4 { [%cal Rc4d5] } 6... bxc3 { Black captures with en passant. } 7. Nxc3 { We recapture with the knight. While we’re currently down a pawn, it’s no problem, just look at our position! Both knights are developed, our bishops can easily develop, we’ve got an open file for the rook, and the queen can quickly get involved. Meanwhile, Black is already faced with an only-move. Definitely worth the pawn! Make sure you've memorized how to come to this point! We'll look at this variation in-dept in the following chapters marked with 📕. } { [%csl Gc3,Gf3][%cal Ba1b1,Yf1b5,Yc1g5,Bd1a4] } *


