{ We're attacking the queen, so it has to move. } { [%cal Rc3d5] }
7... Qa5! { Black moves the queen to a safe square, attacking our knight. This is, by the way, the only good move in this position, any other move immediately gives White a +3 advantage, which we’ll look at later on. Now, our knight is under attack, so we have to protect it, right? Wrong! Instead, we’re going for a much spicier move... } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Ra5c3] } 8. Rb1!! { Rb1!! We sacrifice the full knight! This move 100% not dubious, Stockfish completely approves, the evaluation is still equal, but that's only if both sides play perfect. If you're hesitant of playing down a piece, don't worry, if Black wants to maintain equality, he will have to sacrifice the knight back, if not we'll get huge advantage. Now we place the rook on the open b-file, here it takes away escape squares from the queen (you'll understand it more late on) and is very active here. We allow Black to take our knight, but in return we'll get a huge attack. } { [%cal Gb1b8] } 8... Qxc3+ { Completely fine! The piece isn't poisoned. Although, Black has to be from now on extremely careful. We'll later on also check out the lines if Black declines. } 9. Bd2! { We kick the queen away. She's only left with one safe square. } { [%csl Ga3][%cal Rd2c3] } 9... Qa3 10. d5! { This is the start of some very crazy lines. In the next few chapter I'll cover every response from Black. You'll very often reach this position, so the following chapters will be the most important. } *


