{ From this position, only 16% of the time the best moves are played. First, let’s take a look at what Black shouldn’t play. }
10... Nb8?? { The most popular option. Black simply saves his knight from danger, but this is actually a game-losing blunder! We now throw a series of forced punches. } 11. Qc2!! { Extremely important! This is the only move that leads to a winning position, any other move allows Black to get an equal position. With this move we're creating two major threats: the immediate Qxc8# and Bb4, which completely traps Black’s queen! } { [%csl Ya2,Rc8,Rb4][%cal Yc2a2,Gc2c8,Rd2b4] } 11... Bd7 { This is the most popular move, as it appears to solve both problems: saving the bishop and creating a safe escape square for the queen on a4. But we have a simple response: } { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ba3a4,Yd7a4] } (11... Nd7 { Solves the checkmate problem, but now we just trap the queen. } { [%csl Gc8,Rb4][%cal Ga8c8,Rd2b4] } 12. Bb4 $18 { We get a material advantage and we have a incredibly active position. It's +4.4. } { [%csl Ra3][%cal Rb4a3] }) (11... Na6 { The knight now covers the b4 square and the LSB is defended by the rook. The problem now fro Black is that his king is very exposed, we can take advantage of this fact by immediately giving a check with our bishop. } { [%csl Gc8,Re8,Rd7][%cal Ra6b4,Ga8c8] } 12. Bb5+! { Bd7 transposes to the 12...Na6 variation below. Black's king has to move because there's no piece to block with, except the bishop, which would leave b7 undefended. } 12... Kd8 { f7 is now weakened. } { [%csl Rf7] } 13. Ne5! { We continue attacking! Nf7# is now a threat. Black can't stop us placing a knight on f7, so he has no choice but to create an escape square for the king. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Re5f7] } 13... e6 { [%cal Gd8e7] } 14. Nxf7+ Ke7 15. Nxh8 $18 { Black's position completely crumbles. He's not surviving much longer. It's +7 } { [%csl Re7,Rc7,Rf8,Rg8,Rc8,Ra6,Ra3,Gc2,Gd2,Gb1,Gb5][%cal Be1g1] }) 12. Bb5! { Pinning the bishop! We renew our threat of Qc8#! and Bb4. At this point there's nothing Black can do anymore, most players will just play a normal "developing" move or attempt to save the queen and miss Qc8#. } { [%csl Rc8,Rd7,Ra4,Rb4][%cal Gc2c8,Yb5e8,Rb5a4,Bd2b4] } 12... Qd6 { This is the most popular move, bringing the queen to safety, but unfortunately for Black, it allows us to play a beautiful checkmate. } (12... Nf6 { Tied for 1st most popular, again loses to Qc8#. } 13. Qc8#! { [%csl Re8,Gb5,Gc8][%cal Rd7c8,Yb5e8,Gc8e8] }) (12... Na6 { This one's a bit different, but loses due to forced mate too. } { [%csl Rb7,Rd7] } 13. Bxd7+! { We start by capturing the bishop with check, clearing the way for our rook to infiltrate the 7th rank. } { [%csl Rb7][%cal Rb1b7] } 13... Kxd7 14. Rxb7+ { [%csl Rd7][%cal Rb7d7] } 14... Kd8 (14... Kd6 15. Qc6# { [%csl Rd6,Ge5,Ye6,Yc6,Bd7,Bc7,Re7,Rc5,Rd5][%cal Rc6d6,Gf3e5,Yd5e6,Yd5c6,Bb7d7,Rc6c5] }) 15. Qc6! { Bringing the queen in the attack. We're creating a checkmating net around the king. } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Rc6d7] } 15... Nf6 { Covering checkmate on the d7 square, we now simply bring another piece to join the checkmating attack. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gf6d7] } 16. Ne5 $18 { Checkmate is unavoidable. The knight will always be able to capture f7. } { [%csl Rf7,Gc6,Gb7,Ge5][%cal Re5f7] }) (12... Kd8 { This is another option. Black sees our Qc8# threat and moves his king out of the pin. This is no problem, we now just play our other unstoppable threat; Bb4. } { [%cal Rd8c8] } 13. Bb4! { The queen has no squares to go, we get a material advantage with a beautiful position. The evaluation is +5. } { [%csl Ra3][%cal Rb4a3] }) (12... Bxb5 13. Qc8# { The same thing. }) 13. Qc8#! { Checkmate! The bishop is pinned, so it can't recapture. } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Gc8e8,Rd7c8,Yb5e8] } *


