{ Now let’s look at Black’s second most popular move: 10...Nd8. Our response will be different from the previous chapter, but we’re still completely winning if we play correctly. The following moves might seem like a lot to memorize, but focus on understanding the ideas behind each move. If you do, it will make everything much easier, and you’ll be less likely to make mistakes. }
10... Nd8?? { Now we don't play Qc2, since it doesn't do anything because the c8 bishop is defended now. Black would just play Qd6 and have a winning position. Notice how Black's a4-e8 diagonal is very weak, we'll immediately take advantage of that; } { [%csl Rd7,Re8] } 11. Bb5+! { We now play a series were every move is forced for Black. We give a check, Black is forced to block it with the bishop. } 11... Bd7 { Playing Bxd7+ immediately, to bring the king out, would allow Black's queen to escape. We have to keep her trapped. } { [%csl Ra6] } 12. Bb4! { Not allowing the queen to run away! She only has one "safe" square to go. } { [%csl Ga2,Ra6][%cal Rb4a3] } (12. Bxd7+?? Kxd7 13. Bb4 Qa6 { The queen is safe. }) 12... Qxa2 { Black might think he's gonna get out of this alive, but we already have a winning idea. The plan now is to first bring the king out, and then bring our queen to a4 to attack the king. } { [%cal Bb1a1,Bd1a4,Bb5d7] } 13. Bxd7+! { We force to king to step out to an exposed square. } 13... Kxd7 { We want to get the queen to a4, that's not yet possible because Black's queen controls it, so we first have to kick her away. } { [%csl Ra4,Ra2][%cal Bd1a4,Bb1a1,Ga1a4] } 14. Ra1! { [%csl Ra4][%cal Ra1a4,Bd1a4] } 14... Qb2 { This looks like the a safe square for the queen. We just go after the king, Black's queen is out of the game now. } (14... Qc4 { Loses immediately to a fork. } 15. Ne5+ $18 { A deadly fork! White's again dominating the board. } { [%csl Gd7,Gc4,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rd8,Ra8,Ge5,Gb4][%cal Re5d7,Re5c4] }) 15. Qa4+! Kc8 { Black’s king is completely exposed, and all his pieces are stuck on the 8th rank, unable to join any defense! Our next goal is simple: bring another piece into the attack. The c-file is completely open and aimed at the king, so we’ll place a rook on c1 to take control of it. } { [%csl Rc8,Rd8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Ra8,Rb2,Gb4,Ga4,Ga1][%cal Rc1c8] } (15... Kc7 { Doesn't matter, we continue our plan. } 16. O-O $18 { [%csl Bc1,Rc7,Gb4,Ga4,Ga1,Gf1,Gg1,Gf3,Rd8,Ra8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rb2][%cal Bf1c1,Bb4c3,Bc3e5] }) 16. O-O! { Preparing Rac1! Black can't do anything to save himself anymore. } { [%cal Bf1c1] } 16... Nf6 { It doesn't matter what Black does. } 17. Rfc1+! { Controlling the c-file, we're taking away more squares from the king. } { [%cal Rc1c8] } 17... Kb8 18. Bc3! { We’re threatening Be5#, leaving Black with no choice but to delay checkmate by sacrificing the queen. } { [%csl Re5,Rb8][%cal Rc3b2,Rc3e5] } 18... Qxc3 (18... Qe2 { Black saves his queen, but this still allows Be5+. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Bc3e5] } 19. Be5+ Qxe5 { Black has to sacrifice the queen anyway. } 20. Nxe5 $18 { [%csl Ge5,Ga4,Ga1,Gc1,Rb8,Ra8,Rd8,Rf8,Rh8,Rf6][%cal Gc1c8,Ya1a8,Be5c6,Be5d7,Ba4f4] }) 19. Rxc3 $18 { Material is almost equal now, but that doesn't matter, Black’s pieces are completely stuck and too far away to defend, while all our pieces are perfectly aimed at the exposed king. White can some mating attack with moves like Qf4 or Qd7, or use sacrifice ideas like Ne5-Nc6 to break open the pawn shelter around Black’s king. It’s a forced mate from here. } { [%csl Rb8,Ra8,Rf8,Rd8,Rf6,Rh8,Bc6][%cal Gc3c8,Ga1a8,Ya4f4,Ya4d7,Bf3e5,Be5c6] } *


