10... Na5?? { This is another option that’s played occasionally, though it’s significantly rarer than the moves from previous chapters. Nonetheless, it’s still completely winning for us. } 11. Bb5+! { We immediately take advantage of the weak diagonal. } 11... Bd7 { Black blocks the check. In this case, we don’t play Bb4 since we have another plan. } (11... Kd8 { Instead of blocking the check, Black moves away. } 12. Bb4! { Developing the bishop and hitting the queen. } { [%csl Ra3][%cal Rb4a3] } 12... Qxa2 { The only safe square. We now have Ra1 skewering the queen and knight ideas. But first we can throw in some other moves. } { [%csl Ra5,Ra2][%cal Rb1a1,Ra1a5] } 13. Ne5! { Threatening a Nf7 fork. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rf7d8,Rf7h8,Ge5f7] } 13... Nh6 14. O-O $18 { We bring the king to safety, making sure to avoid any potential checks. We have a completely crushing position. Black's totally stuck, there's just to many threats to deal with. It's +6. } { [%csl Gg1,Ba1,Ra2,Ra5,Rd8,Rc8,Rf8,Rh8,Rh6,Ra8,Ge5,Gb5,Gb4,Gd1,Gb1][%cal Bb1a1,Ba1a2,Ra2a5,Rb4a5] }) 12. Bxd7+ { Bringing the king out. } 12... Kxd7 13. Qc2! $18 { A move with many threats! We prevent the king from escaping to the c-file or manually castling. Now we’re threatening Bb4, trapping the queen since a2 is defended, there's Rxb7 tactics, Qf5+ is potentially dangerous, and Ne4+ is also a complete disaster for Black. } { [%csl Rc8,Rc7,Rb4,Re5,Rf5,Ya2][%cal Gc2c8,Bc2f5,Bd2b4,Rb4a3,Bf3e5,Yc2a2] } 13... Rc8 { The most popular attempt, Black tries to push our queen away. However, we don’t retreat. Instead, we give Black’s king a series of checks to force it away from the rook. } (13... Nf6 { Since, Black really hasn't any good moves, Black decides to just develop a piece. We have a nice response. } 14. Bb4! $18 { We keep things simple. We trap the queen and should have no trouble winning this game considering Black's incredibly weak king. If Black ever play Rc8 just respond with Ne5-Nxf7-Qf5. } { [%csl Rd7,Ra3,Ga4,Ge5][%cal Rb4a3,Gc2a4,Gf3e5] }) (13... b6 14. Bb4 $18 { The same idea. } { [%csl Ra3,Gb4][%cal Rb4a3] }) 14. Ne5+! { [%csl Rd7,Rc8][%cal Ge5d7,Gc2c8] } 14... Kd8 { Black continues to defend the rook. } 15. Nxf7+ { Taking away the d8 square. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Rf7d8] } 15... Kd7 16. Qf5+! { We bring the queen in to take away the d7 square. The only square left for Black to defend the rook is c7. } { [%csl Rd8,Rd7] } 16... Kc7 17. Bf4+! { We continue taking away more squares from the king. Black's now forced to sacrifice the queen because the king has no more legal squares to move to. } 17... Qd6 (17... e5 18. dxe6+! { We just take en passant. } 18... Bd6 19. Bxd6+ Kc6 (19... Qxd6 20. Qxa5+ $18 { Before we take the queen with our knight we can grab this free knight with check, we'll take the queen on the next move. Checkmate will follow soon. } { [%csl Rc7,Rd6,Gb1][%cal Ga5c7,Bf7d6] }) 20. Qb5# { [%csl Rd7,Rc6,Bc7,Bc5,Yb6,Rb7,Yd5,Gb5][%cal Yb5d7,Bd6c7,Bd6c5,Yb5b6,Yb5d5,Gb1b5] }) 18. Bxd6+ exd6 19. Rc1+ $18 { From here it's an easy win. We'll soon have a checkmate (after we win some more material!). } { [%csl Rc7,Rc8][%cal Gf5c8,Bc1c8] } *


