{ Now that we’ve looked at Black’s blunders, let’s see how to play against Black’s best option: 10...e6. This move is played roughly 10% of the time. }
10... e6! { Black accepts that the knight can’t be saved and sacrifices it back to avoid further trouble. It's simply a developing move, it opens the way for the DSB. If White doesn’t capture the knight, Black will simply take on d5 } { [%csl Rd5,Gf8][%cal Re6d5] } 11. dxc6 { We have to capture. } 11... bxc6 12. Qc2! { We protect the a2-pawn while attacking Black’s c6-pawn. Although we’re currently down two pawns, we have plenty of compensation: an active queen, an open b-file for the rook (which can often infiltrate the seventh rank often times), a knight ready to jump into the center, the bishops can easily develop, and we’re just two moves away from castling. This is exactly why we’re playing a gambit! Stockfish evaluates the position as equal. } { [%csl Rc6,Ra2,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Re8,Rc8,Ra8,Gd2,Gf1,Gb1,Ra3][%cal Gc2a2,Bf3e5,Bf1c4,Be1g1,Bc4a6,Bb1b7] } 12... Qc5 { This is the top engine move, Black simply defends the c-pawn and offers a queen trade. But if you know anything about gambits, you’ll know that we’ve sacrificed two pawns for piece activity. Trading pieces, especially the queen, goes completely against our plan. If we trade everything off, we’ll be left with nothing to compensate for the two pawns, and Black will have a winning endgame. } { [%csl Rc2,Gc6][%cal Gc5c6] } (12... Bd7 { The most popular move, Black defends c6. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rd7c6] } 13. Rb3! { You can play Bd3 immediately, but it's a bit better to just throw this move in, the rook's a bit more actively placed here. } 13... Qc5 (13... Qd6 14. Bc3! { White can play this instead of Bd3, since now White isn't pinning himself. We place the DSB on the long diagonal, it will be most active here. There's also Be5 ideas. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Bc3e5,Re5d6] } 14... Nf6 15. Bd3 c5 16. Be5 Qc6 17. O-O $10 { It's an equal, yet active game. Black will however be the defender playing passive here. We are already threatening Bxf6 followed by Bb5, skewering the queen and LSB. Enjoy! } { [%csl Gg1,Gf3,Gd3,Ge5,Gb3,Gc2,Rd7,Rf8,Re8,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Bf1d1,Re5f6,Bd3b5] }) 14. Qb2! $14 { Decline the queen trade! We place our queen here to control the b-file. We develop normally from here. Stockfish gives us a slight edge. } { [%csl Gb3,Gb2][%cal Bf1e2,Be1g1,Be2d3] }) 13. Qa4! { We decline the queen trade and place our queen on her most active square. From this point, there are a ton of possible lines, I won't be able to cover all of them. You’ll need to rely on your intuition, avoid trading material as much as possible, play actively, and make use of Black’s weaknesses; the poorly placed queen and the weak c-pawn, etc... For now, our usual plan is to play Bd3 and safely castle, bringing the king out of the center. } { [%csl Ga4] } 13... Bd6 (13... Bd7 14. Bd3 { We just develop normally. } { [%cal Be1g1] } (14. Bb4?? { Make sure you don't get tempted to play Bb4, hitting the queen, in these types of positions. It's only a one-move-threat. } 14... Qb6 $19 { The queen simply moves away and now our bishop is pinned. c5, winning our bishop is inevitable. } { [%csl Rb4,Rb1,Gf8,Gb6][%cal Rc6c5] }) 14... Nf6 15. O-O $10 { [%csl Gf3,Gd3,Gd2,Gg1,Gb1,Ga4][%cal Bd2b4,Bb1b7,Bf3e5,Bf1c1] }) (13... Nf6 { Same thing. } 14. Bd3 Bd7 15. O-O $10 { [%csl Gg1,Gd3,Gd2,Gf3,Gb1,Ga4][%cal Bf3e5,Bb1b7,Bd2b4,Bf1c1] }) 14. Bd3! { Playing for the win! We're simply preparing to castle on the next move. } { [%cal Be1g1] } (14. Be3 { If you’re aiming for a quick draw, you can go for the Be3 line. Altho, I recommend playing for the win, we have a fantastic, active position, and there’s no reason not to unless you want to go home early form and OTB tourney or something. } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Re3c5] } 14... Qc3+ $7 { Black is forced to repeat moves, since the queen cannot leave the c6-pawn undefended. } (14... Qd5?? { Black is not contented with a draw so he tries to avoid repeating moves, this fails miserably. We can now force the queen away from the c-pawn. } 15. Rd1 $18 { The queen is forced to retreat, and next, we’ll capture the c-pawn, forking the king and rook. This will leave us being up a rook. } { [%csl Rd5,Rc6][%cal Ba4c6,Rc6a8,Rc6e8,Gd1d5] }) 15. Bd2 Qc5 $10 { It's a draw by repetition. } { [%cal Bd2e3,Bc5c3] }) 14... Ne7 15. O-O { We have very active pieces and a safe king. Black's queen is really not actively placed, it served more as a target. Stockfish says it's relatively equal (0.1 for White), but Black can easily make mistakes here. Feel free to explore further the lines with the engine, it might help understand some ideas in these type of positions. } { [%csl Gd3,Gd2,Gf3,Gg1,Rc8,Ga4,Gb1,Rc6,Rc5,Re7][%cal Bd2b4,Bf1c1,Ba4g4] } *


