{ Let’s rewind a few moves. Previously, we analyzed the lines where Black captures our c-pawn with en passant. Now, let’s see what happens if Black chooses not to capture the c-pawn. These lines are a bit more rare, but you’ll still encounter them occasionally. }
6... Qe4+? { This is a common mistake that accomplishes nothing. The queen becomes a target here and is at risk of being easily trapped. In fact, this move was played in some games between Magnus Carlsen and Zhigalko Sergei, where Magnus went on to get a quick win by trapping Zhigalko's queen. } 7. Be3 { We simply block the check. We keep the option open for our LSB to move to d3. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Bf1d3] } 7... Bg4? { By far the most popular move, Black pins our knight. This allows us to play Bd3, attacking the queen. What follows is a rather forced sequence of moves. } (7... Nf6 { The line played in the game between Magnus Carlsen and Zhigalko Sergei. } 8. Bd3 { Kicking the queen away. Again, Qe6 leads to a fork. } { [%csl Re6,Gg4,Re4][%cal Rd3e4] } 8... Qg4 { Zhigalko moves his queen to the only safe square. } (8... Qe6 9. d5! { A fork! } { [%cal Rd5c6,Rd5e6] } 9... Nxd5 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. Qe2 { We want to avoid trading material, so we "unpin" our bishop. Our bishop can now move freely without resulting an a queen trade. Next up is Bc4-O-O and Nbd2. Even tho material is equal, we have a nice advantage because of our amazing development. } { [%csl Rc8,Re8,Rf8][%cal Be1g1,Bd3c4,Bb1d2] }) 9. d5! { Expanding our center, gaining space and kicking away the knight. } { [%cal Rd5c6] } 9... Nb8 (9... Na5 10. h3 Qd7 { Black doesn't take the bait. We can now just develop normally. } 11. O-O $16 { We have a safe king, space advantage, and developed piece. Definitely worth the sacrificed pawn! } { [%csl Gg1,Gd5,Gc4,Ge3,Gd3,Rf8,Re8,Rc8,Rd7,Ra5,Rb4][%cal Bf3e5,Bb1d2] }) (9... Qxg2 10. Rg1 $18 { Suddenly, two pieces are being attacked, Black can't save both. } { [%csl Rg2,Rc6][%cal Rg1g2,Rd5c6] }) 10. h3 { Magnus plays h3, sacrificing the g2-pawn! } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rh3g4] } 10... Qxg2 { Zhigalko takes the bait, thinking that after Rg1, Black's queen can still go to h3. } (10... Qd7 { Black doesn't take the bait. We can just continue by developing normally. } 11. O-O $16 { [%csl Gf3,Ge3,Gd3,Gg1,Rd7,Re8,Rf8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Rh8][%cal Bd1c2,Bc2b3,Bf1e1,Bb1d2,Bf3e5] }) 11. Rh2! { A move many people miss! Magnus keeps his h3 pawn protected, the queen is trapped! He went on to get an easy win from here. } 11... Qxh2 12. Nxh2 Bxh3 13. Qa4+ Nbd7 14. Qxb4 Rb8 15. Nd2 e5 16. Qa4 a6 17. Rb1 Bc5 18. Bxc5 { GM DrNykterstein - GM Zhigalko_Sergei, 1-0, -, https://lichess.org/RsIw6W8E }) (7... e6? 8. Bd3! { Developing with tempo. } { [%cal Rd3e4,Be1g1] } 8... Qg4 9. d5 { Expanding our center. Kicking the knight away. } 9... exd5 10. cxd5 Nce7 11. O-O $18 { We have a big lead in development. Note: Nxd5 loses due to Bb5+. } { [%csl Ba4,Bb3,Ge3,Gd3,Gf3,Gg1,Rc8,Ra8,Re7,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Gd3b5,Bh2h3,Bf1e1,Bb1d2,Bd1b3,Bb3a4] }) (7... e5 { Black decides to counterattack our center. We just continue with our usual Bd3. } 8. Bd3 Qg4 9. h3! { Here we should immediately play h3 instead of d5, since we cannot allow e4; forking our knight and LSB. } 9... Qxg2 (9... Qh5 10. d5 Nd4 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. O-O $18) 10. Rh2 $18) (7... Bf5 { The best move, not allowing us to play Bd3. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rf5d3] } 8. Nbd2 { We continue developing. } 8... Qc2 9. d5 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 Na5 11. c5 $16 { [%csl Rb4,Ra5,Rb7][%cal Bf1b5,Bf3e5,Be1g1] }) 8. Bd3! { The queen has no retreating squares. Qe6 leads to a fork with d5. } { [%csl Re4] } 8... Bxf3 { The only way for Black not lose the queen is by counterattacking our queen. Now Black's queen gets an escape square. } { [%csl Rd1,Gh4][%cal Rf3d1,Be4h4] } 9. gxf3 { We simply recapture with the pawn. Remember, we want to avoid trading queens. } 9... Qh4 { The only safe retreat square. } { [%csl Gh4] } 10. d5! { Our plan now is to open the a4-e8 diagonal, allowing our queen to give the Black king checks. } { [%csl Re8,Rd7,Rc6,Ga4,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh4][%cal Gd1a4] } 10... Ne5 { Black saves his knight. } (10... Nb8 11. Qa4+ Nd7 12. c5) 11. Qa4+! { A critical move. Black's king is now extremely weak, with its only real defender being the e5-knight. All of Black's pieces are stuck on the kingside, far from forming any meaningful defense. Our attack focuses on the queenside, and the c5-c6 pawn push is inevitable. This will leave Black completely defenseless. } { [%csl Ge5,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh4][%cal Bc4c5,Bc5c6] } 11... Nd7 { Blocking the check. We now continue with our c5-c6 pawn storm idea. } { [%cal Bc4c5,Bc5c6] } (11... Kd8 12. Qa5+! { Forcing the king to a weaker square. After b6, we have Bxb6! due to the pin! } 12... Kc8 (12... Ke8 13. Qb5+ Nd7 { Now we transpose to our usual c5-c6 idea. } 14. c5 $18 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Bc5c6] }) 13. Bf5+ { We bring another piece to join the attack. } { [%csl Gf5] } 13... e6 14. dxe6 $18 { It's +4.5, Black's king is way too exposed, and his pieces are all to far from creating any defense. The only way to stop an immediate checkmate, is again sacrificing a ton of material. } { [%csl Ga5,Ge3,Gf5,Re5,Rc8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh4][%cal Be6e7,Be6f7] }) 12. c5 Nf6 { Black can't stop this idea, so Black just plays a developing move. It's hopeless already. } (12... e6 { It's important to note that if Black moves his e-pawn, we shouldn't immediately play c6, that would result in Black being able to defend. We have to pay another idea. } { [%cal Gh4d8] } 13. Bb5! { Adding pressure to d7. } { [%csl Rd7] } (13. c6?? { Doesn't have the same effect. } 13... bxc6 14. dxc6 Nc5 $17 { Black kicks our queen away, if we capture the knight, Black recaptures with his bishop and we have Qxf2 threats. } { [%csl Ra4,Gc5,Rf2][%cal Bf8c5,Rh4f2,Rc5f2] }) 13... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6d7] } (13... Qe7? 14. c6 bxc6 15. dxc6 $18 { Completely crushing position. } { [%csl Gb5,Gc6,Ga4,Ge3] }) 14. c6! { Now c6 works. You'll see why in a few moves. } 14... bxc6 (14... Bd6 15. cxd7+ Ke7 16. dxe6 a6) 15. dxc6 Ne5 (15... Nc5 { Previously, the queen was the one giving a check, now the bishop is, so we get to play c7. } { [%csl Ra4,Gb5][%cal Rc5a4] } 16. c7+ { [%csl Gb5] } 16... Nfd7 17. Bxd7+ Nxd7 18. Qc6 { [%csl Ra8][%cal Rc6a8] } 18... Rc8 19. Qb7 $18 { Black has to sacrifice a ton of material. GG. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Rb7c8] }) 16. c7+ { Same thing. } 16... Nfd7 17. Bxd7+ Nxd7 18. Qxa7 Rc8 19. Qb7 $18 { [%csl Rc8][%cal Rb7c8] }) 13. c6 bxc6 14. dxc6 { [%csl Rd7][%cal Rc6d7] } 14... Ne5 15. c7+ { [%csl Ga4,Re8][%cal Ga4e8] } 15... Nfd7 16. Qxa7! { The most stylish option! The rook can't capture because it must guard the c8 square to prevent our pawn from promoting. But it's already completely losing for Black, our c-pawn is much to far. The only way to stop it is to sacrifice a massive amount of material. } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Ra7a8,Gc7c8] } 16... Rxa7 (16... Nxd3+ { Black tries an in-between move, but simply winning a bishop won't be enough to stop the incoming checkmate. } 17. Kd2 Rc8 18. Qb7 $18 { Black is forced to sacrifice a ton of material. It's +4.1 } { [%csl Rc8,Rd3][%cal Rb7c8] }) 17. c8=R#! { Checkmate! A beautiful underpromotion mate! } { [%csl Re8,Rd8][%cal Rc8e8] } *


