6... Qd8?! { Here's another move that gets played occasionally, though it's a bit of an inaccuracy since it allows us expand our center with tempo on the knight. } 7. d5 { Black has 2 squares to choose from to retreat his knight. Going back to b8 is by far the most popular. But we'll look at both options. } { [%cal Rd5c6] } 7... Nb8 { b4 no longer has a defender. } { [%csl Rb4] } (7... Na5 8. a3 $140 $36 { Playing real Wing Gambit style. If Black captures we get the open a-file for the rook, and our pieces get opened up (Nc3 is possible, Ba3 at some point). } 8... b3 { Not giving White the benefits of an open a-file. } (8... bxa3 { There's a couple of good options here including Bxa3, c5, Ne5, but we'll cover Rxa3 since it is the least complicated imo. } 9. Rxa3 $140 { Opening up the rook, Qa4+ is a threat, winning the knight. } { [%csl Ra5,Ga3][%cal Bd1a4,Ya4e8,Ya4a5] } 9... b6 { Since the knight is trapped, Black protects it with his pawn. This also prepares to retreat the knight to b7. } { [%cal Gb6a5,Ba5b7] } (9... Bd7 { Another option, blocking the potential check. } 10. Ne5 { Threatening Nxd7, which Black cannot capture with the queen because the knight will be left hanging. Capturing with the king's a real pain. } { [%csl Rd7,Ya5][%cal Re5d7,Ya3a5] } 10... b6 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gb6a5] } 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. c5 { Black can't take. } 12... e6 13. Nc3 $140 $40 { Threatening a pin with Bb5. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Bf1b5,Yc3b5,Rb5e8] } 13... a6 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra6b5] } 14. d6 { Saving the c5 pawn and taking space from Black. There's no chance of that king castling. } { [%csl Rd6,Rc5][%cal Rd6e7] } 14... Nf6 15. Be3 Nc6 16. Rxa6 Rxa6 17. Bxa6 bxc5 18. Bxc5 $18 { [%csl Bg1,Re8,Rd7,Rc6,Rf8,Rf6,Rh8,Gb1][%cal Be1g1,Yc3b5,Yb5c7,Gd1b1,Gb1b8] }) 10. c5! { A dangerous pawn push! Black can't capture c5 because the knight would be hanging. Our idea here is ...Rxa5 bxa5 and followed by a powerful Bb5+ Black blocks with Bd7 and then c6! and Black can resign. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ba4a5,Rb6c5,Bf1b5] } 10... e6 { A hopeless developing move, there really isn't anything Black can do. We get the something similar with Nf6. } 11. Qa4+! { Bb5+ and Rxa5 work too, but this is most least complicated. Giving a check, and preparing for c6. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Ra4e8] } 11... Bd7 12. c6! { It's over at this point. Let's see why. } 12... Bc8 13. c7+! { Discovered check and attacking the queen! } { [%csl Bd8,Re8][%cal Ra4e8,Bc7d8] } 13... Qd7 { Saving the queen and blocking check but... } 14. Bb5 $18 { We win a ton of material. Just a quick note that just because I might go pretty deep in the study doesn't mean you should actually memorize 15+ move lines. I've included these to show some ideas and plans that might potentially arise in this opening. } { [%csl Re8,Rd7][%cal Ra4e8] }) 9. Be2 $10 { We continue to develop normally. The b-pawn will be won at some point, but it isn't really a priority, just continue developing. } { [%csl Bg1,Rb3][%cal Be1g1,Bb1d2,Rd2b3,Bc1g5] }) 8. Qa4+! { [%cal Ga4b4,Ga4e8] } 8... Bd7 9. Qxb4 { The material is equal now, but White is obviously better with much easier and more flexible development. All Black's pieces are still on the 8th rank. Shockingly, the most popular move here e6, which immediately loses due to Qxb7. Stockfish gives us a +0.6 advantage. } { [%csl Rb7,Ra8,Rb8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Bb2,Bc3,Bf4,Be3,Yg1,Ye2,Gb4,Gc4,Gd5][%cal Bc1b2,Bb1c3,Bc1f4,Bc1e3,Ye1g1,Yf1e2] } *


