{ Let's revisit this position. Black isn't forced to capture our knight, many higher rated players will see that it could potentially dangerous and instead go for a normal developing move. } { [%csl Gb1][%cal Ga1b1] }
8... e6 { This is the most popular option, Black opens up his DSB and prepares to develop it to b4. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rb4c3,Bf8b4] } 9. Bd2 $7 { Our knight was hanging this time, as we no longer have the d5 pawn push to create an attack (Black can simply capture it). So, we need to protect our knight. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd2c3] } 9... Bb4 { Black adds pressure on our knight. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Ra5c3,Bg8e7,Be8g8] } 10. Rxb4 $44 { The best option here is to sacrifice the exchange, but we'll get enough activity for compensation, it's still equal. } 10... Qxb4 $7 { The correct way to capture. } (10... Nxb4?? { Loses a piece by force. } 11. Nb5! { Opening up our dark-square bishop, pinning the knight and threatening a3, winning it. The queen is now also tied down to defending c7, preventing a fork. Meanwhile, Nd3+ is another threat. } { [%csl Gd2,Rd6,Rc7,Ra5,Rb4,Gb5][%cal Bb5d6,Bb5c7,Ya2a3] } 11... Bd7 $132 $40 { The only move to try to fight back, Black counterattacks our knight. } { [%cal Ga5b5,Gd7b5] } (11... a6 12. Nd6+ Ke7 13. Qb1 $18 { Same idea. } { [%csl Rb4,Rd6][%cal Rd2b4,Rb1b4,Rb4d6] }) 12. Nd6+! { Simply moving out of the attack with check. } 12... Ke7 { Attacking our knight, here we play an important move that's a common theme in these positions. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Re7d6] } (12... Kf8 13. Nc4 Qb5 14. Nce5 $18 { We win a piece in all lines. 3 pieces are attacked, Black cannot save all. } { [%csl Rd7,Rb5,Rb4][%cal Re5d7,Rf1b5,Rd2b4] }) (12... Kd8 13. Nxb7+ $18 { A deadly fork. } { [%csl Ra5,Rd8][%cal Rb7a5,Rb7d8] }) 13. Qb1! $18 { Leaving the knight hanging, but if Kxd6 we fork Black's king a queen with Bxb4+. Black cannot save his knight. } { [%csl Rb4,Rd6][%cal Rb1b4,Rd2b4] }) 11. d5! { Attacking the knight. We want to open up the position, and put our knight on the strong central d5-square, which also frees our dark-squared bishop and we'll be able to gain tempo by kicking the queen around. } { [%cal Rd5c6,Rd2b4,Bc3d5] } 11... exd5 (11... Nd4?? 12. Nb5! Nxf3+ 13. gxf3! { Very important! Qxf3, would allow Qb1 check. } 13... Qe7 (13... Qc5 14. a3 { [%csl Yd6][%cal Bd2b4,Yb5d6] }) 14. d6 Qd8 15. Nc7+) (11... Nce7 12. Nb5 $13 { [%csl Ba4][%cal Bd1a4,Bd2e3,Bf1c4,Bd5e6] }) 12. Nxd5 $40 $36 { Threatening both to take the queen and a king-rook fork on c7. Black is faced with another only-move. } { [%cal Rd2b4,Rd5c7] } 12... Qe4+! { Forced. Black brings his queen to safety with check, thus gaining time to do something about the Nc7+ fork on the next move. Our knight is attacked, } { [%csl Rc7,Re1,Rd5][%cal Ge4e1,Ge4d5] } (12... Qd6?? { Looks like it solves both of White's threats at first; the queen is safe and c7 is covered, but Black has missed one move... } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gd6c7] } 13. Bf4! $18 { The bishop cuts right through the queen to control the c7 square. Black can't prevent us from forking the king and rook on the next move. } { [%csl Rc7,Rd6][%cal Yf4c7,Gd5c7] }) 13. Be3! { Our knight was attacked, so we block the check while activating our queen to defend it. Ne3 would be a waste, since we're just deactivating the knight, which is our most active piece. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Yd1d5] } 13... Kf8! { There's isn't any piece to cover the c7 square, so Black prevents a fork. This is the best and most popular option. } { [%csl Bf8][%cal Be8f8] } 14. Ng5 $36 { There will be many different variations from here. Keep in mind that we're down an exchange, so our priority is to maximize the activity of our pieces and take advantage of Black's poorly placed queen. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rd5c7] } 14... Qe5 { Black has to be very careful; Qe8 allows a fork with Nc7 and Qg6 loses immediately to Bc5+. } (14... Qf5 15. g4 $36 { Yes, we're sacrificing a pawn, but we really want to activate our pieces as much as possible. The open g-file will be great for our rook. } { [%cal Bh1g1,Rg4f5] } 15... Qxg4 16. Be2! { No trading! } 16... Qf5 17. Bc5+ Nge7 18. Rg1 $44 { We're down 4 points in material, but our pieces are much more active than Black's. We have full compensation, Stockfish evaluates the position as equal. From here continue to play active and attack and avoid trading pieces, since that would lead to an endgame where we're down material. } { [%csl Gg1,Gc5,Gd5,Gg5,Rf8,Rh8,Rc8,Ra8,Re7,Rc6,Rf5,Ge2][%cal Bf2f4] }) 15. Bc4! { Activating the bishop and preparing to castle, getting the king out of the pin. } { [%cal Be1g1] } 15... Be6 16. f4! { Before castling, we can first hit the queen further gaining tempi. } { [%cal Rf4e5] } 16... Qd6 17. Ne4! { [%cal Re4d6] } 17... Qd8 18. Bc5+ Nge7 19. O-O $44 { We're down an exchange and a pawn, but we have full compensation. We control more space, all our pieces are on their most active squares, and our king is relatively safe. Black's pieces are all playing a passive role in the game, and they'll be the ones defending. Just remember to continue to play active, attack the king, and avoid trading pieces. } { [%csl Bf6,Rf5,Gg1,Yb3,Gf1,Gc4,Gc5,Gd5,Ge4,Rf8,Rh8,Rd8,Ra8,Re7,Rc6,Re6][%cal Bf5f6,Rf5e6,Rf4f5,Yd1b3] } *


