{ Congrats! You’ve just finished Section 1! 🎉 That was a lot of info, but this section was the most important since you’ll face most of the time and it contained the most double-edged, complicated lines.

💡 In my opinion, the best way to learn an opening is to play it in real games (and analyze them of course)! You’ll probably mess things up at first, but that’s normal. I recommend practicing in casual games against a sparring partner first to avoid tilting and getting frustrated. With experience, you’ll see huge success.

But if you’re like me and have no friends, you probably won’t always get the chance to drill this opening, since your opponents won’t always play the Sicilian. 😞

That’s why I use Noctie, a human-like AI that plays at your level and lets you choose and drill any opening you want. Check it out: https://go.noctie.ai/bosburp-2

🎯 Want to practice the Portsmouth Gambit? Try the custom repertoire made in Noctie here: https://go.noctie.ai/Portsmouth

Psst... Use discount code "BOSBURP50" at checkout for 50% off for 3 months. 😉

📖 Another great tool to build and reinforce your repertoire is ChessBook. It uses spaced repetition to help you review and improve your openings. Link your Lichess/Chess.com account, track your progress, and play through master games from your openings: https://chessbook.com/?ref=bosburp There's a free version available too.

Ok, let's see if you know the first few moves... }
1. e4! { Good! If you're enjoying the study, don’t forget to click the heart button under the h1-square! ❤
This saves the study to your favorites, so you can easily find it again anytime. Plus, it helps more people discover this study. Thanks for the support! 😊 } 1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4! cxb4 4. d4 e6 { 4...e6, the second most popular move and the top-engine move. But don't worry, the traps don't stop here! We'll look at this variation in-dept in the following chapters marked with 📗. } *


[Event "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...Nc6: 📗 5...exd5?!"]
[Date "2025.03.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...Nc6"]
[ChapterName "📗 5...exd5?!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/55CPbtmd/KXYkZnZn"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/1p1PP3/5N2/P1P2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.10"]
[UTCTime "11:04:23"]

{ There's 2 good options to go for here: 5. a3 and 5. d5. a3's great, it transposes to the Wing Gambit (1. e4 c5 2. b4, is one of the move orders, but there are many, it's also played often against the french: 1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4), so if you're into that, feel free to play that line.

However, we'll be looking into the latter, since it's incredibly successful and has quite straightforward ideas, definitely way less complicated than our previous section. Although, all magic comes with a price - if Black really studied this and knows exactly what to do, you get a slightly less comfortable position (we'll still cover that too tho). But it gets seen literally less than 3% of the time (and that’s not even considering if Black actually plays it correctly). So don't worry about that too much. I totally recommend d5 for all levels. }
5. d5! { Ripping the center open! } (5. a3 { Transposition to Wing Gambit: } 5... bxa3 6. c3 d5 7. e5 { Enjoy! }) 5... exd5? { Most popular, but really everything besides what we'll cover in chapter 15 is bad for Black. } 6. exd5 { Already White's winrate is at 62%, but we're used to that kind of numbers in the Porthsmouth. ;)
Black now has to decide what to do with his hanging knight. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rd5c6] } 6... Nce7?? { Accounts for 1/3 of all games. Black applies pressure on the d-pawn and prepares to reroute his knight to g6, but... we actually win on the spot now! } { [%csl Bg6][%cal Be7g6,Re7d5] } (6... Nb8 { Black retreats. Now you *could* play 7. d6 here, which has a 65% winrate. Again having the of idea of Qe2+. But I don't recommend it since we are already at the advantage here. We don't have to push for a fast win. If Black finds 7...Qf6 we lose our advantage. It's a lot more obvious here, because it attacks our rook and creates an escape square for the king on d8. } 7. Bc4 $32 { Instead we simply continue developing. Slow and steady wins the race! } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Be1g1] } 7... d6 8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1+ Be7 10. Qe2 $16 { Black's gonna have difficulties castling. We can develop easily here. } { [%csl Re7,Gc4,Rb4,Gg1,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Ge1,Ge2][%cal Re2e7,Bc1b2,Yb1d2] }) (6... Na5 { Again d6 is a thing, but I don't recommend it. We have a large enough advantage here. } 7. Bb2 $32 { A multipurpose move. Tying the DSB down to g7 and preventing Qf6. } { [%csl Rg7,Rf6] } 7... Nf6 (7... d6 8. a3 { Opening up the a-file. } 8... bxa3 9. Rxa3 $16 { [%csl Ga3,Gb2,Gb1,Gf3,Gd5,Ra5,Ra8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Bf1d3,Bd3b5,Be1g1] }) 8. d6 { Now d6 is fine because there isn't any Qf6. } 8... Qb6 9. Qe2+ Kd8 10. Ne5 $18) (6... Qf6! { The best move in this position, but Black really should've done this earlier. It doesn't have the same effect here. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Rf6a1] } 7. c3 { Saving the rook. } 7... bxc3 { From here on we got some pretty insane lines you'll probably never face, but I'll include them anyway. } (7... Ne5 { Saving the knight. } { [%cal Re5f3] } 8. Be2! { We don't want doubled pawns. } 8... Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3 bxc3 10. O-O c2 (10... Bd6 11. Qd3 $14 { [%csl Gd5,Gf3,Gd3][%cal Bf1e1,Rb1c3,Bg2g3,Bh2h4,Bc1g5] }) 11. Re1+! Be7 12. Qxc2 Qxa1 13. d6 $18 { Black's in huge trouble. } { [%cal Bb1c3] }) 8. dxc6! { Most of this is pretty forced. } 8... c2 { Double attack! } { [%cal Rf6a1,Rc2d1] } 9. Qxc2 Qxa1 { Oh no we lost the rook, but... } 10. Qe4+ { Fork! } { [%cal Rc6b7,Re4e8] } 10... Be7 11. cxb7 Rb8 12. bxc8=N! { You can promote to anything, but this is funniest imo. } 12... Rxc8 { [%cal Rc8c1] } 13. Ba3 $13 { Saving the bishop. If played correctly White's a bit better here with our two pieces for an exchange. We're the ones attacking, we've got very active pieces. } { [%csl Re7,Ge4,Gb1][%cal Ga3e7,Be1g1,Yf1c4,Yc4a6,Bf3e5] }) 7. d6! { Hitting the knight again! You'll see the idea soon enough. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Rd6e7] } 7... Nc6 { It doesn't matter where the knight goes, we'll always just play the same thing. } 8. Qe2+! { Now suddenly, White's plan unfolds. Black must block the check, but no matter which of the four pieces steps in, it has to land on e7, which our d pawn controls! } { [%csl Re8,Re7][%cal Yd6e7,Ge2e8] } 8... Be7 (8... Nge7 9. Bb2 $18 { Same thing, Black isn't saving his piece. }) 9. Bb2! { There's no hurry in taking e7. We can throw this zwischenzug in, attacking g7, forcing Black to play a weakening move. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Gb2g7] } 9... Nf6 10. dxe7 { Now we can take. } 10... Nxe7 (10... Qxe7 { We don't mind trading queens. We'll get a winning endgame. } 11. Bxf6! gxf6 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $18) 11. Bxf6! { Doubling Black's pawns. } 11... gxf6 $18 { We're up a piece for two pawns, but Black's position is a total trash; two sets of doubled pawns (one of them isolated), an isolated d-pawn, an unsafe king, and zero development. You should have no trouble winning the game. :) } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Re8,Rd8,Rh8,Rh7,Rd7,Rb4,Rb7,Rc8,Ra8] } *


