[UTCDate "2025.03.10"]
[UTCTime "11:04:23"]

5. d5! { We'll simply kick the knight way and expand our center. } 5... Ne5 (5... Nb8 { Extremely passive, but the game goes on. It's equal, but probably much easier to play as White with the controlled center and easy development. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd5][%cal Bc1b2,Bd1d4,Ba2a3] }) (5... Na5?! 6. a3 bxa3 7. Nxa3 { [%csl Ra5,Bg1,Ga1,Ga3][%cal Bf1b5,Bc1d2,Be1g1] }) 6. Nxe5! { We're fine trading, it doubles Black's e-pawns. The upcoming e5 pawn is an easy target that we can build initiative against. } 6... dxe5 { [%csl Re5] } 7. Bb2! { Attacking the weak e5-pawn. Black can only defend it with f6 or Qc7/d6, both which aren't attractive options. But most players can't resist the greed and will play them anyway. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gb2e5] } 7... f6?! { Most popular option. This move makes development much harder for Black. } { [%csl Rf6,Re5,Re6,Rf7][%cal Yg8f6,Ye7e6] } 8. c3 { Opening up the queen and we're planning to place our knight on c3. } { [%cal Yd1a4,Gb1c3] } (8. Bc4 Nh6 9. O-O Nf7 10. a3 bxa3 11. Bxa3) 8... bxc3 9. Nxc3 a6 { Preventing any Bb5+ trouble. } (9... e6? 10. Bb5+! { Developing with tempo. } { [%cal Be1g1] } 10... Bd7 11. Qa4! { Lining up with the bishop. } { [%cal Rd5e6] } 11... Bxb5 (11... a6 { Attacking our bishop, but we don't mind we'll just counterattack Black's. } 12. dxe6 { [%cal Re6d7] } 12... axb5 13. exd7+ { If the queen takes, the rook is left hanging. } 13... Kf7 14. Qxb5 $18 { [%csl Rf7,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rd8][%cal Be1g1,Ba1d1,Bc3d5] }) 12. Nxb5 $18 { Black's king is very unsafe and it won't be castling anytime soon. Each piece is still on the back rank. The only way to survive our discovered checks is actually for the king to run to g6, which shows how bad this is for Black. } { [%csl Ga4,Gb5,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Ra8][%cal Re8f7,Bb5c7,Bb5d6,Ba1d1,Rd5e6] }) (9... Bd7 10. Qb3 $16 { Easy development. } { [%csl Rb7,Re8][%cal Bf1b5,Ba1c1,Be1g1] }) (9... Nh6 10. Qb3 $14 { [%csl Gb3,Gc3,Re8,Rf8,Rc8][%cal Bb2a3,Bc3a4,Ba1c1,Bf1e2,Be1g1] }) 10. Qb3! $16 { Putting pressure on b7, tying down the LSB. It's clear that Black has serious development problems; both bishops don't have good squares to go, and castling won’t be easy. Meanwhile, we enjoy a solid space advantage and easy development. Our plan is simple: Be2, castle, and then Rd1/Rc1 to get some play on the queenside. Stockfish evaluates this as +1. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf8,Rc8,Rg8,Re7,Re8,Bg1][%cal Bf1e2,Be1g1,Yc8b7,Ba1c1,Bc1d1,Bc3a4] } *


