7... Qc7 { It looks like this move defends e5, and Black didn’t have to make a weakening move, but we can win the pawn by force. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gc7e5] } (7... Qd6?! { This actually just transposes to the same line. } 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Bxe5 $16 { [%csl Ge5,Gd5,Ge4][%cal Be1g1,Bb1d2] }) 8. Bb5+! { [%csl Re8][%cal Gb5e8] } 8... Bd7 (8... Kd8? { Another way to save the pawn, but again with the expense of losing castling rights. The king will most likely stay in the center for a long time. } 9. a3 { A classic idea we've seen more often in the study. +1.7. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ba3b4,Bc2c4,Bb1a3,Be1g1] }) 9. Bxd7+ { And now, unless Black wants to bring the king up, the queen is forced to abandon her post, leaving e5 hanging. } 9... Qxd7 (9... Kxd7? { The pawn stays protected, but Black loses castling rights, and the king is awkwardly misplaced. This is much worse than giving up the pawn. } 10. O-O $16 { +1.6 with a 65% winrate. } { [%csl Rf8,Rh8,Rg8,Rd7,Gg1][%cal Ba2a3,Bc2c3,Bb1d2,Ba1c1] }) 10. Bxe5 $16 { We have a space advantage, easy castling, smooth development, and full control of the center while Black has absolutely nothing. } { [%csl Bg1,Ge4,Gd5,Rb4,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Ra8,Rd7][%cal Be1g1,Bb1d2] } *


