7... Nf6! { The best move for Black. Counterattacking our e4-pawn. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] } 8. Bxe5 { We can take the pawn. } (8. f4 { Another good move, we'll play Elephant Gambit style. } { [%cal Rf4e5] } 8... exf4 (8... Nxe4 9. fxe5 $13 { [%csl Re4,Gc6,Gd6,Ge6,Gf6,Gb2][%cal Ge5f6,Ge5d6,Gd5e6,Gd5c6] }) 9. e5 { I'll be stopping here since it's to much theory for something not really played. Feel free to analyze further. } { [%cal Re5f6] }) 8... Nxe4 9. Qd4 { Hitting the knight and g7. } { [%csl Rg7,Re4][%cal Gd4e4,Gd4g7] } 9... Nf6 10. a3! { Our classic idea. We want to develop the knight. } 10... Nxd5?? { Looks like a free pawn, but... } (10... Qxd5?? 11. Bxf6 Qxd4 12. Bxd4 $18) (10... bxa3 11. Nxa3) (10... Qb6! { The best move, offering a queen trade to move to an endgame. } 11. axb4 { We take the free pawn and allow the queen trade, otherwise we'll end up in a much worst position. } 11... Qxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxd5 13. c3 $10 { We move to an endgame that's relatively equal. } { [%csl Ra7][%cal Bf1c4,Be1g1,Bb1d2] }) 11. Bb5+! { Forcing Black to block the queen from protecting the knight. } { [%csl Rd7] } 11... Bd7 12. Qxd5 $18 { Free piece! } *


