3... e6?! { Not exactly a rare sideline, since this gets played quite often. Black declines our gambit, hoping to avoid any tricky traps, but you can’t escape the Portsmouth Gambit! This is very comfortable for White to play against. We’ll be playing almost exactly the same style as in the Wing Gambit, except we won't even be down a pawn! } 4. bxc5! { We just take this, preparing to play d4. } { [%cal Bd2d4] } 4... Bxc5 5. d4! { Grabbing the center with tempo. If you've played the Wing Gambit before, you'll know what to do here. It's usually c3-d5-Bd3. } { [%cal Rd4c5] } 5... Bb6 (5... Bb4+? { We want to play c3 anyway, so now we get to do it with tempo. } 6. c3 $16 { [%cal Rc3b4,Be4e5,Bf1d3] }) (5... Be7 6. c3 { Same idea really. } 6... d5 7. e5 f6 8. Bd3 $16 { Very comfortable position. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gc3,Rg8,Re7,Re8][%cal Be1g1,Bb1d2] }) 6. c3 { Supporting the d4-pawn. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3][%cal Gc3d4,Bd1a4] } 6... d5 (6... Nf6 7. e5 { Just following our plan. } { [%cal Re5f6] } 7... Nd5 8. Bd3 O-O (8... Ba5 { Double attacking our c pawn. We can actually just focus on development by getting the king to safety. } { [%csl Rc3] } 9. O-O! Nxc3 10. Nxc3 Bxc3 11. Rb1 Bxd4 (11... Nxd4 12. Ng5 $16 { We'll get a good attack on the king. } { [%cal Bg5e4,Bc1a3,Bd1h5,Bf2f4] }) 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qg4 $18 { It's +5. We get an unstoppable attack on the king. Non of Black's pieces are in the correct state to defend. } { [%csl Rg7,Rd4,Gd3][%cal Rg4g7,Rg4d4,Bc1a3] }) 9. Bxh7+ $18 { Again a Greek Gift! }) (6... Nge7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. e5 $16 { [%csl Gd3,Gf3,Gd1][%cal Be1g1] }) (6... d6 { Preventing any d5. We'll just have to develop differently. } 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O { A comfortable position. Usually the DSB is more happy on a3 instead of g5, where it will easily get kicked. } { [%csl Gg1][%cal Bc1a3,Bb1d2,Bf1e1] }) 7. e5 { Pawn chain complete! } { [%csl Yc3,Yd4,Ye5][%cal Yc3d4,Yd4e5] } 7... Nge7 { We're still going over all the most popular moves here. } 8. Bd3 O-O?? { An incredibly popular blunder! We win on the spot now. I think you guess what our next move is. ;) } 9. Bxh7+! { The Greek Gift! I’ve actually used this exact position in my "Sacrifice like a PRO" study! There, I explained this tactic in depth, so if you haven’t checked it out yet, feel free to do so when you have time: https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/YseTtApC.
Since this is an opening study and not focused on tactics, I won’t be explaining the following moves here, you probably already recognize this theme. } 9... Kxh7 (9... Kh8 10. Ng5! { [%cal Rd1h5] } 10... g6 { [%cal Rg6h5,Gh2h4] } 11. Qf3! { [%cal Bf3f6,Bf3h3] } 11... Nf5 { [%csl Rf6] } 12. Bxg6! { [%cal Rf3h3] } 12... fxg6 13. Qh3+ Kg7 14. Qh7#) 10. Ng5+! { [%csl Rh7][%cal Bd1h5,Gg5h7] } 10... Kg6 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Bh2h4,Bh4h5] } (10... Kg8 11. Qh5 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rh5h7] } 11... Re8 { [%cal Bg8f8] } 12. Qh7+ Kf8 $7 13. Ba3! { Pinning the knight, not allowing Nf8 after Qh8+. } { [%csl Rf8,Re7,Rh8][%cal Ra3f8,Rh7h8] } 13... Nb4 { Checkmate is unstoppable. Black can only delay it. } 14. Bxb4 Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qd6 16. Bxd6 a5 17. Qh8#) (10... Kh6 11. Qg4 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Rg4h4] } 11... g6 12. Qh4+ Kg7 13. Qh7#) 11. h4! { [%csl Rh5,Rh7][%cal Bh4h5] } 11... f5 12. h5+! Kh6 $7 13. Nxe6+ { Discovered check! White wins the queen and will have no trouble winning the game. } { [%cal Rc1h6,Re6d8] } *


