{ Next we have another rather important line that arises from Nxb4. }
3... Nxb4 4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd8?? { Quite a popular choice, actually. We've already looked at Qa5, which transposes into our beloved lines, but here Black retreats the queen back to d8 instead. However, this is a huge blunder, Stockfish already gives +2.5! This move allows us to push our d-pawn further. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rd4d5] } 9. d5 { Kicking the knight away. } { [%cal Rd5c6] } 9... Nb8 { Next we follow an important move order. } (9... Nb4? 10. Qa4+ $18 { A fork! } { [%csl Rb4,Re8][%cal Ra4b4,Ra4e8] }) (9... Na5? { You could play Qa4+ to win a piece, but we have something even better. } 10. Bb5+! Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Ne5 { Forcing the queen off the diagonal. } 12... Qd6 { Wherever the queen goes, we always have Qa4+. } (12... Qc7 13. Qa4+ Kd8 14. Nxf7+ Kc8 15. Qe8+ Qd8 16. Qxd8#) (12... Qf5 13. Qa4+ Kd8 14. Qxa5+ b6 15. Nc6+ Ke8 16. Qa4 $18) 13. Qa4+ Kd8 14. Nxf7+ { [%csl Rd6,Rd8][%cal Rf7d6,Rf7d8] }) 10. Bb5+! { Developing with tempo! Preparing to castle. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 10... Bd7 11. O-O! { Not only do we bring our king to safety, but we’re also preparing to place our rook on the e-file as soon as possible, where it will be an absolute monster as you will see soon. } { [%cal Bf1e1,Re1e8] } 11... Nf6 { Black cannot move the e pawn, since we will capture it, forcing Black to recapture with the f-pawn which leads to an ugly isolated e pawn and light-square weakness. So, instead Black plays the most obvious developing move. } { [%cal Re7e6] } (11... a6 { Here we don't play Qa4 since we a haven't set our rook and DSB in the right position yet. } 12. Bd3 { Simply retreating, we already have the advantage here with a huge lead in development. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc3,Gd3] } (12. Qa4 Bxb5 13. Nxb5 Nd7 14. Nc3 $16 { Black will be able to castle in time. White is still better here tho. } { [%cal Be7e6,Bg8f6,Bf8e7,Be8g8,Bb7b5] }) 12... Nf6 13. Re1 g6 14. Ba3 e6 { Now Black can play e6, because after dxe6 Black recaptures with the LSB since it's no longer pinned. } 15. Bb2! $18 { We have a wonderful position. } { [%csl Gf3,Ge1,Gd3,Gc3,Gb2][%cal Bc3e4] }) (11... Bxb5 12. Nxb5 a6 (12... Nf6?? 13. Qa4! { [%cal Ra4e8] } 13... Nbd7 14. Re1 { Pinning the e pawn threatening a smothered mate. } { [%cal Rb5d6] } 14... Qb8 15. Bf4 $18 { [%cal Rb5c7,Rf4c7] }) 13. Nc3 Nf6 14. Re1 g6 15. Ba3 $18 { [%csl Re7,Ge1,Ga3] }) 12. Re1! { Pinning the e-pawn. This will prove immensely strong very soon. } { [%csl Re8,Re7][%cal Re1e8] } 12... g6 { Played pretty much every time, or a move order variation from it. It's because Black really doesn't have any way to develop. The e-pawn can't move, the b8-knight has no place to go, and the king is stuck. So, Black tries to get rid of all the problems by castling as soon as possible. } { [%csl Bg7,Bg8][%cal Bf8g7,Be8g8] } (12... a6 13. Qa4! { I like Qa4 a lot here. Keeping the pressure whilst pinning the a pawn. } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Ra4a8] } 13... g6 (13... Bxb5 14. Nxb5 $18 { [%cal Rb5c7,Rb5d6] }) 14. Ba3 { And we get the same idea as in the main line. Black can't do anything. It's a zugzwang. } { [%csl Re7,Rf6][%cal Ra3e7,Ba4d4,Bd4f6] } 14... Bxb5 { The most popular move. I've faced this several times. } (14... axb5 15. Qxa8 { Still Black's in a zugzwang. It's +4.4. } { [%csl Ga3,Gc3,Ge1,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Rd7,Rb8,Rf6,Rh8][%cal Ra8b7] }) 15. Nxb5 { Dangerous discovered check threats. } { [%cal Rb5c7,Rb5d6] } 15... Nbd7 { Most popular, covering the king, but... } 16. Nd6# { Smothered mate! } { [%csl Re8][%cal Gd6e8] }) 13. Ba3! { We won't allow that to happen of course! Now the bishop is tied down. Black's in a bit of a zugzwang, he has no moves. } { [%csl Re7] } 13... a6 { The only move that seems to do something. } 14. Qd4! { We'll just ignore it. Counterattacking the knight. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Rd4f6] } 14... axb5 (14... Bxb5 15. Qxf6 Rg8 16. Ng5 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rg5f7] } 16... Rg7 17. Bxe7 Bxe7 18. Qxg7 { It's +10. The king will get checkmated very soon. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rg7f7,Rd5d6,Ra1d1,Rg5f7] }) (14... e6 15. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 16. dxe6 $18 { Black's position collapses. }) 15. Qxf6 { [%csl Rh8][%cal Rf6h8] } 15... Rg8 (15... Rxa3 16. Qxh8 { [%csl Rd8,Re8,Rd7,Rb8,Ra3,Yf8,Yf6,Gd6][%cal Bf3g5,Bg5h7,Bd5d6,Gc3e4,Yh7f8,Yh7f6,Ge4d6] }) 16. Ng5 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rg5f7] } 16... Rg7 17. Bxe7 Bxe7 18. Qxg7 $18 { There's too many threats. Mate will follow very soon. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rg7f7,Rd5d6,Rg5f7,Rg7g8] } *


