[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.19"]
[UTCTime "09:47:28"]

3... Nxb4 4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 e6 { We have a position that looks similar to the one in section 2. Because of that, many players instinctively go for 7. d5, thinking it follows the same idea. But there is a crucial difference here, which is that we don't have a c-pawn. This means Black can play Qf6, attacking our trapped rook, and we have no proper compensation whatsoever. If Black doesn't find 7...Qf6, and falls for a trap, great!, but it's not worth the risk. So don't play 7. d5 here. } 7. Bd3! { Instead we play this perfectly fine move that scores a 54% winrate! Simply developing, getting the king out of the center as soon as possible. We just follow standard development plans now. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } (7. d5?? Qf6! $19 { [%csl Ra1] }) 7... Bb4+ { The most popular move, developing with tempo. } (7... d5 8. e5 Bb4+ 9. Nbd2 { The game continues. We have have a very Wing Gambit-like position. We have a lead in development, a space advantage, and an open b-file for the rook. Enough compensation for the pawn. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1,Ba1b1] }) (7... Nf6 { You don't want to play e5 here, since that creates a nice outpost for the knight on d5, we won't be able to kick it away anytime soon. } 8. O-O $10 { [%csl Ge4,Gd4,Gd3,Gg1,Gf3] }) 8. Bd2! { We simply block the check. } 8... Bxd2+ (8... Qa5 9. O-O Bxd2 10. Nbxd2 Nge7?? { Very common in these type of position. But a blunder here. } (10... Nf6?? 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nc4 { The same idea. } { [%csl Rd6,Ra5][%cal Gc4d6,Gc4a5] }) (10... d5 11. Rc1 $10 { Just play chess now! You can't always get a winning position immediately. We got a nice equal game. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Be4d5,Bd3b5,Bd1b3] }) 11. Nc4! { Hitting the queen and threatening Nd6+, which makes the king lose castling rights. } { [%csl Rd6,Ra5][%cal Gc4d6,Gc4a5] } 11... Qc7 12. e5 { Simply controlling the d6 square. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge5d6,Rc4d6] } 12... O-O?? { The king castles to avoid Nd6+, but... } (12... Kf8 { Avoids Nd6+, but now the king is very unsafely placed here. } 13. Ng5 $18 { We have a strong attacking position. } { [%csl Gd3,Gc4,Gg5,Rf8,Rc8][%cal Rg5h7,Bd1f3,Bc4d6] }) 13. Bxh7+ $18 { We win the game with a Greek Gift again! If you don't know how to continue from here, I have section dedicated to this sacrifice in my "Sacrifice like a Pro" course. }) 9. Nbxd2 Nge7 { Black wants to castle on the next move. } { [%cal Be8g8] } (9... Nf6 10. e5 Nd5 11. O-O $10 { It's a rather equal game. But this position has only been reached a dozen of times. } { [%csl Rd6,Rc8][%cal Bd2e4,Ba1c1,Bd1b3] }) 10. e5! { Setting up a nice trap. } 10... O-O?? (10... d5! { Don't en-passant here, we want to keep our locked center. Opening it would help Black's development. } 11. O-O { The game goes on. }) 11. Bxh7+!! $16 { A Greek Gift! If you don't know how to continue from here, I have section dedicated to this sacrifice in my "Sacrifice like a Pro" course. White is better. } *


