[Event "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games: 🌱 Carlsen - Karjakin🌱"]
[Date "2024.12.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games"]
[ChapterName "🌱 Carlsen - Karjakin🌱"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Bu4LEk6w/Ad0qTh3e"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2R5/4bppk/1p1p4/5R1P/4PQ2/5P2/r4q1P/7K w - - 5 50"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.12.17"]
[UTCTime "05:44:02"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Let's start with this very famous position you might recognize. It's from the 2016 World Championship between Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin. This is the second game of the tiebreaks, and if Magnus Carlsen wins this game, he retains his World Champion title.

The position looks scary for Carlsen, Karjakin is threatening multiple mate-in-ones. However, there is only one move that saves the game and even wins for White. All other moves result in Black delivering a checkmate.

Can you find the winning move that Carlsen played? } { [%csl Rh1,Re1,Rf1,Rg2][%cal Gf2g2,Gf2f1,Gf2e1] }
50. Qh6+!! { Yes!! Sacrificing the queen on an empty square. The queen can be captured in two different ways, but both lead to a mate in one. Kxh6 allows White to play Rh8#, and gxh6 removes the king’s only cover and White plays Rxf7# to finish the game. Karjakin immediately resigned when the move was played on the board. Magnus Carlsen had just kept his title as World Chess Champion. } 50... gxh6 { The final touch! } { [%csl Rf7] } 51. Rxf7# { [%csl Rh7,Rh6,Yg6,Bh8,Bg8,Gg7][%cal Gf7h7,Yh5g6,Bc8h8] } *


