[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This one’s a bit easier, you probably recognize this theme. }
15. Qxe5+! { Yes! Sacrificing the queen to open a dark-squared diagonal (either h4-d8 or a3-f8), allowing our dark-squared bishop to deliver a check. } { [%cal Be3g5,Be3c5] } 15... fxe5 { dxe5 opens the a3-f8 diagonal, allowing Bc5#. } 16. Bg5#! { The two bishops and d-pawn all work beautifully together to checkmate the king! Congrats! You completed this puzzle! } { [%csl Rd8,Re7,Ye8,Yf7,Be6,Gf6,Rd6,Rd7,Rf8][%cal Yg6e8,Gg5d8,Bd5e6] } *


[Event "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games: 🌱 Neugebauer -  Degenkolbe 🌱"]
[Date "2024.12.17"]
[White "Neugebauer, H."]
[Black "Degenkolbe, U."]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games"]
[ChapterName "🌱 Neugebauer -  Degenkolbe 🌱"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Bu4LEk6w/lp4M2Cz0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1r5/1p2Qppk/4R2p/4pN2/4q3/2P5/PP3n1P/2K4R w - - 1 27"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.12.17"]
[UTCTime "05:44:02"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this position, it looks like White is in trouble again. The knight is under attack, the h1-rook is attacked, and Black’s queen and knight are swarming White’s king. Can you find the only winning move? From the previous examples, you may have noticed that we often play very forcing moves; either to drive the king to a specific square, break open its cover, or force Black to take away crucial escape squares } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Re4h1,Rf2d3] }
27. Rxh6+! { Yes! If Black plays gxh6 the king's cover is gone and Qxf7-Qg7# is checkmate. } { [%csl Gf7,Rh6][%cal Ge7f7,Rg7h6] } 27... Kg8 { But Black doesn’t take the rook! The king instead retreats behind his pawns. Now three of our pieces are hanging. Can you find the only winning move? } { [%csl Rf5,Rh6,Rh1][%cal Re4f5,Rg7h6,Re4h1] } 28. Qf8+!! { Yes! After Kxf8, the king is placed on a bad square, no longer controlling h8, allowing White to deliver a beautiful back-rank checkmate with Rh8#. If Black plays Rxf8, we play... } 28... Rxf8 29. Ne7#! { A beautiful Anastasia's Mate! } { [%csl Gh8,Gh7,Rg7,Rf7,Rf8,Bg8][%cal Gh6h8,Be7g8] } *


[Event "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games: 🌱 Tal - NN 🌱"]
[Date "2024.12.17"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "NN"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games"]
[ChapterName "🌱 Tal - NN 🌱"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Bu4LEk6w/FxFKD0Hx"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1b1n2pp/pq2p3/1p2P1B1/6Q1/2N5/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w kq - 2 14"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.12.17"]
[UTCTime "05:44:02"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This position is from another famous game, played by Mikhail Tal in a simul. The game is nicknamed "Trick or Treat". Black is currently up a knight, but Tal’s pieces are so much more active.

Can you find a way to take advantage of Black’s king in the center and passive pieces?

I’ve actually fully annotated this game in one of my previous studies. Feel free to check it out later if you want: https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/sLG4MH4d } { [%csl Re6,Gg4,Gg5,Gd1,Re8] }
14. Rd6! { Yes! Attacking both the queen and the e6 pawn is undefended. If Black doesn't take the rook, Qxe6-Qxe7# is checkmate. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gd6b6,Yg4e6,Bd6e6] } 14... Bxd6 { Black takes the rook, but now the e6-pawn remains undefended. } { [%csl Re6] } 15. Qxe6+! { The king's getting in a checkmating-net. } 15... Kf8 { The king's trapped, but there aren't more pieces that can join the attack. What's a forcing way to bring another piece to action? } { [%csl Rg8,Rf7,Re7,Re8][%cal Ge6e8,Ge6g8] } 16. Bc4! { Yes! Freeing the f1 square for the h1 rook, allowing it to join the assault on Black's king. While moving the bishop anywhere would be winning, going for Bc4 threatens an immediate checkmate with Qf7#, thus gaining a tempo, ending the game a bit sooner! :) } { [%csl Rf1,Gf7][%cal Bh1f1,Rc4f7] } (16. exd6 { Still wins, but slower and less satisfying. It's a bit unnecessary, White can just continue attacking. }) 16... bxc4 { [%csl Gf1][%cal Gh1f1] } 17. Rf1+! { Another piece has joined the attack! } { [%csl Gf1,Ge6,Gg5] } 17... Nf6 { Black can only block the check. There are multiple ways to win here, but can you find the quickest (and most beautiful) option? } 18. Rxf6+! { THE ROOOK! Sacrificing yet another piece to finish in style! } (18. exf6?? { Completely throws the game away! ...Bf4+ is a discovered attack! Then Black wins our queen and we no longer have any mating-net around the king. } 18... Bf4+!! { A discovered attack! Black wins our queen on the next move and we no longer have any mating-net around the king. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Rb6e6] }) 18... gxf6 $7 { Now the h6-f8 diagonal has been opened. Finish the game! } { [%csl Rg7,Rh6,Rf8] } 19. Bh6#! { The queen and bishop deliver a stunning criss-cross checkmate. An absolutely magnificent miniature! White is literally down 11 points in material!! } { [%csl Ye8,Ye7,Yg8,Yf7,Rf8,Rg7,Rb8,Ra8,Rb7,Rh8,Rb6,Rd6][%cal Ye6e8,Ye6g8,Rh6f8] } *


