[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This puzzle is from an online blitz game between Luis Paulo Supi and the former World Champion Magnus Carlsen. It may not look like it, but White has a forced mate here. Can you find the move that defeated Carlsen? }
1. Qc6!! { White sacrifices the queen!! This takes away Black’s escape squares, preparing to follow-up with Ra8#. } { [%csl Rd7,Rb7][%cal Rc6d7,Rc6b7,Gb5c6,Ba2a8] } 1... bxc6 2. bxc6 { Ra8# is unstoppable, Black can only delay it for a few moves. } { [%csl Rd7,Rb7,Ga8][%cal Rc6d7,Rc6b7,Ga2a8] } 2... Qb5 { [%csl Gb8][%cal Gb5b8] } 3. cxb5 Ba3 4. Rxa3 d3 5. Ra8#! { A brilliant checkmate! } { [%csl Gd8,Gc8,Gb8,Rb7,Rd7,Rc7][%cal Ga8d8,Rc6b7,Rc6d7] } *


[Event "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games: 🌀 Tal - Gulko 🌀"]
[Date "2024.12.17"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Boris Gulko"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games"]
[ChapterName "🌀 Tal - Gulko 🌀"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Bu4LEk6w/sgKTW5tA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/1p2b1pp/p4p2/3NQ3/1P1pP1B1/8/2PK3P/3R2R1 w kq - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.12.17"]
[UTCTime "05:44:02"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This position is from another game from Mikhail Tal. Gulko has just played f6 attacking White's queen, but this is a mistake. Can you see why?

I've also fully annotated this game in one of my previous studies. Feel free to check it out later if you want: https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/Ajz9Lmh7 } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Gf7f6] }
21. Bh5+! { Yes! Tal doesn't retreat from Black's attack, he instead counterattacks! } 21... Kf8 { The king has to move out of the check. g6 allows Nxf6+ (making use of the pin) which is completely winning. But now you have to find the correct follow up. :) } { [%csl Re5] } (21... g6 22. Nxf6+ Kf8) 22. Rxg7!! { Yes! The queen and rook are hanging at the same time! But taking one piece, gives the other piece the time to give a mating attack to the king. } { [%csl Rg7,Re5] } 22... fxe5 { After 3...Kxg7 there's 4. Rg1+ Kf8 5. Qg3 doubling on the g-file. Checkmate follows soon from there. In the game Gulko took the queen. How do you get a checkmate from here? } (22... Kxg7 23. Rg1+ Kf8 24. Qg3) 23. Rf7+! { Yes! Don’t take the hanging bishop right away! Every move needs to be forcing. First, we force the king onto a square where we can capture the bishop with check. Taking it immediately would give Black time to get a potential counterattack. } 23... Ke8 { After Kg8, we play Nxe7+. } 24. Rxe7+! { Double check! } { [%csl Ye7][%cal Rh5e8,Be7e8,Yd5e7] } 24... Kf8 $7 25. Rf1+! { We need all the pieces we can gather to deliver checkmate here! } 25... Kg8 { How do you finish it off? } { [%csl Rg7,Rh8,Rh7,Yf8,Yf7,Gh5,Ge7,Gd5,Gf1][%cal Re7g7,Yf1f8] } 26. Nf6+! (26. Rff7! { Also fine. It is 1 move longer tho. This was the move Tal played in the game. Can you find the quickest checkmate? } 26... Qd6 27. Re8+ Qf8 28. Rexf8#) 26... Kf8 27. Rf7#! { Yes, checkmate! All our pieces worked together to deliver the beautiful sight. :) } { [%csl Gf7,Gf6,Gh5,Gf1,Rd8,Rc8,Ra8,Rh8] } *


[Event "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games: 🌀 Podzerov - Kuntzevic 🌀"]
[Date "1971"]
[White "Podzerov"]
[Black "Kuntzevic"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games"]
[ChapterName "🌀 Podzerov - Kuntzevic 🌀"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Bu4LEk6w/zbQ3iAgM"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r3r2k/p2n1Qbp/b7/q2NNp2/1pB5/8/P4PPP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ All our minor pieces and queen are targeting the king, while Black’s pieces are passive and far away. Can you find the winning sequence? } { [%csl Ge5,Gd5,Gc4,Gf7,Rh8,Ra5,Ra6,Rd7,Ra8] }
1. Qg8+!! { Yes! White sacrifices the queen to bring the king to g8, preparing for a brilliant double discovered check by moving the d5 knight. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Bd5e7,Bd5f6,Yc4g8] } 1... Kxg8 { Did you see the mate if Black captures with the rook instead? :) } 2. Ne7+! { Delivering a double check! If White simply moved the knight anywhere, Black could respond with Bxc4, stopping the attack. } { [%csl Rg8][%cal Be7g8,Gc4g8] } (2. Nf6+! { Also works, but not as visually stunning. } 2... Kf8 3. Nxh7+ Ke7 4. Rxd7#) 2... Kf8 { Kh8-Nf7#. } { [%csl Re8,Rg7,Gg8,Gf7][%cal Gc4g8,Rf8e7] } 3. N5g6+ { N7g6+ leads to the same result, but Lichess only accepts one correct move. If you found that, you got it right! } { [%cal Ge7g6] } 3... hxg6 { Now for the final blow! :D } 4. Nxg6# { The knight and bishop work beautifully together to deliver this stunning checkmate, despite being down 11 points in material! :) } { [%csl Bf8,Be7,Rg8,Rf7,Ye8,Yg7][%cal Bg6f8,Bg6e7,Rc4g8] } *


[Event "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games: 🌀 Reefschlaeger -  Astengo 🌀"]
[Date "2024.12.17"]
[White "Helmut Reefschlaeger"]
[Black "Corrado Astengo"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "INSANE Checkmates From Master Games"]
