[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2r1k1r1/4bpq1/p3p3/1p1pNP1p/Q4p2/2N5/P1R1BP1P/1R3K2 w - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.12.17"]
[UTCTime "05:44:02"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Things might look very scary for White, Black has just played b5, attacking White's queen. The knight on e5 is hanging, and Qg1# is a major threat. However, there's only one move that wins! Can you find it? } { [%csl Rg1,Rb5,Re5][%cal Gb7b5,Rb5a4,Bg7e5,Bg7g1] }
24. Bxb5+! { Yes! A forcing move, White fully opens the a4-e8 diagonal for the queen. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Rb5e8] } 24... axb5 25. Qxb5+ { [%csl Gb5] } 25... Kf8 { The queen and the e5 knight are the only pieces close enough to the king to make an impact. Can you figure out how they can work together to deliver checkmate? } { [%csl Rg8,Rg7,Rf7,Re7,Ge5,Gb5] } 26. Nd7+! { Forcing the king to e8, directly into the diagonal of our queen. } { [%cal Rf8e8,Bb5e8] } 26... Ke8 27. Nf6+ { Double check! } { [%cal Rf6e8,Rb5e8] } 27... Kf8 28. Qe8+! { Yes! Sacrificing the queen to surround the king with his own pieces. } 28... Rxe8 { The final blow! :) } 29. Nd7# { A beautiful smothered mate! Because every move we played was a forcing check, Black never had the time to play Qg1. } { [%csl Rf8,Ye8,Ye7,Yf7,Yg7,Yg8][%cal Rd7f8] } *


