{ Here’s another position where only one move wins. It’s the endgame, and Black is up an exchange, but the rook and queen aren’t very actively placed.

Can you find the way to win? } { [%csl Rc8,Rh8,Gh4,Gf3,Gg2] }
2. Qc4+! { Yes! The first move of the winning sequence, giving a check to the king while also attacking the bishop, with a great idea in mind that I won’t reveal just yet. :) } { [%csl Rc6,Ra6][%cal Rc4a6,Rc4c6] } 2... Kb7 { The only move that saves the LSB. } { [%cal Gb7c6] } 3. Qxc6+!! { Yes! Preparing to expose the king into the diagonal of our bishop. } { [%cal Bf3e5,Bf3d4] } 3... Kxc6 4. Ne5+! { We don't allow Black's king to escape to the second rank. The only option is to go forward. } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Re5d7] } 4... Kc5 $7 5. Nd3+! { Again the king must go forward. } { [%csl Yc6,Yd5,Bc5,Bb4,Rb5][%cal Yg2c6,Bd3c5,Bd3b4,Ra4b5] } 5... Kd4 $7 { Now we've reached a critical moment. How does White continue? } 6. Kd2!! { We want to deliver checkmate with c3, so we bring the king over to defend the square and control e3. Even with Black’s extra 9 points in material, he can’t stop c3#. :) } { [%csl Rc3,Be3][%cal Rc2c3,Gd2c3,Bd2e3] } 6... Qf5 { It doesn't matter what Black does. } 7. c3# { [%csl Ye4,Yd5,Be5,Bc5,Ge3,Rc3,Rd4,Rc4][%cal Yg2d5,Bd3e5,Bd3c5,Gd2e3,Gd2c3,Rc3d4,Rb3c4] } *


