47... Bh3!! 48. gxh3 Kf5 49. Kf2 Ke4 50. Bxf6 d4! 51. Be7 Kd3 $19 { ♞ Challenge yourself by converting this against Noctie: https://go.noctie.ai/shirov } *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I: Topalov vs Shirov – Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.13"]
[White "Veselin Topalov"]
[Black "Alexey Shirov"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I"]
[ChapterName "Topalov vs Shirov – Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj/eOCbvbuF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/8/4kpp1/3p1b2/p6P/2B5/6P1/6K1 b - - 2 47"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.13"]
[UTCTime "10:49:30"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1143956

Shirov found the only winning move and even engines at the time couldn’t understand it. It’s very complicated, but I’ll do my best to explain. I had to check several commentators before I finally could understand it. The fact that Shirov found it over OTB and under pressure is insane.

Black is up two pawns, but without a breakthrough, the game is a draw because of the opposite-colored bishops. If Black would've played any other move, White’s king would walk to e3, blocking the d-pawn. And White's dark-squared bishop would shuffle along the h8-a1 diagonal, preventing the a-pawn from promoting. Black has no progress. }
47... Bh3!! { ...Bh3!!, often considered the greatest endgame move (or by many "the greatest move") in chess history.
This has two brilliant purposes: 1. It vacates the f5-square for Black’s king allowing it to run to e4. 2. It ties White’s king to the g-pawn.
Black must get the king to e4 to oppose the White king and support the advance of the d-pawn. At the same time, White must get his king to e3 to stop this idea. 48. gxh3 loses a crucial tempo, allowing the Black king to reach e4, supporting the d-pawn, and wins.
If White declines the sacrifice with 48. Kf2 (thus reaching e3 first to stop Black's king form going to e4), then 48...Kf5 49.Ke3 Bxg2 wins a clean pawn, and White can’t stop all of Black’s passed pawns. } 48. gxh3 (48. Kf2 Kf5 49. Ke3 Bxg2 $19 { [%csl Ga4,Gd5,Rh4,Gg6,Gf6] }) 48... Kf5 49. Kf2 Ke4 { Black's king has reached this important square first. } 50. Bxf6 d4! { Another important moment 50...d4! The point here was to block White's bishop from controlling the diagonal, thus not being able to stop both pawns. } { [%csl Gd4,Rf6][%cal Ba4a3] } 51. Be7 Kd3 { White cannot stop one of the pawns from promoting. In my opinion, truly worthy of all its praise. Topalov resigned a few moves later here. } { [%csl Ga4,Gd4,Yc2,Bd1,Ba1][%cal Yd3c2,Bd4d3,Bd3d2,Bd2d1,Ba4a3,Ba3a2,Ba2a1] } *


