{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1274525

Another very beautiful endgame. If you were using Stockfish, you'll get it wrong. Stockfish only realizes the forced win after the first move is played. :) }
31... Rxb2!! { 31...Rxb2!! The first move of this brilliant sequence! Black creates dangerous past c-pawns. } { [%csl Gc4] } 32. Nxb2 c3 33. Rxb6! { 33. Rxb6! The best try, White "sacrifices" his rook, but if 33...axb6?? 34. Nd3 c4 35. Nc1, Black's pawns can never advance, then the White king moves closer to pick them up. 33...cxb2?? also allows Black to stop all the pawns. } 33... c4!! { 33...c4!! A very unexpected "invisible" move! Black allows both of White's pieces to momentarily hang, as we know taking any of them will allow White to stop promotion. The point is to not allow Nd3 (reroute to c1), thus threatening c2-c1=Q. 34. Rb4, White's last try, threatening Rxc4, thus preventing c1=Q. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rc4d3] } (33... axb6?? 34. Nd3 c4 35. Nc1 $18) (33... cxb2?? 34. Rxb2 $18 { [%csl Rc5,Ra7] }) 34. Rb4 { [%csl Rc4][%cal Rb4c4] } 34... a5! { 4...a5! The final nail in the coffin! Taking away the b4 square from the rook. Promotion is inevitable. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ra5b4] } 35. Nxc4 (35. Rxc4 cxb2 { [%csl Gb1][%cal Gb2b1] }) 35... c2 $19 { White cannot stop the c-pawn from promoting. It's really satisfying to see these 3 simple pawns overpowering the two heavy bodyguards. :) } { [%csl Rb1,Rc4,Rb4][%cal Bc2c1] } *


