32. Qe8+! Kg7 33. Qxd8!! Rxd8 34. Rxc7+ Bd7 35. Rxd7+! Rxd7 36. Bxd7 gxh3 37. Kh2! $16 { ♞ Practice converting this against a humanlike sparring partner: https://go.noctie.ai/wesley_so } (37. Nxh3 { Also good, but play Kh2. }) *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I: So vs Liren - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.13"]
[White "Wesley So"]
[Black "Ding Liren"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I"]
[ChapterName "So vs Liren - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj/WpYf8nLO"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "1rbb2kr/2p4q/ppQp2n1/1B1Pp3/4P1p1/5pPP/P2B1N2/2RN1RK1 w - - 0 32"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.13"]
[UTCTime "10:49:30"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1807346&comp=-1&kpage=3

One of my favorite defensive sequences. In the starting position, we see Ding has a dangerous attacking setup, especially there's a lot of pressure along the h-file and there are ideas like Nf4 and Bh4 to break through the kingside at some point. Also the LSB is hanging. If So would react passively and retreat the bishop, say with d3, Black responds with Bd7, then Qc3 and White's pieces are all quite stuck on the queenside, and it's a matter of time before Black breaks through.

So, So has to extinguish the attack, and he does that with the following brilliant sequence. }
32. Qe8+! { All calculated. ...Kg7 forced, because if Nf8 White wins a free bishop. } (32. Bd3? Bd7 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rd7c6] } 33. Qc3 Rb7 $15 { [%cal Bg6f4,Bd8h4] }) 32... Kg7 { [%csl Re8,Gd8][%cal Rh8e8] } 33. Qxd8!! { Removing the defender of the c-pawn! } { [%csl Gc1,Rc7] } 33... Rxd8 { Recapturing. } 34. Rxc7+! { The idea starts to become clear. Ding can't attack if there aren't enough pieces on the board, thus So forces trades. } 34... Bd7 { The only way not to lose material. } 35. Rxd7+! { Important to take with the rook and not the bishop, because it has to be check. Black's moves should be forced. } 35... Rxd7 36. Bxd7 gxh3 37. Kh2 $16 { Using the "umbrella pawn" technique! White can capture the h-pawn at any time, but for now, it serves as protection, shielding the king from any potential harm. Note that Nxh3 is also perfectly fine, but Kh2 is safer and easier to play as.
Now we've come to the end of the sequence. Ding's attack has been completely neutralized, So's three minor pieces are actually a lot stronger than the queen. They can now reroute to active squares and work towards grinding out a win in the endgame. Black's pieces don't have a clear way to be active. Wesley So went on to win this game 23 moves later. } { [%cal Bd7c6,Bd1e3,Be3f5,Bd7f5,Bf2g4,Bd2b4] } *


