30. Ba3!! Qxa3 31. Nh5+!! gxh5 32. Qg5+! Kf8 33. Qxf6+ Kg8 34. e7 (34. Qd8+ { Also good, but play e7. }) (34. Qf7+ { Also good, but play e7. }) (34. Qg5+ { Also good, but play e7. }) 34... Qc1+ 35. Kf2 Qc2+ 36. Kg3 (36. Kg1 { Prolongs. Unnecessary. }) (36. Ke1 { Prolongs. Unnecessary. }) (36. Kf1 { Prolongs. Unnecessary. } 36... Nd2+) (36. Ke3 { Prolongs. Unnecessary. Play Kg3 } 36... Qd2+) (36. Kf3 { Ok, but play Kg3 }) 36... Qd3+ 37. Kh4 Qe4+ 38. Kxh5 Qe2+ 39. Kh4 (39. g4 { Also good, but play Kh4 avoiding Qxh2 shenanigans. }) 39... Qe4+ 40. g4 Qe1+ 41. Kh5 $18 *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I: Botvinnik vs Capablanca - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.13"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I"]
[ChapterName "Botvinnik vs Capablanca - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj/mNM7xKy5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/p3q1kp/1p2Pnp1/3pQ3/2pP4/1nP3N1/1B4PP/6K1 w - - 5 30"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.13"]
[UTCTime "10:49:30"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1031957 }
30. Ba3!! { The absolute best move! Deflecting the queen from defending the knight and blockading the e-pawn. If Black doesn't accept the sacrifice and retreats his queen ...Qe8, White follows up with Qc7+ followed by Be7 which is deadly. } 30... Qxa3 (30... Qe8 31. Qc7+ Kh8 32. Be7 $18 { [%csl Rf6,Ge7,Gc7,Rh8] }) 31. Nh5+!! { The point of the previous move. Exposing the king, allowing Qg5+, winning the knight back. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Ge5g5] } 31... gxh5 32. Qg5+! { [%csl Rf7,Rg7][%cal Re6f7,Gg5f6,Gg5g7] } 32... Kf8 33. Qxf6+ Kg8 34. e7 { Advancing the pawn. White is threatening 2 dangerous threats: Qf8# and the promotion of the pawn } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Rf6f8] } 34... Qc1+ { Black's only try. Black now tries to either get a draw by the repetitive checks rule, or get a queen trade which would eliminate all danger. } 35. Kf2 (35. Qf1?? Qxf1+ 36. Kxf1 Kf7 $19 { All dangerous is gone. Black stops the pawn. }) 35... Qc2+ { In the following moves Black tries to achieve what has just been mentioned, while White must get his king out of all the checks. He still has to be careful here. For example: 37. Kf4 leads to a draw ...Qe4+ and the king cannot get out of all the checks. } 36. Kg3 Qd3+ 37. Kh4 (37. Kf4?? Qe4+ 38. Kg5 Qxg2+ $10) 37... Qe4+ 38. Kxh5 Qe2+ 39. Kh4 (39. g4 { Also works. But a more complicated line. See in analysis board later. } 39... Qxh2+ 40. Kg5 Qd2+ 41. Kf5 Qf2+ 42. Ke6 Qe3+ 43. Kd7 Nc5+ 44. dxc5 { White has gotten out of all the checks. }) 39... Qe4+ 40. g4 Qe1+ 41. Kh5 $18 { Black no longer can give any checks to our king, thus no longer able to prolong our threat. It was in the position Capablanca resigned. It is absolutely incredible how Botvinnik was able to calculate all this. } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Rf6f8] } *


