19. Ndf5! { Simply bringing the knight closer to the attack, and saving it from the c pawn. } 19... Ba6 { Alekhine's opponent missed his threat. However, there really wasn't anything Black could do. } 20. Qg6!! { Absolutely stunning move! Putting the queen right in front of all the kingside pawns. With the idea of breaking open the h-file, allowing Rh3+. It was in this position, Supico resigned, but we can go a little further to see the idea. } { [%csl Gc4,Rg8,Bh3][%cal Bc3h3] } 20... fxg6 { [%csl Rg8][%cal Gc4g8] } 21. Nxg6+! hxg6 $7 { The h-file has been opened up. f8 is controlled by our bishop. } { [%cal Rh8h1] } 22. Rh3+ Qh4 23. Rxh4# { Checkmate! You might think that's nice and pretty, but maybe not that brilliant.
Well, there's one thing I haven't told you yet. ;) This game was played in a blindfold simul! Alekhine was playing multiple opponents at the same time...completely blindfolded!! Now that definitely earns this a spot on the list. } { [%csl Rg7,Rg6,Yg8][%cal Gh4h8,Yc4g8] } *


