[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I: Tal vs NN - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.13"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "NN"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1b1n2pp/pq2p3/1p2P1B1/6Q1/2N5/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w kq - 2 14"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I"]
[ChapterName "Tal vs NN - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj/gxCLIUoC"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1b1n2pp/pq2p3/1p2P1B1/6Q1/2N5/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w kq - 2 14"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.13"]
[UTCTime "10:49:30"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1139653

You can't make a study called "PURE BRILLIANCE" without Mikhail Tal. \_('-')_/
This whole study could be filled with only his games...That's why I actually have a full study dedicated to him. It also includes this game fully annotated. Feel free to check it out later if you want: https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/0a2BxqyO } { [%csl Re6,Gg4,Gg5,Gd1,Re8] }
14. Rd6! { Tal sacrifices the roook! Now there's nothing Black can do anymore to survive. If he doesn't take the rook, Tal simply grabs e6 with the queen or rook and checkmate will follow soon. And taking the rook, also leads to a beautiful checkmate we will see in the game. :) } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gd6b6,Yg4e6,Bd6e6] } 14... Bxd6 { Black takes the rook, but now the e6-pawn remains undefended. } { [%csl Re6] } 15. Qxe6+! { Forcing the king to move! Tal's aim isn't to capture a free pawn, but to construct a mating net around the exposed king. } { [%csl Yd8,Re8,Rf7,Ge6][%cal Ge6e8,Ge6f7,Yg5d8] } 15... Kf8 { [%csl Rg8,Rf7,Re7,Re8][%cal Ge6e8,Ge6g8] } 16. Bc4! { Tal sacrifices a THIRD piece (He sacrificed a knight earlier, which you can see in the full game)! The purpose behind this beautiful move is to free the f1 square for the h1 rook, allowing it to join the assault on Black's king. While moving the bishop anywhere would be winning, going for Bc4 threatens an immediate checkmate with Qf7#, thus gaining a tempo, ending the game a bit sooner! :) } { [%csl Rf1,Gf7][%cal Bh1f1,Rc4f7] } (16. exd6 { Still wins, but slower and less satisfying. It's a bit unnecessary, White can just continue attacking. }) 16... bxc4 { [%csl Gf1][%cal Gh1f1] } 17. Rf1+! { Another piece has joined the attack! } { [%csl Gf1,Ge6,Gg5][%cal Yf1f8] } 17... Nf6 { Black can only block the check. } 18. Rxf6+! { Opening up the f8-h6 diagonal. } { [%cal Gh6f8] } (18. exf6?? { Completely throws the game away! ...Bf4+ is a discovered attack! Then Black wins our queen and we no longer have any mating-net around the king. } 18... Bf4+!! { A discovered attack! Black wins our queen on the next move and we no longer have any mating-net around the king. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Rb6e6] }) 18... gxf6 $7 { [%csl Rg7,Rh6,Rf8] } 19. Bh6#! { The queen and bishop deliver a stunning criss-cross checkmate. An absolutely magnificent miniature! White is literally down 11 points in material!!
I thought it would be nice to add this game. It’s such a beautiful display of attacking play, packed with fireworks from start to finish. } { [%csl Ye8,Ye7,Yg8,Yf7,Rf8,Rg7,Rb8,Ra8,Rb7,Rh8,Rb6,Rd6][%cal Ye6e8,Ye6g8,Rh6f8] } *


