[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I: Adams vs Repetto - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.13"]
[White "Edwin Ziegler Adams"]
[Black "Carlos Torre Repetto"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1p1q1ppp/3p1b2/p2P4/3Q4/5N2/PP2RPPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I"]
[ChapterName "Adams vs Repetto - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj/JPhFLLko"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1p1q1ppp/3p1b2/p2P4/3Q4/5N2/PP2RPPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.13"]
[UTCTime "10:49:30"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1143989 }
1. Qg4!! { White's goal is to take away each square from Black's queen that defends the rook, but each move must also gain tempo, otherwise Black has time to play Rxe2, relieving the pressure on the backrank. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Re2e8] } 1... Qb5 { Keeping the e8 rook defended. This is the only square, Qd8 loses to Qxc8. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Gb5e8] } (1... Qxg4 2. Rxe8+ Rxe8 3. Rxe8#) (1... Qd8 2. Qxc8 Qxc8 3. Rxe8+ Qxe8 4. Rxe8#) 2. Qc4!! { The same tactic! White's queen can be captured twice, but none of them work because of Rxe8#!! The Black queen is again forced to move back to d7. } { [%csl Gc4,Re8][%cal Yc8c4,Bb5c4,Ge2e8] } 2... Qd7 { Again, Black's only move. By now, you probably know this queen is immortal and can continue dancing next to Black's pieces. } { [%cal Gd7e8] } (2... Qxc4 3. Rxe8+ Rxe8 4. Rxe8#) (2... Rxc4 3. Rxe8+ Qxe8 4. Rxe8#) 3. Qc7!! { Again, non of Black's pieces can capture. } { [%cal Rd7c7,Rc8c7,Be2e8] } 3... Qb5 { The d7-square has now been taken. c6 is controlled by our pawn. That leaves only a4 and b5 left. } { [%csl Re2,Rd7,Rc6,Gb5,Ga4][%cal Bb5e2,Rc7d7,Rd5c6] } (3... Qa4 4. b3 Qb5 5. a4 { Each square has been taken from the queen to defend the rook. We'll win the rook on the next move. } { [%csl Rb5,Rc6,Rd7,Ra4,Re8] }) 4. a4!! { The only winning move! White kicks the queen away from the b5 square, where it's attacking our e2 rook. Black is forced to capture the a4 pawn, because there's no other square she can go that keeps the e8 rook protected.
You might have though of Qxb7??, but this move doesn't work yet because Black's queen isn't forced to capture it. Instead, Black can simply capture the e2 rook, leading to 4...Qxe2 5. Rxe2 Rc1+! 6. Ne1 Rxe1 7. Rxe1, resulting in checkmate. } { [%csl Re8,Rb5][%cal Ra4b5] } (4. Qxb7?? Qxe2 5. Rxe2 Rc1+ 6. Ne1 Rxe1+ 7. Rxe1 Rxe1#) 4... Qxa4 5. Re4!! $18 { Sacrificing the ROOOK! The a4 square is now also controlled by White. If Black were to take it with the e8 rook, he would leave his other rook hanging, and Qxe4 doesn't change anything after Rxe4. } { [%csl Ra4,Rd7,Rc6,Gb5][%cal Re4a4,Re4e8] } (5. b3 Qb5 { Again the rook is under attack. } { [%csl Re2] }) 5... Qb5 { The only square left. } { [%csl Gb5,Ra4,Rc6,Rd7] } 6. Qxb7! $18 { And sacrificing the queen for the final time. But, again, Black cannot take. Now, finally, every square from the queen that keeps the e8 rook defended has been taken away. Black loses a ton of material. } { [%csl Rd7,Rc6,Rb5,Ra4,Rc8,Re8][%cal Bb7c8,Be4e8] } *


