{ BONUS Chapter.

This one's not a world-famous brilliant master game... but I thought it would be fun to include a game of my own that features a nice little sequence. :) }
13... Qc7?? 14. Nxd7! Qxc3+ 15. Bd2! Qxa1+ 16. Ke2 Qxh1 17. Nxf6+! (17. Nxb8+ { Also leads to mate, but longer. }) 17... Kd8 18. Ba5+ (18. Qa5+ { There's a shorter mate. }) 18... Kc8 19. Bd7+ Nxd7 20. Qxd7+ (20. Qc2+ { Also possible. }) (20. Qc4+ { Also possible. }) 20... Kb8 21. Qc7+ Ka7 22. Bb6# *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I: BONUS: Bosburp vs Zainfarid - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.13"]
[White "Bosburp"]
[Black "Zainfarid"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume I"]
[ChapterName "BONUS: Bosburp vs Zainfarid - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj/8VnbpwQP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rn1qkb1r/1p1bpppp/p4n2/1B1PN3/Q4B2/2N5/P4PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 3 13"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.13"]
[UTCTime "10:49:30"]

{ Full game: https://lichess.org/KfkobMc6#25 3+0 blitz. }
13... Qc7?? { Attacking the knight (captured with check). Although, this fails as we see in the following sequence. } { [%csl Rc3,Yb5] } 14. Nxd7! { The absolute best move! Sacrificing a full knight with check! White's DSB now attacks Black's queen, so he's pretty forced to accept the sacrifice. After Black's queen goes on her shopping spree, White ends up getting a deadly attack with the remaining pieces while Black's queen is too far away to defend. } { [%csl Re8,Rc7,Gb5,Rc3][%cal Ya4f4,Rf4c7,Rc3e1] } 14... Qxc3+ { [%csl Ra1,Re1][%cal Rc3a1,Rc3e1] } 15. Bd2!! { The only winning move because now White gains tempo on the queen, forcing her to move away. } { [%cal Rd2c3] } (15. Ke2?? { Fails completely, because now Black has enough time to do something about my threats. } 15... Qb2+ { Simply forking, thus winning a full piece. A simple Nbxd7 would have worked too here. Black just ends up being up in material. } { [%cal Rb2b5,Rb2e2] } 16. Kf3 Qxb5 $19) 15... Qxa1+ 16. Ke2! { Again, White must gain tempo on the queen! } { [%cal Rh1a1] } 16... Qxh1 { White's currently down 11 points in material. Now it's White's turn to start throwing the punches. } 17. Nxf6+ { A discovered check, forcing the king to move. } { [%cal Rf6e8,Rb5e8] } 17... Kd8 $7 { Bringing more pieces into the attack. White's now creating a mating net. Now the rest is pretty straightforward and will require no annotations. } 18. Ba5+! { [%csl Yd8,Re8,Yc7,Rd7][%cal Ya5d8,Rb5e8] } 18... Kc8 19. Bd7+ Nxd7 $7 20. Qxd7+ Kb8 21. Qc7+ Ka7 22. Bb6# { A nice checkmate whilst being down 8 points in material! This game shows that having more pieces isn't always important. A few active minor pieces can be incredibly powerful if the opponent's pieces are just sitting somewhere away from the attack. But always make sure your attack is strong enough to justify any material sacrifice. } { [%csl Gb8,Gb6,Ra6,Ra8,Rb7,Ya7][%cal Gc7b8,Gc7b6,Yb6a7] } *


