{ Mistake #1: Afraid to Move Backwards

Here we have a famous game between 2 World Champions. They're going to show us something that most players make the mistake of not doing.

It's a complicated position. Can you find a move that will give White the most progress? }
1. Nb1!! $146 { Karpov, what are you doing?! Why did you just move you're knight back to it's starting square? 😬
This move might look shocking at first, but it's the best move in this position! It's White's best way of making progress.
This move has several purposes: 1. Black's b4 knight is annoying. By moving the knight, Karpov unblocks his c-pawn, planning to kick it with c3 soon. 2. On, c3 the knight was pretty useless. It couldn't advance to d5 or b5 because of the c6 pawn. It's not attacking or defending anything, it served no purpose there. So, Karpov wants to reroute it to a better place. It can go from here to d2-and to f3 where it will be more active. } { [%cal Rc2c3,Bb1d2,Bd2f3] } 1... Qb7 { Now c3 is totally fine. But Black will play Bg3 which is a bit annoying. So, can you find a way to prevent that? } 2. Kh2! { Keeping things simple! Not allowing Black to give us any annoyance. } { [%cal Rh2g3] } 2... Kg7 { We just continue our plan now. Kick the knight. } { [%csl Rb4] } 3. c3 (3. Rxd8 { Totally fine, but in the game Re2 was played. }) 3... Na6 { Next, we reroute the knight to f3. Clear the d2 square with Re2. } { [%cal Bb1d2,Bd2f3] } 4. Re2 Rf8 5. Nd2 Bd8 6. Nf3 $16 { And White has a fantastic position! The game was finished in just a few more moves.
Full game: https://lichess.org/3SV9t24v#0
So, what can we learn here? Don't be afraid to move your pieces backwards! Of course, make sure it has a purpose, like rerouting it to a better square or clearing the way for other pieces or pawns. Also, often when pieces get attacked and are forced to move, moving backwards might often be the best. As moving forward can get the piece trapped or kicked around.
⚔ Practice converting this against a humanlike bot: https://go.noctie.ai/backwards ⚔ } { [%csl Gf3,Ge3,Gc4,Ge2,Gf1][%cal Be2d2,Bf3g5] } *


