[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/D2rO6Ufn/ZrGgZ3xl"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "4Q3/P5pk/5p1p/3q1P1K/6PP/8/8/8 b - - 6 60"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.08.23"]
[UTCTime "11:49:40"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #2: Auto-Promotion

Here we have a real position from a game between two masters. White's up a pawn here, so this should be an easy win...right? 😏

Pause for a moment and see if you can find the win for White. }
60... Qb7 61. a8=B!! $146 $140 { Absolutely brilliant! Perhaps my favorite endgame move, second only to Shirov's infamous Bh3!!
I'm guessing many of you promoted to a different piece... 😉 But all other promotions lead to a draw. Black's previous move was actually incredibly tricky, a very nice find by him.
If a8=Q?? Black has the move Qf7+! White is forced to capture and... it's stalemate! None of Black's pieces can move! Promoting to a rook leads to the same. And a knight, is also a draw, you can see that variation in the analyze board later. a8=B!! is the only move that works. After Qf7+, it’s no longer stalemate because the king can move to h8. Also, the bishop doesn't get trapped. It will reroute to f7, and checkmate will follow soon.
Well, this is a rather extreme, but educational and stunning, example of an auto-promotion mistake. But this mistake gets made a LOT. You've probably seen a game where one would promote to a queen, and it's an immediate stalemate. I'm almost certain you have experienced it sometime in you chess journey. Even high rated players make this mistake, for an example, check out Eric Rosen's stalemate collections, his opponents have been victims to it countless of times. 😄
So what can we learn here? Always pause before promoting. Make sure to look at your opponents pieces. Ask questions like: Can they still move?, Can he sacrifice material forcefully (with check) and stalemate? Or as we see here, sometimes you must promote to a non-queen piece, maybe to avoid stalemate, or a knight might be best because it forks pieces to win material or even checkmate.
Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1253800
🎯 Can you win this from here? https://go.noctie.ai/auto-promotion 🎯 } { [%cal Ba8c6,Bc6d7,Bd7e6,Be6f7] } (61. a8=Q?? { Nope! Leads to stalemate after Qf7+!! } 61... Qf7+! 62. Qxf7 $10 { Stalemate! }) (61. a8=N { Haha, nice try. But nope, this leads to a draw } 61... Qa7! { The only move that keeps both b6 and c7 controlled. Not allowing the knight to join a checkmating attack. Now it's quite a funny position. White's queen may not move to a square to help the knight escape because she must control the f7 square. If Black gets to play Qf7, it would be checkmate. Both sides cannot make any progress. }) (61. a8=R?? { Nope. } 61... Qf7+ 62. Qxf7) *


