{ Mistake #3: Thinking Doubled Pawns are Always Bad

This one is a mistake I used to make a lot. I used to avoid getting doubled-pawns at all costs. So, if one of my pieces could be taken and it would double my pawns, I would make sure it was defended by a piece or move it away.

But actually, doubled pawns aren't always a bad thing. Doubled pawns can give you open files, improve pawn structures, or control better squares. It really depends on the position.

Here's an example game I played which shows the power of doubled pawns. Let's play through it a bit.

There are multiple good moves here, like g4, a4, d3. But I want you to play d4! }
7. d4 exd4 { Now there's a small problem, the knight is pinned so cannot recapture. That leaves only the queen, but after she captures, Black can double our f-pawns with Bxf3.
This is looking terrible, but play Qxd4 anyway, let's see how it goes. } { [%cal Rf3d4,Yd1d4] } 8. Qxd4! Bxf3 9. gxf3 { Oh no, doubled f-pawns! And an exposed king!
But actually... this is totally fine for White.
First of all, the king is completely safe, Black has no way to attack him. Second, the g-file is now open. This means we can place a rook along the g-file, and it’ll be staring straight at Black’s (future) castled king.
So actually, it’s White who’s going to be launching the attack.
Let's see how the game went. } { [%csl Rf2,Rf3,Rg1] } 9... Nbd7 { Develop the bishop first. } { [%cal Gc1e3] } 10. Be3 Ne5 { Wanting to trade of the LSB and hitting f3. Can you fix both problems? } { [%csl Rf3,Rc4] } 11. Be2 Qc8 { [%csl Rh3] } 12. Kh2! { Defending h2. We we're already planning to play this anyway because we want to bring the rooks over. } { [%cal Bf1g1] } 12... Ng6 { Gain some kingside space. } { [%cal Gf3f4,Bf4f5] } 13. f4 O-O { The g6 knight's annoying right? Let's kick him away. Away from defending the kingside. } { [%csl Rg6] } 14. f5 Ne5 { Now the g-file's half open. Let's make use of it. } { [%cal Gg1g8] } 15. Rg1 Kh8 { How does the other rook come in? } { [%csl Ga1][%cal Bg1g3] } 16. Rg3 Rd8 17. Rag1 { White has an amazing attacking position! Here White went on to slowly break open the kingside and win the game.
So, what can we learn here? Doubled pawns are not always bad, often they can be incredibly good. So don't be afraid to capture with a pawn, even if it doubles the pawns, instead of a piece.
But of course, make sure doubling the pawns has a purpose; opening files, to attack a piece, or help in development, etc. Always make sure that it won't jeopardize the king's safety.
Full game: https://lichess.org/nJbVI8Gq
⚔ Practice converting this against a humanlike AI: https://go.noctie.ai/doubled-pawns ⚔ } { [%csl Gg3,Gg1,Rc8,Rh8,Re7,Ra8,Rd8][%cal Bf2f4,Be3h6] } *


