[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r2q1bnr/ppp2k2/2n1b2p/3B4/3PPppP/8/PPP3P1/RNBQK2R w KQ - 1 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.08.23"]
[UTCTime "11:49:40"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #4: Material > Everything?

Here's a position from a blitz game of mine. White's down a knight currently, but Black's king is badly placed. Can you find the only move that keeps the advantage? }
10. Bxe6+! { Not too hard to find. We force the king forward where he'll walk into a pawn fork. } { [%cal Rd5c6,Rd5e6,Bd4d5] } 10... Kxe6 11. d5+! { Forking the king and knight. } { [%cal Rd5c6,Rd5e6] } (11. Qxg4+ { Also fine, but play d4+ it's a bit better. } 11... Kf7 12. Qxf4+ Nf6) 11... Ke5?? { Here my opponent made a serious blunder. The position was already slightly better for White, until now. White has a clear winning idea here.
What would you do here? } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rd5c6] } (11... Kf7! { Would allow Black to survive a bit more. But now we actually have the same theme as in the game. Take the knight, on the expense that the queens will get traded, or go after the king with Bxf4! } 12. Bxf4! $16 { We'll castle to get the rook joining in the attack along the f-file. Black's in trouble. } { [%cal Be1g1] }) 12. Bxf4+! { Many players would make the mistake of playing dxc6 just to equalize material. But here, White is already down a piece, and now sacrifices another!
Instead of regaining material with dxc6, we must go for something far more important: the king! We force him along the f-file where we'll castle and get a huge attack. } (12. dxc6?? { Nope! A game throwing blunder! You've regained material, but now Black will trade the queens off the board, and there's no attack whatsoever on the king. } 12... Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Rd8+ 14. Nd2 bxc6 $15 { Even tho the king looks badly placed, there's no way to attack it, because the queens have been traded off! }) (12. O-O Bc5+ 13. Rf2) (12. Qxg4! { Yes, perfectly fine too, you have the correct idea in mind. Although in the game I played something else. Both moves are equally good however. }) 12... Kxf4 { There are multiple good moves here. Nc3, Nd2, Rf1+ are all good. But let's play the most simple, O-O. } (12... Kf6) 13. O-O+! { Bringing the king to safety and most importantly, taking control of the f-file. } { [%cal Rf1f8] } 13... Ke5 { The king tries to run back. How do we continue the attack? } { [%cal Be5d6,Bd6d7,Bd7c8] } 14. Qxg4! { Yes! Great job finding these moves! We bring our strongest piece closer to the king. Qg3/Qf4 are serious threats, forcing the king into our territory after Kd4. } { [%csl Rf4,Rg3][%cal Rg4f4,Re5d4,Rg4g3] } 14... Bc5+ { A harmless in-between move. How do we respond? } 15. Kh1! { Simply moving out of check. } (15. Kh2 { Also perfectly fine. But play Kh1. }) 15... Nd4 { And here my opponent blundered mate-in-1, but this position was already completely lost.
Funny thing is, I actually missed the M1 in the game and played Nd2 instead, which leads to checkmate a bit later.😅
Play the M1! } 16. Qf4#! { Checkmate!
So, what can we learn here? Material isn’t the most important, it shouldn't be your top priority. There are many other factors to consider: piece activity, king safety, and initiative,...etc. If the position demands a sacrifice, then do so!
Because in the end, it’s not about who has more pieces...
It’s about whose king is checkmated. 😉 } { [%csl Ye4,Yd5,Rd4][%cal Gf4d6,Gf4f6,Bd5e6] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 3: 🤡 Overextension"]
[Date "2025.08.23"]
