[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #6: Playing complicated openings you’re not ready for

This chapter is meant especially for beginners. It gets seen very often. Some new players see GM's like Magnus Carlsen, Hikaru, or Nepomniachtchi playing a complicated opening like the Grünfeld, or the Sicilian Najdorf and think: they play it, so it must be good! Well... yes and no.

Yes, these are good openings. But, that doesn’t mean you should play them right away. These are super GMs who have years of experience and deep understanding of it. If you’re a beginner, playing such complicated openings right away will likely leave you confused, overwhelmed, and you'll rely more on pure memorization instead of understanding the ideas.

My recommendation, although might be controversial, would be to go play 1. e4 and play the Italian against e5. As Black against 1.e4, just reply with 1...e5 and develop with basic opening principles.

Are these easiest to learn? No, not necessarily, but at this stage you're just learning the fundamentals. It will really help you familiarize with key structures, tactics, principals, etc, which is most important when you're just starting out. You'll probably fall for some traps early on, but these experiences will teach you a lot.

I’d avoid starting with 1.d4, c4, Nf3 it's definitely more positional and advanced. I recommend to play it when your foundation is stronger.

📖 Want to learn the first moves of the most common openings? Try Noctie's interactive opening guide: https://go.noctie.ai/opening-guide 📖 }
 *


