[FEN "rn4r1/2p1kp2/3p1q2/3Pp2p/1p2Pp2/5R1P/PP1N1PPQ/R6K w - - 4 26"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.08.23"]
[UTCTime "11:49:40"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #7: Always playing en passant.

Honestly, most chess players, when they see an en passant, will just play it instantly. Probably we have an urge to play a move that looks so fancy and has such a cool name. 😏

But en passant is just another capture, so if it doesn’t improve your position, don’t play it!

Let's play a4 here, gaining queenside space. }
26. a4 bxa3? { Oh, oh. Your opponent has instantly taken a4 by en-passant, but is this actually good?
In what way does this improve Black's position? In no way. Actually it's helping us gain control of the a-file.
Recapture the pawn. } 27. Rfxa3! { The rooks are doubled. Black is forced to trade. } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Ra3a8] } (27. bxa3? { Not taking advantage. The a-file now gets closed. We we're supposed to control it. }) (27. Raxa3?! { Fine, but we have a better recapture. Capturing with the f-rook doubles the rooks and forces Black to trade. Thus, we gain sole control of the a-file. }) 27... Rxa3 28. Rxa3 $14 { Look at the rook! It controls the entire a-file. It can later infiltrate Black's 8th and 7th ranks and add pressure on the c-pawn.
So, what can we learn here? En passant is tempting, but it’s just another capture. Treat it like any other capture, think if it benefits you before playing it.
Also, quick note: many beginners will misunderstand en passant, example I used to think en passant was still valid a move later after the opponent pushes the pawn 2 squares. So, if you haven't yet fully grasped it, lichess has a section on it here: https://lichess.org/learn#/15/1
Also, special thanks to @Chessmate_0204 for the idea!
🎯 Practice your endgame skills against Noctie: https://go.noctie.ai/en-passant-mistakes 🎯 } { [%cal Ga3a8,Ga3a1] } *


