{ Mistake #8: Trapping your own pieces

Here we have game that illustrates this mistake played by two super-GM's played during the 2011 Candidates Matches. Even the best make mistakes too!

And btw, thanks for still being here! I hope you're learning something useful! I know it took you a few minutes to get to this chapter, but it took me many hours across a few weeks to annotate, investigate, and find these positions. So, if you’re enjoying the study, please leave a heart, it really helps me keep creating these! I appreciate it! 😊 }
16. a3?? { Looks natural at first, kicking away the knight. But it's a huge blunder. Can you find the only winning move?
Psst, remember chapter 8 from Part 1. } 16... c4! { Yes! a3 took away the only escape square. If dxc4, then Black has Nc5 which fully traps the queen. The only way to save the queen now, would be to walk onto the c-file, where a discovered attack awaits her. } { [%csl Rb3,Ra2,Rc2,Ya3,Yb2,Yc3,Ra4,Yb4] } 17. Qxc4 (17. dxc4 Nc5) 17... Bxf3! { Grabbing the free piece, because the rook now attacks the queen. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Rc8c4] } 18. Qh4 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 { Black's simply up a piece and won the game rather comfortably.
This is a more advanced example, but it happens quite often, for example: the Noah's Ark Trap, where the pawns take away all the bishop's squares.
So, what can we learn here? Always pay attention to your own pieces. Look if they have space to move, can they be attacked easily. If not, try to give them breathing room and make them happy by making them more active.
🎯 Can you win this? Practice your technique here: https://go.noctie.ai/trapping-own-piece 🎯 } *


