[FEN "8/2kp4/4p2N/1KP5/8/8/p1n5/6R1 b - - 1 44"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.08.23"]
[UTCTime "11:49:40"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #10 (FINALLY!): Settling Too Soon

What would you play here? }
44... Na3+! { Yes! Many players might play a1=Q, which wins the rook, but that actually leads to a draw. Black will be a pawn ahead, but it won't be able to promote because White's knight is always there to stop it. Being content in life is great... but in chess, where you want to win, not so much. 😄 } { [%cal Ba3b1] } (44... a1=Q?? { Nope leads to a draw! We want to win! } 45. Rxa1 Nxa1 $10) 45. Kb4 Nb1 $19 { The knight blocks the rook from capturing our promoted pawn! Black getting a queen is inevitable.
So, what can we learn here? Many players find a way to get a small advantage, and stop looking for stronger continuations. As the saying goes, "When you see a good move, look for a better one". Don’t settle for the first “good” move you see. There might be something much better.
A nice idea I talk about in Part 2, is to always have at least 3 candidate moves in mind. This stops you from settling too early and forces you to look for other options.
🎯 Can you win this against a humanlike bot? Try here: https://go.noctie.ai/settling-too-soon 🎯 } { [%csl Ba1][%cal Ba2a1] } *


