[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🏰 Automatic Castling #1"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🏰 Automatic Castling #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/MlpJhgyj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pb2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

7... O-O? { Mistake #1: Castling Automatically
This is a very common mistake. Many players, when they can castle, simply do it right away. Let’s take a look at a position from the French Two Knights Variation. As we can see from the database, 55% of the time, Black castles here.
However, this is a mistake because it castles straight into an attack from White. White already has a bishop aiming at h7, a knight on the kingside, and the White king hasn’t castled yet, meaning the g and h pawns are ready for a pawnstorm.
Now with that information, how can we punish Black’s automatic castling? } { [%csl Gd3,Gf3,Rh7][%cal Rd3h7,Bh2h4,Bg2g4,Bh4h5,Bg4g5] } (7... c5! { Counterattacking the center! } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Bb8c6] }) 8. h4! { Yes! We immediately launch a pawnstorm at Black’s king (and actually, we’re already threatening a Greek Gift!), which has just been placed in a dangerous position. The king would have been much safer in the center. Is Black completely losing here? No, the engine gives a +1.2 evaluation, but Black will have a very difficult time defending. And as you can see, White’s winrate is at 77%, which shows that not many players succeed in that.
Black would have avoided all these difficulties if he had paused for a moment to consider whether castling was actually safe. The best move for Black would have been c5, counterattacking the center and keeping the king safely in the center until it’s safe to castle. Alternatively, Black could consider castling queenside or simply keep the king in the center for the rest of the game. } 8... h6 { Well, this isn’t a complete guide on attacking, so we won’t go into all the variations on how White would crush Black. But let’s focus on just one move here (avoiding the Greek Gift) to show how amazing this is for White. But feel free to click "analyze board" at the end of the chapter to see more lines.
White has two good options here: Qe2 and g4. For now, let’s go play Qe2. } (8... b6 9. Bxh7+ Kxh7 10. Ng5+ Kg8 11. Qh5 Re8 $18) (8... Re8 9. Ng5 h6 10. Qh5) (8... g6 9. h5 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rh5g6] }) (8... Nd7 9. Bxh7+! { We win with the Greek Gift! As you can see this is a very popular tactic, so if you're familiar with it, check out my free sacrifice course: https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU }) 9. Qe2! { Bringing the queen to a more active square, she can potentially join the attack with a Qe4 battery. At this point, White is in a very comfortable position. We’ll play g4 and g5, soon ripping open Black’s kingside. Both bishops are aiming at the kingside, with the potential for maybe Bxh6. Also the king will castle queenside, bringing the a-rook to the g-file to join the slaughter. It's not spot on winning, but White has a very comfortable long-term advantage, all of this thanks to Black’s automatic castling.
So, what can we learn here? Don’t castle your king automatically without thinking! First, consider whether it’s safe. Are there any direct threats, like a Greek Gift for example? Can your opponent easily launch an attack on your king?
If you want to practice this scenario further with White, you can play it against Noctie, a human-like AI here: https://go.noctie.ai/iH4Zxgy. Practicing these scenarios will help you improve your attacking skills. We have a nice advantage here, but it's also important to know how to convert these small advantages into wins, this comes with practice and experience. 💡 } { [%csl Ye4,Bc1,Gd3,Gf3][%cal Ye2e4,Bg2g4,Bf3e5,Be1c1,Rc1h6,Rd3h7] } (9. g4 $16 { [%csl Gg4,Gh4][%cal Bg4g5] }) *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🏰 Automatic Castling #2"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🏰 Automatic Castling #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/MIWbUTlC"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pb2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 8"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Wait, isn’t this the same position as the previous chapter? 🤔 Yeah, you’re right! 😆 But we still need to cover something important here.

So, Black has just automatically castled. In the last chapter, we saw how White should play h4 and will get an amazing attack. But here’s the thing: most players actually play something else here...🤯 } { [%csl Rg8][%cal Re8g8] }
8. O-O? { Yes, haha, ironically, White has just automatically castled too! 😅 And no joke, this is actually the most popular move being played, accounting for 37% of the time. And there are even OTB master games that made this mistake in this position!
Play c5 here. } 8... c5 $10 { Black strikes back in the center with c5, and now we have a relatively equal position. White no longer has the h4 and g4 pawn storm or any kingside attack, and while the position isn't losing for White or in any way bad, it's still such a huge missed opportunity.
White could have had an overwhelming attack, but instead, by castling without thinking, has gone to this much more balanced position.
So, what can we learn from this? Just because you CAN castle doesn’t mean you SHOULD. In this case, g1 and f1 were cleared for kingside castling, but it was a bad idea because the kingside pawns and rook COULD have been used for an attack. Instead, consider the option of castling queenside (even if it takes longer) or possibly not castling at all. } { [%csl Gc5,Rd4][%cal Bb8d7,Rh2h4] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🎣 Going for Cheap Tricks"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[White "Phil"]
[Black "Skilled Opponent"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C23"]
[Opening "Bishop's Opening"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🎣 Going for Cheap Tricks"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/t8MKUWPB"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #2: Going for Cheap Tricks

Many beginners watch a random video on YouTube or check out a Lichess study about opening traps and get excited to try them out. This is a very common mistake, but it’s really not a good idea. Beginners often focus on one specific trap, and when their opponent doesn't fall into the lines, they have no idea what to do next. 🤨

Let’s take White, we'll call him "Phil" for example. He’s a beginner who just learned the Scholar's Mate trap from a video. Let's see how this game goes. }
1. Bc4 { There's nothing to say here yet. Play Nc6 for the sake of the study. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gb8c6] } 1... Nc6 2. Qh5?! { Phil plays Qh5, going for the Scholar's Mate, since he just saw it in a video. (It’s an extreme example, but the same logic applies to many traps.) He threatens checkmate in one move, but it doesn't improve his position in any meaningful way. He might be thinking, “Well, my opponent is too bad to see this” or “I hope he doesn’t notice I’m threatening mate in one.” Phil is just hoping, and that’s already a mistake. You can’t just hope your opponent won’t see a threat. If your opponent is that bad, they’ll blunder on their own without you making weak moves to set them up.
So, how do you, the skilled opponent, respond? 😉 } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rh5f7,Rc4f7] } 2... g6! { Phil’s stuck now. His skilled opponent hasn’t fallen for his trap, and he doesn’t really know how to continue here, so he tries Qf3, again threatening mate in 1. Maybe his opponent won’t notice it this time... } 3. Qf3 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rf3f7,Rc4f7] } 3... Nf6 { Phil’s skilled opponent didn’t fall for the trap again. Now, Phil has no idea what to do. The video he watched didn’t cover this line... 😬 } 4. Qb3?? { Phil tries one last resort, attacking f7 again. But you, the skilled opponent, know how to respond, right? 😏 } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rb3f7] } 4... Nd4! { Phil's happy here, his so-called "skilled opponent" left the f7 pawn hanging. 😏 } 5. Bxf7+ Ke7 $7 { The queen's attacked, but it has to protect the bishop too. Ah, Phil sees he can move his queen to c4, keeping f2 protected and the queen safe. He thinks he’s winning... } { [%csl Rb3][%cal Rd4b3] } 6. Qc4 b5! { Yes! Now, Phil's in trouble. The queen has to leave the bishop, since Black covers every square. } { [%csl Rc4,Rb3,Rd5,Re6,Rf7][%cal Rb5c4,Rd4b3,Rf6d5,Rd7e6,Re7f7] } 7. Qd3 { Now you can go ahead and take that free piece! } 7... Kxf7 $19 { Phil has been crushed. He's down a piece and has no development. He wasn't counting on this after seeing the video!
So, what can we learn here? Many beginners and intermediate players focus on a specific trap, and if their opponent doesn’t fall for it, they’re stuck because they haven’t studied the opening well enough or understand basic principles. Traps can sometimes work, but don’t rely on them. You need to have studied the opening well and have a solid understanding of basic principles.
I’m not saying don’t play traps or tricky openings, my repertoire includes dozens of traps, but they should be seen as bonuses you might get. Don't depend on them. You need solid opening knowledge to set you up for success in the long run. } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🔍 Ignoring Opponent's Defense"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/5b2/2pp4/3P3P/2NBPN2/PP3PP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🔍 Ignoring Opponent's Defense"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/blWD2wKc"]
[FEN "rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/5b2/2pp4/3P3P/2NBPN2/PP3PP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #3: Ignoring Opponent's Defense

Pause for a moment in this position. What would you play as White if you had this in a game? Once you've got an answer, click the hint button for further instructions. }
1. Bxh7+?? { I’m guessing many of you probably rushed to say Bxh7+! A Greek gift, and after Black takes, you get Ng5+ and win, right? But... it’s actually a blunder! 😱
Now, to see why and learn from it, let’s dive a little deeper into this line. } 1... Kxh7 { Black captures, we expected this. Play Ng5+ now. } 2. Ng5+ Kg8 { Play Qh5. } 3. Qh5 { This looks winning, right? The queen threatens to take on f7 or go to h7. But hold on... } { [%csl Rh7,Rf7][%cal Rh5h7,Rh5f7] } 3... Be6! { Black defends the f7 pawn. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge6f7] } 4. Qh7+ Kf8 $19 { Black's king simply runs away! There's no attack here for White. After Qh8+, Black's king escapes to safety with Ke7. Now, White is just down a piece with no compensation whatsoever.
So, what can we learn from this? Don’t rush out moves when you see a tactic, especially longer ones like the Greek Gift. It’s crucial to consider your opponent’s defensive resources and not just play the first thing that comes to mind. Always pause and evaluate the full position before committing to a tactical sequence!
Now, what would have been the correct answer at the beginning of this chapter? Well, if you saw that Bxh7 didn't work, then you were correct! The best move dxc5 simply not allowing Black to play ...cxd4 (the e-pawn is pinned btw), and it's 100% equal game! } { [%cal Bf8e7,Rh7h8] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🚫 To TAKE is a MISTAKE"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🚫 To TAKE is a MISTAKE"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/siEfe1L2"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/1bBP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #4: To TAKE is a MISTAKE

This is THE most common beginner mistake ever. It's been popularized by GM Igor Smirnov with this easy-to-remember rhythm.

There are countless examples of this, but let’s look at a this common position form the Queen’s Gambit. In this position, the most popular move played by Black is Bxc3?

Many players will just exchange pieces and pawns automatically whenever they can. But most of the time, this is really bad, it doesn't help your position in any way whatsoever, and in fact, it helps your opponent! We'll see what happens... } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rb4c3] }
1... Bxc3+? 2. bxc3 $16 { And now let’s compare the position before and after Black took the knight.
Before, Black had some tension on our knight with the pin, and now he just freely gives that up. So, what advantages did Black actually get out of this exchange? ...Well, nothing!
What advantages did White gain?
1. White now has the bishop pair.
2. White’s center has been strengthened.
3. The a1 rook now has access to an open b-file.
4. The dark-squared bishop was previously stuck, but suddenly has a great new diagonal it can go to on a3.
All of this White got for free just because Black made one bad capture.
So, what can we learn here? Don’t exchange automatically, you’re only helping your opponent become more active. Keep the tension! And if your opponent really wants to trade, let him be the one to do it.
Of course, I’m not saying you should never take. You absolutely should if it wins material or gives you some kind of positional advantage. But always take a moment to think what you're getting out of it. :)
There were many good options for Black earlier, the most simple being O-O, getting the king out of the center but keeping the tension on the c3 knight.
You can also practice this scenario against the human-like AI Noctie here: https://go.noctie.ai/mdMDyct. This will help sharpen your positional understanding. 🧠 } { [%csl Gc1,Gc4,Yc3,Yd4,Ye3,Yf2][%cal Yf2e3,Ye3d4,Yc3d4,Ba1b1,Bb1b8,Rc1a3,Ra3f8] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 😬 Not Learning Basic Endgames"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "😬 Not Learning Basic Endgames"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/IqLYGd8v"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/4k3/8/8/4PK2/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #5: Not Learning Basic Endgames

This is one I’m definitely guilty of, I honestly didn't even fully understand the opposition until recently.

Many beginners and intermediate players focus more on learning traps and tactics (the tactic part is good tho, but other things also need some time), while completely ignoring endgames. I’m not saying you need to become an endgame master, especially as a beginner, but even the most basic endgames often get ignored, like the opposition. And the Lucena and Philidor are also worth learning for intermediate players, but they’re often ignored too.

Here’s a common basic opposition example. You'd be surprised how many players, both White and Black, mess this up in real games. The position is winning for White, but only if they have learned this endgame. }
1. e5?? { Just like that, in a single move, White has thrown away the win! White should have played Ke5, which is the only winning move, taking the opposition. Now Black can draw, but only if he knows this endgame too.
In this position, any move by Black holds the draw, but we’ll go with Ke6 for now since Lichess only allows 1 correct move. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ge7e6] } 1... Ke6 2. Ke4 { For now, just follow the arrows until something important comes up. All the moves currently hold the draw. } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge6e7] } 2... Ke7 3. Kf5 { Here, Black only has one move that holds the draw. :) } 3... Kf7! { Keeping the opposition! } { [%csl Re6,Rf6,Rg6][%cal Rf7e6,Rf7f6,Rf7g6] } 4. e6+ Ke7 { Ke8 was fine too, to be clear. } 5. Ke5 Ke8! { The only move that draws! Now, if the White king moves to f6 or d6, we can take the opposition! } { [%csl Bf8,Bd8][%cal Be8f8,Be8d8] } 6. Kf6 Kf8! { [%csl Re7,Rf7,Rg7][%cal Rf8e7,Rf8f7,Rf8g7] } 7. e7+ Ke8 8. Ke6 $10 { And it's a stalemate!
So what can we learn here? It's extremely important to have some basic endgame knowledge, or you would sweat through the entire game to gain an advantage... just to throw it all away in the end. :(
If you don't know basic endgames, I recommend checking out @NoseKnowsAll's endgame series:
Beginner Endgames You Must Know!: https://lichess.org/study/wukLYIXj/i8C1m7oU
Intermediate Endgames You Must Know!: https://lichess.org/study/UsqmCsgC/LwKRTWR5
And also, btw if you use Noctie, it allows you to practice essential endgames with the human-like ai, like Lucena, Philidor, and others. More information on that later. } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🐭 Just Reacting"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Garry Kasparov"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🐭 Just Reacting"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/7HIOKPft"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/1pq2ppp/p2pp3/4n1B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 1 11"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #6: Just Reacting

Many beginners and intermediate players will often react automatically to their opponent’s threats. For example, if the opponent attacks a knight, they’ll simply move it to safety. However, it’s many times much better to respond to threats by creating your own!

Let’s look at an example from a game between two World Champs you're probably familiar with. Fun fact: this was actually Mikhail Tal’s final game, and he even dragged himself out of his hospital bed to play. 😢 }
11. f4 { Tal kicks Kasparov's knight. In this position, many beginners would react to the threat by moving the knight to safety, with moves like Ng6, Nc3, Nc4, or Nd7. However, all of these are bad options. We won’t go into detail about each one here, as it would drift from our focus (but feel free to check the analysis later). For example, after Ng6, White follows with f5, hitting the knight again, Ne5 Qh5, and Black’s in a very uncomfortable situation. Nc3, Nc4 and Nd7 are responded with Nd5!! which is winning for White.
Instead, the much better option, and what Kasparov played in the game, is. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf4e5] } 11... h6! { Kasparov reacts to the threat by creating his own threat! Tal doesn't want to take the knight now, because Kasparov will take the bishop and gets the bishop pair with an incredibly useful open h-file. So, Tal is left no choice than to retreat the bishop. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh6g5] } (11... Nc4 12. Nd5 exd5 (12... Qc5 13. b4 Qa7) 13. exd5+ Kd7 14. Qg4+ f5 15. Qxf5#) (11... Nc6 12. Nd5 exd5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. exd5+) (11... Ng6 12. f5 Ne5 (12... Ne7 13. Qh5) 13. Qh5 $16) (11... Nd7 12. Nd5! exd5 13. exd5+ $18 { [%csl Re8,Gd8,Ge7][%cal Re1e8,Gg5d8] }) 12. Bh4 { I'm gonna let you think what's the best move here. ;) } (12. fxe5 hxg5 13. exd6 Bxd6 $19) 12... g5! { Yes! The knight was still attacked but we don't move it away just yet, we create another counter-threat! Now the bishop is attacked and we're also wanting to capture the f4 pawn, which eliminates the attacker of our knight, which allows him to happily stay on e5. } { [%csl Rh4,Rf4][%cal Rg5h4,Rg5f4] } 13. fxe5 { Tal decides to capture the knight. We capture the bishop. } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gg5h4] } (13. Bg3 gxf4 14. Bxf4) 13... gxh4 $15 { It’s a complicated position, but slightly better for Black. We have the bishop pair and an open g-file for the rook, much stronger than simply giving in to the threat by retreating.
If you're interested in checking out the full game, I have a in dept analysis form it in my annotated Mikhail Tal games collection: https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/e0k7Thp8
So, what can we learn here? Reacting to threats doesn’t always mean you have to defend. Often, you can hit back with your own threats. Make your opponent react to you!
Tho, that doesn’t mean you should never ever retreat a piece, sometimes it’s the best move! But don’t react automatically. Look for active options too. } { [%csl Gf8,Gc8][%cal Bh8g8,Bg8g1,Rd6e5] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 🧀 \"That Free Pawn\" Trap"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
