[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "🧀 \"That Free Pawn\" Trap"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/7dScdiPH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/1q1p4/2pP4/4P3/2N5/PPPB1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 4 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #7: 📘 "That Free Pawn" Trap (aka, the "Poisoned Pawn" Trap)

Often, when players see a "free" pawn, they rush to grab it immediately without considering the consequences. Here we have a position from the Smith-Morra Gambit where White has just played Nc3, leaving the b-pawn hanging. According to the database, half of players will take the b-pawn here. But let's see what happens next! }
5... Qxb2?? { It is rather tempting isn't? But now how can you punish Black? } 6. Rb1! { Yep! We cover all the queen's escape squares, leaving only a3 uncontrolled. } { [%csl Rb8,Rb7,Ba3][%cal Rb1b8,Bb2a3] } 6... Qa3 7. Nb5! { A fork! Black can resign. All of this happened because Black got too greedy for that pawn. This is an extreme example, but there are many cases where taking "that free pawn" can be a bad idea. For example, it could open up a file for your opponent to attack your castled king. Trust me, being up a pawn isn’t worth spending the rest of the game defending against attacks down that file.
But often it's more direct, like trapping a queen, or as we saw here, a nice fork. And just a quick note: if the b2 (or b7 for White) pawn looks "free," just don't take it, DON'T TAKE IT! Most of the time it’s poisoned.
So, what can we learn here? Always carefully consider whether taking a "free" pawn is worth it. Does it give your opponent compensation? Or is it poisoned, leading to your piece being trapped? } { [%csl Bc7,Ba3,Ga5][%cal Bb5c7,Bb5a3,Gd2a5] } *


