[FEN "r3k2r/bpp2bpp/p1n2n2/3pp3/6q1/1BNP2N1/PPP2PPP/R1B1QRK1 w kq - 6 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #8: Overlooking Hidden Pins

I've actually seen this very often (including myself making this mistake), and I think it's perhaps not really talked about much, so I decided to add it to this list.

And btw, thanks for still being here! I hope you're learning something useful! I know it took you a few minutes to get to this chapter, but it took me over a dozen hours across a week to annotate, investigate, and find these positions. So, if you’re enjoying the study, please leave a heart, it really helps me keep creating these! I appreciate it! 😊 }
10. h3?? { White wants to get rid of our queen since it’s annoyingly placed here. Can you find the correct response? } 10... Qxg3! $19 { Yep! It's a free piece! Black can't recapture because the f-pawn is pinned by our bishop. Very often players overlook this, because well, Qg3 placing the queen in front of the opponent's pawns isn't really a move you see that often.
So, what can we learn? Don’t overlook hidden pins! Even if a bishop is all the way on the other side of the board, it's still a long-range sniper. Always be aware of its line of fire! } { [%csl Rg3][%cal Rf2g3,Ga7g1] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: ⛔ One-Move Thinking"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "⛔ One-Move Thinking"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/Lo0TA6RE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3rr1k1/pp2bppp/1nq1pn2/6B1/4P3/1QPB1N2/PP4PP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #9: One-Move Thinking

This is another super common mistake amateurs make. They'll see a threat or move that "looks good", make the move... and that’s it. Without any thought about how the opponent might respond, how to follow up, or whether the move weakens their position in the long term.

This next example perfectly displays that kind of thinking. Let’s see how it goes... }
1. Ne5?? { White sees he can attack Black's queen now, and it looks pretty well placed in the center, so must be good right? But how does Black respond? } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Re5c6] } (1. e5? { Tho, not as losing, again an example of 1 move thinking. } 1... Qc5+ 2. Kh1 Ng4 $15 { Double attacking the pawn. But, more importantly, now the d5 square has been cleared giving Black's knight a nice square to jump to later on. e5 did not benefit White, it was just a 1-move threat. } { [%csl Re5,Gd5][%cal Rg4e5,Rc5e5,Gb6d5] } 3. Bf4 (3. Bxe7 Qxe7 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gb6d5] }) 3... Nd5) 1... Qc5+! { Black simply sidesteps the attack and forks the king and knight! This isn’t even hard to see or fancy tactic, it’s literally the most obvious response. If White had just looked a couple of moves ahead, he would've seen it coming, regardless of his level. Some better moves instead would have been the quiet Kh1! calmly avoiding any potential harmful checks, or Be3, rerouting to a more active square preparing Bd4.
So what can we learn here? Don’t think in just 1 move, think ahead! Make sure to consider what your opponent might respond with. Don’t rely on one-move threats, but ask yourself: does this move improve my position? Does it create long-term weaknesses to myself? Can I follow it up?
And as we see here, sometimes the move that looks the most “boring” is actually the best, as Kh1 was the top engine move a while ago! } { [%csl Re5,Rg1][%cal Rc5e5,Rc5g1] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 1: 😤 Tilt"]
[Date "2025.04.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 1"]
[ChapterName "😤 Tilt"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/NioqBWE9/F09THJYR"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.04.19"]
[UTCTime "11:57:58"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #10: Tilt

Wait... why aren't there any pieces on the board?! Because the next mistake isn't on the board, it's in your mind, don't go away yet, this might change your life.

Tilt is extremely common, even among advanced players and masters.
You win a few games, feel great... then lose one.
Instead of stopping, you'll continue playing, in mind: “Just one more. I’ll win it back.” Then another. And another, and so on.

Before you know it, you're angry and frustrated, you've lost all your hard-earned rating, need a new laptop (you threw it out of rage), and you start to hate chess.

How can we stop this? It really comes down to having a good mindset, but the easiest and most effective trick I learned (I believe from GM Noel Studer) is to set a limit on how much you play each day. The number depends on the time control and somewhat on you, but here's what I like: 3+0 blitz = max 7 games a day and 10+0 rapid = max 3 games a day.

This protects your rating, your sanity, your laptop, and your energy. You’re also much more likely to actually play better and improve, because you'll stay focused and won’t be too tired. And since you're not instatly clicking the "new game" button out of frustration and have more time, you can go analyze your games and learn from them.

And also, just a reminder that it’s totally fine to take a break. Even for a few weeks, a couple of months, or as long as you need. You’ll come back with a fresh mind and a renewed love for the game. 💗 }
 *


