[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🔀 Messing Up Tactic Variations"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[White "Lichess Puzzle"]
[Black "Bosburp"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "🔀 Messing Up Tactic Variations"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/QmdnSvhH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/ppp2pp1/3b1q1p/3P1n2/2B5/2P2Q2/PP3PPP/RNB1R1K1 b - - 1 13"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #1: Messing Up Tactic Variations

Here we have a position from a simple lichess puzzle I encountered not long ago. Pause for a moment in this position. What would you play as Black if you had this in a game?

Ok, do you have an answer in mind? Don't play it just yet! First, we'll analyze the mistake together. Click the hint button for further instructions. }
13... Bxh2+ { Within 5 seconds, I played this in the puzzle! I saw White's unprotected c4 bishop, and saw the Qh4 fork idea. I'd end up winning a pawn, expose White's king, and end up with a great position, right?
Was this your answer too? If yes, then I'm sorry to say that you made the same mistake as I did. Bxh2+ is a huge blunder. Black had a much better move. First, let’s see why this move doesn’t work. } { [%csl Gh4,Rc4,Rh2][%cal Gf6h4,Gh4c4,Gh4h2] } (13... Qh4! { Correct! But play Bxh2+ for the sake of the study. }) 14. Kxh2 { White of course takes the bishop. We'll play Qh4+, forking the king and bishop. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gf6h4] } 14... Qh4+ { [%csl Rh2,Rc4][%cal Rh4h2,Rh4c4] } 15. Kg1 { The king simply moves back to safety behind his pawns. } 15... Qxc4 $16 { We’ve come to the end of the variation. And well... Black isn’t even better here. Material is equal (White was up a pawn in the beginning), the queen is vulnerably placed which White can easily kick with tempo with moves like Na3 or Nd2, and the e1 rook nicely controls the e file.
Instead, Black could’ve had a winning position with the simple move 1...Qh4! (If that was your answer at the beginning of the chapter, respect! You didn't fall for the bait.)
White cannot both protect the bishop and stop Qxh2+, which threatens a deadly checkmating attack. White must play h3, and Black ends up with a free piece. Throwing in Bxf2+ had the right idea in mind, but it was the wrong execution!
Summing up the mistake: It’s when you see a tactic and immediately play it, without considering other move orders or variations. Often we overcomplicate things, but the solution might be much simpler.
So, what can we learn from this? Don't rush tactics. As we saw in Part 1, tactics might not work because we often ignore our opponents defensive resources. But as we see here, you might have the correct idea, but you need to make sure to execute the correct move order.
🎯 Head over to Noctie to test your understanding: https://go.noctie.ai/messing_up_tactics } { [%csl Rc4,Ge1][%cal Gb1d2,Gb1a3] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🤖 Autopilot Openings"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[White "Wes"]
[Black "You (Skilled Player)"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B40"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: French Variation"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "🤖 Autopilot Openings"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/RADCwI7N"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #2: Autopilot Openings

This is incredibly common. Many players learn an opening by memorizing the first 3-7 moves of the mainline, and then play those regardless of what the opponent is doing.

Let’s look at a realistic scenario. White, let’s call him Wes, plays the Italian against 1...e5: 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4

But what happens when Black doesn’t play 1...e5? Let's see how the game goes. }
1. e4 { Let's just say you're a Sicilian player, play c5. :) } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gc7c5] } 1... c5 2. Nf3 { Wes isn't familiar with the Sicilian, he'll just go for the same Italian moves, it probably works here too.
Play the French Variation by playing e6. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ge7e6] } 2... e6 3. Bc4? { Wes plays Bc4 because that’s what he has memorized. But pause and ask yourself: what is this bishop really doing on c4? It's useless here. It's aiming at a brick wall and becomes an easy target for us to hit with tempo. We can hit it with an upcoming d5 or b5 (after preparing with a6).
Fun fact: This is literally the second most popular move in the database.
There's a couple of good moves here including d5, Nc6, Nf6, but let's keep things simple and immediately take advantage of the bad bishop placement by playing a6 with the idea of supporting an upcoming b5, which expands on the queenside with tempo. } { [%csl Ye6,Yf7,Rc4,Ga6][%cal Bd7d5,Bb7b5,Ga7a6] } 3... a6 { Stockfish actually recommends White to just retreat the bishop to e2, accepting the fact that he has just wasted a move, it's too much of a target on c4. Wes begins to have some difficulties. He doesn't want to move the bishop back so he plays... } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5] } 4. a4 { Preventing a b5 pawn push. No problem, do you know how to continue? } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra4b5] } 4... d5 { Taking the center and kicking the bishop. } (4... Nf6 { Also good. but let's focus on the theme here of kicking the bishop away. }) 5. exd5 exd5 { And now the bishop is forced to move away anyway. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc5] } 6. Be2 { Here we can play the standard developing move Nf6. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gg8f6] } 6... Nf6 $15 { Black has quite an comfortable position here. Controls the center and has easy development (the bishops can easily move, castling is no problem). Of course, this cannot be called winning, just slightly better for Black (which is great considering White begins with a slight edge). Black scores 53% compared to White 43%.
So what can we learn here? Don't blindly follow your memorized moves without paying attention to what your opponent is doing. Even if you are not familiar with you're opponents' opening, you still have to make moves that make sense. Ask yourself: why am I playing this? Not just “I do this against ----, so I'll just do it here too.”
This is exactly why when learning openings it's sooooo important to not rely on pure memorization but instead actually understand the ideas and plans in them.
Many players will call the London a "stupid brain-off system opening" but as we've seen here, they're unconsciously doing the exact same thing. :)
📖 Best way to learn openings is interactively. Learn the Sicilian Dragon with Noctie: https://go.noctie.ai/learn-sicilian-dragon
📖 Also check out https://chessbook.com/?ref=bosburp to improve your openings. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5,Gf6,Rc1,Rb1][%cal Bf8d6,Bc8g4,Bb8c6,Be8g8,Bd8e7,Bd5d4] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🍴 Missing Pawn Fork Tactics"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[White "Wes"]
[Black "You (Skilled Player)"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C55"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Two Knights Defense"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "🍴 Missing Pawn Fork Tactics"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/ysP0jZH6"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #3: Missing Pawn Fork Tactics

Pawn forks can come at any time: opening, middlegame, endgame. But since our last chapter was set in the opening, let’s take a look at an example set in the Four Knights.

You know how to get there, right? I won't be commenting for the first few moves. :) }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Good! We've reached the Four Knights Game! Here, surprisingly, the most popular move, accounting for 34% of games is a mistake. If you're a beginner, you probably won't be expecting this. } 4. Bc4? { There are quite a few good moves in this position for White: d4, h3, a4, Bb5. But this seemingly innocent move, 4.Bc4, which looks very natural, developing the bishop to its most active square and prepares to castle.
It’s an immensely. popular. mistake. Played 43 million times on lichess alone.
Can you find the only acceptable move for Black? } 4... Nxe4! { Yes! Sacrificing the knight?! Don't worry, it's only temporary. Unfortunately most players as Black miss this, probably because they do the mistake covered in the previous chapter. :( } 5. Nxe4 d5! { We win back our sacrificed piece with a pawn fork! Now, you might be thinking that Black isn't even up in material, so what's the point. But this is actually a very favorable trade for us. Let’s play a few more moves and you’ll see why.
White has a few options here, but only one doesn't give Black an immediate significant advantage. I’ll cover all the possible responses later when you enter "analysis board" mode, but for now, let’s look at the most popular one. } 6. Bxd5? { The most popular move, but a mistake. What would you play in this position? } (6. Bd3! { The best move! But note that 4. Bc4 was already a mistake and this wouldn't have been necessary. The position is now 0.0. } 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6 $10 { It is equal according to the engine, but as we can see from the winrates, Black has an easier time playing here. White's LSB is not awkwardly placed here, and will in many cases trade itself for the c6 knight giving Black the bishop pair. } { [%csl Re4,Rc1][%cal Bf7f5,Be8g8,Bc8g4] }) (6. Bb5? { Another popular try, but perhaps the worst. } 6... dxe4 { [%csl Rf3][%cal Re4f3] } 7. Nxe5 { White thinks he can exploit the pin, but Black has another trick up his sleeve. } 7... Qg5! { Boom! If the knight ever move, the queen takes the bishop. If White defends the knight, Black take g2. } { [%csl Rg2,Gb5,Ge5][%cal Rg5e5,Rg5g2,Re5b5] }) 6... Qxd5! { Let's pause a moment. and check out the position. We now have the bishop pair (which can develop very nicely), a strong pawn in the center, and the queen is placed in the center hitting the knight. } { [%csl Ge5,Gc8,Gf8] } 7. Nc3 { The knight retreats and hits our queen. Most players here will retreat the queen back to d8, but I really don’t like that. Instead, let’s play Qd6. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rc3d5,Gd5d6] } (7. d3 Bg4 $17 { [%csl Bc8,Bf5][%cal Be8c8,Bf7f5] }) 7... Qd6 $17 { This keeps the queen more active and supports our next idea: Bg4, followed by castling queenside, and launching a kingside attack with moves like f5, Qg6, and h5. Black has a nice edge.
So what can we learn here? Always keep pawn forks in mind! Sometimes you'll blunder them directly, but they can also show up in more disguised forms, like this one.
Also, we see that tactics aren't always about material. Often you'll get advantageous trades. Surely, we’ll all still blunder pawn forks now and then, but hopefully after seeing this, you’ll be a little more alert next time. :)
Click the "Analyze Board" for a few more comments and positions.
⚔ Can you win this against a humanlike bot? https://go.noctie.ai/pawn-forks } { [%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Bc8g4,Be8c8,Bf7f5,Bd6g6,Bh7h5] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 😵 Tunnelvision"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[White "Deep Fritz"]
[Black "Vladimir Kramnik"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "BOT"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "😵 Tunnelvision"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/0LieG4V3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "5N1k/q5p1/7p/4P3/pp2Q3/8/1P4PP/2b4K b - - 0 34"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #4: Tunnel Vision

Tunnel vision, a.k.a chess blindness is something we've all experienced. This happens when you're focused on a single idea and stop looking at the rest of the board.

Here we have a painful example, from none other than former World Champion Vladimir Kramnik, back in 2006. He's playing the computer Deep Fritz. }
34... Qe3 { An interesting idea! Kramnik threatens a mate in 1 on the backrank and offers a queen trade. It looks like Deep Fritz has to capture the queen to stop the mate, and once the queens are off the board, Kramnik would be left with a winning endgame. White won't be able to stop one of the queenside pawns from promoting. Although there's one problem here, which we will see on the next move. } { [%csl Re4,Re1][%cal Re3e4,Re3e1] } 35. Qh7#! { It's checkmate! The first position shown was actually 100% a draw. Black could have played the simple Kg8 stopping the checkmate. But Kramnik was too focused on his idea, he stopped looking what was going on on the board!
Sooo, how do we stop tunnel vision? Well, that's a hard question, and we're all human so we probably won’t avoid it all the time. However we can reduce how often this happens. Here are some of my tips:
First of all, go through a quick mental checklist. Ask yourself questions like: "What is my opponent threatening?", "Are there any mating threats?", "Are any pieces hanging?", "Any weak pawns or squares?".
Second, always have multiple candidate moves in mind (In normal positions. Of course, you don't have to do this in the opening but make sure not to do mistake #2). I recommend about 3. Even when you're recapturing. This helps you avoid locking into just 1 idea. Then slowly dismiss the moves that don't work or are, according to you, worst than you're other candidate move.
This sounds like really a lot of work, so that's how we move on to my third tip which is play longer time controls. That's where you familiarize yourself with this method. And in time, it'll become second nature. Then you can cary it over to faster games too.
Once again, we're all human, so we'll blunder now and then. As we saw from the example, even the best do. But by following these tips, we’ll blunder a lot less. :) } (35. Qxe3 Bxe3) *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 👶 Babysitting with High Value Pieces"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "👶 Babysitting with High Value Pieces"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/kmplz5Jl"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r3kb1r/pp3pp1/4pn1p/3pNb2/3q1B2/8/P1PNQPPP/1R3RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #5: Babysitting with High Value Pieces

First of all, thanks for still being here! You're halfway through the study! I hope you're learning something useful! I know it took you a few minutes to get to this chapter, but it took me many hours to annotate, investigate, and find these positions. So, if you’re enjoying the study, please leave a heart, it really helps me keep creating these! I appreciate it! :)

We have here the following position, take some time to look at it. You might notice White's bishop is hanging on f4, but after further examination you should see that we're unable to take it because of White's threat: Qb5+, which is very dangerous because Black will take b7 and follow up with Nc6, and our king is very vulnerable.

So, we have to stop Qb5+. That means covering the b5 square. But now we have the crucial question: with what piece do we defend b5?

There are 2 options: Qa4 or a6. Which do you pick? :) } { [%csl Ya6,Ga4,Rb5][%cal Ya7a6,Gd4a4,Re2b5] }
1... a6! { Yes! This is the correct way to defend b5. Our queen is kept in an active position, attacking f4. We'll go through a few more moves... } { [%csl Gd4,Rb5][%cal Ga6b5] } (1... Qxf4 2. Qb5+ Kd8 3. Qxb7 Rc8 4. Ndf3 $16 { [%csl Rf7,Rc6][%cal Be5f7,Be5c6] }) (1... Qa4? { Nope! } 2. Rxb7 Be7 3. Ndf3 $16) 2. Rxb7 { Looks scary, but there's actually nothing to worry about, the a-pawn has everything under control. } { [%csl Rf7,Rb5,Ga6][%cal Re5f7,Ra6b5] } 2... Qxf4 { Yes, it's safe! } 3. Nxf7 Rh7 $17 { And here, Black is much better! The king is actually very safe here. g5 is coming, which trades off some of White's annoying pieces on the 7th rank.
So, what can we learn here? Try not to make your high-value pieces defend. Especially your queen, she's your most powerful attacker, not a babysitter. You don’t want her tied down defending a pawn or covering one square for the rest of the game.
Generally, the higher value a piece, the worse a defender it is. It can be more easily deflected and you're wasting it's potential. So, when you can, leave the defensive duties to your pawns, they're just 1 point, instead of using you 9 point piece or rook (5 points). Sometimes it's even better to sacrifice a pawn than to passively defend it with a valuable piece.
Of course, keep in mind, all rules have exceptions, and that's how we move on to #6.
Also, thanks to @CheckRaiseMate. I've learned this principal from one of his blogs. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra6b5,Bg7g5,Bf8d6] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🙈 Following Principles... Blindly"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "🙈 Following Principles... Blindly"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/dWx9nA8T"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/1q2p3/2ppP3/3P4/3B1Nn1/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #6: Following Principles... Blindly

All beginners will be taught basic principals like: controls the center, don't put your knights on the rim, castle early, and always capture towards the center... These principals are all good, but if you only rely on principles and stop actually thinking about what’s happening on the board, you’ll suffer for it.

Here we got a position form one of my favorite openings, the Two Knights Attack against the Caro-Kann! I got a whole course on that if you're interested: https://lichess.org/study/64DHMYix/VjAPbAEL

In this position Black has just played Nxg3, and White needs to recapture. Many beginners capture with the h-pawn, following the principal of capturing towards the center. But actually the best move here is to take with the f-pawn! }
9. fxg3! { Capturing with the f-pawn is very beneficial, since we plan to castle kingside. This will give us an open f-file for our rook, making it incredibly active. An open h-file wouldn’t be as useful since we won't have a rook placed there anyway.
To be clear hxg3 isn't that bad, it's just wasted potential. Interestingly, fxg3 has a winrate of 59% compared to hxg3 of 47%! This shows that by blindly following principals, many players have sacrificed their winning chances! :)
Let's go further a few more moves. } (9. hxg3?! cxd4 10. O-O $10 { Meh, that open h-file isn't exactly helping. }) 9... cxd4 { Black has won a pawn, but that's not a major concern since it’s weak and can be easily targeted later. Our priority right now should be on development. } { [%csl Rd4] } 10. O-O! { We don't need to worry about any discovered checks, as our bishop is solidly blocking the d4-pawn. In the near future, we should play Kh1 tho, which will free our bishop from being tied down on d3. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Bg1h1] } (10. Nxd4? { With the idea after Qxd4 bb5+ a discovered attack. But Black is not forced to capture, he can play a standard developing move like Bc5, Nc6, or Nd7 and White will have a lot of trouble castling. } 10... Nd7 { Simply blocking the potential check. The knight is now hanging. } 11. Nf3 $17 { White now cannot castle for a very long time. Very unnecessary, only because of the greed to take the pawn right away. Development comes first. } { [%csl Rf2,Gb6] }) 10... Nc6 { And finally, play a3 here. } { [%csl Ga3][%cal Ga2a3] } 11. a3! { Very important! We want to avoid any trouble with Nb4, so playing a3 will effectively stop any counterplay from Black.
As you can see, we benefit greatly by fxg3.
So, what can we learn here? Principles are meant to guide you, not do the thinking for you. If you see a move that clearly leads to a better outcome, yet breaks principals, go for it. But, it's very important to be able to justify to yourself why. Knowing when to break the principals comes from experience, but never follow them blindly.
⚔ Sharpen your attacking skills in this position: https://go.noctie.ai/principles } { [%csl Gf1,Rd4,Rc8,Re8,Rf8][%cal Bc1f4,Bf3g5,Bg1h1,Bd3e2,Ra3b4,Bb2b4] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🎭 ♞♝ = ♖ + ♙?"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "🎭 ♞♝ = ♖ + ♙?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/9LnEtpsY"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1p1N1/2B1P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 7 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #7: Misunderstanding Piece Value

This is one many beginners will make, especially after learning the basic piece value. I used to this myself all the time lol.

Many players think: "a bishop and knight are each worth 3 points, so trading those for a rook (5) and pawn (1) is an equal trade right?"

Well that's definitely not always true, as we'll see. Let's look at the board.

The king isn't happy in the center, and f7 is being attacked. What do you do? }
5... O-O { Good! Here the third most popular move in this position is the mistake we'll cover. But this same idea shows up in many other positions too.
Let's see what happens. } 6. Nxf7? { White takes our pawn! It's defended, so we can simply recapture. } 6... Rxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 $17 { And now usually players think, "I've made a good trade. It's equal material but I've managed to ruin the king's safety a bit."
First of all, the king is completely safe here, there's no way to attack it. Second, is it an equal trade? Not at all! The bishop and knight were White's most active pieces on the board, and he's given them away for a rook and pawn which weren’t even doing anything.
Two minor pieces coordinate much better than a single rook. They can work beautifully together. Another factor to note is: this is the opening/early middlegame. Rooks aren't powerful at this stage yet, they become stronger towards the endgame, once the files get opened up.
So, what can we learn here? Material value is only relative. Their true value always changes depending on the position.
This is why often you'll high-level players sacrifice the exchange (rook for a minor piece) without any immediate tactical justification. Because in that specific position, the minor piece had more impact on the position than the rook could ever have.
If you want some cool stuff about piece value, check out this cool blog I recently read by @TotalNoob69: https://lichess.org/@/TotalNoob69/blog/the-real-value-of-chess-pieces/bpmshLXx
🎯 Practice converting this against Noctie: https://go.noctie.ai/2minors_vs_rook } { [%csl Gf7] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🔁 Recapturing Without Thinking"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[White "Aron Nimzowitsch"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "🔁 Recapturing Without Thinking"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/tpnWUx91"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "7k/p3n1pp/1p3r2/1PP2p2/P2Pn3/3b1Bb1/1B4P1/R1R4K w - - 1 33"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #8: Recapturing Without Thinking

Often, we tend to recapture automatically, thinking that it's forced. However, more often than you might think, there is a better move on the board. Instead of playing the expected move, we can often throw in an in-between move, or Zwischenzug (German) or Intermezzo in Italian.

Here's a simple straightforward example from a game between two chess legends: Aron Nimzowitsch and Jose Raul Capablanca. }
33. Bxe4 { Nimzowitsch captures the knight, expecting Capablanca to recapture it. But can you find the better move, which was played in the game? } 33... Bf2! { Yes! Taking away the g1 square form the king, setting up the unstoppable Rh6#. White can only delay it for a few moves.
In the game, Nimzowitsch resigned here. } { [%csl Rg1,Gh6][%cal Rf2g1,Bf6h6] } (33... fxe4) 34. Bxf5 { Rh6 cannot be played yet, because of Bh3. } 34... Nxf5! { The threat is again renewed. } { [%csl Rh6][%cal Rf6h6] } (34... Bxf5?? { Allows Ra3/Rc3 to block on h3. } { [%csl Ga3][%cal Ga1a3] }) 35. g3 { [%csl Bg2][%cal Bh1g2] } 35... Be4+ 36. Kh2 Rh6# { Checkmate! To be clear, if Black would have recaptured the bishop he'd still get a winning position. But why complicate things? :)
So, what can we learn here? Don't always rush to play the expected response, like recapturing. Although, often recapturing will be the best move, make sure to pause a moment and consider alternatives too! Even if it just gives you an extra tempo. } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 😨 It Ain’t Over Till It’s Over"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
[White "Carl Pilnick"]
[Black "Samuel Reshevsky"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Mistakes: Part 2"]
[ChapterName "😨 It Ain’t Over Till It’s Over"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ieCOdimW/1jC6K68f"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/kp6/p7/P4Qp1/7p/4q3/8/7K b - - 3 92"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.29"]
[UTCTime "11:54:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Mistake #9: Overconfidence

Often once we've got a clearly winning position, we tend to start playing faster and pay less attention. I personally remember a painful OTB experience. I was up a rook in an endgame, so I started blitzing out moves, and then captured a pawn with my queen... which was defended.

Here we have another very painful example from the 1942 US championship. This is move 93, and Reshevsky has a fully winning position, being up 3 pawns. All he has to do is push the pawns to their promotion square. }
92... g4?? { This one move cost him the entire game! White has a miraculous save here! Can you find it? } 93. Qf2!! { Sacrificing the queen! But if Black takes, it's stalemate! If Black doesn't take, White wins the queen.
This must have been incredibly painful for Samuel Reshevsky, since he fought for 93 moves to get a winning postition, but 1 mistake can make a huge difference. Also, fun fact Reshevsky was victim to these swindles multiple times: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1252040 } 93... Qxf2 $10 { Stalemate.
So, what can we learn here? It ain’t over till it’s over. Don't lose your focus, even a winning position demands full attention. } { [%csl Rh1] } *


[Event "Top Mistakes: Part 2: 🎓 Not Learning From Your Games"]
[Date "2025.06.29"]
