{ ⚜ Welcome ladies and gentlemen, to my newest study! Hi, I'm Bosburp! ⚜

This study is a sequel to my previous study: lichess.org/study/dRde5aVj. We continue our journey in exploring the most beautiful chess moves played in history. We'll be viewing these as puzzles, try to find the brilliant moves played in the actual game!

If you're not in the mood for hard thinking, feel free to jump directly to "notes chapter" following each puzzle, where you'll find full explanations, so you can sit back, enjoy, and maybe you'll learn something from them.

I won’t be spoiling anything with annotations or arrows during the puzzles. All the explanations will be added in the chapter following the puzzle, so you can fully focus on finding the moves yourself if you want. :)

I've also included a link to the full game in each chapter.

If you enjoy this study, please give it a heart 💜 under the pinned comment! It helps more players discover this study and adds it to your favorites so you can always find it easily. 600 likes, and I'll try to prepare Volume 3. Sequels usually don't get popular, but maybe we can break that?

If you have any questions or feedback, feel free to DM me!

Let's dive in...hit the space bar. }
 *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume II: Runau vs Schidt - 1972"]
[Date "2025.07.28"]
[White "Ralf Runau"]
[Black "Lothar Schmidt"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume II"]
[ChapterName "Runau vs Schidt - 1972"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/JQKJOhPn/JpnZLGXe"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2kr1bnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3P3q/2P3b1/5N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQ - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.28"]
[UTCTime "13:29:11"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Qe5+ 9. Be3! Qxb2 10. O-O!! (10. Nd2 { Also a perfectly fine move. Although we get something prettier in the game. }) 10... Qxa1 11. dxc6!! Rxd1 12. cxb7+! Kb8 13. Rxd1 c6 14. Bxc6! Kc7 15. Rd7+ Kxc6 16. b8=N#!! { 🔥 Before we continue, check out this special collection of the most beautiful chess moves, curated by IM & FIDE Senior Trainer Jesper Hall: https://go.noctie.ai/beautiful_moves 🔥 } *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume II: Runau vs Schidt - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.28"]
[White "Ralf Runau"]
[Black "Lothar Schmidt"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume II"]
[ChapterName "Runau vs Schidt - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/JQKJOhPn/ej9lyNjZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2kr1bnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3P3q/2P3b1/5N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQ - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.28"]
[UTCTime "13:29:11"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1507516 Perhaps the most visually stunning game of all time.

White has just advanced the d-pawn. Currently, it isn't much of a threat because it's pinned by the rook. But as we will see it will play the most important role in the game. }
7... Bxf3? { With the idea of removing the defender of e5, preparing to play Qe5+ on the next move. } { [%csl Ge5] } (7... e6! { Much better. Challenging the much-too-advanced-d-pawn. Also the DSB really wants to get developed. } 8. O-O { The d-pawn cannot move, it's pinned. } 8... exd5 9. h3 (9. cxd5?? { Allows Black's rook to become incredibly powerful including gaining tempo on the queen. } 9... Rxd5 $17 { Black's rook controls the d-file, it can also easily shuffle along the 5th rank. } { [%csl Rd1,Gd5,Gg4][%cal Rd5d1,Bf8d6] }) 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Qe5 11. cxd5 Nd4 $10 { An equal game. Although, probably easier to play as Black considering his slightly better development (strong d rook, flexible queen) and White's isolated d-pawn is an easy target. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Rd4f3] }) 8. Bxf3 Qe5+ { Giving check to the king. Black assumes that each way White blocks the check has it's drawbacks. See variations below. } 9. Be3! { The beginning of our brilliant sequence. White sacrifices the d-pawn to avoid long-term drawbacks listed in the variations below. } { [%csl Rb2] } (9. Be2? { Puts the bishop under the pin. Now Black can start adding pressure to the d-pawn, making use of both pins, and will eventually win it. } 9... e6 { The d-pawn is paralyzed. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Re6d5] } 10. Nc3 { An attempt to defend it, although, it doesn't work for long. } 10... exd5 { Simplifying. } 11. cxd5 Nf6 $17 { White has no defenders left. The pawn is lost. } { [%csl Rd5] }) (9. Qe2? { Gives Black an advantageous queen trade. Black was down in development anyway. } 9... Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 Nb4 $15 { An upcoming e6 will undermine White's center. It's a relatively equal game. } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Be7e6,Bg8f6] }) (9. Kf1? { With the obvious drawback of losing castling rights. } 9... Nd4 { Black has a comfortable position. } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Rd4f3,Be7e6,Bg8f6] }) 9... Qxb2 { Black takes the pawn, likely happy he's won a pawn. Although this is not at all bad for White, as he gets plenty of compensation. } (9... e6 { Not as effective as after Be2. } 10. O-O exd5 11. cxd5 { The f3 bishop is a defender of the d-pawn. } { [%csl Gf3] }) 10. O-O!! { He sacrifices the rook! Runau must have calculated the whole upcoming sequence already, as otherwise O-O doesn't work. } (10. Nd2! { Also worth noting that this is a perfectly playable move, although not as aggressive as O-O. The rook is defended, and now dxc6 becomes a threat since the pin has been broken. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rd5c6] } 10... Nd4 11. Bxd4 Qxd4 12. O-O $16 { A very comfortable position. White gets an open g file aiming at the Black king. Additionally, White's has much more flexible development. } { [%csl Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Gf3,Rb7][%cal Ba1b1,Rb1b8,Bd1b3,Bd1c2,Bf1e1] } 12... e6 { Just a quick line worth showing. } 13. dxe6! { Sacrificing the knight! } { [%csl Rd2] } 13... Qxd2 14. Bxb7+!! Kxb7 15. Rb1+ Kc8 16. Qf3 { Threatening checkmate in 1 on a8. There isn't anything Black can do to stop WHite's queen from infiltrating. } { [%csl Ra8] } 16... fxe6 17. Qb7+ Kd7 18. Rfd1 $18) 10... Qxa1 { Black takes the bait. Notice how White's bishop pair is aiming at the kingside. } { [%csl Ge3,Gf3][%cal Be3a7,Yf3a8] } 11. dxc6!! { Sacrificing the queen! The only move that works! At this point Black really doesn't have a choice but take the queen and hope White's attack doesn't work out. } 11... Rxd1 (11... bxc6 { Wouldn't have prolonged the suffering. } 12. Qa4 $18 { With various mating ideas. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rf3c6,Ba4a6] }) 12. cxb7+! { An important intermezzo! The pawn's incredibly valuable, it cannot be taken. } 12... Kb8 { Moving on to the d-file allows White to play Rxd1+ and follow that up with promoting the pawn. } 13. Rxd1! { Threatening checkmate in 1. Notice how Black's entire kingside is useless. } { [%csl Rd8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Rd2d8,Gd1d8] } 13... c6 { Creating an escape square on c7 and cutting off the LSB from defending the b pawn. } { [%cal Rb8c7,Rb8b7] } 14. Bxc6! { Important! The b-pawn must be defended! It's White's most valuable asset. Now there isn't really much Black can do as White's rook will soon move to either d8 or d7 depending on what Black does. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gc6b7] } 14... Kc7 { Black's tries this last move to survive a bit longer, not allowing Rd8+ followed by b8=Q+. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Rc7d8] } 15. Rd7+! { [%csl Rc6] } 15... Kxc6 (15... Kb8 16. Rd8+ Kc7 17. b8=Q+ Kxc6 18. Qc8#) 16. b8=N#!! { The final flourish, a knight promotion checkmate! You don't see that everyday! } (16. b8=Q?? Kxd7 { Not at all clear! With perfect play this should be winning for White, but it's very easy to blunder into a draw. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Ra1b1] }) *


