[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/1b2qppp/pb2pn2/1p2P3/1P3P2/P1NB4/1B2Q1PP/R4R1K b - - 2 20"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.28"]
[UTCTime "13:29:11"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1119679 }
20... Ng4! { Bringing another piece closer to the kingside attack, also opening up the queen. Notice Black magnificent bishop pair both aiming at the kingside. } { [%csl Rh2,Gb6,Gb7][%cal Be7h4,Bh4h2] } 21. Be4 { A good defensive move, trying to exchange to LSBs, thus removing one attacker. A good principle to keep in mind, if you're being attacked, try to trade pieces! However, Black has another idea. } { [%csl Rb7] } 21... Qh4! { Bringing to queen to the party. Qxh7# is a threat. } { [%csl Rh2,Gb7][%cal Rh4h2] } (21... Nxh2 { Also works, but not as easily as what was played in the game. } 22. Qh5 Bxe4 23. Nxe4 Nxf1 24. Rxf1 Rc2 { Black still has to convert this into a win. }) 22. g3 { White defends h7 and attacks the queen. Now Rubinstein releases one of the most brilliant sequences in history. } { [%csl Gh2][%cal Rg3h4,Ge2h2] } (22. h3 Rxc3 23. Bxc3 Bxe4 24. Qxe4 (24. Qxg4 Qxg4 25. hxg4 Rd3 26. Kh2 Rxc3) 24... Qg3 25. hxg4 Qh4#) 22... Rxc3!! { Three pieces are hanging! } { [%csl Rh4,Rc3,Rb7] } 23. gxh4 { White takes the queen as he sees taking the rook leads to mate in 3. If Rubinstein doesn't find the following move, it's a draw or White gets a winning position. } (23. Bxb7 Rxg3 $19 { A crushing position, WHite won't survive long. } { [%cal Rg3h3,Rh3h1,Gh4h1] }) (23. Bxc3 { Mate in 3. } 23... Bxe4+ 24. Qxe4 Qxh2#) 23... Rd2!! { He finds it of course! Why else did he play Rxc3? ;)
Not enough pieces were hanging, he throws in an extra rook. The point is that the queen gets deflected from defending the LSB. } { [%csl Rg4,Rb7,Rc3,Rd2] } 24. Qxd2 (24. Bxb7 Rxe2 { Rxh7# } { [%csl Rh2][%cal Re2h2] } 25. Bg2 Rh3! { Adding an attacker on h7. The bishop cannot take because then the other rook takes h7#. White can only delay checkmate for 3 moves. } { [%cal Rh3h2] }) (24. Qxg4 Bxe4+ 25. Rf3 Rxf3 26. Qxf3 Bxf3#) 24... Bxe4+ 25. Qg2 Rh3! { Checkmate by Rxh2 is unavoidable. Checkmate will come at 3 moves at most. The queen is pinned, so it isn't defending h2. What a game! } { [%csl Rh2,Rh1,Re4][%cal Rh3h1] } (25... Bxg2+?? { No no no. Remember Black has sacrificed 8 points in material and capturing gives White another 3 points. Winning a queen really isn't going to compensate for that. }) *


