[FEN "1k1r2r1/p1p3q1/2p2p2/3pn2p/1P1b2b1/1QN3B1/P1P2PPP/1R2RBK1 b - - 1 23"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.28"]
[UTCTime "13:29:11"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1002083 From a very old game played in 1889. }
23... h4! { The beginning of an incredible combination 8 moves deep. Black kicks the bishop away from the kingside, planning to break open the g file. } 24. Bxh4 (24. Bf4 Nf3+! 25. Kh1 Nd2 26. Bxd2 (26. Re7 { Moving the queen or capturing the knight leads to Bf3, so White must deflect the queen away from the attack. } 26... Nxb3 (26... Qxe7 27. Bxd2 { Black's obviously better, but it isn't over yet. }) 27. Rxg7 Rxg7 28. Rxb3 $19 { Black's up material with a great position. }) 26... Bf3 $19 { Black cannot stop checkmate. The d-pawn is over attacked. It cannot capture because of Qg1#, neither can it advance because of the pin. } { [%csl Rg2] }) 24... Nf3+!! { Crushing open the g-file! } 25. gxf3 (25. Kh1 Qh7! { Nxh4 is possible, but this is even better. } { [%csl Rh2,Rh4][%cal Rh7h2] } 26. Bg3 Nxh2 27. Bxh2 Rh8 { Checkmate is unstoppable. } { [%csl Rh2][%cal Rh8h2] }) 25... Bxf3+! { A discovered check and not allowing the king to run to the corner. } 26. Bg3 Qxg3+!! 27. hxg3 Rxg3+! { The f-pawn is pinned. } 28. Kh2 Bxf2! { A quiet yet necessary move. Defending the rook and preparing for Rh8. } { [%csl Bg3][%cal Bf2g3,Rd8h8] } 29. Bh3 Rxh3+! { Opening the h-file. } (29... Rh8 { Also would have worked, but a bit longer and not as beautiful, no? }) 30. Kxh3 Rh8# { Checkmate! Each piece worked together beautifully. } { [%csl Rh1,Bg3,Yg2,Yg4][%cal Rh8h1,Bf2g3,Yf3g2,Yf3g4] } *


