17... f6 18. Bh6! Rf7 19. Nb4!! axb4 20. Qxd6!! Qd7 21. Qd5!! Kf8 22. Rxg7! Qxd5 23. Rg8+ Kxg8 24. Re8+ Rf8 25. Rxf8# *


[Event "Pure Brilliancy: Volume II: Korchmar vs Poliak - Notes"]
[Date "2025.07.28"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pure Brilliancy: Volume II"]
[ChapterName "Korchmar vs Poliak - Notes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/JQKJOhPn/QJ8CSTzW"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3b1rk1/1pp2ppp/r2n4/p2N1q2/3Q1B2/6R1/PPP2PPP/4R1K1 b - - 1 17"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.07.28"]
[UTCTime "13:29:11"]

{ Full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1269834

White's attacking here. The g3 rook is perfectly placed here aiming at g7. Qxg7# is a threat. } { [%csl Rg7,Gg3] }
17... f6 { Black must obviously stop the threat. This is the only option as Bf6 loses due to the g-pawn pin. The following brilliant sequence even takes Stockfish some effort. } 18. Bh6! { White makes use of the pin! Adding pressure on g7. } { [%csl Rg7,Gg3,Gh6] } 18... Rf7 { Black defends g7 and takes the rook out of the pin. (the g pawn can advance now). The drawback is that it has left as a defender of e8. If White's rook comes there, the game ends quickly (1. Re8+ Rf8 2. Rxg7+ Kh8 3. Rxf8# I'll be referring to this often). The square is now only defended by the d6 knight. } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Re1e8] } (18... c5 { A reasonable attempt. Although the g-pawn is left hanging so this doesn't work. } 19. Rxg7+ { An intermezzo. } 19... Kh8 20. Qd1 { The queen can retreat to a safe square. White's advantage is obvious. } { [%csl Gd5,Gg7,Gh6,Rh8,Rf8] }) 19. Nb4!! { The only move that breaks through! White sees that the d6-knight is crucial for Black's survival, so he plans to get rid of it! The knight was a blockade for Qxd6, so now it moves out of the way while gaining tempo hitting the a6 rook. } { [%csl Gd6,Re8][%cal Gd4d6,Re1e8,Yd6e8,Rb4a6] } 19... axb4 { Black takes the horse, as other alternates don't look attractive either. This leads to forced mate. } (19... Ra8 { Saving the rook, but again the Qxd6 threat has not been dealt with. } 20. Qxd6! { Taking the queen leads to the mate mentioned above. } 20... Be7 { The only move that survives. A key difference now is that the a8 rook controls the 8th rank, thus Rxe7 doesn't work compared to the move 20 variation. } { [%cal Ra8h8] } 21. Qd5 Qxd5 22. Nxd5) (19... Qd7 20. Nxa6 { White just takes it. } 20... bxa6 21. Qd5 $18 { Up material with a great attacking position. Should be an easy win. }) 20. Qxd6!! { The defender of d8 has been removed! } { [%csl Re8][%cal Ge1e8] } 20... Qd7 { A nice try. Black sees that taking the queen leads to the checkmate mentioned above. The queen now covers e8. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Gd7e8] } (20... cxd6 21. Re8+ Rf8 22. Rxg7+ Kh8 23. Rxf8#) (20... Rxd6 21. Re8+ Rf8 22. Rxg7+ Kh8 23. Rxf8#) (20... Be7 21. Rxe7! { X-raying through the rook aiming at g7. The poor pawn now has 3 attackers. Also Qd8+ and re8+ are threats. Black can't deal with all of them. It's forced checkmate. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Re7e8,Rd6d8] }) 21. Qd5!! { A brilliant key move! It's the only move that continues the attack. Other moves like Qxb4 or Qd2 give Black time defend with Rd6, then White's attack is gone. The queen pins the f7 rook, thus it no longer defends g7. Again, the queen cannot be taken because e8 would be left uncovered. } { [%csl Rg8,Rf7,Gg7][%cal Yd5g8] } (21. Qxd7?? { Blunders into a draw. Remember! if you're attacking you don't want to trade of material! } 21... Rxd7 $10 { White no longer has any attack. Re8+ doesn't lead to anything because the king now has f7 as an escape square. } { [%cal Bg8f7] }) 21... Kf8 { Black moves his king out of the pin and covers e8. Now when it looks like all problems have been solved, White strikes with... } { [%cal Rf8e8] } 22. Rxg7!! { Sacrificing the rook! After Rxg7, Black has self-pinned his rook, leaving the queen hanging. } 22... Qxd5 { Black takes the queen, because the king now covers e8. But... } { [%cal Rf8e8] } (22... Rxg7 23. Qxd7 { It's mate in 3 at most. }) 23. Rg8+!! { The final sacrifice! Forcing the king away from the e8 square. } 23... Kxg8 24. Re8+! { At last, the rook reaches e8, the square White has been fighting for so long. } 24... Rf8 25. Rxf8# { Checkmate! } *


