[Event "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!: Mikhail Tal - Andres Vooremaa"]
[Site "Tallin"]
[Date "1972"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Andres Vooremaa"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B48"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Taimanov Variation, Bastrikov Variation, English Attack"]
[StudyName "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!"]
[ChapterName "Mikhail Tal - Andres Vooremaa"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/R33cxdop"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]

{ Mikhail Tal vs Andres Vooremaa, Tallinn 1972 }
1. e4!! { Of course, Tal, known for his aggressive style, opens with 1. e4, the most aggressive starting move! } 1... c5 { The Sicilian! It is by far the most popular starting move at master level. Black immediately counter attacks on the opposite side of the board. } 2. Nf3 { Tal develops and controls the d4 square, preparing for a d4 pawn push. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Bd2d4,Gf3d4] } 2... e6 { The French Variation, but most of the time this opening can transpose to many other Sicilian lines with d6 and/or Nc6. } { [%csl Gf8] } 3. d4 { Tal immediately strikes the center, going for an open game. } { [%csl Gf8] } 3... cxd4 { A symphony of exchanges. } 4. Nxd4! { Recapturing the pawn with the knight. } { [%csl Gd4] } (4. Qxd4? { A common mistake made often by beginners. } 4... Nc6 $15 { Black gains tempo, this could have been avoided with 4. Nxd4. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc6d4] }) 4... Nc6 { Vooremaa goes for the Taimanov. Playing 4...Nc6 helps Black bring out a piece, puts a bit of pressure on d4, and keeps options open for future moves like pushing pawns on the queenside with a6-b5. } { [%cal Ba7a6,Bb7b5] } 5. Nc3 { Tal brings another piece into the game. } (5. Nxc6?! { Another common mistake played commonly among beginners/intermediate players. White has traded a good central knight for Black's c6 knight. Black's the only one benefiting from this exchange. } 5... bxc6 $10 { Black has gained equality. There is no longer a developed knight in the center for White, and Black has just gained a free open b file. } { [%cal Ba8b8,Yb7b8,Yb7b1] }) 5... Qc7 { A flexible move. It develops the queen to a more active square and keeps many options open. } { [%csl Gc7] } (5... Nxd4? { Black has gotten rid of the central knight... } 6. Qxd4 { but now has bigger issues with a strong developed queen in the center that can't get kicked away. } { [%csl Gd4] }) 6. Be3 { Reinforcing the d4 knight. There are many options White could go for in this position. Some interesting ones are in the variations below. } { [%cal Bd1d2,Be1c1,Bf2f3,Bg2g4] } 6... a6 { Vooremaa expands on the queenside. Black can always play a b5 push at some point. } { [%cal Bb7b5] } (6... Be7 7. g4! { A really nice attacking move I'm certain Tal would have gone for it if Vooremaa had gone for 6...Be7 :) A ruined kingside is nothing to worry about, since White is planning to castle queenside anyway. } 7... Nf6? { This move is no longer possible for Black because of: } 8. g5! Ng8 { The only move if Black's wants to keep his knight! } 9. Qd2 $18 { White is absolutely crushing this. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Bh1g1,Bh2h4,Be1c1] }) 7. Bd3 { 7. f4 would have been interesting too, but Tal decides that king safety comes first. } { [%cal Be1g1] } 7... Nf6 { Vooremaa delays the b5 idea and wants to first finish developing his pieces and get his king to safety. } 8. O-O Bd6 { Vooremaa gets his bishop into the game, attacking the h2 pawn while also preparing to castle kingside. } { [%csl Rh2][%cal Be8g8,Rd6h2] } 9. Kh1! { Most folks might opt for the simple h3 or f4 to save the h2 pawn, but hey, we're talking about Mikhail Tal here! He comes up with this beautiful idea instead: Kh1! The idea of this move is that it avoids the check after Bxh2 and then White can play g3, trapping the bishop! } 9... h5 { Vooremaa sees the Bishop takes h2 trap and decides to keep attacking the kingside. With h5 Black can get the h8 rook into the game and try to weaken White's kingside. } { [%csl Gh8] } (9... Bxh2?? { An immediate g3 is possible, but we can trade the knights first. } 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. g3! $10 { The bishop is caged in! } { [%csl Gh2][%cal Rh1h2] } 11... Bxg3 12. fxg3 Qxg3 13. Qf3 $18 { Yes, material is equal, but White is definitely better here. Black's pieces are placed worse and the open files can be used for White to activate his rooks. } { [%csl Rc8,Gd3,Gf3,Ge4,Ge3,Gc3,Gf1] }) 10. f4 { Tal advances the f pawn, threatening an e5 fork and trying to get more activity along the f file. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Be4e5,Re5f6,Re5d6] } 10... Ng4 { Vooremaa doesn't let himself get forked. He wants to trade his knight for Tal's dark-squared-bishop. } { [%csl Re3][%cal Rg4e3] } 11. Qf3 { Tal defends the bishop. Qc1/Qd2 were both equally good as well. } { [%cal Gf3e3] } 11... Nxe3 { Black takes the bishop of the board. } 12. Qxe3 { Recapturing. } 12... Qb6 { Vooremaa pins the knight. } { [%csl Re3,Rd4][%cal Rb6e3,Rd6c5] } (12... Nxd4 { This does win a pawn, but it gives white the open f file. } 13. Qxd4 Bxf4 14. Qf2 $16 { Things get spicy along the f file. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf4,Gf2,Gf1] }) 13. Nce2 { The only way to support the d4 knight. } { [%cal Ge2d4] } 13... e5 { Vooremaa attacks the knight. Tal could continue defending with fxe5-c3, but Tal's an attacking player, so he instead goes for this sacrifice: } { [%csl Rd4,Re3][%cal Re5d4,Rb6e3] } 14. Qg3!? { Sacrificing the knight and attacking the g7 pawn! Stockfish isn't really a huge fan of this move and prefers fxe5, but both lines are really tricky. } { [%csl Rd4,Rg7] } (14. fxe5 { Another good option, preferred by Stockfish, White simple gets rid of the exd4 threat and activates the f1 rook because the f file is opened up. } { [%csl Gf1,Gd4] } 14... Bxe5 { The knight is again attacked. } { [%csl Rd4] } 15. c3 $16 { White wants to keep the queens on the board, because he's the one with the attacking position. Nf4 would result in a queen trade, so it's bad. Next, White can keep follow up with moves like Qg4, unpinning the knight, or Bc4 adding pressure on f7. } { [%csl Rf7,Gf1][%cal Be3g5,Bd3c4,Gc3d4] }) 14... exd4?! { Vooremaa takes the hanging knight, but he now has to be extra careful of Tal's attack! } 15. Qxg7 { Hitting the rook. } { [%csl Rh8][%cal Bg7h8] } 15... Rf8 { The only move that defends it. } { [%csl Gf1,Be1][%cal Be4e5,Bf4f5,Ba1e1] } 16. e5! { Tal attacks the bishop and brings his pawns closer to the king. Now he wants to break open the e and f files for his rooks to come in. } 16... Be7 { Vooremaa defends his bishop. Things are already getting really tricky for Black. As you can see, each of Black's pieces are playing a very passive role, the LSB and rook in the corner are completely stuck. } { [%csl Ra8,Rc8,Rb6,Rc6,Re7,Re8,Gf4,Ge5,Gg7,Gf1,Rf8] } 17. f5 { Continuing the pawn storm. Tal's pawns get closer and now also the f4 square is freed for the knight to hop in and reroute to a more active square. } { [%cal Be2f4,Bf5f6,Bf4d5] } 17... f6 { Vooremaa tries to consolidate his position. There's only one good move for White. } 18. Nf4! { Tal finds it. This move's idea is not to attack the h5 pawn (we completely don't care about that right now, just attack the king), but rather to reroute the knight to a more active square like d5 or g6. } { [%cal Bf4g6,Bf4d5] } (18. exf6?? Bxf6 19. Qh6 Ne5 { The attack is gone. } { [%csl Gf6,Ge5,Gf8] }) 18... Rf7?? { Ends the game for Black, but only if Tal finds the exf6 queen sacrifice! } (18... Nxe5 { Black's best shot. } 19. Qxe7+! { A nice way to trade material. } 19... Kxe7 20. Nd5+ Kd6 21. Nxb6 Rb8 $16 { White still ends up being better because of the better piece placement and pawn structure. } { [%csl Rh5,Rf6,Rd7,Rb8,Rc8,Rf8,Gb6] }) 19. exf6!! { Tal finds it of course! The point of this sacrifice will be shown in the variation below :) } 19... Ne5 { Vooremaa declines the sacrifice. Tal has a KO move now... } (19... Rxg7 20. fxg7 { The g pawn is 1 step away from promoting! the only move to stop that (for now) is Kf7. As you can see all Black's other pieces are completely out of the game and can't join the defense anytime soon! } { [%csl Gg7,Gf4,Rb6,Rc6,Rc8,Ra8,Gf5,Gf1,Ga1] } 20... Kf7 { Black controls the promoting square and attacks the g pawn. } { [%csl Rg8,Rg7][%cal Rf7g8] } 21. f6! { Another key move! Sacrificing it the f pawn, but temporarily protecting the g pawn! } { [%csl Gf6,Gg7] } 21... Bxf6 22. Nxh5 { Exploiting the rook on the f file and double attacking the bishop! The g pawn is now still defended by our knight. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf6,Rg8][%cal Gf1f7,Gg7g8,Gh5f6,Gh5g7] } 22... Ne7 { Covering the g8 square, it's the only try Black's got. } { [%csl Rg8][%cal Re7g8] } (22... Qd8 { Protecting the bishop. } 23. Bh7! { Rxg6-g8=Q tactics are inevitable. } { [%csl Rg8,Rf6][%cal Rh7g8,Rf1f6] }) 23. Rae1! { Another key move! Threatening to take the knight on e7, thus clearing the g8 square for promotion. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Be1e7] } 23... Ng8 24. Bh7! { The only move that forcefully gets rid of the knight. } 24... Qd8 { Protecting. } 25. Bxg8+ { Getting rid of a defender. } 25... Kxg8 26. Rxf6 { It's over. The Rh6-Rh8 maneuver is unstoppable. } { [%csl Rh8][%cal Bf6h6,Bh6h8] }) 20. Bc4?? { Blunder. Qh8+ was best. } { He misses it! Tal went a bit overboard here with the sacrifices. Tal only has a slight advantage now. } (20. Qh8+ { The GG move. } 20... Bf8 21. Rae1 { Absolutely freezing the Black pieces. } { [%csl Re8,Re5,Rf7,Rf8,Rc8,Ra8][%cal Re1e8] } 21... d6 22. Bc4! { Hitting the rook. It's over now. The rook can't move because of f7+, the bishop is pinned, the knight is pinned... Feel free to analyze further. I'll stop here, because there way too many ways Black gets crushed. } { [%csl Rf7,Re5,Rh5,Rf8,Rb6,Ra8,Rc8][%cal Rc4f7] }) 20... Nxc4 { Vooremaa grabs the free piece. } 21. Qg8+! { The only move that keeps the advantage! Black is forced to block with the bishop. } 21... Bf8 (21... Rf8?? { Completely loses. } 22. Qg6+ { Getting somewhere safe and gaining tempo. } 22... Rf7 23. Nd5 { [%csl Rb6,Re7][%cal Rd5b6,Rd5e7] } 23... Qd6 24. fxe7 Qxd5 25. f6 $18 { It's over. Qg8+-f7+ tactics can't be stopped. } { [%csl Gf6,Ge7][%cal Rg6g8,Rf6f7] }) 22. Nxh5 { Threatening Ng7+, winning the rook. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rh5g7] } 22... Nd6 { Protecting the rook. Ng7+ doesn't work anymore. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gd6f7] } 23. Rae1+! { Getting the rook into the game! The rook will soon infiltrate the seventh rank! } 23... Kd8 24. Re7! { Looks scary at first, but none of Black's pieces can take it! } 24... Qb5 { Attacking the f1 rook and bringing the queen to a more flexible square. } (24... Rxe7?? { Loses. } 25. fxe7+ Kxe7 26. Qg5+ { The king is completely unsafe, White's pieces will just come flowing in. } 26... Kf7 27. Qf6+ Ke8 28. Re1+ Ne4 29. Rxe4+ Qe6 { you get the point. }) 25. Rfe1 { Black might be able to hold a bit long with Qa5 attacking the e1 rook (Rxf7 is no longer possible because of Qxe1#), and somehow get the king to safety with Kc7-Kb8/Kb6, but instead Vooremaa blunders, and White again has the advantage. } 25... Qd5?? { Blunder. Qa5 was best. } { This move protects the f7 rook but allows the dreadful Nf4! with tempo! } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gd5f7] } (25... Qa5! 26. c3 (26. Rxf7 Qxe1#) 26... Qxa2 27. Nf4 dxc3 28. Ne6+ dxe6 29. Rxf7 Nxf7 30. Qxf8+ Kc7 31. Qxf7+ Kb8 32. bxc3) 26. Nf4! { The only winning move! This move not only attacks the queen but also prepares for the nasty Ne6+!! } { [%csl Rd5,Re6][%cal Rf4d5,Rf4e6] } 26... Qxa2 { There isn't much left to do anymore, so Vooremaa just grabs a pawn and keeps his rook protected. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ga2f7,Re7f7,Rg8f7] } 27. Ne6+!! { A beautiful finish! Cutting off the protection path from the queen to the rook. } { [%csl Rf7,Ra2] } 27... Qxe6 { Vooremaa just decides to sac the queen, since there's no way to save himself. } (27... dxe6 { The queen no longer defends the poor rook. } { [%csl Rf7,Ra2] } 28. Rxf7 { [%csl Rf8] } 28... Nxf7 29. Qxf8+! { An important move! This forks the knight and king. } { [%cal Rf8f7,Rf8d8] } 29... Kc7 30. Qxf7+ Bd7 (30... Kb8 31. Qe8 { The most simplest option. Just clearing the path for the g pawn. } { [%cal Bf6f7,Bf7f8] }) 31. fxe6 { It's over. White has 2 passed pawns on the sixth rank and will also pick up the LSB later. } { [%csl Rc7,Rd7,Ge6,Gf6,Ge1][%cal Rf7c7,Re6d7] }) 28. fxe6 Rxf6 29. Rf7 { There are too many threats for Black to deal with. It is here where Andres Vooremaa resigned. Tal won this absolutely insane game. } { [%csl Rf8,Ge6,Ge1,Gf7,Gg8][%cal Rf7f8,Rg8f8] } 1-0


[Event "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!: Mikhail Tal - Alexander Koblencs"]
[Site "Riga"]
