[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Alexander Koblencs"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B99"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation, Main Line"]
[StudyName "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!"]
[ChapterName "Mikhail Tal - Alexander Koblencs"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/13wHeXS9"]

{ Mihail Tal vs Alexander Koblencs, Riga 1961
Koblencs is an old trainer of Tal. }
1. e4 { The game begins with the main line of the Sicilian Defense. } 1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6! { This move marks the beginning of the Najdorf Variation, the most popular variation of the entire Sicilian. This may seem strange at first, but it makes sense. 5...a6 is a flexible waiting move, as Black holds off on minor piece development until White's intentions are clearer. Depending on what White does next, Black can decide where to put their knight and bishop. They can also choose between ...e6 or ...e5, depending on how White's bishops are positioned. This flexibility is why top players love the Najdorf. } 6. Bg5 { Tal develops his bishop to an active square, it is threatening to double Black's f pawns with Bxf6. } 6... e6 { Now after Bxf6, the queen can always recapture. } (6... h6? { I put this move to just show what will happen if Black ignores our g5 bishop. } 7. Bxf6 exf6!! { Black's pawn structure is completely ruined. Black has doubled f pawns and an isolated d pawn. It's +1.3. } { [%csl Rd6,Rf6,Rf7] } (7... gxf6 8. Qh5 { White is ready to castle, has two knight's developed and the queen is placed on an active square where it won't be kicked anytime soon. } { [%csl Bc1,Gh5,Gd4,Ge4,Gc3,Rf8,Re7,Rf7,Rf6,Rc8,Rd8,Rb8,Ra8,Rh8][%cal Be1c1] })) 7. f4! { Tal goes for the most aggressive line! He starts a kingside attack and plans to castle queenside. } 7... Be7 { Considered the most sharpest line. Koblencs unpins his knight and plans to bring his king to safety sooner or later by castling kingside. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 8. Qf3 { Tal clears the way for the king to castle queenside. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1] } 8... Qc7 { Koblencs puts his queen on a more flexible square where it controls the c file. Often Black does a queenside pawn storm with b5 at some point. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Bb7b5] } 9. O-O-O { Tal castles queenside. } 9... Nbd7 { Koblencs prepares to support central pawns or potentially reroute the knight at some point. } (9... b5?? { A good idea, but definitely not right now. White's queen can now make use of the h1-a8 diagonal with 10. e5! } 10. e5 { Double attacking. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Re5f6,Rf3a8] } 10... Bb7 { An attempt to save himself. } 11. Qg3 $18 { If the f3 knight ever leaves, we play Bxe7 and take g7. The Black king will then be completely unsafe, especially because of our d1 rook controlling the d file. } { [%csl Rg7,Gd1] }) 10. Be2?! { Inaccuracy. g4 was best. } { A bit passive, but still playable. It connects the rooks, so in the future Tal can play Rhf1, dominating the c file. } (10. g4 b5 { Expanding on the queenside. } 11. Bxf6 { Preparing for the g5 pawn push. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Bg4g5] } 11... Nxf6 12. g5 { Kicking the knight, thus gaining tempo. } 12... Nd7 $16 { Things get really scary for Black, because of White's expanded kingside. Castling the king queenside doesn't work because of the far-too-extended pawns, and castling kingside is scary because of White's massive pawn storm. } { [%csl Gg5,Gf4,Ge4,Gf3,Gd4] }) 10... h6 { Koblencs wants to get rid of the annoying bishop, Tal must choose to either retreat it or trade it for the knight, the downside of that is that Tal loses his bishop pair... } (10... b5 11. a3) 11. Bh4 { So, Tal keeps his bishop on the board. } 11... b5 { Koblencs counterattacks on the queenside. Golden rule: If your opponent attacks on one side, counterattack on the opposite one. } 12. e5?! { Stockfish prefers to first trade some material with Bxf6, and then play e5. But an immediate e5 is also possible. With this move Tal attacks 2 pieces at once, the knight and rook. But Black can still hold because of: } { [%cal Rf3a8,Re5f6] } 12... Bb7! { Tal's queen now has to move before he can grab the knight, or does it? } 13. exf6!! { Tal of course sacrifices the queen (what did you expect?)!! He will get enough compensation for it. } 13... Bxf3 { Koblencs accepts the sacrifice. } 14. Bxf3! { Tal first recaptures with the bishop, keeping 3 of Black's pieces under attack. Koblencs can only save 1. } { [%cal Rf3a8,Rf6e7,Rf6g7] } (14. fxg7?? { Hangs the bishop } { [%csl Rh4] } 14... Rg8 15. Bxf3 { [%csl Rh4] } 15... Bxh4 16. Bxa8 $17 { Equals material, but after Black wins white's g7 pawn, White has no attack whatsoever, and Black just ends up being better. }) 14... d5?! { Inaccuracy. Bxf6 was best. } { Koblencs decides to save his 5-point-worth rook. } (14... Bxf6 { Stockfish's preferred line. } 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Bxa8 O-O 17. Bf3 { White may be up a point in material, but Black gets enough compensation by play on the queenside. White would be the one defending, but with perfect play, white might be able to hold. } 17... b4 $15) 15. Nxe6!! { Tal continues his attack with this brilliant knight sacrifice in order to open the h5-e8 diagonal! Koblencs is forced to accept it. } (15. fxe7?? Qxf4+ { A deadly fork, Black wins a piece. } { [%cal Rf4c1,Rf4h4] }) 15... fxe6 16. Bh5+ { The point of the knight sacrifice. } 16... g6!! { I gotta give credit to Koblencs for this find. The point of this pawn sacrifice is to clear the g7 square for the his king to run to (we'll get to that later). } { [%csl Rg7] } (16... Kf8?? { Playing this immediately is a blunder because... } 17. fxe7+ Kg8 $7 { The only legal move. The h8 rook is now not controlling the e8 square. } { [%csl Rh8] } 18. e8=Q+ Rxe8 19. Bxe8 { If the king wouldn't have blocked the h8 rook, the rook would have been able } 19... Qxf4+ 20. Kb1 Qxh4 21. Bxd7 { White ends up being up material. }) 17. Bxg6+ { [%cal Be8f8,Bf8g7] } 17... Kf8 { Koblencs is walking his king over to the g7 square. } 18. fxe7+ Kg7 { Black ends up controlling the e8 square twice because of the g6 pawn sac. Tal has to be very careful now. Koblencs is now threatening to take Tal's g6 bishop and the deadly Qxf4+, winning the DSB because of the fork. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Rc7f4,Rf4c1,Rf4h4,Gh8e8,Ga8e8,Rg7g6] } 19. Bg3!! { Placing the bishop on the same diagonal as the queen. Now Black's king cannot take the g6 bishop because of f5+!! This is the only move that saves both of White's pieces. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Bf4f5,Rg3c7] } 19... Nf6?! { Inaccuracy. Qc5 was best. } { Better was 19...b4! 19...Nf6?! allows white to get some play attack with f5-Re1. } (19... b4! 20. f5 { [%csl Rc7] } 20... Qc4 21. Nb1 (21. fxe6 bxc3 22. exd7 Kxg6 $10) 21... Rac8 $17 { Black gets an attack on the White king. } { [%csl Gc8,Gc4] }) (19... Kxg6?? { Grabbing the "free" bishop loses on the spot because of: } 20. f5+ { Black loses the queen. } { [%cal Rg3c7,Rf5g6] }) 20. Rhe1 { Tal activates the rook. } (20. f5! { A slightly better option. } 20... Qxe7 21. Rhe1 $16 { Forcefully wins the e6 pawn too. } { [%csl Re7,Re6][%cal Re1e7] }) 20... b4? { Mistake. Qd7 was best. } { A mistake. It allows 21. f5. Better for Koblencs was Qd7, getting out of the h2-a7 diagonal and protecting the e6 pawn. } (20... Qxe7? 21. f5 { Leads to annoying pins. }) (20... Qd7 $10 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd7e6,Rg3c7] }) 21. Rxe6?? { Blunder. f5 was best. } { Tal misses 21. f5! (explained in the variation below). } (21. f5! { Attacking the queen and e6 pawn. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rg3c7,Be1e6,Yf5e6] } 21... Qxe7 22. Rxe6 Qxe6 (22... Qd8 { If the queen moves to any square, white has Nxd5. } 23. Nxd5 $18 { White is completely dominating the central files. Black's pieces are all sitting on the first rank. } { [%csl Ge6,Gd5,Gd1,Gg3,Gg6,Gf5,Ra8,Rd8,Rh8,Rf6,Rg7] }) 23. fxe6 Kxg6 24. Ne2 $18 { We have a rook vs bishop + 2 pawns endgame. Considering Black's poor pawn structure, White is much better. It's +2.0. } { [%csl Rh6,Rd5,Gg2,Gh2,Gc2,Gb2,Ga2,Gd1] }) 21... bxc3 { Koblencs grabs the free knight. } 22. f5 { Attacking the queen and supporting the rook. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rg3c7] } 22... Qb7?? { Blunder. cxb2+ was best. } { Better was cxb2+, because of the variations below. } (22... cxb2+ { White has 2 choices: Take the pawn, or use it as an umbrella. } 23. Kb1 { If White uses it as an umbrella pawn, } 23... Qd7 24. Be5?? { The same idea as played in the game doesn't work anymore, because of this one big change we will see on move 26. I'm showing the moves also played in the game, to illustrate why it doesn't now. } (24. Rde1 Rhc8 $17 { Black's now the one attacking. } { [%csl Gc8] }) 24... Qxe6 { Also played in the game, sacrificing the queen for a rook and bishop. } 25. fxe6 Kxg6 26. Rf1?? { The same in the game, but because the king is placed on a different square, Black has this move. } 26... Ne4! $19 { Threatening to fork the king and rook. Black is now simply up a ton of material. } { [%csl Rd2][%cal Re4d2] }) 23. b3 Qd7? { Koblencs attacks the rook. This is completely losing because Tal's next powerful move: } (23... Rae8 { A way to survive a bit longer, but this just leads to a winning endgame for White. } 24. Be5 { Pinning the knight, Black is unable to protect it. } 24... Qxe7 { The only way to prolong the game a bit. } 25. Rxe7+ Rxe7 26. Bxc3 $18 { [%csl Gc3,Gg6,Gf5,Gh2,Gg2,Gc2,Gb3,Ga2,Ra6,Rd5,Rh6][%cal Ga2b3,Gc2b3] }) 24. Be5! { The knight is lost. } { [%csl Rg7,Rf6,Gf8][%cal Be6f6,Ye5g7,Ge7f8] } 24... Qxe6 { Koblencs sacrifices the queen for Tal's rook and bishop. This is the only way to lose the least amount of material. } 25. fxe6 Kxg6 26. Rf1! { Tal makes the winning move here. The knight's either going to be taken or has to move, and if it does, Tal wins the exchange. Koblencs' rooks can't come to the rescue since Tal's e7 pawn has control over the f8 square. } { [%csl Rh8,Rf6][%cal Re7f8] } 26... Nh7 { Koblencts keep the knight. } 27. Bxh8 Rxh8 { The material's tied up, but here's the big difference: Tal's pawn are just 1 and 2 steps away from thier promotion square. There's only 1 winning move here for Tal... } 28. Rf8! { He finds it! Koblencs has to take the rook with his rook, otherwise Tal promotes to a queen immediately with e8=Q. } 28... Rxf8 (28... Nxf8 29. e8=Q+ $18) 29. exf8=Q { Recapturing. } 29... Nxf8 30. e7! { Another only-move. Tal hits Koblencs' knight and threatens to queen on e8. The king is forced to go to f7 to stop the pawn from promoting (but any move is good for Black, he's completely losing anyway) } { [%cal Re7f8,Be7e8] } 30... Kf7 31. exf8=Q+ { Tal grabs the free knight, promoting to any piece is perfectly fine. } (31. exf8=N!! { :) Same thing. }) 31... Kxf8 { At this point the game is over. After all that craziness, Tal ends up being up a pawn with a supreme pawn structure. Tal will just walk the king over to each pawn to pick it up. Koblencs' king is way too far to protect them. Both players play a couple of moves after this. } { [%csl Rh6,Rd5,Ra6,Rc3,Rf8][%cal Bc1d1,Bd1e2,Be2d3,Bd3c3] } 32. Kd1 Kf7 33. Ke2 Ke6 34. Kd3 d4 35. Kxd4 { 1-0 White wins. } { Koblencs resigns. } 1-0


