{ Mikhail Tal vs Boris Gulko, 1969 }
1. e4 { The first moves are the same as our previous chapter (Mikhail Tal - Alexander Koblencs) } 1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 { Gulko goes for the Scheveningen Variation. 5... e6 is a characteristic move in the Scheveningen Variation of the Sicilian Defense, establishing a "small center." It reinforces Black's control over d5 while preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop to e7. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Bf8e7,Bd6d5] } (5... a6 { The Sicilian Najdorf, seen in our previous chapter. }) 6. f4! { Tal wastes no time and starts a pawn storm with f4, aiming to quickly mobilize his forces for a kingside attack. } (6. g4!? { Another interesting option. This is Stockfish's prefered move and most popular in the master's database. } { [%cal Bg4g5] } 6... Be7 { Let's say Black were to develop normally... } (6... h6 7. Rg1! { It's an interesting game. }) 7. g5! { Immediately Black's knight gets kicked away. } 7... Nfd7 8. h4 $16 { White has a space advantage. } { [%csl Gh4,Gg5,Gf2,Rd7,Rd8,Rc8,Rb8,Re7] }) 6... Nc6 { Taking the c6 knight would be an inaccuracy, because White would simply give up his central knight. } { [%csl Gd4] } 7. Be3 { Tal reinforces his knight and is another step closer to castling queenside. } 7... Be7 { Gulko prepares to bring his king out of the center by castling kingside. } 8. Qf3 { Tal prepares for castling queenside while placing his queen on a flexible square. } { [%cal Be1c1] } 8... a6 { A prophylactic move, stopping any potential threats like Bb5/Nb5. Also, a b5 can be played sooner or later. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra6b5] } 9. O-O-O { Tal castles his king. The d1 rook now joins the game by controlling the d file. } { [%csl Gd1] } 9... Qc7 10. g4! { g4! Tal advances his g-pawn, threatening to push to g5 and disrupt the knight's position. } { [%cal Rg4g5] } 10... Nxd4 { Gulko gets rid of Tal's central knight. } 11. Bxd4 e5 { This looks very scary for Tal, his following moves must be very accurate. Gulko threatens to take the d4 bishop and take the g4 pawn, skewering the queen and rook. There's only one way to avoid all White's problems. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Gc8g4,Re5d4,Rg4d1] } 12. fxe5! { Tal simplifies the center, hitting the knight and temporarily clearing the bishop from attack. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Re5f6] } 12... dxe5 { Gulko recaptures, again threatening to take Tal's two hanging pieces. } (12... Bxg4 13. Qf4 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Qc8 15. Rd3 $16) 13. Qg3! { The only move! Pinning the pawn and threatening to take it. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Rg3c7,Ye5d4] } 13... Nxg4?? { Blunder. Bd6 was best. } { Gulko got too greedy here, this allows Tal to win material, explained in the variation below. } { [%csl Rg7,Rg4][%cal Bc3d5] } (13... Bd6 { Black's best option, breaking the pin and defending it. } 14. Be3 Nxg4?? { Loses. } (14... Bxg4?! { This opens the g file, thus when the bishop moves the g7 pawn will hang. } { [%csl Rg7] } 15. h3 Bxd1 16. Qxg7 Rg8 17. Qxf6 Rg6 18. Qh8+ Bf8 19. Nxd1 $16) (14... Qc6! 15. g5 Nxe4?? { Loses the bishop. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Rd1d6] } (15... Nh5 16. Qf3 Nf4 17. h4 { White has a much more comfortable position. An idea here is Bxf4-Ne5, centralizing the knight. } { [%csl Ge3,Gg5,Gh4,Gc3][%cal Be3f4,Bc3d5] }) 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Rxd6 $18) 15. Nd5 { Gaining tempo. } { [%cal Rd5c7] } 15... Qc6 16. Bd2 $16 { The h3 threat is unstoppable, then Black's knight is forced to retreat and the g7 pawn will hang. } { [%csl Rg7,Rg4][%cal Rh2h3] }) (13... Bxg4?! { Hangs the e pawn. } 14. Bxe5 Qc8 15. Rd3 $16 { White's pieces are way more developed and active. }) 14. Be2?? { Blunder. Nd5 was best. } { Tal misses the Nd5 idea. He instead attacks the knight. Note: White is still slighlty better, but Nd5 would have been pretty much gg. } (14. Nd5! { Gaining tempo. White can always trade it for the e7 bishop, forcing the king to bongcloud. } { [%cal Rd5c7,Rd5e7] } 14... Qa5 (14... Qd6 15. Bc3 { White is completely crushing in this position! There are much to many threats for Black to deal with. } { [%csl Gd1][%cal Bc3b4,Bh2h3,Bf1e2,Bh1g1] }) 15. Bc3! { Again gaining tempo and saving the bishop. } 15... Qxa2 16. Nxe7! { Not allowing the king to castle! } 16... Kxe7 17. h3! $18 { Winning the knight, because if it were to retreat, White has Bb4+, controlling the a3-f8 diagonal, and then White follows up with Qxg7, winning a ton of material. }) 14... Qa5?! { Inaccuracy. Qc6 was best. } { Gulko unpins his queen, Tal's d4 bishop is now hanging but Gulko's knight is hanging, so we get a trade. Stockfish prefers that Gulko would have kept his queen on the c file with Qc6. } 15. Bxg4 { Trading pieces of the board. } 15... exd4 { Tal sees the Qg5+ trap, so he saves his knight and threatens to fork the rook and king. Note: Nb1/Ne2 lose ue to the same Gg5+ trap. } 16. Nd5! { [%cal Rd5c7,Rd5e7] } (16. Rxd4?? { Might be tempting, but loses on the spot because of a fork :) } 16... Qg5+ $19 { So long LSB. } { [%cal Rg5g4,Rc8g4] }) 16... Qxa2 { Now, Tal has to be careful, because Gulko is threatening Bg5+, which is completely winning for Black. } 17. Qe5! { Tal pins Gulko's bishop and threatens checkmate. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Ge5e7,Bd5e7] } (17. Nc7+?? { Forking, but it ignores Black's main threat. } 17... Kf8 { Moving out of check. But still threatening Bg5+. } { [%cal Re7g5,Ra2a1] } 18. Nxa8 Bg5+ 19. Qf4 Bxf4+ 20. Rd2 Qa1# { Checkmate. } { [%csl Rd1,Rc1,Rb1,Rb2,Rc2,Rd2][%cal Ga1d1,Yf4c1] }) 17... Qa1+ { There isn't a piece that can protect Gulko's bishop, so he has to maneuver his queen to d8 by checking Tal's king. } { [%cal Ba1a5,Ba5d8,Gc1d2] } 18. Kd2 Qa5+ { Now he can go to the d8 square to protect his bishop. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Ra5d2,Ra5d8] } 19. b4 Qd8 { Gulko us up 2 pawns, but his king is completely unsafe and all his pieces are playing a defensive role on the backrank. Gulko's position will not hold much longer. Currently, Tal's bishop is hanging, so he simply protects it with Rg1. Bh5/Qxg7 were good choices too. } { [%csl Rg7,Rc8,Ra8,Rd8,Re8,Re7,Rh8,Rd4][%cal Gd8e7,Be5g7,Bg4h5,Bh1g1] } 20. Rhg1 { [%cal Gg1g4] } 20... f6? { Opens up the h5-e8 diagonal. } (20... Bxg4 { Gulko's best try. He should try to trade as much material as possible. } 21. Rxg4 Qd6! { Again trying to get the queen's of the board. } { [%csl Gd6] } 22. Qxg7?? { Ends White's attack. } (22. Nc7+ { Winning an exchange. } { [%cal Rc7a8,Rc7e8] } 22... Kd7 23. Qxd6+ Kxd6 24. Nxa8 Rxa8 25. Rxg7 $18 { White has a better endgame, but at least the game goes on a bit longer. }) 22... O-O-O { White's attack has stopped. It's 100% equal now. } { [%csl Gd8,Gd6,Gc8,Ge7,Gh8] }) 21. Bh5+! { [%cal Rh5e8] } 21... Kf8 { This ends the game immediately because of the following brilliant K.O. move! } (21... Kd7 22. Qxd4) (21... g6 { Leaves the f6 pawn undefended. } { [%csl Rf6] } 22. Nxf6+! { Making use of the pin. } { [%csl Re8,Rd7][%cal Rf6e8,Rf6d7] } 22... Kf8 23. Nd5 { It's gg. After a rook goes to f1, checkmate will follow soon. } { [%csl Rh8][%cal Be5h8,Bd1f1] }) 22. Rxg7!! { Tal sacrifices the queen and the rook at the same time!!! This is forced checkmate. } { [%csl Ge5,Gg7][%cal Rf6e5,Rf8g7] } 22... fxe5 { Gulko grabs the queen. } (22... Kxg7 { Also results in checkmate. } 23. Rg1+ { Caging up the king. } { [%csl Yg8,Yg7,Re8,Rf7][%cal Yg1g8,Rh5e8] } 23... Kf8 24. Qg3! { The Qg7# threat is unstoppable! If Black were to play perfectly it's #13. } { [%csl Gg7,Ye8,Yf7,Re7][%cal Gg3g7,Gg1g7,Yh5e8] }) 23. Rf7+! { Keeping the rook protected. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gh5f7] } 23... Ke8 24. Rxe7+ { A double check. } { [%csl Ye7][%cal Rh5e8,Ge7e8,Yd5e7] } 24... Kf8 25. Rf1+ { Bringing in the final piece to join the attack. } { [%cal Gf1f8,Ye7e8] } 25... Kg8 26. Rff7 { 1-0 White wins. } { Here Gulko resigned, because the checkmate in 2 is unstoppable. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Rd5f6] } (26. Nf6+ Kf8 27. Rf7#) 26... Qd6 (26... b6 27. Nf6# { A nice knight checkmate. } { [%csl Gg8,Yf7,Yf8,Rh7,Rh8,Yg7][%cal Gf6g8,Yf7h7,Ye7f7,Yf7f8] }) 27. Re8+ Qf8 28. Rexf8# { A beautiful checkmate with both rooks working together. You don't see something like this everyday! } { [%csl Rh8,Rh7][%cal Yf7h7,Bf8h8] } 1-0


[Event "Bled-Zagreb-Belgrade Candidates"]
[Site "Bled, Zagreb & Belgrade YUG"]
[Date "1959.09.18"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Vasily Smyslov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Breyer Variation"]
[StudyName "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!"]
[ChapterName "Mikhail Tal - Vasily Smyslov"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/uLZEYtdD"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]

{ Mikhail Tal vs Vasily Smyslov, Candidates Tournament 1959 }
1. e4! { Of course, Tal begins with 1. e4! } 1... c6 { The Caro-Kann Defense! This opening has become incredibly famous lately, mostly because of youtubers like GothamChess, aka Levy Rosman. It is considered one of the most solid and safe replies against 1. e4. } 2. d3!? { Tal goes for a very interesting choice, the Breyer variation. Today online it's being played only 3% of the time. } 2... d5 { In the Caro-Kann, d5 is always played on the second move. } 3. Nd2 { Now allowing Black to trade queens after dxe4. } (3. Nf3 { Here's an interesting gambit I want to share that's been very successful. These days you see this quite a few times, but in 1959, this was a bit too crazy. Especially in classical chess against world-class players. } 3... dxe4 4. Ng5!? { This line is very tricky for Black to face. On move 4, White's winrate is already at 63%!!! } 4... exd3 5. Bxd3 { Now White sets up a very very successful trap. The two most popular moves from Black lose immediately because of a beautiful tactic. } 5... Nf6?? { Most popular, but it's the same thing with h6. } 6. Nxf7!! { Sacrificing the knight!! Black can resign now because if the king doesn't take the knight, White just grabs the free rook (or queen), and if Black takes the knights...you'll just see on the next move :) } { [%cal Rf7d8,Rf7h8] } 6... Kxf7 7. Bg6+!! { Clearing the d file with check! The queen is now left undefended. } { [%csl Ge8,Rg7,Rf8,Re7,Rf6,Rd8][%cal Yg6e8,Bd1d8] } 7... Kxg6 8. Qxd8 $18 { With an extra queen on the board, it shouldn't be that hard to win this. Just don't fall for the following line: 8...e5 9. Qxc8 Bb4+!, and there goes the advantage. }) 3... e5 { Smyslov takes the center. } 4. Ngf3 { Tal attacks e5. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Bf3e5] } 4... Nd7?! { A slight inaccuracy because it allows d4, opening up the center, which is favorable for White. } (4... Bd6! { the main move. } 5. d4 exd4 6. exd5 Nf6 $10 { Now the LSB is not blocked and the b8 knight can capture c6. Also, the king can castle on the next move. } { [%csl Gf6,Gc8,Gd6][%cal Be8g8,Bb8c6] }) 5. d4 { We get some exchanges of the central pawns. } 5... dxe4 (5... exd4 6. exd5 cxd5 7. Nxd4 $14 { White is slightly better because of the poor position of Black's knight. } { [%csl Rd7,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Gd4,Gf1] }) 6. Nxe4 exd4 7. Qxd4 { While it's true White lost a tempo by moving the d-pawn twice in the opening, and all central pawns are now exchanged, White enjoys a significant lead in development. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gc1,Gf1,Rc8,Rd7,Rf8,Rg8] } 7... Ngf6 { Pretty much Smyslov's only option. All the other pieces are stuck and the f8 bishop has to guard g7. } 8. Bg5! { Tal continues with his development, gets ready for long castling, and puts some pressure on the f6 knight. } { [%csl Rf6,Rd8][%cal Be1c1,Yg5d8] } 8... Be7 { Supporting the knight, but it has a drawback, which we see in the variation below. } { [%csl Rf6] } 9. O-O-O?! { Inaccuracy. Nd6+ was best. } { This is somewhat imprecise as it permits Black to castle without encountering any problems. } (9. Nd6+! { A nice move, because it forces Black to give up his DSB, except if he wants to play Kf8 of course, but that would be more miserable. } { [%csl Re7] } 9... Bxd6 { Forced. } 10. Qxd6 { White now is the only one with the bishop pair. } { [%csl Gf1,Gg5,Rc8][%cal Rd6f8] } 10... Ne4 { Any other move gives Black castling problems. } 11. Bxd8 Nxd6 12. Bc7 $16 { This is quite unpleasant for Black, because White has the bishop pair and a slight lead in development. } { [%csl Gc7,Gf1,Bc1,Gf3,Rd7,Rd6,Rc8][%cal Be1c1] }) 9... O-O { Smyslov castles too. } 10. Nd6 { Not bad, but it doesn't have the same effect as one move ago, because Black doesn't have to take it because he's not in check. } 10... Qa5 { A flexible move, bringing the queen into the game and attacking the a2 pawn. } { [%csl Ra2,Ga5] } 11. Bc4 { Tal defends his a2 pawn while developing. Now there's also a bit of pressure on f7. } { [%csl Gc4,Rf7,Gd6][%cal Gc4a2] } 11... b5 { Hitting the bishop and inviting Tal to take f7. } 12. Bd2!? { Inaccuracy. Bxf7+ was best. } { Tal responds to Smyslov's attack by counterattacking. The plan is to eventually maneuver the bishop to c3, targeting the black king. } { [%csl Ra5][%cal Bd2c3,Gc3h8] } (12. Bxf7+ { Stockfish's preferred option. Smyslov definitely saw this, but he didn't think this exchange was unfavorable for him. } 12... Rxf7 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. Kb1 $13 { Stockfish seems to prefer being White here, but it's still unclear. }) 12... Qa6 { Retreating, but still keeping pressure on the a2 pawn. } { [%csl Ra2] } 13. Nf5! { Instead of retreating his bishop, Tal places his knight on an active square, while gaining tempo by hitting the bishop. } { [%csl Gf5,Re7] } 13... Bd8 { The only way for Smyslov to save his bishop. } (13... bxc4?? 14. Nxe7+ Kh8 15. Bc3 { Tal has a strong attack. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3,Ge7][%cal Bd4h4] }) 14. Qh4! { Tal sacrifices a piece to stir up serious kingside threats! It's this daring style that makes analyzing Tal's games so enjoyable! } { [%csl Gf5,Gf3,Gh4,Rc4][%cal Bd2c3] } 14... bxc4 { Smyslov grabs the free piece, there isn't anything better for him than to be up material and hope to survive the onslaught. } 15. Qg5! { Tal keeps attacking. He's now threatening mate in 1. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Gg5g7,Rf5g7] } 15... Nh5! { Smyslov defends the g7# threat and returns the piece, it's a nice defensive move signaling an intent to play for the win. It's no surprise he's aiming for more than a draw, especially considering he actually beat Tal in the tournament's first round. } 16. Nh6+! { The best move, Tal temporarily delays taking the knight. } (16. Qxh5?? { Would have been losing because of the following sequence. } 16... Nf6! { Gaining tempo, whilst putting the knight on a more active position. } { [%csl Gf6] } 17. Qg5 Bxf5! { Getting rid of one of White's main attacking pieces. } 18. Qxf5 Qxa2 $19 { Black successfully exchanges nearly all the key attacking pieces, leaving him with a clearly winning position. } { [%csl Ga2] }) 16... Kh8 17. Qxh5 Qxa2 { Grabbing a free pawn and getting some counterattack on Tal's king. He's threatening mate in 1 now. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Ra2a1] } (17... gxh6?? { Leaves Black with a completely unsafe king. } { [%csl Rh8,Rh7,Rh6,Rf7] } 18. Qxh6 Rg8 19. Bc3+ f6 20. Ng5 $18 { White is completely winning because of his huge attack. } { [%csl Rh8,Rf6][%cal Yc3h8,Rf6g5,Bg5h7,Gh6h7] }) 18. Bc3 { Freeing up the d2 square for the king and aiming the bishop at Black's king. } { [%csl Gc3,Rg7,Rh8][%cal Bc1d2,Rd4h8,Rc3h8,Ra1h8] } 18... Nf6?? { Blunder. Bc7 was best. } { A big blunder. Tal has one winning move here, try to find it yourself :) } (18... Bc7! $10 { The best move, avoiding the threat. Now the best thing for Tal to do is make a draw by repetition, going for a win might backfire because Smyslov has a solid defense. } { [%cal Rc7d8] } 19. Nxf7+! Kg8 20. Nh6+ { It's a draw by threefold repetition. } 20... Kh8 (20... gxh6 { Blunder a forced mate. } 21. Qg4+ Kf7 22. Rxd7+! Bxd7 23. Qxd7+ Kg6 24. Qe6+ Kh5 25. g4# { Checkmate. } { [%csl Yg6,Yh6,Bh4,Bg5,Gh5][%cal Ye6h6,Bf3h4,Bf3g5,Gg4h5] }) 21. Nf7+ Kg8 $10) 19. Qxf7!! { Sacrificing the queen!! The point of this is that the rook is unable to capture the queen because it would leave the d8 bishop undefended, and Tal gets a checkmate. } 19... Qa1+ { This is the only move Black can play if he wants to prolong the game. } (19... Rxf7 { Forced mate in 3. } 20. Rxd8+! Ng8 21. Nxf7# { Ending with a smothered mate! } { [%csl Rg7,Rh7,Rg8,Gh8][%cal Gf7h8] }) 20. Kd2 { The point of Qa1+, now the king is blocking the rook from infiltrating the backrank. } { [%csl Rd2,Rd1,Rd8] } 20... Rxf7 { Now Smyslov grabs the queen, but his queen is still hanging. } { [%csl Ra1] } (20... Qxd1+ { Loses material too. } 21. Rxd1 Rxf7 22. Nxf7+ { A decisive fork. } { [%cal Rf7h8,Rf7d8] } 22... Kg8 23. Nxd8 $18 { White's simply up a full knight in a winning endgame. }) 21. Nxf7+! { Tal takes the rook with check, Smyslov's queen will get taken on the next move. } 21... Kg8 $7 22. Rxa1 Kxf7 { Being down an exchange may not seem so bad, but Smyslov's pawns are very weak, and will not be hard for Tal to win. Both players play a few more moves, but there isn't anything Smyslov can do, the position is hopeless. } { [%csl Rc4,Rc6,Ra7,Gb2,Gc2,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2] } 23. Ne5+ Ke6 24. Nxc6 { There goes a pawn. } 24... Ne4+ 25. Ke3 Bb6+ 26. Bd4 $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { And so, Smyslov resigned here. Tal went on to win the tournament with a very convincing score and then defeated Botvinnik in the 1960 World Championship match and became the 8th World Champion. } 1-0


