[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]

{ Mikhail Tal vs NN, 1963 "Trick Or Treat" }
1. e4 { You guessed it, 1. e4! } 1... c5 { We get another Sicilian game! The next few moves will be the standard opening moves of the Sicilian Najdorf, as seen in chapter 4 (Mikhail Tal vs Alexander Koblencs, Riga 1961) } 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 { Until now we have the same moves from chapter 4. } 7... b5!? { Ok, something different! The Polugaevsky Variation. This variation is quite rare, being played only 3% of the time, but the point of this move is that Black immediately wants to gain space on the queenside and place the LSB on b7, where it will be active along the a8-h1 diagonal. } { [%csl Gb5,Ga6][%cal Bc8b7] } 8. e5! { Tal plays this strong pawn break to open up the position. } 8... dxe5 9. fxe5 { You may think that Tal is currently completely winning because Black will lose his knight because it's pinned, but this is still equal after Qc7. } { [%csl Rd8,Rf6][%cal Gg5d8,Ye5f6] } 9... Qc7 { After White takes the f6 knight, Black can simply fork Tal's king and bishop and win back the piece! } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gc7e5] } 10. Qe2! { Tal obviously saw the variation below, so went for this line instead. He defends the e5 pawn/square and gets ready to castle queenside. exf6 is now a threat, because Qe5+ no longer works. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge2e5,Re5f6,Be1c1] } (10. exf6 { Temporarily sacrificing the knight... } 10... Qe5+ $10 { Black wins back his sacrificed piece and White ends up losing the bishop pair. It's an interesting game! } { [%csl Re1,Rg5,Gc8,Gf8][%cal Ge5g5,Ge5e1] }) 10... Nfd7 { We now see the strength of e5 because it forces Black's knight to retreat, compelling Black to move the same piece twice in a position where development is already challenging. } { [%csl Rd7,Rc7,Rc8,Rb8,Rf8,Re8,Gd4,Gc3,Gg5,Ge2][%cal Rg8f6,Rf6d7] } 11. O-O-O { Tal castles his king on the queenside. Now the d1 rook is also joining the game. The e pawn may seem like it's hanging, but if Black were to take it, White has a very nice sequence (shown in the variation below). } { [%csl Ge2,Gd4,Gc3,Gg5,Gc1,Gd1] } 11... Bb7 { Black develops the bishop, Tal has a nice surprise... } (11... Qxe5?? { A free pawn, but... } 12. Qxe5 Nxe5 13. Ndxb5!! { Nxe6!! is equally good! White opens up the d1 rook. White threatens mate in 1 with Rd8# and to fork the king and rook with Nc7+, Black can't stop both. This reminds me a lot of: Richard Reti vs Savielly Tartakower https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1250654 } { [%csl Rd8,Rc7][%cal Bb5c7,Rc7a8,Rc7e8,Yd1d8,Gg5d8] }) (11... Nxe5?? 12. Ndxb5!! { The same thing, GG! } { [%csl Rd8,Rc7][%cal Gg5d8,Gd1d8,Bb5c7] }) 12. Nxe6!! { Tal sacrifices the knight!! A beautiful positional sacrifice! The purpose behind this move is to open the e8-h5 diagonal, exposing weaknesses around the king. It's important to note that this sacrifice isn't an immediate, decisive blow, but rather a beginning of an attack. } 12... fxe6 { Black has many light-square weaknesses. } { [%csl Re8,Rf7,Re6] } 13. Qg4! { Immediately Tal activated the queen! } { [%csl Re6,Gg5,Gg4] } 13... Qb6?? { Blunder. Qxe5 was best. } { A decisive blunder, this completely doesn't do anything to improve Black's position. Tal now just dominates the d file and has much more active pieces. } { [%csl Rb8,Rb7,Rb6,Rd7,Ra8,Rf8,Re8,Gd1,Gg4,Gg5,Re6,Rf7][%cal Yd1d8] } (13... Qxe5! { The best move, getting rid of Tal's central control and activating the queen. } { [%csl Ge5] } 14. Bd3! { Clearing the way for Rhe1. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Bh1e1] } 14... Be7 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Rhe1 $14 { White dominates the center and still has an attack. Black's king is weak and his pieces aren't well placed. White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed knight. } { [%csl Gd1,Ge1,Gg4,Gc3,Re7,Rb8,Rb7,Ra8,Gd3][%cal Ye1e8,Yd1d8] }) 14. Rd6! { Tal sacrifices the roook! Now there's nothing Black can do anymore to survive. If he doesn't take the rook, Tal simply grabs e6 with the queen or rook and checkmate will follow soon. And taking the rook, also leads to a beautiful checkmate we will see in the game. :) } { [%cal Rd6b6,Rd6e6,Rg4e6] } 14... Bxd6 { Black takes the rook with the bishop, this leaves e6 undefended. } { [%csl Gd6] } (14... Qd8 { Here are some ways the game can end immediately. } 15. Rxe6+ Qe7 16. Bxe7 Bxe7 17. Rxe7+ Kxe7 18. Qxg7+ Kd8 19. Qxh8+ $18 { [%csl Gh8] }) (14... Qc5 15. Qxe6+ Be7 16. Qxe7# { [%csl Ge8,Gd8,Gf8,Gf7,Rd7][%cal Ge7e8,Ge7d8,Ge7f8,Ge7f7] }) 15. Qxe6+! { Forcing the king to move! Tal's aim isn't merely to capture a free pawn, but to construct a mating net around the exposed king. } { [%csl Re8,Ge6,Yd8,Rf7][%cal Ge6e8,Yg5d8,Ge6f7] } 15... Kf8 (15... Be7 { Simply mate in 1. } 16. Qxe7#) 16. Bc4!! { Tal sacrifices a THIRD piece! The purpose behind this beautiful move is to free the f1 square for the h1 rook, allowing it to join the assault on Black's king. While moving the bishop anywhere would be winning, going for Bc4 threatens an immediate checkmate with Qf7#, thus gaining a tempo, ending the game a bit sooner! :) } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Bh1f1,Rf1f8,Yc4f7] } 16... bxc4 17. Rf1+! { Black's literally up 9 points in material right now. } { [%csl Gf1,Ge6][%cal Rf1f8,Ye6g8,Ye6e8] } 17... Nf6 { Black's king has no more squares to run too, he can only block the check. } 18. Rxf6+!! { Ending the game in style! This opens up the f8-h6 diagonal. } { [%csl Ge8,Gg8,Rf7,Re7][%cal Re6e8,Re6g8] } 18... gxf6 19. Bh6# { 1-0 White wins. } { And that's game over! Tal's relentless attack culminates in an incredibly stylish checkmate, despite being down 11 points in material! It's a beautiful 19-move miniature that showcases Tal's tactical brilliance. Props to his opponent for allowing Tal to finish with such finesse! } { [%csl Yg8,Yf7,Ye8,Ye7,Bf8,Bg7][%cal Ye6g8,Ye6e8,Bh6f8] } 1-0


[Event "Moscow Blitz Tournament"]
[Site "Moscow RUS"]
[Date "1992.05.28"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Garry Kasparov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B51"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Moscow Variation"]
[StudyName "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!"]
[ChapterName "Mikhail Tal - Garry Kasparov"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/e0k7Thp8"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]

{ Mikhail Tal - Garry Kasparov, Moscow 1992 "Swan Song"
In a remarkable display of determination, Mikhail Tal, despite battling declining health at 55 years old, rose from his hospital bed to play his final game of chess against the World Champion, Garry Kasparov. This final match, called his "Swan Song," showed how much Tal loved chess and how he never gave up, even when things were tough. Note: This was a 5+0 blitz game. }
1. e4! { Tal starts the game with his favorite starting move, 1. e4! } 1... c5 { Kasparov respond with the Sicilian Defense. } 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ { Tal goes for the Moscow Variation. In the previous game Tal went for Open-Sicilian variations with 3. d4. Bb5+ is a common Anti-Sicilian move, developing the bishop with tempo and facilitating kingside castling. White might aim to mimic the Ruy Lopez's rapid development or control d5 with c4, often followed by exchanging the bishop to prevent it from being stuck behind the c4 pawn. } { [%csl Bg1,Re8][%cal Be1g1] } 3... Nd7 { Kasparov blocks the check. } 4. d4 { Tal strikes the center, opening files and challenging Black's c-pawn. White can always castle later. } (4. Bxd7+?! { A common beginner mistake. White has just moved his bishop twice in the opening, this is usually not a good idea. Also, exchanging a perfectly fine bishop for Black's passive d7 knight doesn't improve White's position in any way. } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Rf1b5,Rb5d7] }) 4... Nf6 { Kasparov develops his knight. } { [%cal Bb1b2] } 5. O-O! { Tal brings his king to safety by castling. The e4 pawn is hanging, but taking it leads to bad consequences for Black, shown in the variations below. } { [%csl Re4] } 5... a6 { Kasparov hits Tal's bishop, forcing him to either trade it or retreat it. } { [%cal Ra6b5] } (5... Nxe4? { A mistake. This allows White to get some activity. } 6. Re1! { The rook now dominates the d file and hits the knight, gaining tempo. } { [%csl Ge1,Re4] } 6... Nf6 7. dxc5 { Simplifying the center, opening up the d file. } { [%csl Gd1] } 7... dxc5 8. Ng5 $16 { Black has very hard development. White can develop very easily. Ng5 is the most tricky variation, there are quite a few traps. I'll show a few. } { [%csl Gg5,Gb5,Rd7,Rd8,Rc8,Rf8,Re8,Rf6,Re7,Ge1][%cal Bb1c3,Bc1f4,Bb5c4] } 8... a6?? { A losing blunder because of... } (8... h6? 9. Nxf7 Kxf7 10. Bc4+ Ke8 11. Nc3 { Black's king has lost his castling rights, now has an incredibly hard time developing his pieces, and now has light-square weaknesses. White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed knight. It's +2. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc3,Ge1,Rf7,Re8,Rg6,Rd8,Rd7,Rf8,Rf6,Rc8][%cal Bd1d3,Bc1f4] }) 9. Bc4! { Simply saving the bishop and attacking f7. } 9... e6 10. Nxf7!! { Forking. } { [%csl Ge1,Gc4,Re6][%cal Rf7d8,Rf7h8] } 10... Kxf7 11. Rxe6 { It's +6 because the king is way too weak and all Black's pieces are undeveloped. White's pieces are/or can easily attack Black's weak king. } { [%csl Gc4,Rf7,Rd8,Rd7,Rf6,Rf8,Rc8,Ra8,Rh8,Ge6][%cal Bd1f3,Bc1g5,Bb1c3,Bc3d5,Be6f6] }) 6. Bxd7+ { Tal trades the bishop for the d7 knight with check. } 6... Nxd7 { Kasparov recaptures with the knight, maintaining control over the center. } { [%csl Ge5,Gc5][%cal Yd7c5,Yd7e5] } 7. Nc3 e6 { Kasparov challenges control over the d5 and f5 squares, setting up to bring the Bishop to e7 and prepare for castling. } { [%csl Ge6,Rd5][%cal Ge6d5,Bf8e7] } 8. Bg5 { Tal develops his bishop and gains tempo by hitting the queen. } { [%csl Rd8,Gg5][%cal Gg5d8] } 8... Qc7 { Kasparov puts his queen on a safe square. } (8... f6! { Another possible move, usually you don't want to play f6/f7 because it weakens the kingside, but in this scenario it's fine because it kicks the bishop away and doesn't have a bad effect on Black's position after: } 9. Be3 Be7 { Getting ready to castle. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 10. a4 O-O { The f6 pawn is no weakness. It controls the e5 square, helping for a potential e5 pawn push or it can advance to f5, making the f8 rook more useful. } { [%csl Be5,Gf8][%cal Be6e5,Gf6e5,Bf6f5] }) 9. Re1?! { Inaccuracy. d5 was best. } { Tal chooses a slightly inaccurate move, aiming for active piece play but overlooking a stronger alternative. } { [%csl Ge5] } (9. d5 { The best move, closing the center, but it's for White's advantage. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd5] } 9... e5 (9... exd5? { Already a mistake. } 10. Nxd5 $18 { White has an in incredibly strong knight on the d5 outpost. } { [%csl Gd5,Gg5,Gf3][%cal Rd5c7,Ba2a4,Bf1e1] }) 10. a4 g6 11. Nd2 Bg7 12. Nc4 $16 { It's hard for Black to activate his pieces. The queenside pieces have no good place to go and the DSB's diagonal is fully blocked. white can easily start an attack with a potential f4 or even g4 at some point. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc3,Gg5,Rd7,Rc7,Rc8,Rg7][%cal Bf2f4,Bg2g4] }) 9... cxd4 { Kasparov exchanges in the center, taking away White's pawn which controls the e5 square. } { [%cal Bd7e5] } 10. Nxd4 (10. Qxd4 f6 { Gaining tempo and reinforcing the e5 square. } { [%cal Bf6e5,Bd6e5] } 11. Be3 Ne5 $10 { [%csl Ge5] }) 10... Ne5 { Kasparov now has a strong well-placed central knight. This was the point of the trade on d4. } { [%csl Ge5] } 11. f4 { Tal kicks Kasparov's central e5 knight. } { [%cal Rf4e5] } 11... h6! { Kasparov counters Tal's threat by kicking the g5 bishop. } (11... Ng6? { If Kasparov would have just reacted to the threat, Tal could just keep hitting him. } 12. f5 $16 { [%csl Gf5,Gg5,Ge4,Gd4,Gc3,Rg6,Re8,Ge1] }) 12. Bh4 { Tal retreats his bishop, but Kasparov's knight is still hanging. } { [%cal Rf4e5] } (12. fxe5?? { This allows Black to simply get an open h file, then the h8 rook becomes a real threat. } 12... hxg5 { White will have to do his best defending here. It's -2.0. } { [%csl Gh8,Rh2] }) 12... g5 { Another in-between move. Kasparov's plan is to get rid of the f-pawn, aiming to open up a vulnerability on e5 that he can take advantage of. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Rg5h4] } 13. fxe5 gxh4 { Tal now doesn't have the problem with the open h-file. } { [%csl Rh6,Rh4] } 14. exd6?! { A slight inaccuracy, as this move only aids Kasparov in developing his dark-squared bishop. Nonetheless, Tal's intention was clear: to delay any immediate threats to his position while also working to eliminate the doubled e-pawns. } (14. Qh5! { Activating the queen! } { [%csl Gh5] } 14... dxe5 15. Nf3 $10 { It's still equal, but White definitely has more activity compared to exd6. Black has doubled e and h pawns that are weaknesses and White can dominate the d file with a future Rd1. } { [%csl Re5,Rh4][%cal Ba1d1,Bf3h4] }) 14... Bxd6 { Recapturing. The bishop is now developed and aiming at h2. } { [%csl Gd6,Gc7,Rh2][%cal Rc7h2] } 15. Nd5!? { Mistake. e5 was best. } { A typical Tal move! Not most accurate, but keep in mind that this was a blitz game, so Tal wanted to complicate the position more. } { [%cal Rd5c7] } (15. e5! { Would have been better. } 15... Bxe5 16. Nd5! { Tal would have still gotten this fancy sacrifice. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rd5c7] } 16... exd5 { Pinning the bishop. } { [%csl Re8,Re5][%cal Ge1e8,Ge1e5] } 17. Qh5 { Double attacking the pinned bishop, f6 is not possible because it's pinned too. } { [%csl Re5,Re8][%cal Gh5e5,Ye1e5,Rf7f6] } 17... O-O 18. Rxe5 $16 { Black's king is now very unsafe because he doesn't has any pawns to protect him anymore. The two h-pawns can be won very easily. } { [%csl Rg8,Ge5,Gh5,Rh6,Rh4,Gd4] }) 15... exd5 { Kasparov probably took some good seconds thinking over his move, but eventually, he went for it and accepted Tal's knight sacrifice. } 16. exd5+ { Discovered check! } { [%csl Re8][%cal Ge1e8] } 16... Kf8 17. Qf3 { 1-0 White wins. } { This is where Garry Kasparov's time ran out. Yes, Stockfish might say Kasparov had the upper hand, but in the end, a win's a win. Despite its controversy, I included this game because it marked Tal's final match and showed his enduring passion for chess. } { [%csl Gf3] } 1-0


