[Event "Simul"]
[Site "Riga LAT"]
[Date "1949.??.??"]
[White "Ratmir Kholmov"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D44"]
[Opening "Semi-Slav Defense: Botvinnik Variation"]
[StudyName "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!"]
[ChapterName "Ratmir Kholmov - Mikhail Tal"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/zK4a19Yy"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]

{ Ratmir Kholmov vs Mikhail Tal, Riga 1949 "A Star Is Born"
This is Tal's first ever recorded game. He was only 12 years old at the time and facing a 24 year old GM, double his age in a simul. It's a true underdog story, marking the beginning of Tal's incredible journey in chess. }
1. c4 { Kholmov starts the game with 1. c4, the English Opening. } 1... e6 { Tal fights for control of d5 and plans to put a pawn there. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ye6d5,Bd7d5] } 2. Nc3 { Kholmov continues developing } 2... d5 { Tal immediately strikes the center with d5. } 3. d4 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] } 3... c6!? { With 3...c6, we have now transposed into the Semi-Slav Defense, a solid and flexible opening choice having become more popular in the recent years. Tal now has a very solid pawn chain and the queen can potentially move somewhere along the d8-a5 diagonal. The drawback here is the LSB, which is stuck behind the pawn chain. It usually gets preserved for very later on in the game. } { [%csl Yd5,Yc6,Yb7,Ye6,Yf7,Gd8,Rc8][%cal Yb7c6,Yc6d5,Ye6d5,Yf7e6,Bd8a5] } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 { Kholmov pins Tal's knight. } { [%csl Rf6,Rd8][%cal Yg5d8] } 5... dxc4 { Tal takes the c4 pawn, this allows Kholmov to control the center with e4, becasue the d5 pawn no longer controls that square, but Tal will get more activity on the queenside. } { [%csl Be4][%cal Be2e4,Yd5e4] } 6. e4 { We have now arrived in the Botvinnik Variation, a scary line in which both players will have to find some only-moves. I have a chapter on this variation in my Queen's Gambit study (White's perspective): https://lichess.org/study/0uRBskUV/KOz2yr9l } 6... b5! { Protecting the c4 pawn. Black has just sacrificed the center for the c4 pawn, so he'll have to keep it. } 7. e5 { At first it might look like White's winning a piece here because the pinned knight can't move (he can actually, but then the queen's a goner), but Black has a nice resource. } { [%csl Rd8,Rf6][%cal Yg5d8,Re5f6] } 7... h6! { Counterattacking the bishop! } 8. Bxf6?! { Inaccuracy. Bh4 was best. } { An inaccuracy by Kholmov, he gives up his strong light-squared-bishop for Tal's knight and is a pawn down. } (8. Bh4 { The only move that keeps the advantage. This is what I mean with "both sides will have to play some only-moves." } 8... g5! { Again counterattacking the bishop! The pin is now broken. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh4] } 9. Nxg5! { The f6-knight is still hanging so White's not really sacrificing the knight. } 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 $14 { White is now temporarily down a knight, but keeps the pin, so he'll forcefully win the f6 knight. Stockfish gives White a slight advantage, but the game can still go both ways. It's an interesting battle! } { [%csl Rf6] }) 8... gxf6 9. exf6 { [%csl Rf6] } 9... Bb4? { Mistake. Qxf6 was best. } { The bishop doesn't have any intentions here. Trade it for a passive knight? Get ready to castle in a broken kingside? They don't benefit Black. Better was a simple Qxf6, activating the queen. } { [%cal Be8g8,Bb4c3] } 10. Be2?! { Inaccuracy. g3 was best. } { Better was g3, going for a fianchetto and kingside castling. Then White gets a bishop controlling the long diagonal and the king is more safely placed because of the solid setup. } { [%cal Bg2g3,Bf1g2] } (10. g3 { [%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1] } 10... Bb7 11. Bg2 Nd7 12. O-O { [%csl Gh2,Gg2,Gg3,Gf2,Gg1] }) 10... Qxf6 { Tal now takes the hanging f6 pawn. } 11. O-O { Kholmov castles kingside. } 11... Bxc3?! { Inaccuracy. Bb7 was best. } { A bit of an inaccuracy by Tal. Now he no longer has the bishop pair and Kholmov's d pawn will be no longer isolated. Kholmov can now also get some activity on the queenside with a4. It was better for Tal to just continue developing with either Bb7 or Nd7. } (11... Bb7 12. Rc1 Nd7 { [%cal Bf8g6,Bd7f8,Bc6c5,Bh8g8,Ba7a5] }) 12. bxc3 { [%csl Gd4,Gc3][%cal Gc3d4,Ba2a4] } 12... Nd7 { Tal's getting his pieces moving, turning the passive ones active. } 13. a4! { Kholmov wants to get some activity on the queenside. With a4 he disrupts Tal's pawn structure and tries to get an open a-file for his rook in the near future. } 13... Bb7 { Placing the LSB on the long diagonal. It can become active in the future with a potential c5 pawn push. The h8 rook can join on g8 to create more pressure. } { [%cal Bh8g8,Bg8g1,Bc6c5] } 14. Ne5? { Mistake. Nd2 was best. } { I don't know why Kholmov played this, it simply loses a pawn. He wants to clear the f3 square for the LSB, but he could have also done this with Nd2. The difference tho, is that the d-file will be opened. } (14. Nd2! { Looks useless at first, but it makes sense. } 14... a6 { Protecting b5. } 15. Bf3! { Meeting Black's LSB! c5 can no longer be played to activate the bishop. } { [%csl Rb7][%cal Gf3b7] }) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 { Tal is now up 2 pawns, but his pawn structure is quite bad. Like Tal's queenside can be easily weakened. } { [%csl Rc4,Rb5] } 16. Bf3 { Kholmov prevents a future c5, which opens up the h1-a8 diagonal for Tal's bishop. } { [%csl Gf3,Gb7][%cal Rc6c5] } 16... Rd8 { Tal brings his a8 rook into the game. It now controls the d-file and hits the queen. The downside here is that it leaves the a7 pawn unprotected. } { [%csl Ra7,Gd8] } 17. Qc2 { Kholmov puts his queen on a safe square. } 17... Rd3! { Double attacking the c3 pawn, but Tal has a secret much bigger unstoppable threat... } { [%cal Gd3c3,Ge5c3] } 18. axb5 { Attacking the a7 pawn, after Rxa7 the LSB is trapped. } { [%csl Ra7][%cal Ga1a7] } (18. Rac1 { Lets say White would protect his c3 pawn, then Black has the same beautiful combination played in the game. } 18... Rxf3!! { Sacrificing the ROOOK! } 19. gxf3 { Now the g-file has been opened and Kholmov's king is fully exposed. } { [%csl Rg1][%cal Bh8g8] } 19... Rg8+! 20. Kh1 c5 { Threatening Bxf3#. This is unstoppable. After Qd1, Black simply plays Qf4 and double attacks the f3 pawn. With perfect play, this is mate in 7 for Black. } { [%csl Rf3,Yg1,Yg2,Rh1][%cal Be5f4,Bb7f3,Yg8g1] }) (18. Rfe1 { Kholmov's best option, hitting the queen gaining tempo, thus stopping Black from playing Rxf3. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Ge1e5] } 18... Qxc3 { The next sequence is kinda forced. } 19. Qxc3 Rxc3 20. axb5! { Attacking the a7 pawn (if taken, White traps the b7 bishop), Black can't protect it, so the best way to lose the least amount of material is Rxf3. } { [%csl Ra7] } 20... Rxf3! 21. Rxa7 (21. gxf3 { Gaining time to save the bishop. } 21... Rg8+ { An optional in-between move. } 22. Kf1 cxb5 { This wasn't possible before, because White's bishop would just capture ours. } { [%csl Gb7] } 23. Rxa7 Bxf3 $19 { It's a rook vs bishop + 3 pawns endgame. This is definitely much easier to play as black. It's -2.3. } { [%csl Gf3,Gg8,Gc4,Gb5] }) 21... cxb5 22. Rxb7 Rd3 { Rb1+ Rd8. } 23. Rxb5 Kd7 $19 { Black ends up being up a clean pawn. It will still definitely take some work to convert this into a win. }) 18... Rxf3!! { Tal finds the only move that keeps the advantage! He sacrifices the ROOOK! This completely breaks down the White king's defense. } 19. Rxa7 { Kholmov attacks Tal's bishop first. } { [%cal Ra7b7] } 19... Qxb5! { A very calm move! This simply deals with the Rxb7 threat. } (19... Rh3!! { A really fancy move that completely works (not necessarily better than what Tal played tho)! Black threatens checkmate on h2. } { [%csl Rh2] } 20. gxh3 Rg8+! 21. Kh1 $7 cxb5+!! { Temporarily sacrificing the bishop. } 22. Rxb7 (22. f3 Bxf3+!! 23. Rxf3 Qe1+ 24. Rf1 Qxf1# { Checkmate! }) 22... Qd5+ { A fork! } 23. f3 Qxb7 { Considering White's trash pawn structure and that all his pieces have to babysit the pawns around the king (because Qxf3 is checkmate) this is completely hopeless for White. } { [%csl Rh3,Rh2,Rf3,Rc3][%cal Gf1f3] }) 20. gxf3 { The game ending move. } (20. Qb1 { Kholmov's best try. } 20... Qxb1 21. Rxb1 Rxc3 22. Raxb7 O-O $19 { Black will lose the c6 pawn, but he'll then still be up a nice passer and be in a winning position. } { [%csl Gc4,Rc6] }) 20... Qg5+ { Rg8+ is an alternative. } { [%csl Gg1][%cal Gg5g1] } 21. Kh1 $7 Rg8 { 0-1 Black wins. } { Qg2# is unstoppable. It is at this point that Ratmir Kholmov resigned. Mikhail Tal, just 12 years old, has just taken down this famous grandmaster. This beautifully illustrates the power of an open g-file against a defenseless king. } { [%csl Rg2][%cal Gg5g2] } 0-1


[Event "USSR Championship"]
