{ Bukhuti Gurgenidze vs Mikhail Tal, Moscow 1957 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 { Tal goes for the Benoni Defense, one of the most aggressive responses to 1. d4. This isn't really a gambit because A. Black can just win the pawn back with Qa5+, a fork (it doesn't mean Black has to play this) B. Taking c5 leads to bad consequences for White (shown in the variation below). } 3. d5 { White declines the "gambit" (the best option) by pushing the pawn forward, going for a closed game. } (3. dxc5?! { White is wasting time by taking a pawn he can't keep anyway. } 3... e6! { The best move! Developing while attacking the pawn. } { [%csl Rc5,Rc4,Gf8] } 4. b4 { Common among beginners. Again, developing comes first. } (4. Be3 { [%csl Re3,Rh1,Rg1,Rf1,Rd1,Re2,Re1,Rb1,Ra1,Gd8,Gf8][%cal Ba7a5,Bb8a6,Bb8c6,Bf6g4] }) 4... a5 $17 { There is no way to keep the pawn anymore, } { [%csl Rb4,Rc4,Rc5,Gf6,Gf8,Ga5,Ga8] } 5. Bd2? axb4 6. Bxb4 Nc6 { Hitting the bishop. Black just wants to stop it from defending c5. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4] } 7. Ba3?? { Loses due to a simple tactic. } (7. Qb3 { Doesn't work either. } 7... Nxb4 8. Qxb4 Ne4 $19 { Black is completely winning. } { [%csl Rb4,Rc4,Rc5,Re1,Rf1,Rg1,Rh1,Rh2,Rg2,Rf2,Re2,Rb1,Ra1,Ga8,Gf8,Gd8][%cal Re4c5,Rf8c5,Bd8f6,Bd8a5] }) 7... Rxa3! { Temporarily sacrificing the exchange. } 8. Nxa3 Qa5+ { The famous fork! } { [%csl Ra3,Re1][%cal Ra5a3,Ra5e1] } 9. Qd2 $7 { The only legal move, or resigning is probably the best option. } 9... Qxa3 { Material might be equal, but because White is completely undeveloped, Black has a huge advantage (eval: -5.5). Black's main threat is Ne4, kicking away the queen, and then Black follows up with Qa5+, forcing White's poor king to bongcloud, and it will be over soon after that. } { [%csl Rh1,Rg1,Rf1,Re1,Rd2,Ra1][%cal Bf6e4,Bf8c5,Bc6b4] }) 3... e6! { The Modern Variation. Tal himself is the man who popularized this opening. In this opening, Black accepts a pawn weakness on d6 but compensates with increased activity. } (3... b5 { The Benko Gambit, one of my favorites. } 4. cxb5 e6 5. dxe6 fxe6 6. Nc3 d5 7. e3 Bd6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Qe7 11. a4 O-O $10 { Black's winrate is at 67%. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge6,Gd6,Ge7,Gd7,Gf6,Gg8,Gb7] }) 4. Nc3 { Prepares for the central pawn advance of e4. } { [%cal Be2e4] } 4... exd5 { Tal simplifies the center. } 5. cxd5 d6 { Tal strengthens his central pawn structure and gives the LSB some space to breathe. Often the d7 square is used for the b8 knight. From d7 it can jump to b6 or hop in the center on e5. } { [%csl Gc8][%cal Bb8d7,Bd7e5] } 6. Nf3 { A standard developing move. } 6... g6 { Tal prepares to castle kingside by fianchettoing the bishop. The bishop is most active there. It has no life along the f8-a3 diagonal because of the closed pawn structure. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Bf8g7,Be8g8] } 7. e4 { Gurgenidze occupies the center. } { [%csl Ge4] } 7... Bg7 { Putting the bishop on the long diagonal. It can become very powerful in the future. } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7h8,Gg7a1] } 8. Be2 { Preparing to castle. } 8... O-O { [%csl Gg8] } 9. O-O { Both players bring the king to safety. } { [%csl Gg1,Gg8] } 9... Re8 { Tal develps the rook to a more active square. Here it puts pressure on White's e pawn. } { [%csl Ge8,Re4] } 10. Nd2 { Retreating the knight in order to defend e4. From here it can also reroute to more active squares in the future, once the e4 pawn is strengthened. } { [%cal Bd2c4,Bd2b3,Be2f3,Bf1e1] } 10... Na6 { Yes, a knight on the rim is grim, but the idea of this move is to reroute to c7 where it will play a better role. Like a Rb8-a6-b5 idea is possible and many more. } 11. Re1 { Improving the rook's placement. } (11. Bxa6?! { Yes, it gives Black doubled pawns, but what does this compensate enough for all the good Black receives? } 11... bxa6 { Black has the bishop pair, an open b file for the rook, and Black controls the b5 square so that no knight can hop in. This is enough to compensate for the doubled a pawns. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ba8b8,Ba6a5,Ba5a4,Ba4a3,Ra6b5] }) 11... Nc7 12. a4 { Gurgenidze expands on the queenside, preparing for possible pawn breaks and giving the rook some air. } { [%csl Ga1,Ga4] } 12... b6 { Tal goes for a solid pawn setup. } { [%csl Gb6,Gc5,Ga7,Gd6][%cal Ga7b6,Gb6c5,Gd6c5] } (12... a6 { Another good option. Going for the b5 idea. } { [%cal Ba6b5,Ba8b8] } 13. h3 Rb8 { Reinforcing. } 14. Bf3 b5 15. axb5 { [%csl Gb5] } 15... axb5 { Black gets an expanded queenside. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd6,Gb5] }) 13. Qc2 { Gurgenidze places the queen on a more flexible square. } 13... Ng4?! { Inaccuracy. Rb8 was best. } { Tal initiates an attack on the kingside, tho Stockfish gives this the ?! mark because of the variation below. } 14. h3?! { Inaccuracy. Bxg4 was best. } { Gurgenidze wants to get rid of the annoying knight on g5 without having to trade away his bishop pair. He missed one thing tho, that Tal likely saw beforehand: } (14. Bxg4 Bxg4 15. Nc4 $16 { White has a strong knight on c4. The g4 bishop has no role on it's current square. } { [%csl Rg4,Gc4] }) 14... Nxf2!! { Tal sacrifices his knight for an attack, taking advantage of the weakened kingside. The best move for White is to ignore everything with Nf3, and with perfect play that would have been a draw. But it very doubled-edged, both sides will have to play quite a few 'only' moves. You can analyze further with Stockfish to see how crazy things get after 15. Nf3. } 15. Kxf2?? { Blunder. Nf3 was best. } { A blunder, this allows Black to get a huge attack on the exposed king. } 15... Qh4+! { Bringing the queen into action! The king is forced to go to f1, to keep the rook protected. g3 is mate in 6. } 16. Kf1 (16. g3 { Ends the game. } 16... Bd4+ { Next Black will always be able to take h3 and bring the white king out. Checkmate is inevitable. } { [%csl Rh3,Gc8,Gh4][%cal Bh4h3,Bc8h3] }) 16... Bd4 { Another piece is brought into the attack. Tal also Threatens mate in 1 on f2. As you can see, most of Gurgenidze's pieces are all squished up on the queenside, while Tal's attack is on the kingside. } { [%csl Rf2,Rc1,Rd2,Rc3,Rc2,Ra1,Re1,Re2][%cal Gd4f2,Gh4f2] } 17. Nd1 $7 { The only move to stop checkmate. } 17... Qxh3!! { Tal, the master of sacrifices, of course finds this beautiful queen sacrifice! White is unable to take the queen because that's #-1. At this point White is forced to move the e2 bishop because otherwise Qh1 is checkmate. } 18. Bf3 { Moving the bishop anywhere elsewhere leaves the g2 pawn unprotected. } (18. gxh3 Bxh3# { A brilliant Boden's mate! } { [%csl Rf1,Yg1,Yf2,Re1,Re2,Gg2][%cal Yd4g1,Gh3f1] }) 18... Qh2 { Things are really starting to get scary for Gurgenidze. Black's main threat is Nxd5, making use of the rook pin. } { [%csl Rg1,Rd5][%cal Bh2g1,Bd4g1,Bc7d5] } 19. Ne3 { The knight acts as a barrier and protects d5. } { [%csl Ge3,Ge8][%cal Ge3d5] } (19. Rb1 { A random move, just to show Black's initial threat. } 19... Nxd5!! 20. exd5 Qg1# { [%csl Be1,Be2,Rg2,Gf1,Gf2][%cal Rg1e1,Be8e1,Gg1f1,Gg1f2] }) 19... f5! { Tal continues the attack! Pushing the f pawn to get some pawn exchanges, opening up more lines for the rook. } 20. Ndc4 { Gurgenidze tries to get his pieces more active. The queen now reaches more squares. } { [%csl Gc2,Gc1] } 20... fxe4! { Tal opens the f and e files. } 21. Bxe4 { [%cal Ge4e1,Ge4e8,Gf5f8,Gf5f1] } 21... Ba6! { Bringing the bishop into the game by placing it on this active square where it pins the knight and controls the a6-f1 diagonal. The a8 rook can now also join the game. } { [%csl Ga6,Ga8] } (21... Rf8+?? { May seem tempting, but the attack is stops after Ke2. } 22. Ke2 { The king always ends up escaping, the position is 100% equal because Black will always be able to get some repetition, nothing more. } { [%cal Ge2d1,Ge2d3,Ge2d2] }) 22. Bf3 Re5 { Tal plans to double his rooks to add pressure on White's pinned knight (if the e3 knght ever moves, Qg1 is checkmate). Note: Re5 and Re7 are equally good because they both keep the same idea in mind. } 23. Ra3 { Gurgenidze supports his knight. } 23... Rae8! { Tal doubles the rooks. } 24. Bd2? { Mistake. b4 was best. } { Gurgenidze should have tried to run his king over to safety with Ke2, but it's already really bad for White. } { [%cal Bf1e2,Be2d1] } 24... Nxd5! { Grabbing a free pawn by making use of the pins. } { [%csl Re3,Gd4,Ge5,Ge8] } 25. Bxd5+ Rxd5 { Again, Nxd5 loses due to Qg1#. Tal has just gotten rid of White's f3 bishop, one of White's best pieces, because it defended his king. There are way too many threats from Black, White's position crumbles just a couple of moves later. } { [%cal Bh2f4,Bd5g5,Bh2h1] } 26. Ke2 { An attempt to run the king to safety. } 26... Bxe3 { There are many ways to win for Black, this is the most simplest option. } 27. Rxe3 Bxc4+ { 0-1 Black wins. } { Here Gurgenidze resigned the game. We'll go a couple of moves further to show why this position is hopeless for White. } 28. Qxc4 { Simply mate in 2. } (28. Kd1 Rxe3 29. Rxe3 Qg1+ 30. Re1 Qf2 { It's -9 because there's always the fancy Bb3, forcing the queen away from defending e2. } { [%csl Rb3,Rd2][%cal Bc4b3,Bf2d2] }) 28... Qxg2+ 29. Kd1 Qxd2# { Checkmate. } { [%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2d1,Gd2e1,Gd2c1,Gd2c2,Gd2e2,Yd5d2] } 0-1


