{ Milko Bobotsov vs Mikhail Tal, Varna 1958 }
1. d4 { Bobotsov starts with 1. d4, and it's no surprise that Tal, with his Black pieces, often opts for either the Benoni, as seen in the previous game, or the King's Indian Defense (KID) in this match, given its sharp, counterattacking nature. } 1... Nf6 { The starting move in the KID. Next, Black fianchettoes the DSB by g6-Bg6 and plays d6 before castling to prevent e5 from Black. } { [%cal Bg7g6,Bf8g7,Be8g8,Bd7d6] } 2. c4 { Next we see some standard opening moves. } 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 { Preventing Bobotsov from kicking the f6 knight with e5. } { [%csl Ye5][%cal Re4e5,Yd6e5] } (4... O-O { Playable in this specific line, but I don't recommend it if you're not familiar with this opening. } 5. e5 Ne8 { [%csl Gf4] } 6. f4 $10 { White gets a big space advantage, it's still 100% equal tho. } { [%csl Gf4,Ge5,Gd4,Gc4] }) 5. f3 { The Sämisch Variation, a popular and favored line in the King's Indian. This solid move strengthens White's center without committing to a specific king-side castling. It keeps Black guessing and can pose a challenge since Black often hopes for White to overextend in the King's Indian. } { [%csl Ye4,Yf3,Yg2][%cal Yg2f3,Yf3e4,Bc1e3,Bd1d2,Be1c1] } 5... O-O 6. Nge2 { Bobotsov goes for this variation, which interestingly bears his name! The point of this move is that, sooner or later, it can potentially reroute to g3, where it can join in a future kingside attack. } { [%cal Be2g3,Bc1e3,Bd1d2] } 6... c5 { Tal puts some pressure on d4. This is a typical pawn structure in the Benoni Defense. } { [%csl Rd4] } 7. Be3! { Bobotsov reinforces d4 with his bishop. He now also gets another step closer to castling queenside. } (7. Ng3?! { Not a good move at the moment, because Black gains tempo after the following sequence. } 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 $15 { The queen has to move again. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] }) (7. dxc5?! { Not good either. } 7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 { Black ends up dominating the d file. } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gd8d1] }) 7... Nbd7 { A bit passive, but perfectly fine. From here the knight can jump to the e5 outpost once the d pawn were to move. } { [%cal Bd7e5,Yd4d5] } 8. Qd2 { Bobotsov prepares to bring his king to safety by long-castling. Also, at some point, Bh6 can be played to force a dark-squared-bishop trade. } { [%csl Bc1,Rg7,Rf8][%cal Be1c1,Be3h6,Rh6f8] } 8... a6! { Tal prepares to play b5, to get an attack going on the queenside. } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Bb7b5,Ba6b5] } 9. O-O-O { Bobotsov castles on the queenside, this is not bad, but a bit risky because Tal gets some play on the queenside and Bobotsov will have to defend. } (9. Rd1 { Stockfish's top move, controlling the d-file. This is a more safe option. Now White keeps his king in the center, but it's harder for Black to attack it. From here, White can start a pawn storm with h4 and g4. } { [%csl Gd1,Gd2,Ge1][%cal Bg2g4,Bh2h4] }) 9... Qa5 { Tal activates his queen first before playing b5. } { [%csl Ga5][%cal Bb7b5] } 10. Kb1 { On b1, the king is slightly more protected behind his pawns. } 10... b5! { Tal begins to expand on the queenside! He now wants to open up more files for his rooks to become more active. } 11. Nd5? { Mistake. h4 was best. } { Bobotsov likely had his eye on this tactical move, making use of the queen's position on a5, but Tal has an unexpected surprise! } (11. dxc5! { The best move, opening up the d file. } 11... dxc5 12. h4 $13 { White gets an attack on the kingside and should be able to defend against Black's attack. } { [%cal Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Be2f4,Bg2g4] }) 11... Nxd5!! { He sacrifices the queen (you were probably fully expecting this)!! This move is 100% correct according to the engine. In return for the queen, he gets two minor pieces with a strong attack. } 12. Qxa5 Nxe3 { Surprisingly, this position has been reached over 600 times in the lichess database! The engine gives an evaluation of -0.5. While this may not seem like a significant advantage, Black has won 62% of the time! This clearly demonstrates the ease of playing as Black in this position, thanks to the well-placed pieces (strong knight and powerful dark-squared bishop) and solid pawn structure. } { [%csl Ge3,Gg7,Yh7,Yg6,Yf7,Ye7,Yd6,Yc5,Ya6,Yb5][%cal Ya6b5,Yd6c5,Ye7d6,Yf7g6,Yh7g6,Re3c4,Re3d1] } 13. Rc1 Nxc4 { Grabbing the free pawn. } 14. Rxc4!? { Bobotsov sacrifices the exchange to get rid of the annoying knight while simultaneously creating weaknesses in Tal's pawn structure. } 14... bxc4 { [%csl Rc4,Ra6,Rc5] } 15. Nc1? { Mistake. Nf4 was best. } { The knight doesn't really have a good role on this square. } (15. Nf4 { Best } 15... Bxd4 16. Bxc4 $17 { The knight is more actively placed. } { [%cal Bf4d5] }) 15... Rb8! { Tal puts his rook to aim at the b2 pawn, now the DSB starts to get immensely powerful, the only thing in it's way is the d pawn, which will be no problem to get rid of. Tal is in complete control in this game. Bobotsov's pieces are all not doing much. } { [%csl Rb2,Gg7,Rb1,Rc1,Rh1,Ra5,Gb8][%cal Yg7b2,Yb8b2] } 16. Bxc4 Nb6 { Tal brings his knight into the game and hits Bobotsov's bishop. } { [%csl Gb6] } (16... Bxd4 { Fine too, but the reason Tal didn't go for this is because after... } 17. Nb3 { the bishop is forced back. } { [%cal Rb3d4,Bd4g7] }) 17. Bb3 Bxd4 { It starts to get very dangerous for Bobotsov, Bxb7-Nc4/c4 is Tal's current threat. } { [%csl Rb2,Rb1,Gb8,Gd4][%cal Rd4b2,Rc5c4,Bb6c4] } 18. Qd2?? { Blunder. Ne2 was best. } { A losing mistake because now Tal's attack is unstoppable. } (18. Ne2! { The only move to survive. } 18... Bxb2 19. Kc2 { Getting out of the b file, Kxb2 loses to Nc4+ again. } 19... Bf6 20. Rb1 $17 { White's pieces are more active compared to other moves than Ne2. Also, Bxf7+-Rxb6 is a threat from White. } { [%csl Rf7,Rb6][%cal Rb3f7,Bb1b6] }) (18. h3 { A random move to illustrate the main threat. } 18... Bxb2 19. Kxb2 Nc4+ { [%cal Rb8b2,Rb3c4,Bc4a5,Bc4b2] }) 18... Bg7! { Tal calmly removes the bishop from the center to g7, where it is safe, now the c4 advance is inevitable. } { [%cal Bc5c4,Bc4c3] } 19. Ne2 { Doesn't have the same effect as the move before. } { [%cal Bc5c4,Bc4c3] } 19... c4 { The c pawn storms up the board, breaking open the white king's defense. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Rc4b3,Bc4c3] } 20. Bc2 c3! { The position is hopeless now for Bobotsov, the power of the fianchettoed bishop and b8 rook is way too much for Bobotsov to deal with. } { [%csl Gb8,Gg7,Rb2,Rb1][%cal Rc3d2,Yb8b2,Yg7b2,Bc3b2] } 21. Qd3 (21. Nxc3 { Ends things faster } 21... Nc4 { gg } { [%csl Rc3,Rb2,Rd2][%cal Rc4b2,Bg7c3,Rc4d2,Yb8b2] }) 21... cxb2 { The king is trapped. Bobotsov currently uses the b pawn as an umbrella, Tal now only has to force the king away so that he can promote. } { [%csl Rb1,Gb2] } 22. Nd4 Bd7! { Tal clears the c8 square for his f8 rook to join the attack. } { [%cal Bf8c8] } 23. Rd1 Rfc8 { Th rook now controls the c file. Tal prepares Na4. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Ba4c3,Bb6a4,Yc8c3] } 24. Bb3 { Using the bishop as a blockade on the b file, but it doesn't do anything at this point. } 24... Na4! { Threatening the deadly Nc3+, it's now really over. Bobotsov can resign now, but he plays a couple more moves. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Ba4c3] } 25. Bxa4 Bxa4 { Threatening to take the rook, but if it moves there's Bxd4-Bc2#. } { [%csl Rd1,Rc2,Rd4][%cal Ba4d1,Ba4c2,Bg7d4] } 26. Nb3 { Acting as a blockade. } (26. Rd2 Rc1# { Simply mate in 1. } { [%csl Ra2,Gb2,Yb1][%cal Yc1a1,Bb8b2,Yc1c2] }) (26. Re1 Bxd4 27. Qxd4 Bc2# { [%csl Gb1,Ra2,Ya1,Yc1,Bb2,Bc2][%cal Gc2b1,Yb2c1,Yb2a1,Bc8c2,Bb8b2] }) 26... Rc3! { Tal kicks Bobotsov's queen away and now attacks the knight thrice. } { [%cal Rc3d3,Ra4b3] } 27. Qxa6 Bxb3 { Getting rid of White's main defender/blockade. } 28. axb3 Rbc8 { Tal stacks up his rooks. Rc1 is unavoidable without sacrificing the queen. } { [%csl Yc8,Yc3,Rc1][%cal Gc8c1] } 29. Qa3 Rc1+ 30. Rxc1 Rxc1+ { 0-1 Black wins. } { Here, just one move before checkmate, Bobotsov threw in the towel. It's a beautiful game that highlights the strength of the fianchettoed bishop and demonstrates how to launch a successful attack, even without a queen. I wished Bobotsov would've let Tal play the following underpromotion mate tho. } 31. Ka2 $7 b1=B#!! { A beautiful underpromotion checkmate! } { [%csl Ga2,Ya1,Yb2,Rb3,Ra3,Bb1][%cal Gb1a2,Yg7a1,Bc1b1] } 0-1


[Event "Match for USSR Master title"]
[Site "Riga"]
[Date "1954.??.??"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Vladimir Sergeevich Saigin"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A31"]
[Opening "English Opening: Symmetrical Variation, Anti-Benoni Variation"]
[StudyName "Mikhail Tal's BRILLIANT Games: Annotated + Analyzed!"]
[ChapterName "Vladimir Sergeevich Saigin - Mikhail Tal"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/HmKIJWjn"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]

{ Vladimir Sergeevich Saigin vs Mikhail Tal, Riga 1954 }
1. d4 { Saigin goes for 1. d4 } 1... Nf6 2. c4 c5! { The Benoni Defense! } 3. Nf3 { Saigin decides to sidestep the Benoni by transposing into a variation of the English opening, commonly referred to as the Anti-Benoni Variation. } 3... e6 { Tal opens up his bishop and more importantly, prepares to strike the center with d5. } { [%csl Gf8][%cal Be6d5,Bd7d5] } 4. g3 { The standard move in the English, White wants to fianchetto the LSB and castle kingside. } { [%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1] } 4... cxd4 { Simplifying the center. } 5. Nxd4 { Saigin recaptures with the knight. Qxd4?! would be met with Nc3, gaining tempo } (5. Qxd4?! Nc6 { Black develops while attacking White's queen, it now has to move away, wasting time. This could be avoided with Nxd4. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc6d4] }) 5... d5 { Tal controls the center. } 6. Bg2 { Saigin wants to finish kingside development, this isn't bad but it requires him to deal with Tal's next move, which is a bit annoying to face as White. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } (6. cxd5? { A common mistake. White doesn't benefit in any way whatsoever from this exchange. } 6... Qxd5 { Attacking the rook. } { [%csl Rh1,Gd5] } 7. Nf3 { This is kinda forced because White has to save the rook. Rb1 is a bit awkward, and f3 damages White's pawn structure. } 7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nc6 { White has lost castling rights and Black enjoys a lead in development. } { [%csl Rd1,Gc6,Gf6] }) 6... e5! { Tal gains space in the center and gains tempo by kicking the knight. } { [%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Re5d4] } 7. Nf3 { Saigin retreats his knight. } 7... d4! { Tal expands and now takes away the valuable c3 square from the knight. e5 isn't actually hanging, because of Qa5+ :D } { [%csl Gd4,Rc3,Re1,Re5][%cal Rd4c3,Bd8a5,Ba5e5,Ba5e1] } 8. O-O { Saigin sees Tal's trap and finishes kingside development. Now, e5 is hanging because Qa5 no longer works. } (8. Nxe5?? { A nice trap! } 8... Qa5+! { Black wins a free piece! } { [%csl Re1,Re5][%cal Ga5e5,Ga5e1] }) 8... Nc6! { Tal simply develops his knight and is now protecting his e5 pawn. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e5] } 9. e3 { Saigin wants to get rid of Tal's central pawns by trading them. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Re3d4] } 9... Be7 { Tal wants to bring his king out of the center. } { [%cal Be8g8] } 10. exd4 exd4 { Despite having an isolated pawn on d4, Mikhail Tal's position doesn't suffer much. In fact, this pawn, though seemingly weak, serves several strategic purposes. It restricts White's knight from occupying the c3 square and also functions as a potential passed pawn, offering dynamic possibilities in the mid to late game (as we will see later on the game). } { [%csl Gd4,Rc3][%cal Rd4c3] } 11. Nbd2 { Because c3 is unavailable, Saigan tries to develop his knight another way. } 11... Be6 { Tal holds off on castling for a move, using that time to tie Saigin's knight to the c4 pawn. } { [%csl Rc4,Rd2][%cal Ge6c4] } 12. Re1 { Saigan activates his rook. It's a lot more active here than on f1. } { [%csl Ge1][%cal Ye1e8] } 12... O-O { Tal brings his king out of the center. } 13. b3 { Saigan's d2 knight is really a pain. It can't move away because it has to protect the c4 pawn and it blocks the bishop. To solve most of his problems, he goes for b3; it protects the c4 pawn while freeing up the dark-squared bishop's diagonal potential with Bb2. } { [%csl Gd4,Yc4,Yb3,Ya2,Rd2][%cal Ya2b3,Yb3c4,Bc1b2] } 13... Qd7 { This allows Tal to potentially trade the LSB's with Bh3 and it frees up the d8 square for the a8 rook. } { [%csl Rh3,Gd8][%cal Bd7h3,Rh3f1,Ba8d8] } 14. Bb2 { Putting the bishop on the long diagonal and putting some pressure on d4. } { [%csl Gb2,Rd4] } 14... Rad8 { Tal activates his a8 rook by putting it on the central d file. } { [%csl Gd8,Ra8] } 15. a3 { Saigan prepares to expand on the queenside with b4, which could be very dangerous for Tal. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Bb3b4,Ra3b4] } 15... a5! { A prophylaxis move! Tal doesn't allow Saigan to get any play on the queenside. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ra5b4,Bb3b4] } (15... Kh8 { A random move, just to show what happens if Black allows b5. } 16. b4 $16 { Suddenly, White gets all the play here. Black will have to do a good job defending here. } { [%csl Gb4,Gc4,Ga3,Rc6][%cal Bb4b5,Ba1c1,Bd2b3,Bc4c5] }) 16. Ne5 { Saigin offers a trade of the knights. This allows him to activate the d2 knight with Ndf3. } { [%csl Rd2][%cal Bd2f3] } 16... Nxe5 17. Rxe5 b6! { It's interesting to note that Tal is positioning his pawns on dark squares on the queenside. This is because Saigin's kingside bishop is a light-squared-bishop, now it aims at empty squares. His queenside bishop is also not doing much because it's reach is mostly blocked. } { [%csl Gb6,Ga5,Rd4,Rf6,Rg7][%cal Rg2a8,Rg2h1,Bb2a1,Bb2h8] } 18. Nf3 { Putting some pressure on d4. } { [%csl Rd4] } 18... Bc5 { Tal defends his d4 pawn and also aims at f2, where it can do some action in the future. } { [%csl Gd4,Rf2][%cal Gc5d4] } 19. Qd2 { Preparing for the a1 rook to come into the game. } { [%csl Bf1,Be1,Bd1][%cal Ba1f1,Ba1e1,Ba1d1] } 19... Ng4! { Tal attacks the rook. He's also threatening to push the d4 pawn, thus opening the diagonal of the DSB. } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Rg4e5,Bd4d3,Yc5f2,Yg4f2] } 20. Ree1 d3 { Double attacking the pinned f2 pawn. } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Yc5f2,Yg4f2] } 21. Rf1 { The rook's now stuck babysitting the f-pawn. Tal's position is looking good, but Saigin can end Tal's attack with a simple h3, kicking the knight away. To prevent this, Tal plays a really nice move: } { [%csl Rf1,Rf2] } 21... Qd6! { Aiming at g3, h3 is no longer possible. } { [%csl Rg3] } 22. Qc3? { Mistake. Bc3 was best. } { Saigin tries to get some activity along the h8-a1 diagonal, but this is easily countered with: } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Gb2g7] } (22. Bc3! { Saigin's best chance, trying to get a b4 pawn push. } { [%csl Bb4][%cal Bb3b4,Rc3b4] } 22... Rfe8 23. b4 $15) (22. h3? Nxf2! 23. Rxf2 Bxh3! { Sacrificing another piece! } 24. Bxh3 Qxg3+ { [%csl Rg1,Rh3,Rf2][%cal Rg3h3,Rg3f2,Rg3g1] } 25. Bg2 Rfe8 { Black may be 2 pieces down, but Black's pressure is huge! The biggest threat is Re2. White won't come out of this alive without sacrificing a bunch of material back. } { [%csl Rd2,Re2,Rf2,Rg2,Gg3,Gc5,Ge8][%cal Be8e2,Re2g2,Re2d2] }) 22... f6! { Tal plays f6, putting an end on any dreams Saigan might have of getting a checkmate along the diagonal. } { [%csl Gf6,Gg7,Rc3,Rb2][%cal Gg7f6] } 23. Rad1 { Saigin adds pressure to the d3 pawn. But it is currently still defended, so Tal can ignore it for now. } { [%csl Gd3] } 23... Rfe8! { Tal prepares to put his e8 rook on e2, where it will be an absolute monster. There is no way for Saigin to prevent this idea, he can only prolong it. } { [%csl Ge8,Ge2,Rf2][%cal Be8e2] } 24. Rd2 { Controlling the e2 square. } { [%csl Re2][%cal Bd2e2] } (24. Rde1 { Doesn't work } 24... Bf7 { Opening up the e file. } { [%csl Ge8] } 25. Rxe8+ Rxe8 { Tal will still get his rook on e2. } { [%csl Be2][%cal Be8e2] }) 24... Bf5! { Tal opens the d file. All his pieces are now perfectly placed and ready for a breakthrough! } { [%csl Re2,Gf5,Gc5,Gg4,Rf2,Rf1,Rg1,Rg2][%cal Be8e2] } (24... Bf7! { Worked too! It bears the same idea in mind. } { [%csl Re2][%cal Be8e2] }) 25. Ng5!? { Taking the knight would blunder mate in 1 with Qxg2#. Saigin was probably hoping to get some counterplay with Bd4+. } { [%csl Gc3,Gb2,Rd5][%cal Bg2d5,Rd5g8,Bg5f7] } 25... Ne3!! { Tal unleashes a brilliant sacrifice, bringing his pieces to life and setting the stage for a powerful attack. } { [%csl Rg2,Rf1][%cal Re3f1,Re3g2] } (25... h6 { To illustrate White's threat. } 26. Bd5+ Kf8 { Kh8-Nf7+ is a royal-family fork. } 27. Nf7 { [%csl Gd6,Gd8][%cal Gf7d6,Gf7d8] } 27... Qe7 28. Nxd8 Rxd8 29. Qc1 $10 { The position is equal. }) 26. fxe3 { Everything loses, so there isn't much Saigin can do anymore. } (26. Ra1 { If the rook were to move away, Tal would get something like this: } 26... Nxg2 { Removing pieces around the king. } 27. Kxg2 Qc6+! 28. Nf3 (28. f3 Be3 { A fork. } { [%csl Rg2,Rh2,Rg3,Rf3,Rc3,Rb2,Ra1,Gd8,Ge8,Gf5][%cal Re3g5,Re3d2] }) (28. Kg1 h6 { White's position completely collapses. } { [%csl Rg5,Bh3,Rh1,Rg2,Rf1,Rf3,Rd2,Rc3,Rb2][%cal Bf5h3,Rc6h1,Be8e2] }) 28... Be4 { There's no way to save the knight. GG } { [%csl Rg2,Rf3][%cal Rc6g2] }) 26... Bxe3+ { A triple fork! } { [%cal Re3g1,Re3d2,Re3g5] } 27. Kh1 Bxd2! { Tal isn't interested to take the knight, because by taking the rook Tal gains tempo on the queen. } { [%csl Rc3,Bh2,Bg2][%cal Rd2c3,Be8e2,Be2h2] } 28. Qxd2 { In terms of material, Black has a rook and pawn against White's two minor pieces. However, the sacrifice wasn't aimed at creating a material imbalance; rather, it was to pave the way for the advance of the d-pawn! } 28... Re2! { Finally Tal gets to bring his rook on the 2nd rank! Tal kicks away the queen for his d pawn to continue advancing. } { [%csl Rd2,Gd3,Ge2,Rb2][%cal Bd3d2,Re2b2] } 29. Qc3 Rxg2!! { 0-1 Black wins. } { And Tal ends with a bang! Saigin resigned at this point because the advance of the d-pawn is unstoppable without sacrificing a considerable amount of material, leading to a completely lost endgame. Here are some potential variations to illustrate the point. } 30. Kxg2 d2! { Advancing further! } 31. Rd1 Bg4 { Kicking the rook. } { [%csl Rd1] } 32. Nf3 (32. Ne4 { Forking the d pawn and the queen. But Black has a simple response. } { [%csl Rd2,Rd6][%cal Re4d2,Re4d6] } 32... Qc6 { Pinning the knight, White's position is completely crushing. } { [%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Rc6e4,Re4g2] }) 32... Qd3 { Forcefully trading. } { [%csl Rf3,Rc3][%cal Rd3f3,Rd3c3] } 33. Qxd3 Rxd3 34. Nxd2 Bxd1 35. Bc1 Rc3 { Tal will always win a piece, and be up 5 points of material. } { [%csl Rg2,Rd2,Rb2,Rc2,Rc1][%cal Bc3c2,Rc2b2,Rc2g2,Rc2c1] } 0-1


