[Event "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack: 🟢 Rooks, Queen & Pin Trouble"]
[Date "2025.10.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack"]
[ChapterName "🟢 Rooks, Queen & Pin Trouble"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mROjE2f7/LDuYfHQ1"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "6k1/5ppp/p1q1p3/1pb5/1P6/2P2P1P/2RB2P1/5R1K b - - 0 34"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Here we have a queen + pawn vs. two rooks endgame. Black is slightly better here mainly because White's rooks don't have open files and currently aren't very active. The queen however can move diagonally, so has more potential to infiltrate into White's territory.

Black's bishop is attacked. }
34... Bxb4 { Making use of the pin taking a pawn. How do you respond? } { [%csl Rc2,Rb4][%cal Rc3b4,Gc6c2] } 35. cxb4! { Correct! Sacrificing the rook! the Do you you see the idea?
This was however not played in the game. White instead played Rc1, which is losing. } (35. Rfc1?? { The move played in the game! But now Black's much better because of the passed queenside pawns. Black will now just move his bishop to safety.
White actually had a winning move. Here we see another common mistake made all the time: Always believing your opponents. Instead White should have double checked if what Black calculated is correct. } { [%csl Ga6,Gb5][%cal Bb4c5] }) 35... Qxc2 { Black grabs the rook. What's the follow up? } 36. Rc1! { A skewer! Once the queen moves away, Rc8 is a backrank checkmate. Now we see that Bxb4 was a huge blunder!
Here, I'm reminded by an important rule I've read in a blog of @Mcie: "Calculate until the end.. and one move more!"
Black stopped calculating after seeing that cxb4 Qxc2 wins a rook, but missed this deadly follow up. } { [%csl Rc2,Rc8][%cal Gc1c8] } 36... Qxc1+ { Forced, otherwise Black gets mated. } 37. Bxc1 $18 { White has a winning endgame, although White will still have to show proper endgame technique.
White's bishop can go to d2, defending the b4, making sure Black's queenside pawns never advance. The king will then go after Black's kingside pawns.
Match link: https://lichess.org/wd5fqEWw } { [%cal Bc1d2,Bh1g1,Bg1f2,Bf2e3,Be3e4,Be4e5] } *


