[ChapterName "🔴 Drama Queen Trapped"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mROjE2f7/TweSJAc0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r3k2r/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/R2B4/2N5/1qPQ1PPP/4KB1R w Kkq - 1 14"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Here Black's queen has just gone into a dangerous rabbit hole. She's too far into White's territory, trapped.

But how does White manage to win the queen? ;) } { [%csl Rb2] }
14. Nd1!! { Brilliant! I talk about backward moves in one of my previous studies, Top Chess Mistakes: Part 3.
White's knight hits the queen, opens up the DSB hitting the queen, and blocks check on the 1st rank. If Ng5, then Black's queen would only be attacked once by the bishop, allowing Black to take it with the knight. } { [%csl Rb2,Gd4,Gd1][%cal Bd1b2,Yd4b2] } (14. Ra2? { Nope! Queen escapes to b4. } { [%csl Gb4] }) (14. Nb5? { Black can play Nxd4, and the queen ends up escaping. } 14... Nxd4) 14... Qb1 { The queen's only safe square. How does White follow up? Again a key move, take your time. } 15. Bb2!! { Locking the queen up in a cage! The most important idea from Nd1. White would love to play Ra1, but then the queen could escape to b4, which is supported by the knight. Now the queen is fully enclosed. Ra1 is inevitable. } { [%csl Gb2,Rc1,Ra1,Ra2,Gc2,Gd1][%cal Yd1b2] } (15. Ra1? { Nope! Allows the queen to escape to b4. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gb1b4,Yc6b4] } 15... Qb4) 15... O-O { There's nothing else. } 16. Ra1 $18 { An absolutely stunning example of a queen trap. White's pieces worked wonderfully together.
Note: White didn't have to play Ra1 here immediately, because the threat remains. White could also play a developing move like Bd3, Be2, h4. But Ra1 keeps it simple. ;)
Match link: https://lichess.org/tpWRcuAY#26 } { [%csl Rb1,Gb2,Ga1,Gd1,Gc2,Gd2,Gf1] } (16. h4! { Haha, nice. Totally possible because the Ra1 threat remains. }) (16. Bd3 { Haha, nice. Totally possible because the Ra1 threat remains. }) (16. f4 { Haha, nice. Totally possible because the Ra1 threat remains. }) (16. Be2 { Haha, nice. Totally possible because the Ra1 threat remains. }) *


