[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ A harder puzzle. What's the best way to gain a positional advantage? }
11. Bxe6!! { Correct! This was missed in the game. It was actually also playable a move before. Instead, Be3 was played here. } (11. Nxe6?? { Not much of a continuation after fxe6 Bxe6 and then Nc5. The king will be quite safe. There's something much better. } 11... fxe6 12. Bxe6 Nc5) (11. Be3? { Played in the game. It leads to an equal game after Black castles. White had a way to get the advantage. }) 11... fxe6 { Black could also castle here, or play a developing move like Nc5, in which White will simply retreat the bishop back to b3 and enjoy the free pawn. } 12. Nxe6 { Forking the queen and g-pawn! } { [%csl Rd8,Rg7][%cal Ge6d8,Ge6g7] } 12... Qc8 13. Nxg7+! { Grabbing the pawn with check! The king is forced to move, losing his castling rights. } 13... Kf7 { How do you save the knight? } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rf7g7] } 14. Nf5 $16 { Now everything becomes clear. White has sacrificed the bishop for three pawns. Material is equal, but White has gained a nice positional advantage. Black’s king is badly placed with no pawns surrounding him. Also, Black's pieces aren't very active, particularly the LSB, which aims at a brick wall and will most likely not be much in the game. It's +1.6.
Match link: https://lichess.org/wd5fqEWw#20 (Same as previous puzzle) } { [%csl Gf5,Yf3,Ye4,Rb7,Re7,Rf7,Rg6,Re6,Re8,Rf8,Rg7][%cal Bc1g5,Bf5h6,Ba2a4,Ba1d1] } (14. Bh6?! { Possible, but it's not best to tie the bishop down defending the knight. It's a waste of it's potential. }) *


