[FEN "4rrk1/ppp2pp1/3q3p/3Nb3/3nP3/2PB3P/PP3PP1/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Black's knight is attacked. But where should it retreat? Only one square is correct. } { [%cal Gd4c6,Yd4e6,Rc3d4] }
17... Nc6?? { Black retreated to the wrong square! Can you find the reason why it's bad? } (17... Ne6 18. f4 Nxf4 19. Nxf4 Bxf4 20. Rxf4) 18. f4! { Hitting the bishop. It only one square to move to. This is why Ne6 would have been the correct retreat, as it would help control the f4 square, preventing this.
In the game, White missed this and instead played Ne3, which is explained in the analysis variation. } { [%csl Re5,Rd4,Gf6][%cal Yf4e5] } (18. Ne3?? { Played in the game. White's still better here, but it's no longer a decisive advantage. The most simple response from Black is Rd8, adding control along the d-file, attacking White's LSB. After it is forced to move, e.g. Bc2, Qe6 refusing a queen trade (As Black is down in material) and the rook has gained control of the d-file. }) (18. Nf6+?? { WHY! }) 18... Bf6 { The most crucial moment. What was the point of f4? } 19. e5! { Forking the Queen and bishop, but this also leaves the knight hanging. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Ge5f6,Ge5d6] } (19. Nxf6+? { Playable, but not decisively winning. White's still better however after Qxf6 and e5, gaining space in the center. } 19... Qxf6 20. e5 Qe6) 19... Qxd5 (19... Bxe5 20. fxe5 Nxe5 21. Bc2 { Simply opening up the queen, defending d5. White's much better with the extra material and active piece placement. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc2][%cal Yf1f8,Yd1d5] }) 20. Bh7+! { A discovered attack! If the queen doesn't take d5, White can simply grab on of the forked pieces. A nice instructive example of combining two tactics. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rh7g8,Gd1d5] } (20. exf6?? { No! After g6, White's only up a pawn. There was a way to get a decisive advantage. }) 20... Kxh7 21. Qxd5 $18 { Black can resign.
Match link: https://lichess.org/CGYVQOxK/black#27 } { [%csl Gd5,Rf6] } *


