{ In the following position White's a bit better due to easier development and space on the kingside. After White castles queenside, Black's a bit stuck because O-O isn't very attractive due to White's kingside pawn storm. }
10. g5 { Before castling, White decides to gain extra space on the kingside and kick away the knight. This is a good move. What do you do? ;) } 10... Ne5! { Instead of passively retreating to g8, Black counterattacks! Now also d7 is freed for the knight to retreat to. This was found in the game.
White must be careful here where to retreat the queen. } (10... Ng8?! { So passive! }) 11. Qg3?? { Oh oh, the wrong square! Can you find the only winning move? } 11... Qxd2+!! { SAC THE QUEEN! But do you know why?
The last position was reached 22 times in the database, but only 4 people found this! Sadly, in the game, Black played Nd7, which is very natural, but lets White keep the advantage.
If the queen would have moved somewhere else, Nd7 was the correct move. } 12. Kxd2 $7 Nxe4+! { A brilliant fork! Making use of the pin on the c3 knight. } { [%csl Rg3,Yd2,Rc3][%cal Yb4d2,Rc2d2,Ge4d2,Ge4g3] } 13. Ke3 Nxg3 14. fxg3 $19 { It's -2.8. Black's up a pawn, has a superior structure, and the DSB is much better than White's LSB. Black has also eliminated any kind of potential attack from White.
Full game: https://lichess.org/sC2hUaEx } { [%csl Rg5,Rg3][%cal Bh7h6] } *


