[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In the following position, White's up a clean piece, with a fully winning position. But now, after 7 seconds, White plays a huge blunder: } { [%csl Rb7,Rb6,Rg7] }
32. Rxb7?? { White takes the "free" pawn, but this allows Black to get counterplay. Can you find a way to draw? } (32. Raf1 { Trying to exchange a rook by R1f2 or Rf8+. } { [%cal Bf1f2,Bf7f8] }) 32... Rdd2! { The only move! Placing both rooks on the 2nd rank. White's king is trapped on the first rank, and Black's rooks can perpetually check him.
White should have played a move like Raf1or Rf2, wanting to simplify, by trading material. } 33. Rf7 { There's nothing White can do to stop it. This is his last attempt. Multiple moves draw, but let's keep things simple. Play a forcing move. } (33. Re1 { Played in the game. Black just gets perpetual check. } 33... Rg2+ 34. Kh1 Rxh2+ 35. Kg1 Rhg2+ 36. Kh1 Rh2+) 33... Rg2+! 34. Kf1 { Now Rf2+ doesn't work because of White's f7 rook. There's only one move here. } 34... Rxh2! { Threatening checkmate! White's king is forced to leave f1. } { [%csl Bh1][%cal Bh2h1] } 35. Kg1 { Again, there are multiple good moves here, but let's play the most simple. } { [%csl Rg2][%cal Gh2g2] } 35... Rhg2+ { Just keep checking. } 36. Kf1 { Same thing as before. } 36... Rh2! { Threatening mate again. } { [%csl Rh1][%cal Rh2h1] } 37. Ke1 { This time White tries something different. There are many good moves here, but Rh1+ loses! Now, White can block the check with Rf1, also offering a trade. After Rh2, White can play Nd4 controlling the e2 square, preventing checks.
Play Re2+ } { [%csl Ye2][%cal Bh2e2] } 37... Rhe2+ (37... Rh1+?? { Did you read the comments? } 38. Rf1 Rhh2 39. Nd4) 38. Kf1 Rh2 $10 { And again renewing the threat. It's draw. Here we can learn that even in a seemingly winning position, always be on the lookout if your opponent can create counterplay!
Match link: https://lichess.org/bnbm7fuS } *


