{ Let's test your endgame skills. I really love this position, it's like an art piece.

Here we have an endgame where both players have equal material, however White has a passed d-pawn just 1 square away from promotion. Black must remain careful. }
48. Ke7 { The most critical moment. There's only one move that draws. } 48... Kg7! { The only move! White's threat was Rg8+, followed by promoting the pawn. Now the king controls the g8 square. Also, White's king is now trapped on the e-file. Kh7 wouldn't have worked, check later in the analysis to see why.
In the game, Black played h5??, but White blundered too and it ended up being a draw. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf6,Rf8,Rg8] } (48... h5?? { Played in the game. } 49. Rg8+ { If you're playing in black's perspective, white shouldn't make blunders out of puzzle. } 49... Kh7 50. d8=R) (48... Kh7?? { Allows Rf5, rerouting to f7 or f6. After, Re3/2+, the White king can still move to f8, getting out of any checks. Black's in trouble. } { [%csl Bf7,Bf6,Yf8][%cal Be5f5,Bf5f7,Ye7f8] } 49. Rf5 Re2+) 49. Ke8 { White's main threat here now is Re7+, defending the d-pawn, preparing to move the d8 rook away, allowing the pawn to promote. There are multiple moves that draw here, but let's play the most nicest, forcing move, that addresses this issue. Rf2 or Rf3 are equally good, but play Rf3 because lichess only allows one correct move. } { [%csl Gf2,Re7][%cal Gd2f2,Re5e7,Bd8c8,Gd7d8] } (49. Rf5) 49... Rf2! { White can only move his pieces along the e-file! If the e5 rook moves away from the e-file, it's mate in 2: Re3+ Re5 forced, and Rxe5#. If Ke7, Black perpetually checks him by moving the rook along the 6th-8th rank. If the d8 rook moves, the d7 pawn lacks a defender. Black wins it via Rf8+ Re7 Rf7+. There's simply no way to make progress. } (49... Rf3) (49... Rd6 50. Re7+ Kg8 51. Rc8) (49... Kg8 50. Re7) (49... Rd1?? 50. Re7+ Kg8 51. Rc8) 50. Re7+ { White attempts his idea. There's only one correct move. } { [%cal Bd8c8] } 50... Kg8! { Threatening Rf8#! White must create an escape square for his king, that's again only possible by moving along the e-file. } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Bf2f8] } (50... Kh8?? { Allows White's idea we've discussed before. } { [%csl Yd8][%cal Bd8b8,Yd7d8] }) 51. Re4 Kg7! { And each rook is tied down to their file. It's a draw.
Match link: https://lichess.org/YWTMoBfh } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Yf2f1,Yf2f8,Be4e1,Be4e8,Gd3d1,Gd3d6] } (51... Rf7 { Also possible, but let's repeat. }) *


