{ Black has just played fxg3. Now White must decide with which pawn to take. the f or h pawn? Which is correct?

Black is up a bishop, but the position is 100% equal because White has a very active knight, and Black's king is quite exposed.

This might be seen as a bonus puzzle. Try to see why taking with the wrong pawn doesn't work. :) } { [%csl Gd5,Gb2][%cal Bd5f4] }
23. fxg3?? { Played in the game, but the wrong recapture! White most likely played this in order to open the f-file for the rook, this however creates a huge weakness for the king. The g1-a7 diagonal has been opened. Can you find a way to punish white? } { [%csl Gf1,Rf2,Rg1] } 23... Bc5+! { The purpose for this move will be seen later. } { [%csl Rg1][%cal Rc5g1] } 24. Kh1 Be6! { Opening up the queen, double attacking the knight. } { [%csl Rd5,Yd4][%cal Gd8d5,Ge6d5] } 25. Nf4 { If Nf6+. Black sacrifices the exchange Rxf6 exf6 and then follows up with Bd5, a skewer. Or Bd5+/Qd5+ work equally well. } { [%cal Rf4e6] } 25... Bd4! { A skewer! But our LSB is also attacked. Did you calculate the following sequence? } { [%csl Ra1,Rb2,Re6][%cal Gd4a1] } (25... Bd5+ { Also possible, but more complicated. }) 26. Nxe6 Bxb2 (26... Qd5+ 27. e4!! Qxe4+ 28. Qg2) 27. Nxd8 Bxa1 28. Ne6 Bxe5 { Saving the bishop. } 29. Nxf8 Rxf8 30. bxa6 bxa6 { After all those captures Black is left with a winning endgame. The key was to force trades, simplifying. Match link: https://lichess.org/JI0bzLfB } *


