{ Here we have a variation from the game from the previous puzzle. This time for White. Both queens are attack. Black tries the following move to win more material. But remember, if Black calculated correctly, he would see he's already winning. This a greedy attempt to win more. } { [%csl Rd8,Rb2][%cal Gd4b2,Ge6d8] }
26... Qd5+?? { Giving a check and "saving" the queen. Thinking that after Black does something about the check, Black's free to grab the White queen. But White has another idea. } { [%csl Rh1] } (26... Bxb2) 27. e4! { Sacrificing the pawn to block the check, hitting the queen, bringing the queen away from White's knight, and allowing the White queen to move to g2. } { [%csl Gg2][%cal Re4d5,Bb2g2] } 27... Qxe4+ { If fxe4 White can simply win the bishop with Nxd4. See the Bxb2 variation in the analysis board later. } (27... Bxb2 28. exd5 Bxa1 29. Rxa1 axb5 30. Nxf8 Kxf8 31. a5 $16 { [%csl Gd5,Ge5,Rb7,Rb5,Rf5,Rh6][%cal Bh1g2,Bg2f3,Bf3f4] }) (27... fxe4 28. Nxd4) 28. Qg2 { Of course! Remember the f rook is still attacked. } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Re6f8] } 28... Bxa1 { We get some trades. } 29. Nxf8 (29. Qxe4 { Also possible. } 29... fxe4 30. Nxf8) 29... Rxf8 30. Qxe4 fxe4 31. Rxa1 axb5 32. axb5 { It's a fully equal rook endgame. Match link: same as previous chapter. } *


