[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Let's practice your checkmating skills! }
23. Rb1?? { Here White played a critical blunder. Black has a winning idea. } 23... Rd1! { In the game Qe5 was played, and it ended up being a draw.
Infiltrating the first rank! The only way to stop an immediate checkmate is by sacrificing the queen. Let's see what happens if White plays something random. } { [%csl Rh1,Rg1][%cal Re1h1] } (23... Qe5??) 24. b3 Qh1+! { Forcing the king further forward. We want to bring the king into a mating net. } (24... Qg1+ { Also possible but not quickest. Take the f3 square away to make things easier. }) 25. Kg3 Rg1+ { Bringing another piece in. The king is forced to f4. } { [%csl Rg3,Rh2,Rg2] } 26. Kf4 $7 Bg5+! { The quickest way! Bringing the king into the net. } 27. Kxg5 Qf3 { Not letting the king run to f4, threatening Qf6#. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Bf3f6] } (27... Qxh3 { Also works, but let's take away f4. It's a more simpler way. } 28. Kf4 Qxg4+ 29. Ke3 Re1+ 30. Kd3) 28. Kh4 { The king tries to escape. } 28... Rh1! { Attacking h3 with the rook. White cannot stop the capture. The king has no where to escape.
Qf6+ loses! White has Bg5, a double attack! } { [%csl Rh3,Rh4][%cal Bf3h3] } (28... Qf6+?? { Loses! White has Bg5 a double attack! }) 29. Qd2 Rxh3+ (29... Qxh3+ { Also perfectly fine. } 30. Kg5 Qh6#) 30. Kg5 $7 Qf6# { Checkmate! That king had a long journey! A nice example of a mating attack. Lots of players always only give checks, but this doesn't work always. You must also look for moves that trap your opponent's king, and make sure his other pieces don't have the opportunity for counterplay.
Match link: https://lichess.org/0jfyzeBJ } { [%csl Rh4,Rg5][%cal Rf6h4,Bg1g2,Bg2g3,Bg3f4,Bf4g5,Bg5h4,Bh4g5] } *


