Full game: https://lichess.org/gREJ2Imu } { [%csl Rg7,Rd7][%cal Ba3d6,Bf1e1,Ba1b1] } (18. Qd2! { Also good! } 18... Nd5 19. c4 { [%csl Rb4,Rf4] }) *


[Event "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack: 🟢 Check ≠ Good"]
[Date "2025.10.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack"]
[ChapterName "🟢 Check ≠ Good"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mROjE2f7/4xTD4dHX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/5q2/6PK/5k1P/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 76"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This is a winning endgame for Black. But White's pawns are almost at their promotion squares. Black must be careful.

PS: In the game Black had under 1 second left, so anyone would have blundered here. But this puzzle serves as an example that giving check is not always good, which is something a lot of new players keep doing. }
76... Qf8+?? { This blundered into a draw. But only if White plays the correct sequence of moves. } { [%csl Rh6] } 77. g7! { Pushing further! } { [%cal Rg7f8] } 77... Qf6+ { Qg1, blocking the pawn, is stalemate.
This is a really hard moment. Think carefully. } 78. Kh7 $7 { The only legal move ;) } { [%cal Rg7g8] } 78... Qe7 79. Kh8! $10 { The real hardest move of the puzzle. Even with only 5 pieces on the board, you must be very very careful. One endgame mistake will cost you the entire game. This is now a draw. White must shuffle along h7-h8, and Black must continue stopping the pawn from promotion. If Black plays a move to prevent Kh7, White can promote and force a draw by insufficient material.
Match link: https://lichess.org/XJUEWCPt } (79. h6?? { Allows Kg5! hitting the h6 pawn. If then Kh8, there's Qf6 pinning the g pawn stopping promotion and attacking the h7 pawn. Black wins. } 79... Kg5 80. Kh8 Qf6 81. Kh7) *


