[Date "2025.10.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack"]
[ChapterName "🟢 Look at Your Opponent's Responses!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mROjE2f7/tgeMipww"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2r2k2/1q1r1bp1/5p2/pP1ppN1p/P7/2P2P1P/1Q4P1/1RR2K2 b - - 3 31"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ After Bg6, Black is better because of the better piece, pawn structure, and rooks. But Black rushed taking the advantage and played: }
31... Rc4?? { Hitting the a4 pawn, but loses due to White's following sequence. } { [%csl Ra4] } (31... Bg6 32. Qa3+ Kg8 33. Nd6 Bd3+ 34. Kg1 Qb6+ 35. Kh2 Rxd6) 32. Qa3+! { Found in the game! A nice preparation move. Controlling d6 with tempo.
Here's a nice example of always looking at how your opponent might respond to your move. Qa3, is fairly intuitive, defending the a4 pawn, but Black didn't see it came with this tactic. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Bf5d6] } 32... Kg8 { Ke8 is much much worse after 33. Nxg7+ Kd8 34. Qf8+ Kc7 35. b6+ Kc6 36. Nf5 is crushing. } (32... Ke8 33. Nxg7+ Kd8 34. Qf8+ Kc7 35. b6+ Kc6 36. Nf5) 33. Nd6 $16 { Fork! White wins an exchange. It's +1.3.
Match link: https://lichess.org/XJUEWCPt#61 } { [%csl Rc4,Rb7][%cal Bd6b7,Bd6c4] } *


[Event "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack: 🔴 Possible to Save?"]
[Date "2025.10.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack"]
[ChapterName "🔴 Possible to Save?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mROjE2f7/LNO2fn6D"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2np4/4n3/2BPQPb1/8/PP4PP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ One of my favorite puzzles from this collection.

A very scary looking position for Black. The knight is pinned and attacked twice by pawns. It looks hopeless. But...

can you save the game? } { [%csl Re8,Ge4][%cal Rf4e5,Rd4e5] }
11... Qh4+! { Correct! Only works if you can find the follow-up too. :)
In the game Black castled, leading to White winning the game. } { [%csl Re1] } 12. g3 { Mmh, it looks like Qh4+ didn't do anything. Now 2 pieces are under attack. But Black has only one move that works. } { [%cal Rg3h4,Rd4e5] } (12. Kf1 { Actually a very complicated line, but Black ends up better. } 12... O-O-O! { [%cal Rd6d5] } 13. fxe5 d5 14. Bxd5 Rxd5 { Sac the rook! With huge compensation. } 15. Qxd5 Bf5 { Bd6 mate in 2 threat. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rf5d3] } 16. Qf3 (16. g3 Qh5 { [%csl Rd1][%cal Rh5d1,Rd1c1] } 17. Kf2 Nb4 $17 { [%csl Rc2,Rd5][%cal Rb4c2,Rb4d5] }) 16... Nxd4 17. Qg3 Qxg3 18. hxg3 Nc2) 12... Bf3! { Counter attacking! If White captures the queen, Black will do so to, and the rook ends up still attacked. Black wins material. } { [%csl Re4,Rh1][%cal Rf3h1,Rf3e4] } 13. Qe3 { White moves away. The queen and knight are still attacked. What to do? } { [%cal Rd4e5,Rg3h4] } (13. gxh4 Bxe4 14. dxe5 Bxh1 15. exd6 cxd6) 13... Qe7! { The only move! Saving the queen, breaking the pin, and the rook remains attacked by the bishop. Also, by breaking the pin on the knight, c4 is now under attack. } { [%csl Rc4,Rh1][%cal Re5c4,Rf3h1] } 14. O-O { Black saves his most valuable piece and remains attacking Black's bishop. If Black takes the bishop, White does so too! A beautiful example of back and forth counter threats! :) } { [%csl Rf3] } 14... Nxc4 { Yup taking is fine. The knight is saved. } { [%csl Re3][%cal Rc4e3] } 15. Qxf3 { White captures too. Now for the hardest move of the entire puzzle. } 15... d5!! { Brilliant! The reason for this is because of White's 2 main threats. Qc3 and d5. If Nxd4?? White would play Qc3, hitting the knight and controlling the e1 square for the dangerous Re1 skewer.
If Black plays something like castling, White has d5, pushing the c6 knight away. Then after it moves away, Nc3 and White's pieces are quite solid. Black's only slightly better.
With d5 we prevent d5, and keep the d pawn on d4, where it remains a long term target. } { [%csl Rd4] } (15... Nxd4? { Allows Qd3 fork. } 16. Qd3) (15... O-O-O { Allows d5. } 16. d5 Nb8 17. Nc3) 16. Qxd5 Nb6 $17 { Remember the starting position? Look now, all threats are dealt with! Black has a very nice position. The d4 pawn will be won soon, it's just too weak. White's bishop is quite stuck, and the king has vulnerable diagonals around him. It's -1.6.
Match link: https://lichess.org/vMJcNAFB } { [%csl Bc8,Rd4,Rg1,Rc1][%cal Be8c8] } *


[Event "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack: 🟡 The Final Push"]
[Date "2025.10.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Everyday Games Puzzle Pack"]
[ChapterName "🟡 The Final Push"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mROjE2f7/yIU3EXXN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/5pp1/p1p4p/1p2pN2/1PP1Pq2/P7/2Q2P1P/4K2R b K - 4 25"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.04"]
[UTCTime "11:19:41"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Here Black has a winning position, being up an exchange and White has a weak king. There are multiple winning moves here. But which one ends things immediately? }
25... Rd2! { Found in the game. Sacrificing the rook! Throwing it right in White's face! It's a deflection. If the queen takes, e4 is left hanging. If White doesn't take, Black either checkmates on f2 or wins the queen. } { [%csl Rf2,Ge4][%cal Rf4f2,Yd2c2,Yd2f2,Gf4e4] } (25... g6! { Also works, but it's not yet a clear GG yet is it? }) 26. Qxd2 Qxe4+ { [%csl Rh1,Re1][%cal Re4h1,Re4e1] } 27. Qe3 (27. Kd1 Qxh1+ 28. Kc2 Qe4+ 29. Qd3) 27... Qxh1+ 28. Ke2 { Now we've reached this far, might as well finish the game in checkmate. } 28... Rd8! { Cutting off the king. } { [%csl Rd1,Rd2,Rd3][%cal Rd8d1] } 29. Qg3 { Now checkmate! } (29. Qc3 Qe4+ (29... Qd1+ 30. Ke3) 30. Ne3) 29... Qd1+ 30. Ke3 Qd3# { Full match: https://lichess.org/Ntf6BDkU/black#0 } *


