[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📌 Section 1: Tactical Sacrifices"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📌 Section 1: Tactical Sacrifices"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/TNuUfsBK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Before we start, it's important to know the two different types of sacrifices in chess: "real" sacrifices and "sham" sacrifices. Let's start with "sham" sacrifices, also known as pseudo sacrifices. These are tactical sacrifices where you temporarily give up material but get it back after a few moves, ending up with a better position, a material advantage, or even a checkmate, so it's not really a sacrifice. These sacrifices can usually be fully calculated until the end, so you already know what you will get in return.

In this section, we'll explore different patterns of tactical sacrifices.

By familiarizing yourself with these patterns, you will learn to think more tactically and recognize these opportunities when they arise in your games.

Click the space-bar! 🚀 }
 *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Deflection Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Levon Aronian"]
[Black "Peter Svidler"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Deflection Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/vJkT2nqT"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1p3pbp/6p1/p5B1/P1qP4/3Q4/5PPP/R2R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Let's start off with the deflection sacrifice, it's a tactic that forces your opponent's piece away from defending another piece or a crucial square. Typically, the deflected piece is overloaded, meaning it's responsible for protecting multiple pieces or squares. By sacrificing one of your own pieces, you can pull the opponent's piece away from its defensive duties. It is important to note tho, that sometimes you can also use the deflection without sacrificing, but we'll get to that later on. This is a position from the game between Levon Aronian and Peter Svidler that perfectly illustrates this tactic. Aronian has just played 24. exd4??, opening up the e-file for Svidler's e1 rook. Black now wins immediately with: }
1... Re1+! { The deflection! Aronian resigned here because of the fact that he is forced to capture the rook (because his king is in check), thus leaving his queen undefended. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rc4d3,Re1g1] } (1... Qxd3?? { Completely throwing away the win. } 2. Rxd3 $16 { Black is only slightly better here because of White's isolated d-pawn which can be a target, but the game can still go both ways. Re1+ would have been an immediate win. }) 2. Rxe1 (2. Qf1 { Simply mate in 1. } 2... Qxf1# { [%csl Gh1,Gg1][%cal Gf1h1] }) 2... Qxd3 $19 { Black enjoys a nice material advantage and will have no trouble winning this game. } { [%csl Gd3] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Deflection Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Deflection Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/94uYDPz7"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/6N1/8/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 6"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have another example of the deflection sacrifice. (1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. Ng5 exd3 5. Bxd3 Nf6 were the previously played moves) Notice how Black's queen is only protected by her king. If there was a way to deflect the king from protecting her and open the d-file, we could play Qxd8, winning the queen. } { [%csl Gd1,Gd8,Rd3][%cal Re8d8] }
6. Nxf7!! { The winning move! White wants to get Black's king away from his queen! If Black were to not take the knight, White simply takes one of the forked pieces and enjoys a nice material advantage. } { [%csl Rd8,Rh8][%cal Rf7d8,Rf7h8] } 6... Kxf7 7. Bg6+!! { Now comes the final blow. White sacrifices the bishop to open the d-file, and also the black king is in check, so he has no time to do something about his undefended queen. } { [%csl Rd8,Re8,Rf7][%cal Bd1d8,Rg6e8] } (7. Bc4+?? { Doesn't work because Black can solve all his problems with Nd5, closing the d-file and blocking the check. } 7... Nd5 $19 { Black enjoys being up a full knight. }) 7... Kxg6 { 7...hxg6 is the same thing, Black's queen remains undefended. } 8. Qxd8 $18 { White enjoys a nice material advantage. Plus, Black's king is in a bad spot, which means it's vulnerable to getting attacked. Sometimes, to win, it's not enough to just use one tactic. Instead, you might need to plan ahead and use a series of tactical sacrifices (in this case, the deflection). } { [%csl Gd8] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Deflection Sacrifice | Example #3"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Deflection Sacrifice | Example #3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/XfnJWIaE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/8/4N1P1/3n4/8/K1p4k/8/8 w - - 0 67"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have another interesting example. Both sides have an equal amount of material, and both pawns are two squares away from promotion. We would love to just push our g-pawn and get a queen, but Black can always respond with either Nf6 or Ne7, preventing our pawn from reaching its promotion square and leading to a draw. However, there is only one move that leads to a win for White. Try to see if you can find it first! } { [%cal Gg6g7,Gg7g8,Rc3c2,Rc2c1,Bd5f6] }
67. Nf4+!! { The deflection! A knight forks a knight?! White forces the knight away so that we can continue to push our g-pawn and reach its promotion square without being disturbed! If Black doesn't accept the sacrifice, we simply grab the knight on d5! } { [%cal Rf4d5,Rf4h3] } (67. g7?? Nf6 { Black's knight will always stop the pawn from promoting. At some point the king comes closer and grabs it. And of course a K+N vs K+N endgame is a draw. } { [%cal Rf6g8,Bh3h4,Bh4h5,Bh5g6,Bg6h7,Bh7g7] }) 67... Nxf4 { [%csl Rf4][%cal Bg6g7,Bg7g8] } 68. g7! { The knight can no longer stop it! } { [%csl Rg8][%cal Bg7g8] } 68... c2 { No problem! Our king is near enough to stop it. } 69. Kb2 $18 { Now the g-pawn will promote on the next move to a queen. So, always look for these opportunities to promote pawns, they can completely turn the table of the game! } { [%cal Gg7g8,Rb2c1] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📕 Greek Gift Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📕 Greek Gift Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/1PZzsNpw"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/1bn1p3/3pP3/3P4/2PB1N2/P4PPP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 9"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Let's move on to one of the most famous tactical sacrifices in chess, the Greek Sacrifice (also known as the classical bishop sacrifice). It happens when one side sacrifices their bishop by capturing the pawn in front of the opponent's castled king (either with Bxh7+ for White or Bxh2+ for Black). Usually, this sacrifice aims to either checkmate the opponent's king or to win a lot of material. It's a must-know tactical sacrifice that can change the course of the game dramatically! In this position the Greek Gift sacrifice is an immediate win. } { [%csl Gg8,Rh7] }
9. Bxh7+! { We're sacrificing the bishop to draw out the black king into a the open where we can attack it. The h-file is now opened, so it gives us a clear path to launch our offense. It is important to note that if Black were to be able to play a move like Bf4, Nf6, Nf8,... which all cover the h7 square OR the king can run to safety after taking the bishop, the Greek Gift wouldn't work. So it's very important to calculate the lines here before going for it. } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Bf3g5,Yd1h5] } 9... Kxh7 (9... Kh8 { Also seen frequently, players decline the sacrifice because it will likely be dangerous. } 10. Ng5! { If you feel like Black is able to defend form your attack, you can simply bring the bishop back to d3/c2, and enjoy Black's weakness of an open h-file. In this case, we have a more straightforward win. Ng4 protects the bishop and prepares for a deadly Qh4. } { [%cal Rd1h5] } 10... g6 { Black takes away the h5 square from us. No problem! You just have to find a way to continue the attack. } { [%cal Rg6h5,Gh2h4] } 11. Qf3! { The best move! Threatening Qf6# and Qh4 aligning with the king. I have to note tho, that often this move isn't possible (example if there were no knight on e7, this wouldn't have the same effect, in those cases h4 is a good alternative, simply trying to get the rook active by breaking open Black's defense via h5-take-take... mate. } { [%cal Bf3h3,Bf3f6] } 11... Nf5 { Blocking off the f6 square. } { [%csl Rf6] } 12. Bxg6! { A nice finish! Opening the h file. This is an example of the square clearance sacrifice, we'll get to that later on. } { [%cal Rf3h3] } 12... fxg6 13. Qh3+ Kg7 14. Qh7# { Checkmate! }) 10. Ng5+! { The next important move in the Greek Gift sacrifice. We give a check and clear the way for the queen to go to h5, joining the attack. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Bd1h5,Gg5h7] } 10... Kg6 { Now, in these type of positions you almost always play h4, with the threat of h5+ which is most times unstoppable. } { [%csl Rh5][%cal Bh2h4,Bh4h5] } (10... Kg8 { It might seem like this is the best option, because the king goes back to hide behind his pawns, but this actually leads to forced checkmate. } 11. Qh5! { Threatening mate in 1 on h7. Now if Black were to play a move that protects the h7 checkmate threat, which I mentioned earlier, our sacrifice would have been for nothing because our attack would stop here and White would be down a bishop. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rh5h7] } 11... Re8 { The rook moves so that it creates an escape square for the king. } { [%cal Bg8f8] } 12. Qh7+ Kf8 $7 { Now White would love to play Qh8#, but it doesn't work yet because Black can block with the e7 knight. So, we still have to play another important move. } { [%cal Bh7h8,Re7g8] } 13. Ba3! { Pinning the knight! Qh8# is now inevitable. } { [%csl Rh8,Rf8,Re7][%cal Rh7h8,Ra3f8] }) (10... Kh6 { If you're not sure this leads to checkmate, you can go ahead and play Nxe6+, winning the queen. But in this case there's a quicker way to end this. } 11. Qg4! { Simply going to h4. } { [%cal Bg4h4] } 11... g6 { It doesn't matter what Black plays, it's forced checkmate. } 12. Qh4+ Kg7 13. Qh7# { [%csl Rg7,Rg6,Rf7,Rf8][%cal Gh7g7,Yg5h7,Gh7g8,Gh7h8,Be5f6] }) 11. h4! { As you can see the king is kinda trapped. It can't go back to h7 and going to h6 leads to Nxe6, a discovered check (the DSB gives a check), winning the queen. Moving forward is also not a good idea because it's mate in 2 after 12. Qd3+ Kg4 (only move) 13. Qg6#. So now our goal is to force the king away to a bad square. We can successfully do this with h5+, which is unstoppable for Black. } { [%csl Rh5,Rh7][%cal Bh4h5] } 11... f5 { You'll probably see this move the most, but any move loses. } 12. h5+! { Simply pushing the king to another square. } 12... Kh6 $7 13. Nxe6+ { Discovered check! White wins the queen and will have no trouble winning the game. } { [%cal Rc1h6,Re6d8] } *


