[ChapterName "📕 Greek Gift Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/skvdkHeF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/2qp4/8/2PBP3/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have another example of the Greek Gift sacrifice. This position is from a game played between two strong grandmasters; Gata Kamsky and Samuel Shankland. Black has just played Qxc5, which is a blunder because of Kamsky's next move. }
13. Bxh7+!! { The only winning move! At first glance, it might seem like White has no effective follow-up. However, as you'll see, White does have a strong follow-up, although it requires executing the moves in a more unique order this time. } 13... Kxh7 (13... Kh8 14. Qh5 $18 { it's pretty obvious here Black's going to lose. } { [%csl Rh8][%cal Rh5h8,Bh7g6] }) 14. Qh5+! { Well, since White doesn't have any piece blocking the queen from moving to h5, there's no reason to delay! } 14... Kg8 $7 15. Ne4!! { The key move to make the bishop sacrifice work. White makes use of the pinned d-pawn in order to reroute his knight. Black has to move his queen because it's attacked by the knight, giving White the time to bring the knight over to g5, the usual follow-up of the Greek Gift. A queen alone can't get the job done! } { [%cal Yh5c5,Rd5e4,Be4g5] } 15... Qc4 16. Ng5! { Reroute complete! The knight now joins the party. Currently, Kamsky's threatening mate in 1 with Qh7#. } { [%csl Rh7,Gh5,Gg5] } 16... Rfd8 { Since Black has no piece to cover the h7 square, he's forced to create an escape square for the king to run to after Qh7+. The big downside here for why Black's not gonna be okay is that he is now forced to leave the f7 pawn unprotected. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Bg8f8,Bf8e7] } 17. Qxf7+ { Grabbing the free pawn and thus weakening the Black king more. White is in total control here. } 17... Kh8 18. Qh5+ { The queen's job on f7 is done, so she can come back to h5 where she will be more active. } (18. Rd1?? { This move order fails miserably. } 18... Qh4! { Black's queen now joins to defend and hopes to get a queen trade, so White's attack is more or less gone. } { [%csl Gh4,Rg5] }) 18... Kg8 19. Rd1! { Of course Kamsky doesn't go for a perpetual check draw, he knows this is a winning position! All Black's pieces are on the other side of the board chilling, meanwhile White can just slowly but surely launch an attack on the kingside with example f4/g4 and slowly try to get a rook to join the attack. It's only a matter of time then, before Black's position crumbles. This game beautifully illustrates how sometimes the move pattern is a bit different and you'll have to find a creative way to make it work. PS: If you want to see the full game: https://lichess.org/Ea9BSBkh } { [%csl Ra8,Rd8,Rd7,Rc6,Rc4][%cal Bf2f4,Bg2g4,Bh2h4] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📘 Clearance Sacrifice | Example #1"]
