[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2br1rk1/1p2bpp1/p1p2n1p/q3Np2/PnBPP3/2N3B1/1P2Q1PP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here's another example of a clearance sacrifice. This one doesn't lead to an immediate checkmate, but White gains a decisive amount of material. Notice how Black's queen has very few squares to move to. If White can find a way to hit it, the queen will be trapped. } { [%csl Ra5] }
1. Bxf7+!! { The only winning move! White removes the light-squared-bishop to vacate the c4 square for the knight. Because Black's king is in check, he has no time to do anything about White's Nc4 threat. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Be5c4] } 1... Rxf7 2. Nc4 $18 { It's game over! The queen has no squares to go and will be captured on the next move. Because of White's huge material advantage then, Black can resign. } { [%csl Ga5,Gb6,Yb5,Bc7,Rd8,Ra6,Rb4,Ya4,Ye5,Yc5,Rf5,Yd5][%cal Gc4a5,Gc4b6,Ya4b5,Bg3c7,Yd4c5,Yd4e5,Ye4d5] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📙 Double Rook Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Bosburp"]
[Black "Zainfarid"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2084"]
[BlackElo "2043"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📙 Double Rook Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/o0z00fZZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1pqbpppp/p4n2/1B1PN3/Q4B2/2N5/P4PPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 4 14"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Next, we have the Double Rook Sacrifice, one of my personal favorite tactical patterns. It happens when a one side allows the opponent's queen to capture one rook with check and then immediately wins another rook. Pretty cool right? Here I have an example from one of my games I played some time ago (3+0 online blitz). Black's previous move was Qc7 (actually a blunder because of the next sequence). So in this position my knight is being attacked (captured with check), and the state of my LSB is looking scary too, but it's actually safe on b5 because of the pinned h pawn. Here I took a moment to think, and played: } { [%csl Rc3,Yb5] }
14. Nxd7!! { The absolute best move! Sacrificing a full knight with check! My DSB now attacks Black's queen, so he's pretty forced to accept my sacrifice. I figured after Black's queen goes on her shopping spree, I'd end up getting a deadly attack with my remaining pieces while Black's queen is to far away to defend. } { [%csl Rc7,Rc3,Gb5,Re8][%cal Ya4f4,Rf4c7,Rc3e1] } 14... Qxc3+ { My opponent took my knight, here I have to make another important decision; move my king up to e2 protecting my rook or play Bd2 sacrificing both rooks. } { [%cal Rc3e1,Rc3a1] } 15. Bd2!! { After some thought, I played Bd2!!, which is the only winning move because now I gain tempo on the queen, forcing her to move away. } { [%cal Rd2c3] } (15. Ke2?? { Fails completely, because now Black has enough time to do something about my threats. } 15... Qb2+ { Simply forking, thus winning a full piece. A simple Nbxd7 would have worked too here. Black just ends up being up in material. } { [%cal Rb2b5,Rb2e2] } 16. Kf3 Qxb5 $19) 15... Qxa1+ 16. Ke2! { Sacrificing my second rook. I'm again gaining tempo on the queen. } { [%csl Rh1] } 16... Qxh1 { I'm currently down 11 points in material, but now it's my turn to start throwing the punches. } 17. Nxf6+! { A discovered check, forcing the king to move. } { [%cal Rf6e8,Rb5e8] } 17... Kd8 $7 18. Ba5+! { Bringing more pieces into the attack. I'm now creating a mating net. Now the rest is pretty straightforward and will require no annotations. } { [%csl Ye8,Yd7,Rd8,Rc7][%cal Yb5e8,Ra5d8] } 18... Kc8 19. Bd7+ Nxd7 $7 20. Qxd7+ Kb8 21. Qc7+ Ka7 22. Bb6# { A nice checkmate whilst being down 8 points in material. This game shows that having more pieces isn't always important. A few active minor pieces can be incredibly powerful if the opponent's pieces are just sitting somewhere away from the attack. Always think a few moves ahead. Make sure your attack is strong enough to justify any material sacrifice. Full game: https://lichess.org/KfkobMc6#27 } { [%csl Yb8,Yb6,Ga7,Rb7,Ra6,Ra8][%cal Gb6a7,Yc7b6,Yc7b8] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📙 Double Rook Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Alexander Alekhine"]
[Black "Grigory Levenfish"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📙 Double Rook Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/PIzW9EbW"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/1p2p2p/p3Pnp1/2p5/2B2B2/2N2P2/PqP1Q2P/R3K2R w KQkq - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here's another example of the Double Rook Sacrifice, this time from a game between two legendary grandmasters; 4th World Champion Alexander Alekhine and Soviet Champion Grigory Levenfish. Alekhine's rook and knight are being attacked and the only move for White to save both pieces would be Kd2. But that would be a very uncomfortable position to play as White. Instead, Alekhine plays the winning tactical sacrifice: } { [%cal Rb2c3,Rb2a1] }
15. Nb5!! { Leaving both the rook and knight hanging! The point of this is that White saves his knight, which gets an attack after Nc7+ at some point. The knight in this position is much stronger that rook in the corner. } { [%csl Rb5,Ra1][%cal Bb5c7] } 15... Qxa1+ { Levenfish takes the rook, there isn't anything else to do really. } (15... axb5 { Also loses. } 16. Bxb5+ { Giving a check to the king. } { [%cal Re6f7,Re6d7,Gb5e8] } 16... Kd8 17. Rd1+ $18 { Saving the rook. Black is now forced to sacrifice back a piece, because the king has no squares to run, and White will end up with a very strong checkmating attack. } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Bf6d7,Bc8d7] }) 16. Kf2! { Important! The reason for sacrificing both rooks is to gain tempo, as we've seen in the previous example. 16. Qd1 wouldn't work because it doesn't gain tempo. } { [%csl Gh1,Ra1] } 16... Qxh1 { Now the black queen's shopping spree is finished, it's Alekhine's turn to throw some punches. } { [%csl Gf4,Gc4,Rh1][%cal Bb5c7] } 17. Nc7+! Kd8 $7 18. Qd2+! { Controlling the d-file. } { [%cal Rd2d8] } 18... Bd7 19. exd7 Nxd7 20. Be6 { Here Levenfish resigned because checkmate is unstoppable. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Rd2d8,Ye6d7] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📒 Novotny Sacrifice | Example"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "David Navara"]
[Black "Anna Dergatschova-Daus"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2656"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2239"]
[BlackTitle "WIM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📒 Novotny Sacrifice | Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/Wh1CHdpF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "4q3/1b2Pk1p/r5p1/4Q2n/1p1B4/5P2/1P4PP/2R1R2K w - - 3 36"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Next we have the Novotny, it's extremely rare, but it's still good to know what it is. A Novotny is when a player sacrifices a piece on a square where it can be captured by two or more different opposing pieces, whichever piece makes the capture ends up obstructing the other. Here is an example of the Novotny tactic from a game between GM David Navara and WIM Anna Dergatschova-Daus. Of course, this is a winning position for White because of the material advantage and attacking position, but White has only one move that leads to a mate in 4. Notice how the rook, queen, and knight are all controlling an important square and that's why an immediate checkmate hasn't been played yet. The queen blocks the e7 pawn from promoting, the rook controls e6 (preventing Qe6#), and the bishop controls d4 (preventing Qd4+-Qe6#). } { [%csl Rb7,Ra6,Re8][%cal Gb7d5,Ga6e6] }
36. Rc6!! { An absolutely brilliant find by Navara! The rook can be captured 3 different ways, but each of them fails. Taking with the rook, would obstruct the bishop from controlling d4, taking with the bishop would block the rook from controlling e6, and taking with the queen would simply allow e8=Q. And if Black were to just ignore the rook, Qe6 is checkmate. Note: On this move Anna Dergatschova-Daus resigned because checkmate can't be stopped, but I'll show how the checkmates look like for educative purposes. } { [%csl Ga6,Gb7,Ge8][%cal Re8c6,Rb7c6,Ra6c6,Be5e6] } 36... Qxc6 { Now the queen has left her post of blocking the e pawn. } { [%cal Be7e8] } (36... Rxc6 { The rook now obstruct the bishop! } { [%csl Gd5,Rc6][%cal Bb7d5] } 37. Qd5+ { [%csl Rf7,Ge6,Gg8,Yg7,Yf6,Be7,Re8,Rg6,Bf8][%cal Gd5g8,Yd4h8,Be1e7,Be7f8] } 37... Re6 38. Qxe6# { [%csl Ge7,Gg8,Gf7,Bf8,Re8,Rg6,Yg7,Yf6,Ge1][%cal Ge6e7,Ge6g8,Be7f8,Yd4g7] }) (36... Bxc6 { Blocks the rook! } { [%csl Rc6,Ge6][%cal Ba6e6,Ye5e6] } 37. Qe6# { [%csl Rg6,Re8,Bf8,Gg8,Gf7,Ge7,Yg7,Yf6][%cal Be7f8,Ge6g8,Yd4g7] }) 37. e8=B+! { A nice underpromotion works here! e=Q worked too of course. } { [%csl Gh8] } 37... Kf8 38. Qh8# { 37...Kg8 would lead to the same. } { [%csl Gf8,Gg8,Be7,Yh8,Yg7,Rf7,Be8][%cal Gh8e8,Be1e8,Yd4h8,Re8f7] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Undermining Sacrifice | Example"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Johann Carlos Alvarez Marquez"]
[Black "Tomi Nyback"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2379"]
[WhiteTitle "IM"]
[BlackElo "2448"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Undermining Sacrifice | Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/JDoCNAsT"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "4rrk1/R5bp/3qp1p1/3p3n/2pB1P2/6PP/1P3PB1/3QR1K1 w - - 2 24"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Next, we arrive at the tactic known as the Undermining Sacrifice, also referred to as the removal of the guard or removing the defender. This tactic is fairly straightforward, as the name suggests. Undermining is when a player sacrifices a piece to eliminate an opponent's key defensive piece, leaving one of the opponent's pieces undefended or insufficiently defended. Here we have an example from a game between two masters that beautifully illustrates this tactic. Notice how there's quite a bit of pressure on the g7 bishop, it's only protected by the h5 knight. Now material is equal, but White has a killer-move to win a massive amount of material. } { [%csl Rg7,Gh5,Gd4,Ga7][%cal Yd4g7,Ba7g7] }
24. Qxh5! { Well, since the knight is the only piece protecting g7, White just takes it out! } 24... gxh5 { Now the g7 bishop is left undefended. } { [%csl Rg7] } (24... Rf7 { Played in the game, but it loses just as well. } 25. Rxf7 { Again attacking the bishop. } { [%csl Bg7][%cal Rd4g7,Rf7g7] } 25... gxh5 26. Rxg7+ Kf8 27. Rxh7 { It's +8.3 because White's incredible strong position and +3 material advantage. Black's king is also incredibly weak will most likely get checkmated very soon. A simple winning idea here is Ra1-Raa7 and it's gg. Tomi Nyback resigned here. } { [%csl Gg2,Re8,Rf8,Rd6,Gh7][%cal Be1a1,Ba1a7,Ba7f7] }) 25. Rxg7+ Kh8 $7 26. Rd7+ $18 { Discovered check! White wins the queen back and will enjoy a +6 material advantage, Black can resign. PS: Sorry for the green book emoji again, There aren't any other colors left :) } { [%csl Bd6,Rh8][%cal Bd7d6,Rd4h8] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📕 Sac on g7 | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Black "Vasily Borisovich Malinin"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2523"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2434"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📕 Sac on g7 | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/obkKQQLJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/5N2/q7/2PB1P2/P1P3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 12"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ A "sac on g7" in chess involves sacrificing a piece, usually a bishop or knight, on the g7 square to attack the opponent's castled king. This sacrifice typically exposes the king, opens lines for other pieces, and creates tactical opportunities, often leading to a checkmate or significant material gain. Here we have an example of a game between (12 year old at the time) GM Sergey Karjakin and GM Vasily Borisovich Malinin. It looks like Black has extinguished any potential attack from White by castling his king kingside, but this leads to a beautiful sequence: } { [%csl Gg8] }
12. Nxg7!! { The winning move! White breaks the black king's pawn wall, exposing the king. It is important to note that you shouldn't just randomly sacrifice a piece on g7 and hope you'll get a checkmate somehow. You have to look if you have a follow-up that works and your opponent's pieces can't defend. } { [%csl Rc8,Rc6,Ra4] } 12... Kxg7 { Now the king is exposed, but there isn't a way to immediately take advantage of it because White's pieces are still to far away. But the reason the knight g7 sac works is because of Karjakin's brilliant follow-up. } { [%csl Rg7,Rd1,Rf1,Rd3] } 13. Bh6+!! { The only move! The king has to come forward to a square where White can attack him. The only way to do this was by sacrificing the bishop. } 13... Kxh6 (13... Kh8 14. Bxf8 $18 { Now Black ends up being down material and and unsafe king! } { [%csl Gf8] }) 14. Qd2+! { Now the king is on a square where the queen can start hitting him. } 14... Kh5 { The king is now fully exposed. White can now start making a mating net. } { [%csl Rg6,Rh6,Rg5][%cal Rd3g6,Rd2h6,Rd2g5] } (14... Kg7 { Going back doesn't work. } 15. Qg5+ Kh8 16. Qxf6+ Kg8 17. Qg5+ Kh8 18. Qh6 { Both checkmate threats, queen taking on h7 or f8, cannot be stopped. } { [%cal Rh6h7,Yd3h7,Rh6f8] }) 15. g4+! { The easiest way. White just keeps throwing checks. } 15... Nxg4 { Forced. Kh4 leads to mate in 2 after Qh6+ } (15... Kh4 16. Qh6+ Nh5 17. Qxh5#) 16. fxg4+ Qxg4+ 17. Kh1! { White simply moves the king out of check. There are now a bunch of open files to attack the king. The queen is the king's only defender, all his other pieces are too far away to do anything. } { [%csl Rh5,Rg4,Gd3,Gd2,Rf8,Rc6,Ra8,Rc8][%cal Gf1f6] } 17... d6 18. Rf6! { Threatening Rh6# } { [%csl Rh6][%cal Rf6h6] } 18... Qg5 19. Be2+ Bg4 20. Bxg4+ { Removing the defender. } 20... Qxg4 (20... Kh4 21. Qe1+ Kxg4 22. Qe4+ Kh5 23. Qxh7+ Kg4 24. Rg1#) 21. Rh6# { Checkmate! See the full game here: https://lichess.org/uk4cXCIh } { [%csl Gh4,Gh5,Gg6,Yh6,Yg5,Rg4][%cal Gh6h4,Gh6g6,Yd2h6] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📕 Sac on g7 | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Stean, Michael"]
[Black "Langeweg, Kick"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2510"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2450"]
[BlackTitle "IM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📕 Sac on g7 | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/0CYN0ILr"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "1q3rk1/1p2Qppp/p1b5/8/3B4/1P4P1/P1r1PP1P/R2R2K1 w - - 1 21"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have another example from a game between two strong masters. First, notice how Black's rook is kinda just loosely sitting on c2 undefended. Additionally, Black's other pieces are quite passive, and far away from their king. Now White only has one winning move here that makes use of the fact that's Black's rook is undefended. } { [%csl Rb8,Rc6,Yc2,Rf8] }
21. Bxg7!! { Breaking open the kingside, exposing the king! } 21... Kxg7 { Recapturing is quite forced. } { [%csl Rg7] } 22. Qg5+ { Now White's queen wants to hit the c2 rook, but she can't go do it immediately, she has to do some maneuvering. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rg5g7,Bg5f6,Bf6f5] } (22. Rd4! { Another great alternate! White simply brings the rook to join the attack. The queen can't win alone! } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Bd4g4] } 22... Qc8 { Controlling the g4 square. } { [%csl Rg4] } 23. Qg5+ { The queen now prepares for the rook to come over to g4. } { [%cal Bg5g4,Rg5g7] } 23... Kh8 24. Rg4 { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rg5g7] } 24... Rg8 (24... Qxg4 25. Qxg4 $18 { White is up 3 points in material and has a great position. } { [%csl Rh7,Rf7] }) 25. Qf6+ Rg7 26. Qxg7#) 22... Kh8 $7 23. Qf6+! { Important! We want the king to sit on a more exposed square. The king is much more exposed on the open g-file than in the corner. } { [%cal Rf6h8,Bh8g8] } (23. Qf5?? { Now this position is a draw, because after Rxe2, the Qg4+ fork doesn't work anymore because the king is hiding in the corner. } { [%csl Rc2][%cal Rf5c2] } 23... Rxe2 $10) 23... Kg8 24. Qf5 { In this position IM Langeweg resigned, because it doesn't matter where he puts his rook, the queen will always be able to fork it somehow with the exposed king. } { [%cal Rf5c2] } 24... Rxe2 (24... Be4 { The only way to save the rook. } 25. Qxe4 Qc8 26. Rd5 $18 { White is up 2 pawns and has a very dangerous attack against the exposed king using the queen and rook. } { [%cal Rd5g5] }) (24... Rc3 { Doesn't work either. } 25. Qg5+ Kh8 26. Qf6+ $18 { [%cal Rf6c3,Rf6h8] }) 25. Qg4+! { A fork! } { [%cal Rg4g8,Rg4e2] } 25... Kh8 26. Qxe2 { Not only is Black down 3 points in material, he also has 2 isolated pawns and a weak king, White will have no trouble winning this game. Full game: https://lichess.org/g4ySdeve#47 } { [%csl Bh4,Bg4][%cal Re2g4,Rg4h5,Bd1d4,Bd4h4] } *


