[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1bqpnpp1/2n1p2p/1R2P3/p2N1B2/P5PP/1P1Q1PB1/2R3K1 w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Next, we have the iconic Bxh6 sacrifice, a tactic you're likely to encounter in your games. Here's how it works: one side sacrifices their bishop on h6 (or h3 from Black's perspective), which opens up the opponent's kingside. This typically occurs when a queen is behind the bishop, ready to recapture on h6 and launch an attack on the king. Although, not always does that happen, sometimes some rerouting of the attacking pieces is required to get the attack done. Here we have a position from a game between 2 grandmasters. First, notice how most of Black's pieces are located on the queenside. This means that they are too far away to defend against White's impending kingside onslaught. } { [%csl Re7,Rc6,Rc7,Rb7,Gd2,Gf4,Yh6] }
25. Bxh6! { Crushing open the kingside! Often, your opponent might decline the sacrifice and make another move instead. In such cases, simply retreat the bishop to a safe square and enjoy the extra pawn. Additionally, the open h-file could become a long-term weakness for your opponent. Sometimes you might have to play Bxg7 to fully expose the king, but I'll explain why it might not work in the variation below. } 25... gxh6 (25... Rab8 26. Bxg7?? { In this case, this doesn't work because Black can maintain solidity with Ng6. There are moments when it's crucial to fully open the kingside like this, but only if you have enough pieces ideally positioned to follow up with the attack. There are some similar examples in the "Double Bishop Sacrifices" chapter. } 26... Kxg7 27. Qg5+ { Doesn't do anything. } 27... Ng6 $17 { Black's position remains solid, we don't have an immediate attack here. Black will soon play Qd1, trying to exchange the queens of the board, then Black just remains with a +1 material advantage. } { [%csl Gf7,Gg6,Gf8,Gg7][%cal Bc7d8,Bg7h7] }) 26. Qxh6 { Lets asses the situation. Bad stuff for Black: fully exposed king, each piece is on the opposite side of the board, the king has no where to run, and White's pieces are ready to come into the attack. Good stuff: uh...is up a single point in material. Seeing this, it's pretty convincing White's doing amazing here. } { [%csl Gh6,Rg8,Rh7][%cal Yd4f3,Yf3g5,Bg2e4] } 26... Ng6 { A move that looks like Black's consolidating, but it's hopeless already. White now just has to bring his next piece to help the queen. A queen alone can't get the job done! } { [%cal Bd4f3,Bf3g5] } (26... Ra5 { Played in the game, but everything fails. } 27. Be4 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Re4h7] } 27... Ng6 (27... f5 28. exf6 Rxf6 29. Qxf6 $18) 28. Bxg6 fxg6 29. Qxg6+ Kh8 30. Nxc6 dxc6 31. Qh6+ Kg8 32. Rc4 { The power of the queen and rook against the fully exposed king is unstoppable. } { [%cal Bc4g4,Rh6g7] }) 27. Nf3! { Rerouting to g5, preparing for Qh7#. The only way to stop this is with Qd8, followed by capturing the knight. This would leave White with a significant material advantage, ensuring an easy path to victory. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Bf3g5,Rh6h7] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📘 Sac on h6 | Example #2"]
