[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pb1nbpp1/1p5p/2pp2N1/3P1B1P/P2BP3/1P3PP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have another unique example from a game between two very strong GM's; Andrey Esipenko and Étienne Bacrot. So as we can see Esipenko's the one attacking here, but Black still seems to be able to defend, Esipenko needs to find a breakthrough to attack the king here. } { [%csl Gg5,Gf4,Gd3,Gh4] }
13. Nh7! { The best move! The knight was previously blocking the dark-squared bishop from sacrificing on h6. Now, Esipenko frees the DSB while gaining tempo by hitting the rook on f8. } { [%csl Gf4,Rh6][%cal Bf4h6,Rh7f8] } 13... Re8 { The only move from Black in order to save his rook. The DSB is now ready. } { [%csl Rh6][%cal Bf4h6] } 14. Bxh6!! gxh6 { Now the king is much more exposed compared to two moves ago. The g-file is opened up, allowing the queen to exploit this new weakness. } { [%csl Rg8,Rf8][%cal Rg4g8,Bh7f8] } (14... Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. hxg5 Qxg5 18. Qf3 $16 { [%csl Rh8,Rh7,Gh1,Gd3][%cal Bd3h7,Bf3h3,Be1c1] }) 15. Qg4+! { The queen joins the party! White's h7-knight is doing a great job not allowing the king to escape to f8, making the king stuck in his little corner. } { [%csl Gh7,Gg4][%cal Rh7f8] } 15... Kh8 { [%csl Gh1] } 16. Ng5!! { White still can't get a checkmate with his current attacking pieces (queen, light-squared bishop, and knight), so Esipenko prepares to bring his h1 rook into the game by breaking open the h-file. If Black doesn't take the knight, Nxf7 would be checkmate. } { [%csl Rf7,Gh1][%cal Rg5f7] } 16... Bxg5 { Quite forced. } (16... hxg5 { Helps White by just opening the h-file. } { [%cal Rg4h5] } 17. Qh5+ Kg7 18. Qh7+ Kf6 19. Qh6# { [%csl Rf7,Re7,Ye6,Yf6,Yg6,Yg7,Be5,Gf5,Rg5][%cal Yh6e6,Yh6g7,Bd4e5,Gd3f5] }) (16... Rf8 { Protecting the f pawn, but this doesn't work too. } { [%cal Gf8f7] } 17. Qh5 { Forced mate in 9. } { [%csl Rh8,Rh6][%cal Rh5h8] }) 17. hxg5 { The rook is now in the game, preparing infiltrate via the h-file. } { [%csl Gh1,Rh8][%cal Rh1h8] } 17... Nf8?! { Bacrot probably played this so that his queen will no longer be tied down to it, but this ends things a bit quicker. } (17... Re6 18. Rxh6+ Rxh6 19. gxh6 Qf6 20. Qxd7 { [%csl Rh8,Gd7,Rb7,Ra8,Ge1] }) 18. Rxh6+ { [%csl Gh6][%cal Rh6h8] } 18... Kg7 19. Qh5 { Esipenko builds up a battery to go to h7. It's 3 against 2, and Black no longer has another piece to join the defense. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Bd3h7,Gh6h7,Yh5h7] } 19... cxd4 (19... Re6 { Would have prolonged the game a bit. The rook now controls h6, preventing the immediate mate we saw in the game. } { [%csl Rh6][%cal Re6h6] } 20. O-O-O $18 { White just brings another piece into the attack; it's completely winning. } { [%cal Bd1h1] }) 20. Rh7+! { Finally giving the check. } 20... Nxh7 21. Qh6+!! { A very important move!! Immediately taking the knight would have led to a draw! Esipenko has to make sure the king can't escape via f8-e7, which would allow it to find safety. With this intermezzo, the queen first controls f8 and forces the king back. It was here that Bacrot resigned because it's a forced mate in 4. I'll just show the next few moves so you can see how the mate would have looked. } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Rh6f8,Bg7f8,Bf8e7] } (21. Qxh7+?? { A complete throw. } 21... Kf8 { The king is now safe. White can only achieve a perpetual check, as trying to play down a full rook definitely won't work. } { [%cal Bf8e7] } 22. Qh8+ Ke7 23. Qe5+ Kf8 $10 { White has to go for the draw. }) 21... Kg8 22. Bxh7+! { Again, taking with the queen would have allowed the king to run over to f8, leading to a draw. } { [%cal Rh6f8,Yh7g8] } 22... Kh8 $7 23. Bg6+ Kg8 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Qxf7# { Check out the full game here: https://lichess.org/JK1MA7a5#41 } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📙 Tactical Desperado | Example"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Shakhriyar Mamedyarov"]
[Black "Igor Kurnosov"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2724"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2602"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📙 Tactical Desperado | Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/4wqXN8DP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r5k1/ppp1p1rp/8/3P3Q/2nRPqb1/2N5/PP2N1P1/1K5R b - - 2 21"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ A tactical desperado is when a piece that’s going to be captured anyway makes a final, impactful move. Instead of just losing the piece, you use it to take an opponent's piece or create a strong threat, forcing your opponent to react and potentially gaining an advantage. It's a clever way to get the most out of a piece that's about to be lost. Note: there's also a positional desperado, but we'll get to that later. Here we have a beautiful example from a game between 2 very strong grandmasters; Shakhriyar Mamedyarov and Igor Kurnosov. The last move from Black was Bg4, attacking White's queen, instead of moving away, White responded with Ngf2 counterattacking Black's queen. Now the queen could just run away, but instead Kurnosov finds a brilliant way to win an exchange. }
21... Qd2!! { The queen was going to get captured anyway, but now White has to capture with the rook, allowing Black to recapture the rook with check. This is an in-between sequence before capturing White's queen, which remains hanging. If White doesn't take the queen, Qxb2 is checkmate. } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Rd2b2,Yc4b2,Rg4h5] } (21... Bxh5?? 22. Nxf4 $18 { Black has two pieces hanging, he can't save both. } { [%csl Rh5,Rc4] }) (21... Qf6?? { Moving the away would leave Black slightly better because of White's more looser structure, but it will take a lot of time to convert this into a win and many things could still go wrong. } 22. Qh2 $15) 22. Rxd2 Nxd2+ { A check! White's queen is still hanging. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Rd2b1,Rg4h5] } 23. Kc2 Bxh5 24. Rxh5 Nf1 $19 { Mamedyarov resigned here because Kurnosov simply has a winning endgame. So, when one of your pieces will get captured, make sure to check if it can still make threats or opportunities before it is inevitably captured. } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📒 Double Bishop Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Fabio Bruno"]
[Black "Norbert Stull"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2325"]
[WhiteTitle "IM"]
[BlackElo "2250"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📒 Double Bishop Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/7cOMo14h"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1b1nbppp/pq2p3/1pppB1P1/3P4/2PBPQ1P/PP1N1P2/3RK2R w K - 1 15"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Now we've arrived at the Double Bishop Sacrifice. We can call it that, or we can call it a combination of the Greek Gift (chapter 6) and Sac on g7 (chapter 13). You probably already guessed what this sacrifice is by the name; One side sacrifices both bishops to clear the covering from the opponents king and wins material or gets a checkmate. Here we have an example from a game between Italian IM Fabio Bruno and Norbert Stull. Most of Bruno's pieces are aiming at the kingside, and Black's pieces are quite far away to defend. So, White sees his sacrifices are worth it so he plays: } { [%csl Ge5,Gd3,Gf3,Re7,Rd7,Rb6,Rb7] }
15. Bxh7+!! { Sacrificing the bishop! This clears away the h-pawn from the king's defense. } { [%csl Rh7] } 15... Kxh7 { The king is now exposed, White has to bring another piece closer. } 16. Qh5+! { The queen has now joined the attack. } { [%csl Gh5] } 16... Kg8 $7 { The queen is alone, thus can't get an attack. The Black king still is too safe behind his pawns. } { [%csl Gh5,Gg8,Gg7,Gf7,Gf8] } 17. Bxg7!! { The second bishop sacrifice! Opening up the kingside further! } { [%csl Rg7] } 17... Kxg7 { The king is now fully exposed, he has no more pawns to run behind. } { [%csl Rg7,Rh7,Rh8,Rg8,Gh5] } 18. Qh6+! { A critical move! White must not allow the defensive Rh8, stopping the attack, then the king will get to run to f8 and Black's simply up 2 bishops. } (18. Nf3?? Rh8! { [%csl Rh5,Gh8][%cal Bg7f8,Bf8e8] }) 18... Kg8 { The rook now can't go to h8. } { [%csl Rf8,Rg8] } 19. g6!! { The killer-blow! White further opens up the position and threatens mate on h7. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rh6h7] } 19... Nf6 { Quite forced, he has to defend against the h7 mate threat. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rf6h7] } (19... fxg6 { Doesn't work because it opens up the g-file. } 20. Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Rg1 { Checkmate is unstoppable. } { [%csl Gg1,Gg6][%cal Rg6h6,Rg6h5,Rg6g7] }) 20. Nf3! { White simply brings another piece to join the attack. Threatening both Ne5 and Ng5. With the power of the knight, queen, and pawn White will be unstoppable. } { [%cal Bf3e5,Bf3g5] } 20... Rfd8 21. Ne5 { Here Norbert Stull resigned becasue gxf7# tactics are unstoppable. } { [%cal Rg6f7,Rh1g1] } (21. Ng5 { A perfectly fine alternative. } 21... Rf8 22. g7 b4 23. Qh8#) 21... fxg6 (21... Rab8 22. gxf7#) (21... Rf8 22. Rg1 b4 23. gxf7#) 22. Qxg6+ Kf8 (22... Kh8 23. Nf7#) 23. Qf7# *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📒 Double Bishop Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Johann Hermann Bauer"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📒 Double Bishop Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/thVDA716"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1b2bppp/ppq1pn2/2ppB3/5P2/1P1BP1N1/P1PPQ1PP/R4RK1 w - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have a famous game between two chess legends: Emanuel Lasker, the 2nd World Champion, and Johann Hermann Bauer. On the previous move, Bauer made a serious blunder with 13...a6??, which sets him up to fall victim to the powerful Double Bishop Sacrifice. But White can't do it right away. The key piece holding Black's position together is the knight, which defends h7 and blocks the dark-squared bishop. So, how do we get rid of this defensive piece? If you're not sure, you might want to check out Chapter 3 again. The answer is Deflection! } { [%csl Gf6,Gh7] }
14. Nh5! { Lasker cleverly deflects the knight away from protecting h7. In this case, the deflection isn't a sacrifice, since the queen still covers the knight, but it still does the job perfectly. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh7][%cal Rf6h7,Bh5f6] } 14... Nxh5? { Now the knight has left protecting h7. } { [%csl Rh7] } (14... Rfc8 { Black's best try was a waiting move like this. } 15. Nxf6+ { If Black's knight doesn't want to move, we just get rid of it. } 15... Bxf6 { Here the Greek Gift still works! } 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7?? { Loses due to: } (16... Kf8 17. Rf3 $16 { Black does survive, but it's really White having the fun here + he's got an extra pawn on the board. } { [%cal Bf3g3,Bf4f5,Be5f6] }) 17. Qh5+ { Bringing the queen in! } 17... Kg8 18. Bxf6! { Weakening the kingside further! } 18... gxf6 19. Qh6! $18 { An important move! We can't just let the king run away via f8-e7. Now the Rf3-Rg3 idea is unstoppable. } { [%csl Yf8][%cal Bf1f3,Bf3g3,Rg3g8,Yh6f8] }) 15. Bxh7+!! { Sacrificing the first bishop! This is the same pattern as we've seen in the previous chapter. Now the knight will be captured with a check. } { [%csl Rh5] } (15. Qxh5?? { It's no check, so Black gets enough time to play a defensive move. } 15... f5 $10 { Black has now a fortress. White's attack can be successfully defended, it's equal } { [%csl Be8][%cal Bc6e8,Be8g6] }) 15... Kxh7 (15... Kh8 16. Qxh5 { It's forced mate by Bg6-Qh7# tactics. } { [%cal Bh7g6,Bh5h7] }) 16. Qxh5+ { [%cal Rh5h7] } 16... Kg8 $7 { If Black plays the defensive f6, it would completely neutralize White's attack, leaving Black up a piece. White cannot allow this, so another forcing move is necessary. } { [%cal Rf7f6] } 17. Bxg7!! { Sacrificing the second bishop completely exposes the king! } 17... Kxg7 { [%csl Rg7] } 18. Qg4+! { Very important! Lasker must prevent Black from playing Rg8 or Rh8, as this would enable the king to escape via f8. By playing Qg4+, Lasker forces the king onto the h-file, where it is unable to find refuge behind its pawns. } (18. Rf3?? { Throws away the win, it allows Rg8. } 18... Rg8! { [%cal Bg7f8] } 19. Rg3+ Kf8 $15) 18... Kh7 { [%csl Rh7] } 19. Rf3! { With the king's escape routes now sealed off, Lasker continues his attack by bringing in a new piece. He now threatens Rh3#, the only way for Black to stop this is by sacrificing his queen. } { [%cal Bf3h3] } 19... e5 { Opening the path for the queen to come to h6. } { [%csl Rh6][%cal Rc6h6] } 20. Rh3+ { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rh3h8,Rg4g8] } 20... Qh6 21. Rxh6+ Kxh6 { White now has won the queen and 2 pawns, but this it has costed 2 bishops and a rook, so material is still equal. But now White has managed to give Black an extremely weak king and the positioning of Black's pieces are very loose. } 22. Qd7 $18 { The final move secures the win, as White ends up winning one of the bishops due to the fork, gaining a material advantage and achieving a dominant position due to Black's weak pawns and exposed king. Not every attack leads to an immediate checkmate; sometimes, you might have to continue the game from a winning endgame. } { [%cal Rd7e7,Rd7b7] } *


