[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/bpq2ppp/p1b1p3/2P5/1P2B3/P4Q2/1B3PPP/2R2RK1 w - - 3 18"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here's another awesome example from a game between two grandmasters: Anthony Miles, the first English GM, and Walter Browne, a six-time U.S. Champion. }
18. Bxh7+!! Kxh7 19. Qh5+! { The queen can move to h5 right away, since there's no knight blocking it's path! } 19... Kg8 $7 { It seems like the king is safe behind his wall of pawns, and with no knight on the board, White's attack appears to be over. But hold on! White is actually in a completely winning position, he just has to get rid of the only thing keeping the black king safe: his wall! } { [%csl Gg8,Gf8,Gf7,Gg7] } 20. Bxg7!! { Completely exposing the king! This sac on g7 will be explained more in chapter 15 and 16. } 20... Kxg7 21. Qg5+! { Important! First White has to make sure the king can't gets no chance to run away, so he makes a kind of mating net. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Rg5f6] } (21. Rc4?? { Bringing in the piece immediately fails, because it allows Black to create an escape route. } 21... f5! $19 { Black's just up 2 bishops. } { [%cal Bg7f6,Bf6e7,Rf5g4] }) 21... Kh8 (21... Kh7 22. Rc4 { No stopping it! } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Rc4h4] }) 22. Qf6+! { Blocking the f pawn to make sure it can't move forward to create a escape path or allow the queen to defend. } { [%csl Rh8,Rf6,Rc7][%cal Rf6h8] } 22... Kg8 { Now the king will definitely not get away. It's time to bring in another piece, since a queen alone can't do anything except give some checks. } { [%csl Rh8,Rg7][%cal Rf6h8] } 23. Rc4! { There's no stopping the rook from going to g4! It's forced checkmate. Full game: https://lichess.org/UnquXe54#0 } { [%csl Rg4,Rg8,Gf6][%cal Bc4g4] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Empty Square Sac | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Napoleon Marache"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Empty Square Sac | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/QVreHzUQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3r2k1/ppp2ppp/6q1/b4n2/3nQB2/2p5/P4PPP/RN3RK1 b - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ The Empty Square Sacrifice is when one side doesn't capture anything, but just leaves a piece or pawn on an empty square where it can be captured. This usually happens to open up files, gain control of key squares, weaken the opponent's king, or lure the opponents pieces to an unfavorable square. Here we have an example from a game played in 1857! Napoleon Marache, know for composing many chess problems vs Paul Morphy, who was considered the best player during his time. This position is completely winning for Black, but only one move ends the game immediately. }
19... Ng3!! { In this game, the empty-square-sac was used to open the h7-b1 so that the queens are now staring at each other. So even though the knight can be captured 3 different way, it doesn't matter with what Black captures, Morphy just grabs the undefended queen. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rg6e4] } 20. Qxg6 { This is one variation where Black doesn't win the queen, instead we see this other thing; } { [%csl Re2] } (20. Bxg3 { The queen remains hanging. } 20... Qxe4 $19 { [%csl Ge4] }) (20. hxg3 { Same thing } 20... Qxe4) (20. fxg3 Qxe4) (20. Qxb7 Nde2#) (20. Qe1 Nde2+ 21. Qxe2 Nxe2+ 22. Kh1 Nxf4 { +10 points in material. }) 20... Nde2# { It's checkmate! You don't see that everyday! } { [%csl Yh1,Gg1,Rf1,Rf2,Rg2,Rh2][%cal Yg3h1,Ge2g1] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Empty Square Sac | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Robert Fischer"]
[Black "Pal Benko"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Empty Square Sac | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/3Q3x9Ip3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r3qr1k/pp3pbp/2pn4/7Q/3pP3/2NB3P/PPP3P1/R4RK1 w - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Congratulations on making it to the final chapter of tactical sacrifices! If you're still here, kudos to you—many would have given up by now. If you've enjoyed the study so far, please drop a heart; it will help more people discover this study! Here we have an epic example from a game between two chess legends: Robert Fischer, the 11th World Champion and often hailed as the greatest player of all time, and Pal Benko, a former top-10 player and Grandmaster renowned for his incredible books and contributions to chess education. Let's assess the position. Material is still equal, but Fischer's knight is hanging. The key idea here is that Fischer's light-squared bishop would become much more powerful if the e5 square could be opened up. However, if Fischer plays e5 directly, Benko can simply respond with f5, maintaining a solid position. To make this idea work, Fischer finds the only winning move: } { [%csl Rc3,Rh7][%cal Be4e5,Yd3h7,Gh5h7] }
19. Rf6!! { Absolutely brilliant! The point of the move is that after Black takes the free rook, Fischer plays e5, opening up the bishop and threatening mate in one on h7. At this point, Benko can no longer play f5 because the bishop on f6 is in the way. And if Benko doesn't take the rook, Fisher can still play e5, because the hanging rook on f6 still prevents f5. } (19. e5?? { Playing this immediately fails. } 19... f5 $10 { Black's completely fine, and now White is forced to trade queens becaus ethe knight remains hanging. } { [%csl Rh5,Rc3][%cal Re8h5] }) 19... Bxf6 (19... Kg8 { Played in the game, but the position was hopeless. } 20. e5 { Opening up the bishop as planned. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7,Gh5h7] } 20... h6 { The only move that stops mate. Now this part is really cool, Black can't do anything. Every piece is stuck, the knight has to control f5 (because of Qf5-Qh7#), the bishop has to keep protecting h6, the g7 rook is stuck, and the queen and a8 rook can just shuffle around but that's it. They can't do anything to defend or create counterplay. Now Fisher can slowly just reroute his knight to g4 and grab the h6 pawn, then it's over. } { [%csl Rg4] } 21. Nd1! { [%cal Bd1f2,Bf2g4,Bg4h6,Bc3d1] } (21. Ne2 $18 { Played in the game, works just as well. Fisher saves his knight and on the next move can just play Rxd6 or Raf1. Here Pal Benko resigned. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Ba1f1,Be2g3,Rf6d6,Bh5f5] })) 20. e5! { There's nothing Black can do! No piece can cover the h7 square. It's forced checkmate. The full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1008421 } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7][%cal Bh5h7,Yd3h7] } *


