[ChapterName "📌 Section 2: Positional Sacrifices"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/nCDCyS3y"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ As I said before, there are two main types of sacrifices in chess: "real" sacrifices and "sham" sacrifices. While we've already covered sham sacrifices, which are temporary and tactical in nature, let's now delve into "real" sacrifices.

Real sacrifices, or positional sacrifices, involve giving up material without immediate tactical gains, aiming for long-term strategic advantages instead. Unlike tactical sacrifices, where the material is often regained shortly after, positional sacrifices are made with the understanding that the sacrificed material might not be recovered. Instead, the goal is to achieve benefits such as improved piece activity, better pawn structure, control of key squares, or creating weaknesses in the opponent's camp.

Positional sacrifices often require a deep understanding of chess strategy and long-term planning. In this section, we'll look at different kinds of positional sacrifices.

Click the space-bar! 🚀 }
 *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Queen Sac for Piece Activity | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Milko Bobotsov"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Queen Sac for Piece Activity | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/LnPpJljJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/3nppbp/p2p1np1/qpp5/2PPP3/2N1BP2/PP1QN1PP/1K1R1B1R w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Sometimes, you have to be willing to give up your queen for a couple of minor pieces. Two active minor pieces can be much stronger than a queen, working together to control the board. Here we have a famous example from Milko Bobotsov vs Mikhail Tal, Varna 1958. }
11. Nd5? { Bobotsov now opens the queen's diagonal and targets the e7 pawn. The only way for Tal to save it is with Qd8, but that's a pretty uncomfortable move for Black. } { [%cal Rd2a5,Rd5e7] } 11... Nxd5! { If you've seen Tal's games, you were probably fully expecting this! This move is 100% correct. In return for the queen, he gets two minor pieces. } { [%cal Rd5e3] } (11... Qxd2?? 12. Nxe7+ { It is with check. } 12... Kh8 13. Rxd2 $18) (11... Qd8? { Protects the pawn, but leads to a very uncomfortable sequence. } { [%cal Rd8e7] } 12. Nxf6+! { With the plan of opening the d-file. } 12... Nxf6 13. dxc5 { The d6-pawn is pinned. } { [%cal Rd6c5,Gd1d8] } 13... bxc4 14. cxd6 $16 { Now White is up a pawn, can develop easily with moves like Nf4 followed by Bxc4, and controls the d-file. Black's c-pawn is weak and probably won't last long, and has a hard time developing the pieces. } { [%csl Rc4,Gd6,Gd2,Gd1][%cal Be2f4] }) 12. Qxa5 Nxe3 { The knight's not finished yet! He forks the rook and c-pawn. } { [%cal Re3d1,Re3c4] } 13. Rc1 Nxc4 $17 { Lets look at the position. Tal has a solid pawn-structure, an insanely well-placed knight on c4, a fianchettoed bishop that can turn into a monster after the diagonal is broken up (it absolutely was in the game), and can easily reroute the d7 knight to become active too. The engine gives an evaluation of -0.5. While this may not seem like a significant advantage, Black has won 62% of the time! (this position has been reached 312 times on lichess) This clearly demonstrates the ease of playing as Black in this position } { [%csl Gg7,Gc4,Yh7,Yg6,Yf7,Ye7,Yb5,Ya6,Yd6,Yc5][%cal Yh7g6,Yf7g6,Ye7d6,Yd6c5,Ya6b5,Rc4a5,Bd7b6,Bb6a4,Rc5d4,Rg7b2] } 14. Rxc4!? { This was played in the game. Because the knight was so incredibly strong on c4, Bobotsov decided he'll just have to get rid of it. } (14. Qe1 cxd4 15. Nf4 Nde5 $15 { Black's only down a single point in material, has 2 super well-placed knights dominating the center, and a DSB which has a lot of potential. Black has a slight edge. Positional sacrifices are never an immediate win, you are sacrificing for a long-term positional advantage. } { [%csl Ge5,Gc4,Gg7][%cal Ba6a5,Bb5b4,Ba8b8] }) (14. Qc3 Ndb6 $17 { [%csl Gb6,Gc4,Rd4,Gg7,Rf1,Rc3,Rb2][%cal Yg7d4,Bb5b4,Ba6a5,Ba8b8] }) 14... bxc4 $17 { Tal's pawn structure is weakened, but he now has an open b-file for the a8 rook. By combining the power of his pieces, especially the rook, dark-squared bishop, knight, and a pawn storm, Tal won a magnificent game. You can check out the fully annotated game in my collection of Tal's games study: https://lichess.org/study/r072zv4F/55Mlt5Mg } { [%csl Gg7,Rc4,Rc5][%cal Ba8b8,Yb8b2,Yg7b2,Bd7b6] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Queen Sac for Piece Activity | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Nigel Short"]
[Black "Richard Miles"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Queen Sac for Piece Activity | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/RGd8xYi4"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/4P3/2BP4/2N5/PPP1QPPP/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have another example where sacrificing the queen for active minor pieces can be devastating for your opponent. This position is from a game between GM Nigel Short and GM Richard Miles. Short is attacking the f6 knight, but the d pawn is left hanging. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Re5f6] }
6... Nxd4 { Instead of retreating the knight, Miles counterattacks the queen, demonstrating the principle of looking for active counterplay rather than just reacting to threats. } { [%cal Rd4e2,Re5f6] } 7. exf6! { The best move! Sacrificing the queen, but hitting the g7 bishop. } { [%cal Rf6g7,Rd4e2] } (7. Qd3?? { Lets see what would have happened if White was to scared to part with the queen. } 7... dxe5 $19 { White has nothing here. Down 2 pawns, pieces aren't active, and the queen will probably get kicked around. Stockfish says -3.5. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf6][%cal Bc8f5,Be8g8] }) 7... Nxe2 8. fxg7 { Black must save the rook to prevent White from regaining their queen. In doing so, Black leaves their knight hanging. } { [%cal Rg7h8,Rg1e2] } 8... Rg8 { Forced. } 9. Ngxe2 Rxg7 { Short has sacrificed a queen and two central pawns for three minor pieces. But these 3 minor pieces are dominating the board, all Miles' pieces still haven't crossed the 7th rank. } { [%csl Ge2,Gc3,Gc4][%cal Bc1h6,Be2f4,Bc3e4,Be1c1] } 10. Bh6! { Quite important! Short brings the bishop out, preparing to castle, with tempo by hitting the rook. If he would have brought the bishop to any other square Black would get a move to develop. By hitting the rook first, Short gains an extra free move. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1] } 10... Rg8 11. O-O-O { Now the king is brought to safety, and the rook controls the d-file. Notice how Miles has zero development. It's important to note, though, that the position is still completely equal. With perfect play, Black should be able to maintain solidity. However, it's easier for White to play due to the active pieces, while Black must carefully defend and aim to stay solid. } { [%csl Gd1,Gc1,Ra8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rg8,Ge2,Gc4,Gc3,Gh6] } 11... e6?! { An inaccuracy, it creates weaknesses on the dark-squares. Moves like Ne4 and Bg5 would make use of that weakness. } { [%csl Rf6,Re7][%cal Bc3e4,Bh6g5] } (11... c6 { A better move. It would allow queenside expansion with b5 or d5 at some point, and it's always nice for the queen to have a diagonal to run around. } { [%csl Yc7,Yb6,Ya5][%cal Yd8c7,Yc7b6,Yb6a5,Bd6d5,Bb7b5] }) 12. h4! { Prepares Bg4 by supporting that square. } { [%csl Yg5][%cal Bh6g5,Yh4g5] } 12... Bd7 { Miles prepares to castle queenside as soon as he can. } { [%cal Bd8e7] } (12... f6 { Stops Bg4, but creates a new weakness; e6. } { [%cal Rf6g5] } 13. Nf4 $18 { [%csl Re6][%cal Gc4e6,Gf4e6,Bh1e1] }) 13. Ne4! { Activating the knight! The main threat here is Bg4-Nf6, winning material. } { [%cal Bh6g5,Be4f6] } 13... f6 { Miles has to take care of that threat. } { [%cal Rf6g5] } (13... d5?? { In case you're wondering, this fork doesn't work. } 14. Bg5 { Hitting the queen, and controlling the f6 square for the knight to jump to. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Rg5d8,Be4f6] } 14... Qc8 15. Nf6+ $18 { [%cal Rf6g8,Rf6e8] }) 14. Nf4 $16 { Who would you want to play as in this position? I'd definitely choose White. White's pieces are well-developed and have good control over the board, while Black's pieces are undeveloped and stuck on defense. Check out how Nigel Short absolutely crushed Miles with his minor pieces here: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1123803&kpage=2 SPOILER: Short's minor pieces got such a devastating attack, Miles NEVER had the chance to move his queen or a8 rook because he was to busy defending. } { [%csl Gf4,Ge4,Gc4,Gh6,Gd1,Gc1,Rd8,Re8,Rg8,Ra8,Rd7,Re6][%cal Bh4h5,Bg2g4,Bh1e1] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📕 Sac to Neutralize an Attack | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Wesley So"]
[Black "Ding Liren"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2760"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2782"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📕 Sac to Neutralize an Attack | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/qog3Nmpk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "1rbb2kr/2p4q/ppQp2n1/1B1Pp3/4P1p1/5pPP/P2B1N2/2RN1RK1 w - - 0 32"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Sometimes, you have to make sacrifices to neutralize an opponent's attack. This could involve trading pieces to reduce their attacking potential, eliminating key attackers, or even setting up a defensive fortress. Here's a great example from a game between two super GMs, Wesley So and Ding Liren. As you can see Liren is pressing hard against So on the h-file, creating a tense situation. Meanwhile, So's pieces are playing a more defensive role, trying to withstand the pressure. However, there's only one sequence that completely neutralizes Liren's attack. } { [%csl Gh8,Gh7,Rh3,Rg1,Gg4,Gc8,Rd2,Rd1,Rc1,Rf2,Rf1,Gf3][%cal Ra6b5] }
32. Qe8+! { it might look like a mistake at first, because after the king move, both the queen and bishop remain under attack, but this is all part of the plan. } 32... Kg7 { [%csl Rb5,Re8] } 33. Qxd8!! { Sacrificing the queen for a bishop, removing the defender of the c-pawn. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Bc1c7] } 33... Rxd8 { The rook is now removed from the kingside attack on the h-file. } { [%csl Rc7,Rd8,Rh8] } 34. Rxc7+ Bd7 35. Rxd7+! { Taking with check is important, White wants to force the trades. } 35... Rxd7 36. Bxd7 $16 gxh3 37. Kh2 { Using the "umbrella pawn" technique, White can capture the h-pawn at any time, but for now, it serves as protection, shielding the king from any potential threats. Now Liren's attack has been completely neutralized, So's three minor pieces are actually a lot stronger than the queen. They can now reroute to active squares and work towards grinding out a win in the endgame. It's was a challenging task, but after 23 moves, So managed to secure victory in this game. The full game: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1807346&comp=-1&kpage=3 } { [%cal Bd1e3,Be3f5,Bd7f5,Bf2g4,Bd2b4,Bd7c6] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📕 Sac to Neutralize an Attack | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Samuel Reshevsky"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📕 Sac to Neutralize an Attack | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/67DsrwgN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3rq1k1/4rppp/2n3b1/pp2P3/2pP1QB1/P1P1R3/1B4PP/4R1K1 b - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here we have a very famous example from a game between GM Samuel Reshevsky and GM Tigran Petrosian, two world-class players from the 1960s. Petrosian is in a tough spot, as Reshevsky has a dangerous attack brewing. The big threat here is Bf3, followed by a powerful d5 pawn advance. To survive, Petrosian must find a way to control the d5 square. He found a brilliant defensive move: } { [%cal Rd4d5,Bg4f3,Rd5d6] }
25... Re6!! { Vacating the e7 square for the knight! The knight can then hop to e7 on the next move, controlling the d5 square. You might wonder, "Can't the rook just move anywhere else, like a7, b7, or c7?" But after any of these moves, Black is met with a crushing e6. } { [%cal Bc6e7,Be7d5] } (25... Ra7 26. e6 f6 $16 { It is incredibly uncomfortable to play in this position as Black. } { [%csl Ge6,Rg6,Rc6,Ra7][%cal Rg4f3,Ba3a4,Bh2h4] }) (25... Rd5? 26. Bf3! $18 { The rook just gets kicked back. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rf3d5] }) 26. a4!? { Before capturing the exchange, Reshevsky tries to undermine Black’s queenside. } (26. Bxe6 { Could also have been played, but Black remains solid. } 26... fxe6 { [%csl Yf5,Yd5][%cal Be7f5,Be7d5,Bc6e7,Ye6d5,Ye6f5] } 27. Rg3 Ne7 { Now an outpost has been prepared for the knight on d5, or even going to f5 is playable. } { [%cal Be7f5,Be7d5] } 28. Rf1 Nd5 $10 { Black remains firm, with perfect play it should be a draw. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Bg6d3] }) (26. Bf3 Ne7! { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge7d5] }) (26. h4!?) 26... Ne7! { Petrosian ignores it and carries on with his plan. } { [%cal Be7d5] } 27. Bxe6 fxe6 { The d5 square is now completely under control, White can never get a d5 pawn push here. } { [%cal Be7d5,Ye6d5] } 28. Qf1 Nd5 29. Rf3 Bd3 { Now compare this to the position at the start! Black has sacrificed the exchange to stop the e and d pawn's advance, but this was done with a few other key points in mind: Reshevsky had to give up his best minor piece and can now forget about any central breakthrough. And now Petrosian's knight is insanely well placed on the d5-outpost, tying White’s pieces to defending c3. Plus, Black’s bishop is dominating the light squares. } { [%csl Gd5,Gd3,Ge6,Rb2,Rc3] } 30. Rxd3! { Counter-sacrificing the exchange! Because the LSB was so incredibly strong on d3, Reshevsky has to get rid off. } (30. Qf2? b4 { [%csl Ra4][%cal Be8a4] } 31. cxb4 axb4 { Because of Black's two passed pawns, Black is actually winning here. The a pawn can easily be won. } { [%csl Gb4,Gc4,Ra4] }) 30... cxd3 31. Qxd3 b4 32. cxb4 axb4 $10 { The position is now completely equal! Reshevsky does have an extra d-pawn, but it won't be able to advance due to Petrosian's knight. The passed a and b pawns won't be able to promote either; they can always be stopped in time. The game continued for a few moves, but then both players agreed to a peaceful draw. } { [%csl Ra4,Rb4][%cal Bd8a8] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📘 Crippling Sacrifice | Example"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Pentala Harikrishna"]
[Black "Hikaru Nakamura"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2763"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2787"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📘 Crippling Sacrifice | Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/KcapWuaz"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppppnppp/1b3n2/3P4/8/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 3 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ A crippling sacrifice is when you give up a pawn or piece to severely weaken your opponent's position. This can limit their mobility, weaken their pawn structure, or let you gain control over crucial squares. This type of sacrifice can cause your opponent to have a hard time developing their pieces and disrupt their plans. Here's an example from a game between GM Pentala Harikrishna and World no. 2, Hikaru Nakamura. }
10. d6! { A crippling sacrifice! Harikrishna sacrifices a full pawn, but if Nakamura takes it, he ruins his pawn structure. } 10... cxd6 $16 { Now suddenly, Nakamura has isolated d-pawns, disrupting the light-squared bishop's development. So sometimes you have to be willing to part with some material, easy and fast development is definitely worth more than a pawn. Stockfish gives White a +1.1 advantage here. This concludes the sacrifice, but let me show you the rest of the game because it was kinda cool. } { [%csl Rd6,Rd7,Rc8] } (10... Ng6 11. Nc3 c6 $16) 11. Bg5! { Harikrishna threatens to take the knight on f6, which would really ruin Hikaru's pawn structure and expose his king. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Rg5f6] } 11... Ng6 { Getting ready to recapture with the queen. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Gd8f6] } (11... Ned5 12. c4 Nc7 13. Nc3 { [%csl Rb6,Rc7,Rc8,Rd6,Rd7] }) 12. Nc3! { Continuing development. Note: White should definitely not have taken f6, since that would activate Black's queen and doesn't help White whatsoever. Harikrishna simply maintains the pressure with the pin. } { [%csl Gg5,Gc3,Gd3,Gf3] } (12. Bxf6? Qxf6 { The queen is now active. } { [%csl Gf6] } 13. Nc3 { We now have a very similar position to the game (only difference is the moved h pawn), but now it's Black's turn. } 13... Ne7 { Stopping Nd5. To be clear, White's still a bit better here, but playing 12. Nc3 would have been quite a bit better. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Re7d5] }) 12... h6 { [%cal Rh6g5] } 13. Bxf6! { "But you just said don't take it?!" Yeah, but that was a move ago. Now the bishop faces a choice: take on f6 or passively retreat back to c1. And more importantly, White's c3 knight is now developed, ready to hop into the center on the next move. } { [%cal Bc3d5] } 13... Qxf6 14. Nd5! { Activating the knight. } { [%csl Gd5] } 14... Qd8 (14... Qxb2 15. Bxg6 fxg6 16. Qd3 { White's down 2 pawns, but has a really active pieces. } { [%csl Gd3,Gd5,Gf3,Rg8,Rg6,Rd6,Rd7,Rc8,Rb6,Rb2][%cal Be1e7,Ba1e1,Yd5e7,Yf3g5] }) 15. Bxg6! { Weakening Black's pawn structure further. } 15... fxg6 16. Qd3 { Now look at the position; Black has two sets of doubled pawns, every piece except the DSB is on the backrank, the DSB is pretty useless on b6, and Black has a hard time developing. } { [%csl Rg6,Rd6,Rd7,Rc8,Rb6,Rd8,Rg8,Rf8,Ra8,Gf3,Gd5,Gd3][%cal Rd3g6,Ba1e1,Be1e7] } 16... Qe8? { Kinda ends it already, Hikaru is like provoking Re1, which just gains tempo and controls the e-file. } 17. Rae1 Qf7 { Now we get a really cool sequence. } 18. Ne7+ { Controlling the g8 square. } { [%csl Rg8][%cal Re7g8] } 18... Kh7 19. Ng5+!! { Wow, so beautiful! Opening up the h-file. Hikaru resigned here, because it's forced mate, I'll just show it. } 19... hxg5 (19... Kh8 { The long, less, beautiful mate. } 20. Nxf7+ Rxf7 21. Nxg6+ Kh7 22. Nf8+ Kg8 23. Qh7+ Kxf8 24. Qh8#) 20. Qh3#! { An Anastasia's Mate! Isn't this such a satisfying sight? All this resulted from the 10. d6 sacrifice. A crippling sacrifice can benefit your position quite a lot! } { [%csl Gh8,Gh7,Gh6,Rg7,Rg6,Rg5,Yg8,Rd7,Rd6][%cal Gh3h8,Be7g8] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📙 Exchange Sac for a long-term edge | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Octavio Troianescu"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "IM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📙 Exchange Sac for a long-term edge | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/fp6GCX1y"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "3r2k1/1q3pb1/2bpp1pp/pp6/2r1PP2/P1P1N1P1/1P1RQ1BP/4R1K1 b - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Another common sacrifice is the exchange sacrifice. It involves giving up a rook for a minor piece (bishop or knight). While it may seem like a material loss, the exchange sacrifice often leads to significant positional advantages that will benefit you in the long term. This could be things like better piece activity, control over crucial squares, superior pawn structure, or the bishop pair, etc. Let’s check out this example from a game between IM Octavio Troianescu and GM Tigran Petrosian. So in this position, Petrosian's rook is under attack, he can save it by moving it to a4 or c5, but instead he finds something much better: } { [%csl Re4,Yc4,Gc6,Gb7][%cal Ye3c4] }
25... Rxe4!! { Petrosian sacrifices the exchange for a pawn! We'll see why on the next move. } (25... Rc5 { Was possible too, but leads to a position were nobody really makes any progress. } 26. Nc2 h5 27. Red1 $10) 26. Bxe4 Bxe4 $15 { Petrosian is down a point in material, but in return, he now has the bishop pair and a better pawn structure. With the fianchettoed light-squared bishop on g2 gone, White's light squares are much weaker, leaving the king more vulnerable, which Black's bishop can exploit. Notice: in these types of positions, a bishop is much stronger than a rook. The rooks are just stuck behind the pawns, but Black's light-squared bishop is dominating so many squares with nobody to challenge him. With this small advantage, Petrosian went on to squeeze out a win. Check out the full game here: https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1106236 } { [%csl Gb7,Ge4,Gg7,Ga5,Rd2,Re1,Rh1,Rg2][%cal Ye4h1,Ye4b1] } *


