{ Here's another example from a game between two GM's; Curt Hansen vs Jonny Hector. This theme gets seen quite frequently in openings such as the Sicilian and the English. }
15. Rxc6! bxc6 { The defender of e5 has been removed, so White can take it now. } { [%csl Re5] } 16. Nxe5 $16 { Now suddenly, Black's pawn structure is ruined, with isolated a and c pawns. The c6 pawn is set to be lost, while White's bishops completely dominate the diagonals. Check out the full game here: https://lichess.org/S1PM94Ca#23 } { [%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rc7,Gg2,Gb2,Ge5] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📒 Positional Desperado | Example"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp3ppp/2pnpn2/2Pp1b2/3P4/1N1BPNP1/PP3PP1/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📒 Positional Desperado | Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/MjJjJhTG"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp3ppp/2pnpn2/2Pp1b2/3P4/1N1BPNP1/PP3PP1/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the "Tactical Desperado" chapter, I mentioned that there's also a positional type of desperado. In this position, White is attacking the knight on d6, while Black is targeting the bishop on d3. If White tries to save the bishop by moving it to e2 or c2, Black can save the knight and place it on a strong outpost like e4 or c4. If White captures with Bxf5, Black recaptures with the knight. There's only one move that gains a significant advantage for White: } { [%cal Rc5d6,Rf5d3] }
1. Ba6! { Since it was going to get captured anyway, White might as well use it to ruin Black's pawn structure! } (1. Bxf5? Nxf5) (1. Be2 Nde4) 1... bxa6 2. cxd6 { Now suddenly, Black has doubled a-pawns and a weak backward c-pawn. So, if one of your pieces is about to get captured, check if you can force your opponent to capture in a way that disadvantages him. Stockfish gives White a +2.3 advantage. } { [%csl Ra6,Ra7,Rc6][%cal Bf3e5,Bb3a5,Bb3c5] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Sac pawns to open files | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Yue Wang"]
[Black "Ivan Cheparinov"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2703"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2670"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Sac pawns to open files | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/bNcLMquw"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1pp3bp/p2p2p1/2nPpp1n/2P1P3/2N1BP2/PPBQ2PP/1K1R2NR b - - 5 12"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Sometimes, giving up a pawn can be the key to unlocking a powerful attack. By sacrificing a pawn to open up files, you can create open lines for your rooks, activate your pieces, and put serious pressure on your opponent. Here's one of the countless examples that use this idea. This position is from a game between two very strong GMs: Yue Wang vs. Ivan Cheparinov. Both players' kings are castled on opposite sides of the board, meaning they will be attacking on opposite sides. Black wants to attack the queenside, but right now, there isn't much going on there yet, so to get an attack going, he plays: }
12... b5! { Sacrificing a pawn in order to open up the queenside! } 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Ba6 { Activating the bishop too. } { [%csl Ga6] } 15. Nc3 Qb8 $40 { Now that the b and a pawns are gone, the files are opened up. This creates opportunities for a long-term attack. Is Black better here? Not quite—White still retains their initial advantage. However, Black's pieces are now more active, and White will have a harder time defending in the long run. Check out the full game here if you want (it's really cool): https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1480587 } { [%csl Gb8,Ga8][%cal Gb8b1,Ga8a1] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📗 Sac pawns to open files | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense: Lion Variation, Shirov Gambit"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Sac pawns to open files | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/vQ5v3rWz"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here's a position from the Philidor Defense: Lion Variation. So Black scores really well with this opening, having a winrate of 50%. But here's an interesting variation that's really successful which uses the idea we have just discussed. }
5. g4! { Sacrificing a full pawn! This variation is called the Shirov Gambit, named after GM Alexei Shirov. Immediately, the win rate for White goes up to 54%. Is this the absolute top-engine move? No (but still the engine likes it tho). But it makes things very tricky for Black. Castling kingside, which Black was planning via Be7 and O-O, suddenly starts to get dangerous. With this gambit, White gains the open g-file for the rook early on and in the near future White can potentially launch a kingside attack. Black must be very precise to navigate the complications and avoid falling into a worse position. } { [%cal Bg4g5] } 5... Nxg4 { If Black decides to not take it, his knight will get kicked with g5. } (5... Be7?! 6. Rg1 O-O 7. g5 Ne8 8. h4 $16 { It's already looking scary for Black. } { [%csl Gh4,Gg5,Rg8,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Rd7,Re7,Rc8] }) 6. Rg1! { Sliding the rook over with tempo. The rook now aims at the kingside. } 6... Ngf6 (6... h5 7. h3 Ngf6) 7. Bc4 $14 { Next up is Be3-Qd2 followed by long castling. White then just focuses on a kingside attack. The open file now benefits White in the long term. The g-pawn sacrifice is a very common theme, especially effective if your opponent has already castled kingside but you haven't yet. There's also a lot of potential in sacrificing the h-pawn against a short-castled king. Don't be afraid to give up a pawn if it opens lines and creates attacking chances! } { [%csl Gc4,Gc3,Gf3,Gg1][%cal Bc1e3,Bd1d2,Be1c1] } *


