[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📗 Pawn Breakthrough | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/1ZKhj480"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/5ppp/8/5PPP/8/2k5/8/K7 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here's another position I set up quickly. There's only one winning move here: }
1. g6! { Not a sacrifice, but we're still breaking through to reach the backrank. } 1... hxg6 { We have to get the h-pawn to advance without getting disturbed. There's only one move that does that. } { [%cal Bh5h6,Bh6h7,Bh7h8] } (1... fxg6 { Here we just do the opposite. } 2. h6! { [%cal Bf5f6,Bf6f7,Bf7f8,Rg7f6] } 2... gxh6 3. f6 { [%cal Bf6f7,Bf7f8] }) 2. f6! { Bringing the g-pawn to f6 so our h-pawn can advance without getting captured. } { [%cal Rg7h6] } 2... gxf6 3. h6 { White will promote and will have no trouble winning the game. } { [%cal Bh6h7,Bh7h8] } *


[Event "Grand Chess Tour Cote d’Ivoire (Rapid & Blitz)"]
[Date "2019"]
[Round "04"]
[White "Hikaru Nakamura"]
[Black "Veselin Topalov"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📕  Simplification Sacrifice | Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/NZMfp0Hp"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "8/6pk/5pb1/6Rp/P2B4/4PPK1/1P1r2P1/8 w - - 0 39"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A simplification sacrifice occurs when you give up material to reduce the game's complexity. This tactic aims to guide towards a better endgame, neutralize potential counterplay, or transform a challenging situation into a clear path to victory. By sacrificing material, the goal is to exchange pieces and simplify the board, thereby mking it easier to capitalize on your advantage and secure a win. Let's explore a position from a game between two super-GMs you've probably heard of: current world No. 2 GM Hikaru Nakamura and former World Champion GM Veselin Topalov. Here Nakamura has a winning endgame, but Topalov's bishop is quite annoying because it can later potentially be stop the advancing pawns. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Ba4a5,Bb2b4] }
39. Rxg6! { Hikaru simply gets rid of the bishop! It actually wouldn't have mattered if the g5 rook was a queen, it's a winning endgame anyway! } 39... Kxg6 { Now the annoying bishop is off the board, Nakamura can start advancing those pawns so they'll promote. } { [%cal Ba4a5,Ba5a6,Ba6a7,Ba7a8] } 40. a5 Rd1 { Trying to stop it, but it's really too late. } { [%cal Rd1a1,Ra1a5] } 41. a6 Ra1 42. a7 { [%cal Gd4a7] } 42... Kf7 43. b4 { Now the next pawn advances, the rook can't stop both. } 43... Ra2 44. b5 { Here GM Veselin Topalov resigned, because the b-pawn will advance to b7 and then either the b or a pawn will become a queen. } { [%csl Ra2][%cal Bb5b6,Bb6b7,Ba7a8] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📘 Swindle Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Larry Melvyn Evans"]
[Black "Samuel Reshevsky"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📘 Swindle Sacrifice | Example #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/WxzS20Uj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2Q5/5Rpk/8/1p2p2p/1P2Pn1P/5Pq1/4r3/7K w - - 0 49"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ The "swindle sacrifice" is when a player in a losing position sacrifices material to create a tactical trap, hoping the opponent will make a mistake. This tactic relies on deception and unexpected moves to turn the game around or at least draw from a losing position. This is an example from a game between 2 legendary grandmasters; Larry Evans and Samuel Reshevsky. Reshevsky has just played Qxg3 taking a free pawn. It now looks hopeless for Evans, since there's literally 4 different mate-in-one's here, which White doesn't seem to have a defense for. Reshevsky was probably expecting Evans to resign right now, but...actually this is a forced draw! } { [%csl Rh2,Rg2,Re1][%cal Bg3g2,Bg3h2,Be2e1,Be2h2] }
49. Qg8+!! { All White's pawns and king couldn't move. Only the queen and rook could, so Evans gets rid of them! When the queen and rook are off the table, the position is a stalemate! } { [%csl Rb4,Re4,Rf3,Rh4,Rh1] } 49... Kxg8 { Black is forced to take, since moving the king to another square leads to checkmate. } (49... Kh6?? 50. Qh8+ Kg6 51. Qxg7#) (49... Kg6 50. Qxg7#) 50. Rxg7+!! { Now the queen's gone, it's time to get rid of the rook! } 50... Kxg7 { It doesn't matter if Black takes the rook with the king or queen, they both lead to stalemate! It's always good to look out for these things in your games, they happen surprisingly often. When you're in a position which is hopeless, you sometimes can still try to setup a trap like this. This can involve putting your king in the corner, making sure your pawns can't move and sometimes sacrificing some material. Example when you're down a full queen, sacrificing a rook really won't make a difference except higher the chances of your opponent blundering into a stalemate. } { [%csl Rf3,Rh4,Rb4,Re4] } (50... Kf8 { Doesn't matter. White keeps checking and gets a draw by perpetual check. } 51. Rf7+ Ke8 52. Re7+ Kd8 53. Rd7+ $10) *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!: 📘 Swindle Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Wang, William Huang"]
[Black "Liu, Austin"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "1554"]
[BlackElo "1594"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "📘 Swindle Sacrifice | Example #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/4KkOpcCU"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "4r3/1R2P2k/3p3b/p3p3/2B1Pn1q/P4P2/5QP1/5RK1 b - - 2 36"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]

{ Here's another example I found in a forum from a game between two amateurs rated under 1600. So White's up 4 points in material, has a 7th rank pawn, and has just played Qf2 to trade the queens. Pretty bad right? Well, guess what, it's a forced draw. Qf2 was a blunder because Black now has a miraculous save. You can't only get a draw by stalemate, it can also happen by threefold repetition, which we see in this game. }
36... Nh3+!! { Breaking open the kingside! White's forced to take, because otherwise Black would just take the queen on f2. } { [%cal Rh3g1] } 37. gxh3 Be3!! { Absolutely beautiful! Black uses the deflection sacrifice (which we've learned in chapter 3) to deflect the queen away from the g6 square, where then the Black queen can come. } { [%csl Rg1,Rf2,Gg3][%cal Re3g1,Bh4g3] } 38. Qxe3 { White is forced to take, because his queen is pinned, and not taking would lead to him losing the queen. } 38... Qg3+! { Now even tho White's up literally 10 points in material, it's a draw. All of White's pieces are too far away to stop the 3-fold repetition. } 39. Kh1 $7 Qxh3+ 40. Kg1 $7 Qg3+ { Now Black just keeps repeating. The king is forced to move back and forth. } 41. Kh1 $7 Qh3+ { It's a draw. Hats off to Austin Liu for pulling off this sequence, that save was pure beauty. } *


