{ Here's another cool example, from a game between Carl Pilnick and Samuel Reshevsky. Black was completely winning here, being 3 pawns up and having a safe king. His paws just had to advance to promote. But, on move 93 Reshevsky played g4??, simply advancing his pawns, but now the position is a draw because of Carl Pilnick's following amazing move! } { [%csl Gg4,Gh4,Gb7,Ga7] }
93. Qf2!! { White sacrifices the full queen! Black is forced to take it because otherwise he loses his own queen because of the pin. } { [%csl Ra7,Re3,Rh1][%cal Rf2a7] } 93... Qxf2 $10 { It's a stalemate, the king has no squares to move, and the a-pawn is blocked. This must have been incredibly painful for Samuel Reshevsky, since he fought for 93 moves to get a winning postition, but 1 mistake can make a huge difference. } { [%csl Rh1] } *


[Event "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Masterclass: 💀 Deflection sacrifice | Practice"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/VmzzZVqk/5YOvPSeu"]
[Date "2024.11.02"]
[White "Edwin Ziegler Adams"]
[Black "Carlos Torre Repetto"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1p1q1ppp/3p1b2/p2P4/3Q4/5N2/PP2RPPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sacrifice like a PRO! | Free Course!"]
[ChapterName "🧩 Epic Puzzle 🧩"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU/4g5QNhPt"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1p1q1ppp/3p1b2/p2P4/3Q4/5N2/PP2RPPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.11.02"]
[UTCTime "09:47:54"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Here's a fun (and rather extreme) exercise that will blow your mind. This is just one puzzle I wanted to include here, but you can find a few more in the blog linked in the pinned comment. I might also create a puzzle study in the future. This position is from a game played between Edwin Ziegler Adams vs. Carlos Torre Repetto titled "Please take my wife!" Based on what you've learned from the study, can you identify the winning move here? The first move might take some time to find, but once you've found it, the subsequent moves will be easier.

Interestingly, Stockfish doesn't yet recognize this position as a definitive win for White! }
1. Qg4!! { Brilliant! A deflection! White sacrifices a full queen! Black cannot take it because his queen has to keep defending the e8 rook. After 1...Qxg4 2. Rxe8+ Rxe8 3. Rxe8# White gets a backrank checkmate.
Now Black has to do something about his queen on d7 because it's currently attacked. } 1... Qb5 { Keeping the e8 rook defended. Note: Qd8 loses due to 2. Qxc8! Qxc8 3. Rxe8+ Qxe8 4. Rxe8#
Now, White must once again find another brilliant deflection sacrifice. It should be easier now that you understand the theme. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Gb5e8] } (1... Qxg4 2. Rxe8+ Rxe8 3. Rxe8#) 2. Qc4!! { The same tactic! White's queen can be captured twice, but none of them work because of Rxe8#!! The Black queen is again forced to move back to d7. } { [%csl Gc4,Re8][%cal Yc8c4,Bb5c4,Ge2e8] } 2... Qd7 { Again, Black's only move. By now, you probably know this queen is immortal and can continue dancing next to Black's pieces. :D } { [%cal Gd7e8] } (2... Qxc4 3. Rxe8+ Rxe8 4. Rxe8#) (2... Rxc4 3. Rxe8+ Qxe8 4. Rxe8#) 3. Qc7!! { Again, none of Black's pieces can capture the queen! } { [%cal Rd7c7,Rc8c7,Be2e8] } 3... Qb5 { White's goal now is to take away each square from Black's queen that defends the rook. Remember that each move must also gain tempo! } { [%csl Re2,Rd7,Rb5,Ra4,Rc6][%cal Bb5e2,Rc7d7,Rd5c6] } (3... Qa4 4. b3 Qb5 5. a4) 4. a4!! { The only winning move! The point of this move is that White kicks the queen away from the b5 square, where it's attacking our e2 rook. Black is forced to capture the a4 pawn, because there's no other square she can go that keeps the e8 rook protected.
You might have though of Qxb7??, but this move doesn't work yet because Black's queen isn't forced to capture it. Instead, Black can simply capture the e2 rook, leading to 4...Qxe2 5. Rxe2 Rc1+! 6. Ne1 Rxe1 7. Rxe1, resulting in checkmate. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Ra4b5] } (4. Qxb7?? Qxe2 5. Rxe2 Rc1+ 6. Ne1 Rxe1+ 7. Rxe1 Rxe1#) 4... Qxa4 { Finally, Stockfish now realizes this is winning for White. White now has to find the final key move. } 5. Re4!! $18 { Yes! Sacrificing the ROOOK! The a4 square is now also controlled by White. If Black were to take it with the e8 rook, he would leave his other rook hanging, and Qxe4 doesn't change anything after Rxe4. } { [%csl Ra4,Rd7,Rc6][%cal Re4a4,Re4e8] } (5. b3 Qb5 { Again the rook is under attack. } { [%csl Re2] }) 5... Qb5 { The only square left. } { [%csl Gb5,Ra4,Rc6,Rd7] } 6. Qxb7! $18 { Finally, every square from which the queen can defend the e8 rook is occupied. Regardless of Black's next move, White will win a rook and gain a significant material advantage.
A big congratulations if you found some of these moves, if not, don't worry at all! :D } { [%csl Rd7,Rc6,Rb5,Ra4,Rc8,Re8][%cal Bb7c8,Be4e8] } *


