3... dxe4 { Taking on e4 is Black’s main response here. We’ll simply recapture. } 4. Nxe4 { Now we have a strong knight sitting right in the center. Most of the time, Black will try to get rid of it immediately, either with 4...Nf6 (we’ll dive into that in the next section) or 4...Bf5?!, which isn’t the best response but—lucky for us—is one of the most popular! } { [%csl Ge4] } 4... Bf5?! { This move is mostly seen at the beginner and intermediate levels, but you’ll occasionally run into it against advanced players too. It gives us the chance to gain some immediate tempi by chasing the bishop around. Black will end up wasting several moves just trying to keep the bishop safe, while we calmly develop and grab space! We’ll explore 4...Bf5?! in the upcoming chapters marked 📘. } *


[Event "CRUSH the Caro-Kann!: 📘 5...Bg6: Common Traps"]
[Date "2024.12.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Caro-Kann!"]
[ChapterName "📘 5...Bg6: Common Traps"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/64DHMYix/f6w7rRKR"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/5b2/4N3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.12.02"]
[UTCTime "09:41:44"]

{ Now the following sequence of moves is very important! }
5. Ng3! { We start with 5. Ng3, bringing our knight to safety while forcing the bishop to move. At this point, Black has mainly two responses. The first is 5...Bg6, which is played a staggering 87% of the time. The other option is 5...Bg4, which is actually Black’s best move now. However, Black should have played it earlier; as it stands, Black will end up moving the bishop twice, wasting a move. } 5... Bg6 6. h4! { We follow up with another punch: 6. h5! This move threatens to trap Black's bishop, forcing Black to postpone development and find a way to save it. } { [%cal Rh4h5] } 6... h6 { The most popular move, creating an escape square for the bishop. Now, we don’t want to play 7. h5 immediately, as the h5 square might prove useful later on. Instead, we'll hit Black's bishop with our f3 knight. } { [%cal Bg6h7] } (6... h5 { Another popular option, blocking our h-pawn from advancing. We now just continue with our usual plan. } 7. Ne5! { Hitting the bishop, Black now has to protect it with his queen, otherwise we just play Qxh5. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Ge5g6] } 7... Qd6 { Preparing to recapture with the queen. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gd6g6] } 8. Nxg6 Qxg6 9. Be2! { This is another tricky move I highly recommend. By playing 9. Be2!, we add pressure on the h5 pawn. Black will now need to respond with 7...Nf6 to defend it. } { [%csl Rh5][%cal Rd1h5,Re2h5,Rg3h5] } 9... Nf6 { Now Black's queen is awkwardly placed and is almost getting trapped. } { [%csl Rg6] } (9... Qe6 { The best option, though rarely played, is pinning the bishop. We can now simply castle. } { [%csl Re2][%cal Re6e1] } 10. O-O g6 { [%cal Bf8g7] } 11. Re1 { Putting the rook on a more active square. } { [%csl Ge1] } 11... Qd7 12. d4 Nf6 13. c3 $16 { White has a nice edge of +1.3. } { [%csl Gg3,Gc3,Gd4,Gb2][%cal Gb2c3,Gc3d4,Be2c4,Bc1g5,Bd1b3] }) 10. d4! { Freeing our dark-squared-bishop. } { [%csl Gc1] } 10... e6 { Black tries to develop his bishop and castle soon. } { [%csl Gf8] } 11. Bg5! { This move further restricts the Black queen's mobility. We're also preparing to play Bd3, which we couldn’t do earlier because the queen could still escape to g4. } { [%csl Rg6,Gg5,Rg4][%cal Be2d3] } 11... Nbd7 { Any move other than 11...Qh7 will result in trapping the queen. } (11... Qh7 { The only way for Black to save the queen, but all of Black's pieces are now in poor positions. Meanwhile, we can easily develop our pieces and bring our king to safety. Although it might seem tempting to win a pawn with Bxc6, this move opens up files and gives Black chances for counterplay. Instead, simply castle kingside and focus on expanding on the queenside. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh7,Rh8,Rb8,Re8,Rf8,Ra8] } 12. O-O $18 { [%csl Rh7,Rh8,Rf6,Rf8,Rb8,Ra8,Gg1,Ge2,Gg3,Gg5][%cal Bc2c4,Ba2a4] }) 12. Bd3! { The queen is trapped! } { [%csl Rg7,Rf7,Rf6,Gh7,Gg6,Gf5,Ge4,Gd3,Yg5,Rh5][%cal Gd3h7,Yg5h6] }) 7. Ne5! { White once again gains tempo, we've now got a strong knight in the center of the board and Black must address the threat to the bishop. Ignoring it would result in losing the bishop pair, with doubled g-pawns and an isolated e-pawn—an absolutely dreadful position for Black. The best move here is 7...Qd6, but keep in mind that White is already better due to Black's poor choice of 4...Bf5?! I cover 7...Qd6 in the variation below. However, over 70% of the time, Black plays 7...Bh7. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd1,Rg6][%cal Re5g6] } 7... Bh7? { Black’s bishop has now moved for the third time. White can now execute a very strong sequence that often leads to an immediate win. } { [%csl Rh7] } (7... Qd6! { The surviving move, Black prepares to recapture the bishop with the queen, avoiding a ruined pawn structure. } { [%cal Bd6g6] } 8. Nxg6 { We can take the bishop now, though 8. d4 works perfectly fine too. } 8... Qxg6 { From here on, continue with standard developing plans. We maintain an advantage due to our easier development, the bishop pair, and the fact that Black’s queen is on a square where it can be easily attacked. } 9. d4 Nd7 10. c3 { Forming a pawn chain could be an idea, but standard developing moves like Bc4, Bd3, a4, and c4 also work well. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3,Gb2][%cal Gb2c3,Gc3d4] } 10... Qd6 11. Bc4 e6 12. Qf3 { Bringing the queen to a more active square, Black can’t attack it here, so it’s safe. } 12... Ngf6 13. Bf4 Qe7 14. O-O-O $16 { Castling queenside is usually preferable in these positions, given our extended h-pawn. White is in a strong position, with the bishop pair, full development, and all pieces well-placed. Stockfish evaluates White’s position with a +0.9 advantage. } { [%csl Gf4,Gf3,Gg3,Gc4,Gc1,Be1][%cal Bh1e1] }) 8. Qh5! { Throwing the next punch: Black is pretty much forced to play 8...g6 now, otherwise 9. Qxf7 would be checkmate. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rh5f7] } 8... g6 { Our queen is now under attack, but before we retreat it, let’s develop another piece: } { [%csl Rh5,Rh7][%cal Rg6h5] } (8... Qd5?? { It might look like Black's covering f7 now, but we have a simple response: } { [%csl Bf7][%cal Bd5f7] } 9. Bc4! { Piercing right through the queen and aiming at f7. } { [%csl Yd5,Yf7][%cal Rc4f7] } 9... g6 { Counterattacking. } 10. Bxd5 gxh5 11. Bxf7+ Kd8 12. Bxh5 { 13. Nf7, winning the trapped h8 rook, is unstoppable. Stockfish gives an evaluation of +5.4. } { [%csl Rh7,Rg8,Rf8,Gf7,Yh8,Yd8][%cal Ge5f7,Yf7d8,Yf7h8] }) 9. Bc4! { Threatening checkmate again! Our bishop is now developed and we're gaining tempo. 16% of players actually takes the queen, but then 10. Bxf7 is of course checkmate. :) } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rc4f7,Ye5d7,Ye5f7] } 9... e6 { Forced. } 10. Qe2! { Another important move! This seemingly innocent move actually has a really deadly threat that around 90% of your opponents are likely to fall for. At this point, all natural-looking responses will fail due to the same sequence... } 10... Bg7?? { The most popular move (though the next two most popular moves also fall victim to the same trap). Black is unaware of our deadly threat and simply tries to develop. } (10... Nf6?? 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Kg7 13. Qf7# { [%csl Gg7,Rh8,Rh7,Rh6,Rg6,Rf6,Rf8,Gg8,Yf7][%cal Gf7g7,Gf7g8,Yc4f7] }) (10... Nd7?? 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Kg7 13. Qf7# { [%csl Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh6,Rh7,Rg6,Yf7,Gg7,Gf6][%cal Gf7g7,Gf7f6,Yc4f7] }) (10... Bd6?? 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Kg7 13. Qf7# { [%csl Gg7,Gf8,Yf7,Rh7,Rh8,Rg8,Rg6,Rh6,Gf6][%cal Gf7g7,Gf7f8,Yc4f7,Gf7f6] }) (10... Ne7?? 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Ke8 13. Qf7+ { This one's a bit different. } 13... Kd7 14. Qe6+ Ke8 15. Ne4! { There's threats all over the place. } { [%cal Re4d6,Re4f6] } 15... Qc7 16. Nd6+ Kd8 17. Nf7+ Ke8 18. Nxh8 $18) (10... Qe7! { The only surviving move. } 11. Ne4! $16 { We have a very flexible position here. Possible plans include d4, followed by Bd2 and long castling. The rook on h1 can also potentially be activated via Rh3 to Rf3, for example. Black faces significant difficulty in development. Stockfish evaluates this position with a solid +1.6 for White. } { [%csl Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh7,Rb8,Ra8,Re7,Re8][%cal Bd2d4,Bh1h3,Bh3f3,Bc1d2] }) 11. Nxf7!! { The killer blow! The point of 10. Qe2! was to target the e6 square. We play the same thing if Black plays any other move that does not protect the f7 square. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Rf7d8,Rf7h8] } 11... Kxf7 { If Black doesn’t capture the knight, you can happily take one of the forked pieces. } 12. Qxe6+ Kf8 $7 13. Qf7# { Checkmate! 🎉 } { [%csl Yf7,Ge8,Gf8,Ge7,Rg7,Rg8][%cal Yc4f7,Gf7e8,Gf7f8,Gf7e7] } *


