5... Bg4 { As I mentioned in the previous chapter, Black had two main options: 5...Bg6 and 5...Bg4. In this chapter, we’ll explore the latter and see how to handle it. } 6. Bc4! { A flexible, multi-purpose move! We’re preparing to castle on the next move while also aiming at the vulnerable f7 square, setting up a sneaky trap. } { [%csl Bg1,Rf7][%cal Be1g1] } 6... Nf6?? { Black develops his knight. While it seems like a natural move, it’s actually a huge blunder because of the fancy next move we’re about to unleash! } (6... e6 { The best move } { [%csl Re6,Rf7] } 7. h3! { We force Black to trade their developed bishop for our knight. The bishop doesn't have any better squares to retreat to, so Black is left with no choice. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 $14 { From here on, it’s all about standard development. You can aim to form a strong pawn chain with c3 followed by d4, then castle kingside for safety. Also, consider gaining space on the queenside with moves like a4. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc4,Gg3][%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d4,Be1g1,Ba2a4] }) (6... Bxf3 { Nothing to worry about here—this move only benefits White. } 7. Qxf3 $16 { Now Black has just done us a favor by helping activate our queen, and he no longer has the bishop pair. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc4,Gc1] } 7... e6 $14 { Now we’ve reached a position similar to the one in the variation above. Stick with the same plans—continue with standard development, build your pawn chain, and castle kingside. You’ll maintain a solid edge of about +0.5. } { [%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Gc4,Gf3,Gg3,Gc1][%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d4,Be1g1,Ba2a4] } (7... Nf6?? { Here's another little side-trap to watch out for. } 8. Qb3! { Forking f7 and b7, there's no way for Black to save both. White ends up winning a nice amount of material. } { [%csl Rb7,Rf7][%cal Rb3b7,Rb3f7] })) (6... Nd7?? { A big blunder, it again ignores our threat. } 7. Bxf7+! Kxf7 8. Ng5+ { Freeing up the queen. } { [%csl Gf7,Bg4][%cal Gg5f7,Bd1g4] } 8... Ke8 9. Qxg4 $18 { White's now up a pawn and Black has lost his castling rights, and has an isolated e pawn. It's +3.3. } { [%csl Re7,Rf8,Re8,Rd8] }) (6... e5?? { Same thing as above. } 7. Bxf7+! Kxf7 8. Nxe5+ Ke8 9. Qxg4 $18) 7. Ne5!! { We sacrifice the queen! If Black takes it, 8. Bxf7 delivers a beautiful checkmate. Even if Black notices the trap and avoids it, they’re already in a significantly worse position because of the Nf6 blunder. } { [%csl Rd1,Yg4][%cal Rg4d1,Ye5g4,Bc4f7,Ye5f7] } 7... Be6 { The only surviving move, as Black had to save the hanging bishop. } (7... Bxd1 8. Bxf7# { Checkmate whilst being down a full queen! } { [%csl Ye8,Bd7,Bf7,Rf8,Rd8,Re7][%cal Be5f7,Be5d7,Yf7e8] }) (7... e6? 8. Nxg4 Nxg4 9. Qxg4 $18 { White ends up being up a full piece. You should have no trouble winning this game. } { [%csl Gg4] }) 8. Bxe6! { We can simply capture the bishop, and in doing so, Black’s pawn structure is completely ruined. } 8... fxe6 { [%csl Re6,Re7,Rf8] } 9. O-O $18 { White is in a great position here. Black's doubled isolated e-pawns are a major weakness, making their development much more difficult. The main plans for White now are to play c3 followed by d4, or d4 immediately if possible. After that, just continue applying pressure to Black's central pawns with moves like Re1. Stockfish gives an evaluation here of +1.8. Well, that's all the lines after 4...Bf5?! Let's move on to the next section where we’ll explore 4...Nf6. } { [%csl Re7,Re6,Rf8,Re8,Rb8][%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d4,Bf1e1] } *


