{ We won’t be trading knights, as that would benefit Black. If Black wants to exchange pieces, they’ll have to make the capture themselves. }
5. Qe2! { If Black captures, our queen becomes more active. Most players will go for 6. Nxe4; otherwise, we can capture the knight, and Black cannot recapture with the e-pawn due to the pin from our queen. This forces Black to take with the g-pawn, disrupting their plan to castle kingside—something most players will find uncomfortable. But before we go into that, let's look at some 5th move mistakes. } { [%cal Be2e4] } 5... e6?! { With the idea of recapturing on f6 with the queen to avoid doubled pawns, this isn’t ideal because Black plans to place their queen on a square where it can be easily attacked. } { [%cal Bd8f6] } (5... Nbd7?? { This has happened over 30,000 times on lichess! } 6. Nd6#! { A Smothered Mate! Black can't capture our knight because it's pinned by the queen. :) } { [%csl Re8][%cal Gd6e8,Ye2e8,Re7d6] }) (5... g6?? { Black prepares to fianchetto his DSB, but this is another big blunder, though it’s been played around 4000 times on Lichess, so you might encounter it in faster time controls. :D } { [%cal Bf8g7] } 6. Nxf6# { [%csl Bd7,Re8][%cal Re7f6,Ye2e8,Bf6d7,Bf6e8] }) 6. Nxf6+! { We can just capture it. } 6... Qxf6 { It's now placed pretty bad here. } { [%csl Rf6] } (6... gxf6 { Now Black has doubled f-pawns. Castling kingside becomes a lot more dangerous. } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Re6] } 7. g3 $16 { You can also play 7. d4, followed by Bd2 and castling queenside, but 7. g3 is a bit simpler and safer. Even though Black's open g-file for the rook might seem scary, there's really nothing to worry about—White's kingside structure is super solid. After you've castled kingside, you can focus on queenside expansion with moves like c3, b4, and h4, for example. Stockfish gives +0.9. } { [%csl Gf2,Gg3,Gh2][%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1,Gh2g3,Gf2g3,Rh8g8,Bc2c3,Bb2b4,Ba2a4,Ba4a5,Bd2d3] }) 7. d4! { We immediately want to free our dark-squared bishop so it can start attacking the queen. Also, note that 7. d4 is much better than 7. d3, as d3 would leave the b2 pawn undefended if the bishop moves from its home square. } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Bc1g5] } 7... h6 { The most popular move from Black, preventing us from putting a piece on g5. From here, it’s straightforward: just play Bd2 and castle queenside. After Black castles kingside, you can launch a pawnstorm with g4. We have a very flexible position, with Stockfish evaluating it at +1.2. } { [%csl Rg5] } 8. Bd2 $16 { The blue arrows mark some moves you can go for in the near future. } { [%cal Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Bf1g2,Bh1g1,Be1c1,Bc2c3,Bf3e5] } *


