[UTCTime "09:41:44"]

5. Qe2! { [%cal Be2e4] } 5... Nxe4 { As mentioned in the previous chapter, most players will choose to trade on e4. } 6. Qxe4 { We'll, of course, recapture. } 6... Nd7!? { The most popular move. This move might look weird, but there’s a solid plan behind it. The knight on b8 had no good squares to move to due to the pawn on c6 blocking its typical route. Now Black is rerouting the knight to f6, there it becomes much more active and useful. } { [%csl Gf6,Rb8][%cal Bb8d7,Bd7f6] } 7. Bc4! { We place the light-squared bishop on its most active square and now we can potentially castle kingside. } { [%csl Bg1,Rf7][%cal Be1g1,Rc4f7] } 7... Nf6 { Black finishes rerouting his knight and now attacks our queen. We have a nice response. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Rf6e4] } (7... e6 { Here, castling kingside isn't ideal since we might prefer castling queenside and launching a pawn avalanche on the kingside. This approach gives us more attacking chances. } 8. d4! { We occupy the center and free up the DSB. } { [%csl Gc1,Gd4] } 8... Nf6 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Bg5 O-O 11. h4 $14 { Here we have lots of attacking chances, Black will have to defend very carefully. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1,Bc2c3,Bf3e5,Bg2g4] }) 8. Ne5! { Sacrificing the queen! If Black captures it, we deliver checkmate with Bxf7. The idea behind this in-between move is to develop our f3 knight for free and force Black into complications. With the forced move e6, Black’s light-squared bishop gets blocked, making their development a bit harder. } { [%csl Rd7,Gf7][%cal Re5f7,Re5d7,Bc4f7] } (8. Qe2?! { Kinda misses an opportunity. } 8... Bf5 $10 { Black's LSB now gets developed, White could've stopped that. } { [%csl Gf5,Gf6] }) 8... e6 { Stopping checkmate. } (8... Nxe4?? { Played over 7,000 times on lichess. } 9. Bxf7#! { Checkmate! :D } { [%csl Ge8,Rd8,Rf8,Re7,Yf7,Yd7][%cal Gf7e8,Ye5d7,Ye5f7] }) (8... Nd5 { Also a possibility, although it only gets played 1% of the time. } 9. O-O $16 { Now White's got already his king castled to safety, LSB developed, knight in the center, queen on a flexible square. Black has all his pieces on the backrank except for his knight, which is pinned. Stockfish gives White an edge of +0.6. } { [%csl Ge5,Ge4,Gc4,Rd5,Gg1,Ra8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rh8] }) 9. Qe2 { Retreating to a safe square, keeping all the pieces protected. The queen is out of danger and can’t be harassed here. } { [%cal Ge2c4,Ge2e5] } 9... Bd6 { [%cal Be8g8] } (9... Be7 10. O-O! { Here we need to castle kingside, as d4 is no longer possible with Black's queen controlling the d4 square. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rd8d4] } 10... O-O $14 { White has several good options for continuation. The simplest approach might be to play 1. c3 followed by 2. d4, forming a solid pawn chain. With White's pieces more actively placed, while Black’s pieces are somewhat stuck, we hold a slight advantage. } { [%csl Rc8,Ge5,Gc4,Gg1,Re7][%cal Ba2a4,Bc2c3,Bd2d4,Bf1e1,Be1d1] }) (9... b5! { A good move, Black expands his queenside while gaining tempo by hitting our bishop. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Ba7a5,Ba5a4] } 10. Bd3! { The bishop is a bit better placed on d3 than on b3, where it would be chased away by a5-a4. The drawback is that it blocks the d4 pawn push, so we’ll need to find another way to develop the dark-squared bishop. Although, it's good to note that Bb3 is still a perfectly playable move, and perhaps even a better choice if you don't want to go into very complicated theory. } { [%csl Gd3,Rb3] } (10. Nxc6?? { Might be tempting, but fails. } { [%cal Rc6d8] } 10... Qc7 $17 { Now White has 2 pieces under attack, we can't save both. } { [%csl Rc6,Rc4][%cal Rc7c6,Rb5c4] }) (10. Bb3! { Also fine. I recommend lower rated players to go for this instead. } 10... Qc7 11. d4 { Now d4 works here. } 11... Bd6 12. O-O $10 { It's an equal position. Next up could be c3 to defend d4 and because we want to reroute the LSB to a more active diagonal. } { [%cal Bc2c3,Bb3c2,Bc1f4] }) 10... Qc7 { Putting a bit of pressure on our knight and protecting the c6 pawn. } { [%cal Rc7e5,Rc7c6] } 11. a4! { Before playing b3 to develop the DSB, we can play a4, countering Black's queenside expansion, also threatening an immediate axb5. There are too main moves here, b4 and Bd6, attacking our knight. } { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ra4b5,Bb2b3] } 11... b4? { Now we can just continue making our DSB active. } { [%cal Bb2b3,Bc1b2] } (11... Bd6 { Because we played a4 on the last move, we have a very nice fix. } { [%cal Rd6e5,Rc7e5] } 12. Nxc6! { Now if Black captures we win their queen with Bxb5, a skewer. } { [%cal Bd3b5,Rb5e8] } 12... b4 13. Nd4 $13 { It's a relatively equal game with perfect play, but both sides will have to still be extremely careful. } { [%cal Bb2b3,Bd4f5,Bf5d6,Bc1b2,Bd4b5,Be1g1] }) 12. b3 $16 { Next up is Bb2 followed by castling queenside, you'll have a great position. } { [%cal Bc1b2,Be1c1,Bf2f4] }) 10. d4 { We can now reinforce the knight on e5 while opening up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop to join the game. } { [%csl Gc1][%cal Yd4e5] } 10... O-O { Black castles his king, and White has a variety of strong options. Castling kingside is solid, and playing c3 to form a strong pawn chain works well too. However, in my opinion, the most aggressive and trickiest move for Black to handle is 11. Bg5!, putting immediate pressure on the pinned knight and preparing to castle queenside. } 11. Bg5! { The plan now is to castle queenside and launch a massive pawn storm on Black’s kingside. While technically equal with perfect play, it's incredibly challenging for Black to defend correctly. In fact, White has a 59% win rate from this position. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Be1c1,Bh2h4,Bg2g4] } 11... h6? { This is the most popular response from Black, aiming to get rid of our bishop. However, it's a mistake because it weakens Black's kingside. We have a really nice response: } 12. h4! { Going for the classic fishing-pole tactic! If Black captures the bishop, we gain a massive advantage as the h-file opens up for our rook on h1, opening up a powerful attack on Black's king. } 12... Be7 { The most popular move, Black unpins his queen. We can now simply finish our development by bringing the king to safety. } { [%csl Rf6,Re7,Gd8][%cal Be1c1] } (12... hxg5?? 13. hxg5 $18 { Next, we'll follow up with Qh5, aiming for Qh8#. Black can’t prevent this without losing a significant amount of material, and even then, they'll be left with a very weak king. Even with perfect play from Black, White stands at +3.2, but in most cases, Black gets checkmated quickly.. } { [%csl Rh8,Rf6][%cal Be2h5,Bh5h8,Rg5f6] }) (12... Qa5+! { The only move to survive. Black unpins his queen with check to gain tempo, allowing the knight to move freely. } { [%csl Ga5] } 13. Bd2! { It's important to play Bd2 instead of c3 here. If you play c3, Black can respond with Nd5, which opens up dangerous threats like Nxc3 followed by Qxc3+, winning a rook. } { [%csl Ra5][%cal Rd2a5] } (13. c3? { Loses the advantage. } 13... Nd5 $10 { The position is equal. Black manages to get enough counterplay before White can fully break through on the kingside. Both sides still have chances, but White’s aggressive plans have been neutralized for now. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rd5c3,Ra5c3] }) 13... Qb6 { Black attacks two of our pawns, here it's crucial to castle queenside. } { [%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Rb6b2,Rb6d4] } 14. O-O-O! { We now hold on to our b2 pawn. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gc1b2] } 14... Qxd4 { Black takes our d-pawn, but now we have a great tactical sequence that lets us win the material back. } 15. Nxf7! { Very important! You'll see why in a couple of moves. } 15... Rxf7 16. Be3! { Now the rook skewers both the queen and the bishop. Our next move is to force Black's queen away from protecting the bishop. } { [%csl Rd6,Rd4][%cal Rd1d6] } 16... Qe5 { The only move that keeps the bishop protected. We just continue chasing it away. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge5d6] } 17. f4! { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf4e5] } 17... Qa5 18. Rxd6 $16 { White has a nice edge here. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Bh1d1,Bg2g4,Bg4g5] }) (12... b5?! { No problem! We just move it back a square. } 13. Bd3 { Now Black has a weak c-pawn he has to protect. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Re5c6] } 13... Bb7 14. Rh3! $18 { With the idea of immediately bringing the rook into action! White has a massive attack here, it will be hard for Black to survive much longer. It's +2.0. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge5,Ge2][%cal Bh3g3,Rg5h6,Rg3g8,Be1c1] }) (12... c5?! 13. O-O-O $16 { [%csl Gc1,Gd1,Rg8,Rd8,Rf6][%cal Bg2g4,Yh1h3,Yh3g3,Rg5h6,Rg5f6] }) 13. O-O-O $18 { This is total domination. White will eventually break through on Black's kingside. Some general plans include playing g4 and retreating the bishop to d2, preparing g5 to completely bulldoze Black’s kingside. Even Bxh6 could be an option depending on the position. White has a 72% winrate here. I definitely recommend checking out a few games in these positions to get a better feel for attacking with opposite-side castling. } { [%csl Gc1][%cal Bg2g4,Bg5d2,Yg5h6,Bg4g5] } *


