6... Qd5!? { A solid move by Black, aiming for equality by trading queens. However, we prefer to avoid exchanges that could simplify the position, as that would likely lead to a dead equal game. We only consider trading queens if it benefits us in some way. Our goal is to maintain the pressure and fight for the advantage. } 7. Qh4! { We keep the queens on the board! There really isn't any better place for the queen to go than h4. } (7. Qxd5?! { Doesn't benefit us in any way. } 7... cxd5 $10 { It's pretty dead equal now, and Black even scores much better here. }) 7... Qe6+ { Black is persistent with the queen trade. With 10...Qe6+, the queen reroutes to g4. } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Bd5e6,Be6g4] } (7... Bf5?! { The most popular move, but this allows us to gain tempo by kicking Black's queen around. } 8. Bc4! { Developing with tempo. Surprisingly, the most popular move here from Black is a huge blunder! } { [%cal Rc4d5,Be1g1] } 8... Qe4+?? { Black forces a queen trade, but this fails due to our tactical resource! } { [%cal Re4e1,Re4h4] } (8... Qd6 9. d3 $14 { White has an edge of about 0.5 here, thanks to a more flexible position and better development. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc4,Rc6,Rf8][%cal Be1g1,Bc1f4,Ba2a4] }) 9. Qxe4 Bxe4 10. Bxf7+! { Bringing the king out! If Black doesn't take our bishop we just continue developing normally, we're happy with our free pawn. } { [%csl Yg5][%cal Bg5e4,Bg5f7,Yf3g5] } 10... Kxf7 11. Ng5+! { We win our piece back with this fork! } { [%csl Re4,Rf7][%cal Gg5e4,Gg5f7] } 11... Kg6 12. Nxe4 $18 { In the process, we've won a free pawn! Black ends up with a terrible position: a misplaced king, an isolated e-pawn, and undeveloped pieces. Stockfish evaluates this as +2. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Be1g1,Bd2d4,Bc2c3,Ba2a4,Ba4a5] }) 8. Be2 Qg4 { We have to accept the queen trade since our queen has no safe squares left, but we'll do it on our own terms, gaining an open h-file for our rook. } { [%cal Rg4h4,Rg4h5,Rg4h3,Rg4g3,Rg4g5,Yc8g4] } 9. Qg3! { We force Black to make the capture, and then we benefit from an open h-file for our rook. } { [%cal Bh2g3] } (9. Qxg4?! { Remember the 'TO TAKE IS A MISTAKE' rule: we want Black to be the one to capture, as taking would only benefit them. } 9... Bxg4 { Black now gets his bishop developed. } { [%csl Gg4] }) 9... Qxg3 (9... g6 { Since Black doesn’t agree to our terms, we both continue with development as usual. } 10. d4 Bg7 11. Be3 O-O 12. O-O-O $14 { [%csl Gc1,Ge3,Gf3][%cal Bh2g3] }) 10. hxg3 $14 { Next, we continue developing normally. Thanks to our open file, we have a slight edge. White scores 48% here compared to Black's 38%. } { [%csl Gh1][%cal Gh1h8,Bd2d4,Bc2c3,Ba2a4,Be1c1,Bc1f4] } *


