6... e6?! { This is the third most popular 6th move. Black plans to castle soon with Be7 followed by O-O, aiming for a quick and solid kingside setup. } { [%cal Bf8e7,Be8g8] } 7. d4 { We immediately take the center. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc1] } 7... Be7 { Now we have a nice response that halts Black's plan: } { [%cal Be8g8] } (7... Nd7 { We can just play the same as the mainline, we'll 90% of the time just transpose. } 8. Bd3 { [%cal Be1g1] } 8... Nf6 9. Qh4 Be7 10. O-O { We transpose to the mainline. } { [%csl Gg1,Gd3,Gf3][%cal Bh4g3,Bc2c3,Bf1e1] }) (7... Bd6 { This is pretty much the same thing as the Be7 line. } 8. Bd3 { We continue with our standard plan. } { [%cal Be1g1] } 8... Nd7 9. O-O Nf6 10. Qh4 $16 { It's a similar position, but keep in mind that after Black's Nd5, you'll need to play Bg5, as the queen can't be placed on g3 in this setup. Stockfish gives +1.0. } { [%csl Gd3,Gf3,Gh4,Rg3,Gd6][%cal Bc1g5] }) 8. Bd3! { We develop the bishop and prepare to castle kingside. With our battery now formed on the b1-h7 diagonal, Black is unable to castle without losing immediately to Qxh7 checkmate—surprisingly, this mistake has been played 19% of the time! :D } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Be1g1,Gd3h7] } 8... Nd7 { Black reroutes the knight to f6 to defend the h7 square, preparing to castle. } { [%csl Bf6,Gh7][%cal Bb8d7,Bd7f6,Yf6h7] } (8... O-O?? 9. Qxh7# { [%csl Gg8,Gh8,Rf7,Rf8,Rg7][%cal Gh7g8,Gh7h8,Bd3h7] }) (8... Bf6?! { Honestly, I’m not sure what the idea behind this move is, but it does get played about 10% of the time for some reason. } 9. O-O { We are the side whose attacking here, we're almost fully developed, and all Black's pieces are placed on the 8th rank except for the awkwardly placed bishop on f6 which is pretty useless there. } { [%csl Gg1,Ge4,Gd3,Gf3,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rh8,Rf6][%cal Bc2c3,Bf1e1,Be4g4,Ba2a4] }) 9. O-O { Bringing the king to safety with castling kingside. Note that the alternative Bd2 followed by O-O-O is also a solid plan, so choose whichever you're more comfortable with. } { [%csl Gg1] } (9. Bd2! { A perfectly fine alternative! White castles queenside and launches an attack on the kingsside with h4-g4. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Bh2h4,Bg2g4,Be1c1] } 9... Nf6 10. Qh4 O-O 11. O-O-O $16 { [%csl Gc1,Gd2,Gd3,Gf3,Gh4][%cal Bh2h4,Bg2g4,Yh4g3,Bh4h5] }) 9... Nf6 { Black protects the h7 square and forces our queen to move. } { [%csl Gh7,Re4][%cal Gf6h7,Rf6e4] } 10. Qh4 { Preparing to move to g6, where the queen will exert strong pressure on Black's kingside. } { [%cal Bh4g3] } 10... Nd5 { Black places his knight in the center and kicks our queen away with his bishop from e2. We don’t mind, as the queen is well-placed on g3. } (10... h6? { This move worsens Black's situation by weakening their kingside pawn structure. } { [%csl Rg7,Rh6] } 11. Qg3 { [%csl Rg7] } 11... Nh5?! { Black protects the g-pawn, but it fails due to White’s next move. } { [%csl Rg3,Rg7][%cal Rh5g3,Rh5g7] } (11... g5 12. c3 { Black has a tough time developing here. His kingside pawns are overextended, making castling kingside impossible. The position is +1.5 for White. } { [%csl Yd4,Yc3,Yb2,Rh6,Rg5,Re7,Rf6,Rd8,Rc8,Re8,Ra8,Gf3,Gg3,Gd3][%cal Yb2c3,Yc3d4,Bf3e5,Bf1e1,Ba2a4] }) 12. Qg4! { Keeping things simple! We attack the knight and continue to pressure the g7 pawn. Black can’t save both. } { [%csl Rh5,Rg7][%cal Rg4h5,Rg4g7] } 12... g6?? { A common attempt to save both, but it loses on the spot. } 13. Bxg6! Nf6 14. Bxf7+! { Bringing the king out. } 14... Kxf7 15. Ne5+! { [%csl Rf7][%cal Be5f7,Bg4g6] } 15... Kf8 16. Qg6 { Threatening checkmate and attacking the h6 pawn. } { [%csl Rf7,Rh6][%cal Rg6h6,Rg6f7,Bc1h6] } 16... Qe8 $7 17. Bxh6+ Rxh6 18. Qxh6+ Kg8 $18 { This is completely winning. The king is weak and Black's down material. } { [%csl Rg8,Gh6,Ge5][%cal Ba1e1,Be1e3,Be3g3] }) (10... O-O?! { Black castles, but this only seems to bring him closer to our attack. } 11. Bg5 { Bringing the next piece into action. We're already threatening Bxf6 followed by Qxh7#. } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gh4h7,Gd3h7,Rg5f6] } 11... g6 (11... h6 12. Bxh6! gxh6 13. Qxh6 $18 { There are too many attackers for Black to handle. At this point, resignation is a strong option. } { [%csl Rh7,Gh6,Gf3,Gd3,Rg8,Rd8,Rc8,Re7,Ra8,Rf6][%cal Bf3g5,Rd3h7,Yh6h7] }) 12. Ne5 $16 { We have a beautiful attacking position here. Black's pieces are cramped, defending with limited mobility. Stockfish says +1.9. } { [%csl Gg5,Ge5,Gh4,Rg8,Re7,Rd8,Rc8,Ra8,Rf8,Gd3][%cal Bc2c3,Bf2f4,Ba1d1] }) 11. Qg3 $16 { White has a strong and flexible attacking position here. Black's pieces are quite cramped, and the bishops are struggling to become active. The king isn’t exactly safe, and castling kingside will lead to danger. The knight on d5 isn't much of a threat either. } { [%csl Gg3,Rc8,Re7][%cal Bf3e5,Bc2c3,Bf1e1,Ba2a4] } *


