6... g6?! { Played 9% of the time, Black aims to quickly castle with Bg7 followed by O-O. However, we have a nice response here that gives Black difficulties: } { [%cal Bf8g7,Be8g8] } 7. Qe5! { Hitting the rook! Now Black is forced to respond with either f6 or Rg8, and neither of these moves are particularly comfortable for Black. } { [%csl Rh8][%cal Re5h8] } 7... f6 { Most players will opt for f6, trying to preserve the option of castling kingside. However, this weakens Black's pawn structure and creates significant light-square weaknesses. } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rg8] } (7... Rg8 { Now Black can no longer } 8. Bc4 Bg7 9. Qe2 $16 { Here we just continue with normal development. Note that if Black ever plays Bg4 (a common mistake), you can respond with Bxf7+! followed by Ng5, and then Qxg4 to win a pawn. } { [%csl Rg8,Re8][%cal Be1g1,Bd2d4,Bc2c3] }) 8. Qe3 { The queen can now retreat back again, staying flexible for future attacks . } 8... Bg7 { This move gets played almost every time, as Black is eager to castle kingside and bring the king to safety. However, White can now target the light square weaknesses created by f6. } { [%csl Rg8,Rf7][%cal Be8g8] } 9. Bc4! { White's bishop pierces right through Black's kingside! Once again, Black is forced to delay castling and must find a way to make it work. } { [%cal Gc4g8,Be1g1] } 9... Nd7 { With the idea of rerouting all the way to d5, Blocking our bishop. While Black's doing that, we can just continue development. } { [%cal Bb8d7,Bd7b6,Bb6d5] } (9... e5?! { The second most popular move, but it weakens Black's position significantly. } 10. d4! { Immediately, we put pressure on Black's pinned e-pawn, forcing him to make a defensive move. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rd4e5,Bf3e5,Ye3e5] } 10... Qe7 { Black defends his pawn. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e5] } (10... Nd7 { Another option, we just play something similar to the Qe7 line. } 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Bd2 { Getting ready to castle queenside. We can take d5 on the next move. } { [%cal Be1c1] } 12... Qe7 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 { Black takes with the queen to trade queens, but we don't mind because we have a much better endgame. } (13... fxe5 14. O-O-O $16 { We're again completely dominating. The e-pawn will definitely fall sooner or later. } { [%csl Gc1,Re5,Gc4,Re8,Rg7][%cal Bd2c3,Bh1e1] }) 14. O-O-O Qxe3 15. Bxe3 $18 { Even tho material is equal here, White is much much better because of our incredibly well placed pieces. It's +3.4. } { [%csl Gc4,Ge3,Gd1,Ra8,Rc8,Rg7,Rh8,Re8][%cal Bh1e1,Be3c5] }) 11. dxe5! { We can just take that pawn, opening up the d-file and leaving Black with a weak isolated e-pawn. } 11... fxe5 12. Bd2! { We want to immediately control the d-file by putting a rook d1, where it will be a total monster. } { [%cal Be1c1,Gd1d8] } 12... Bf5 { Black doesn't have any better options. } 13. O-O-O $16 { White has a completely dominating position here! Black's king is stuck in the center, unable to castle either side due to our active pieces. The weak e5 pawn is a prime target, and we're likely to win it soon, further improving our position. All of Black's pieces are passive, while we hold full control of the game. For the next few moves we have to focus on maximizing pressure on the center, we can do this with moves like Rhe1 and Bc3. } { [%csl Gc1,Gc4,Rg8,Rf7,Re5,Gd1][%cal Yc4f7,Yf7g8,Bh1e1,Bd2c3,Gd1d8] }) (9... b5 { We just retreat to b3, keeping the bishop on the strong diagonal. } 10. Bb3 a5 { Always answer a5 with a4! } 11. a4 b4 12. O-O $16 { We have a beautiful position. Our LSB is incredibly strong, so make sure not to trade that off. Black again has a much harder time developing. It's +1.7. } { [%csl Gf3,Ge3,Gb3,Rg8,Rf7,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rh8,Rg7][%cal Bd2d4,Bf1e1,Yb3g8] }) 10. d4 { Taking the center and giving our DSB some air. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc1] } 10... Nb6 { Black hits our bishop, and we need to move it. It's important to keep our light-squared bishop on the board for as long as possible because it’s one of our strongest pieces. } { [%cal Bb6d5,Rb6c4] } 11. Bb3 Nd5 { Black's knight now acts as a barrier. Black will castle on the next move. } { [%csl Gg8,Gf7,Gd5][%cal Be3e2,Rd5e3] } (11... a5 { After a5, always respond with a4 to block Black's pawn from advancing. } 12. a4 { [%csl Ra5,Ga4] } 12... Nd5 13. Qe2 O-O 14. O-O $16 { Now we have transposed into the main line, with the only difference being the two a-pawns. White's has a bit more comfortable position here. General plans include playing c3 or potentially c4 if the position allows (but usually that doesn't really work because Black could play Nb4 and we have no h-pawn to kick it away), and moving the light-squared bishop to b2, where it is often more active and can aim at the kingside. With the a-pawn advanced, another idea for the near future could be to play Ra3, then maneuver the rook along the 3rd rank to increase its activity. Stockfish gives White an edge of +0.7. } { [%csl Ge2,Gg1,Rg6,Rh7,Rf6,Gf3,Gb3][%cal Bb3c2,Bc2c3,Bc3c4,Ba1a3,Bf1e1,Ba3h3] }) 12. Qe2 O-O 13. O-O $16 { From here, we can just develop normally. A good idea would be to kick away Black's knight on d5 with c4 in the next move, if Black doesn't play a direct threat. If Black responds with Nb4, we can still push it away with h3, something that wasn't possible in the variation above. The overall plans remain similar to the a5 variation, with White looking to gain space and develop the pieces actively. Stockfish gives an evaluation of +0.7 because of our flexible position compared Black's. } { [%cal Ba2a3,Bc2c4,Bb3c2,Bf1e1,Bh2h3] } *


