5. Qe2 Bf5!? { An alternative to the usual 5...Nxe4 is 5...Nf6. This is much rarer because most players are uncomfortable with the kingside structure ruined after 6. Nxf6+, but the open g-file can be advantageous for Black’s rook, potentially becoming more active. Black typically aims to castle queenside in this line. } { [%cal Rg7f6] } 6. Nxf6+ { Trading the knights is indeed the best move here. If we retreat the knight to a different square, Black can capture the pawn on c2 with Bxc2, gaining material advantage. } 6... gxf6 { [%cal Bh8g8,Gg8g1] } 7. d3 { Now we go for a King's Indian-style setup. We begin with d3 to free up our dark-squared bishop, then follow up with g3 and Bg2, preparing to castle kingside. This setup is quite reliable and solid. If Black plays Bg4, respond with h3 and then g4 to kick the bishop away. } { [%csl Gd3] } 7... Nd7 { It doesn't really matter what Black does, we just play our setup. } 8. g3 (8. Bd2!? { You might have considered castling queenside (which is playable), but it often leads to relatively equal games. It's not the best option here because Black is likely to castle queenside as well. By castling kingside, we can use our queenside pawns to launch an attack on Black's king, creating more dynamic opportunities and a more challenging position for Black. } { [%cal Be1c1] }) 8... e6 9. Bg2 Bd6 10. O-O $16 { Even though it might seem scary to castle into the side where Black has an open g-file with a rook aiming at you, White is actually doing great here. Our kingside setup is incredibly solid, and Black won’t be able to break through. Next up just continue expanding on the queenside. White scores an amazing 55% winrate here. } { [%csl Gg1,Gg2,Gg3,Gh2,Gf2,Gf1,Gf3][%cal Ba2a4,Ba1b1,Bb2b4,Bd8c7,Be8c8,Bh8g8] } *


