{ The main move here is h3, but I recommend a line that's only played 5% of the time. It leads to some really fun and insane positions, and Black will have to be extra careful to avoid falling into tricky traps. }
5. d4! { Many players will think this is a mistake, believing they can now play 5...Bxf3. This forces White to either recapture with the queen, which would hang the d-pawn, or take with the g-pawn, resulting in isolated doubled f-pawns for White. However things aren't as simple as they seem! } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rg4f3] } 5... Bxf3?! { Many players will go for this. } 6. Qxf3! { We're going for this insane gambit! Black might win some material, but we'll gain significant compensation with superior piece activity and dynamic play. } { [%csl Rd4] } 6... Qxd4? { Lets first look at this move, it leads to the most insane lines, so be prepared! The queen is now centrally placed where it can be attacked, allowing us to develop our bishop with tempo. } { [%csl Rd4] } 7. Be3! { The b2 pawn is hanging now, but we don’t mind! Our focus is on using this gambit to generate dynamic piece activity and create chances for a strong attack. } { [%csl Rb2,Ge3] } 7... Qxb2 { Most players will just grab the b2 pawn, but here’s where Black gets a huge surprise: we’re going to sacrifice not just two pawns, but two full rooks! } (7... Qb4+? 8. c3! { We have to gain tempo. } 8... Qxb2 9. Rd1 $18 { From here on most of the time you just transpose to a variation below. } { [%cal Bf1c4,Bf3f4] }) 8. Bc4!! { If you’ve seen my “Sacrifice Like A PRO!” study, you might have seen this coming. We’re now sacrificing a ton of material, but once Black's queen has gone on her shopping spree, it will be far from any defense, and it’s our turn to deliver the knockout punches. } { [%csl Ra1,Rh1,Gf3,Ge4,Gc4,Ge3] } 8... Qxa1+?? { Black isn’t forced to accept our sacrifice, and we’ll explore those variations below. However, Black gets a bit too greedy here. Let’s see how it plays out. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3f7] } (8... Nf6 { This is the best move. Black stops us from capturing the f7 pawn. Now our rook is hanging, so we need to protect it immediately before continuing to attack. } { [%csl Gf6] } 9. O-O! { We get our king out of the center and protect the a1 rook. } { [%csl Ga1,Gg1,Gf1] } 9... Qxc2?? { This is another game-losing blunder! Black got too greedy, and we're about to punish them for it right away! } (9... Nbd7 { The most safe move, Black simply tries to get another piece active. But White still has the advantage because of Black's earlier mistakes. } 10. Rab1 { We can kick the queen away, and now we control the b-file. The rook can potentially move to the 7th rank in the near future } { [%csl Gb1,Rb7][%cal Bb1b7] } 10... Qxc2 { [%cal Rc2e4] } (10... Qe5 11. Ng5 e6 12. Rxb7 $16 { [%csl Gg5,Gf3,Ge3,Gc4,Gb7,Re8,Rf8,Rd7,Rf6,Re5,Ra8][%cal Be3f4,Bf1d1] }) 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. Rfc1 Qe4 13. Qg3 $16 { Black may be up 3 pawns for the moment, but with almost no development and weak queenside pawns, we’ll surely win those back soon. White has a +0.8 advantage here, but Black is walking on thin ice—one wrong move could lead to an immediate collapse. Note: Be careful of backrank checkmates after 13...Rd8! } { [%csl Rb7,Re8,Rf8,Rh8,Ra8,Gc4,Ge3,Ra7][%cal Bg3c7,Bb1b7] }) 10. Qf5! { We're winning the queen by force! With Qf5, we threaten checkmate with Qc8. Plus, the queens are now aligned, so we're also threatening Nxf6+. After that, we’ll capture Black’s queen. } { [%csl Rc8,Rc2][%cal Rf5c8,Rf5c2,Ge4d6,Ge4f6] } 10... e6 { Black stops checkmate, now we have the check. } (10... Kd8 { Black may have stopped checkmate and blocked any knight checks—nice try, but it loses as well! } 11. Rad1+ { Or Rfd1+, doesn't matter. We simply bring another piece into the game. } { [%cal Gd1d8] } 11... Nbd7 12. Bxf7! { The simplest move! We eliminate the f-pawn, clearing the way for Be6, which overloads the d7 knight. Plus, the bishop takes control of the e8 square, preparing for Qa5—a deadly check. } { [%csl Rd7,Rd8,Re8][%cal Gf5d7,Gd1d7,Bf7e6,Rf7e8,Bf5a5] } 12... b6 { Black controls the a5 square. } { [%cal Rb6a5] } (12... Qxe4 { Doesn't actually win material, due to our tactical resource. } 13. Rxd7+ { Black's knight is overloaded. } { [%csl Rd7,Re4] } 13... Kc8 (13... Nxd7 14. Qxe4 $18) 14. Qxe4 Nxe4 15. Be6 $18 { After Rfd1, Black can't prevent us from overwhelming their king. Checkmate is just around the corner! } { [%cal Bf1d1,Bd7d8] }) 13. Rxd7+ Nxd7 14. Bb3 $18 { It’s over. We’ll play Rd1 on the next move, and Black won’t be able to handle all the threats coming their way. } { [%csl Rd8,Rd7][%cal Bf1d1,Bd1d8,Yf5d7] }) 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Qxc2 $18 { With a 6 point material advantage, you should have no trouble winning here. :) }) (8... Qb4+ { Another popular try. We now have to play Nd2, otherwise the c4 bishop is hanging. } { [%csl Gc4] } 9. Nd2 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gd2c4] } 9... Nf6 { Black deals with our Qxf7+ threat. } 10. Rb1 $16 { On the next move, our rook will capture on b7, where it will become a major nuisance for Black on the 7th rank. } { [%csl Ge3,Gc4,Gd2,Gb1,Rb7,Gf3,Re8,Rf8][%cal Be1g1] }) (8... e6 9. O-O $18 { is completely developed. None of Black's pieces have even left the homerank. It's +3 for White. } { [%csl Gc4,Ge3,Gf3,Ge4,Ra8,Rb8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rb2][%cal Bf1d1,Ba1b1,Bb1b7] }) 9. Ke2! { Grabbing the rook was a game-ending blunder! White now has two powerful threats: capturing the f7 pawn with the queen and taking Black's queen with the rook. Black can't escape now! } { [%csl Ra1,Rf7][%cal Gh1a1,Gf3f7] } 9... Qxh1 { Now Black has made four consecutive captures, gaining a massive 12 points in material. But now it’s finally our turn to throw the punches! } (9... Qf6 { The only move that doesn't lead to an immediate checkmate. } 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Rb1! $18 { With Rb1 we really maximize the pressure, now Black's has lots of weaknesses on his queenside, and the pieces are stuck. Black might still be up a point in material, but none of their pieces are doing anything! Thanks to White’s incredibly active pieces, White is in a much better position here. } { [%csl Gc4,Gf3,Rb7,Ra7,Ra8,Rb8,Rc6,Re8,Ge3] }) (9... Qe5 10. Qxf7+ Kd8 11. Qxf8+ Kc7 12. Bf4 { Checkmate will come very soon. }) 10. Qxf7+! { Now Black has literally no pieces left to defend! There's no escaping our checkmate. } { [%csl Rh1,Ra8,Rb8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Rf7e8] } 10... Kd8 11. Qxf8+ Kc7 (11... Kd7 12. Nc5+ { We just keep throwing checks. } 12... Kd6 13. Qd8+ Ke5 14. Qd4+ Kf5 15. Bd3# { [%csl Bg6,Bf5,Yh4,Yg4,Ye4,Yf6,Ye5,Ge6,Rh6,Rg5,Rf4][%cal Bd3g6,Yd4h4,Yd4f6,Gc5e6,Re3h6] }) 12. Bf4+! { Taking away the c7 square. The pieces have to work together. } { [%csl Rc8,Rd8,Yc7][%cal Rf8c8,Yf4c7] } 12... Kb6 (12... Kd7 13. Nc5# { [%csl Gd7,Re7,Yc8,Yd8,Ye8,Bc7,Bd6,Be6][%cal Gc5d7,Yf8c8,Bf4c7,Bc4e6] }) 13. Qd8# { Checkmate! } { [%csl Ra7,Rb7,Rc6,Gc7,Ya6,Yb5,Gb6,Ga5,Bc5][%cal Gd8b6,Yc4a6,Gb6a5,Be4c5] } *


