6... Nf6?! { Black decides not to grab the "free" pawn, sensing the danger of bringing out the queen (which, as we saw in the previous chapter, was indeed risky). Instead, Black opts for a sort of Tartakower-style setup. However, this isn’t ideal because White's queen is already developed. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Be7f6,Bf8d6,Be8g8] } 7. Nxf6+! { We’re going for a straightforward plan: castle long and launch the kingside pawns toward Black’s king. } 7... exf6 (7... gxf6 { This is another option, though rarely played. Going for the Be3 and long castling plan is still fine, but it's not as effective since Black isn't planning to castle kingside, which means we won’t be able to launch a pawn storm on their king. Here I recommend a much trickier move: } { [%cal Bh8g8] } 8. Bc4! { We target the f7 pawn and set up some traps that Black is likely to fall for. } { [%csl Rf7,Gc4][%cal Bf3b3,Rb3f7] } 8... Qxd4?! { Black gets greedy, we now have a nice fork: } (8... e6 9. Be3 $16 { White is better here due to the lead in development and the strong bishop pair. } { [%cal Be1c1] }) (8... Nd7? 9. Qb3! $18 { We're winning 2 pawns by force. } { [%cal Rb3f7,Rb3b7,Rb7c6,Rb7a7] }) 9. Qb3! { This is a move Black often overlooks! We're now threatening both f7 and b7, which will also win us an exchange. } { [%cal Rb3f7,Rb3b7] } 9... e6 { Black saves f7, we can now happily grab b7. } { [%csl Rf7,Ge6] } 10. Qxb7 { [%cal Rb7a8] } 10... Qxc4 { IMPORTANT: It’s crucial here NOT to take the hanging rook! Many players make that mistake, but it actually leads to a forced draw by perpetual check. The problem is Black’s response, 11...Bb4+! I’ll show that variation below so you can see why Qxa8 is a bad idea. } { [%cal Bf8b4] } 11. Qc8+! { Very important! We must first take away the king;s castling rights. } (11. Qxa8?? Bb4+! 12. c3 (12. Bd2?? { Even much worst, Black's winning now. } 12... Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Qf4+ { Rerouting to c7. } { [%cal Bf4c7] } 14. Ke1 Qc7 $19 { Our queen is officially trapped! Black will castle and follow up with Nd7, winning our queen. There’s nothing we can do to stop this plan. } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Be8g8,Bb8d7] }) 12... Bxc3+! 13. bxc3 Qxc3+ { Now our king is wide in the open with no defense. } 14. Ke2 Qc4+ $10 { Wherever our king goes Black will always be able to just give checks. It's a draw. }) 11... Ke7 12. Qb7+ { [%cal Rb7a8,Rb7e7] } 12... Ke8 13. a3! $18 { We first stop Bb4+, and the rook remains hanging—we’ll grab that on the next move. Playing 11. a3 wouldn’t work, because after 11...Bc5 12. Qxa8, Black could play O-O, bringing the king to safety. Then Black could force a perpetual check with moves like Qe4+ followed by Bxe3. But now, this tactic doesn’t work because we’ll be attacking the b8 knight with check. } { [%cal Rb7a8] }) 8. Be3 { The simplest move: we bring out the bishop to protect d4 and prepare to castle. } { [%cal Be1c1,Ge3d4] } 8... Bd6 { It doesn't matter what Black does, we always just stick to our plan. } (8... Be7 $16 { It doesn’t matter; Black will usually opt for the same type of setup. There might be some variations in move orders or specific choices, but the overall plan remains the same usually. } { [%cal Be1c1,Bh2h4,Bf1d3,Bg2g4] }) (8... Qd5!? { We have to respond differently to this move, but it almost never gets played. Here it's best to trade queens, since it will leave Black with a weak isolated d-pawn. } 9. Qxd5! cxd5 { Our light-squared bishop isn’t developed yet, and the best spot for it would be g2. From there, it can control the a8-h1 diagonal while putting pressure on Black’s weak d-pawn. } { [%csl Rd5,Gg2][%cal Bf1g2] } 10. g3 Nc6 11. Bg2 O-O-O { [%csl Rd5] } 12. Ke2! $16 { Connecting the rooks! With fewer pieces on the board, there's no need to castle—the king is perfectly safe and more flexible in the center. White has the advantage in the endgame, thanks to Black's weaker pawn structure. The evaluation here is +1.5. } { [%csl Rd5,Rf6,Rf7][%cal Ge1a1,Ge1h1,Bc2c3,Ba2a4,Bh2h4] }) (8... Nd7 9. O-O-O Bd6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. h4 $16 { [%csl Ge3,Gd3,Gf3][%cal Bg2g4,Bh4h5,Bf3f5,Bc1b1] }) 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Bd3 $16 { White is much better here. From this point, White can launch a kingside attack with moves like h4-h5 and g4, aiming to break through to Black’s castled king. White has a 66% winrate from this position. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge3,Gf3][%cal Bh2h4,Bg2g4,Bc1b1,Gb1a2] } *


