6... e6 { This is a better move than the previous ones we’ve seen, although White is still better because Bxf3 was an inaccuracy. Black is preparing to play Nf6, and if we capture the knight, Black can recapture with the queen, slightly improving their position. } { [%cal Gd8f6,Bg8f6] } 7. Be3 { We can prepare to castle long, and we’re now protecting the d4 pawn. } 7... Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { We want to keep the queens on the board for as long as possible. You might think Qxf6 is good because it creates doubled pawns for Black, but in this case, it actually benefits Black. Black gains an open g-file and can easily get rid of the doubled pawns later, for example with a move like e5. } (8... gxf6 { Black wants to use the g-file for his benefit. } { [%cal Bh8g8] } 9. O-O-O $16 { We have a big lead in development, the open g-file from Black isn't so scary. } { [%csl Gf3,Ge3,Gc1,Gd1,Gd4,Re8,Rf8,Rd8,Rb8,Ra8,Rh8] }) 9. Qg3! { The queen is best placed here, as it avoids Bd6 and has the potential to infiltrate into c7 in the future. } { [%cal Bg3c7,Rc7b7] } 9... Nd7 10. O-O-O $16 { White has the advantage here due to the bishop pair and greater control over the center. } { [%csl Gc1,Ge3,Gf1][%cal Bf1d3,Be3g5,Bh1e1] } *


