5. d4 { Now that we’ve covered everything that happens if Black plays Bxf3 and seen that it’s not such a great move, let’s check out the lines if Black develops normally, which is the best option. } 5... e6 { e6 is the most popular move, as Black simply frees up their pieces. From here, both sides can develop normally. } { [%csl Gf8,Gd8] } 6. c3 { We keep our position solid by forming a pawn chain. Often, Black can still go wrong here, but if Black plays relatively good developing moves, it should end up quite equal—though White still retains the starting edge. } { [%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gd4] } 6... Nd7! { Black prepares Ngf6. Since our knight on e4 can’t stay in the center forever and will be chased away with Ngf6, it's best to retreat it to g3. From there, it will be safely placed and can potentially join a kingside attack in the future. } { [%cal Bg8f6] } (6... Nf6?! { This is the most popular move from this position, but it would have been better to play Nd7 first to support Ngf6. Now, Black will be forced to recapture with the queen. } 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { White would love to play Ne5 here, but that’s not possible yet because our knight is pinned. We first need to unpin it. Now, we have a nice sequence of moves: } { [%csl Rf3] } 8. Qb3! { We aim at the b7 pawn, which, if taken, also wins us the rook, gaining tempo. Now that the knight is unpinned, it can move to e5 on the next move. } { [%csl Rb7][%cal Bf3e5] } 8... b6 { Black prevents us from taking b6, but this also significantly weakens the c6 pawn. } { [%csl Rc6] } (8... Qe7 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Bf4 $16 { We have a significant lead in development and a space advantage. } { [%csl Gf4,Ge5,Re7,Rf8,Re8][%cal Be5c4,Bg2g4,Bh2h3,Bf1e2,Be1c1,Be1g1] }) (8... Bxf3 9. Qxb7 { [%cal Rb7a8] } 9... Bd5 10. Qxa8 $18 { White is up a pawn and an exchange and Black has many weaknesses. } { [%csl Rb8,Ra7] }) 9. Ne5 { Hitting the LSB and putting pressure on c6. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Re5g4] } 9... Bf5 10. h4 $16 { White is completely dominating here. We’re threatening to trap the queen with Bg5, and with easy development, we have a huge space advantage. The c6 pawn, the queen, and the light-squared bishop can all be targets. } { [%csl Ge5,Rc6,Rf6,Rf5][%cal Bc1g5,Bb3a4,Bg2g4,Bf2f3] }) 7. Ng3! { [%csl Gg3] } 7... Ngf6 8. h3 { Forcing Black to give up the bishop pair, as it must trade, will benefit us. } 8... Bxf3 (8... Bh5?! 9. Nxh5 Nxh5 $16 { Black's knight is on the rim, and if it moves back to f6, it will have wasted 2 moves. White can just continue developing normally here. The position is very flexible. } { [%csl Rh5][%cal Bh5f6,Bf6h5,Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bc1f4,Bf3e5] }) 9. Qxf3 { We now also have the queen developed on a safe square. } { [%csl Gf3] } 9... Bd6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O $14 { The position is relatively equal, with both sides having solid setups. However, it’s likely a bit easier to play as White due to the bishop pair and the queen being on a more flexible square. Even though it’s quite balanced, White has a 55% winrate here! } { [%csl Gg3,Gf3,Gd3,Gc1,Gd7,Gf6,Gd6,Gg8] } *


