5. d4 Nf6 { Black again doesn’t trade the bishop for our knight, and instead plays Nf6, which is one of the better options if followed up correctly. Black now attacks our knight, so we are forced to either trade it or retreat. } 6. Nxf6+ { Trading the knights is best. } 6... exf6 { Now we have transposed into one of the popular variations of the Tartakower Variation. } 7. Bd3 { White develops the LSB, and prepares to castle kingside. } { [%csl Gd3] } 7... Bd6 { Black usually goes for the same idea. } { [%cal Be8g8] } (7... Bxf3? { Black eliminates the defender of d4, but this only helps us get a lead in development. } 8. Qxf3 Qxd4 (8... Be7 { Black decides to castle quickly via Be7 followed by O-O, (but then what was the sense of Bxf3, since that just helped us develop the queen and win the bishop pair). We can castle too, and we set up another trap. } 9. O-O O-O? { By far the most popular move! We now have a beautiful way to forcefully win material or even achieve checkmate. } (9... Qxd4 10. Be3 $18 { [%csl Gd3,Ge3,Gf3][%cal Bf1e1,Ba1b1,Bb1d1] }) (9... Nd7 $16 { The only move that really survives is rerouting the knight to e6, which will help with the kingside defense. After that, Black can castle kingside. From here, White can continue developing normally. One interesting idea is to rook-lift the f1-rook to the third rank, increasing pressure and potentially preparing for an attack on Black’s kingside. } { [%csl Gd3,Gc1][%cal Bf1e1,Be1e3,Be3g3,Bf3h5] }) 10. Bh6!! { Black can't take it! gxh6 leads to mate in 2 after Qf5, and Black can't stop us from taking h7. Black is now forced to play g6, giving away the exchange. } { [%cal Bf3f5] } 10... gxh6 (10... g6 11. Bxf8 { We can happily take that. } 11... Bxf8 $18 { We’re up in material and have a superior position thanks to a better pawn structure and piece placement. }) (10... Re8 { Taking the rook out of the way of our bishop, but this fails due to the beautiful: } 11. Bxg7!! { We just bring that king out! } 11... Kxg7 12. Qg4+ { Taking away the g-file. } 12... Kf8 13. Bxh7 { Threatening Qg8#. } { [%cal Rh7g8,Rg4g8] } 13... Bd6 { Black creates a running route for the king after Qg8+, so the simplest move for White is Rae1, cutting off the e-file. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge7d7,Gd7c8] } 14. Rae1 { [%cal Ge1e8,Gg4g8] } 14... Rxe1 15. Rxe1 $18 { Black can resign now, checkmate will come soon. } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Ge1e8,Gg4g8] }) 11. Qf5) 9. Bf4! { We’re going full gambit mode here! Our focus is pure development. Sacrificing pawns for the sake of rapid piece activity will give us a big lead in the position. } { [%csl Rb2] } 9... Qxb2?? { Black gobbles up another pawn, but this move allows us to castle. Meanwhile, Black's pieces remain undeveloped and out of play. Our lead in development will soon become a decisive factor. } (9... Be7 10. O-O-O { [%csl Gc1] }) 10. O-O $18 { Now there’s no stopping White! We’ll play Rae1 next, stacking pressure on Black’s king with Rae1, Re4, and Rfe1. Black will be unable to castle and will soon find it impossible to defend. All our pieces will storm the king, and it’s only a matter of time before Black’s defenses crumble. It's +4.2. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Ba1e1,Be1e4,Bf4d6,Yf1e1] }) (7... Be7 { Actually the best move, the reason this is better than Bd6 is because it prevents any Qe2 checks from White. } { [%csl Ge7] } 8. h3 { We can kick this away, or immediately play Be3, doesn't matter too much. } 8... Bh5 { It's fine because there's no Qe2+. } 9. Be3 { The reason we don't castle kingside yet is that castling queenside is a bit better. It sets us up for a more aggressive game. } 9... O-O 10. Qd2 Nd7 11. O-O-O $14 { White may only have a slight edge, but it’s definitely easier to play as White. Black will be on the defensive side. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge3][%cal Bg2g4,Bh3h4] }) 8. h3! { I recommend playing h3 first, while both sides have not castled yet. From here, about 90% of players will mess up. } 8... Bh5?! { This move might seem fine, but White can now force a slightly better endgame (or middlegame is some variations) with the following sequence: } (8... Bxf3? { By now, you should see that Bxf3 is usually a bad move. It gives White the bishop pair and helps with quicker development. } 9. Qxf3 O-O { From here, we stick to our classic plan: castle queenside and launch a pawn storm on the kingside. } 10. c3 Re8+ 11. Be3 Nd7 12. O-O-O $16 { [%cal Bg2g4,Bh3h4,Bh4h5] }) (8... Be6! 9. O-O O-O 10. c4 $14 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4][%cal Ba2a3,Bb2b4,Bf1e1,Bd1c2,Bc1e3] }) 9. Qe2+! { White's win rate immediately spikes to 63% with this move! The point of this is that we wanted to play Nh4, controlling the g6 square, followed by g4/f4, either winning the bishop pair or material in many lines. The issue is that we can't play Nh4 right away because our knight is pinned, so with Qe2+, we aim to trade queens. Once the queens are off the board, our knight will no longer be pinned, freeing us to execute the plan. } { [%cal Bf3h4,Bg2g4] } 9... Qe7 { This is by far the most popular move. If Black plays either Be7 or Kf8, we simply respond with Bd2 and castle long. This sets us up for an incredible attacking position, with all our pieces poised to storm the kingside while Black struggles to defend. } (9... Be7 10. Bd2 O-O 11. O-O-O { [%cal Bg2g4] }) 10. Qxe7+ { We trade the queens off the board. } 10... Bxe7 { It doesn't matter with what piece Black recaptures. } 11. Nh4! { We're controlling the g6 square, which is crucial. If Black plays Bg6, we can simply capture with our knight, allowing us to maintain the powerful bishop pair. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rh4g6,Bg2g4,Bf2f4] } 11... Bg6 { This is the top engine move. We can now comfortably trade our knight for Black's light-squared bishop, which leaves them with a worse pawn structure. } (11... O-O? 12. f4! { [%cal Bg2g4,Bf4f5] }) (11... Nd7 12. f4 g6 13. g4 f5 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. gxh5 $16 { [%csl Rf5,Rh5,Rh3,Rf4,Rf7,Rh7][%cal Bd3f5] }) (11... g5 12. Nf5 Bg6 13. Be3 $16 { [%csl Rg6,Re7,Rf6,Rf7][%cal Bf5e7,Bg2g4,Be1c1] }) 12. Nxg6! hxg6 { Take a look at Black's pawn structure now—it's a pawn cube! We can simply move the king out of the center, connecting the rooks by castling. Long castling is better here. } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rg7,Rg6][%cal Bc1d2,Be1c1] } 13. Bd2 Nd7 14. O-O-O $16 { We’re pretty much in the endgame now, and White holds the advantage thanks to the bishop pair and better pawn structure. This endgame will require some work, but the position is in your favor. Black’s best hope is to fight for a draw, but you should be able to press for a win with careful play! } { [%csl Gc1,Gd2,Gd3,Yf7,Yf6,Yg6,Yg7] } *


