5. Bc4! { We'll respond with Bc4, immediately applying pressure on the weak f7 pawn. } { [%csl Rf7] } 5... Ngf6 { Black will almost always respond with Nf6, although sometimes the move orders might vary, like e6 followed by Nf6. This attacks our knight, so we can either trade, retreat, or choose a better option: apply more pressure on f7 with Neg5! } (5... e6 { We simply continue with our usual move order, Black will just transpose. } 6. Qe2 Ngf6 7. Neg5 { We've now simply transposed to our main line. }) 6. Neg5! { We threaten an immediate mate in one with Bxf7#. Black is forced to block it. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7] } 6... e6 7. Qe2! { We're hitting hard again with aggressive play! At this point, our setup is very similar to chapter 3 and we have the exact same threat: 8. Nxf7! The seemingly natural moves like Be7, h6, b5, and Bd6 from Black are all blunders in this position! } 7... Be7?? { Although most advanced players will notice our threat, there are still quite a few who will fall for it. We play the exact same sequence after h6, Bd6, b5... Black's hoping to castle kingside on the next move, but we've got: } { [%cal Be8g8] } 8. Nxf7! { We're taking away the defender of e6, and on the next move, we can capture that pawn with our queen! If Black doesn't take our knight and instead tries to save the queen, we happily scoop up the free rook, leaving us with a huge material advantage. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8,Ye2e6] } 8... Kxf7 { Black will typically take the knight to bring the game to a swift conclusion. Now, we have a stunning forced checkmate in 4 moves! } 9. Qxe6+! { Advancing the king forward! If it retreats to e8 or f8, then Qf7# delivers checkmate in 1 move. } 9... Kg6 10. Qf7+ { We advance the king further into the center! } 10... Kf5 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rf7g6] } (10... Kh6 11. d3+ { Bringing the bishop into the game. } { [%csl Gc1] } 11... g5 $7 12. Bxg5# { [%csl Gh6,Yh5,Yg6,Yg7,Rh7,Bg5][%cal Gg5h6,Yf7h5,Yf7g7,Bf3g5] }) 11. Be6+! { We're taking away more squares, the king is now forced to move to the 4th rank. } 11... Ke4 { 12. d3 is checkmate, but I like to throw something in here: } (11... Kf4 12. d3# { Checkmate! } { [%csl Gg5,Gf4,Ge3,Be5,Yg4,Yf5,Re4,Rg3,Rf3][%cal Gc1g5,Bf3e5,Ye6g4,Rd3e4,Rh2g3,Rg2f3] }) 12. Qg6+! { Sacrificing the queen to add a touch of elegance to the checkmate! :) } 12... hxg6 13. d3# { A stunning checkmate right in the heart of the board, even while down 10 points in material! All the minor pieces work together to deliver this checkmate, definitely a rare sight! :D } { [%csl Re4,Ge5,Gd4,Bd5,Bf5,Yf4,Ye3,Rd3][%cal Rd3e4,Gf3e5,Gf3d4,Be6d5,Be6f5,Yc1f4] } *


