7... Nb6?! { This is the most popular move. Black attacks our bishop and, more importantly, frees up their light-squared bishop, which now supports the e6 pawn, so we can't sacrifice there anymore. However, this move is a bit of an inaccuracy because White can actually win a pawn by force here. } { [%cal Rb6c4,Gc8e6] } 8. Ne5! { Instead of retreating, we'll counterattack! It's always good to first look at the threats you can make rather than just responding to your opponent's threats. Our knights are now double attacking the f7 pawn, and there's nothing Black can do to defend it! } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gg5f7,Ge5f7] } 8... Nxc4 { We'll first recapture the knight with our queen. The f7 pawn will still remain hanging on the next move. } { [%csl Rf7] } 9. Qxc4 Qd5 { Because we're threatening Nxf7, which would also fork the rook and queen, Black moves the queen to avoid the fork. We have to again delay taking f7 and trade the queens. } (9... Qa5 { This is another possible response. Black avoids getting forked but keeps the queens on the board } 10. Ngxf7 Rg8 (10... Be7 { Many players will make a mistake here. DON'T take the rook! If you do, Black's queen will capture our knight on e5, and the h8 knight is trapped and will eventually be lost. Two minor pieces for a rook is not a good trade in this situation. } 11. Qc3! { We simply protect the e5 knight and hit the queen. Black is now forced to trade or he'll lose a big amount in material. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc3e5,Rc3a5] } 11... Qxc3 12. dxc3 O-O 13. Ng5 $16 { [%csl Re6,Gg5,Ge5][%cal Be1g1] }) 11. O-O $18 { White is much better. We can always protect the knights, they're not getting trapped. } { [%csl Re6,Re8,Rg8][%cal Bd2d4,Bf7g5,Bg5f3,Bf1e1,Bc4c3] }) 10. Qxd5! { We don't mind taking the queens off the board since we're going to be up material, giving us a clear advantage in the endgame. } 10... exd5 { Now it's finally time to take what we've been waiting for—grab that free pawn! } (10... Nxd5 11. Ngxf7 { We simply take it. } 11... Rg8 12. Ng5 $16) (10... cxd5 { Same thing. } 11. Ngxf7 Rg8 12. Ng5 $16) 11. Ngxf7 { This is a bit easier to play compared to Nxf7, which is totally fine but can lead to complications with h6, where the knights are defending each other and things get tricky. By capturing with the g5 knight we keep things simple. } { [%cal Rf7h8] } 11... Rg8 12. Ng5 $16 { White is simply up a free pawn! The game is still far from over, but you'll definitely have a slight advantage with that extra pawn in the endgame. } { [%csl Gf2] } *


