4... Nfd7?! { Black retreats the knight to d7, sensing that advancing it might be too risky. While bringing it back to g8 would waste a move, on d7, the knight still ends up awkwardly placed, blocking other pieces. Now, take a moment to consider White's best response. If you've checked out my previous study, "Sacrifice like a Pro!", you probably already have an idea of what's coming next: } (4... Ng4? { A common beginner mistake } 5. h3! { We can just kick it. The only retreating square is gh6. } 5... Nh6 6. d4 $16 { It's clear White is in a much better position here. We control the center, have two knights developed, and our development is smooth. Meanwhile, Black has already wasted three moves just shuffling the knight around, and it's only move six! } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf3,Gc3,Rh6][%cal Bf1d3,Bc1g5] }) (4... Ng8?! 5. d4 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. Bd3 $16 { Black has literally no pieces developed! } { [%csl Gd3,Gf3,Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Ra8,Rb8,Rd8,Re8,Rg8,Rh8,Rf8][%cal Be1g1] }) 5. e6! { A crippling sacrifice! While 5. d4 is a strong move too, with e6 we completely shut down Black’s development. All their pieces will get in each other’s way. White's win rate jumps up to 60%! } 5... fxe6 { [%csl Re6,Re7,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Rd7,Rc8,Rb8] } 6. Ng5! { Now we immediately start attacking! We also prepare to bring the queen out. Black has to be extremely cautious, especially with multiple mating threats looming along the weak e8-h5 diagonal. } { [%csl Rh5,Re6,Re8,Rf7][%cal Gd1h5,Gg5e6] } 6... Nf6 { Black retreats the knight to f6, freeing the light-squared bishop to help defend e6. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gc8e6] } (6... h6?? { Leads to mate in 2. } 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qxg6# { [%csl Re8,Rf7][%cal Gg6e8] }) 7. d4 { We take the center and free up the DSB. From here many many players will go wrong. Since they'll try to get rid of our knight with h6. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc1] } 7... h6? { This just creates a big new weakness, the g6 square. } { [%csl Rg6] } (7... g6 { Black tries to get some development by fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop and castling kingside. We can immediately strike the kingside with h4. } { [%cal Bf8g7,Be8g8] } 8. h4 Bg7 9. h5 { We sacrifice another pawn, but in return, we open up the rook and gain a strong initiative. } { [%cal Gh1h8] } 9... Nxh5 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. Qf3 $16 { We have a big lead in development, meanwhile Black's really stuck. Keep an eye for Nxh7 tactics here. } { [%csl Gf3,Gg5,Gd3,Gc3,Rg6,Re6,Re7,Re8,Rd8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Gh1][%cal Rg5h7,Bd3g6,Bc1f4,Be1c1] }) 8. Nf3 { We can simply retreat the knight, and from here our plan is clear: place the bishop on g6, where it will be real trouble for Black. } { [%csl Rg6,Rf7][%cal Bf1d3,Bd3g6] } 8... Nbd7 { With Black's pieces stuck, this is essentially Black's only option to try to develop. } (8... g5 9. Bd3 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Gd3g6] } 9... Rg8 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Gg8g6] } 10. Ne5 $18 { Bg6+ is unstoppable. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Gd3g6] }) 9. Bd3 { We reroute to g6, and there's really nothing Black can do to stop this idea. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Gd3g6] } 9... Kf7 { The only move to stop Bg6+ is to bongloud! } { [%cal Rf7g6] } (9... Qc7 { Creating an escape square for the king. } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Be8d8] } 10. Bg6+ Kd8 11. Qe2 $18 { It's very clear who's better here. :) } { [%csl Rf6,Rd7,Rf8,Rd8,Rc8,Rc7,Rh8,Ra8][%cal Bg2g3,Bc1f4,Bf3e5] }) (9... Nb6?? { The most popular move, but we have an immediate win here. } 10. Ne5! { Before playing Bg6+, we first take away the d7 square from Black, setting up a checkmate with Bg6#. } { [%csl Rd7,Rg6][%cal Re5d7,Gd3g6] } 10... Qc7 { [%cal Be8d8] } (10... Qd6 11. Bg6+ Kd8 12. Nf7+ $18 { [%cal Gf7d6,Gf7d8] }) 11. Bg6+ Kd8 12. Bf4 { We win the queen by force. Black can't prevent Nf7+, which leads to a discovered attack on the queen. Black can resign now. } { [%cal Be5f7,Rf4c7] }) 10. Ne5+ Nxe5 11. dxe5 $18 { Black will have to sacrifice the knight to prevent an immediate checkmate threat with Qh5+. } { [%csl Rh5,Rg6,Rf7][%cal Re5f6,Bd1h5,Bd3g6] } *


