4. e5 { [%cal Re5f6] } 4... Ne4 { This is the best and most popular option. } { [%cal Bc3e2,Be2g3] } 5. Ne2! { Instead of trading knights just yet, we’ll reroute our knight to g3. From there, we won’t mind a trade because we can recapture with either the f or h pawn, which will give us an open file to place our rook. } { [%cal Yf2g3,Yh2g3,Be2g3] } 5... Qb6 { This is the main move. Black threatens checkmate on f3 while also putting pressure on the queenside. } { [%csl Rb2,Rf2] } (5... Bg4 { Black's 2nd most popular move. Black now threatens to double our f-pawns by capturing f3. } { [%cal Rg4f3] } 6. Nfg1!! { The absolute best move! It might look crazy at first glance since we're just moving everything backward, but it’s absolutely the best. The idea is that we’re now threatening to fork Black’s pieces with f3. } { [%csl Rf3,Gg1][%cal Rf2f3,Bb1c3,Bc3e2] } 6... Bxe2 { Black captures, otherwise he loses tempi. } (6... Bh5?! { This allows us to immediately start hitting Black's knight and bishop around. } 7. f3! { Kicking the knight away. } { [%cal Rf3e4] } 7... Nc5 (7... Ng5? { It might seem like Black is safe since the knight isn’t trapped, but the real issue is that Black’s bishop is also poorly placed. By combining the attack on both pieces, we actually end up winning the bishop! } { [%cal Bg5e6] } 8. h4! { Hitting the knight! } { [%cal Rh4g5] } 8... Ne6 9. g4! { We get a classic Noah's Ark Trap. } { [%cal Rg4h5] } 9... Bg6 10. h5 $18 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rh5g6] }) 8. Nf4! { We continue developing with tempi! } 8... Bg6 9. d4! Nca6 10. c3 $16 { We’ve gained three free moves by pushing Black’s pieces around. White now enjoys a strong space advantage and effortless development, while Black's pieces are poorly positioned and struggling to develop. This leaves White with a comfortable +1.3 advantage. } { [%csl Yb2,Yc3,Yd4,Ye5,Rg6,Ra6,Rb8,Rd8,Re8,Ra8,Rf8,Rh8,Gf4][%cal Yb2c3,Yc3d4,Yd4e5,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bg2g4] }) (6... Qb6 { No problem! We'll just have to block the checkmate threat first. } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Rb6f2] } 7. d4! Bxe2 8. Nxe2 $16 { [%csl Rf8,Rb8][%cal Bf2f3,Be2f4,Bc2c3] }) (6... Nc5 7. d4! { We just hit Black's pieces! } 7... Ncd7 { [%csl Gd4] } (7... Nca6 8. h3 Bf5 9. g4 Bd7 10. c3 $16 { [%csl Rd7,Rb8,Ra6,Rf8,Re8][%cal Bg1f3,Be2f4,Bf1g2] }) 8. f3 Bf5 9. g4 Be6 10. Nf4 $16 { We'll be taking the bishop on the next move, doubling Black e-pawns, which causes Black to have even a more harder time developing. We have a huge space advantage. All Black's pieces are totally stuck. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Bc2c3,Rf4e6] }) 7. Nxe2! { We capture with the knight, placing it on e2 where it can easily jump to more active squares like g3 or f4. } { [%csl Ge2][%cal Be2g3,Be2f4] } 7... e6 8. d4 $16 { White's doing great! You usually want to play h4, taking away the g5 square from the knight, and follow that up with f3, trapping the knight, or it even works in reverse order in many cases. } { [%csl Rf8,Rb8][%cal Bf2f3,Bg2g3,Bf1g2,Be1g1,Bc2c3,Bh2h4,Be2f4] }) (5... e6 6. d3 Nc5 7. Nf4 $16 { [%csl Rf8,Gf4,Gf3][%cal Bd3d4,Bc2c3,Bf1d3] }) 6. d4 { We can simply block the threat. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gf2][%cal Gd4e5] } 6... e6 { [%csl Gf8] } (6... Bg4 7. Nfg1! { We play the same idea as above! } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Rf2f3] } 7... Bxe2 8. Nxe2 $16 { We transpose to a very similar position. } { [%cal Bf2f3,Be2f4,Bf1d3] }) 7. Ng3 { Now we've successfully rerouted our knight to a desirable square. If Black decides to trade, we gain an open file. If Black doesn’t trade, we can keep our knight here, as it’s well-positioned to potentially join future kingside attacks. } 7... c5 { This is really Black's only option to gain more activity. The c6 square is now cleared for the knight on b8 and Black applies pressure on our center. } { [%cal Gc5d4,Bb8c6,Bf8c5] } (7... Nxg3 { This transposes to the mainline. } 8. fxg3 c5 9. Bd3 cxd4 10. O-O { [%csl Gg1] }) 8. Bd3! { We threaten to win a pawn by capturing the knight, leaving Black with no choice but to trade since the knight has no other squares to move to. } { [%cal Gd3e4,Gg3e4,Be1g1] } 8... Nxg3 9. fxg3! { Typically, you want to avoid recapturing with the f-pawn due to potential weaknesses around the king. However, in this situation, it's actually beneficial since we plan to castle kingside. This will give us an open f-file for our rook, making it incredibly active. An open h-file wouldn’t be as useful since we won't have a rook placed there anyway. } 9... cxd4 { Black has won a pawn, but that's not a major concern since it’s weak and can be easily targeted later. Our priority right now should be on development, ensuring our pieces are active and well-coordinated. } { [%csl Rd4] } 10. O-O! { We don't need to worry about any discovered checks, as our bishop is solidly blocking the d4-pawn. In the near future, we should play Kh1 tho, which will free our bishop from being tied down on d3. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Bg1h1] } 10... Nc6 11. a3! $16 { Very important! We want to avoid any trouble with Nb4, so playing a3 will effectively stop any counterplay from Black. In this position, White has a nice advantage with various options available for further development and potential attacks. Stockfish says +0.5. } { [%csl Gf1,Rc8,Re8,Rd4,Rf8][%cal Bg1h1,Bb2b4,Bd3e2,Bf3g5,Bc1f4,Ra3b4] } *


