4. Ne2! { White doesn't mind rerouting the knight at all. In fact, a knight on g3 would be fantastic, adding pressure and flexibility for future kingside play! But, more importantly, we are now double-attacking Black's d4 pawn. This is what I meant when I said Black gains no long-term benefits from pushing the knight. Now, Black is on the defensive, and the only move that keeps the d4 pawn safe is c5. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Be2g3,Gf3d4,Ge2d4] } 4... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4] } 5. c3! { We want to eliminate Black's central pawns here. White actually wins a pawn in all lines, except for 5...dxc3, which still grants us a significant lead in development. Many players attempt 5...d3 to save their pawns, but this doesn't work either. } { [%cal Rc3d4] } 5... d3? { Black pushes their pawns deeper into our territory, but we can simply attack it again. } (5... dxc3 { Recapturing with the knight is fine, but it's actually better to take with the b-pawn. Doing this opens the g-file for our rook, lets the DSB move along its diagonal, and most importantly, sets up a future d4 pawn push. Plus, the knight is better placed on g3 than c3 anyway. } 6. bxc3 $16 { White's looking great here! We'll pretty much always play Ng3 next, then bring out Bc4 and castle kingside. After that, there are plenty of good options, like Rb1 to take over the open file, d4 to grab more control in the center and open up the DSB more...etc. Lots of flexibility! } { [%csl Ba3,Ba4,Ra8,Rc8,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Rb8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Bd1a4,Bc1a3,Ba1b1,Ge2g3,Gf1c4,Ge1g1,Bd2d4] }) (5... Nc6 { The most popular move, protecting d4, but this too doesn't save Black. } 6. cxd4 cxd4 7. Qa4! { We pin the knight! There's no way to save the pawn anymore! } { [%csl Rd4,Rc6][%cal Ra4e8,Ga4d4,Bf3d4,Ye2d4] } 7... e5 { The most popular, but we can just take it! The knight is pinned! } (7... Bd7 8. Nexd4! { It's free! } 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 $16 { It's clear White is much better here. Just play Bc4/Be2 and castle on the next move. } { [%csl Gf3,Gd4,Ge4,Rd7,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Ra8][%cal Bf1c4,Bd2d3,Be1g1] }) (7... d3 { A nice try from Black, it looks like it's safe now, but it's way too overextended, so Black won't be able to defend it anymore. } 8. Ned4! $16 { Threatening to take c6 and d3, Black can't save both. } { [%csl Rd3,Rc6][%cal Yf1d3,Gd4c6] }) 8. Nxe5! $16 { White's simply up material with a great position. } { [%csl Ga4,Ge5,Ge2,Rc6][%cal Be2f4,Be5c6] }) (5... Bg4!? { Many players actually fail to refute this move properly, but there's a really nice sequence here. } 6. Ne5! { Actually, only 9% find this! The point of this is we're forcing the bishop away and we're secretly aiming at the f7 pawn. } { [%csl Rg4,Rf7][%cal Re5f7,Ge5g4] } 6... Bxe2? { Many players take here in order not to lose tempi, but we have s rather shocking response: } (6... Bh5?? { Loses on the spot. } 7. Qa4+! { Black is forced to block with the knight. } { [%cal Ga4e8] } 7... Nd7 8. Nf4! $18 { Absolutely best! We have now an unstoppable threat; Nxd7 followed by Bb5, pinning the queen and winning the game. With Nf4 we free our LSB and hit Black's DSB. } { [%csl Gf1,Gb5][%cal Gf1b5,Ra4e8,Rf4h5] } 8... Bg4) 7. Qb3! { White's winrate jumps to 91%! Instead of recapturing, we attack! The queen is threatening checkmate on f7 and we're attacking the undefended b7-pawn. } { [%csl Rf7,Rb7][%cal Rb3f7,Rb3b7] } 7... e6 { Blocking checkmate. } { [%csl Ge6,Rf7] } 8. Qxb7 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rb7a8,Rb7f7] } 8... Nd7 { The only way to protect from both threats. } 9. Nxd7 Bxf1 10. Ne5 { [%cal Re5f7,Rb7f7] } 10... Ne7 11. Rxf1 $18 { After all that chaos, we end up winning a pawn! Black now also has lots of weaknesses. We're getting nearer to the endgame, which will be much better for us. } { [%csl Ge5,Gb7,Rc5,Rd4,Re7,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Ra8,Rh8] }) 6. Nf4 { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rf1d3,Rf4d3] } 6... c4 7. Qa4+! { A fork! White can grab the pawn on c4 in the next move, and after that, Black's d3 pawn will be impossible to defend. White will end up two pawns ahead. } { [%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Ra4e8,Ga4c4,Yf4d3,Bf1d3] } *


