{ In this chapter we'll look at 4...e5, which is quite rare, but it can be tricky if you don't know how to play against it. }
4... e5!? { Black plays kinda Petroff style. Black sacrifices a pawn but then tries to win our e4 pawn by attacking the knight along the e-file. } { [%cal Bd8e7,Bg8f6] } 5. Nxe5 Nf6 { Black is putting pressure on our pawn. It seems like White is in a strong position (and we are), but if we're not careful, there are still plenty of tricks Black can pull. In fact, 61% of players end up making a big blunder here! } { [%cal Gf6e4] } (5... Qe7 { [%csl Re4,Re5][%cal Re7e4] } 6. Nf3 { Counterattacking d4. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Ge2d4,Gf3d4] } 6... Qxe4 { Before capturing d4 we can develop with tempo by kicking the queen away. } 7. d3 { [%csl Gc1][%cal Rd3e4] } 7... Qe7 8. Nxd4 $16 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Bc1f4,Bd1d2,Be1c1] }) 6. Nf3! { Instead of just protecting our e4 pawn, we move our knight to safety and launch a counterattack on Black's d4 pawn. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf3d4,Ge2d4] } (6. d3?? { Blunders a fork! } 6... Qa5+ $18 { GG, Black wins a free knight. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Ra5e1,Ra5e5] }) 6... Nxe4 7. Nexd4 { We're not out of the trickery yet. } 7... Bc5 { It looks scary, but we have a simple response. } { [%csl Rd4,Rf2][%cal Gc5f2] } 8. Bd3 { Counterattacking the knight and preparing to castle. } 8... Bxd4 (8... Nxf2?? { DON'T take the knight with the king! Instead we take it with our queen with a little maneuver. } 9. Qe2+! $18 { We win a piece. } { [%cal Ge2f2,Ge2e8,Ge1f2] }) 9. Bxe4 O-O 10. O-O $16 { White's king is now safe. We're up a clean pawn with a great position! } { [%csl Gg1,Gf3,Ge4][%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d4] } *


