[UTCTime "09:41:44"]

4. h3! { The mainline, we kick the bishop and force it to make the decision to either retreat or trade. } { [%cal Rh3g4] } 4... Bxf3 { Trading is the most popular option since it's what the bishop was aiming for all along. Black exchanges a potentially passive piece for our knight, but the downside is that they’ve wasted a tempo and now lose the bishop pair. } { [%cal Bc8g4,Bg4f3] } 5. Qxf3 { [%csl Gf3] } 5... e6 { This is the main move. We'll look at everything that comes after 5...e6 in this chapter. It simply supports the center, opens the queen, and the bishop. } { [%csl Gf8,Gd8][%cal Ge6d5] } (5... Nf6 { This is the second most popular move. We will just transpose to the main line, so I'm not going to add a chapter for this. } 6. d3 e6 { It's the same position. }) 6. d3 { We support the e-pawn and open up our dark-squared bishop. I prefer this over 6. d4, since pushing the d-pawn can make it vulnerable. Black could easily challenge it later with a move like c5 or dxe4, which would tie our pieces down to its defense. Plus, d4 doesn’t really help our light-squared bishop, as it doesn't have any good squares anyway. It will become more useful later on once the position is opened up more. } { [%csl Gc1][%cal Gd3e4] } 6... Nf6 { From here, you have two solid options: 1. You can play Be2 and castle kingside, leading to a more quiet positional game where both sides have their chances. 2. You could go for Bd2, castle queenside, and launch a pawn storm on the kingside, setting up a more aggressive game with both players attacking on opposite flanks. Both plans are fine, so it really depends on your style! } (6... Nd7 { We can just continue with our standard plan. } { [%cal Bc1d2,Be1c1,Bg2g4] } 7. Bd2 { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1] } 7... Ngf6 (7... Qb6 { This variation is a bit more unusual and not something you’ll encounter frequently. In this case, castling queenside—our usual plan—might not be the best choice. Although it's playable, it requires precise defense. If we castle queenside, Black can launch a pawn storm with moves like h5-h4, making the position quite uncomfortable for us. We won't be able to counterattack Black's king. } { [%cal Ba7a5,Bc6c5] } 8. Qg3! { Here, I suggest this weird looking move. It puts pressure on g7, tying Black's bishop to its starting square, and positions our queen more actively. The queen could also potentially infiltrate Black’s position through the h2-b8 diagonal. The b-pawn is hanging now, but that’s not a problem. } { [%csl Rg7,Rf8,Rb2][%cal Bg3g7,Bg3c7] } 8... Qxb2?! { Black has now opened the b-file for our rook! } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Rb1b7,Ba1b1] } (8... d4 9. Na4 Qb5 10. b3 Ngf6 11. c4 dxc3 12. Nxc3 $14 { [%cal Bf2f4,Bf1e2,Be1g1] }) 9. Rb1! Qxc2 10. exd5! { An important move! We want to allow our knight to jump to either e4 or b5 after Black would play d4 at some point. } { [%cal Bc3e4,Bc3b5] } 10... cxd5 (10... exd5 11. Rxb7 { [%cal Bg3c7,Rb7a7,Rb7h7,Bf1e2,Be1g1,Be2g4] }) 11. Rxb7 d4 12. Nb5 $16 { White has a lot more activity along the 7th file. It's more than enough compensation for the pawn. } { [%csl Gb7,Gg3,Gb5][%cal Bf1e2,Be1g1] }) 8. g4 { Starting a kingside pawnstorm. } { [%cal Bg4g5,Bh3h4] } 8... h6 9. O-O-O $14 { We have a similar position as the main variation. } { [%csl Gc1,Gd2,Gd1][%cal Bf3g3,Bf2f4,Bh3h4,Bg4g5,Bc3e2,Bh1g1] }) (6... Bb4 { Black pins our knight, thus threatening d4. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rb4c3] } 7. Bd2 { We unpin it. } 7... d4 (7... Nf6 8. a3 { [%cal Ga3b4] } 8... Ba5 9. e5 Nfd7 10. Qg3 $16 { Now we can castle queenside and launch gain space on the kingside with moves like f4 and h4. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Gg3g7,Be1c1,Bf2f4,Bh3h4] }) 8. Nb1 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 $14 { Now, play 10. Qg3, targeting the g7 pawn on the next move, it doesn't matter what Black does. After Black castles, you can continue with Be2 and castle kingside. From there, you might consider playing f4 to open the f-file for your rook. Additionally, the c4 square could serve as a strong outpost for your knight. } { [%cal Bf3g3,Bf1e2,Bf2f4,Bd2c4] }) 7. Bd2 { I prefer going for the long-castling idea, it also scores quite good in the lichess database. } (7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O $14 { White keeps their initial edge, but it's relatively equal. You can still go for a more aggressive approach here with Qg3 followed by f4. } { [%cal Bf3g3,Ba2a4,Bc1f4,Bf4g5] }) 7... Be7 (7... Qb6 { Here we can again go for our Qg3, which we've seen in a variation somewhere above. } 8. Qg3 { Tying down the DSB to g7. } { [%csl Rg7,Gg3] } 8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qxc2 10. Rxb7 $14 { We have a very similar position. } { [%csl Gb7,Gg3][%cal Be4d5,Bc3b5,Bf1e2,Be1g1] }) (7... Bb4 { We shouldn't rush into castling just yet. If we do, Black can respond with d4, forcing a trade of our bishop—something we prefer to avoid. } 8. a3! { [%cal Ra3b4] } 8... Ba5 (8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 $16 { We enjoy the bishop pair. } { [%csl Gf1,Gc3][%cal Be1c1,Bf3g3,Bf2f4,Bc3d2] }) 9. e5 { Kicking away Black's knight and preparing to close the center with d4. } { [%cal Bd3d4] } 9... Nfd7 { Before playing d4 just yet, we can throw in another move that weakens Black's kingside significantly. } (9... d4! { The best move, but almost no one finds this! } 10. exf6 dxc3 11. bxc3 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. Be2 $14 { We've reached the endgame. Because of our bishop pair, Stockfish still gives White the advantage, but you'll definitely have to do some grinding. } { [%csl Ge2,Gd2][%cal Be1g1,Ba1b1] }) 10. Qg3! { Attacking g7. Castling leads to Bh6, winning the exchange. Black is forced to play g6, weakening the dark squares, if he wants to keep his castling rights. } { [%csl Rg7] } 10... g6 11. d4 $16 { [%csl Rg7,Rf8,Rh6,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Bf1d3,Be1c1,Bh3h4,Bh4h5] }) (7... Nbd7 8. g4 { We go for the same idea. } 8... h6 9. O-O-O { [%cal Bh3h4,Bg4g5] }) 8. g4 { Instead of castling right away, we can immediately go for the pawnstorm! } 8... O-O (8... h6 { Stopping a g5 pawn-push. } 9. O-O-O $16 { We’ve got another fantastic attacking position here! I recommend checking out some games from similar setups to pick up ideas on how to continue the attack. } { [%csl Gc1,Gd2,Gf3][%cal Bh3h4,Bg4g5,Bh1g1,Bf3g3,Bf2f4] }) 9. g5 { Bringing the pawns closer. } 9... Nfd7 10. h4 $14 { White's doing great here! Every piece is in a solid attacking position, and Black will have to defend really well to survive this. White's win rate is sitting at 62%! } { [%csl Gg5,Gh4][%cal Bc3e2,Bf3h3,Be1c1,Rd5d4,Bh4h5,Bg5g6,Bf2f4] } *


