4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 dxe4?! { The best move for Black would be to keep things closed. Playing dxe4 is a bit of an inaccuracy, as it opens up the position and gives White more activity to work with. } 6. Nxe4 { We've now got a knight in the center, and Black will need a few moves to get rid of it. While Black tries to deal with the knight, we can continue developing our pieces. } { [%csl Ge4] } 6... Nd7 { Black prepares to play Nf6, aiming to trade off our knight. With Nd7, Black can recapture with the other knight, avoiding doubled pawns. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Yd7f6,Bg8f6] } (6... Nf6?! { Not that great, it leads to a position which is really easy to play as White. } 7. Nxf6+ exf6 { Black now has doubled pawns. } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7] } 8. c3! { The simplest plan here is to prepare d4 and get ready to castle queenside. This setup will give us control of the center while keeping our king safe, allowing for a more aggressive push on the kingside later on. } { [%cal Bd2d4,Gc3d4] } 8... Bd6 9. d4 O-O 10. Be3 Re8 11. O-O-O $16 { White has a solid position with a safe king, the powerful bishop pair, and a strong pawn structure. From here, the plan is pretty straightforward—launch a kingside pawn attack. Try to keep the bishop pair on the board for as long as possible, as they can be very effective. Meanwhile, Black has a lot more harder position: their knight lacks good squares, and the bishop isn't doing much. White has a winrate of 70%. } { [%csl Rb8,Rf6,Gf3,Ge3,Gf1][%cal Bg2g4,Bh3h4,Bh4h5,Bc1b1,Bf1d3] }) (6... e6 7. d3 { We can’t push d4 here, so the plan shifts to developing with Bd2 and castling kingside. The d3 pawn is ready to recapture our knight later, keeping a strong central pawn structure. } { [%cal Gd3e4,Bc1d2,Be1c1] } 7... Nf6 { [%cal Bc1d2] } 8. Bd2 Nxe4 9. dxe4 { We recapture with the pawn. } 9... Nd7 10. Bc3 $16 { We can throw this in before castling. The bishop is quite well placed here, piercing through the center and aiming at the g7 pawn. Next, we'll castle queenside. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Be1c1,Bf3g3] }) 7. d4 { From here we just continue developing normally. } 7... Ngf6 { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] } 8. Bc4 { Black can't take the knight yet, because Qxf7 would be checkmate. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Be1g1] } 8... e6 9. c3 { Protecting the d4 pawn. } { [%csl Yd4,Yb2,Yc3][%cal Yb2c3,Yc3d4] } 9... Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nf6 11. Qf3 $14 { White's a bit better here with the active queen and bishop pair. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc4,Gc1][%cal Be1g1,Bc1g5] } *


