5... d4 { This is another option you'll see occasionally. Black wants to lock the center by playing e5 on the next move. But we’ve got a nice refutation for that. } 6. Bc4! { Aiming at the weak f7 square } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rf3f7,Gc4f7] } 6... e6 { Black blocks our bishop. Now our knight is hanging, so we can simply retreat it. } { [%csl Re6,Rf7] } (6... dxc3?? 7. Qxf7+ Kd7 8. dxc3 $18 { White is completely winning in this position! Black's king is incredibly exposed, and once our dark-squared bishop comes out and we castle queenside, placing a rook on the d-file, Black's position will collapse. There's no way Black can hold on for long here. } { [%cal Bc1f4,Be1c1] }) (6... Nf6?! { Another option, though less popular, leads to a sharp and double-edged forcing line. In many cases, Black ends up making mistakes } 7. e5 { We counterattack the knight, which can’t move from f6 because that would leave the f7 pawn undefended. So, Black has no choice but to capture our knight. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Re5f6] } 7... dxc3 8. exf6 e6 { Blocking the bishop. } { [%csl Re6] } (8... cxd2+?? { Here's where most people mess up. This allows us to quickly castle long, thus getting a rook on the d-file. } 9. Bxd2 exf6 (9... e6 10. Bc3! { Simply threatening to take g7, Black can't take our pawn. } { [%cal Rf6g7] } 10... Rg8 (10... g6 11. Bxe6!! { Totally works great here! We again want to give a check to the the king. } 11... fxe6 12. f7+ { There are lots of ways to win here. } { [%cal Bc3f6,Rf6d8,Rd1d8,Be1c1] }) 11. Bxe6! { A very beautiful idea! } 11... fxe6 { Our f-pawn can now fork the king and rook! } 12. f7+ { We win another queen! } { [%cal Rf7g8,Rf7e8] }) 10. O-O-O $18 { It's +5! Black can't stop all our threats! The Black king won't be able to castle because we'll just play Rhd1 and build up pressure with moves like Bb4. } { [%cal Gd1d8,Bh1e1,Bd2b4] }) (8... exf6 9. bxc3 $16 { We give an open file to our rook. Also the c3 pawn now supports a d4 push. White here simply has better development, and activity. } { [%cal Ba1b1,Bd2d4,Be1g1] }) 9. fxg7 cxd2+ 10. Bxd2 Bxg7 11. Qg3 $16 { We've got a solid position here! We've got the bishop pair, easy king safety, and flexible development options. It's worth noting that 11...Bxb7 doesn't actually win a pawn for Black because after Rb1, our rook skewers the bishop, capturing the b7 pawn, and it'll be strong on the seventh rank. } { [%csl Bc1,Rg7,Gc4,Rb7][%cal Be1c1,Bg3b3] }) 7. Ne2 c5 8. Qg3! $14 { It's a nice multipurpose move! The queen now ties down the dark-squared bishop to the g7 pawn, and by moving the queen, we’re paving the way for an eventual f4 pawn push. After that, we’ll castle and play d3. We’re setting ourselves up for a solid and aggressive attacking position! } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Bd2d3,Bf2f4,Be1g1,Ba2a4] } *


