4. h3 Bh5?! { This is the second most popular move, though Stockfish isn’t a big fan of it. With perfect play, White should come out better in most lines. But it does lead to incredibly tricky positions, so it's best to be prepared. } 5. exd5! { We start with quite a forcing sequence. Trading the pawns, which opens up the a4-e8 diagonal. } 5... cxd5 6. Bb5+! { We develop with tempo, preparing to castle kingside and now Black is forced to play Nc6. } { [%cal Be1g1] } 6... Nc6 { We’d love to play Ne5 here to pile more pressure on Black's c3-knight, but we can’t just yet because our knight is pinned. We'll need to deal with that pin first. } { [%csl Rd1,Rc6][%cal Bf3e5] } 7. g4! { Kicking the bishop away and preparing to play Ne5. } { [%cal Bf3e5] } 7... Bg6 { Although playing Ne5 right away works fine, I prefer to throw in h4 first, chasing the bishop further. } 8. h4 { We’re not immediately threatening to play h5 because of Be4, but once we get Ne5 or Nd4 in, h5 becomes a real threat. If Black responds with Be4 at that point, we can just play f3 to trap it. } { [%cal Rh4h5,Bf3e5] } 8... h6?! { The most popular move! Black creates an escape square for the knight, but this isn’t that great because it allows Ne5 and weakens the bishop. } { [%cal Bg6h7] } (8... e6 { It might look like we can trap the bishop now with h5, but Black can actually still play Be4. So, instead we go ahead with our plan to play Ne5. } 9. Ne5 { We're now threatening to capture on c6, and h5 is now a threat. If Black plays Be4, we can play f3, which we couldn't do before, trapping the bishop . } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rh4h5] } 9... Qc7 { Supporting the knight and attacking ours. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gc7c6,Gc7e5] } (9... Rc8? { Supports the knight but doesn't deal with our h5 threat. } 10. h5! Be4 11. f3! Bd6 { Black tries counterattacking our knight, but this is no problem, we simply defend it. } 12. d4 $18 { We've successfully trapped the bishop. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf3e4] }) 10. Qe2 $13 { This position is extremely double-edged, but mainly for Black. There are a lot of wild lines, and I can't cover them all here, so I recommend checking things out with an engine if you're curious. Just remember, there are plenty of crazy tactics, especially involving Nxd4 sacrifices! }) (8... h5 { Black stops any potential h5 push. We can now play Ne5. } 9. Ne5 Qd6 { White supports both the knight and bishop. } { [%cal Gd6c6,Gd6g6,Rd6e5] } (9... Rc8?! 10. Nxg6 fxg6 11. gxh5 gxh5 12. d4 $16 { Black has light-square weaknesses and no development. } { [%csl Rf7,Rg6][%cal Bc1g5,Bd1f3] }) 10. d4 a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. g5 $14 { Taking away the f6 square from the knight. Black's pieces are all now quite stuck compared to ours. Next is Qf3-Bf4 and castle long. } { [%csl Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Re8][%cal Bd1f3,Bc1f4,Rg5f6,Be1c1] }) (8... f6!? { Quite good actually. Black creates an escape square for the bishop and avoids any Ne5 trickery. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Bg6f7,Rf6e5] } 9. h5 Bf7 10. d4 $14 { White's got a slight edge here thanks to better development and more space. Black’s pieces are a bit cramped, but the pawn structure is solid, so breaking through isn’t going to happen immediately. It’s a position where White has more options to improve, but Black can hold if they play carefully. } { [%csl Gb5,Gd4,Gf3,Gc3,Rf7,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Re8,Rd8,Rc6][%cal Bc1f4,Bd1e2,Be1c1] }) 9. Ne5 { We’re now attacking the pinned knight, so Black has to defend it. Plus, there’s the added threat of capturing the light-squared bishop, which would ruin Black's pawn structure and create weaknesses on the light squares. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Re5c6,Rb5c6,Ye5g6] } 9... Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c6] } (9... Qd6? { Black supports both his pieces, but the drawback is that the queen is on a vulnerable square. } { [%cal Rd6c6,Rd6g6] } 10. d4 a6 (10... Bh7 11. Bf4! { Aligning the bishop with the queen, we're now threatening Nxc6, with windmill tactics. } 11... Qe6 12. Qe2 $18 { Still tricky, but White has the advantage here. After we castle queenside, we should have easier play. } { [%csl Gb5,Ge5,Gc3,Gf4,Rh7,Rh8,Re8,Rg8,Rf8,Ra8,Rc6,Re6][%cal Be1c1,Bh1h3,Bh3e3] }) 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Bf4! $16 { We align our bishop with the queen, creating all sorts of threats! If Black decides to retreat and leaves his bishop undefended, we can just take it and mess up his pawn structure. Things are looking good for us! } { [%cal Re5f7,Rf7h8,Yf4d6,Bc3a4,Ba4c5] }) 10. Qf3 { Nxg6 is an option, but playing Qf3 first is even stronger. Now we're aiming at f7, setting up the serious threat of h5 to kick the bishop, which can't move since it's tied down to defending f7. Plus, we’re also double-attacking the d5 pawn. } { [%csl Rf7,Rd5][%cal Rh4h5] } 10... Nf6 { Acting as a blockade. We can now take the light-squared-bishop. } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7] } (10... e6 11. h5 { We kick the bishop, it can't move away because it has to protect f7. So the only surviving move here is: } { [%csl Rf7,Ge5][%cal Rh5g6,Ge5f7,Gf3f7] } 11... Qc7! $132 { Black counterattacks our knight. } { [%csl Re5] } (11... Qf6?? { Loses material. } 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ba6 $18 { Saving the bishop with tempo. Black now has 2 pieces under attack, he can't save both. } { [%cal Ra6c8,Rh5g6] }) 12. Nxg6! { We take the bishop, damaging Black pawn structure, creating weaknesses and winning a pawn. } 12... fxg6 13. hxg6 $13 { Still incredibly doubled-edged, but with careful play White should be better here. } { [%csl Gb5,Gg6,Gf3,Gc3,Rc6,Re8,Rf8,Rg8][%cal Bd2d4,Bc1f4] }) (10... h5 { Preventing h5. } 11. Nxg6 fxg6 (11... hxg4 { [%cal Rg4f3] } 12. Qd3! { Taking g4 is met with Nf6, so better is moving here the d3, where we can still take g6 later. } 12... fxg6 13. Qxg6+ Kd7 14. Nxd5 $16 { White's doing amazing! } { [%csl Rg6,Rd5,Rb5,Rd7,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rg4] }) 12. gxh5 Rxh5 13. Qg4 $16 { Black has many weaknesses to deal with. Also all the pieces have a hard time getting out. } { [%csl Rg8,Rf8,Re8,Rg6,Rh5,Rd5,Rd8,Rc8,Rc6,Gb5,Gc3][%cal Bh1g1] }) 11. Nxg6 fxg6 { [%csl Rg6] } 12. g5! { Kicking away the defender of d5. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Rg5f6] } 12... hxg5 (12... Ng8 13. Nxd5 $16 { White's doing great here, we're up a pawn with much easier development. White's in control. } { [%csl Gd5,Rg6,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rd8,Rc8,Gb5,Gf3] }) 13. hxg5 { The knight is still forced to leave. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rg5f6] } 13... Rxh1+ (13... Nh5 14. Qxd5 Qxd5 15. Nxd5 { Black has a disgusting pawn structure and is down a pawn. White's doing great. } { [%csl Gd5,Gb5,Gh1,Re7,Rg6,Rg7,Rf8,Re8] }) 14. Qxh1 { [%cal Rg5f6,Rc3d5,Rh1d5] } 14... Nh5 15. Qxd5 { We can finally take the pawn! } 15... Qxd5 16. Nxd5 $18 { White's obviously better here due to the extra pawn and better pawn structure. Stockfish gives White +1.7. } { [%csl Rg6,Rg7,Re7,Rf8,Gd5,Gb5][%cal Bd2d3,Bc1d2,Be1c1] } *


