[Event "CRUSH the French!: 🚀 == Introduction  == 🚀"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense: Two Knights Variation"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the French!"]
[ChapterName "🚀 == Introduction  == 🚀"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/QC0VBa2r"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ ✨ Hi, I'm Bosburp! Welcome to my new study! ✨

🇫🇷 🥖The French Defense... ugh. If you're here, I’m guessing you hate playing against it as much as I do.

But in this study, I’ll share a KILLER repertoire to help you take it down. It’s very tricky to handle as Black, and we have very high win rates! 😃

If you find this study helpful, please give it a heart 💓 under the pinned comment! It helps more players discover this study and adds it to your favorites so you can always find it easily.

If you have any questions or feedback, feel free to DM me! 💬

Let’s get started! Play 1. e4! 🚀 }
1. e4! { "Best by test" } 1... e6! { The French Defense, known for being very solid, and a favorite of Black, being very popular among all levels; beginner or master. There's over 374,000,000 games played only here on lichess. Black prepares to play d5 on the next move.
If you've seen my study against the Caro-Kann ( https://lichess.org/study/64DHMYix ), you might guess what we'll be playing. ;)
Play Nf3! :) } { [%csl Yd5,Gf3][%cal Bd7d5,Ye6d5,Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3! { Our weapon is the Two Knights Variation, a rare yet extremely powerful opening with plenty of traps and great win rates. You could also play 2. Nc3; the move order doesn’t matter much, but Lichess only allows one move.
I also want to note that this opening is played by many top players like Ian Nepomniachtchi, Daniil Dubov, and it's even a favorite of Eric Rosen! } 2... d5 { What do you play now? } 3. Nc3! { Great! This is the beginning of the Two Knights Variation!
You might be looking at the engine and thinking, What? It’s 0.0? Why would I give away my starting advantage?? But with higher risk comes higher rewards, and in this case, the ‘cost’ is almost nothing. Seeing the win rates later on will prove it. Plus, this opening is just so much fun.
There are quite a few lines to explore, but hopefully, I’ve covered most of them.
Remember, don’t just focus on memorizing all the moves and theory, understanding the main ideas and plans is way more important.
Feel free to use the engine and the Lichess database! 🕵
Now, let’s dive into the lines after 3...dxe4. Hit the space bar to move on to the next chapter! 😄 } *


[Event "CRUSH the French!: 💎 Section 1: 3...dxe4"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
