[ChapterName "💎 Section 1: 3...dxe4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/iuKGwIGJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]

1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 { The most popular move, but it isn’t that great, as it allows us to get a knight on e4 immediately. We've already regained our initial edge. This is the move we’ll be looking at in the following chapters marked with 📘. } *


[Event "CRUSH the French!: 📘 4...Nf6"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the French!"]
[ChapterName "📘 4...Nf6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/jU7xaWOc"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/4p3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]

{ Note: I've added a lot of variations in this chapter, so make sure not to skip them! If they’re not showing, click the '+' icon to expand them. :) }
4. Nxe4! { We’ll, of course, recapture the pawn. Now, we have a really annoying knight in the center of the board, which Black obviously doesn’t like. By far the most popular move here is Nf6, challenging our knight and forcing us to either exchange or retreat. } { [%csl Ge4] } 4... Nf6 { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] } 5. Nxf6+! { We can exchange the knights off the board. Now, Black will have to capture with either the queen, bringing it out too early and making it a target, or with gxf6, which doubles the pawns and ruins the kingside structure, making castling kingside no longer an option. } 5... Qxf6 { Pretty much everyone (that is 93%) will capture with the queen, not wanting to give up their kingside castling plans and perhaps thinking the queen is developed nicely here. } 6. d4 { We strike the center with d4 controlling the center, opening up our DSB which might want to go to g5 at some point. So far, we’ve been going over Black’s most popular moves. Now take a moment to look at the win rates. We’re only on move 6, and White’s win rate is already at 59%! That’s not bad against the French! } { [%csl Gc1,Rg5,Yd4][%cal Yd4e5,Bc1g5] } 6... Bd6?! { Most popular under 1800 level. Black simply wants to castle soon. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } (6... h6 { Black sees Bg5 is a potential danger, so Black takes precautions to prevent it. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh6g5,Bc1g5] } 7. Bd3! { We develop normally, preparing to castle and placing the LSB on it's most active square. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Gf1d3,Be1g1] } 7... Bd6 (7... c5 { White's dominating the center, so Black counterstrikes it. } { [%cal Bc7c5,Rc5d4] } 8. Be3! { Simply developing and reinforcing d4. Remember not to play dxc5, since that would only help Black develop his dark-squared- bishop. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ge3d4] } 8... Nc6 { Black develops another piece and adds pressure on our d4 pawn. } { [%cal Rc6d4] } 9. dxc5! { We can take on c5 now since Black won’t be able to recapture with the bishop anyway. And if we don’t take, Black will. Our well-developed pieces will be much more active in the upcoming open position. We're not winning a pawn here, though, because b2 is hanging. } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Ba1b1,Gb1b8] } 9... Qxb2 10. O-O $16 { Bringing the king out of the center. Notice how Black’s bishops will remain passive for a long time, while ours are very actively placed. A good idea here is to trade our f3 knight for Black’s c6 knight, as it’s really Black’s only (potentially) active piece. Oh, and note that there might be Nd4 ideas since we have Bb5 discovered check tactics. We can easily control the b-file, and the d- and e-files are also well within our grasp. Stockfish gives +1.3, and White has a 59% win rate. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge3,Gf3,Rf8,Rc8,Yc6][%cal Ba1b1,Bf1e1,Bf3d4,Yd4c6] }) (7... Nc6 8. c3 { Forming a pawn chain. Note that the d-pawn wasn't really attacked, since we have Bb5 discovered check tactics. So, if you're lower rated, you might want to castle instead here hoping for your opponent to fall for the trap. } { [%csl Yd4,Yb2,Yc3][%cal Yb2c3,Yc3d4,Bd1a4] } 8... Bd6 9. Qe2 $16 { We have a solid position with well developed pieces. Stockfish gives us an edge of +0.6. } { [%csl Be3,Bg1,Yd4,Yc3,Yb2,Gd3][%cal Bc1e3,Be1g1,Yb2c3,Yc3d4,Ba2a4] }) 8. Qe2! { We transpose to a variation below in this chapter. }) (6... Qd8 { Black passively retreats. Not giving his queen up as a target. } 7. Bd3! { We simply develop our LSB. Note how it's move 7 and Black has zero development. } { [%csl Gd3,Bg1,Gf3,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Rh8][%cal Be1g1] } 7... Be7 8. Qe2 { As you've seen in previous lines, this is our standard setup. We don’t want to castle immediately, as we want to keep the option open for a kingside storm with h4-h5 } 8... O-O?! { Black castles into our attack. } (8... Nd7 9. Bf4 Nf6 10. O-O-O $16 { [%cal Bh2h4,Bf3e5,Bg2g4,Bh1e1] }) (8... c5 9. Be3 cxd4 10. Bxd4 $16) 9. h4 $16 { We have a great attacking position. Stockfish gives +1.4, which may not seem like much, but White has a whopping 82% win rate here! It’s almost impossible to survive White’s attack with human play.
Note: There might be Greek Gift ideas, but remember the rules I listed in my Sacrifice like a PRO! study! :) } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7,Bf3g5,Bg2g4,Bh4h5,Bc1d2,Be1c1,Bc2c3] }) 7. Bd3 { We’ll also prepare to castle while setting up a highly successful trap. } { [%csl Rg6,Gd3,Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 7... O-O?? { Very popular! We win on the spot now! } (7... h6 { Higher level players will see that Bg5 is a potential danger. So, Black now controls the g5 square. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh6g5] } 8. Qe2! { Another tricky move! With the idea of forming a battery on e4 if Black were to castle kingside. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Be2e4] } 8... O-O? { Most popular, but Black just castles into our attack. } (8... Nc6 { Developing a piece. Our d-pawn is attacked now. } 9. c3 { Simply forming a solid pawn chain. } { [%csl Gc3,Gb2,Gd4][%cal Yb2d4] } 9... O-O 10. h4! { Striking on the kingside! We have a great attacking position, both our bishops are aimed at the king, while Black's are staring into nothingness. There might be Bg5 ideas here, even a fishing pole! It’s actually a huge threat now since the queen would be trapped, and if Black captures the bishop with hxg5, our rook takes over the entire h-file, leading to checkmate just a few moves later. From here, we just keep attacking. Castling isn’t really a priority. Castling kingside would make our rook inactive, while castling queenside might give Black a chance to counterattack. The engine gives +0.9 } { [%csl Rh6,Yd3,Rc8,Rd6,Gf3][%cal Bc1g5,Rg5h6] }) (8... Nd7 9. Be3 $16 { We have a very comfortable position. We'll castle queenside and attack on the kingside and in the center. } { [%csl Bc1,Gf3,Ge3,Gd3,Ge2,Rc8][%cal Be1c1,Bh1e1,Bh2h4,Bf3d2,Bd2e4,Bf2f4] }) 9. Qe4! { Threatening mate in 1. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rd3h7] } 9... g6 { Most popular, but this hangs the h pawn. } (9... Qf5 { Black blocks the checkmate, but this doesn't work either. } { [%csl Rh7,Gf5] } 10. Qh4! { A discovered attack! } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Rd3f5] } 10... Qa5+ { The queen escapes. Notice how all our pieces are aiming at the kingside, while Black’s pieces haven’t even developed yet. If you’ve seen my Sacrifice like a PRO! study, you’ll know what’s coming, our idea is to rip open the kingside with Bxh6. } { [%csl Rh6,Rg7,Rf7,Rg8,Rf8,Gh4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc1,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Rd6][%cal Yc1h6,Yd3h7] } (10... Qf6 11. Bg5! $18 { A very stylish finish! The queen is trapped. Black can't capture our bishop because of Qh7#. } { [%csl Rg5,Bh7][%cal Rh6g5,Bh4h7,Gd3h7] }) (10... Qd5 11. Bxh6! $18 { Same idea, just we don't have to Qa5+ delay. }) 11. Bd2! { We block with the bishop, not the pawn, to gain valuable tempi. } { [%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2a5] } 11... Qb6 { It doesn't matter where the queen goes. We now continue with our idea. } 12. Bxh6! { The kingside gets ripped open! We'll win very soon now. } 12... gxh6 (12... Qxb2 { Black counterattacks our rook. But we don't mind, we simply play a quiet killer. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Rb2a1] } 13. Qg5! { Both our rooks are hanging, but we have an unstoppable Qg7# threat. All Black's pieces are too far away to do anything. } { [%csl Ra1,Rg7][%cal Bg5g7] } 13... Qxa1+ { If g6, then Qg6, and we Qg7# is still unstoppable. } 14. Ke2 Qxh1 { Black is up 9 points in material, but none of that matters, it's time for checkmate! } 15. Qxg7#!) (12... f5 13. Bd2 $18 { Most simple. Black's kingside is already wrecked—it's only a matter of time before we break in. } { [%csl Rg7,Rg8,Rf8,Rh7,Rh8,Gh4,Gf3][%cal Be1c1,Bf3g5] }) 13. Qxh6 f5 14. Qg6+ Kh8 15. Ng5 $18 { [%csl Gh7][%cal Rg5h7,Rg5f7,Gg6h7] }) 10. Bxh6! { [%csl Rf8][%cal Rh6f8] } 10... Re8 11. O-O-O $18 { Simply bringing our king to safety. Now, we unleash an unstoppable onslaught on the kingside with h4-h5. We have a dominant position, it's already +3.5! } { [%csl Gc1,Bh5,Rg5,Ge4,Gd3,Gf3][%cal Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Rh6g5] }) (7... Nc6 { Again, Black ignores our threat. } 8. Bg5 $18 { [%csl Rd8,Rf6,Yg6,Yf5,Rf4,Rh6,Gg5,Ge5][%cal Rg5d8,Yd3g6,Rg5f4,Rg5h6,Gf3e5,Gf3g5] }) 8. Bg5! $18 { The queen is trapped! You'll have no trouble winning the game from here! :) } { [%csl Rd8,Rf6,Yg6,Yf5,Rf4,Ge5,Gg5][%cal Rg5d8,Yd3g6,Rg5f4,Gf3e5,Gf3g5] } *


[Event "CRUSH the French!: 📘 4...Nd7"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the French!"]
[ChapterName "📘 4...Nd7"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/DsuBAZD0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/4N3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]

4... Nd7 { A better response. Might look weird at first, but the idea behind this move is to support Nf6 on the next move, allowing Black to recapture with the d7 knight instead of weakening the pawn structure by capturing with a pawn or bringing the queen out to early. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Bg8f6,Yd7f6] } 5. d4 { We'll immediately take the center. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd4e5] } 5... Ngf6 { Challenging our knight. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] } 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 { Now Black has a knight on f6 instead of the queen, as we saw in the previous chapter. This is a much more solid approach. } { [%csl Gf6] } 7. g3! { Here, I recommend playing g3, going for the LSB fianchetto and an O-O setup. I think most players will mess up by trying to force an attack or action too soon, but there isn’t anything, Black’s setup is still quite solid. The best option here is to calmly continue developing all our pieces. No need to rush. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1] } 7... Be7 (7... c5 8. Bg2 $16 { Same idea. Of course, if Black captures d4, recapture. } { [%csl Gg2][%cal Be1g1,Ba2a4,Bc2c4] }) (7... b6 { Top engine move. Black also wants to place the LSB somewhere active. } { [%cal Bc8b7,Gb7h1,Gb7a8] } 8. Bg2 { We just continue our plan. } 8... Bb7 9. O-O Be7 10. Qe2 { Many developing moves work here. But I like to get the f1 rook to the d-file. } 10... O-O 11. Rd1 $14 { White has a small edge, but it's equal with perfect play. White's winrate is at 55%. } { [%csl Gd1,Ge2][%cal Bc2c4,Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Ba2a4] }) 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O $16 { We’ve finished our kingside development, and there’s nothing to complain about in our position. From here, just play chess! White has a 58% win rate. } { [%csl Gg2,Gg1,Rc8][%cal Bc2c4,Bf3e5,Bf1e1,Bd1e2] } *


[Event "CRUSH the French!: 📘 4...Be7"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the French!"]
[ChapterName "📘 4...Be7"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/TvH9aNwQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/4N3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]

{ Here’s one more move we need to look at in this section. We’ve covered the main ones, and more importantly, the ideas behind them, since other moves like 4...Nc6 will usually transpose to the same or very similar positions we’ve already covered. }
4... Be7 { Black's idea is to support Nf6 again, this time preparing to recapture with the bishop. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Gg8f6,Be7f6] } 5. d4 { As usual d4, taking the center. } 5... Nf6 (5... Nd7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 (7... Bxf6 8. Qe2 O-O 9. h4! { We've transposed to a very similar position below. The only difference being the knight on d7, but our plans remain the same. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Yd3h7,Bh4h5,Bf3g5,Bf3e5,Bc1d2,Be1c1] }) 8. Qe2! { And we have transposed again! }) 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 { [%csl Gf6] } 7. Bd3 { We play Bd3 again, aiming at Black's kingside. We're still be going for the same setup as in chapter 3; Qe2-h4 } { [%csl Gd3,Rh7] } 7... O-O?! { Very popular, but it castles into our attack. } (7... b6? { With the idea of developing the LSB, since it's stuck behind the e6-pawn. } { [%csl Bb7][%cal Rc8b7] } 8. Be4! { Attacking the rook! The only way to save it is by blocking with c6. } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Re4a8] } 8... c6 { Now, the pawn on c6 is a nuisance, it blocks the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and prevents Black from playing Nc6. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Yb8c6,Yc8b7] } 9. Bf4 $16 { We have a great game. We'll castle queenside and launch a pawn storm on the kingside. } { [%csl Bc1,Gd4][%cal Bd1e2,Bc2c3,Bh2h4,Be1c1,Bg2g4] }) (7... Nd7 8. Qe2 O-O (8... c5 { This is something new. Here we'll take advantage of our queen on e2. } 9. d5! { Threatening dxe6. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Rd5e6] } 9... Nb6 { Opening up the LSB. But this also opens the diagonal to the king. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gc8e6] } 10. Bb5+! { Now anything Black blocks with results in the e6 pawn being undefended. That's why the best move here is Kf8. } 10... Bd7 (10... Kf8! 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. O-O { The position is actually near equal, but I think we can agree that it's more comfortable to play as White here. } { [%csl Gg1,Gf1][%cal Bf1d1,Bc1f4,Bc2c3] }) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Qxe6+ Qe7 13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. Qxe7+ Kxe7 15. Bg5 $16) 9. h4 $16 { [%csl Rh7,Ge4][%cal Yd3h7,Bf3g5,Bf3e5,Ge2e4,Bc2c3,Bg2g4,Bh4h5] }) (7... c5 8. Be3 { Defending the pawn. } 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 { We actually aren't losing a piece here, because of Bg5 discovered check tactics. } 9... O-O 10. c3 $14 { [%cal Bh2h4,Bd1d2,Be1c1,Bg2g4] }) 8. h4 { Threatening a Greek Gift. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7,Bf3g5,Yh4g5] } 8... h6 (8... b6 { Actually most popular, along with other moves that ignore our Greek Gift like Nd7, c5, Nc6, etc... } 9. Bxh7+! $18 { We win with the Greek Gift! As you can see this is a very popular tactic, so if you're familiar with it, check out my free sacrifice course: https://lichess.org/study/q22lMoJU } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Bf3g5,Yd1h5] }) (8... g6 { Stopping Bxh7, but now we just break through the kingside. } 9. h5 $16 { We have a very strong kingside attack. } { [%csl Gh1][%cal Rh5g6] }) (8... c5 9. Bxh7+ $18) 9. Qe2 $16 { Next just keep attacking on the kingside. It's +1.5 } { [%csl Bc1,Ye4,Gf3,Gd3][%cal Be1c1,Ye2e4,Rd3h7,Bf3e5,Rc1h6,Bg2g4] } *


[Event "CRUSH the French!: 🦢 Section 2: 3...Nf6"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense: Two Knights Variation"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the French!"]
[ChapterName "🦢 Section 2: 3...Nf6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/io6dj58N"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Congrats! You’ve just finished Section 1! 🎉 That wasn’t too much, huh?

Let’s move on to Section 2, but first, let’s see if you’ve been paying attention... Do you remember the first few moves? }
1. e4! { Yup! If you didn’t get that, you might want to review the previous chapters. 😉 } 1... e6 2. Nf3! { Or Nc3. } 2... d5 3. Nc3 { Good! } 3... Nf6 { Black plays Nf6, this is the move we’ll be looking at in the following chapters marked with 📖. It’s the most popular move at higher levels. Black applies pressure on our e4 pawn, forcing us to make a decision. exd5 transposes to the (boring) Exchange Variation, which Black doesn’t mind. And d3 defends the pawn but allows Black to play d4, kicking our knight. Instead, we’ll push the pawn forward, kicking Black’s knight. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Ge4e5] } 4. e5 { Hit the space-bar! } *


[Event "CRUSH the French!: 📖 5...c5 with 6...Be7?"]
[Date "2025.03.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the French!"]
[ChapterName "📖 5...c5 with 6...Be7?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Rb4AyiUo/ts8EQsCt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
