4. e5 Nfd7 { Pretty much everyone plays Nd7 here, as we get a position similar to the Steinitz Variation. But we’ll also briefly look at other 4th moves later on. } 5. d4 { We take the center. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4][%cal Gd4e5] } 5... c5 { Black counterstrikes the center with c5. Played pretty much every time. } 6. Bg5!? { Here, I recommend Bg5, the trickiest option for Black to deal with. I first learned about this line from Jonathan Schrantz's channel. Stockfish considers it slightly dubious, but hey, higher risk equals higher rewards! Plus, it’s incredibly hard for Black to find all the computer moves. Black’s queen is now under attack, so they have to either move it or block.
Fun fact: 14% of players just blunder their queen here by playing something like Nc6 or a6. :D } 6... Be7? { In this chapter we'll look at Be7, the most popular move. But this is actually a mistake as we will see soon. } 7. Bxe7 { We take first. } 7... Qxe7 { The reason this is a mistake is that we now have an unstoppable idea, Nb5! Black can’t prevent both the Nc7 fork and the Nd6 outpost, which forces him to lose castling rights. } { [%csl Rd6,Rc7][%cal Bb5d6,Bb5c7,Gc3b5] } 8. Nb5! { Our win rate is at 67%! The only way for Black to kind of survive for now is Kd8, but that move gets played only 2% of the time. We'll look at all the responses. } { [%csl Rd6,Rc7][%cal Bb5d6,Bb5c7] } 8... O-O? { The most popular. Bringing the king to safety. } (8... Na6? { 2nd most popular, covering c7. But d6 is still up for grabs. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Ra6c7] } 9. Nd6+! Kf8 { Black loses castling rights. } (9... Kd8 10. Bxa6 bxa6 11. c4 $18 { the same thing, but this is even worse since the king is on a more dangerous square. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Ba1c1] }) 10. Bxa6 bxa6 11. c4 $18 { And this is horrible for Black, an uncastled king, doubled flank pawns, and undeveloped pieces. Now, we aim to open up the c-file and activate our rook. Stockfish gives +2.5. } { [%csl Ra6,Ra7,Rf8,Bg1,Yc1][%cal Be1g1,Ya1c1,Gc1c8] }) (8... Nb6? { Covering c7. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Ge7c7] } 9. Nd6+ Kf8 (9... Kd8 10. dxc5 N6d7 11. c4 $18 { We break through the center and attack the uncastled king. It's +5 } { [%csl Gd6,Ge5,Gc5,Rb8,Rc8,Re7,Rd7,Ra8][%cal Rc4d5] }) 10. dxc5 $18 { We win a piece. } { [%csl Rb6,Rc8][%cal Rc5b6,Rd6c8] }) (8... Qd8? 9. Nd6+ Kf8 10. c3 $16 { What more could you wish for? :) } { [%csl Yb2,Yd4,Ye5,Yc3,Gd6,Rc8,Rd8,Rf8,Rh8,Rb8,Ra8,Rd7,Gf3,Bg1][%cal Yb2c3,Yc3d4,Yd4e5,Bf1d3,Be1g1] }) (8... Kd8 { The best move. Avoiding Nd6+ and covering c7. } 9. dxc5 { Nd6 isn’t great here since it doesn’t actually achieve anything, Black has already lost castling rights. } 9... Qxc5 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. O-O-O { Black is still in the game, though quite uncomfortably. We’re well developed here. Also, if Black takes on e5, we win with Qg5+! } { [%csl Rg5,Gc1,Gd1,Gb5][%cal Bd2g5,Rg5e5,Rg5g7,Rg5d8] }) 9. Nc7 { We'll now just get that trapped rook. } 9... cxd4 { It doesn't matter what Black does, just take the rook on the next move. } 10. Nxa8 $18 { We won the rook. Yes, the knight will probably not survive, but then we'll still end up being up an exchange with a great position. It's +2.0. Next, focus on getting the king to safety and remember not to hang the e-pawn. :) } { [%csl Rd4,Bg1][%cal Bf1e2,Be1g1,Bd1d2] } *


