7... Bxc5! { This is Black’s best move, developing while attacking our f2 pawn. He's not getting greedy and wisely staying away from the b2 pawn... it’s poisoned! } { [%csl Rf2,Bg8][%cal Rc5f2,Be8g8] } 8. Qd2 { We protect it. } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gd2f2] } 8... Nc6! { Black develops the knight, doubling the attack on e5. This is the best way to continue. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gc6e5,Gd7e5] } (8... Qxb2? { Black can always still give in to temptation! } 9. Rb1! { Taking away most of Black's escape squares. Black has one safe square. } { [%cal Gb1b6] } 9... Qa3 10. Nb5! { Forking the queen and c7. } { [%csl Ra3,Rc7][%cal Gb5a3,Gb5c7] } 10... Qxa2 11. Nc7+ { [%csl Re8,Ra8][%cal Gc7a8,Gc7e8] } 11... Kf8 12. Rc1! $18 { Important! We simply bring our rook to safety. Black's rook remains trapped and we'll take it later. } { [%csl Ra2,Ra8,Rc8,Bg1][%cal Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bc7a8] }) (8... Bxf2+?! { Tho rare, this is an extremely critical and complicated line that we must look at. Out of the entire study, this is the craziest line you’ll see! If you remember all the correct moves you should end up with a winning position. So the point of this move is to deflect our queen from defending our c3 knight, allowing Black to fork our rook and knight with Qxb2. } 9. Qxf2 Qxb2 { [%csl Rc3,Ra1][%cal Gb2a1,Gb2c3] } 10. Kd2!! { We defend the knight, leaving the rook hanging, but Black can’t take it with check anymore. } 10... Qxa1 11. Bb5!! { We sacrifice another rook!! We also pin the d7 knight, which will prove very crucial later on. } { [%csl Re8,Rd7,Ra1][%cal Gb5e8,Gh1a1] } 11... Qxh1 { We’re literally down 9 points in material, but now, we unleash an amazing move. } 12. Qc5! { The point of Bb5! The knight is pinned and can’t capture our queen. Black’s king is trapped like a sardine in a can, and we’re threatening Qe7# and Qxc8#. Now, Black must find a precise sequence to not lose immediately. } { [%csl Rg2,Re7,Rd7,Re8][%cal Gc5e7,Yb5e8,Bg5e7] } 12... Qxg2+ (12... f6?? { Common try, but doesn't work. } 13. exf6 { Qe7# is unstoppable. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Rf6e7,Rc5e7] } 13... gxf6 14. Bxf6 $18) 13. Kc1! { We're able to run the king to safety, so perpetual checks don't work here. } { [%cal Bd2c1,Bc1b2] } 13... Qxg5+! { Black must sacrifice the queen to eliminate the Qe7# threat. } (13... Nc6 { Transposes. } 14. Bxc6 Qxg5+ 15. Nxg5 bxc6 16. Qxc6 Rb8 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Kd8 19. Qxd5) 14. Nxg5 { We're still threatening Qxc8. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Gc5c8] } 14... Nc6 { We get a forced sequence. } 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Qxc6 { [%csl Ra8][%cal Rc6a8] } 16... Rb8 17. Nxe6!! { Absolutely necessary! We cannot let the king castle to safety, we're not actually up material, we only keep our advantage if the king is left vulnerable. } 17... fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Kd8! { Kf8 loses due to Qd6 fork. } 19. Qxd5 $16 { And finally, after all that insane stuff, we’re actually left with a better position! Black’s incredibly weak king gives us the long-term edge. It’s not an instant win, tho, it’ll still take some work but you should be able to manage it. } { [%csl Rd8,Rd7,Rc8][%cal Be5e6] }) 9. Na4! { We want to get rid of Black’s bishop pair by trading our knight for their active DSB. } { [%cal Ra4b6,Ra4c5] } 9... Bxf2+ { This is the top engine move and the choice most advanced players will go for. By deflecting our queen from b4, Black grabs a pawn and wins back the piece with a Qb4+ fork.
Now, you’re probably thinking this looks really bad for us, especially looking at the engine and win rates. But don’t worry, if we go a few moves deeper you'll see we're doing completely fine! } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Bb6b4,Rb4a4,Rb4e1] } (9... Qb4 { Many players, of course, won’t find the Bxf2 line and will simply move the queen to safety instead. } 10. Nxc5 { Taking Black's bishop pair. } 10... Qxc5 (10... Qxd2+ 11. Bxd2 Nxc5 12. O-O-O $14 { We have a queenless middlegame, but we’re slightly better thanks to our bishop pair. } { [%csl Gd2,Gf1][%cal Bh2h4,Bf1b5,Bd2e3] }) 11. Bf4 $14 { Defending the pawn. Our pieces are well-placed, and we’ll castle queenside on the next move. } { [%csl Gf1,Gf4,Rc8,Bc1][%cal Be1c1,Bh2h4] }) (9... Qc7 10. Nxc5 Nxc5 11. Bf4 $13 { Still a very complicated, double-edged position, you’ll see this if you analyze a bit further. But if both players manage correctly, it should be rather equal. Just don’t castle queenside! You’ll run into serious problems with Black’s open c-file and all their pieces aiming at you. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Gf1d3,Be1g1] }) (9... Qa5?? { Small side trap here. } 10. Qxa5 Nxa5 11. Nxc5 Nxc5 12. b4! $18 { Fork! } { [%csl Ra5,Rc5][%cal Rb4a5,Rb4c5] }) 10. Qxf2 Qb4+ { [%cal Rb4a4,Rb4e1] } 11. c3! { Here’s another common mistake White players make. They might play Nc3, but then Black simply plays Qxb2, forking our rook and knight while getting a strong attacking position. So, we must play c3 instead, not deactivating any of our developed pieces! } (11. Nc3?? Qxb2 $19 { We don't actually save the piece. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Rb2c3,Rb2a1] }) 11... Qxa4 12. Be2! { Another key move, we want to castle as soon as possible. We have to prioritize development. Note that Be2 is better than Bd3 because after Nxe5, Black hits our bishop. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 12... Ndxe5 (12... Qe4! { The absolute engine move, but seriously, who plays this? It’s literally only been reached three times ever. } 13. O-O O-O 14. Rae1 Ndxe5 15. Nd4 $15 { Black is slightly better here, -0.6, but it’s really unclear. We still have plenty of compensation for the two pawns, the potentially active bishop pair and an active f-rook. } { [%csl Ge1,Gf1,Gf2,Gg5,Ge2,Rc8] }) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. O-O $10 { And now, despite being down two pawns, the engine says it's equal! We’ve got the bishop pair, a safe king, and a strong battery along the f-file. Our win rate is a whopping 74%, which shows just how quickly Black can go wrong in this position.
A common sample line where Black collapses: 14...O-O 15. Be7 (rerouting to d6) Re8?? and after 16. Bd6! White is completely winning because we remove the defenders of f7, exactly where our battery is aiming.
Another: 14...f6? and 15. Bxf6!! gxf6 16. Qxf6+- White wins. } { [%csl Gg5,Ge2,Gf2,Gf1,Rc8] } *


