{ In this chapter, we’ll rewind a few moves and look at Black’s other 4th moves, specifically, Ne4. }
4. e5 { We’ve looked at 4...Nd7, but you’ll often face 4...Ne4 here as well, especially at lower levels. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Re5f6] } 4... Ne4 { Surprisingly, only 5% of players actually know how to deal with this move correctly.
Most people play 5. Nxe4, getting rid of the annoying knight in the center, but that move is just bad. Black simply recaptures, and our f3 knight is forced to retreat, leaving us with zero development. Plus, our e4 pawn becomes incredibly weak. So, do NOT play Nxe4!
The second most popular move is 5. d4, which is also bad (though not as bad as Nxe4). After Bb4, pinning the c3 knight, we have an uncomfortable position. Black's knight on e4 won’t be removed anytime soon. } { [%csl Ge4] } (4... Ng4? { The knight doesn't do anything here, we'll just kick it away. } 5. h3 Nh6 6. d4 { We have an obvious lead in development. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gc3,Gf3] }) (4... Ng8? { So passive. Black has just wasted 2 moves. } { [%csl Gd4] } 5. d4 { [%csl Ge5,Gf3,Gd4,Gc3,Rg8] }) 5. Ne2! { The correct way to continue! It might look weird at first glance, but there’s a very good idea behind it. We’ll reroute our knight to g3. From there, we won’t mind a trade because we can recapture with either the f or h pawn, which will give us an open file to place our rook. } { [%csl Bg3][%cal Be2g3,Yh2g3,Yf2g3,Rd2d3,Bc3e2] } 5... Bc5 { Threatening Bxf2#. } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Rc5f2] } (5... c5?? { A common blunder from Black. } 6. d3 $18 { All the knight's escape squares are controlled by us! } { [%csl Ge4,Rd6,Rf6,Rg5,Rc5][%cal Gd3e4] }) (5... Nc5 6. d4 Ne4 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 Nxg3 9. fxg3 cxd4 10. O-O $16) 6. d4 { We kick it away. } { [%cal Rd4c5] } 6... Bb6 (6... Be7 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 Nxg3 9. fxg3 { Same idea. } { [%csl Gf3,Gd3,Rf7,Rc8][%cal Be1g1] }) 7. Ng3 { We’ve successfully rerouted our knight to its ideal square. If Black captures on g3, we’re happy, we get an open file. If not, we don’t take the e4 knight right away. Instead, we first add an attacker with Bd3, forcing it to either capture or retreat. } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Bf1d3,Rd3e4] } 7... c5 { Black counterstrikes the center, but we should focus on development and ignore it. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } (7... Nxg3 8. fxg3 c5 9. Bd3 cxd4 10. O-O $16 { [%csl Gf1,Rf7][%cal Bf3g5,Bb2b4,Bb4b5,Ba2a4,Ba4a5] }) 8. Bd3 { We threaten to win a pawn by capturing the knight, leaving Black with no choice but to trade since the knight has no other squares to move to. } { [%cal Be1g1,Rg3e4,Rd3e4] } 8... Nxg3 { Black captures, preventing us from taking him and placing a piece in the center. Here you can actually choose how you recapture, with either hxg3 and fxg3 being good. It's your pick! } (8... Ba5+ 9. Kf1! { Simply bringing the king out of check. } 9... cxd4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Bxe4 $16 { Now, we focus on applying more pressure in the center and attacking on the kingside with h4-h5. Even a Rh3-Rg3 rook lift could be an idea! } { [%csl Ge4,Rd4,Yg3][%cal Bh4h5,Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Bh2h4,Yh1h3,Yh3g3] }) (8... cxd4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 $16 { We have well placed pieces and easy development. The overextended d pawn could be a target. } { [%csl Ge4,Rd4,Bg1][%cal Be1g1,Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Bd1e2,Ba1d1] }) 9. fxg3!? { My preference is taking with the f-pawn, since we’ll castle and our rook will be very active along the open f-file. If you go for hxg3, you’ll focus on activity along the h-file and keep your king in the center. } 9... cxd4 { Black is up a pawn, but we’re focusing on what’s more important: development. } 10. O-O $16 { We have a very comfortable position here, a safe king, a potentially active rook, and well-placed pieces. Black struggles to develop, and moves like O-O?? lose immediately to a Greek Gift. You might not get this exact line in your games, but the ideas are usually the same when Black plays Ne4. } { [%csl Rh7,Rc8,Rb6,Re8,Gg1,Gf1][%cal Bb2b4,Ba2a4,Bb4b5,Bf3g5,Gd3h7,Bd1e2,Bg1h1,Bf3h4,Yf1f8] } *


