Ok, play the first few moves! }
1. e4! { If you're enjoying the study, don’t forget to click the heart button under the h1-square! ❤
This saves the study to your favorites, so you can easily find it again anytime. Plus, it helps more people discover this study. Thanks for the support! 😊 } 1... e6 2. Nf3 { Good! Or Nc3, but personally, I prefer Nf3 first. If Black decides to transpose into the Sicilian French Variation by playing 2...c5 instead of d5, we can go for the Wing Gambit with 3. b4!, which I’m a fan of.
The fellow leader in our team actually made a study on it, so if you’re interested, you can check it out here: https://lichess.org/study/RP1MIzYg/M6OIJAHl } 2... d5 3. Nc3 d4 { Black plays 3...d4, another important move you must be prepared for. (Actually, all 3 sections, 3...Nf6 and 3...dxe4 are played almost equally often, so all sections are pretty important.) Black kicks our knight away, this is the move we’ll be looking at in the following chapters, marked with: 📕. Now we'll retreat our knight to e2, double attacking the d4 pawn. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rd4c3,Gc3e2] } 4. Ne2 { Hit the space bar! :) } *


