[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/3pP3/5N2/PPPPNPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.03.31"]
[UTCTime "10:47:15"]

4... c5 { Black defends his d-pawn. } 5. c3! { We want to eliminate Black's central pawns here. Our queen now gets opened up as well. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc3d4,Gd1a4] } 5... Nc6 { The most popular move, adding another defender to the pawn. } (5... d3? { Black pushes their pawns deeper into our territory, but we can simply attack it again. } 6. Nf4! { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rf4d3,Rf1d3] } 6... c4 7. Qa4+ $18 { A fork! White can grab the pawn on c4 in the next move, and after that, Black's d3 pawn will be impossible to defend. White will end up two pawns ahead. } { [%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Ga4c4,Ra4e8,Bf1d3,Yf4d3] }) (5... dxc3 { Recapturing with the knight is fine, but it's actually better to take with the b-pawn. Doing this opens the g-file for our rook, lets the DSB move along its diagonal, and most importantly, sets up a future d4 pawn push. Plus, the knight is better placed on g3 than c3 anyway. } 6. bxc3 $14 { White's looking great here! We'll pretty much always play Ng3 next, then bring out Bc4 and castle kingside. After that, there are plenty of good options, like Rb1 to take over the open file, d4 to grab more control in the center and open up the DSB more...etc. Lots of flexibility! } { [%csl Ba3,Ba4,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Ba1b1,Bd1a4,Bc1a3,Bd2d4,Gf1c4,Ge2g3,Ge1g1] }) (5... Nf6 { The top engine move, though quite rare. Instead of defending, Black counterattacks our e4 pawn. } 6. cxd4 { We trade. } 6... cxd4 7. Nexd4 Nxe4 8. b3! { Here, I like b3, activating the DSB via a fianchetto. It can't be active with d3, since Black has Qa5+, which is really annoying. We can't move the d-pawn yet without castling first. } { [%csl Bb2][%cal Bc1b2] } (8. Nxe6!? { Actually, this is also an interesting line that leads to a relatively equal position where we trade most of our material and head into an endgame. } 8... Bxe6 9. Qa4+ { Winning the piece back with a fork. } { [%csl Re4,Re8][%cal Ga4e8,Ga4e4] } 9... Nc6 10. Qxe4 Qd5! { The best option for Black is to trade queens; otherwise, it might become potentially dangerous here in the center, where it cannot be easily kicked away. } 11. Qxd5 Bxd5 12. Bb5 { The is quite equal. } { [%cal Be1g1,Bd2d3,Be8c8,Bc1e3] }) 8... Bc5 9. Bb2 $10 { From here, it's equal, and you just play chess. The usual development plans are Qc2-Bd3 and O-O. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Bd1c2,Bf1d3,Be1g1] }) 6. cxd4 { Simplifying. } 6... cxd4 7. Qa4! { Pinning the knight! d4 is now left hanging. } { [%csl Re8,Rc6,Rd4][%cal Ga4d4,Ra4e8,Bf3d4,Ye2d4] } 7... Bc5 { The most popular move, Black defends his pawn. } { [%cal Gc5d4] } (7... Bd7 8. Nexd4! { It's free! } 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 $16 { White is better here. We're up a pawn, control the center, and have easy development. Next is Be2 and castle. Qe3-and pushing the d-pawn is an idea too. The DSB can be activated via b3-Bb2 controlling the diagonal. } { [%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Bd4e3,Bd2d4,Yb2b3,Yc1b2] }) 8. b4! { The only good move! We 'sacrifice' a pawn, but if Black takes, he leaves his d4 pawn undefended. If he doesn't take but moves the bishop away, b5 is a threat, kicking away the knight. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Bb2b4,Bb4b5] } 8... Bxb4 (8... Bb6 9. Bb2! $16 { Adding another attacker to d4. It’s inevitable that we’ll play b5, kicking away a defender and adding another attacker, the queen. We’ll win the pawn and get a great position. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Bb4b5,Yf3d4,Ye2d4,Gb2d4,Ba4d4] }) (8... d3? 9. bxc5 dxe2 10. Bxe2 { White's doing great. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1,Ba1b1,Bc1a3,Bd2d4] }) 9. Nexd4! { We take the pawn with the e2 knight, which also opens up our light-squared bishop. Black has to be very careful now, as we're threatening to capture on c6, which also removes the defender of the bishop. } { [%csl Rc6,Rb4][%cal Bd4c6,Ga4b4] } 9... Qb6?? { A common blunder, Black might think both pieces are protected, but we win a piece by force now. } { [%csl Rc6,Rb4][%cal Bb6b4,Bb6c6] } (9... Ne7 { Black supports his c6 knight, and plans to castle soon breaking the pin. } { [%csl Bg8,Gc6][%cal Be8g8,Ge7c6] } 10. Bb5! { We keep applying pressure! Qxb4 is now a serious threat. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1,Rd4c6,Rb5c6,Ra4b4] } 10... Qa5 { The best move that survives. Black offers a queen trade to relieve White’s pressure. } (10... Bc5? 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Ne5+ Ke8 16. Rb1! $18 { We're up a pawn with a great position. } { [%csl Gb1,Ge5][%cal Be1e2,Bh1c1,Bd2d3,Bc1e3] }) 11. Rb1! { Adding another attacker on the bishop. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rb1b4] } 11... Qxa4 12. Bxa4 Bc5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. d4 $16 { We have a great position with the active rook, strong center, and potentially powerful bishops } { [%csl Rc5,Rc6,Ra7,Ge4,Gd4,Gf3,Gb1,Ga4][%cal Rd4c5,Bc1a3] }) (9... Be7 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6 Nf6 13. Ne5 Bxc6 14. Qxc6+ Nd7 15. Nxd7 Rc8! 16. Nf6+ Kf8 17. Qd7 gxf6 18. Qxa7 $16) (9... Qa5 10. Qxa5 Bxa5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Ba3 $16 { Our DSB is an absolute menace, causing Black significant difficulties, including issues with castling. The c6 pawn is weak, our knight has easy access to active squares, and our rook can quickly take control of the b- or c-file. } { [%csl Rc6,Ga3,Bb1,Bc1][%cal Bf3e5,Ba1b1,Bb1c1] }) 10. Nxc6 { Removing a defender of the bishop. } 10... bxc6 { Black must capture with the pawn, because the queen has to keep the bishop protected. } 11. Rb1! { A skewer! Bxd2+ doesn't work because of Nxd2, keeping the rook protected. } { [%csl Rb6,Rb4][%cal Gb1b6] } 11... a5 { Black defends his bishop, here you could play a3 which is equally good. But we have a much more stylish option. } 12. Rxb4!! $18 { We sacrifice the rook! If axb4, we take Black's a8 rook. If the queen captures on b4, it leaves the c6 pawn undefended, allowing us to take it with a fork on the king and rook. Black can resign. :) } { [%csl Rc6,Ra8,Yb4][%cal Ya5b4,Ga4a8,Ba4c6] } *


