4... Nc6?! { You're almost always going to get a line from the previous chapter, but some beginners will play Nc6 here, which isn't great since it blocks the c-pawn. From here, we just play the same ideas as in the previous chapter, except this is worse for Black because of his blocked c-pawn. } 5. c3 { Same idea as the previous chapter. } 5... e5 { This is slightly different, Black can now play e5 because the c3 knight supports it. But we have the same idea, cxd4 and Qa4 pinning the knight. } (5... dxc3 6. bxc3 $14 { Same idea as the previous chapter! } { [%cal Be2g3,Bc1a3,Ba1b1,Bd2d4,Bf1b5] }) (5... d3 6. Nf4 $16 { We win the pawn by force. After that, we can play g3, fianchetto, castle, and expand on the queenside. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rf4d3,Bg2g3,Bf1g2,Bb2b4,Ba2a4,Bb4b5] }) 6. cxd4 exd4 7. Qa4! Bc5 (7... Qe7 { A move not playable in the previous chapter, but it's no problem. } 8. d3 { We simply defend. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] } 8... Qb4+ (8... Bd7 9. Nexd4 { White is up a pawn. } { [%csl Gd4] }) 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. Bd2 Bc5 11. Rc1! { [%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c5] } 11... b6 12. Bf4 $16 { Black cannot defend his c-pawn without leaving the d pawn hanging. } { [%csl Rc7,Gf4,Gf3,Ge2,Rd4] }) 8. b4 Bb6 9. Bb2! $16 { Same ideas. } *


