{ [EDIT]: Thank you all for 500 hearts!

Hello everyone! 🌟 Welcome to my new study about how to crush with 1. f4!!, or the Bird opening 🦅 (named after 19th-century player Henry Bird), also known as the Dutch Attack. 1. f4 might at first sound like a joke to you, but in this study, I'll reveal its intriguing aspects that make it a worthwhile opening to learn. Even famous grandmasters like Magnus Carlsen, Hikaru Nakamura, and Maxime Vachier Lagrave have used this opening regularly in their games.

The Bird is quite rare, played only 1% of the time, making it a fantastic way to surprise your opponents! 🎉

Feel free to utilize the engine and the Lichess database, and don't forget to explore the variations! 🕵️

Let's launch right in! 🚀 Play 1. f4 this time :) }
1. f4! { This is the Bird Opening!
1. f4 does weaken the h4-to-e1 diagonal, so white should definitely not play any careless moves. The point of f4 is to control the center and also in the future if white would castle kingside, our rook will enjoy the extra space.
The Bird Opening is definitely an aggressive and tactical opening, so if you are a more positional and safe player, this opening is probably not for you.
There are many moves here for black, but hopefully I covered most of them.
Note: my lines will not always be the absolute top engine move, they are rather based on which one is more comfortable to play as a human and have a decent winrate.
Go to the next chapter! :D } (1. e4 { 1. f4 this time ;) }) *


