2. Nf3 c5 { You'll come across this situation often, but no worries if black goes for something different like Nf6 or Nc6. We just stick with the setup we talked about in the last chapter. } 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Bg4 { No need to worry about this in the current variation, thanks to the following move: } 4. Bb5+! { Just take whatever black blocks with. } 4... Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3! { Now we just continue the setup. } 6... e6 7. Bb2 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2) 4. Bb5! { Preparing to execute a castling move. } 4... Bd7 (4... a6) 5. b3! { Preparing to fianchetto the dark squared bishop. } { [%csl Bb2][%cal Bc1b2] } 5... a6 { You'll often see this situation, and it's important to know what to do. Usually, it's not a good idea to trade a bishop for a knight, but here's a special case. Our light-squared bishop isn't doing much, while Black's knight is strong (or has the potential to become strong), controlling two important squares in the center. So, it's okay to happily exchange our bishop for their knight in this situation. } { [%csl Rb5,Gc6] } (5... Nf6 6. Bb2! { We just continue the setup! } 6... e6 7. O-O Be7 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 a6 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Ne5 { Setup complete! } 11... Qc7 12. Rf3! { [%csl Bh3,Bg3,Gb2,Ge5,Gd2,Gg1,Re7,Rc6,Rc7][%cal Bf3g3,Bg3h3] }) 6. Bxc6! Bxc6 { Now, Black's bishop isn't in an ideal position either. } { [%csl Rc6] } 7. Ne5! { Now, White can quickly benefit from the fact that Black isn't controlling the crucial e5 square. White's knight is fantastically placed here. } { [%csl Ge5] } 7... Qc7 (7... f6?? { A common beginner mistake! Black really wants to get rid of our annoying knight on e5, but this fails miserably due to Qh5+. } 8. Qh5+! g6 $7 9. Nxg6! { the pawn is pinned. } { [%csl Rg6,Yh8][%cal Rh7g6,Yh5h8] } 9... hxg6 10. Qxh8 $18 { We enjoy the extra exchange. }) (7... Nf6?! 8. Nxc6! { It's okay to exchange these, because it damages black's pawn structure. If we wouldn't have traded, black would play something like Qc7 followed by Nd2, and our e5 knight is forced away anyway, and we can no longer damage black's pawn structure. } 8... bxc6 $14 { 2 doubled pawns and an isolated a pawn. At this point we can just continue with our usual setup. } { [%csl Rc6,Rc5,Rd5,Ra6,Rf8,Re8,Rd8][%cal Be1g1,Bc1b2,Bd2d3,Bb1d2] }) 8. Bb2 { Continuing with our setup. Our bishop is very strong here, it now controls the a1-h8 diagonal. } { [%csl Gb2] } 8... Nf6 { A developing move. } (8... f6?? 9. Qh5+ { The same thing as the variation above. }) 9. d3 { Preparing to bring the knight to d2. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Bb1d2] } 9... e6 10. Nd2 Be7 { A better option is keeping the knight protected. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge7f6] } (10... Bd6?! { A slightly dubious move, because it will lead to some problems in the future involving leaving the knight only protected by an important kingside pawn. } 11. O-O O-O? { Black has just castled into disaster. We now play a nice sequence: } 12. Nxc6! { Opening up the monster on b2! } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gb2f6] } 12... Qxc6 13. Bxf6! { We rip open the kingside! } 13... gxf6 14. Qh5! { Bringing the queen closer to black's king. The poor king is now fully exposed, so our plan now is to bring more pieces into action. } { [%csl Rf6,Bg3,Yh6,Yh4][%cal Bf1f3,Bf3g3,Yh5h6,Yh5h4] } 14... Kh8 (14... f5 15. Qg5+! Kh8 $7 16. Qf6+ Kg8 17. Rf3! { Mate is unstoppable without losing huge amounts of material. White will get on the next move get the rook on the g file and the king is completely exposed. } { [%csl Rg8,Yg7,Yh8][%cal Yf6g7,Yf6h8,Bf3g3,Bg3g8] }) (14... Kg7 15. Rf3 { The same idea! } { [%csl Bg3][%cal Bf3g3] } 15... Rg8 16. Raf1 $18 { Bringing another monster to the party. Meanwhile black's queen and bishop are just chilling behind their own pawns. After the king runs away, we will definitely grab some free pawns and get a great position! } { [%csl Rd6,Rc6,Bg3,Bg8,Bg7,Rh7,Rf6][%cal Bf3g3,Bg3g8] }) 15. Rf3 $18 { It's no surprise black will get mated soon. In fact, there's only one move that doesn't lead to an immediate mate, which is Rg8. Mr. Fish gives +3.0 } { [%csl Gh3,Yh7,Rf7,Rf6][%cal Gf3h3,Yh3h7] }) 11. O-O O-O 12. Rf3! { And white gets all the fun! Stockfish says it's equal, but for a human, it's really hard to survive. Look at white's winrate, it's 67%!! :D } *


