2. fxe5 d6! 3. exd6 Bxd6 { Black gets enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. Black is actually already threatening mate in 3. White only has one good move here. } { [%csl Gd6,Gd8] } 4. Nf3! { Controlling h4. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gf3h4] } (4. Nc3?? { Leads to checkmate. } 4... Qh4+! 5. g3 $7 Qxg3+! 6. hxg3 Bxg3# { Checkmate! Don't fall for this. } { [%csl Re1][%cal Gg3e1] }) 4... g5!? { The most popular move, black plays hyper-aggressive. Black immediately wants to kick away our knight. If we just play some random move, it will lead to us losing material. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Bg5g4,Bd8h4] } 5. g3 (5. h3?? { 20,000 players have made this blunder, so DO NOT play h3! } 5... Bg3# { [%csl Ge1,Gf2,Gg3][%cal Gg3e1] }) (5. Nc3?? g4 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Bd8h4,Rg4f3] } 6. Nd4?? Qh4+ 7. g3 $7 { Same tactic. } 7... Qxg3+ 8. hxg3 Bxg3# { Checkmate! } { [%csl Re1,Rf2][%cal Gg3e1] }) 5... g4 { Black kicks our knight away. } 6. Nh4! Ne7 { black wants to reroute to g6, to get rid of our knight. } 7. d4 Ng6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 { Black now has an open file. Black is also threatening to take g3, because the h pawn is pinned. } { [%cal Gh8h1] } 9. Qd3! { An important move! White protects g3. } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gd3g3] } 9... Nc6 10. c3! { Forming a solid pawn chain. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Gb2][%cal Gb2c3,Gc3d4] } 10... Bf5 11. e4 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge4f5] } 11... Qe7 { pinning the e pawn } { [%csl Rf5,Ye1][%cal Re4f5,Ye7e1] } 12. Bg2 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gg2e4] } 12... O-O-O 13. Be3! { Unpinning the e pawn. } 13... Rde8 14. Nd2 $16 { White survives all that chaos, and can now castle queenside on the next move. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Gd2e4,Yg2e4,Bd3e4,Be1c1] } 14... Rxh2?? { A very common try from black, but it fails... } 15. Rxh2 Bxg3+ 16. Ke2! { Keeping the bishop protected, now black's LSB is hanging. } { [%csl Ge3,Rf5][%cal Ge2e3] } 16... Bxh2 17. exf5 $18 { White gets a free bishop. } 17... Bf4 *


