2. fxe5 { White can go ahead and chomp up that pawn. } 2... d6 { We can take that too. } 3. exd6 Bxd6 { Now black has already developed the DSB. Black's already threatening mate in 3, so white has only 1 good move. } { [%csl Gd6] } 4. Nf3! { Controlling h4. The queen can no longer go there. } { [%csl Bh4][%cal Bf3h4] } (4. Nc3?? { A common beginner mistake, white has ignored black's main threat. } 4... Qh4+! { [%csl Ge1][%cal Gh4e1] } 5. g3 $7 Qxg3+! 6. hxg3 $7 Bxg3# { it's checkmate! } { [%csl Ge1,Gf2,Re2,Rd2,Rd1,Rf1][%cal Gg3e1] }) (4. g3? h5! { White's gonna have some trouble. }) 4... Nf6 (4... Bg4 { The second most popular move. } 5. e3! { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gd1f3] } 5... Nc6 { Note: after Nf6 we play the same thing. } (5... c5 { Controlling d4 } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] } 6. Be2 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nc3 Re8 10. e4 $14 { White has a solid setup, an open f file for the rook, and up a clean pawn. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge4,Gc2,Gf1][%cal Gc2d3,Gd3e4] }) 6. d4 { [%csl Gd4,Ge3][%cal Ge3d4] } 6... Nf6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. c3 { Building a solid pawn pyramid. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge3,Gb2][%cal Gb2c3,Gc3d4,Ge3d4] } 8... Re8 9. O-O $16 { White has a nice and solid position, up a pawn, a half open f file, and a safe king. Now an idea for white is to push the e pawn and free up the dark squared bishop. }) 5. Nc3 { White's knights are now controlling the center. } { [%csl Ye4,Yd5,Bd4,Be5][%cal Yc3e4,Yc3d5,Bf3d4,Bf3e5] } 5... O-O { Black gets the king out of the center, we should do the same. } (5... Ng4 6. g3! { White avoids any Nxh2-Bg3 checkmates. } 6... h5! { Black keeps going for the attack and will almost always play h4 on the next move. } 7. d3 { freeing the DSB. } { [%csl Gc1][%cal Bc1g5] } 7... h4 8. gxh4 Nxh2!? { An interesting move! White can't take the knight on h2 because black wins it back with Qxh4 tactics. Then our king is forced to bongcloud. } (8... Rxh4? 9. Bg5! { We're actually not forking the rook and queen, instead white's forcing black to trade material. } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gg5d8] } 9... Be7 { DON'T take the rook, white gets in trouble after 9...Bxh4+, and the king has to dance around. } 10. Bxe7! { trading a bad bishop for black's good bishop. } 10... Qxe7 11. Qd2! { White's king will castle queenside now and be up clean pawn. Ne3 is responded with Nd1. Be careful with the e1-h4 diagonal though. }) 9. Bg5! { A very important move! White can not allow the queen to take h4. } 9... f6 { The d8-h4 diagonal is now blocked. } { [%csl Rf6,Rd8] } 10. Be3! $14 { White is now safe. Yes, it looks scary, but white's actually a bit better because of more pieces developed. The king will have to go to d2 after Bg3+, but black can't hurt him further from there. After 10...Ng4 just keep the DSB on the bird by playing Bf1 and get an e4 pawn push. }) 6. g3! { Preparing to fianchetto the LSB, and castle. } { [%csl Bg2][%cal Bf1g2] } 6... Nc6 7. Bg2 { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 7... h6 8. O-O $14 { Next up is d4, and then try to push e4. White's up an extra pawn, has a safe king, and has the f file opened up for the rook. It's still about equal, but it's a bit easier to play as white with the extra pawn. } { [%csl Gf1,Gg1,Gg2][%cal Bd2d4] } *


