2. fxe5 Nc6 { The Schlechter Gambit. Most times Black will transpose into similar positions as the From's Gambit. } 3. Nf3 { Simply protecting the pawn. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5] } 3... d6! { Black wants to trade pawns for a lead in development. } 4. exd6 { We are now up a full pawn. } 4... Bxd6 { Black has a lead in development. We still have to be very careful, black often still has a few tricks up his sleeve involving the e1-h4 diagonal. } { [%csl Gd6] } 5. d4 { Taking the center and freeing the DSB. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc1] } 5... Nf6 { Black prepares to castle and often plays Ng4 at some point. } { [%csl Bg4,Bg8][%cal Bf6g4,Be8g8] } 6. Bg5 { Preventing Ng4 by pinning the knight. } { [%csl Rf6,Rd8] } 6... h6 { Kicking the bishop away. } 7. Bxf6! { A VERY important move, we simply get rid of the knight, which can potentially get really annoying. } 7... Qxf6 8. c3! { Keeping everything solid. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Gb2][%cal Gb2c3,Gc3d4] } 8... Bg4 (8... O-O 9. e4 { Same thing. } { [%csl Bd2,Bc1][%cal Bb1d2,Bd1c2,Be1c1] }) (8... Bf5 { Preventing an immediate e4. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf5e4] } 9. Nbd2 { Preparing to play e4. } { [%csl Be4][%cal Gd2e4,Be2e4] } 9... O-O-O 10. e4 Bg4 11. Be2 Bf4 12. O-O $16 { White is completely fine. }) 9. Nbd2! { Again, keeping everything solid. The plan now is to castle queenside and play e4 at some point freeing the LSB. } { [%csl Bf3,Bd2][%cal Bd2f3] } 9... O-O-O 10. Qc2 $16 { Next up is e4 and O-O-O and white has a slight advantage because of the extra pawn. } { [%csl Bc1,Be4][%cal Be1c1,Be2e4] } *


