{ In this chapter we'll be looking at common beginner mistakes. }
2... fxe4 { Black happily takes the free pawn. } 3. d3! { Offering a pawn trade, most of the time black accepts. } 3... exd3 4. Bxd3 $32 { White is down a pawn, but now white dominated the b1-h7 and d1-h5 diagonals! White is actually already threatening mate in 3. } { [%csl Gd3,Rf7,Rg6,Rh5][%cal Gd3b1,Gd3h7,Bf3h5,Bf3d1] } 4... Nc6?? { Or any other random move that completely ignores our threat. Surprisingly, this has been played over 1,400 times in the lichess database. } (4... g6? { A common attempt. } 5. f5! $16 { We just immediately start crushing black's kingside open. gxf5 loses due to Qh5#. No matter what, just take g6 on the next move and white has a nice advantage. }) 5. Qh5+! { [%csl Re8][%cal Gh5e8] } 5... g6 $7 { The only legal move. } 6. Qxg6+! { Bxg6 also works, but isn't this a bit nicer? } 6... hxg6 $7 { Again, the only legal move. } 7. Bxg6# { A nice checkmate while being down a full queen. } { [%csl Rd8,Rf8,Re7,Rd7,Gf7,Ge8][%cal Gg6e8] } *


