3... Nf6 { Black doesn't want to let white get the developed LSB. } 4. dxe4 { Just recapturing. } 4... Nxe4 5. f5! { Controlling the g6 square. White immediately has the dangerous threat of Qh5+. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Bf5g6] } 5... Nf6! { The only good move. Black controls the h5 square. } { [%csl Rh5][%cal Rf6h5] } 6. Be2!? { g4 is also possible, but I find this the most trickiest move for black to deal with. There's only 1 move that keeps the advantage for black. That is the very surprising c6! The point of this is that it opens the diagonal for the queen. Sample line: 6...c6 7. Bh5+? g6 8. fxg6 Qa5+! wins the bishop. } 6... h5? (6... c6! 7. Bd2! { Preventing any checks. } 7... Qb6 8. Nc3! Qxb2? { White gets lots of compensation for the pawn. } (8... d6 9. Bh5+ g6 10. fxg6 hxg6 11. Bxg6+ Kd8 12. Nf3 $13) 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Bh5+ g6 11. fxg6 hxg6 12. Bxg6+ Kd8 13. Nf3 $10 { You get an interesting game. }) (6... g6? 7. fxg6 hxg6 8. Bd3 Rg8 9. Nf3 $14 { White has more than enough compensation for the pawn. Surprisingly, Stockfish only gives white a slight advantage. } { [%csl Bg1,Rg6][%cal Be1g1] }) (6... d5? 7. Bh5+! g6 (7... Nxh5 8. Qxh5+ g6 9. fxg6 hxg6 10. Qxh8 $18) 8. fxg6 hxg6 9. Bxg6+ Kd7 $18) (6... e5? 7. Bh5+ Ke7 8. Bg5 $16 { [%csl Re7] }) 7. Nf3 { White has a very comfortable position. If black allows us, white should reroute the knight to g6 by Nh4-Ng6. 7...h4 is followed by Bg5 which wins the pawn. } { [%csl Bh4,Bg6,Bg1,Rf7,Re8,Rf8,Rd8,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Rh8,Bg5][%cal Bf3h4,Bh4g6,Be1g1,Bc1g5] } *


