1. f4 g5!? { This is the Hobbs Gambit. It's really rare, so you probably won't face this, but it's still good to know what to do against it. Black actually has a pretty decent winrate. } 2. d4! { Stockfish's favorite option. Black has damaged their own kingside, white can just continue developing. The f pawn is now defended. } { [%csl Bc1] } 2... gxf4 3. Bxf4! { Our bishop is well placed here. } { [%csl Gf4,Gd4] } 3... Bg7 4. e3 { Protecting d4, and freeing up the light squared bishop. } { [%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Ge3d4,Ge3f4] } 4... c5 (4... d6 5. Nf3 { We can just continue developing. } 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg4 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. O-O $16 { White is fully developed. Stockfish gives +1.0 } { [%csl Gd3,Gf4,Gf3,Gf1,Gc3] }) 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. exd4 Qb6 7. Na3! { A very rare move, it sets up a really nice trap. } 7... Qxb2?? { Black got a bit too greedy ;)
We can punish it immediately. } (7... Nf6 8. c3! { Forming the solid pawn chain and still tempting black with the juicy b pawn. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3,Gb2][%cal Gc3d4,Gb2c3] } 8... Qxb2?? 9. Nc4! { Same thing } 9... Qxc3+ (9... Qb5 10. Nd6+! exd6 11. Bxb5 $18) 10. Bd2 $18 { Again it's trapped. }) 8. Nc4! { We win the queen in all lines! } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gc4b2] } 8... Qc3+ (8... Qb5 9. Nd6+! { Discovered check! } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gf1b5] } 9... exd6 10. Bxb5 $18) (8... Qb4+ { Another attempt to save the queen. White must now play a bit more harder move to find: } 9. c3! { White must not let the queen escape to a4! } { [%csl Ra4][%cal Gd1a4] } 9... Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 { The queen is finally trapped. After black sacrifices it for the rook or something, white will end up with a sweet material advantage. } { [%csl Ga5,Gb4,Gc3,Ba3,Be3,Rb3,Rc2,Bb2,Yd3,Yc4,Gd2][%cal Gd2a5,Bc4a3,Bc4e3,Rd1b3,Bc4b2,Yf1d3] }) 9. Bd2 $18 { The queen is trapped! } { [%csl Ga5,Gb4,Gc3,Ra3,Yc4,Yd3,Ge3,Rb2][%cal Gd2a5,Rc4a3,Yf1c4,Gd2e3,Rc4b2] } *


[Event "WIN with 1. f4! | Bird Opening: 🔍Horsefly Defense 1...Nh6!"]
[Date "2024.02.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A02"]
[Opening "Bird Opening: Horsefly Defense"]
[StudyName "WIN with 1. f4! | Bird Opening"]
[ChapterName "🔍Horsefly Defense 1...Nh6!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/jTcC0b7Q/50aC1mVk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2024.02.21"]
[UTCTime "09:25:23"]

1. f4 Nh6!! { This is honestly an absolute brilliant move. It's probably the most annoying defense Bird players face. The point of this move is that the Knight is actually much better placed on f5 than f6. I recommend that you check out this amazing study by @GRXbullet which almost fully covers it. https://lichess.org/study/qpTWyTks Thankfully, Nh6 is very rare, so you probably won't have to deal with it to much. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Bh6f5] } 2. Nf3 d5 3. b3 { Doing our usual setup. It doesn't matter if you play e3 or b3 first. } 3... Bg4 { Recommended by GrX, this line is really annoying for white. Black's winrate is at 54% :| } (3... c5 { The most popular move. White can now just continue the 'setup'. } 4. Bb2! { Just continuing with our setup. } 4... Nc6 { You might start to get scared seeing that black's winrate is at 52%, but don't worry, they equal out real soon. :D } 5. e3 Bg4 6. Bb5 e6 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 $16 { White has a slight advantage. In some lines you can even decide to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the kingside where black's king is. } { [%cal Bb1d2,Bd2d3] }) 4. e3 { Solidifying and freeing the LSB, also white's queen can now recapture f3 if black captures it. } 4... Nf5 { The best move and recommended by @GRXbullet. } 5. h3! { @GRXbullet doesn't cover this move, but it's actually top-engine. } (5. Be2!? { If you absolutely want to avoid the draw, 5. Be2 is the best option. } 5... e6 (5... Bxf3?! 6. Bxf3 { Suddenly, the position doesn't look dangerous anymore. We can now just continue developing how we always do. } 6... h5 7. Bb2! { IMPORTANT! In these type of positions you DO NOT want to take the h pawn, black will get the open h file for the sacrificed pawn. That will lead to all sort of trouble for white. Instead we just continue developing. Note that when black wants to trade their knight for our light-squared bishop we don't mind. The knight on f4 is very strong, so we'll be glad to see it off the board. }) 6. O-O h5! { Black immediately attacks on the kingside. } 7. Nc3 { Just developing more pieces. } 7... Nc6 8. d4 $15 { This move avoids the dangerous d4 pawn break. White has a very Stonewall-ish setup. It is scary considering black's kingside attack, but with accurate play white should be able to defend. Stockfish gives black a -0.3 advantage. If you don't want to risk playing in this position, you should probably go for the draw line. } { [%csl Gf4,Gd4,Ge3,Gh8][%cal Ge3f4,Ge3d4] }) 5... Ng3 { This is not such a huge problem. } 6. Rg1 Bh5 (6... Nxf1?! 7. hxg4! Ng3 8. Bb2 $14 { From the eight moves black made, five of those were knight moves. White's doing completely fine. } { [%cal Bg8h6,Bh6f5,Bf5g3,Bg3f1,Bf1g3] }) 7. Kf2! { Attacking the knight. The only safe square is e4. } 7... Ne4+ 8. Ke1! { If black doesn't go for the draw line, just expand the kingside with g4 and it's 100% equal. Stockfish recommends black to just take the draw. } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Bg2g4] } 8... Ng3 (8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 $10 { White is actually okay. It's 100% equal. Yes, white's king has lost castling rights, but it's actually okay in the center. Castling kingside for black is not a good idea anymore. White will just get a massive attack on the kingside with a pawn storm. } { [%csl Bb2][%cal Bc1b2,Bg2g4] }) 9. Kf2 Ne4+ 10. Ke1 { If both players agree, you get this draw line. } *


