{ Welcome to section 1! Let's first introduce you to the gambit we'll play. Follow the arrows! } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd2d4] }
3. d4! { Immediately we are threatening to take e5. } { [%cal Rd4e5] } 3... exd4 { Black takes on d4, breaking down the central tension. This is most popular and the mainline.
Now we are going to hit black with a much more rarer move which is only being played 3% of the time.
Play 4. c3! } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 4. c3! { This is the beginning of the Bird Gambit! (Not actually named after Henry Bird, by the way.) We gambit a pawn but in return will get a ton of development and initiative.
"Hey, this isn't Stockfish's top move!" Yes, that's true, but as I've mentioned in the intro, we are going for FUN + AGGRESSIVE, and this opening absolutely delivers! It's kinda has the Danish, Goring Gambit vibes. } 4... dxc3 { Again, most popular, and actually leads to the most fun stuff.
We'll be looking at this move in the following chapters. We'll respond with... } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4] } 5. Bc4! { Has white gone mad, sacrificing a second pawn!? Yes, we are, but in return, we're get HUGE compensation for it, and this is the move I’m recommending. Of course, White could have just recaptured the the pawn with the knight and white would also get some compensation for it, but 5. Bc4! will lead to way more active and tactical positions. With Bc4 we are aiming at the vulnerable f7 pawn and we are able to castle anytime we want.
Btw, this position is also reachable directly with the Danish Gambit: 1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Bc4 d6 5. Nf3
Our winrate is at 58%. The eval is -0.2, so really nothing dubious. I fully recommend you play this OTB.
🎯 Practice the Bird Gambit through gameplay 🎯
📕 Double Accepted: https://go.noctie.ai/bird-double-accepted
📕 Accepted: https://go.noctie.ai/bird-accepted } *


