[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

5... cxb2 { This is the double-accepted variation. } 6. Bxb2 $44 { Advantages for white:
1. The king is ready to castle
2. The two bishops are dominating the a1-h8 and a2-g8 diagonals
3. The queen can come join the attack very easily
Advantages for Black:
1. Has 2 extra pawns
White is almost fully developed and it's still move 6, meanwhile every single piece from black is on the 8th rank.
With perfect play it's 100% equal, but for humans, I think white's going to have lots of fun :) } { [%csl Gf3,Gc4,Gb2,Bg1,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rg8,Rf8,Rh8,Bd5,Bb3][%cal Rb2a1,Rb2h8,Be1g1,Yc4a2,Yc4g8,Bd1d5,Bd1b3] } 6... Be6 { The most popular move for Black. Looks dubious, but it's totally playable, Black will have to be careful in the following moves. } 7. Bxe6! { We can trade, giving Black a weak e-pawn. } 7... fxe6 { As you can see, e6 and b7 and Black's weak points. We will immediately exploit both with our following move. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7] } 8. Qb3! { Forking both pawns. Black's best option is to accept the fact that they're gonna lose a pawn and develop with Nc6 or another developing move. Just a reminder. The position is still 100% equal, but White has a whopping 64% winrate. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7] } 8... Qc8?? { By far the most popular, but a losing blunder. Black got too greedy here. } (8... Nc6! { Instead of taking one of the pawns (and getting chased away) we can bring the king to safety. } 9. O-O! Qc8 { Never too late to get greedy. Black decides he wants to defend the pawns anyway. } (9... Qd7! { Your opponent is very high level. Do not take b7, Black will skewer the queen and bishop. } 10. Nbd2 { Instead we prioritize finishing development. We have a very comfortable (yet, according to the computer, equal) position. White's winrate is at 56%. o-o-o, is a dubious move here, because we've got the open b and c files to attack the king. if Nf6, follow up with Ng5 - e5 breaking the center and get the rooks on the d file. } { [%csl Gd2,Gf3,Gb2,Gb3][%cal Ba1b1,Bb1d1] }) 10. Ng5! { Adding pressure. } 10... Nd8 11. f4 $16 { And we try to attack along the f-file. Black's king isn't castling to safety any time soon. } { [%csl Gb3,Gb2,Gg5,Gf1,Rd8,Rc8,Ra8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8] }) (8... b6? { Also very popular. } 9. Nd4 { Of course not Ng5 as it would leave the knight hanging. ;) it's 2 attackers vs zero defenders. } { [%csl Re6] } 9... e5 { The only way to not lose the pawn, but we just hop the knight in here. } 10. Ne6 $16 { [%csl Ge6] }) 9. Ng5! { Attacking the pawn again. } { [%cal Bg5e6,Yb3e6] } 9... Ke7 { The only way to protect the e6 pawn, but we take it anyway! } (9... Nf6 { A bit too late huh? } 10. Nxe6 Nc6 11. O-O $18 { Stockfish gives white a +3.3 advantage! Our king is much safer, and we got a octopus knight on e6. You don't want to trade the knight for the passive DSB tho, the knights worth much more. Also, Nxe4 leads to Re1 which is absolutely crushing. } { [%csl Gg1,Re8,Ge6,Gb3,Gb2][%cal Be6c7,Be6d8,Be6f8,Be6g7,Be6g5,Be6f4,Be6c5,Be6d4] }) (9... e5?? { Also too late, should have been played a move earlier. } 10. Qf7+ Kd8 11. Qxf8+ Kd7 12. Qf5+ Kd8 13. Nf7+ { Forcing the king away from the queen. } 13... Ke7 14. Qxc8 Kxf7 15. Qxb7 $18) (9... d5?? { Another attempt. } 10. exd5 { Simplifying. } 10... exd5 11. O-O $18 { And Black's just stuck. White has too much development. All the pieces will flow in soon. It's 4.3. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Bf1e1,Bb1c3,Bg5e6,Bb2a3] }) 10. Nxe6! Qxe6 { Now the queen has left her b pawn hanging. } 11. Qxb7 { The rook is trapped. } { [%csl Ra8] } 11... Nc6! { It's very important that this is covered. A very nice trap from black. DO NOT TAKE THE ROOK! Black will get enough counterplay after Qxe4. If Black plays anything else besides Nc6, just take a8 and be happy with your great position and material advantage. } 12. Qxc6! Rc8 { Keeping c7 defended. } (12... Rb8?? { This is the most played move being played 50% of the time. This just loses immediately. } 13. Qxc7+! { [%cal Rc7e7,Rc7b8] } 13... Qd7 14. Qxb8 $18) 13. O-O Nf6 14. Nd2 { The computer gives white a +3 advantage. Black's king is awkwardly placed and Black's pieces have a hard time developing. White has a great attacking position. } { [%csl Gb2,Gd2,Gc6,Re7,Re6,Rf6,Rf8,Rc8][%cal Bf2f4,Ba1c1,Bc1e1] } *


