6... Nf6 { Here Black's idea is to castle as quickly as possible. Extinguishing most of White's attack, leaving Black with 2 clean pawns up. } { [%cal Bf8e7] } 7. Qb3!? { Of course we won't allow that. We have to take the initiative. This is the most successful and aggressive option, setting up a battery aiming f7. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 7... Qe7?! { Black defends the f7 pawn, but the downside of this move is that the DSB takes longer to develop longer, resulting that the king isn't castling soon. ;) } { [%csl Rf8][%cal Ge7f7,Ge7e4] } (7... d5! { This is the best move, although rare. } 8. Bxd5 Nxd5 { Black gets rid of the annoying LSB. } 9. exd5 { We keep the queens on the board of course. Note that our DSB is aiming at g7. } { [%csl Gb2] } 9... Qe7+ { Black gives a check, as there is no good way to block it. } 10. Kd1! { A nice resource. Threatening Re1. } { [%csl Be8,Be7][%cal Bh1e1,Be1e8] } 10... Kd8 { Black also forced to move the king, getting out of the e-file. } 11. Re1! { And here Qb4 is forced due to tactical resources that allow White to win some material. Then the queens get traded of and it's a roughly equal game (0.3 for Black), although more double-edged than you might think. }) (7... Be6? { I don't know why people play this, but it's the 2nd most popular move. } 8. Bxe6 fxe6 { Black has voluntarily created these weaknesses. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7] } 9. Ng5 $16 { The best way to exploit it. Taking with a knight is much better than with a queen. } { [%csl Gg5,Re6][%cal Bg5e6] }) 8. O-O! { Bringing the king to safety and indirectly defending the e pawn. If Black would take e4 white plays Re1 and is winning. } 8... Nc6? (8... Qxe4?? 9. Re1 { Bxf7 is even better, but it's more complicated, so Re1 is just the most simple way to win. } 9... Qxe1+ 10. Nxe1 $18) (8... Nxe4?? { Causes so many unnecessary complications. } 9. Re1 { [%csl Ge8,Re4,Re7][%cal Ge1e8] } 9... f5 10. Nc3 { Adding pressure. } 10... Nc6 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Bd5 $18 { White's completely winning. } { [%csl Re4,Gb2,Gb3][%cal Rd5e4,Be1e4,Rd5c6] }) (8... Nbd7 9. Ba3! $16 { Nc6 developing also works, but Black has Nc5 which is just a bit annoying, having to move the queen and all. Now the bishop covers c5, if Black plays it anyway just take it and follow up with e5 which is completely winning.
From here develop normally. Make sure not to trade queens and play aggressively. } { [%csl Re7,Re8,Rf8,Rd7,Rc8][%cal Bb1c3,Ba1d1] }) 9. Nc3 $16 { Here you get a very good game with a 75% winrate. Below are the general ideas and common (pretty much you'll always face them if you reached this point) blunders from Black. I urge you not to attempt to actually memorize all these, but I'm giving you some ideas, if familiarized with a bit, will help you play this opening very successfully. As, many transpositions will lead to this position. But feel free to move on to the next chapter if you want. } 9... g6?? { This is a common attempt to try to bring the king to a safer place, white can just execute the same idea, which is hopping the knight to d5 and try to break open the center. This is a blunder because it opens the diagonal for our DSB to shine! } (9... Na5?? { The most popular option, attempting to get rid of the very strong LSB, but it fails miserably because of Qa4+ and the knight is forced back to c6. } { [%csl Gb3,Gc4][%cal Ga5b3,Ga5c4] } 10. Qa4+! Nc6 11. Nd5! { [%csl Ge7,Gf6][%cal Gd5e7,Gd5f6] } 11... Qd8 (11... Nxd5 12. exd5 { The knight is pinned, so there is no way to save it. } { [%cal Gd5c6,Gf1e1] } 12... Bd7 13. dxc6 Bxc6 14. Qb3 { White is totally winning here. } 14... O-O-O 15. Bxf7 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 $18 { [%csl Gg1,Gb2,Gf7,Rf8,Rd8,Rc8,Re7,Rh8,Rc7,Rb7,Ra7][%cal Bf1c1,Ba1b1] }) 12. Rae1! { The idea of this move is to support pushing the e pawn. } 12... Bd7 (12... h6?? { Now white can demonstrate the power of the rook on the e file. } 13. Nxf6+! gxf6 14. e5!! { Immediately ripping open the center. } 14... dxe5 15. Nxe5! fxe5 16. Bxe5 { White is crushing here, there is no way to stop all white's threats. } { [%csl Gh8][%cal Ge5h8,Ya4e8,Be1e8] } 16... Rg8 17. Bxc7+ $18) 13. Qb3 Na5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qc3 Nxc4 16. Nxf6+ Ke7 17. Nd5+ Ke8 18. Qxh8) (9... Be6?? 10. Nd5! { We can take the b7 pawn anytime! } { [%csl Ge7,Gc7,Gf6,Yb7][%cal Gd5e7,Gd5c7,Gd5f6,Yb3b7] } 10... Bxd5 11. exd5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxb7 Rd8 14. Rfe1 { There is to much pressure on e5, and black's largest problem is that the king is still stuck in the center. Stockfish gives white a +8.4 advantage. } { [%csl Re8,Re7,Rd8,Rf8,Rf6,Ge1,Ga1][%cal Bb2e5,Be1e5,Yb7a7,Yb7c6,Yc4b5] }) (9... Bd7?? 10. Nd5 { again hopping in the center. } { [%csl Gc7,Ge7][%cal Gd5c7,Gd5e7] } 10... Nxd5 (10... Qd8 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Bxf7+ Ke7 13. Bh5 $18 { [%csl Re7,Rd7,Rf8,Rd8,Rc6,Gb3,Gb2,Gh5,Gf3] }) 11. exd5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxb7 { White just grabs the free pawn. } 13... Rd8 14. Bxe5! Qxe5 15. Rfe1 $18 { again skewering the queen. } { [%csl Ge8,Ge5][%cal Ge1e8] }) (9... b6?? 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Na5 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qc2 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 O-O-O 15. Rac1 $18 { White is clearly winning. An idea here if the bishop moves away is to bring the knight to c6 and get a Lolli mate. } { [%cal Gc1c8,Bc4a6,Bf3d4,Bd4c6] }) (9... Bg4?? 10. Qxb7! $18 { a fork! } { [%cal Gb7a8,Gb7c6] }) (9... Qd7 10. Rfe1 Na5 11. Bxf7+!! Qxf7 12. Qb5+ Nc6 13. e5!! dxe5 (13... Ng4 14. exd6+ Be6 (14... Kd8?? 15. Qg5+ Nf6 16. dxc7+ Kxc7 17. Qf4+ Bd6 (17... Kb6 18. Qe3+ Kc7 19. Nb5+ Kd8 20. Rad1+ $18) 18. Nb5+) 15. Qxb7 $18) 14. Nxe5 $18 { There are too many threats for black to deal with. White has a + 8 advantage. }) 10. Nd5! { Immediately opening the diagonal! There is nothing black can do to save their self. } { [%csl Yh8,Yf6][%cal Yb2h8,Bd5f6,Bd5e7] } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5! { [%cal Gd5c6,Gb2h8] } 11... Ne5 { blocking the DSB. } 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bxe5! { We can now take advantage of the fact that the king is stuck in the center and the e file is open. After Qxe5 we play Re1 and win the queen. } 13... f6 { a attempt to save the rook. } 14. Bg3! { Just moving over to let the rooks do their job. } { [%cal Bf1e1,Ba1d1] } 14... Kd8 { Getting out of the e file. } 15. d6 { Now we crush open the d file. } 15... cxd6 16. Rfe1! { White just has to keep hitting the queen. } 16... Qd7 (16... Qc7 17. Bb5 { threatening mate on e8. } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gb5e8,Ge1e8] } 17... Bd7 18. Rac1 Qb8 19. Bxd7 Kxd7 20. Qf7+ Kd8 21. Re8#) 17. Bb5 Qc7 18. Re8# { [%csl Gd8,Ye8,Yd7,Rc7,Rc8,Ge7][%cal Ge8c8,Yb5e8,Ge8e7] } *


