6... Nc6 { Very often Black will be transposing to the same position as the previous chapter. } 7. Qb3 { Setting up the battery aiming at f7. We will be seeing this Qb3 idea very often :) } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 7... Nh6 { Protecting the f7 pawn. } (7... Qe7? 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nc3 { We have transposed to the same position as the previous chapter. }) (7... Be6 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. O-O $10 { The b-knight will usually develop to a3, where doesn't block any pieces and can reroute somewhere better. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7,Gb2,Gb3][%cal Bb1a3] }) 8. O-O! { We bring our king to safety. } 8... Na5 { The most common move from Black and the engine's top choice. Black wants to get rid of our annoying LSB, we want to keep it, so we only have one good move here: } { [%cal Ra5b3,Ra5c4] } 9. Qa4+! { This way we can move our bishop away. } { [%cal Ra4a5,Ra4e8] } 9... c6 { Blocking check and defending h5. } { [%cal Gd8a5] } (9... Nc6?! { This move just doesn't achieve anything, Black's just horsing around :) } 10. Nbd2! $16 { We just continue developing! Note that 10. Nc3?! would be worse because it blocks the diagonal of our monster on b2. }) 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 { Retreating the bishop. Or Bd3, both are fine. } 10... b5 { Of course, Black won't allow our queen to sit comfortably here. } 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Nbd2 $10) 10... b5 11. Qc2 $14 { With a very comfortable position. Black's knights are grim on the rim, and castling remains a huge difficulty. from here continue playing aggressively, try to keep Black's king in the center, and refrain from trading material. h4 is an idea, undermining b5, thus Nbd2-c4 reroute is possible. } { [%csl Gd3,Gc2,Gb2,Ye4,Gf3,Rh6,Ra5,Re8,Rf8,Rd8,Rc8,Rh8,Ra8][%cal Bf1e1,Ba2a4,Bb1d2] } *


