{ Ok, let's take a few steps back. We've now (pretty much) covered everything about the double-accepted variation. Now we move on to other 5th moves. So this might be considered the beginning of section 1.5. }
5. Bc4 { WARNING: This is definitely the most crazy line of the entire study. Don’t say I didn’t warn you. ;) } 5... h6? { 5. h6 is played 11% (242,000+ games) of the time. Black was probably scared of a future Bg5, but now we have a INSANE series of BRILLIANT moves that no human would survive and even if Black plays perfectly White will still have an advantage. } 6. Bxf7+!! { Incredibly rare, but top engine move. This isn't some crazy dubious nonsense, the engine approves all this! None of Black's pieces are developed, so we will get a huge attack! } 6... Kxf7 7. Ne5+!! { The pawn is pinned! The most popular move here is Ke8?? which loses immediately. } { [%csl Bd8,Re5][%cal Bd1d8,Rd6e5] } 7... Kf6 (7... Ke8?? { Most popular. Ends things to quickly, we sadly can't go into the crazy lines above. } 8. Qh5+! { White will get the queen to f7, which is checkmate! } { [%cal Bh5f7,Ge5f7,Ge5d7] } 8... Ke7 (8... g6 9. Qxg6+ Ke7 10. Qf7# { [%csl Gd7,Ge8,Ge7,Ge6,Gf6,Rd6,Rd8,Rf8,Bf7][%cal Gf7d7,Gf7e8,Gf7e6,Gf7f6,Be5f7] }) 9. Qf7# { [%csl Gd7,Ge7,Ge8,Ge6,Bf7,Rd6,Rd8,Rf8,Gf6][%cal Gf7d7,Gf7e8,Gf7e6,Be5f7,Gf7f6] }) (7... dxe5? 8. Qxd8 $18 { White is better. We will probably still pick up a few more pawns later on. } { [%csl Gc8,Gc7,Gc3,Bg1][%cal Gd8c8,Gd8c7,Gb1c3,Be1g1] }) (7... Ke7 { Avoids the crazy kinghunt by giving up the rook. } 8. Ng6+ Kd7 9. Nxh8 $18 { it's +2.6. The knight isn't getting trapped here. } { [%cal Bb1c3,Bc3d5,Bh2h4] }) 8. Qf3+!! { Again the only move that keeps the advantage. The king must not move back. } 8... Kxe5 9. Qf7!! { The only winning move again! White now doesn't allow the king to come back home. Bf4+ is a serious threat. } { [%csl Ge6,Gf6][%cal Gf7e6,Gf7f6] } 9... Nf6 { Controlling d5 and cutting of the queen from defending stuff along the f-file. } { [%csl Rd5,Rf7][%cal Rf6d5] } (9... Qf6?? 10. Qd5# { [%csl Gf5,Ge5,Ge6,Gd4,Bd5,Rf6,Rd6,Yf4,Ge4][%cal Gd5f5,Gd5e6,Gd5d4,Be4d5,Yc1f4] }) 10. Nxc3! { From here on, I recommend you don't trust the engine too much. The position is simply too complicated, it often shows a move as best, only for the eval to suddenly drop after you play it. But don’t worry, I’ve dug deep into this line, and what I’m showing here is fully analyzed and practical.
Now we're supporting the e4 pawn (not allowing the king to take it).
This point has almost never been reached before, either White doesn’t know the previous key moves, or Black has already fallen into one of the losing lines before getting this far. } { [%cal Rf2f4] } 10... Be6?? { This move seems to be one the most natural, being the most popular of the handful of games that have reached this position. If your opponent plays it, be happy, you’re going to play an Immortal Game worthy of your personal collection.
There are a too many possible 10th moves here, and we can’t cover them all. But I’ve included a few key examples so you get a feel for the attacking ideas. If Black chooses something else, you’ll need to rely on your attacking skills, but know the position is fully winning for you. } (10... d5! { This will be the PERFECT line for Black. The only move that survives. } 11. Bf4+!! Kxf4 12. Nxd5+ Qxd5!! { The only move that doesn't lose immediately. } (12... Kxe4 13. O-O-O $18) 13. exd5 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 Bd7 15. Qxg7 Bb5+ 16. Kg1 Nbd7 17. Qg3+ Kf5 $14 { White's still a bit better because of Black's horrible king placement. But you'll never face this line. }) (10... Qe8?? { Most times Black will probably play a pretty random move that doesn't address our threat. } 11. f4+! Kd4 $7 12. Qb3! { The key, keep these two in mind. From here it's impossible to stop mate (except sacrifice the queen and a ton of other material). The king's in a mating net. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Be1g1,Bc3e2,Bc1e3,Rb3c4] }) (10... Qd7?? 11. f4+ Kd4 12. Qb3 { The same thing. } { [%cal Rc3e2,Bc1e3,Ya1c1,Be1g1] }) 11. Bf4+!! { The only move that leads to mate! White forces the king away from the LSB and is always ready to bring the rook into action. } { [%csl Ga1] } 11... Kxf4 (11... Kd4 12. Qxe6 d5 13. O-O-O+ Kc4 14. b3+ Kxc3 15. Bd2+ Kd3 16. Be1+ Ke2 17. Rd2# { Checkmate on the 2nd rank! }) 12. Ne2+!! { The only move that leads to mate. Preparing an f4 push. } { [%cal Bf2f4] } 12... Ke5 { Defending the LSB. } { [%cal Ge5e6] } (12... Kxe4 13. Qxe6+ Kd3 14. O-O-O#) 13. f4+!! { The only move that wins, again. We force the king away from the bishop. } 13... Kxe4 $7 14. Qxe6+! Kd3 $7 15. O-O-O#!! { What a beautiful way to finish of the game! White castle checkmates while being down 7 points in material! } { [%csl Ye2,Yc4,Ye3,Ye4,Gd4,Gd3,Gd2,Bc3,Rc2][%cal Ye6e2,Ye6c4,Gd1d4,Be2c3,Rc1c2] } *


