[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

{ We're still in the 5th moves. Most often, Black doesn't feel safe taking 2 pawns, so they'll play a seemingly "safer" move. This next line will be very similar to chapter 3. The only difference being that Black hasn't taken b2. }
5... Be6! { This is the most popular move. We can follow our ideas. } 6. Bxe6 fxe6 { [%csl Re6] } 7. Qb3! { [%csl Re6,Rb7,Rc3] } 7... Qc8?? { By far the most popular move, being played 50% of the time. } (7... b6? { Another common mistake } 8. Nxc3! { we don't have to take the e pawn immediately, first let's pick up the hanging c pawn. } 8... Qd7 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd7e6] } 9. Nd4! { double attacking the e pawn. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd4e6,Gb3e6] } 9... e5 10. Ne6! Nf6 11. Bg5 Nc6?? (11... c6 12. f4 $16) 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nd5! { [%csl Gf6,Gc7][%cal Gd5f6,Gd5c7,Ge6c7] } 13... Qxe6 14. Nxc7+ { [%csl Ge6,Ge8][%cal Gc7e6,Gc7e8] } 14... Kd7 15. Nxe6 { white is up a queen. }) (7... cxb2 { We simply transpose to the lines in previous chapters. } 8. Bxb2) 8. Ng5! { [%cal Gg5e6,Yb3e6] } 8... Ke7 9. Nxc3! { Nxe6 right away is fine, but Black might get some counterplay with a 10...d5. Now we simply keep the e pawn protected. The Nxe6 idea remains. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc3e4] } 9... h6?? { By far this is the most popular move. } (9... Na6 10. f4! h6 11. Nf3 $18 { White can now castle and try to break open the f file to make the rook active. Meanwhile Black's pieces haven't left the 8th rank except the grim knight on the rim and the king. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc3,Gb3,Bg1,Ra6,Re7,Rf8,Rg8,Rc8][%cal Be1g1] }) (9... b6? 10. Nd5+ { A nice resource. } 10... exd5 11. Qxd5 { Black will have to play Nh6 to prevent Qf7+ and then we take the free rook. } { [%csl Ra8,Rf7][%cal Rd5a8,Rd5f7] }) (9... Nc6 10. Nxe6 Qxe6 11. Qxb7 { Our idea. } 11... Nd4 { A counterattack that looks scary, but it's nothing to fear. } 12. Bg5+ { Bringing the bishop out with tempo, clearing the backrank connecting the rooks. } 12... Nf6 13. Qxa8 Nc2+ 14. Kd2 { [%csl Gh1] } 14... Nxa1 15. Rxa1 { We have an amazing position. We'll still pick up a couple of pawns later on. } { [%csl Ra7,Rc7] }) 10. Nxe6! { Note: we can take e6 after Black plays any move, except after Na6 white has to play f4, and also gets a great position. Or b6, which are in the variations above. } 10... Qxe6 { Now b7 is left undefended, so we can just go ahead and take it! } 11. Qxb7 $18 { Nice, white wins in 11 moves. Whatever black plays just take the rook and you have a sweet advantage. :) } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gb7a8] } *


