5... Nc6 6. O-O! { Qb3 is also fine, the move order doesn't matter too much. We simply bring the king to safety. Note if Black would ever take b2 we will have transposed to one of the positions in the previous chapters. } 6... Nf6 7. Qb3! { [%csl Rf7] } 7... Qe7?! (7... Qd7! { This is better than Qe7 because now black blocks any future checks from White on the a4-e8 diagonal. } 8. Nxc3! { We develop while recapturing. } 8... Na5 9. Qb5 Nxc4 10. Qxc4 Be7 11. e5! { we want to open up the d file, so that we can place our rook on d1. } 11... dxe5 12. Rd1! { Now our rook dominates the d file. } { [%cal Gd1d8] } 12... Qe6 (12... Qc6 13. Qxc6+ bxc6 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Ra7] } 14. Nxe5 $10 { it's an equal game. } { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Ra7,Ge5,Gd1,Gc3] }) (12... Bd6 13. Nxe5! { White takes advantage of the pinned bishop. } { [%csl Re5,Gd7][%cal Rd6e5,Gd1d7] } 13... Qe7 14. Qb5+! Bd7? { A mistake! it leaves the b7 pawn undefended. } (14... c6?? 15. Nxc6! { [%csl Ge7,Be8][%cal Gc6e7,Bb5e8] } 15... bxc6 16. Qxc6+ { A fork! } { [%csl Ga8,Ge8][%cal Gc6a8,Gc6e8] } 16... Qd7 17. Re1+! Be7 18. Qxa8 $18 { White is up an exchange with an amazing position. }) (14... Kf8 15. Bf4 $10 { It's an equal game. }) 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Re1+! { we can just throw in this check, the rook will be more active on the e file than the d file. } 16... Be7 17. Qxb7 $16) 13. Qxc7 O-O?? { By far the most popular move, being played a whopping 82% of the time! This natural/safe looking move loses due to this simple yet game-winning move. } (13... Bd7 14. Qxb7 O-O { It's an equal game. }) 14. Ng5! $18 { The queen is forced to leave the bishop undefended! The next move white can just take the bishop on e7 } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gg5e6] }) 8. Nxc3 { At this point, the top 3 most popular moves are really bad for Black. } 8... Na5?? { The most popular move. Black wants to trade their passive knight for our active bishop. We won't allow that of course! } (8... g6?? { Now the g pawn is no longer protecting the knight on c6. We can take advantage of this with this next move: } 9. Bg5! { pinning the knight. } { [%csl Ge7,Gf6][%cal Gg5e7] } 9... Bg7 10. Nd5! { reinforcing the pressure on the f6 knight. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gd5f6,Gg5f6] } 10... Qd8 11. e5 dxe5 12. Rad1 { Lining the rook up with the queen. } { [%csl Rd8] } 12... Bd7 13. Nxf6+ { Opening up the diagonal for our battery. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 13... Bxf6 14. Bxf7+ Kf8 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Rxd7 $18 { White has an extra piece on the board. }) (8... Be6?? { This move simply leaves the b7 pawn up for grabs. } 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Qxb7 { forking two pieces } { [%csl Gc6,Ga8][%cal Gb7c6,Gb7a8] } 10... Rd8 11. Qxc6+ Nd7 12. Bg5 Qf7 13. Bxd8 $18) (8... Ne5? 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Bg5 { Pinning the knight. } { [%csl Ge7,Rf6][%cal Gg5e7] } 10... c6 11. Rfd1! { Now the rook dominates the d file. } 11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nb5! { Threatening to fork, and we have a nice trap... } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gb5c7] } 13... cxb5?? (13... Bc5 14. Nc7+ Kf8 15. Nxa8 $18) 14. Bxb5+ { The rook controls the d file so black is forced to bongcloud or sac the queen! } { [%csl Bd8,Bd7][%cal Bd1d8] } 14... Ke7 15. Qb4+ Qd6 16. Qxd6# { A beautiful checkmate! } { [%csl Ge7,Gd8,Gf6,Ge6,Be8,Bd7,Rf8,Rf7][%cal Gd6f8,Gd6d8,Gd6f6,Yb5e8] }) (8... Qd7! { Black prevents any future checks if the knight were to move away. } 9. Re1 Na5 10. Qb5 Qxb5 11. Bxb5+ c6 (11... Kd8 12. Ng5 Be6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Rxe5 $14 { [%csl Ge5,Gg5,Gb5,Gc3][%cal Bc1e3,Ba1d1] }) 12. Bf1! Be7?? (12... Be6 13. b4 Nc4 14. Nd4 Nb6 15. b5 c5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. a4 $16 { [%csl Gc3,Gf1,Gg1,Re6,Rd6] }) 13. b4 $18 { The knight is trapped. }) 9. Qa4+! { The knight is forced back again! } 9... Nc6 10. Ng5! { Double attacking the f7 pawn! There is no way to protect it without losing material. } { [%cal Gg5f7,Yc4f7] } 10... Be6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Ba6!! { This move is not really hard to find, but it's definitely beautiful! If Black takes our bishop we win a full rook with Qxc6 forking the king and rook. } { [%csl Gb7,Rc6,Ra8][%cal Ga6b7] } 12... O-O-O (12... Rb8 13. Bxb7! { The only winning move! White eliminates the defender of the c6 knight. } 13... Rxb7 14. Qxc6+ { [%csl Gb7,Ge8][%cal Gc6b7,Gc6e8] } 14... Qd7 15. Qxb7 $18 { White is up a rook, you should be able to win this easily. :) }) 13. Qxc6! { We can take this free knight because the pawn is pinned. } { [%csl Rb7,Bc8][%cal Rb7c6,Ba6c8] } 13... bxa6 14. Be3! { There is no need to immediately take Black's pawns. White should just bring more pieces into the attack on the weak king. } 14... Kb8 15. Rac1 $18 { White is way better. Black will very probably get mated very soon. An idea is to lift the rook to the b-file. } { [%csl Gc1,Gc6,Ge3,Ra6,Rb8,Ra7,Rc7,Rf8,Rh8,Rf6,Gg1] } *


