5... Nf6 6. e5!? { An interesting move with a clever idea! } 6... dxe5?! { Most popular again. Black has now opened up the d file. } (6... Ng4! 7. Qb3! { Continuing with our aggressive play. } { [%csl Rf7] } 7... Qd7 (7... Qe7 8. O-O Nxe5 9. Nxc3 $16 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Bf1e1,Bc1g5] }) 8. O-O Nxe5 9. Re1 Nc6 10. Nxc3 Be7 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 dxe5 13. Bxf7+ Kf8 14. Be3 $10 { [%csl Rf8,Rc8,Ra8][%cal Ba1d1,Bc3a4,Bc3e4,Bf7c4] }) (6... Qe7 { Leads to a really crazy line. } 7. O-O dxe5 { If you want to play for a win you can play Nxc3. It's an equal position. If you want a quick draw, you can follow the next moves. } 8. Ng5 Be6 { Forced defending f7. } 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Qb3 { Hitting b7 and e6. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7] } 10... cxb2 11. Qxb7! { Sacrificing the rook and allowing Black to promote?? } 11... bxa1=Q 12. Qc8+! { Don't take the rook! Then Black is up a queen! } 12... Qd8 13. Qxe6+ Be7 14. Qf7+ Kd7 15. Qe6+ { A draw despite being down 16 points in material. ;) }) 7. Bxf7+! { A classic deflection! Black cannot take the bishop, because otherwise the king will lose his wife. To be clear, with perfect play White only remains with a small advantage, but Black messes up almost all the time. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Rd1d8] } 7... Ke7 { Here most people mess up. White must play the following key move. } (7... Kxf7 8. Qxd8 $18) 8. Qb3! { Important! Keeping the bishop defended and refusing a queen trade. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 8... Nc6 { [%csl Ge5] } (8... Qd6 9. O-O $16 { White's just better here because of the better placed king and development. 70% winrate. Many people as Black here mess up with Be6. Trade bishops, and then Qxb7 and White's winning. } { [%csl Gf3,Gb3,Gf7][%cal Bb1c3] }) (8... c2! { Top engine. The queen cannot take it because she's busy defending the LSB. } 9. Nc3 Nc6 { Defending the e pawn. } 10. Bc4 $14 { Simply retreating the LSB, so that the queen is no longer tied down. From here it's quite equal. Although much easier to play as White because of active development and Black's misplaced king. The c2 pawn is most likely able to be won at some point, but no need to rush taking it. Also, Na5 for Black is bad here because of Qb4+, winning material. } { [%csl Rc2,Gc4,Gb3,Re7,Rf8][%cal Be1g1,Bc1g5] } 10... Na5) 9. bxc3! { A better recapture than Nxc3, because now the DSB is opened up. } { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gc1a3] } 9... Na5?? { This is the 2nd most popular move. } (9... Qd3 { the best move for black. } 10. Ng5! h6?? { Ignores our threat. } (10... b5! { The only surviving move. Not allowing the bishop to come back to c4. } { [%csl Rc4] } 11. Nd2 $14 { White's a bit better here. It's a nice attacking crazy game. }) 11. Ba3+ Kd8 12. Bc4! { Preparing to put the knight on f7. } { [%csl Yf7][%cal Yg5f7,Bc4d3] } 12... Qg6 13. Nf7+ Ke8 14. Nxh8 Qxg2 15. Rf1 Qe4+ 16. Be2 $18) (9... Qd6?? { For some reason this is the most popular move, it blunders away the queen. } 10. Ba3 $19 { [%csl Ge7,Gd6][%cal Ga3e7] }) 10. Ba3+! Kd7 (10... c5 11. Bxc5+! { Just take it! } 11... Kd7 12. Qe6+ Kc7 $7 13. Qxe5+ Bd6 14. Bxd6+ Qxd6 15. Qxa5+ b6 16. Qe5 $18 { White has an extra horse and will also get the queens of the board, eliminating any counter-play for black. }) 11. Nxe5# { [%csl Gd7,Ye8,Ye6,Be7,Bd6,Rc7,Rd8,Rc8,Gc6][%cal Ge5d7,Yf7e8,Yf7e6,Ba3e7,Ge5c6] } *


