5... Bg4?? { A move that gets played sometimes, mostly by beginners. This move completely ignores our threat of Qb3 forking up 2 pawns. } { [%csl Rf7,Rb7] } 6. Qb3! { [%csl Rf7,Rb7][%cal Gb3f7,Gb3b7] } 6... Be6 (6... Qe7?? 7. Qxb7 $18 { The rook is trapped, we can take it on the next move. } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gb7a8] }) (6... Bxf3 7. Bxf7+! Ke7 (7... Kd7 8. Qe6+ Kc6 9. Be8+ Nd7 10. Be3 { Stopping the king from going to c5/b6 and threatening mate in 1 with Qd5# or Qc4# } { [%csl Gb6,Gc5,Bd5,Bc4][%cal Ge3b6,Be6d5,Bd5c4] } 10... Kb5 11. Nxc3+ Ka5 12. Qc4 { There is no way to stop mate, we are threatening b4# and Qb5# } { [%csl Bb5,Bb4][%cal Bc4b5,Bb2b4] }) 8. Qe6# { GG } { [%csl Ge8,Ge7,Gd7,Gf7,Rf8,Rd8,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Ge6e8,Ge6d7,Ge6f7,Ge6f6] }) (6... Bh5?? 7. Qb5+ $18 { White wins the bishop. } { [%csl Ge8,Gh5][%cal Gb5e8,Gb5h5] }) 7. Bxe6 { Simplifying. } 7... fxe6 8. Nxc3! { First we can chomp up this pawn, the other two are still hanging. } { [%csl Rb7,Re6] } 8... b6 (8... Qc8 9. Ng5 $18 { Leads to the same ideas we discussed before. ;) } { [%csl Re6] }) (8... Nd7 9. Qxe6+ Qe7 10. Qb3 $16 { [%cal Bc1e3,Be1g1] }) 9. Ng5! { The classic move we've discussed in previous chapters. This is the same stuff. We could have taken e6 immediately with the queen, but wouldn't an octopus knight on e6 be better? } { [%csl Re6][%cal Yb3e6,Bg5e6] } 9... Qe7 { e5 hangs mate in 1 with Qf7# } 10. Nxe6 { This knight is really well placed here! } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ge6c7,Ge6g7,Ge6f8,Ge6d8] } 10... Nf6 11. Bg5 { Pinning the black horse. Preparing for Nd5 jumps. } { [%cal Bc3d5] } 11... h6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nd5! { We want to fork on c7 and there isn't anything black can do about it. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rd5c7,Re6c7] } 13... Qxe6 14. Nxc7+ { [%csl Ge8,Ge6][%cal Gc7e8,Gc7e6] } 14... Kd8 15. Nxe6+ $18 { White has enough extra material to win the game. } *


