[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

4... Nf6 5. Qc2! { This is probably the most simple and non-complicated line for white. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4] } 5... dxc3 { Most times Black will decide to take at some point. This however doesn't transpose to previously covered lines because we've now play Qc2. } (5... Be7 { Black's still to scared to take. In this case we'll just take. } 6. cxd4 { Important not to take immediately but only after Qc2, defending e4. } 6... O-O 7. Nc3 $16 { And this is an amazing position for White. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Yg1][%cal Bf1d3,Bc1g5,Ye1g1] }) 6. Nxc3 Be7 { Black prepares to castle. It doesn't really matter how Black develops, we'll go for the same ideas. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 7. Be3 { Preparing to castle queenside. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1] } 7... O-O 8. O-O-O! (8. h3 Nc6 9. a3) 8... Nc6 9. h3 { This is the kind of setup we play pretty much every time, whatever black plays. The point of h3 is to support a future g4. Also, Bg4 is prevented. } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Bg2g4,Bh3g4] } 9... Be6 (9... Nb4 10. Qb1 c6 11. a3 Na6) 10. a3 { We won't let black place a knight on b4, it's just unnecessarily annoying. } { [%csl Bb4][%cal Ba3b4] } 10... a6 11. g4 $14 { White's slightly better here. We'll be launching a huge kingside attack. Black's on the defensive side. } { [%cal Bg4g5,Bh3h4] } *


