[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0wRf6tr3/kY2CgXS5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.26"]
[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

3... Nc6?! { Quite popular online. Stockfish doesn't like it, but it's quite tricky to handle correctly. } 4. Bb5! { The most successful response. White's threatening two large threats: d5, hitting the pinned knight, and Bxc6, removing the defender of e5. } { [%cal Rd4d5] } 4... exd4 { You have two options here. Both giving about a 60% winrate for White. Nxd4, preferred by Stockfish, but leads to more lines and a bit more complicated. Or Qxd4, a bit more successful according to the database and very simple. } (4... a6? { Loses a clean pawn. } 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. dxe5 $16) (4... Bd7 { The second most popular move. } 5. Bxc6 Bxc6 { d5 is tempting, but don't play it! We want to keep the tension in the center. } 6. Nc3! { Defending e4. Remember, Black's e5 pawn is still hanging. } { [%csl Ge4] } 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Qe2 Nf6 9. Bf4 $16 { Very comfortable for White. } { [%cal Be1c1,Bh1g1,Bg2g4] }) (4... Bg4 { Counter pinning us. There are many tempting moves here, like d5, dxe5, h3, which are okay, but we have something better. } 5. Nc3! { Played 1% of the time. Keeping things simple. Simply prioritizing development. } 5... a6? { Most popular, but as we saw in a variation above, this leads to something pretty bad. } (5... exd4 6. Qxd4 { Taking with the queen of course! } 6... Bxf3 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. gxf3 $16 { The doubled f-pawns are no problem. The open g-file is more of a strength for the rook. We'll castle queenside. } { [%csl Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Re8,Rd8,Ra8,Gc3,Gd4][%cal Bh1g1,Bc1e3,Be1c1] }) 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. dxe5 Bxf3 { dxe5 loses a pawn after we exchange the queens. } 8. Qxf3 dxe5 9. O-O $16 { Black doesn't have a single piece developed and has a disgusting pawn structure. } { [%csl Re5,Rc6,Rc7,Ra6,Gg1,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Re8,Rd8,Ra8] }) 5. Qxd4 { I'll be showing this line to keep things simple. The queen can now take here in the center, because there's no way for Black to kick her away. } 5... Bd7 { Black breaks the pin. Now we can follow up by trading the bishop for the knight. Removing the only piece that could chase away the queen. } 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 { Defending the pawn. From here the plan is simple, develop the DSB on f4 or g5, castle queenside, and attack on the kingside. } { [%cal Gc3e4] } 7... Nf6 8. Bg5 { Bf4 is also perfectly fine. } 8... Be7 9. O-O-O { Even though the computer says is roughly equal, the winrates say otherwise. White has a very comfortable position. } { [%csl Gc1,Gd4,Re7][%cal Bh2h4,Bg2g4] } *


[Event "Punish the Philidor Defense!: 📗 3...Nd7: Hanham Variation"]
[Date "2025.10.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense: Hanham Variation"]
[StudyName "Punish the Philidor Defense!"]
[ChapterName "📗 3...Nd7: Hanham Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0wRf6tr3/jOTA0IRX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.26"]
[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

3... Nd7 { This is known as the Hanham variation. Black supports e5. } 4. Bc4! { This is the most aggressive approach, white immediately aims f7. } 4... Be7?? { Black develops and gets one step closer to castling, it is a blunder due to the following sequence. } (4... c6 5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5! { It might look at first like we are sacrificing a knight but we win it back immediately } { [%cal Bg5f7,Yc4f7] } 7... Bxg5 8. Qh5! { We win back the sacrificed piece. } { [%csl Gg5,Gf7][%cal Gh5g5,Gh5f7] } 8... Qe7 9. Qxg5 Qxg5 10. Bxg5 Ngf6 11. f3 O-O 12. Nd2 $16 { White's pieces are way better placed than black's. The engine gives white a +2.1 advantage. } { [%csl Gc4,Gg5,Gd2,Rc8,Rd7] }) (4... h6 { Black prevents any Bg5/Ng5 } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh6g5] } 5. dxe5 dxe5?? { A huge blunder! It gets played 82% of the time! } 6. Bxf7+!! Kxf7 7. Nxe5+!! { Exploiting the pin. } { [%csl Re5,Bd8][%cal Rd7e5,Bd1d8] } 7... Kf6 8. Nc3!! { The only move that wins. The following is a demonstration of a king hunt. } 8... Kxe5 9. Qd5+ Kf6 10. Qf5+ Ke7 11. Nd5+ Kd6 12. Bf4+ Kc6 13. Qe6+ Bd6 14. Nb4+! Kb6 15. Bxd6 Ndf6 16. Bc5+ Kxc5 17. Nd3+ Qxd3 18. Qe5+ Kc6 19. cxd3) (4... Ngf6?? { A blunder, it allows us to win the important f pawn by force. } 5. dxe5! { Opening the d file. } 5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+! { It is important to note that white doesn't win the queen because after 7...Kxf7 8. Qxd8 Bb4+ and black wins the queen back. White is much better though because white has just won the important f pawn. } 7... Ke7 (7... Kxf7 8. Qxd8 Bb4+ 9. Qd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. f3 $18 { We're gonna break Ben Finegold's rule and play f3. It solidify s everything, 9. Nc3, and we would have to deal with an annoying Bb4 pin. }) (4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Ngf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Nf5 O-O 8. O-O $16 { [%csl Gf5,Gc4] }) 5. dxe5! { Opening up the d-file, preparing for a battery with Qd4. } { [%csl Yd5][%cal Gd1d5] } 5... dxe5 (5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qh5! { The only good move! White simply forks the e and f pawn. } { [%csl Gf7,Ge5][%cal Gh5f7,Gh5e5] } 7... g6 8. Qxe5 Nf6 9. Bh6! { Preventing black from castling. } 9... Qd6 10. Qxd6 cxd6 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. O-O-O $18 { White is up a clean pawn. Also black has a very weak d pawn that we will be able to put some pressure on. } { [%csl Rd6] }) 6. Qd5! { We threaten mate in 1 on f7 and black has no way to defend the f pawn without losing material. The move 4...Be7 has blocked the queen from coming out. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } 6... Nh6 7. Bxh6 { It's free! } 7... O-O 8. Be3 $18 { White has an extra knight on the board. } { [%csl Gc4,Re5,Gf3,Ge3,Gd5,Gb1,Bg1,Rc8,Rd8,Re7,Rd7][%cal Be1g1] } *


[Event "Punish the Philidor Defense!: 📗 3...f5?!: Philidor Countergambit"]
[Date "2025.10.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense: Philidor Countergambit"]
[StudyName "Punish the Philidor Defense!"]
[ChapterName "📗 3...f5?!: Philidor Countergambit"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0wRf6tr3/BGw4bYcN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.26"]
[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

3... f5!? { This is the Philidor Countergambit, if you don't know how to play against it it can be quite tricky. Most people will probably take either f5/e5 but these moves lead to lots of traps for Black. White must play very carefully to retain the advantage. @BunnyMommyIsHappy, a member of our team, actually made a study on this variation from Blacks' perspective: https://lichess.org/study/UeByH3ZL A big problem now for Black is that the king is weakened. We can take advantage of the weak light squares with the move... } { [%csl Rf7] } 4. Bc4! { Played only 3% of the time! Not covered by @BunnyMommyIsHappy. Immediately taking control of the light squares. The absolute best move. } { [%csl Gf7,Ge6][%cal Gc4f7] } 4... fxe4 { Black usually is not prepared for this. exf5 is by far the most popular move being played almost 70% of the time. } (4... f4?? 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nxe5 $18 { Just horrible for Black. +4.3. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf4,Rd8] }) 5. Nxe5!! { The only winning move! Freeing up the queen! } { [%csl Gd1,Gh5][%cal Yd1h5] } 5... dxe5 (5... d5 6. Qh5+! { Ke7?? loses due to Qf7+ } { [%csl Ge8,Bg6][%cal Gh5e8,Be5g6] } 6... g6 7. Nxg6 { Exploiting the pin. } { [%csl Yh8,Ye8][%cal Gg6h8,Yh5h8,Yh5e8] } 7... Nf6 8. Qe5+ Be7 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 10. Bg5 Qxe5 11. dxe5 dxc4 12. Bxf6 Rg8 13. Nc3 Rxg2 14. O-O-O $18 { [%csl Gd8,Gc3,Re4,Rc4,Rh7,Re8,Rb8,Rc8,Ra8,Gf6][%cal Gd1d8,Ge5f6] }) 6. Qh5+! { We get the classic rook king fork. } 6... g6 (6... Kd7 7. Qf5+ Kc6 8. Qxe5 { Threatening to go to b5 } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ge5b5] } 8... a6 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra6b5] } 9. d5+! Kb6 10. Be3+ Bc5 11. Bxc5+ Kxc5 12. b4+ Kxc4 13. Qxe4+ Kb5 14. a4+ Kb6 15. Qd4+ c5 16. Qxc5# { [%csl Ga7,Gb6,Gc7,Ga5,Bc5][%cal Gc5a7,Gc5c7,Gc5a5,Bb4c5] }) 7. Qxe5+ Qe7 8. Qxh8 $18 { White is clearly winning. } { [%csl Gh8,Gc4] } *


[Event "Punish the Philidor Defense!: 📗 3...Nf6: Nimzowitsch Variation"]
[Date "2025.10.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense: Nimzowitsch Variation, Rellstab Variation"]
[StudyName "Punish the Philidor Defense!"]
[ChapterName "📗 3...Nf6: Nimzowitsch Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0wRf6tr3/v0CyKIbj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.26"]
[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

3... Nf6!? { This is the Nimzowitsch variation. An interesting counter. Instead of defending the e5 pawn, Black decides to counter attack e4. } 4. dxe5 Nxe4! (4... dxe5? { surprisingly the most popular move, we can now win a pawn. } 5. Qxd8+! Kxd8 6. Nxe5 { Black won't be able to take e4 because white is threatening to take f7+ } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5f7] } 6... Be6 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. f3 $16 { White solidifies. We now have a nice pawn chain and white is up a pawn! } { [%csl Yg2,Yf3,Ye4][%cal Gg2f3,Gf3e4] }) 5. Qd5! { Our weapon! Bringing the queen to action and we are attacking the knight. Don't worry about it getting attacked, Black won't have time for that. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4] } 5... Nc5 (5... Bf5? { The second most played move, it leaves the b7 pawn undefended. } 6. Bc4! { First we can develop this bishop with tempo. The b7 pawn will still be hanging on the next move. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] } 6... Qe7 (6... Bg6 7. Qxb7 Nd7 8. Qc6 $16) 7. Qxb7 $18 { We'll get the rook on the next move! } { [%csl Ra8] }) 6. Bg5! { Bringing another piece in the game with tempo. If c6, play the cool Qxf7 to win a pawn and deflect the king from the queen. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Re5d6] } 6... Be7 (6... Qd7 7. exd6 Bxd6 8. Nc3 { Next up is castling queenside. It's a very comfy position. Remember the To Take is a Mistake rule. So after Qe6+, White can respond with Be3. If Black wants to trade queens, let him make the action. That would help developing the c3 knight. } { [%cal Be1c1] }) (6... c6 7. Qxf7+ Kxf7 8. Bxd8) 7. exd6! Qxd6 (7... Bxg5?? 8. Nxg5 { Threatening mate in one and the knight's unprotected. } { [%csl Gf7,Gc5][%cal Gg5f7,Gd5c5] } 8... Ne6 9. Nxe6 Bxe6 (9... fxe6 10. Qh5+! Kf8 11. dxc7 Qxc7 12. Nc3 $18 { next is O-O-O and white is way better. } { [%csl Bc1,Bd3,Re6,Rf8,Rc8,Rb8][%cal Be1c1,Bf1d3] }) 10. Qxb7 Nd7 11. dxc7 Qc8 12. Ba6 O-O 13. Qxc8 Raxc8 14. Bxc8 Rxc8 $18 { white has an extra 5 points in material. }) (7... cxd6 8. Nc3 Be6 9. Bb5+ Nbd7 10. Qd2 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gd2g5] } 10... O-O 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O-O $16 { [%csl Gc1,Gd1,Gd2,Rd6] }) 8. Nc3 { We continue developing and get ready to castle queenside. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1,Bc3d5] } 8... Be6 9. Qxd6 Bxd6 10. Nb5 { We force Black to trade the bishop, the bishop is unable to leave the c pawn undefended. } 10... Nc6 11. Nxd6+ { Creating a weak isolated pawn. } 11... cxd6 12. O-O-O $16 { White's better here due to the better pawn structure, bishop pair, and strong d-rook. } { [%csl Gc1,Rd6,Gg5,Gf3,Gc5,Gc6,Ge6] } *


[Event "Punish the Philidor Defense!: 📗 3...f6?"]
[Date "2025.10.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Punish the Philidor Defense!"]
[ChapterName "📗 3...f6?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0wRf6tr3/leoXNlBB"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.26"]
[UTCTime "18:16:04"]

3... f6? { Not sure why this gets played, but it accounts for 2.5 million games in the database. Clearly, your opponent is not following Ben Finegold's advice. This move weakens the light squares, prevents Nf6 development, and doesn't do anything to improve the position. } { [%csl Rf7,Re6] } 4. Bc4! { A nice idea in these type of positions, as we saw in the Phillidor Countergambit. We immediately control the light squares. } 4... Ne7? { There are many moves here, this one being the most popular. In other cases, continue standard development, you're already positionally better. } (4... c6 { A better move. From here standard development. There's no immediate way to punish Black. } 5. Nc3 g6 { As you can see Black already has to make some unpleasant moves in order to get somewhere. } 6. Be3 Nh6 { Black must reroute this way. Other wise the king cannot castle due to the strong LSB. Black's DSB also has trouble. } { [%csl Bf7][%cal Bg8h6,Bh6f7] } 7. h3 { Here I like h3, preventing an annoying Ng4, hitting our DSB. } { [%csl Rg4] } 7... Qe7 8. Qe2 Nf7 9. O-O-O $16 { [%csl Gc1,Gc4,Gc3,Ge3,Rf8,Re8,Rc8,Rb8,Rf7,Re7,Rf6,Rd6,Gf3] }) (4... Qe7 5. O-O Be6 { Remember the rule: To TAKE is a MISTAKE! If Black really wants to trade, we do it on our terms. } 6. Bb3! { [%cal Ba2b3] } 6... Bxb3 7. axb3 { We get an open a file } { [%cal Ga1a8] } 7... a6 8. Nc3 $16) (4... Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 exd4 7. Qb3! { Forking the knight and b7 pawn. } { [%csl Gb7,Gg8][%cal Gb3b7,Gb3g8] } 7... Qe7 (7... Ne7 8. Bf7+! Kd7 9. Be6+ Ke8 10. c3 dxc3 11. Nxc3 $18 { [%csl Gb3,Gc3,Ge6,Gg1,Rb8,Ra8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Re7,Rh8][%cal Ge1g1] }) 8. Qxb7 $18 { On the next move just take the rook! } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Rb7a8] }) 5. dxe5 { in this case, trading in the center is fine because we have some tactics here. } 5... fxe5 (5... dxe5 6. Bf7+! { [%cal Rd1d8] } 6... Kxf7 7. Qxd8 $18 { Same thing. }) 6. Nxe5!! $18 { Threatening mate in 1. And we have the classic following tactic. } { [%cal Ye5f7,Bc4f7] } 6... dxe5 7. Bf7+ { [%csl Ge8,Rd8][%cal Gf7e8,Rd1d8] } 7... Kxf7 $7 8. Qxd8 $18 { White is up a queen! } *


