{ Hello, everyone! Welcome to my new study! Today, we're exploring the Queen's Gambit, a popular chess opening. It's widely favored by modern players, especially when starting with 1. d4. This opening is known for its solid and strategic approach.

Top grandmasters around the world are frequently using the Queen's Gambit in their games. Feel free to use the chess engine and check out the Lichess database for more insights and variations.

Let's begin! Play 1.d4! }
1. d4 (1. b3 { You found the Easter Egg ;)
🥚 }) (1. e4 { You found the Easter Egg! :D
🥚 }) 1... d5 { Now "sacrifice" a pawn! } 2. c4 { This is the beginning of the Queen's Gambit! The Queen's Gambit is not really regarded as a "gambit" because after 2. dxc4 white could just win the pawn back with 3. Qa4+, but white usually plays something else.
Black has two options:
1. Accept the gambit by taking c4
2. Decline it by playing something else
I have divided this study into four sections.
- Queen's Gambit Accepted
- Queen's Gambit Declined
- Slav/Semi-Slav Defense
- Move 2 sidelines
There are many defenses for black, but hopefully I have covered most of them. I've also added plenty of traps :)
Note: my lines will not always be the absolute top engine move, they are rather based on which one is more comfortable to play as a human and have a decent winrate.
Go to the next chapter! :) } *


[Event "Queen's Gambit | Full Repertoire: ✦ Section 1: Queen's Gambit Accepted ✦"]
[Date "2024.01.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D21"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Accepted: Normal Variation"]
[StudyName "Queen's Gambit | Full Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "✦ Section 1: Queen's Gambit Accepted ✦"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0uRBskUV/BrbC1nB8"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.01.17"]
[UTCTime "11:00:33"]

2... dxc4 { This is the Queen's Gambit Accepted. It gets seen much more often at -1500 level. At higher levels you will mostly see 2...c6 or 2...e6. This move doesn't come without risk for black, 2. dxc4 is not really a "great" move for black, but with perfect play black will be okay. } 3. Nf3 { This is the Normal Variation, it's the most popular move in the masters database. Note that 2. e3/2. e4/Nf3 are all perfectly fine moves, but this study will only cover 2. Nf3. } *


[Event "Queen's Gambit | Full Repertoire: QGA: Rosenthal Defense 3...e6"]
[Date "2024.01.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D21"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Accepted: Rosenthal Variation"]
[StudyName "Queen's Gambit | Full Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "QGA: Rosenthal Defense 3...e6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0uRBskUV/N0x4kKuk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.01.17"]
[UTCTime "11:00:33"]

3... e6 { The Rosenthal Variation. It's the second most popular move. } 4. e3 { Aiming at the c4 pawn and keeping a solid pawn setup. } { [%csl Gc4,Bf2,Be3,Bd4][%cal Gf1c4,Bf2e3,Be3d4] } 4... c5 (4... b5?! 5. a4! { A common theme in the Queen's Gambit, we usually always respond to b5 with a4. } 5... c6 { Protecting b5. } 6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3 { Challenging the c pawn. } 7... Bb4+ { The most popular move. We just block it. } 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 $16 { Black's b and c are really weak, we'll probably win them later on. White's position is quite a bit better. Stockfish gives +1.1 for white. } { [%csl Rb5,Rc4,Ga1] }) (4... Nf6 { Getting one step closer to castling. } 5. Bxc4 { We transpose to the same position as chapter 2. }) (4... Bb4+?! { Black wants to trade the DSB's, this not so great because this is black's good bishop, ours was locked behind some pawns. } 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 $16 { [%csl Gd2,Gf3,Rc4] }) 5. Bxc4 { We just grab this. } 5... cxd4 (5... Nf6 { This transposes to the Classical Defense (chapter 4) }) (5... Nc6 6. O-O Nf6 7. Nc3 $14 { White gets a good game. The next step is to free up the DSB by either trading the e pawn or pushing it. } { [%csl Gc3,Gf3,Gc4] }) (5... a6 { Preparing for b5 } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Bb7b5,Ra6b5] } 6. O-O b5 7. Be2 { Tucking the bishop safely here. } 7... Bb7 8. dxc5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. a4! $14 { Breaking open the queenside! White has a slight edge after this move. } { [%cal Bb1d2,Bd2b3] }) 6. O-O! { The top-engine move! } 6... dxe3 (6... Nf6 7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 $14 { White's doing well. White does have an isolated queen's pawn, but it's not really a huge problem. White will usually play d5 at some point to get trade it (get rid of it). } { [%csl Gf3,Gc3,Gc4,Gd4] }) (6... Nc6 7. exd4 Nf6 8. Nc3 $14 { It's the same thing as the previous chapter. } { [%csl Gf3,Gc3,Gc4] }) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bxe3 $14 { White has enough compensation for the lost pawn. All of Black's pieces are still stuck on the 8th rank, making it challenging for them to contribute actively. While Stockfish indicates a slight advantage for White, it's important to recognize that the technical nature of the position suggests a probable draw. The game is finely poised between White's compensation for the pawn and the potential for Black to hold the position, making it a complex and balanced situation where both players need to carefully maneuver to achieve their desired outcome } { [%csl Gc4,Ge3,Gf3,Gg1,Ra8,Rc8,Rb8,Rd8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Bd1,Bc1][%cal Bb1c3,Ba1c1,Bc1d1] } *


[Event "Queen's Gambit | Full Repertoire: QGA: Classical Defense 3...Nf6-4...e6-5...c5"]
[Date "2024.01.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D27"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Accepted: Classical Defense, Main Line"]
[StudyName "Queen's Gambit | Full Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "QGA: Classical Defense 3...Nf6-4...e6-5...c5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0uRBskUV/XJPoTJzs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.01.17"]
[UTCTime "11:00:33"]

3... Nf6 { This is the most popular move, there are quite a few variations that arise after Nf6. The next few chapters will still cover them too. } 4. e3 { Forming a solid pawn chain and attacking c4. } { [%csl Gf1,Bd4,Bf2,Be3][%cal Bf2e3,Be3d4] } 4... e6 (4... b5 { Always respond b5 with a4! } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gb5c4] } 5. a4! { [%csl Rb5] } 5... c6 6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3 $16 { White will soon win these two pawns. } { [%csl Ga1,Rc4,Rb5] }) 5. Bxc4 c5 { This marks the beginning of the Classical Defense. } 6. O-O a6 { The mainline. Black wants to expand on the queenside with b5. } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Ra6b5,Bb7b5] } (6... cxd4 { The Steinitz Variation. } 7. exd4 Be7 { Preparing to castle. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1 $14 { White is a bit more developed. Stockfish gives white a slight edge. } { [%csl Gc4,Gf3,Gc3,Ge1,Gg1,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8] }) 7. dxc5 { Wanting to exchange queens. Declining the queen exchange would be bad for black. } 7... Qxd1 (7... Bxc5 { The Furman Variation. White can just exchange the queens now. } 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $10 { It's a pretty drawish position. This position has been reached over 800 times in the master's database, 70% ended in a draw. }) (7... Qc7? 8. b4 $17 { White is up a pawn. } { [%csl Gc5,Gb4][%cal Gb4c5] }) (7... Qa5 8. a3 { [%csl Bb4][%cal Bb2b4,Ra3b4] } 8... Qxc5 9. Nbd2 $14 { [%csl Gd2,Gf3,Gc4,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Re8,Rf8,Rh8,Gg1][%cal Bb2b4,Bc1b2] }) 8. Rxd1 { We get a symphony of exchanges. } 8... Bxc5 9. b3 $14 { White plans to fianchetto the DSB on the next move. If black hits the light-squared-bishop with b5, white can retreat it to f1/e2. Stockfish gives white a very slight edge. } { [%csl Gb3,Gc4,Bb2,Be2,Bf1][%cal Ga2b3,Gb3c4,Bc1b2,Bc4e2,Be2f1] } *


