2... e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 { This is the beginning of the Exchange Variation. It is the most popular variation in the Masters database. } 4... exd5 (4... Nxd5 5. e4 { White takes the center and kicks the knight. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4] } 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4] } 6... c5 (6... Be7?! 7. Qg4 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg4g7] } 7... O-O? (7... g6 8. Nf3 $14 { We get an interesting game. White has a 68% winrate. }) 8. Bh6 $16 { White wins an exchange. Bf6 is responded with e5. } { [%csl Bf8,Yg7][%cal Bh6f8,Yg4g7] }) 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 { Blocking the check. } 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 $14 { You get a good game. } { [%csl Bg1,Gd4,Ge4,Gc4,Gf3][%cal Be1g1] }) 5. Bg5 { The Positional Variation, this is played 99% of the time in the masters database. White simply pins the f6 knight. } 5... Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 6. e3 { Forming a solid pawn chain, the LSB is now ready to be free. } { [%csl Gf1,Ye3,Yf2,Yd4][%cal Yf2e3,Ye3d4] } 6... O-O { Bringing the king to safety. } 7. Bd3 { Staring at the h7 pawn and getting one step closer to castling. } { [%csl Gd3,Bg1,Rh7][%cal Bg1e2,Bg1f3,Be1g1] } 7... c6 { Black supports the d5 pawn, also the queen has more space to roam. } { [%csl Gd8,Yc6,Yd5,Yb7][%cal Yb7c6,Yc6d5] } 8. Qc2 Nbd7 { Placing the knight on a more flexible square. It can jump to b6, or even in the future to g6 with Re8-Nf8-Ng6. This move is being played 82% of the time in the masters database. } { [%cal Bd7b6,Bf8e8,Bd7f8,Bd7f6,Bf8g6] } 9. Nf3 { Getting ready to castle. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 9... Re8 { Black goes for the knight Nf8-Ng6 route. This move gets played 95% of the time in the masters database. } { [%csl Bg6,Bf8][%cal Bd7f8,Bf8g6] } 10. O-O { Finally, our king is brought to safety. } { [%csl Gg1] } 10... h6?! { Black wants to get rid of our annoying bishop. We have a nice trap ready now! } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh6g5] } (10... Nf8 { Rerouting the knight to g6, or it's quite happy here too! } { [%csl Bg6][%cal Bf8g6] } 11. h3 $14 { Controlling the g4 square to avoid any complications with Bg4/Ng4. } { [%csl Rg4,Bf2,Be3,Bd4,Bh3,Bg2,Gg5,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3,Gc2][%cal Rh3g4,Bf2e3,Be3d4,Bg2h3] }) (10... Ne4? { This just loses a pawn \('-')/ } 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxg5 13. Nexg5 $16 { White is up a clean pawn. }) 11. Bf4 Nh5?? { Black thinks that they win our valuable DSB because it's trapped, but white has a nice surprise! :D This blunder has been played a handful of times by masters too! } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Rh5f4] } 12. Nxd5!! { A brilliant move! } 12... cxd5 { A game-over move. } (12... Nxf4 { Black hopes to play a bit longer. But has to suffer longer too. } 13. Nxf4 $18 { White is up a clean pawn, a safe king, and every piece is beautifully placed! Mr. Fish give +2.3 for white. } { [%csl Be3,Bd4,Bf2,Gc2,Yf4,Yf3,Gd3,Gg1][%cal Bf2e3,Be3d4] }) 13. Bc7 { The queen is trapped in her own pieces! Black can resign now! This trap is called the Rubenstein Trap } { [%csl Gd8,Rc8,Re8,Re7,Rd7,Yc7][%cal Gc7d8,Yc2c7] } *


