3... c5 { The Tarrasch Defense. Black is assertively striving to control the central area, although this comes at the cost of ending up with an isolated pawn on d5 following some pawn exchanges. } 4. cxd5 exd5 (4... cxd4 5. Qa4+! { Forcing black to put something in front of the queen. } { [%csl Rd7] } 5... Bd7 6. Qxd4 $16 { White's up a clean pawn! }) 5. Nf3 Nf6 (5... Nc6 6. g3 { Same thing. } { [%csl Bg2,Bf4,Bg5][%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1,Bc1f4,Bf4g5] }) (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. g3! Bc5 (7... Bb4? { We have a nice response } 8. Qa4+ { The only way for black not to lose the bishop is to play Nc6. } { [%csl Bb4,Be8][%cal Ba4b4,Ba4e8] } 8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 Bxc3+ { White is in check. } 10. bxc3 bxc6 11. Ba3 $16 { Qxc6 is also possible, but this is slightly more annoying for black ;) } { [%csl Rf8,Re7,Bc6][%cal Ra3f8,Ba4c6,Bf1g2,Be1g1] }) 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. Bg2 { [%csl Bg1,Gc3,Gb3,Gg2][%cal Be1g1] }) 6. g3! { First, we position our bishop on a diagonal by fianchettoing, which helps us control important areas on the board. After that, we simply castle to make sure our king is safe and our pieces are well-coordinated for the game ahead. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1] } 6... Nc6 { Black just develops. } 7. Bg2 { Just following the plan. } 7... Be7 (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 { Just recapture! } 8... Bb4 9. O-O { Bringing the king to safety. }) 8. O-O $14 { White holds a slight advantage in the current position. The fianchettoed bishop contributes to controlling important diagonals, giving White a bit more spatial influence. Additionally, the securely placed king and straightforward piece development make it easier for White to navigate the early stages of the game. These factors collectively contribute to White's slightly better position. } { [%csl Bg5,Bf4][%cal Bd4c5,Bc1f4,Bf4g5,Bd1b3] } *


