3... a6!? { This move aims to prevent White's pieces from occupying the b5 square. } 4. cxd5 exd5 { Black captures on d5 with the pawn, establishing a solid pawn structure and maintaining pawn symmetry. } 5. Nf3 Nf6 { Both sides continue developing their pieces. Knights are brought out, and both sides prioritize control over the center. } 6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Bg5d8] } 6... Be6 (6... Be7 7. Qc2 O-O 8. e3 c6 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bf4 Be6 11. h3 { The most accurate option. } (11. O-O-O!? { Not the most accurate, but definitely worth a try. White's king is safely tucked into the queenside. Meanwhile white can launch an attack on the kingside with h3-g4. There are also many lines where white directly plays g4 sacrificing a pawn, but it actually helps white get activity because the g file is half open. } { [%cal Bh2h3,Bg2g4,Bd1g1,Bf3e5] }) 11... Nbd7 12. O-O $14 { White's pieces are all very well coordinated. Black's aren't bad too, but it will take some time for the DSB to be more active, and the LSB currently acts as a tall pawn. White has a 61% winrate. } { [%csl Gf4,Gd3,Gc3,Gf3,Gc2,Gg1,Yd4,Ye3,Yf2,Re7,Gd7,Gf6,Re6][%cal Yf2e3,Ye3d4] }) 7. e3 { Building a pawn chain. } { [%csl Ge3,Gd4][%cal Gf2e3,Ge3d4] } 7... Nbd7 { Placing the knight in a defensive position. Also, black definitely doesn't want to block the c pawn from advancing. } 8. Bd3 { Preparing to castle. } 8... Bd6 9. O-O $14 { Stockfish grants a 0.5 advantage to white; however, capitalizing on this advantage proves challenging for human players. The solidity of black's position remains a significant factor. } { [%csl Gd3,Gc3,Gf3,Gg5,Ye3,Yd4,Yf2,Gg1][%cal Yf2e3,Ye3d4,Bd1c2,Bc2b3,Bg5f4,Bf1e1,Be3e4] } *


