3... Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This move marks that black wants to play a pure-Slav game. The most popular move is 4...e6, but that's the Semi-Slav, we'll get to that later ;) } 5. a4! { The Alapin Variation! Moving the a-pawn forward stops Black from controlling b5, and as a result, the c4 pawn becomes vulnerable to capture. } 5... Bf5 { There are quite a few variations for black after 5. a4, so the next few chapters will start from this position. This is the Czech Variation, it's the most popular one. } (5... Nbd7?! 6. e4 { Immediately dominating the center. Black c pawn will get captured later on. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4] } 6... e6 (6... Nb6 7. a5 { [%csl Gb6,Rc4][%cal Ga5b6] } 7... Nbd7 8. Bxc4 $16 { White has an amazing position, almost every piece is developed, the position is flexible for white, white is ready to castle, and white controls the a file. Meanwhile black's pieces are all pretty cramped up. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4,Ga5,Ga1,Bg1,Gf3,Gc3,Gc4,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rf6,Rd7][%cal Be1g1] }) (6... Qa5 { e4 is now attacked. } { [%csl Re4] } 7. Bd2 { Breaking the pin. } 7... e5 8. Bxc4 exd4 9. Bxf7+!! { A beautiful sequence comes next! } 9... Kxf7 10. Ng5+! Ke8 11. Nd5!! { The two horses come closer into black's territory. } { [%csl Bc7,Rd2,Ra5][%cal Bd5c7] } 11... Qd8 12. Ne6! { The queen is trapped! Well, black will get 2 horses for it, but white will still be the one having the more comfortable position. } { [%csl Bd8,Bc7,Rb6,Ya5,Re7][%cal Be6d8,Be6c7,Rd5b6,Yd2a5,Rd5e7] }) 7. Bxc4 $16 { White is obviously better. } { [%csl Bg1,Ge4,Gd4,Gc4,Gc3,Gf3][%cal Be1g1] }) 6. Ne5! { Hitting the c pawn, there really isn't anything black can do to save it. } { [%csl Rc4] } 6... Nbd7 (6... e6 7. f3! { Usually, don't play f3, but in this position, it's a total must-play move. We almost always play e4 on the next move. Then Be2 and O-O. You get a good game. } { [%csl Be4][%cal Be2e4] }) (6... Na6 7. e3! { The absolute best move! A common mistake is Nxc4, but after Nb4, white's in a lot of trouble. } 7... Nb4 { Now it doesn't work, because of this really lucky sequence. } 8. Bxc4 { Threatening mate in 1 and now we are free to castle. } { [%csl Rf7,Bg1][%cal Rc4f7,Re5f7,Be1g1] } 8... Nc2+ (8... e6 9. O-O $16 { White is safe now! }) 9. Qxc2! { Mate is still hanging. } 9... Bxc2 { [%csl Gf7] } 10. Bxf7# { GG! } { [%csl Ge8,Yf7,Yd7,Rd8,Re7,Rf8][%cal Gf7e8,Ye5f7,Ye5d7] }) 7. Nxc4 Qc7 8. g3 $14 { Next up is Bg2-O-O-Bf4-e3, and you get a good game. Stockfish give white a +0.5 advantage. } { [%csl Bg1,Bf4,Gc4,Gc3][%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1,Be2e3,Bc1f4] } *


