3... Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 { Black opts for a solid setup by playing e6. This move supports the d5 pawn and prepares for potential pawn exchanges in the center. The pawn structure after this move is characteristic of the Semi-Slav Defense. } { [%csl Ge6,Gd5,Gc6,Gb7,Gf7][%cal Gf7e6,Ge6d5,Gb7c6,Gc6d5] } 5. Bg5! { We simply pin the knight and the bishop is now developed. Next we want to build our pawn chain with e3. } { [%cal Be2e3] } 5... dxc4 { This is the Semi-Slav Accepted. Because black is no longer controlling the e4 square, we can take it immediately. } 6. e4 { We have entered the Botvinnik Variation. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4] } 6... b5 { Played 99% of the time in the masters database. It's the only good move because it protects c4. } { [%csl Yc4,Yb5,Yc6][%cal Yb5c4,Yc6b5] } 7. e5! { Now comes an important line you have to know! It gets played 99% of the time. } 7... h6! { Counterattacking our bishop. Here comes a sequence of must-play moves. } 8. Bh4! { The only good move! The knight is still hanging. } { [%csl Rf6] } 8... g5! { Once again counterattacking the bishop, the knight was unable to move because it was pinned. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Rg5h4] } 9. Nxg5! { The f6-knight is still hanging so we're not really sacrificing the knight. } 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 { The knight cannot leave because it's still pinned. } { [%csl Rf6] } 10... Nbd7 (10... Be7 { Another option for black. } 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Be3! { White gets a good game. } { [%csl Ge3,Gf2,Gd4,Bc1][%cal Gf2e3,Ge3d4,Ba2a4,Bd1f3,Be1c1,Bc3e4] }) 11. exf6 Bb7 12. g3 $13 { White is only temporarily up a pawn. Next up is Bg2 -> O-O. c5 is met with d5. } { [%csl Bg1,Rf6][%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1] } *


