5... Nbd7 { Another popular option for black. Black keeps everything solid. Often times the d7 knight will at some point reroute to g6, by going to f8 first. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Bd7f8,Bf8g6] } 6. cxd5 exd5 (6... cxd5 7. e3 { Solidifying everything. } { [%csl Bd4,Bf2][%cal Bf2e3,Be3d4] } 7... Be7 8. Bd3 { The bishop is well placed here. } { [%csl Gd3] } 8... O-O 9. O-O $16 { White has a very flexible position. There are many ideas for white: 1, reroute the c knight to g6 to start getting some action on the kingside. 2, gain space on the queenside by a4. 3, try to get a e4 pawn push at some point. } { [%csl Rc8,Yf2,Ye3,Yd4,Bb3,Bc2,Gd3,Gg5,Gf3][%cal Yf2e3,Ye3d4,Bd1c2,Bc2b3,Ba1c1,Bf1e1,Be3e4,Bc3e2,Be2g3,Ba2a4] }) 7. Qc2! { The queen is most active here. } 7... Be7 { Preparing to castle and breaking the pin. } 8. e3 { Solidifying and freeing the LSB. } { [%csl Bd4,Be3,Bf2,Gf1][%cal Bf2e3,Be3d4] } 8... O-O 9. Bd3 { Setting a battery controlling the b1-h7 diagonal. And getting ready to castle. } { [%csl Bg1,Gc2,Gd3][%cal Be1g1] } 9... Re8 { Clearing the f8 square for the knight. } { [%csl Gf8][%cal Bd7f8] } 10. O-O { Bringing the king to safety. } 10... Nf8 11. h3 { A prophylactic move. White restricts black from placing anything on g4. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rh3g4] } 11... Ne4 { [%csl Rg5] } 12. Bf4 { Keeping the bishop on the board. } 12... f5 13. a4! $14 { White immediately turns the tables by gaining space in the queenside. You get an interesting game. White might want to use the outpost on e5 for the knight. White is slightly better. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Bf3e5] } *


