4... Nf6 5. Bg5 { Pinning the knight. } 5... h6 { By far the most popular move in the masters database. Next up comes a very critical line you should definitely know. } 6. Bh4 (6. Bxf6 { Also possible. It's a bit more simple. } 6... Qxf6 7. e3 { Constructing the pawn chain. } { [%csl Bf2,Be3,Bd4][%cal Bf2d4] } 7... Nd7 8. Be2 g6 (8... dxc4 9. O-O! { It's not necessary to take c4 right away. We can take it anytime later. } 9... b5?! 10. a4 $16 { White wins back the sacrificed pawn in all lines. } { [%csl Rc4,Rb5][%cal Bc3e4] }) 9. O-O { White is fully developed. White usually pushes e4 very soon. } { [%csl Gg1,Gc3,Gf3][%cal Be3e4,Bd1c2,Bc2b3] }) 6... dxc4 { Played 94% of the time in the masters database. } (6... Be7 { A more popular move online. } 7. e3 { [%csl Ge3,Gd4][%cal Gf2e3,Ge3d4] } 7... O-O 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O $14 { Both sides have a solid pawn setup. Black has a very defensive piece setup, so it will take a while for them to be more active. White's pieces are all decently placed. If you want a closed game, you can play c5 on the next move. } { [%csl Gg1,Bf2,Be3,Bd4,Yb7,Yc6,Ye6,Yf7,Yd5,Yg7,Yh6,Gf3,Gh4,Gd3,Rc8][%cal Yf7e6,Ye6d5,Yb7c6,Yc6d5,Yg7h6,Bf2e3,Be3d4,Bh4g3] }) 7. e4 { Grabbing the center and attacking c4. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4][%cal Re4e5] } 7... g5 { First black breaks the pin on the knight before reinforcing c4. } 8. Bg3 b5 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gb5c4,Gc6b5] } 9. Be2 { The iconic a4 doesn't really work right now because of b4, and black's doing well. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 9... Bb7 10. O-O { Bringing the king out of the center. } 10... Nbd7 { The best square for the knight. } 11. Ne5 { Placing it in the center. } 11... h5 (11... Nxe5?! 12. Bxe5 { White has a nice bishop in the center that's hard to get rid of. } { [%csl Ge5] }) (11... Bg7 { Black prepares to castle kingside. } 12. Nxd7 { Nxf7 also works here. } 12... Qxd7 13. e5 Nd5 14. Ne4 $14 { White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. } { [%csl Ye5,Yd4,Rd6,Ge4,Gg3,Rc5][%cal Yd4e5,Re4d6,Re4c5,Bf2f4,Be2h5,Ba2a4,Bb2b3] }) 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Be5 Rh6 (13... Bg7? { This self pins the knight, it can no longer move. } { [%csl Rf6] } 14. Qc1! { The most simple way to take advantage. There is no way for black to save the pawn. We can grab it on the next move. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Bc1g5] } 14... g4?? { This saves the pawn, but loses a piece :) } 15. Qg5 $18 { White wins a free piece. } { [%csl Rg7,Rf6][%cal Gg5g7,Gg5f6,Be5f6] }) (13... Be7?! 14. f4 $14 { White gets plenty of activity. It is very easy for black to go wrong soon. } { [%csl Gg1,Ge5,Gc3,Ge4,Gd4,Gf4,Rb7,Rg5,Rf6,Re7][%cal Bf4f5] }) (13... Qe7?! 14. f4! $16 { The same thing. } { [%csl Gf4,Gd4,Ge4] }) 14. Qc1 $13 { A very sharp position. This has been played over 200 times in the masters database, and 67% ended in a draw. Both sides have held everything together. Black will most likely castle queenside, at some point. White can then get some action with a4. } *


