4... f5!? { Black opts for a Stonewall-ish Defense, creating a pawn structure with pawns on d5, e6, and f5. This can lead to a solid but somewhat rigid position. } { [%csl Gc6,Gb7,Gd5,Gf5,Re6][%cal Ge6f5,Ge6d5,Gc6d5,Gb7c6] } 5. Bf4 { White develops the bishop to an active square. } { [%csl Gf4] } 5... Nf6 { A standard developing move. } 6. e3 { Solidifying everything. } 6... Be7 { Preparing to castle, there really aren't many good squares for the bishop. } 7. h3! { White makes a prophylactic move, preventing potential black pieces from coming there. And also it's a breathing hole after our king is castled. } 7... O-O 8. Bd3 { White completes development with the bishop on d3. } 8... Nbd7 { Pretty much the only good square for black. It can potentially reroute to g6 or b6. } { [%cal Bd7f8,Bf8g6,Bd7b6] } (8... dxc4 9. Bxc4! { [%csl Re6,Rc8,Rb8,Ra8,Rd8,Re7,Gf4,Gc4,Gc3,Gf3] }) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. O-O $16 { Stockfish gives white a +1.1 advantage. } { [%csl Re6,Rc8,Rd7,Ye3,Yd4][%cal Bf3e5,Ye3d4,Yf2e3] } *


