2... b5? { The Zilbermints Gambit. This is an extremely rare gambit, but if you don't know how to play against it, white can mess up early. } 3. cxb5! { The simplest way to continue, chomping up the free pawn. } 3... a6 { The most common option for black. If we take the a pawn, black will get an active bishop after recapturing. The best way to continue is to defend it. } 4. e3! { Simply protecting it. } { [%csl Gb5,Gf1] } 4... axb5 (4... Nf6 $32 { Black continues developing. } 5. Nc3 { Reinforcing b5 and controlling e4. } { [%csl Gb5,Re4][%cal Gc3b5] } 5... e6 6. Nf3 $16 { Next up, white just has to continue developing and enjoys being up a clean pawn. }) 5. Bxb5+ { Recapturing. } 5... c6 { Solidifying and gaining tempo. This is no problem. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc6][%cal Gc6d5] } 6. Bd3 { Simply retreating to the most active square. } { [%csl Gd3] } 6... Nf6 $32 { Developing... } (6... Ba6 7. Nf3! { Simply ignoring it, and getting ready to castle. White's doing great. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1,Bb1c3,Bf3e5] }) 7. Nf3 $32 { Getting ready to O-O. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 7... Bg4 { Black pins our knight. The best way for white to avoid anything annoying is Nbd2, simply allowing our queen to move away without allowing black to give us double f pawns. } { [%csl Rf3,Rd1] } (7... e6 8. O-O Bd6 9. b3! { Simply trying to get the DSB as active as possible. White's doing great. } { [%csl Bb2,Gf3,Gd3][%cal Bc1b2,Bb1c3] }) 8. Nbd2 $16 { White has a very comfortable position and is up a pawn. Next, we can castle the king to safety, and get the DSB more active with b3 followed by Bb2. Besides the rook having much space, black doesn't have much compensation. } { [%csl Bg1,Bb2,Rf8,Re8,Rd8,Ga8,Yf2,Ye3,Yd4,Gd3][%cal Bb2b3,Bd1c2,Bh2h3,Be1g1,Bc1b2,Yf2e3,Ye3d4] } *


