[Event "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...d6: 🚀 == Introduction  == 🚀"]
[Date "2025.09.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B50"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Modern Variations"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...d6"]
[ChapterName "🚀 == Introduction  == 🚀"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Vpb6r3Wq/aZ8yc3ia"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2025.09.11"]
[UTCTime "13:27:12"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ ✨ Welcome to my new study! ✨

In one of my previous studies, I shared a rare but powerful weapon against the Sicilian, which was well received. However, it only covered how to play against 2...Nc6, the Old Sicilian.

But what if Black plays 2...d6 instead? 🤔 That's what we'll be covering here. I’ll show you a simple, yet powerful weapon to CRUSH the 2...d6 Sicilian! 🏹🔥

If you haven’t yet, make sure to check out the one against the 2...Nc6 Sicilian when you have time: https://lichess.org/study/55CPbtmd 😃

If you find this study helpful, please give it a heart 💓! It helps more players discover this study and adds it to the "favorites" list to help you find this study again easily.

If you have any questions about the study, feel free to DM me. 💬

💡 Btw, get this entire repertoire for FREE in Noctie and practice it against a humanlike bot: https://go.noctie.ai/crush-sicilian 😉

Let’s get started! Play 1. e4! :) 🚀 }
1. e4! { First of all, some notes. This study is aimed for Beginner to Late-Intermediate players.
Sorry it took me so long to release this one, I've actually been planning to create this study since about a year ago. But the problem is, I never found any good lines I was satisfied with. I've looked at the Delayed Alapin, Haag Gambit, Ginsberg Gambit, Chekhover, 3. d4-c3, etc. But I wasn't satisfied, many have to follow specific lines that aren't always played, or would force you to learn an immense amount of theory.
I was looking for something, rare, not too hard to learn, high-winrates, and takes your opponents out of their prep. And then... I saw a video by GM Igor Smirnov ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M1ZZYP5pPQc ), and honestly I really liked the line he showed. Of course, no opening is perfect, but until now, I think this is the best repertoire to share with you. I'm pretty happy with it and have started using it in my own games.
Also, don't worry, this is way less complicated and crazy that the Portsmouth Gambit. It relies a lot on knowing the ideas, so please don't do aimless memorization and instead try to learn from the notes given. } 1... c5 { You should be familiar with this by now. ;) } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Rc5d4,Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 d6 { Oh, Black plays 2...d6, called the Modern Variations. Often leading to the Classical, Dragon, or Najdorf, each of these we're not really in the mood to face. This is actually the most popular Sicilian line at higher levels. It supports the c-pawn and frees Black’s light-squared bishop.
We can't play the Portsmouth Gambit against this sadly.
We'll play, a rather shocking move, Bc4! } { [%csl Yc8,Bc5,Bd6,Be7,Gc4][%cal Bd6c5,Be7d6,Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4!? { This is a move that looks like only absolute beginners play. And at first glance, the winrates don't look good either with Black scoring 50%. But don't worry! That's only because many White players follow up badly. We'll play lines that have over a 55% winrate for us!
Bc4 has multiple purposes:,
It aims at the f7 pawn, which you will see later on, is a very popular theme and our king is ready to castle.
Go to the next chapter to start! } { [%csl Bg1,Rf7][%cal Be1g1] } *


