1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4!? Nf6 { Welcome to section 1! This is the most popular move and also it's the most important section, because most of the time you'll transpose into one of these lines. It's important to understand the ideas here, as you'll see similar positions again and again. We'll look at this move in the upcoming chapters marked with📕. } *


[Event "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...d6: 📕 6...Nbd7?? + 5th moves"]
[Date "2025.09.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...d6"]
[ChapterName "📕 6...Nbd7?? + 5th moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Vpb6r3Wq/Y3DZslvq"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/3p1n2/2p5/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.09.11"]
[UTCTime "13:27:12"]

{ We'll start off with a move being played only 7% of the time. }
4. e5!? { Not the top engine move, but definitely the trickiest! It isn't dubious however, as the position is still equal. The idea is to place our knight on the active central e5 square, while also attacking f7, which later on will be a hidden resource for us more often than you’d expect. } { [%cal Gf3e5] } 4... dxe5 { Quite forced as we're attacking the knight and played almost every time. I might add a sidelines section later covering d5 and Ng4 though. } 5. Nxe5 { Fun fact: 20% of the time, according to the lichess database, your opponent isn't paying attention and will blunder mate in 1 or a large amount of material. :)
The knight is actually quite hard to get rid of here, which we will discuss more later. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rc4f7,Ye5f7] } 5... e6 { Quite forced. The rest of this section will cover from here. } (5... Qd4?? { Actually accounting for about 25,000 games here on lichess. } 6. Bxf7+ { Not mate, because the king has an escape square, but definitely winning for us. } 6... Kd8 7. Qe2! $18 { The key move you need to know. Simply defending the knight. Here White is much better due to the extra pawn, Black's king cannot castle, and the queen's bad position. Because we're already better, we can keep things simple. If the knight is attacked/trade offered, simply move it back to f3. If the Bishop is attacked, move it to b3. Try not to trade material tho, a general principle if you have a positional advantage. It's +2.3. } { [%cal Bf7b3,Rb1a3,Ra3b5,Be1g1,Bc2c3,Bd2d3] }) (5... Nbd7?? { Another 20k games. } 6. Bxf7#! { [%csl Be8,Rd8,Rd7,Re7,Rf8][%cal Bf7e8] }) (5... Be6? { Not sure why, but gets played. } 6. Bxe6 { We simply take. } 6... fxe6 7. O-O $16 { No immediately winning position, but Black's pawn structure is disgusting. It will be a long term nuance for him. } { [%csl Ge5,Gg1,Re6,Re7,Re8,Rf8,Rd8][%cal Bf1e1,Bd2d3,Bb1d2,Bd2f3] }) 6. Qe2!? { Here we'll play another key move! The incredibly rare Qe2! Immediately our winrates are at 56%! We delay castling for now, we can do that anytime. We now support the knight and actually set up a very successful idea, which involves that the queen is indirectly aiming at e6. } { [%csl Ge5,Re6] } 6... Nbd7?? { Black wants to get rid of our central knight, which is a theme we'll see very often in this opening, and thus offers a trade. This is the third most played move, but loses immediately! } 7. Nxf7!! { Sacrificing the knight! Removing the defender of e6. Now you can see one of the ideas of Qe2. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Be2e6] } 7... Kxf7 { If Black doesn't take, just take one of the forked pieces and enjoy the huge material advantage. :) } (7... Qe7 8. Nxh8 $18) 8. Qxe6+! { Take with the queen of course! Taking with the bishop loses the entire advantage. The king is forced out of his camp. } (8. Bxe6+?? Ke8 $17 { Mmh, now what? }) 8... Kg6 $7 9. h4! { Another very important moment! The only way to correctly continue the attack. Taking away the d5 square and threatening to move forward. (d3/d4 takes away g5, but does not have the follow up threat, allowing Qe8, forcing a queen trade ending the attack. } { [%csl Rg5,Bh5][%cal Rh4g5,Bh4h5] } 9... h5 { Most popular try, preventing h5. If Black plays anything else, always play h5+ followed by d4+ and you should get a checkmate very soon. Black tries to flee to h7, we must prevent that. He cannot hide. } { [%csl Rh7] } (9... Ne5 10. h5+ Kh6 11. d4+ { Our usual follow up. } 11... g5 12. Bxg5+ Kxg5 13. Qxe5+ Kg4 14. f3#) (9... Qe7 { Wanting to trade queens, but it's too late. Our other pieces can finish the job. } 10. h5+ Kh6 11. d4+ g5 12. hxg6+ { En passant! } 12... Kxg6 13. Bd3+ Kg7 14. Bh6# { White's pieces work wonderfully together! } { [%csl Gh6,Gh1,Gd3,Ge6] }) 10. Bd3+! { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7] } 10... Kh6 $7 { [%csl Rg6,Rh7][%cal Gd3h7] } 11. Qe3+ { [%csl Rh7,Rg6,Rh6][%cal Gd3h7,Ye3h6] } 11... g5 $7 12. Qxg5# { Checkmate! Game I played: https://lichess.org/1fBv8rIm4v2F } { [%csl Yg7,Yh6,Rh5,Gh7][%cal Yg5g7,Yg5h6,Bd3h7] } *


