[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...d6"]
[ChapterName "📕 6...Be7"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Vpb6r3Wq/D05AbgXr"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2p1N3/2B5/8/PPPPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 6"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.09.11"]
[UTCTime "13:27:12"]

{ Now we'll look at Be7, the second (almost tied to first) most popular move. }
6... Be7 { Black prioritizes castling. There really aren't many options for Black, the LSB cannot be moved, moving Nbd7 is bad as we've seen in the previous chapter, and Nc6? of course leads to an unfavorable pawn structure, so he's left with the DSB. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 7. O-O { We play the most simple move, bringing the king out of the center and planning to give the rook activity. } { [%csl Be1][%cal Bf1e1] } 7... O-O (7... Nbd7?? { Oh oh, Black again wants to get rid of the knight, but this fails to the same ideas as the previous chapter. } 8. Nxf7! Kxf7 9. Qxe6+ Kg6 { Now h4 doesn't do much, because there's no rook. The king must be forced further out. } 10. Qf7+ Kh6 11. d4+ g5 12. Bxg5+! { Further! } 12... Kxg5 13. Qg7+ Kf5 14. Re1 $18 { Checkmate will follow soon. } { [%cal Bc4d3,Bc4e6,Ge1e8,Yg8g1] }) 8. Re1! { Bringing the rook to the e-file. We actually have another trick up our sleeve that's immensely successful. } 8... a6 { Very popular. Threatening b5. You'll see a6 very often throughout the study. We almost always will respond with a4, preventing b5. Remember: If a6 (or a5 although rare), respond with a4 (unless mentioned otherwise).
After that, we'll usually just transpose to a similar line with this difference. Same ideas usually apply. } (8... Nbd7 { Often played immediately or after a6 first. Here, it's actually not really a blunder, but the fact is Black will 80% of the time mess up on the next move. } 9. Nxf7! { Our same idea as the main variation. } 9... Rxf7?? (9... Kxf7! 10. Bxe6+ Ke8 { In the a6 a4 variation White has Ra3, here it isn't available. } 11. d3 Nb6 12. Bb3 $10 { White's down 1 point in material, but has more than enough compensation with control of the e-file, Black's stuck king, etc. } { [%csl Gb3,Ge2,Ge1,Re7,Re8][%cal Bb1c3,Bc1g5] }) 10. Qxe6 { Same as main variation. } 10... Qf8 11. Qxe7 $18) (8... Qc7 { Top engine, going for a different plan of getting rid of the pesky knight. With Nc6, then after Nxc6 Black can recapture with the queen. } { [%cal Bb8c6] } 9. a4 $32 { Gaining space on the queenside. Rook lifting is an idea, rerouting to g3, although a bit risky as all the pieces are still on the board. From here just play chess. Black will definitely play Nc6, just trade and develop. There's three developing plans, b3 and fiachetto or d3 and Bf4. I personally prefer the b3 line tho. And of course for the aggressive fellas there's Ra3-Rg3. White has a 71% winrate, only based on 66 games, however. } { [%cal Bd2d3,Bc1f4,Bf4g3,Yb2b3,Yc1b2,Ga1a3,Ga3g3] }) 9. a4 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra4b5] } 9... Nbd7? { Most popular. The theme recurs. Black wants to get rid of our central knight, but this blocks the LSB, allowing our following sequence: } (9... b6 { Trying to develop the LSB. } { [%cal Bc8b7] } 10. b3 Bb7 11. Bb2 $36 { We have a nice setup. The d-pawn usually doesn't move till the endgame. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Bb1a3,Ba1d1,Bc4d3,Ba3c4] }) (9... Qc7 { The best move. } 10. a5! Nc6 (10... Nbd7? 11. Nxf7 { Same idea. }) 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. b3 $10 { [%csl Gc4,Ge2][%cal Bc1b2,Bd2d3,Bb1d2,Bf2f3] }) 10. Nxf7! { Removing the defender of e6! } 10... Rxf7 { Almost everyone takes with the rook. } (10... Kxf7 { This requires a different response. } 11. Bxe6+! (11. Qxe6+?? Ke8 $17 { The king is... safe? Black will play Ndb6 which kicks our queen. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Bd7b6] }) 11... Ke8 12. Ra3! $16 { Genius! The rook will almost always move to d3, building pressure along the d-file. Only after Qc7, does the rook move to g3 (as there wouldn't be a pin). Then the remaining queenside pieces can develop with Na3 and fianchetto. Black's pieces are completely trapped. It's +2. This is the reason why the Nbd7 variation in the non-a6 line isn't as bad.
Game using this idea: https://lichess.org/iXQc20xH#4 } { [%csl Rg7,Rd8,Rd7,Gd3,Re7,Rc8,Rf8][%cal Ba3d3,Bd3g3,Bg3g7,Bb1a3,Bb2b3,Bc1b2] }) 11. Qxe6 { We're threatening to take the rook, but notice the DSB is also hanging because of the pin! Black cannot save both pieces. } { [%csl Rf7,Re7] } 11... Qf8 12. Qxe7 { Making use of the pin! White's fully winning here. } { [%csl Rf7,Ge7][%cal Yc4g8] } *


