[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH the Sicilian! 2...d6"]
[ChapterName "📕 6...Bd6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Vpb6r3Wq/7pAPtW5R"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2p1N3/2B5/8/PPPPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 6"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.09.11"]
[UTCTime "13:27:12"]

6... Bd6 { Almost tied for most popular move together with Be7. There aren't many traps here compared to the previous chapters, but instead we'll get a very comfortable attacking setup. } { [%cal Be8g8] } 7. b3! { The most successful move! The winrates jump from 47 to 55%. We'll go for similar setups shown in the previous chapter. } { [%cal Bc1b2] } 7... O-O (7... Nbd7?? 8. Nxf7! { Same idea as the previous chapters! :) }) (7... Qc7 { With the idea of supporting Nc6. The following line will show great typical developing ideas you'll often face. } { [%cal Bc7c6] } 8. Bb2 O-O 9. f4 $32 { [%cal Bc4d3,Be1g1,Ba2a4,Bb1c3] } 9... a6 10. a4 { You know the rule. } 10... Nc6 { Now Black plays Nc6. Note, Black still couldn't force our knight away, as Nxc6, then we recapture with a fork. But, it's time to give up our knight's central presence. This is because we'll then open up our DSB and Nd4 would've been very annoying for us. So, trading here is fine. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Rc6d4] } 11. Nxc6 { The DSB becomes much more powerful. } { [%cal Gb2g7] } 11... Qxc6 { Now Bxf6 is possible, but it's better not to trade. This will damage Black's pawn structure, but we costs us our DSB. We don't have enough pieces to launch a mating attack, so Black will be able to have enough time to defend. } 12. O-O { Instead we can castle. Defending the f pawn, bringing the king to safety, and making the rook active. It can potentially join in an attack with Rf3-g3 or after a future f5 push. } { [%csl Gf1][%cal Bf1f3,Yf3g3,Bf4f5] } 12... b6 { Black continues developing. So can we. No need to rush to break open the position or get an attack with f5 or Rf3. First we improve all our pieces. } 13. Na3! { We don't want to block our DSB! The knight can potentially later reroute to c4 after Bd3. } { [%cal Ba3c4,Bc4d3] } 13... Bb7 { Bd3 immediately is possible, but why not finish the development of every piece first? } { [%csl Ga1] } 14. Rae1! $40 { Now every piece is developed. We didn't rush to break open the position or attack right away! We weren't ready for that yet.
This is a really great aggressive setup. Though equal, White has a 80% winrate here. Already Black can go wrong very fast. For example: 14...Nd5 is already very bad, White has Qg4! g6 and f5 White has a very strong kingside attack. 14...Rad8 loses a pawn after Bxh6.
One thing to look out for; often Black has this Q + LSB battery, so make sure not to blunder mate in 1. Often Rf2 is necessary in order not to let our queen be tied down. } { [%csl Rg2,Gg1,Gf1,Ge1,Ge2,Gc4,Ga3,Gb2][%cal Yf1f2,Be2g4,Bc4d3,Ba3c4,Bb2e5] }) 8. Bb2 Nbd7 { Now Nbd7, wanting to get rid of the central knight, is possible. But we'll annoy Black more: } (8... a6 { "If a6... } 9. a4 { " } 9... Nbd7 10. f4 { Same stuff. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Be1g1,Bb1c3,Bb1a3,Bc4d3] }) (8... Nc6? 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $16 { Now castling queenside is a nice option, Black cannot launch a pawn storm with this pawn structure. } { [%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Bb1c3,Be1c1] }) 9. f4! $10 { Now Black (again) cannot force our knight away. If he captures, we recapture with the f-pawn and gain tempo + and open file. We have a very comfortable position, nice bishop pair, central knight, advanced f-pawn. Often the b knight will not develop to c3, as this would block the DSB which is one of our most powerful pieces. Instead a4-Na3 would be better, with the idea of rerouting to c4 in the future. The d-pawn has no need to move. It's still equal, but Black will be on the defensive side. I wouldn't recommend castling queenside here.
Make sure to check out the variation above for typical developing plans.
Let's end theory and this section here. Btw, there's no need to create a separate chapter for 6...a6 as it will transpose to positions we've already covered.
If you're serious about mastering this opening, I recommend you check out some of the games in the database. It'll definitely help you familiarize with attacking ideas and plans. One interesting game definitely worth checking out: https://lichess.org/Oz1z8mv8#0 } { [%cal Be1g1,Bb1c3,Ba2a4,Bc4d3,Bb1a3] } *


