[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2025.09.11"]
[UTCTime "13:27:12"]

4. Qe2 Nc6 { Black develops the other knight, strengthening control over e5. This means we can’t push the e-pawn, so we’ll go for a different setup. } { [%csl Gc6,Re5] } 5. c3! { Preparing to push d5 at some point. Also, the LSB can potentially reroute to c2, where it will be more active if the a2-g8 diagonal gets closed. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4,Yc4b3,Yb3c2] } 5... Nf6 { Black will most likely develop in some way as this, getting the knight out, Be7 and castle, although the move order might be different or a move like h6 thrown in-between. } (5... a6 6. d4 b5 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. cxd4 { [%csl Ge4,Gd4][%cal Ba2a4,Bd4d5] }) (5... g6 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bg7 8. d5 exd5 (8... Ne5 9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. dxe6 Bxe6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 { [%csl Rf7,Re6][%cal Be1g1,Bb1d2,Bd2f3,Bc1e3,Bb1a3] }) 9. exd5+ Nce7 10. O-O $16 { [%csl Gg1,Gf3][%cal Bb1c3,Ba2a4,Bc1d2] }) 6. Bb3! { d4 is playable immediately, but I prefer playing Bb3 first. This is a very important moment. The point is that Black had Nxe4 Qxe4 and then d5 forks the 2 pieces winning a very favorable exchange. By retreating the bishop, we don't have such issues. } (6. O-O? Nxe4 7. Qxe4 d5 { Black has a favorable exchange. } { [%csl Rc4,Re4][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] }) 6... Be7 { Next we'll castle and strike the center with d4. } 7. O-O O-O { If ever Black strengthens control of d4, with Qb6 or e5 for instance, do the same by playing Rd1. } (7... e5 { Preventing an immediate d4. } 8. Rd1 $10 { Strengthening the d4 push. From here it's standard development. } { [%cal Bd2d4,Bh2h3,Bb1a3,Ba3c4,Bc1g5] }) 8. d4! { [%csl Gd4,Ge4] } 8... cxd4 (8... d5 9. e5 Ne4 (9... Nd7 10. Re1 { [%cal Bc1e3,Bb1d2] }) 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 11. Bxd2 cxd4 12. cxd4 { [%cal Bb3c2,Bf1e1] }) (8... e5 9. d5 $16 { Locking the center, giving Black a backward d-pawn and a stuck DSB. From here on it's a slow positional game. } { [%csl Rd6,Re7][%cal Bb1d2,Bb3c2,Bh2h3,Bf1e1,Bd2f1,Bf1g3,Bb1a3] }) 9. cxd4 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4] } 9... d5 { Black wants to counterstrike the center. Make sure not to take here, as that helps Black develop. } (9... e5?! { Allows us to push d5. } 10. d5 { The knight doesn't have a good square to go. } 10... Nb8 (10... Na5 11. Bc2 b6 12. Nc3) 11. Nc3 $16 { Black is left with a backward d-pawn and most of his pieces on the backrank. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Bc1e3,Bh2h3,Bb3c2,Ba2a4] }) (9... a6 10. Nc3 { Standard development. We got a nice position. } { [%csl Rc8,Re7,Gb3][%cal Be4e5,Bf1d1,Bc1e3,Bb3c2] }) 10. e5 { We lock the center and kick Black's knight. } 10... Ne4 { Black's knight is annoying here, but thankfully it's easy to get rid of it. } (10... Nd7 11. Nc3 f6 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Re1 $16 { [%cal Bb3c2,Bc1g5,Ba1d1,Ba2a4] }) 11. Nc3! { We don't mind a trade, as it helps out our pawnstructure. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rc3e4] } 11... Nxc3 (11... f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Re1 $16 { White has strong control of the e-file, potentially active bishop, and Black has a backward e-pawn. } { [%csl Re6,Rc8][%cal Bc1g5,Bb3c2,Ba1d1,Ba2a4] }) (11... Ng5 12. Bxg5 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 Qxg5 14. Rad1 $16 { Defending d4. From here the idea is to attack on the kingside. We can do so by pushing our kingside pawns, as Black really has no way of attacking our king. Black's pieces aren't really active, asides the queen which can easily be kicked. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Bf2f4,Bg2g4,Bb3c2] }) 12. bxc3 { We have a nice pawn chain and an attacking setup. Our bishops are also nicely aiming at the kingside. Black's pieces are quite stuck. The LSB is behind the pawns, and the DSB doesn't have a good way to become active. } { [%csl Gc1,Gb3,Yc3,Yd4,Ye5,Rc8][%cal Bb3c2,Be2d3,Ba1b1] } *


