4. Qe2 a6 (4... Be7 5. O-O Nf6 6. e5 dxe5 7. Nxe5 { Our lines. }) 5. a4 { To not confuse ourselves, we can play a4 here, although Bb3 or c3 are also very good moves. } 5... Nc6 (5... Nf6 6. e5 dxe5 7. Nxe5 { Transposes to section 1. }) 6. c3 Nf6 (6... e5) 7. Bb3 { Again avoiding any Nxe4 tactics. We continue with normal development like the previous chapter, but a main difference here is that d4 is usually not great. This is because Black will have Qb6, which hits our now undefended LSB and d4 indirectly. That's something to keep in mind. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 $10 { h3 is almost always a good idea which is playable at any moment really. It's a nice prophylaxis move that prevents any future Ng4 or Bg4 and creates a breathing hole for our king. Don't play d4, instead play d3 and continue slow standard development. There's no need to rush an attack or break open the position.
That's all for this section. I know this was more boring positional, no trap stuff, but we can't really avoid that and playing well in positional positions is an important part of chess. } { [%cal Yb3a2,Yb3c2,Bb1d2,Gd2d3,Bd2f1,Rf1e1] } *


