4. Qe2!? { We play our move again! Keeps things simple, doesn't make us confused, and takes the opponent out of his prep. :)
An idea of this move is that we're now defending the e-pawn with the queen. So, we don't have to worry about it after Black attacks it later. Not having to play Nc3 defending it, keeping the option of c3 open. } { [%cal Bc2c3] } 4... Nf6 { Developing, also preparing Bg4, which was previously not playable due to Bxf7+. } (4... e6 5. c3) (4... Bg4?? { A common blunder. } 5. Bxf7+ { Exposing the king! } 5... Kxf7 6. Ng5+ { Discovered attack. } { [%csl Rg4] } 6... Ke8 7. Qxg4 Nf6 8. Qe6 $16 { White has a very nice advantage. Black has lost castling rights, and has difficulties developing. } { [%csl Rf7,Re8,Rf8][%cal Re6f7,Bg5e6] }) 5. h3! { As I've said in the previous chapter h3 is almost always a good move. Now's a very nice time to play it, as Bg4 might be annoying. } { [%csl Rg4] } 5... g6 { Black will almost always develop in some way as this, or transpose to the previous section. } { [%cal Bf8g7] } (5... e6 6. Bb3 { Now we've transposed into the previous section. }) 6. O-O { Castling, c3, or a4 first. The move order doesn't matter too much. } 6... Bg7 { Both sides develop. } 7. c3 { Preparing for a d4 push. } { [%cal Bd2d4,Yc4b3,Yb3c2] } 7... O-O { d4 is playable right away, but let's support it even more. } (7... e5) 8. Rd1! a6 9. d4 $10 { We've gained the center. It's an equal game, but White has the 61% winrate here. If b5 simply retreat the bishop to b3 and c2. If cxd4, we can recapture with the c-pawn. With all the ideas you faced in this study you should be ready to face almost anything in the d6 Sicilian. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4][%cal Bc1g5,Bb1d2,Bd2f1,Be4e5,Bd4d5] } *


