{ Let's very quickly check out some 3rd move sidelines. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 Bg4?? { Quite a common blunder among beginners. So we'll quickly cover this move. Here we'll play a simple tactic. } 4. Bxf7+! { Bringing the king out, preparing for out next move. } (4. Ne5? { Cool try, but Black isn't forced to take the queen. :) } 4... dxe5 5. Qxg4 Nf6 { We now just traded our knight for Black's bishop. There's no attack or other advantage for us. }) 4... Kxf7 (4... Kd7 5. Ne5+! { Again a discovered attack! } 5... dxe5 6. Qxg4+ Kc7 7. Bxg8 Rxg8 8. Qe6! { A fully winning position. } { [%csl Rg8,Re5,Rc7][%cal Re6e5,Re6g8] }) 5. Ng5+ { Discovered attack! } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Yd1g4,Rg5f7] } 5... Ke8 6. Qxg4 { We're up a pawn and Black has lost castling rights. White has a very comfortable advantage. Also, the most popular move by far (81% of the time) here for Black is Nf6, but that loses on the spot after Qe6! } { [%csl Gg4,Gg5,Re8] } *


