[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/artxS9bL/zEMcjXf7"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

2. d4 { White immediately controls the center.
Black has a really nice response now: } { [%cal Ge4f5,Gd4c5,Ge4d5,Gd4e5] } 2... e5! { Black moves to challenge the center right away. In response, White has three main options. I'll explain each of them in the upcoming chapters. But for now, let's start with the move that White plays most often: } 3. d5 { White opts for a more closed game, initiating what's known as the Linkspringer Variation. Each chapter having 3. d5 is marked with 📗. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rd5c6] } *


[Event "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense: 📗 Linksspringer Variation 3. d5 with 4. c4"]
[Date "2024.04.16"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B00"]
[Opening "Nimzowitsch Defense: Kennedy Variation, Linksspringer Variation"]
[StudyName "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense"]
[ChapterName "📗 Linksspringer Variation 3. d5 with 4. c4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/artxS9bL/trjOxQJa"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

3. d5 { White moves to kick our knight. Black isn't concerned since the knight will find a strong position on g6, ready to participate in a potential attack on the kingside. } { [%csl Bg6][%cal Bc6e7,Be7g6] } 3... Nce7! { [%csl Bg6][%cal Be7g6] } 4. c4 { The most popular move. We now just continue our plan by playing Ng6. } 4... Ng6! { Reroute complete! Before you go to the next move I want you to look at the winrates in the lichess database. As you can see black scores incredibly well. :D } { [%csl Bg6][%cal Bb8c6,Bc6e7,Be7g6] } 5. Nc3 (5. Nf3 { The second most popular response. } 5... Nf6 { Slightly better than Bc5, this attacks the e pawn. } 6. Nc3 { White protects the e pawn. It doesn't matter if it's Nc3 or Bd3, we play the same thing. } 6... Bc5 { We play the same setup as before. } { [%csl Rf2] } 7. Bd3 { White prepares to castle, we can castle too now. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 7... O-O! 8. O-O a5! { Now black gets a great game! The winrate for black is already at a whopping 64%!! Now how do you continue? We always play d6 on the next move, except after Na4 we retreat the bishop to a7, we want to keep it at all costs. After 9...d6 is played black often plays 10...Na5! rerouting to f4 and letting the queen join the party by going to f6, then black gets a nice kingside attack. } { [%csl Bf4,Gf6,Gg6][%cal Bd7d6,Bf6h5,Bh5f4,Bc5a7] }) (5. Be3 { A slightly more annoying move, this interferes with our plan, the DSB can no longer be placed on c5. } 5... b6! { We won't let this stop our plan! With b6 black supports the future DSB. } { [%csl Yc5][%cal Gb6c5] } 6. Nc3 { It doesn't actually matter what white plays, they all transpose to very similar positions. } 6... Bc5! { It doesn't matter if black gets doubled pawns, we'll still get a nice structure. } 7. Bxc5 bxc5 8. Nf3 d6 { Black has an amazing position! The b file is open for the rook (don't use it for the LSB, it doesn't have any good squares there), and a future f pawn push is coming. Also Nh6 works to further support the f pawn push. } { [%csl Gc7,Gd6,Ge5,Gc5,Bf5][%cal Ba8b8,Gd6c5,Gc7d6,Gd6e5,Bf7f5,Bg8h6] }) 5... Bc5! { The best move. We want to get that bishop out before we close the position with d6. It also aims at the f pawn. } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Rd7d6] } 6. Bd3 { White prepares to castle. } (6. Nf3 Nf6 { We transpose to the same position above somewhere. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Bd7d6,Be8g8,Bf6h5] }) (6. a3 a5! { Important rule of thumb: ALWAYS meet a3 with a5. For the rest, just continue with our standard moves: Nf6, d6, O-O... } { [%csl Gc5,Ba7,Rb4][%cal Bc5a7,Ba5b4,Bb2b4] }) 6... Nf6 { Black prepares to castle and sets up an insanely successful trap for black. } { [%csl Bg8,Gg6,Gf6][%cal Be8g8] } 7. Nge2?? { A game losing blunder! This is by a pretty far margin the most popular move! Even at 2500+ level it gets played 53% of the time!! } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } (7. Na4 { White want to get rid of our bishop. } 7... Bb4+ { There's actually only 1 good move for white: Kf1!, it never gets played tough. } 8. Kf1! (8. Bd2?! { We can just trade now... } 8... Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Nf4 $17 { Black's knight is now well placed here. Taking the LSB is always an option. } { [%csl Gf4] }) (8. Nc3?! { We can just take it. } 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 d6 $15 { Solidifying. Nd2-Nc4 is now a very good idea, it can't be kicked away there. Black's winrate is at 58%. } { [%csl Bc5,Gd6,Ge5,Gc7][%cal Bf6d7,Bd7c5,Gc7d6,Gd6e5] }) 8... c6! { Black's doing totally fine. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8,Bb4e7,Bd7d6] }) 7... Ng4! { The only winning move. f6 is under attack. } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Bg4f2,Bc5f2] } 8. O-O { We win on the spot now. } 8... Qh4! { The queen, bishop and knight work together to destroy black. Black's threatening mate in 1 and triple attacking f2. It's over now, but let's see the most common endings. } { [%csl Rf2,Gg4,Gc5,Rh2][%cal Bh4h2,Bh4f2] } 9. h3 { The only move that stops checkmate. } 9... Nxf2 { There's threat's all over the place. } { [%csl Rg1,Gc5,Rd1] } 10. Rxf2 Qxf2+ 11. Kh1 d6 { Freeing up the LSB, preparing to sac on h3. } { [%csl Gc8,Rh3] } 12. Na4 { The most common line. } (12. Qg1 { The only move that survives a bit longer. } 12... Qxg1+ { Now that the queens are off the board white doesn't have any chances of winning and we get closer to an endgame where black's up an exchange. } 13. Nxg1 O-O $19 { Black is definitely better here. It's -3.5 } { [%csl Gg8,Ga8,Gf8,Gc5] }) 12... Bxh3! { Wrecking the white king's only defense. } 13. gxh3 Qf3+ 14. Kh2 Nh4 { Bring another piece into the attack. } { [%csl Rg2][%cal Gf3g2,Yh4g2] } 15. Qh1 Qf2+ 16. Qg2 Qxg2# { Checkmate! } *


