3. d5 Nce7 4. f4? { This is the third most popular move. Black can quickly get the advantage now, although many times black messes up. } 4... Ng6! { The absolute best move, other move lose the advantage. } 5. f5? { By far the most popular move. We just do a simple fork ;) } 5... Qh4+! { Immediately white's rethinking their life choices. Everything goes downhill for white. But, black still has to pay careful attention. } { [%csl Re4,Re1] } 6. Kd2 { Only move that survives. Here black has to play a MUST-move, many players don't find this. } (6. g3?? Qxe4+ { [%csl Ge1,Gh1][%cal Ge4h1,Ge4e1] } 7. Qe2 Qxh1 { Black grabs the free rook. } 8. fxg6 hxg6 { The most simple option. Black's up 4 points in material. Nf3 isn't anything to be afraid of because the queen won't get trapped because of d6-Bh3. } { [%csl Rg1,Rh2,Rd5,Bh3,Gf3][%cal Bd7d6,Bc8h3,Yg1f3] }) 6... Nf6!! { Just keep attacking the king by bringing in more pieces! } { [%csl Re4] } 7. fxg6 { It's game-over now! } (7. Nc3 Bb4! { Pinning the knight, thus preparing to capture e4 with check without having to trade more material. } 8. fxg6 (8. Bd3? Nxe4+ 9. Bxe4 Qxe4 $19 { And everything falls apart for white. This position is very similar to a variation below. } { [%csl Rg2,Rd5,Rd2][%cal Be4g2,Be4d5] }) 8... Nxe4+ 9. Ke2 Qf2+ 10. Kd3 Nc5+ 11. Kc4 a5! $17 { Even though white has an extra horse, black has the advantage because of white's horrible king placement. Note: after gxf2 recapture with the queen NOT the king. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Bc7c6,Bb7b5] }) (7. Bd3 { Another pretty common attempt. There's only one winning move here: } 7... Nxe4+! { No need to worry about the knight on g3, we have to keep attacking. } 8. Bxe4 Qxe4 { Suddenly everything falls apart for white. } { [%csl Rg2,Rd5,Rf5,Rd2][%cal Ge4g2,Ge4d5,Ge4f5] } 9. fxg6 Qxg2+ { Checking the king and hitting the rook. } { [%csl Rh1,Rd2][%cal Gg2h1,Gg2d2] } 10. Ne2 Qxd5+! { Giving another check and just grabbing the free pawns. Note that the rook will be hanging after white brings the king the the first rank. } { [%csl Rh1] } 11. Kc3 { Any check (that doesn't hang material) is good. } 11... Qa5+ { We have to keep the queens on the board. The king is weak, so the queen is are most strongest piece to attack it and keep it from moving to safety. } 12. Kd3 hxg6 $19 { And black's totally winning. Literally the only piece over the second rank is the king. It's absolutely not safe there. Black can play d5 on the next move, gaining space in the center, and develop the LSB. White's king is currently staying here near the center. Black can try to keep him from running away with queen checks. It's -5 in favor for black. } { [%csl Rd3,Rc1,Rb1,Ra1,Rd1,Rh1,Re2,Gh8,Ga5,Gf8][%cal Bd7d5,Bc8f5,Bf5g4] }) (7. Qf3 { The best move according to Stockfish. } 7... Nxe4+ { Taking the free pawn. } 8. Ke2 { Anywhere else results in Nf2+. Or after Ke3 there the deadly Qe1+. } 8... Nf4+ 9. Bxf4 Qxf4 10. Qxf4 exf4 $17 { Black ends up having a better endgame. }) 7... Nxe4+! { Only move that wins, forcing the king to move further down the board. } 8. Ke3 (8. Kd3 Nf2+ $19 { A royal family fork. } { [%csl Rd1,Rd3][%cal Gf2d1,Gf2d3] }) 8... Bc5+! { We just keep bringing in more pieces. } { [%csl Bf2,Be3][%cal Bc5f2] } 9. Kf3 { There's lots of checkmates here, we'll just pick the fastest one. } (9. Ke2 Qf2+ { Finding these check mates aren't that hard, just keep throwing sensible check. } 10. Kd3 Qd4+ 11. Ke2 Ng3+!! 12. hxg3 Qe4+ 13. Kd2 Qe3# { [%csl Bd2,Ye1,Ye2,Yc3,Yd3,Rc2,Rc1,Rd1][%cal Ge3c1,Ye3e1,Ye3c3] }) 9... Ng5+! { Preparing for e4+. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Be5e4] } 10. Bxg5 e4+! 11. Ke2 Qf2# { Checkmating while being down 2 knights! Beautiful! } { [%csl Gd2,Ge2,Ge1,Yf2,Ye3,Bf3,Bd3,Rd1,Rf1][%cal Gf2d2,Gf2e1,Yc5f2,Be4f3,Be4d3] } *


