3. d5 Nce7 { The usual stuff. } 4. Nf3 Ng6 { We just go for pretty much the same thing as chapter 3 when possible: Nf6-Bc5-d6 and O-O. } 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bg5? { The most popular move by a pretty far margin. } (6. Bd3 Bc5 7. O-O { [%cal Rc3a4] } 7... a6! { a6 is almost always good. It makes sure that we won't be forced to trade the DSB. } { [%cal Bc5a7,Bb7b5] } 8. Bg5 d6 $15 { Everything is going well. We'll kick the DSB away with h6 and castle. Then we can always do stuff like Nh5 followed by f5 if you want to be aggressive. } { [%csl Gg6,Gf6,Gc5][%cal Bh7h6,Be8g8] }) 6... h6! { This is why 6. Bg5 is bad. We question what this bishop is even doing here. Usually in these type of positions, you'd simply slide the bishop back a square, while keeping the pin. This doesn't work now because our knight is controlling the h4 square. Also trading it for our knight is not really favorable for white. } { [%csl Rh4] } 7. Bxf6 (7. Bh4? { It's a bit hard to see at first, but this loses a pawn by force. } 7... Nxh4 8. Nxh4 Nxe4! { A nice tactic. Black opens up the queen, and wins the sacrificed piece back. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Bd8h4] } 9. Nxe4 Qxh4 $17 { Black's up a clean pawn. It's -1.1. }) (7. Be3 { White just kinda wasted a move by moving it back and forth. } { [%csl Re3][%cal Bc1g5,Rg5e3] } 7... Bb4! { Immediately causing complications for white. The e pawn is hanging. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] } 8. Bd3 c6! $17 { Black is a bit better. } { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] }) 7... Qxf6 $15 { White has just wasted 2 moves to give black a developed queen and the bishop pair. To be clear, Stockfish says it's equal, but the winrates speak for themselves. Now a good idea is to start expanding on the queenside. You can start doing this with a6-b5-c6. I don't recommend closing the center up with d6 anytime soon, we won't be able to play c6 then. We can keep the LSB for now, it doesn't have a good role in the game currently, we'll preserve it for later. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Ba7a6,Bf8c5] } *


