[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

3. d5 Nce7 { Just doing what we always do. } 4. h4! { Ok, stop! This gets played only 1% of the time, but it's actually incredibly strong, and your opponent is probably well prepared. @Jisu101 has made an amazing study covering everything in this variation (White's perspective): https://lichess.org/study/DDSdbgcf. So, if you're looking for a weapon against the Nimzowitsch, check it out! We can't do our usual thing with Ng6, because white will just kick us with h5, then black's in huge trouble. } 4... Nf6! { The best move! Black immediately strikes back by hitting the pawn. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Bf6e4] } 5. f3 { Recommended in @Jisu101's study. Controlling the g4 square and protecting e4. The downside of this move is that it takes away the f3 square for the knight. } { [%csl Gg2,Gf3,Ge4,Rg1][%cal Yg2f3,Yf3e4,Rf3g4] } (5. Bd3 h5! { Avoiding a kingside pawn storm after g4. Of course, the downside of this is that we can't kick white's bishop when it goes to g5. } { [%csl Rg4,Rg5][%cal Rh5g4] } 6. Bg5 a6! { A prophylactic move, it avoids any annoying future Nb5/Bb5/...
We can now just follow up with Ng6, Nc5, d6. } { [%cal Be7g6,Bf8c5,Bd7d6] }) (5. Nc3 h6! 6. h5 d6 $10 { Just play c6 on the next move. Then black will be okay. } { [%cal Bc7c6] }) 5... d6! { Protecting the e pawn. Next we want to play c6. By now the winrates have equaled out. } { [%csl Ye5][%cal Gd6e5,Bc7c6] } 6. Ne2 { A developing move. It also controls the g3 square, avoiding black's Nh5-Ng3 reroute. } { [%csl Rg3][%cal Bf6h5,Bh5g3] } (6. c4? Nh5 { Wanting to jump into g3. } { [%csl Bg3][%cal Bh5g3,Bf7f5] } 7. Ne2 { Controlling g3. } { [%cal Re2g3] } 7... f5! { Expanding on the kingside and trying to break through. } 8. exf5 Nxf5 9. g4 { No actually a problem. } 9... Nhg3! { Attacking the rook. } { [%cal Rg3h1] } 10. Rh3 Nxe2 11. Qxe2 Nd4 $15 { Black has a great position. Next we'll make the DSB active with Be2 and castle on the kingside. } { [%csl Gd4,Yd6,Ye5,Yc7,Bh4,Bg8][%cal Yc7d6,Yd6e5,Bf8e7,Be7h4,Be8g8] }) 6... c6 7. c4 { Reinforcing the d pawn. } { [%cal Gc4d5] } 7... b5! $13 { At this point the position is very doubled-edged. Continue attacking on the queenside and when ready, you can castle on the kingside with Bg7 followed by O-O. } { [%cal Bg7g6,Bf8g7,Bh7h5,Bd8c7,Ba8b8] } *


