3. d5 Nce7 { [%cal Be7g6] } 4. Nf3 Ng6 { [%csl Gg6] } 5. h4! { This is Stockfish's favorite option. It's also the most popular move at master level. This is usually a sign your opponent is well prepared. White wants to kick our knight on g6 with h5 soon. There's only one move to stop that. } { [%cal Rh4h5] } 5... h5! { The only good move, every other move will lead to huge trouble after 6. h5. Of course, the disadvantage of this is that we can't kick White with h3 after White puts a piece on g5. } { [%csl Rg5,Gh5] } 6. Bg5 { The most popular move, putting the bishop on an active square where it will pin Black's pieces. It is also hard to get rid of it because h6 is unavailable. } (6. c4 Bc5 { Our standard move. Getting the bishop out of the pawn chain before we close it. } 7. Bg5 Nf6 8. Nc3 d6 9. a3 a5! $10 { Avoiding getting the bishop trapped. Just play c6 on the next move, and it's an equal game. } { [%cal Bc7c6] }) 6... Nf6! { The best move. Blocking by putting something on e7 is responded by White with 7. d6! which is very very annoying for Black. } 7. Nc3 Bb4 { Pinning the knight. Bc5 also works, it's your choice. } { [%csl Rc3,Re4] } 8. Bd3 d6 $10 { Next play c6, except after a3, then exchange on c3. After c6 you get an equal game. Very often the king actually stays in the center, but that's okay since we just attack on whatever side white castles. } { [%cal Bc7c6,Bb4c3] } *


[Event "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense: 📌 Section 2: 2. Nf3 📌"]
