[Opening "Nimzowitsch Defense: Declined Variation"]
[StudyName "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense"]
[ChapterName "📌 Section 2: 2. Nf3 📌"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/artxS9bL/POhZUz1C"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

2. Nf3 { White's most popular move. Often premoved or hoping to just transpose to a familiar line for white after 2...e5. } 2... d5!? { You could play e5 and transpose to your e4-e5 repertoire, but if you want to continue playing aggressive, d5 is your choice. With d5 we immediately strike the center. I like to call this variation "Nimzo-Scandi", because it's kinda the same idea, but the knight on c6 actually makes a huge difference compared to the normal Scandinavian, since Black can't play c6, a common idea in the Scandinavian. We'll look at this move in the next few chapters marked with 📘. } *


[Event "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense: 📘 2. Nf3 with 5. d4"]
[Date "2024.04.16"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense"]
[ChapterName "📘 2. Nf3 with 5. d4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/artxS9bL/8ZK6iKvG"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3p4/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

3. exd5 { By far the most popular move. We simply recapture. } 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 { White develops, but also gains tempi by hitting the Black queen. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rc3d5] } 4... Qa5 { The best move. The queen is most active here. } (4... Qh5?? { A very very common blunder. This loses due to the simple 5. Nb5! } 5. Nb5 $18 { Suddenly, Black's in trouble. The only way to protect the c7 pawn is by walking the king over to d8. } { [%csl Re5,Rc7] }) 5. d4 { White takes the center. Black usually just plays the same kind of ideas. Those are: 1. Pin the knight with Bg4 2. Castle queenside 3. Play Nf6. } 5... Bg4! { Preparing to castle queenside and scaring white a bit with our pin. } { [%csl Bc8][%cal Be8c8] } 6. Be2 { The most common move, unpinning the knight. } (6. Bd2 { This is nothing to be scared about, we just follow our plan. } 6... O-O-O! { Controlling the d file. } 7. Be2 (7. d5 Ne5 { The f3 knight is pinned. } 8. Be2 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nf6 { Black scores a noice 54%. } { [%csl Ge5,Gf6,Gd8][%cal Be7e6,Bg7g6,Bh7h5,Ba5b6] }) (7. Nb5 { No problem at all. We just retreat a square. } 7... Qb6 8. a4 (8. c3 e5! $17 { Everything crumbles for White. Don't hesitate to take the knight on f3 if you'd win a pawn. Black actually wins a pawn by force. } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Re5d4] }) 8... Nxd4 9. Nbxd4 Rxd4 { Winning a pawn, it's still equal tho. }) 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 $19 { Black is simply up a free pawn. You will get these type of things A LOT. Next up is Nf6-e5/e6 and if white castles kingside you can start a kingside attack with h5. } { [%csl Gd4,Gd8,Gc8][%cal Bg8f6,Be7e5,Bh7h5] }) (6. Bb5! { It damages our queenside by force. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Bb5c6] } 6... O-O-O 7. Bxc6 bxc6 { Damaging our queenside. :( } 8. O-O?! { Immediately throws the advantage, because it loses a pawn by force. } (8. Qd3! { The knight is no longer pinned. } { [%csl Rf3,Rg4] } 8... c5! 9. O-O! cxd4 10. b4! Qb6 $13 { It's an interesting game. }) 8... e5! $15 { Black wins a pawn by force, because of the Bg4 pin and our amazing rook on the d file. Black still has to be careful tho, because of the weak queenside. } { [%csl Gd8,Gg4] }) (6. Be3 O-O-O! { Controlling the d file again. } { [%cal Be7e5] } 7. Be2 { Unpinning the knight. } 7... Nf6 { We continue developing. } 8. a3 { Preparing to expand on the queenside. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Bb2b4,Ra3b4] } (8. O-O? e5 $17 { Wins a pawn by force, because of Bxf3 tactics. }) 8... Qf5 9. O-O e5! { The draw line, a long series of exchanges is coming up! } 10. d5 { Attacking our knight (but not really because of our d file pin), we just respond to that by counter attacking. } 10... e4! 11. Nd4 Bxe2 12. Nxf5 Bxd1 13. Raxd1 Ne7 14. Nxe7+ Bxe7 $10 { With most of the pieces of the board, this will probably end in a draw. }) 6... O-O-O { Finally castling. Black now controls the d file, things are looking very pleasant for us. } { [%csl Gd8,Ga5,Gc6,Rd4,Rd1,Rc3,Re2][%cal Be7e5] } 7. Be3 Nf6 { We now transpose into similar positions as shown in the variations above. The e5 pawn push is always an idea. } *


