3. e5 { Another declined variation. White advances the e pawn and hopes to get a more closed position. } 3... Bg4! { Pinning the knight, thus threatening to take the e pawn. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Bc6e5] } 4. d4 { The most popular move. Defending the e pawn. } (4. Bb5 { Responding by pinning us too. } 4... e6 { [%csl Ge7,Yd5,Ye6,Yf7][%cal Yf7e6,Ye6d5,Bg8e7,Be7g6,Be7f5] } 5. Bxc6+ (5. d4 a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 $10 { We just have the same ideas. } { [%csl Bb4,Bc5][%cal Bc6c5,Bg8e7,Be7g6,Be7f5,Bg7g6,Bf8h6,Be8g8,Ba8b8,Bf8b4,Bf8c5] }) 5... bxc6 $15 { Just follow the arrows, they're the same ideas as before. Black is slightly better. } { [%csl Bc5,Bb4][%cal Bg8e7,Be7f5,Bf8b4,Bd6c5,Bc6c5,Be7g6,Ba8b8] }) (4. Be2? { Makes zero sense, but some players respond to pins like this by instinct. } 4... Bxf3! { Removing the defender of the e pawn. Same thing after 4. h3. } 5. Bxf3 Nxe5 $17) 4... Bxf3 { Giving White doubled pawns. } 5. gxf3 (5. Qxf3? { Loses a pawn. } 5... Nxd4 $17 { Black's simply up a clean pawn. Just play c5 or Nc6 on the next move. } { [%cal Bc7c5,Bd4c6] }) 5... e6 { Freeing up the DSB, but more importantly freeing the e7 square for a knight to reroute. } { [%csl Ge7,Gf8] } 6. c3 Qh4! { Black's winrate is at 52%, Stockfish gives White a slight edge, but I'm pretty sure most people will be more comfortable playing as black here. Next up is Nge7 to reroute it to f5. Also, the DSB can be made active with g6 and maybe Bh6 at some point. It's then up to you to castle kingside or queenside. } { [%csl Gh4,Rf2,Rf3][%cal Bg8e7,Be7f5,Bg7g6,Be8c8,Be8g8] } *


