3. dxe5 d6! 4. exd6 { The Accepted Variation. } 4... Bxd6 { Black has now sacrificed a pawn, but we get enough compensation for it. Black already has two pieces developed, white has none. The usual ideas in this gambit is to play Bg4 at some point and castle queenside. Black usually gets plenty of action along the d file. :) } { [%csl Gd6,Gc6] } 5. Nf3 { The most popular move. Black usually plays the same moves every time: Bg4, Nf3, Qe2, O-O-O. The order doesn't matter too much. } { [%csl Bc8][%cal Bc8g4,Bg8f6,Bd8e7,Be8c8] } 5... Bg4 { Pinning the knight and getting one step closer to castling queenside. } 6. Be2? { White gets scared and blocks the pin. Now we'll hit white with a a bunch of punches. } (6. Nc3 Qe7 7. Be2 (7. h3! { The best move, but almost never played. } 7... Bh5 8. Bb5! { Again the best move. Wanting to damage our pawn structure. } 8... Nf6 9. Bg5 Bb4 $16 { White's a bit better, but we still have a fight. } { [%csl Gb5,Gg5,Gb4,Gh5] }) (7. Bb5 Nf6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O O-O-O $13 { Black's queenside is damaged, but we're still fine because of Black's superior piece placement. Back controls the center and can start launching an attack on the kingside with a pawnstorm. } { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Ra7,Gd8,Gd6,Gf6,Gg4,Ge7][%cal Bg7g5,Bh7h5] }) 7... O-O-O $15 { Black has a very comfortable position. You can see by the winrates ;) }) 6... Qe7! { Attacking the e pawn and clearing the way for the king. } 7. Nc3 { Defending e4. } (7. O-O { Now DO NOT take the free e pawn! We've played a gambit, we want to get activity and continue attacking, not just waste time by taking a measly pawn. Plus, white would gain tempi with Nd2 hitting the queen. } 7... O-O-O! { Black's winrate is at a whopping 64%. Black's main threat right now is Bxh2+, clearing the d file, thus winning the queen. Next up is Nf6 and you can start a kingside attack with h5. Even after white plays h3, just play h5 sacrificing the bishop, and usually it will end very well for black because of the dangerous open h file. } { [%cal Bh7h5,Bg8f6] }) (7. Nbd2 O-O-O { We pretty much play the same thing every time. O-O-O and Nf6. }) 7... O-O-O { The king is now finally safe and black will control the d file very soon. Already things are getting scary for white. Example castling would be a blunder because of Bxh2+ tactics. } { [%csl Gc8,Gd8] } 8. Bd2? { The top 2 most popular moves are mistakes. This safe and natural looking move is a mistake because it's kinda self-pinning the queen after our bishop moves away. White's pieces are getting really cramped up. Now we throw a series of hard punches. } { [%csl Rd2,Rd1,Gd8,Gd6] } (8. O-O?? Bxf3! { The best move, we delay Bxh2+ for a while. If black plays it immediately white will still get some compensation and things start getting tricky. } 9. Bxf3 Bxh2+ 10. Kxh2 Rxd1 11. Rxd1 $19 { Black's only 1 point up in material, but considering white's bad piece placement, black gets a sweet advantage. }) 8... Bxf3! { Getting rid of a defender of d2. } 9. Bxf3 Bf4! { Building up pressure on the DSB, stockfish recommends white to just sac the queen with Bxf4 } 10. Nb1 { The most popular move here is Nd5, but that loses immediately due to Rxd5, and black's up a piece with a great position due to the queen pinning the e pawn. } (10. Bxf4 Rxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Nf6 $15 { Material is equal, but I think most people will prefer being black here. Stockfish gives black a -0.5 edge. }) (10. Nd5?? Rxd5 $19 { [%csl Ge4,Re1][%cal Re4d5,Ye7e1] }) 10... Nf6 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] } 11. Qe2 { This leads to some absolutely insane lines. } (11. O-O Rxd2! { Temporarily sacrificing the exchange. } 12. Nxd2 Rd8 $19 { Black wins the knight, and gets an amazing position. Black has a -2.1 advantage. } { [%csl Rd2][%cal Yd8d1,Bf4d2] }) 11... Nd4! { Hitting the queen and threatening to take c7 with a fork. } { [%cal Rd4c2,Rd4e2] } 12. Qd3 (12. Qd1 { Hangs the e pawn. } { [%csl Re4] } 12... Nxe4! { There's still a lot of pressure in white's position. } { [%csl Rd2,Rf3,Gd8,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4] } 13. O-O Nxd2 14. Nxd2 Bxd2 15. Bg4+ (15. Qxd2 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Rxd2 { Black is up a full queen. }) 15... f5 $19 { Black wins material. }) 12... Be3!! { Behold, an absolutely brilliant move! The bishop can be captured in 3 different ways, but every one of them results in Black gaining the advantage!! The point of this move is that Black blocks White's queen from recapturing the bishop on f3, thus capturing the f3-bishop with check and opening the d file, which wins the queen. } { [%csl Rf3,Ge3,Rd3,Gd8,Gd4,Re1] } 13. fxe3 (13. Bxe3 Nxf3+ { [%csl Rd3,Re1][%cal Bd8d3] } 14. gxf3 Rxd3 15. cxd3 $19 { This is much easier to play as black. Black has a 2.3 advantage. } { [%csl Bd8,Bb4,Rf2,Rf3,Rb1,Ra1,Re1,Rh1][%cal Be7b4,Bh8d8] }) (13. Qxe3 Nxc2+ $19 { A triple fork!! Although, we'll only grab the queen. ;D } { [%csl Re1,Re3,Ra1][%cal Gc2e3,Gc2e1] }) (13. O-O Nxf3+! { Discovered check! We win the queen again. } { [%csl Rd3,Rg1][%cal Bd8d3] }) (13. Kf1 { An attempt from black to avoid any checks from the black knight. } 13... Bxd2 14. Nxd2 Nxf3 15. Qxf3 Rxd2 { White wins a free piece. }) 13... Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Rxd3 15. cxd3 Qd7 $19 { With the material balanced, Black holds a significant advantage due to White's unfavorable pawn structure and the lag in development of their pieces. The weaknesses in White's pawn formation, combined with the lack of coordinated piece activity, contribute to Black's strategic superiority. } { [%csl Rd3,Rf3,Re3,Re4,Rb1,Rd2,Re1,Rh1,Ra1,Gc8] } *


