4. Nf3 { White declines our gambit. If you want you can take on e5 with the knight and it will lead to a drawish position with the queens of the board, or you can go for: } 4... Bg4!? { A more spicy option, still offering the d6 pawn while developing. } 5. Bb5 { White insists on not taking the d6 pawn but now focuses on damaging our pawn structure with Bxc6. } (5. exd6 Bxd6 { Black can now transpose into similar positions as the previous chapter. } { [%csl Bc8][%cal Bd8e7,Be8c8,Bg8f6] }) 5... dxe5 { Finally taking the e pawn. I know this looks scary but it'll work out. } 6. Bxc6+ { Doubling our c pawns } 6... bxc6 7. Qxd8+ Rxd8 { The doubled c pawns are really annoying, but we'll get some compensation. } { [%csl Rc7,Rc6,Gd8,Rf3][%cal Bf8b4,Bg4f3] } 8. Nc3 (8. Nxe5?? { A very common blunder accounting for 17% of the games. } 8... Rd1# { GG! } { [%csl Gh1,Ge1,Gf1,Yd1,Ye2,Rf2,Gd2][%cal Gd1h1,Yg4d1,Gd1d2] }) (8. Nbd2 f6 $10 { Solidifying. It's okay because the most dangerous pieces (the queens) are off the board. } { [%csl Gf6,Ge5,Gg7,Bb4,Bc5][%cal Gg7f6,Gf6e5,Bf8c5,Bc5b4,Bg8e7,Be7g6] }) 8... Bb4! { Pinning another knight. } { [%csl Rf3,Rc3] } 9. Bd2 f6 10. O-O-O Ne7 $10 { It's 100% equal. Our doubled pawns are annoying, but we can usually always give White doubled pawns too by capturing a knight at some point. } { [%csl Gb4,Gg4,Rc3,Rf3] } *


