{ In this section we'll look at some move 2 sidelines. Moves other than the common 2. d4 or 2. Nf3. These chapters are marked with 📒. I only added 2 because others are so rare you'll probably almost never face them. }
 *


[Event "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense: 📒 Common 2. Bc4?!"]
[Date "2024.04.16"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense"]
[ChapterName "📒 Common 2. Bc4?!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/artxS9bL/uj0KRwRV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

2. Bc4?! { Played more often at beginner level, but you will probably even face this from advanced players. You probably won't see why this is an inaccuracy immediately, but I'll explain why on the next move. :) } 2... e6! { The only move that keeps the advantage! Black prepares to strike with d5 on the next move to kick the bishop with tempo and control the center. } { [%cal Bd7d5,Re6d5] } 3. Nf3 { The most popular move. } (3. Nc3 { Reinforcing the d5 square. We can't strike immediately yet. } { [%cal Rc3d5] } 3... Nf6 { Also reinforcing. } 4. d3 { White doesn't have any pieces left to reinforce d5 (except Qf3, but that fails due to Ne5 fork). } 4... d5! { Finally striking. } 5. exd5 (5. Bb5 dxe4 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 $15 { [%cal Bc8a6,Bf6g4,Bf8b4] }) (5. Bb3 Bb4 $17 { Pinning the knight. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Bb4e1,Rd5e4] }) 5... exd5 6. Bb3 Bb4 { Black has a nice position. } { [%csl Bg8,Gb4,Gc6,Gf6,Gd5][%cal Be8g8] }) 3... d5! { Kicking the LSB. } { [%cal Rd5c4] } 4. exd5 exd5 { Still hitting it :D } { [%cal Rd5c4] } 5. Bb3 { The most popular move. We have a nice response :) } 5... Qe7+! { White cannot block the check with anything other than the queen. } 6. Qe2 { Blocking the check. You could take the queens off the board, or just continue developing and take care of that later. } (6. Kf1 { White insists on keeping the queens on the board. This is no problem, we just continue developing. } 6... Nf6 7. d4 Bg4 $17 { Black obviously has the advantage. } { [%csl Bc8,Ge7,Gf6,Gc6,Rb3,Rf3,Gg4,Rc1,Rb1,Ra1,Rd1,Rf1,Rh1][%cal Be8c8] }) 6... Bg4 { Developing the bishop to the most active square. Preparing the take the f3 knight sooner or later. } 7. Qxe7+ Ngxe7 { Defending the d pawn. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge7d5] } 8. Ng1 { More or less forced if White doesn't want to get doubled f pawns. } (8. O-O?! { Makes thing simpler for us. } 8... Bxf3! { Ruining white's pawn structure. } 9. gxf3 Nd4 $19 { Black is absolutely dominating this game. White's bishop is useless on b3 and every other piece is chilling on the 1st rank. Also White's pawn structure is total trash with the isolated doubled f pawns and isolated h pawn. } { [%csl Gd4,Be7,Rb3,Ra1,Rf3,Rf2,Rf1,Rg1,Bc8,Rh2,Rc1,Rb1][%cal Be8c8,Be7g6,Be7f5,Bd4f3] }) (8. Ng5?! { Another attempt to not get doubled pawns. We have a simple solution: } 8... h6! { Simply kicking the knight back. } 9. Nh3 Bxh3 10. gxh3 $19 { Again Black dominates. } { [%csl Rh3,Rh2,Rf2,Rh1,Re1,Rc1,Rb1,Ra1,Rb3,Bc8][%cal Be8c8,Bc6d4,Bg7g5] }) 8... Nd4 $17 { Black has an amazing position. White has slow development, bad piece placement, and an uncastled king. Note: there's no need to trade our beautiful knight in the center for some useless trash bishop. } { [%csl Gd4,Gd5,Gg4,Rg1,Rh1,Re1,Rb1,Rc1,Ra1,Rb3,Bc8][%cal Be8c8,Be7g6,Be7f5,Bc7c6] } *


[Event "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense: 📒 2. f4"]
[Date "2024.04.16"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "CRUSH 1. e4! | Nimzowitsch Defense"]
[ChapterName "📒 2. f4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/artxS9bL/VVgqpdtO"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.16"]
[UTCTime "10:11:14"]

2. f4!? { A more aggressive approach. } 2... d5! { Striking the center! If you're familiar with the Queen's Knight Defense in the King's Gambit as Black, you could transpose to that with 2...e5. } 3. e5 { The most popular move. White opts for a closed position. } (3. exd5 { White opts for an open position. } 3... Qxd5 { Recapturing. } 4. Nf3 Bg4 { Pinning the knight, our standard stuff. } 5. Be2 O-O-O { King safety } 6. O-O h5 $15 { Striking the kingside aggressively. We have some f6-e5 ideas and Nh6-Nf5 ideas. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc8,Gd8,Gg4,Gh5][%cal Be7e5,Bf7f6,Bg8h6,Bh6f5] }) 3... Nh6! { A more aggressive and highly successful approach. The point of this move is that the knight is very well placed on f5, so we reroute it there. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Bh6f5] } 4. Nf3 { Again most popular. } 4... Bg4! { Immediately putting White under pressure. } 5. Be2 { White blocks the pin. } (5. h3 Bxf3! { Just trading. } 6. Qxf3 f6! $15 { Wanting to trade our f pawn for White's strong central pawns. Next up keep developing normally and castle queenside. } { [%cal Bd8d7,Be8c8,Bh6f5,Be7e6,Bf6e5] }) (5. d4 Bxf3 6. gxf3 e6 $19 { Black has a wonderful position. If possible we'll make our queen active with Qh4. We'll bring the h3 knight to f5, and castle queenside. } { [%csl Bc8,Rf4,Rf3,Rf2,Rg3,Rh4,Rc1,Rb1,Ra1,Rd1,Re1,Rf1,Rh1][%cal Bh6f5,Bd8h4,Be8c8] }) 5... Nf5! { Reroute complete. } 6. O-O h5 $13 { Black has a very aggressive attack. As you can see Black's winrate is already at a whopping 61%! Anything other than c3 from white now leads to us getting a pretty nice edge, currently Stockfish says it's equal, but White has to be very careful. } { [%cal Bf5g3,Rh2h3,Be7e6,Bf8c5,Bg4f3] } 7. h3? { A mistake, Black will get a great position, but only if Black knows these critical moves! } 7... Ng3! { Attacking the rook, we don't mind sacrificing the bishop for an open h file. } { [%cal Rg3f1] } 8. hxg4 hxg4! { A critical move! Everything else is bad. We are still hitting the rook and attacking the knight. } { [%cal Rg4f3,Rg3f1] } 9. Ng5 e6!! { DON'T take the f1 rook immediately! With e6 we open up the DSB, preparing to play Bc4+, which leads to checkmate or White has to sacrifice the queen. } { [%csl Bc5,Rh1][%cal Rf8c5,Bh8h1] } 10. Kf2 { Forced. The king has to run to e1. } { [%csl Be1][%cal Bf2e1] } 10... Nxf1! { Now we can finally grab that. } 11. Qxf1 { Kxf1?? is met with Rh1+! a skewer. } 11... Bc5+! { Developing with tempo. } 12. Ke1 Nd4 $19 { Black is obviously much better. } { [%csl Gd4,Bc8,Gc5][%cal Bd8d7,Be8c8] } *


