[StudyName "Crush Philidor with this RARE Gambit!"]
[ChapterName "What is the Bird Gambit?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/oWDGCamn/7Bwj1RjU"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2023.11.19"]
[UTCTime "11:18:31"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Hello everyone! Welcome to another study in my series: Crush with RARE Gambits! This study will be about how to crush the extremely annoying Philidor Defense. I will show you a very rare, but extremely powerful, opening called the Bird Gambit. It is full of traps and because it is so rare, you can surprise your opponents with it.

Feel free to use the engine and the Lichess database, and don't forget to look at the variations :)

Also if you want to be updated for new studies, please join this team: https://lichess.org/team/study-creators--friends :D

#antipublishingothersstudiesasyourown

Let's start!

play 1.e4 }
1. e4 e5 { Play 2. Nf3 :) } 2. Nf3 d6 { This is the Philidor Defense. It is a solid opening for black and is the second most popular choice after 2. Nf3 in the Lichess database.
So, I'm gonna show you how to crush it! :D
And btw, if you want a weapon as white after 2. Nc6, here's a study about the Scotch Gambit: https://lichess.org/study/J3Vkt5pj
Strike the center with 3. d4! } { [%csl Ge5,Gd6,Gc7][%cal Gd6e5,Gc7d6] } 3. d4 { Immediately we are threatening to take e5. Usually black takes d4. } 3... exd4 { Now we are going to hit black with a much more rarer move which is only being played 3% of the time.
Play 4. c3! } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 4. c3 { This is the beginning of the Bird Gambit! This is the position you want to get to start crushing people. There are many options here for black, but hopefully I have covered most of them.
This study will not only be about this position, I will also cover move 3 sidelines.
Note: my lines will not always be the absolute top engine move, they are rather based on which one is more comfortable to play as a human and have a decent winrate.
Go to the next chapter! :) } *


[Event "Crush Philidor with this RARE Gambit!: Section 1: Black takes c3"]
[Date "2023.11.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense: Bird Gambit"]
[StudyName "Crush Philidor with this RARE Gambit!"]
[ChapterName "Section 1: Black takes c3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/oWDGCamn/tCaQalBv"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2023.11.19"]
[UTCTime "11:18:31"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { We have arrived at the Philidor Defense. } 3. d4! { White has to immediately strike the center! } 3... exd4 4. c3! { The Bird Gambit! } 4... dxc3 { This is the most popular move. In the next 9 chapters I'm going to show you how to play against this move. } *


[Event "Crush Philidor with this RARE Gambit!: 5...h6? EPIC CASTLE CHECKMATE!"]
[Date "2023.11.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crush Philidor with this RARE Gambit!"]
[ChapterName "5...h6? EPIC CASTLE CHECKMATE!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/oWDGCamn/77wudg7l"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/4P3/2p2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.11.19"]
[UTCTime "11:18:31"]

{ The move 5. Bc4 will be explained more in the next chapter :) }
5. Bc4 { I want to start with sharing a EPIC TRAP where every move white plays is brilliant, and it's almost impossible to survive as black. } 5... h6? { 5. h6 is for some reason being played 11% of the time. This doesn't do anything. Black was probably scared of a future Bg5, but now we have a INSANE series of BRILLIANT moves that no human would survive and even if black plays perfectly white will still have an advantage. } 6. Bxf7+!! { Top engine move! none of black's pieces are developed, so white will get a huge attack! } 6... Kxf7 7. Ne5+!! { The pawn is pinned! The most popular move here is Ke8?? which loses immediately. } { [%csl Bd8,Re5][%cal Bd1d8,Rd6e5] } 7... Kf6 (7... Ke8?? 8. Qh5+! { White will get the queen to f7, which is checkmate! } { [%cal Bh5f7,Ge5f7,Ge5d7] } 8... Ke7 (8... g6 9. Qxg6+ Ke7 10. Qf7# { [%csl Gd7,Ge8,Ge7,Ge6,Gf6,Rd6,Rd8,Rf8,Bf7][%cal Gf7d7,Gf7e8,Gf7e6,Gf7f6,Be5f7] }) 9. Qf7# { [%csl Gd7,Ge7,Ge8,Ge6,Bf7,Rd6,Rd8,Rf8,Gf6][%cal Gf7d7,Gf7e8,Gf7e6,Be5f7,Gf7f6] }) (7... dxe5? 8. Qxd8 $18 { White is better. We will probably still pick up a few more pawns later on. } { [%csl Gc8,Gc7,Gc3,Bg1][%cal Gd8c8,Gd8c7,Gb1c3,Be1g1] }) 8. Qf3+!! { Again the only move that keeps the advantage. } 8... Kxe5 9. Qf7!! { The only winning move again! White now doesn't allow the king to come back home. } { [%csl Ge6,Gf6][%cal Gf7e6,Gf7f6] } 9... Nf6 { Controlling d5 } (9... Qf6?? 10. Qd5# { [%csl Gf5,Ge5,Ge6,Gd4,Bd5,Rf6,Rd6,Yf4,Ge4][%cal Gd5f5,Gd5e6,Gd5d4,Be4d5,Yc1f4] }) 10. Nxc3!! { Again, the only move. } (10. f4+ Kd4) 10... Be6?? { It's now mate in 10 for white, but only if white is able to find this brilliant sequence. } (10... d5 { This will be the PERFECT line for black. } 11. Bf4+!! Kxf4 12. Nxd5+ Qxd5!! { The only move that doesn't lose immediately. } 13. exd5 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 Bd7 15. Qxg7 Bb5+ 16. Kg1 Nbd7 17. Qg3+ Kf5 $14) 11. Bf4+!! { The only move that leads to mate! White forces the king away from the LSB and is always ready to bring the rook into action. } 11... Kxf4 (11... Kd4 12. Qxe6 d5 13. O-O-O+ Kc4 14. b3+ Kxc3 15. Bd2+ Kd3 16. Be1+ Ke2 17. Rd2# { Checkmate on the 2nd rank! }) 12. Ne2+!! { The only move that leads to mate, all other moves lose for white. } 12... Ke5 13. f4+!! { The only move that wins, again. We force the king away from the bishop. } 13... Kxe4 $7 14. Qxe6+! Kd3 $7 15. O-O-O#!! { What a beautiful way to finish of the game! White castle checkmates while being down 7 points in material! :D I hope you get this trap in your games. } { [%csl Ye2,Yc4,Ye3,Ye4,Gd4,Gd3,Gd2,Bc3,Rc2][%cal Ye6e2,Ye6c4,Gd1d4,Be2c3,Rc1c2] } *


