4... dxc3 { Now we are going to play a move inspired from the deadly Danish Gambit: } 5. Bc4! { Has white gone mad, sacrificing a second pawn!? yup, we're sacrificing another pawn, but white's gonna get HUGE compensation for it. This is the move I'm recommending. Of course, white could have just recaptured the the pawn with the knight and white would also get some compensation for it, but 5. Bc4! will lead to way more active and crushing positions. With Bc4 we are already aiming at the vulnerable f7 pawn and we are able to castle anytime we want now. btw this position is also reachable directly with the Danish Gambit: 1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Bc4 d6 5. Nf3 } { [%csl Gg1][%cal Ge1g1] } 5... cxb2?! { An inaccuracy, it helps white develop. } 6. Bxb2 $44 { Advantages for white:
1. the king is ready to castle
2. the two bishops are dominating the a1-h8 and a2-g8 diagonals
3. the queen can come join the attack very easily
Advantages for black:
1. has 2 extra pawns
White is almost fully developed and it's still move 6, meanwhile every single piece from black is on the 8th rank.
With perfect play it's 100% equal, but for humans, I think white's going to have lots of fun :) } { [%csl Yc4,Rb2,Bb3,Bd5,Gf3,Bg1,Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Rb2h8,Rb2a1,Yc4a2,Yc4g8,Bd1b3,Bd1d5,Be1g1] } 6... Be6 { The most popular move from black } 7. Bxe6 fxe6 { Now the e6 pawn is weak. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7] } 8. Qb3! { forking the 2 pawns, the best move here for black is to accept the fact that they're gonna lose a pawn and develop with Nc6. } { [%csl Ge6,Gb7][%cal Gb3e6,Gb3b7] } 8... Qc8?? { The most popular move from black! black has gotten greedy and wants to keep everything. } { [%csl Ge6,Gb7][%cal Gc8b7,Gc8e6] } 9. Ng5! { We attack the pawn once again. } { [%cal Bg5e6,Yb3e6] } 9... Ke7 { The only way to protect the e6 pawn, but we take it anyway! } (9... e5?? { This loses immediately because it opens the a2-g8 diagonal, so our queen can just hop in. } 10. Qf7+ Kd8 $7 11. Qxf8+ Kd7 { Don't be contended with that bishop, we want more! } 12. Qf5+ Kd8 13. Nf7+! { Forcing the king away from the queen } 13... Ke7 14. Qxc8 Kxf7 15. Qxb7 $18 { You should be up enough material to win this ;) }) (9... Nf6 10. Nxe6 Nc6 11. O-O $18 { Stockfish gives white a +3.3 advantage! Our king is much safer, and we got a octopus knight on e6. } { [%csl Ge6,Re8] }) (9... d5? 10. exd5 exd5 11. Qxd5 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 Bxc3+ 13. Bxc3 Qd7 14. Qxb7 Qe7+ 15. Kf1 Qxg5 16. Qxa8 Qb5+ 17. Kg1 Nf6 18. Re1+ Kf7 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Qe4 $18) 10. Nxe6!! Qxe6 { The queen has left defending the b7 pawn. } 11. Qxb7 Nc6! { A very nice trap from black. DO NOT TAKE THE ROOK! Black will get enough counterplay after Qxe4. } 12. Qxc6! Rc8 { Now white just has to finish developing. } (12... Rb8?? { Surprisingly, this is the most played move being played 52% of the time. } 13. Qxc7+ { [%cal Gc7e7,Gc7b8] } 13... Qd7 14. Qxb8 $18 { white has an extra rook on the board. } { [%csl Re7,Rf8,Rg8][%cal Be1g1,Bb1c3] }) (12... Rd8 13. Qxc7+ Rd7 14. Qc2 Nf6 15. O-O g6 16. Nd2 $18) 13. O-O Nf6 14. Nd2 $18 { Mr. Fish gives white a +4.5 advantage. Black's king is awkwardly placed and black has a hard time developing. } { [%csl Gg1,Gb2,Gd2,Gc6,Gf1,Re7,Rf8,Rh8,Re6,Rf6] } *


