,Gd5f6] } 11... Qd8 (11... Nxd5 12. exd5 { The knight is pinned, so there is no way to save it. } { [%cal Gd5c6,Gf1e1] } 12... Bd7 13. dxc6 Bxc6 14. Qb3 { White is totally winning here. } 14... O-O-O 15. Bxf7 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 $18 { [%csl Gg1,Gb2,Gf7,Rf8,Rd8,Rc8,Re7,Rh8,Rc7,Rb7,Ra7][%cal Bf1c1,Ba1b1] }) 12. Rae1! { The idea of this move is to support pushing the e pawn. } 12... Bd7 (12... h6?? { Now white can demonstrate the power of the rook on the e file. } 13. Nxf6+! gxf6 14. e5!! { Immediately ripping open the center. } 14... dxe5 15. Nxe5! fxe5 16. Bxe5 { White is crushing here, there is no way to stop all white's threats. } { [%csl Gh8][%cal Ge5h8,Ya4e8,Be1e8] } 16... Rg8 17. Bxc7+ $18) 13. Qb3 Na5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qc3 Nxc4 16. Nxf6+ Ke7 17. Nd5+ Ke8 18. Qxh8) (9... Be6?? 10. Nd5! { We can take the b7 pawn anytime! } { [%csl Ge7,Gc7,Gf6,Yb7][%cal Gd5e7,Gd5c7,Gd5f6,Yb3b7] } 10... Bxd5 11. exd5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxb7 Rd8 14. Rfe1 { There is to much pressure on e5, and black's largest problem is that the king is still stuck in the center. Stockfish gives white a +8.4 advantage. } { [%csl Re8,Re7,Rd8,Rf8,Rf6,Ge1,Ga1][%cal Bb2e5,Be1e5,Yb7a7,Yb7c6,Yc4b5] }) (9... Bd7?? 10. Nd5 { again hopping in the center. } { [%csl Gc7,Ge7][%cal Gd5c7,Gd5e7] } 10... Nxd5 (10... Qd8 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Bxf7+ Ke7 13. Bh5 $18 { [%csl Re7,Rd7,Rf8,Rd8,Rc6,Gb3,Gb2,Gh5,Gf3] }) 11. exd5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxb7 { White just grabs the free pawn. } 13... Rd8 14. Bxe5! Qxe5 15. Rfe1 $18 { again skewering the queen. } { [%csl Ge8,Ge5][%cal Ge1e8] }) (9... b6?? 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Na5 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qc2 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 O-O-O 15. Rac1 $18 { White is clearly winning. An idea here if the bishop moves away is to bring the knight to c6 and get a Lolli mate. } { [%cal Gc1c8,Bc4a6,Bf3d4,Bd4c6] }) (9... a6?? { The same thing... } 10. Nd5! Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bxe5 $18) (9... Bg4?? 10. Qxb7! $18 { a fork! } { [%cal Gb7a8,Gb7c6] }) (9... Qd7 10. Rfe1 Na5 11. Bxf7+!! Qxf7 12. Qb5+ Nc6 