6... Nc6 { Very often black will be transposing to the same position as chapter 5. } 7. Qb3 { Setting up the battery aiming at f7. We will be seeing this Qb3 idea very often :) } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 7... Nh6 { Protecting the f7 pawn. } (7... Qe7? 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nc3 { We have transposed to the same position as the previous chapter. }) 8. O-O! { We bring our king to safety. } 8... Na5 { The most common move from black and the engine's top choice. Black wants to get rid of our annoying LSB, we want to keep it, so we only have one good move here: } { [%cal Ra5b3,Ra5c4] } 9. Qa4+! { This way we can later move our bishop away. } 9... c6 (9... Nc6?! { This move just doesn't achieve anything, black is just horsing around :) } 10. Nbd2! { We just continue developing! Note that 10. Nc3?! would be worse because it blocks the diagonal of our monster on b2. }) 10. Bd3! { We want to keep the bishop pair on the board. } { [%csl Gd3] } 10... Bg4 (10... b5 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Re1 f6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxe5!! fxe5 15. Nxe5! Be7 16. Nc3! Qc8 (16... O-O?? 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Rad1! $18 { White's gonna win black's LSB. And a rook on the seventh rank is very dangerous/ }) 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Rad1! O-O-O 19. Nxb5 $16 { White has full compensation for the sacrificed piece. Black is really walking on thin ice now. The engine gives white a small plus. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Rc6b5,Gc2c8] }) 11. Nbd2 b5 12. Qc2 $16 { All of white's pieces are well placed, meanwhile black's king is still in the center and the knights are awkwardly placed. The engine gives white a +1 advantage. } { [%csl Gb2,Gc2,Gd2,Gd3,Gf3,Ra5,Rh6,Re8,Rf8,Rc6] } *


