5... Be6 { This is the most popular move. White can now take it and black will have a weak e6 pawn. } 6. Bxe6 fxe6 7. Qb3! { Three pawns are now hanging from black. } { [%csl Re6,Rb7,Rc3] } 7... Qc8?? { By far the most popular move, being played 60% of the time. } (7... b6? { Another common mistake } 8. Nxc3! { we don't have to take the e pawn immediately, first let's pick up the hanging c pawn. } 8... Qd7 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd7e6] } 9. Nd4! { double attacking the e pawn. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd4e6,Gb3e6] } 9... e5 10. Ne6! Nf6 11. Bg5 Nc6?? 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nd5! { [%csl Gf6,Gc7][%cal Gd5f6,Gd5c7,Ge6c7] } 13... Qxe6 14. Nxc7+ { [%csl Ge6,Ge8][%cal Gc7e6,Gc7e8] } 14... Kd7 15. Nxe6 { white is up a queen. }) 8. Ng5! { Immediately we want to bring the knight to e6 } { [%cal Gg5e6,Yb3e6] } 8... Ke7 9. Nxc3! h6?? { By far this is the most popular move, white can now play the same brilliant move as in chapter 4. } (9... Na6 10. f4! h6 11. Nf3 $18 { White can now castle and try to break open the f file to make the rook active. Meanwhile black's pieces haven't left the 8th rank except the grim knight on the rim and the king :D } { [%csl Gf3,Gc3,Gb3,Bg1,Ra6,Re7,Rf8,Rg8,Rc8][%cal Be1g1] }) 10. Nxe6!! { Note: we can take e6 after black plays any move, except after Na6 white has to play f4, and also gets a great position. } 10... Qxe6 { Now b7 is left undefended , so we can just go ahead and take it! } 11. Qxb7 $18 { Nice, white wins in 11 moves. Whatever black plays just take the rook and you have a sweet advantage. :D } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gb7a8] } *


