5... Bg4?? { A move that gets played sometimes, usually by beginners. This move completely ignores our threat of Qb3 forking up 2 pawns. } { [%csl Rf7,Rb7] } 6. Qb3! { [%csl Gf7,Gb7][%cal Gb3f7,Gb3b7] } 6... Be6 (6... Qe7?? 7. Qxb7 $18 { The rook is trapped, we can take it on the next move. } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gb7a8] }) (6... Bxf3 7. Bxf7+! Ke7 (7... Kd7 8. Qe6+ Kc6 9. Be8+ Nd7 10. Be3 { Stopping the king from going to c5/b6 and threatening mate in 1 with Qd5# or Qc4# } { [%csl Gb6,Gc5,Bd5,Bc4][%cal Ge3b6,Be6d5,Bd5c4] } 10... Kb5 11. Nxc3+ Ka5 12. Qc4 { There is no way to stop mate, we are threatening b4# and Qb5# } { [%csl Bb5,Bb4][%cal Bc4b5,Bb2b4] }) 8. Qe6# { GG } { [%csl Ge8,Ge7,Gd7,Gf7,Rf8,Rd8,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Ge6e8,Ge6d7,Ge6f7,Ge6f6] }) (6... Bh5?? 7. Qb5+ $18 { White wins the bishop. } { [%csl Ge8,Gh5][%cal Gb5e8,Gb5h5] }) 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Nxc3! { First we can chomp up this pawn, the other two are still hanging. } { [%csl Rb7,Re6] } 8... b6 9. Ng5! { We could have taken e6 immediately with the queen, but wouldn't an octopus knight on e6 be better? } { [%csl Re6][%cal Yb3e6,Bg5e6] } 9... Qe7 { Note: e5 hangs mate in 1 with Qf7# } 10. Nxe6 { This knight is really well placed here! } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ge6c7,Ge6g7,Ge6f8,Ge6d8] } 10... Nf6 11. Bg5 { pinning the black horse. } 11... h6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nd5! { We want to fork on c7 and there isn't anything black can do about it. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rd5c7,Re6c7] } 13... Qxe6 14. Nxc7+ { [%csl Ge8,Ge6][%cal Gc7e8,Gc7e6] } 14... Kd8 15. Nxe6+ $18 { White has enough extra material to win the game. } *


