3... Bg4?! { This move actually gets played quite often, usually by beginners but even by intermediate players. Now we have a nice counter: } 4. dxe5! { black doesn't want recapture immediately because otherwise the king would lose castling rights. } 4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3! { 5. gxf3?! would give us a damaged structure, but white would still be better. } 5... dxe5 6. Qb3! { The best move! This is only being played 2% of the time. White immediately aims at the unprotected b7 pawn and stares at the vulnerable f7 pawn. White has the idea of playing Bc4 soon and castling. } { [%csl Rb7,Rf7] } 6... b6 { By far the most popular move, black simply saves the b pawn. } 7. Bc4! { setting up the battery. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 7... Qe7 { black protects the important f7 pawn. White has a really nice counter move here: } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge7f7] } (7... Qd7 8. Nc3 { [%csl Bd5][%cal Bc3d5] } 8... Nf6 9. Bg5 $18 { There really isn't anything for black to do now: Be7 hangs the f pawn, c6 results to 10. Rd8! and on the next move we take the knight and black's structure is total trash, and Nc6 results to Bb5! and black is completely miserable. }) (7... Qf6 8. Nc3! { [%cal Bc3d5,Bc3b5] } 8... c6 9. Nd5! cxd5 10. Bb5+!! Nd7 (10... Nc6 11. Bg5!! Qg6 12. Qxd5 { [%csl Rc6] } 12... Rc8 13. O-O-O { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gd2d8] } 13... Qxg5+ 14. f4!! Qxf4+ 15. Kb1 { [%csl Gd7,Gc6] } 15... Bc5 16. Qd7+ Kf8 17. Qxc8+ Ke7 18. Qxc6 $18 { [%csl Re7,Gd8,Gd7,Bf6,Be6,Bd6,Be8][%cal Gd1d8,Bc6f6,Bc6e8] }) 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. Qxd5+ $18 { [%csl Ga8,Gd7][%cal Gd5a8,Gd5d7] }) 8. Bg5! { Attacking the queen. If black takes the bishop we win material. (see variation) } 8... f6 (8... Qxg5 9. Bxf7+! Kd8 (9... Ke7 10. Qe6+ Kd8 11. Qe8# { GG } { [%csl Gc8,Gd8,Gd7,Rc7,Ge7,Be8][%cal Ge8c8,Ge8d7,Ge8e7,Bf7e8] }) (9... Kd7 10. Qe6+ Kd8 11. Qe8#) 10. Qd5+ { Forking } { [%csl Gd8,Ga8][%cal Gd5a8,Gd5d8] } 10... Bd6 11. Qxa8 Qc1+ { Black might think that they're okay, because black will win our rook, but now the knight is undefended. } 12. Ke2 Qxh1 (12... Qxc2+ { A attempt to get a 3 fold repetition. } 13. Nd2 $16 { The only move that wins. Black has no checks anymore. }) 13. Qxb8+ Ke7 14. Qe8+ Kf6 15. Qe6+ Kg5 16. Qf5+ Kh4 17. Qh5# { [%csl Yh3,Yg3,Gh4,Gg4,Bh5,Gg5][%cal Yg2h3,Yh2g3,Gh5h4,Gh5g4,Bf7h5,Gh5g5] }) (8... Nf6 9. Nc3! { Getting ready to castle and we want to hop the horse into d5. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Bc3d5] } 9... Nbd7 10. Nd5 Qd6 11. O-O-O Nxd5 12. Bxd5 $18 { There are too many threats for black to deal with. If black saves the rook, white wins the queen with Bxf7!, if black saves the queen, white happily takes the rook on a8. } { [%csl Ra8,Rf7] }) 9. Bd2 { The knight on g8 is hanging and we prepare for a potential Bb4 in the future (not now black would just take it) } { [%csl Gb4,Rg8][%cal Gd2b4] } 9... Nh6 { The only move that saves the knight. } 10. Bxh6 gxh6 { damaging black's structure. } 11. Nc3! { preparing to hop into d5. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Bc3d5] } 11... c6 { Black controls the important d5 square, although we won't let this stop us... } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rc6d5] } 12. Nd5! { Hopping in anyway! } 12... cxd5 13. Bxd5 $18 { The rook is trapped! There is nothing black can do to save it. Mr. Fish gives white a +8 advantage. } { [%csl Ra8][%cal Gd5a8] } *


