{ This chapter is analyzed and annotated by @Peng_Dehuai1898-1974, aka @Sooin_Cho }
3... Nc6?! { Played in 9% of games online, mostly by beginners but sometimes by intermediate or even advanced players too! This move doesn't look horrible but we have a cool counter: } 4. Bb5! { A very nice move, threatening the e5-pawn and d5. } { [%cal Gd4d5,Gd4e5] } 4... exd4 { The best move and the most common online } (4... Bd7 { The 2nd most common move online, played in one-third of games. } 5. Bxc6! { This might seem weird, but we have a good point behind it: } 5... Bxc6 6. Nc3! { Protecting e4 and threatening the e5-pawn. } { [%csl Re5] } 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 $16 { There's no rush to take on c6, we are going to play Qe2, Be3, and O-O-O!, if Black castles kingside then we will launch an onslaught there. We have a space advantage and development advantage, and are just more comfortable in general. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Gc1e3,Be1c1,Yd1e2] }) (4... a6? { The 3rd most common move, one-third of games!! it loses the game } 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. dxe5 $16 { this is just a clean extra pawn. you might win another clean extra pawn after 6...dxe5 7.Qxd8+ Kxd8 8.Nxe5. }) (4... Bg4 { The 4th most common move, probably by a beginner who's like "well they pinned my knight so i'm gonna pin their knight!", but this will be punished. } 5. Nc3! { Played only 1% of the time but just developing is the best! } 5... a6? { The most common move shockingly!! this shows that 4...Bg4 is probably played by a beginner. } (5... exd4 6. Qxd4! { Exploiting the pin. } 6... Bxf3 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. gxf3 $16 { Although both sides have doubled pawns, the development lead decides. Also we can use the g-file as a basis for attack, while Black will find it harder to use the b-file. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3,Ra8,Rd8,Re8,Rg8,Rf8,Rh8][%cal Gh1g1] }) (5... Bxf3 6. gxf3! exd4 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxd4) (5... Ne7 { this loses to } 6. d5 a6 7. Ba4 b5 8. Nxb5! axb5 9. Bxb5 $18 { and we'll be up a clean extra pawn on the queenside, which one day you can promote and get a queen. } { [%csl Ga2,Gb2][%cal Ga2a8,Gb2b8] }) (5... Nf6?? 6. d5 a6 7. Ba4 b5 8. Nxb5! axb5 9. Bxb5 $18 { With the knight on f6 it doesn't even support c6 so this is even worse than 5...Ne7?. }) 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. dxe5 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 dxe5 9. O-O $16 { Black's position is just gross, with no development and a disgusting structure } { [%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rc7,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh7,Rg7,Rf7,Ra8,Gc2,Gb2,Ga2,Gc3,Ge4,Gf3,Gg1,Gf1][%cal Gc1e3] }) 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3! { Developing more forces. } 6... Nxd4?! { Again by far the most common online, and it makes sense since most people who play 4...d6 are beginners and ...Nxd4 is usually the sign of a beginner. } (6... Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. Bxc6!? { The computer wants 8.Nxc6 but this is thematic for us, and doesn't lose a tempo. } 8... bxc6 9. Qf3! { A nice move, threatening e5. Also the queen might slide over to the kingside sometimes with Qg3 } { [%cal Gf3g3,Ge4e5] } 9... O-O 10. Re1 $16 { Next up is b3 and Bb2/Bd2, and h3 - if you're alert you might notice that we are building a light-squared pawn chain to complement our dark-squared bishop! The DSB will always be very happy with the light-squared pawns. } { [%csl Ga2,Gc2,Ge4][%cal Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Bh2h3] }) 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Qxd4 $16 { Next up is Be3 and you have a choice of which way to castle! } { [%csl Bg1,Bc1,Gd4,Gc3,Rf8,Rg8][%cal Bc1e3,Be1g1,Be1c1] } *


