3... f5?? { This is the Philidor Countergambit, if you don't know how to play against it it can be quite tricky. Most people will probably take either f5/e5 but these moves are bad (white is still better though). A big problem now for black is that the king is weakened. We can take advantage of the weak light squares with the move... } 4. Bc4! { Immediately taking control of the light squares. This move is only played 3% of the time, but it is the absolute best move. } { [%csl Gf7,Ge6][%cal Gc4f7] } 4... fxe4 { By far the most popular move being played 67% of the time. } (4... f4 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nxe5 $18) 5. Nxe5!! { The only winning move! We now free up the queen. } { [%csl Gd1,Gh5] } 5... dxe5 (5... d5 6. Qh5+! { Ke7?? loses due to Qf7+ } { [%csl Ge8,Bg6][%cal Gh5e8,Be5g6] } 6... g6 7. Nxg6 { Exploiting the pin. } { [%csl Yh8,Ye8][%cal Gg6h8,Yh5h8,Yh5e8] } 7... Nf6 8. Qe5+ Be7 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 10. Bg5 Qxe5 11. dxe5 dxc4 12. Bxf6 Rg8 13. Nc3 Rxg2 14. O-O-O $18 { [%csl Gd8,Gc3,Re4,Rc4,Rh7,Re8,Rb8,Rc8,Ra8,Gf6][%cal Gd1d8,Ge5f6] }) 6. Qh5+! g6 (6... Kd7 7. Qf5+ Kc6 8. Qxe5 { Threatening to go to b5 } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ge5b5] } 8... a6 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ra6b5] } 9. d5+! Kb6 10. Be3+ Bc5 11. Bxc5+ Kxc5 12. b4+ Kxc4 13. Qxe4+ Kb5 14. a4+ Kb6 15. Qd4+ c5 16. Qxc5# { [%csl Ga7,Gb6,Gc7,Ga5,Bc5][%cal Gc5a7,Gc5c7,Gc5a5,Bb4c5] }) 7. Qxe5+ Qe7 8. Qxh8 $18 { White is clearly winning. } { [%csl Gh8,Gc4] } *


