3... Nf6!? { This is the Nimzowitsch variation, it's actually pretty interesting although there are many ways black can go wrong. } 4. dxe5 Nxe4! (4... dxe5? { surprisingly the most popular move, we can now win a pawn. } 5. Qxd8+! Kxd8 6. Nxe5 { Black won't be able to take e4 because white is threatening to take f7+ } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5f7] } 6... Be6 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. f3 $16 { white solidifies (I think that's the word) we now have a nice pawn chain and white is up a pawn! } { [%csl Gf3,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg2f3,Gf3e4] }) 5. Qd5! { Bringing the queen to action and we are attacking the knight. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4] } 5... Nc5 (5... Bf5? { The second most played move, it leaves the b7 pawn undefended. } 6. Bc4! { first we can develop this bishop. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } 6... Qe7 7. Qxb7 $18 { We'll get the rook on the next move! }) 6. Bg5! Be7 7. exd6! Qxd6 (7... Bxg5?? 8. Nxg5 { Threatening mate in uno and the knight's unprotected. } { [%csl Gf7,Gc5][%cal Gg5f7,Gd5c5] } 8... Ne6 9. Nxe6 Bxe6 (9... fxe6 10. Qh5+! Kf8 11. dxc7 Qxc7 12. Nc3 $18 { next is O-O-O and white is way better. } { [%csl Bc1,Bd3,Re6,Rf8,Rc8,Rb8][%cal Be1c1,Bf1d3] }) 10. Qxb7 Nd7 11. dxc7 Qc8 12. Ba6 O-O 13. Qxc8 Raxc8 14. Bxc8 Rxc8 $18 { white has an extra 5 points in material. }) (7... cxd6 8. Nc3 Be6 9. Bb5+ Nbd7 10. Qd2 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gd2g5] } 10... O-O 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O-O $16) 8. Nc3 { We continue developing and get ready to castle queenside. } 8... Be6 9. Qxd6 Bxd6 10. Nb5 { We force black to trade the bishop, the bishop is unable to leave the c pawn undefended. } 10... Nc6 11. Nxd6+ { Creating a weak isolated pawn. } 11... cxd6 12. O-O-O $16 { Black has a weak d pawn. Mr. Fish says +1.3 for white. } { [%csl Gc1,Rd6,Gg5,Gf3,Gc5,Gc6,Ge6] } *


