[Event "40 TRAPS in the Scandinavian Defense: What is the Scandinavian?"]
[Date "2023.06.27"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B01"]
[Opening "Scandinavian Defense: Mieses-Kotroc Variation"]
[StudyName "40 TRAPS in the Scandinavian Defense"]
[ChapterName "What is the Scandinavian?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/g29gizvW/NRnotDYd"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2023.06.27"]
[UTCTime "06:12:58"]

{ The Scandinavian Defense is a very agressive defense that comes after: }
1. e4 d5 { White already has to make a decision "Should I take? push? defend? play the Tennison gambit?" } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Ge4d5] } 2. exd5 (2. Nf3 { Tennison gambit }) (2. d4 { Blackmar gambit, I've already faced this transposition, you can transpose back to a Caro-kann or a French if you want. } 2... c6 { Caro-Kann } (2... e6 { French })) (2. e5 { This is the Advance variation, you can transpose to a Caro-Kann or a French (but the French sucks, so play the Caro-Kann please) }) (2. d3?! { We will look at this and f3 in the next chapters, to satisfy theory avoiders to not play those moves. }) (2. f3 { I've something against the theory avoiders, no worries! }) 2... Qxd5 { The Scandi demands to bring the queen out early, but perso I don't prefer this because it's not very good to begin chess openings where you bring out your queen early and move it multiple times. } (2... Nf6 { Most of the traps we will show you are based on Nf6, but if you want to stick to the main line, Qxd5 }) *


