1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 { For this trap, you should take with the queen. } { [%cal Rb1c3,Gd5a5] } 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Nf3 { lets say white develops the pieces normally } 4... Bg4 { This pin helps with the trap, and even it you dont pull off the trap, its a good move anyway :D } 5. d4 { White plays a good and natural looking move. } 5... Nf6 { We play nf6, hoping our opponent will go bg5, putting pressure on the Knight on f6. } 6. Bg5?! Nbd7 { We play nbd7, because nc6 doesn't work well for this trap. } 7. Bb5?! { The best thing for them to do is to get rid of that DSB } { Bb5 is inaccurate because of c6, which just gives black a free tempo. } { [%csl Rg5] } 7... c6 { Here, The best move for white is to give their DSB for the Knight on f6. If they dont do this, they will be in some trouble ;) } { If they move the LSB, we've removing the defender of the bishop on g5 to win it! } { [%csl Bg5,Bf3,Rb5,Bd1][%cal Ba5g5,Bg4f3,Bd1f3,Gf3d1] } 8. Bc4?? { If something like bishop c4, then we have a sequence of moves that wins a piece! (If they go any light sqaured bishop move, then they lose in the same sequence of moves! } (8. Bxf6 Nxf6 { but White still had a little advantage! } (8... exf6 9. Be2 Ba3 10. bxa3 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 Bxe2 12. Qxe2+ Kd8) 9. Be2 { After this, Black has a slight advantage of -0.8, even though it might be equal. The Blue arrows show some future plans you have. } { [%cal Be7e6,Bf8b4,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Ba8d8] }) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qxg5 { And you're up a piece! } *


