1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nxd5 4. Nxd5 Qxd5 { Now, there's no knight on b1 to attack the queen. From here, you can develop like you would in the scotch: } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rb1c3,Rc3d5] } 5. Nf3 e5 { e5 prevents the move d4 and threatens to trap the knight on f3! } { [%csl Ge4,Gg5,Gh4][%cal Ge5e4,Gf3h4,Gg7g5] } 6. Be2?? e4 { [%csl Gg5,Ge5,Gd4][%cal Gd5g5,Gd5d4] } 7. Nh4 (7. Ng1 { This is disgusting, you will continue your development and White will struggle with castling } { [%csl Rh3,Rf3,Re2][%cal Rg1h3,Rc8h3,Rg1f3,Re4f3,Rg1e2] } 7... Bc5 8. d3 exd3 9. Bxd3 (9. Qxd3 Qxg2) 9... Qxg2) (7. c4 Qd8) 7... g5 { The knight is trapped! } { [%csl Rf3,Rf5,Rg6][%cal Re4f3,Rc8f5,Rh7g6] } 8. c4 { This does nothing: } 8... Qd8 *


