1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4! cxb4 (3... Nxb4 4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qa5 9. Rb1 Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 Qa3 { This transposes to the same position. }) 4. d4 { Now we are threatening to push our d pawn and kick the knight, which is very annoying for black. most players will play d5, stopping the d4 pawn. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd4d5] } 4... d5 5. exd5 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gd5c6] } 5... Qxd5 6. c4! { white is now hitting the queen, but black can now capture the pawn with en passent. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] } 6... bxc3 7. Nxc3 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 7... Qa5 { now instead of just protecting the knight we're going to play a super cool move..... } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Ga5c3] } 8. Rb1! { We are sacrificing a full knight! You might think that this is a super dubious opening, but no, it is a completely fine opening. Stockfish doesn't even give this move as an inaccuracy. Of course you could just play bd2, or d5, which are perfectly fine moves, but I highly recommend Rb1, it just leads to more exciting positions and it surprises your opponent. } (8. d5 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qf6 10. dxc6 bxc6) (8. Bd2 e6) 8... Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd2c3] } 9... Qa3 { this is the only safe square for the queen } 10. d5 { now we are attacking the knight. If black tries to save the knight, we will get a huge advantage! } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gd5c6] } 10... Nb8?? { This is good looking move is actually a blunder, it is also black's most common response. I will cover other moves in the next chapters. Even though we are down 4 points in material in the opening, Stockfish gives white a +4.8 advantage! White can now throw a series of punches at black starting with the important Qc2. } 11. Qc2! { This is the only move that keeps an advantage. Keep in mind that this move not only attacks the bishop but also defends the a2 pawn, threatening Bb4, which traps the queen. } { [%csl Gc8,Ga2,Ba3,Bb4][%cal Gc2c8,Gc2a2,Bd2b4,Bb4a3] } 11... Bd7 (11... Nd7 12. Bb4 { The queen is trapped! } 12... Qxb4+ 13. Rxb4 $18) (11... Na6 { [%csl Gc8,Yb4][%cal Ga8c8,Ya6b4] } 12. Bb5+ { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gb5e8] } 12... Bd7 (12... Kd8 13. Ne5 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5f7] } 13... e6 14. Nxf7+ Ke7 15. Nxh8 Bd7 16. Bxd7 Kxd7 17. Rxb7+ Kd6 18. Qc6+ Ke5 19. Qxe6+ Kd4 20. Be3+ Kd3 21. Qf5+ Kc3 22. Qe5+ Kc4 (22... Kc2 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ge5e4] } 23. Qe4+ Kc3 (23... Qd3 24. Rb2+ Kxb2 25. Qxd3 Nf6 26. Qb3+ Ka1 27. O-O# { castle checkmate! }) 24. Qd4+ Kc2) 23. Qd4#) 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Rxb7+ Kd8 15. Qc6 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6d7] } 15... Nc5 16. Qc7+ Ke8 17. Rb8+ Rxb8 18. Qxb8+ Kd7 19. Ne5# { [%csl Gd7,Ye8,Yd8,Yc8,Yd6,Yc7,Be6,Bc6,Re7][%cal Ge5d7,Yb8e8,Yb8d6,Bd5e6,Bd5c6] }) 12. Bb5! { pinning the bishop } { [%csl Ye8,Gd7][%cal Yb5e8] } 12... Nf6? { this is black's most popular move, which hangs mate in 1, but every move loses. } (12... Bxb5? 13. Qc8# { checkmate! } { [%csl Ge8,Gd7,Gd8,Rf8,Ye7,Yf7][%cal Gc8e8,Gc8d7] }) (12... Qd6 13. Qc8# { the same thing again } { [%csl Ge8,Gd8,Rd7,Rf8,Be7,Bf7][%cal Gc8e8,Rd7c8,Yb5e8] }) (12... Na6 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Rxb7+ { [%csl Gd7,Yc8,Yc7,Yc6][%cal Gb7d7,Yc2c8] } 14... Kd8 15. Qc6! { threatening Qd7# } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6d7,Yb7d7] } 15... Qd6 16. Ba5+ { [%csl Gd8][%cal Ga5d8] } 16... Nc7 (16... Qc7 17. Bxc7+ Nxc7 18. Qxc7+ Ke8 19. Qd7#) 17. Bxc7+ Kc8 18. Bxd6+ Kd8 19. Qd7#) (12... Kd8 13. Bb4 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gb4a3] } 13... Qxf3 14. Bxd7! { threatening mate in 1 } { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gc2c8,Rd7c8] } 14... Nxd7 15. gxf3) 13. Qc8# { Checkmate! the bishop is pinned so it can't recapture. } { [%csl Ge8,Gd8,Be7,Bf7,Rd7,Rf8][%cal Yb5e8,Gc8e8,Rd7c8] } *


