1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4! Nxb4 4. c3 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gc3b4] } 4... Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd4d5] } 6... d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 8... Qa5 9. Rb1! Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 Qa3 11. d5 Nd8?? { also a blunder! } 12. Bb5+! { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gb5e8] } (12. Bb4 { also works. } 12... Qxa2 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. Ra1 Qb2 16. Qa4+) 12... Bd7 13. Bb4 { [%csl Ga5,Ga3,Ya4,Ya6,Gc3][%cal Gb4a5,Gb4a3,Yb5a4,Yb5a6,Gb4c3] } 13... Qxa2 { this is the only way for black to save their queen. } 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. Ra1 { now white's rook is controlling the a file. white's plan is to get the queen on a4 } { [%csl Ba4][%cal Ga1a8,Bd1a4] } 15... Qb2 { again the only safe square for the black queen. } 16. Qa4+ { [%csl Gd7,Ge8,Bd6,Re6,Rc6][%cal Ga4d7,Gd7e8,Bb4d6,Rd5e6,Rd5c6] } 16... Kc8 (16... Kc7 { we continue to do the same as when black's king goes to c8 } 17. O-O! { [%csl Gc8,Gc7][%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c8] }) 17. O-O! { [%csl Gc1,Gc8][%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c8] } 17... Nf6 18. Rfc1+ { this forces the king to b8 } { [%csl Gc8,Bd7][%cal Gc1c8,Ba4d7] } 18... Kb8 19. Bc3 { White is rerouting the bishop to e5, which is checkmate. } { [%csl Ge5,Gb8,Gb2][%cal Gc3e5,Ge5b8,Gc3b2] } 19... Qxc3 (19... Qe2 20. Be5+ Qxe5 21. Nxe5 Nxd5 (21... a6 22. Qa5 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Ga5c7] } 22... Ne6 23. dxe6 Nd5 24. Qc5 { [%csl Gc8,Gc7][%cal Gc5c8] } 24... Nc7 25. Qxc7+ Ka7 26. Nc6#) 22. Nd7#) 20. Rxc3 { white is dominating the board. Black will get mated very soon. } { [%csl Ga8,Yb8,Bc8][%cal Ga1a8,Yb1b8,Bc1c8] } *


