1. d5 Qf6! { This is the best move for black, this position is still most likely a draw with perfect play. Luckily, this move is only played 4% of the time! Even though this still looks kinda scary for white, we still have some more tricks! } 2. c3! bxc3 3. dxc6 c2 4. Qxc2 Qxa1 5. e5! { This move blocks down the attack of the queen and this pawn cannot be taken! we are not letting the queen go back to f6. Our plan now is to play Bc4 protecting the a2 pawn and then we follow up with Bb2 trapping the queen } { [%csl Rf6,Bc4,Ba2,Yb2,Ya1,Gb1,Ge5][%cal Ra1f6,Bf1c4,Bc4a2,Yc1b2,Yb2a1,Gc2b1,Gf3e5] } 5... Bb4+ (5... bxc6 6. Bc4 { [%csl Ga2,Bb2,Ba1][%cal Gc4a2,Bc1b2,Bb2a1] } 6... Rb8 7. Bb3 Bb4+ 8. Kd1 Ba6 9. Bb2 { [%csl Ba1][%cal Bb2a1] } 9... Bd3 10. Bxa1 Bxc2+ 11. Bxc2 { still unclear. Stockfish prefers white in this position. }) (5... dxc6?? 6. Bc4 { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gc4a2] } 6... Bb4+ 7. Ke2 Ne7 8. Bb2 { [%csl Ga1,Ya2,Bb1][%cal Gb2a1,Yc4a2,Bc2b1] }) 6. Kd1! { now the only good move for black is Ne7. } 6... bxc6?? 7. Bc4 { we are preparing to trap the queen! } { [%csl Ga2,Bb2,Ba1][%cal Gc4a2,Bc1b2,Bb2a1] } 7... d5 8. Bb3! { we save the bishop, because our threat of Bb2 is unstoppable } { [%csl Gb2,Ga1][%cal Gc1b2,Gb2a1] } 8... Ne7 9. Bb2 { [%csl Ga1,Ga2][%cal Gb2a1,Gb3a2] } 9... Qxb2 10. Qxb2 $18 { White has a queen for a rook and two pawns. Stockfish gives white a +4.1 advantage. } *


