1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 exf4? 4. e5 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] } 4... Ng8 5. Nf3! { we want to avoid any annoying Qh4 checks! } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gf3h4] } 5... d6 6. d4 { keeping our center intact } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf3,Gc3] } 6... dxe5 7. Bb5+! { this is a more rare move, but it is actually Mr. Fish's top choice } 7... c6 (7... Nc6? 8. Nxe5 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Ge5c6,Gb5c6] } 8... Bd7 (8... Qh4+ 9. Kf1 a6 10. Ba4 Ne7 11. Qe2 Qf6 12. Ne4 Qh6 13. Nc5 $14) 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. d5 a6 11. Qe2+ Qe7 12. dxc6 axb5 13. cxb7 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Rb8 15. a4 b4 16. a5 bxc3 17. a6 Bc5 18. Bxf4 Bb6 19. Bxc7 Bxc7 20. a7 Rxb7 21. a8=Q+ { a fun line I wanted to show you guys, where white sacs a bunch of material for a unstoppable past pawn. }) 8. Bc4 { aiming at the delicate f7. Now why doesn't white just play Bc4 immediately? well, after Bc4 black plays Nc6 and is gonna be okay. with the c pawn in the way black can't put the knight on that nice square } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } 8... exd4 9. Bxf4! dxc3?? 10. Bxf7+! { after Kxf7 we win the queen } { [%csl Rf7,Gd8][%cal Re8f7,Gd1d8] } 10... Ke7 (10... Kxf7 11. Qxd8) 11. Qe2+! { the only move that wins!! } 11... Kxf7 12. Ne5+ { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5f7] } 12... Kf6 (12... Ke8 13. Nxc6+ Qe7 14. Nxe7 Nxe7 15. bxc3 { [%csl Bg1,Bc1,Bd8,Bf8,Be8,Bb8,Bc7][%cal Be1g1,Be1c1,Bd1d8,Bf1f8,Be2e8,Bf4b8] } 15... Nc6 16. O-O Bd7 17. Rae1 { [%csl Ge7,Gd6][%cal Ge1e7,Gf4d6] }) 13. Bg5+ Kxg5 { we literally sacrificed 10 points of material at this point :D } (13... Ke6 14. Nxc6+) 14. Nf7+ { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gf7g5] } 14... Kg6 15. Nxh8+ Kf6 16. O-O+ Bf5 (16... Kg5 17. h4+ Kxh4 18. g3+ Kxg3 (18... Kg5 19. Nf7+ Kg6 20. Qe4+ Kh5 21. Qh1+ Bh3 22. Qxh3+ Kg6 23. Qf5#) 19. Qh2+ Kg4 20. Rf4+ Kg5 21. Qh4#) 17. Rxf5+ Kxf5 18. Rf1+ { bringing the final piece into attack } 18... Kg5 19. Nf7+ Kg6 20. Qg4+ Qg5 21. Qxg5# { Finally after the 15th check black gets mated. You don't have to memorize all these moves, just understand the basic checkmating ideas. Just keep throwing sensible checks. } { [%csl Gf7,Yf6,Yg6,Yh6,Yh5,Gf5,Rg7,Rh7][%cal Gf1f7,Yg5f6,Yg5g6,Yg5h6,Yg5h5] } *


[Event "CRUSH with the Vienna!: Vienna Gambit: 3...d5 crushing attack!"]
[Date "2023.09.25"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C29"]
[Opening "Vienna Game: Vienna Gambit, Paulsen Attack"]
[StudyName "CRUSH with the Vienna!"]
[ChapterName "Vienna Gambit: 3...d5 crushing attack!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/nq1GGbNO/CRzDycyz"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Bosburp"]
[UTCDate "2023.09.25"]
[UTCTime "06:44:29"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5! { this move is seen more often at higher levels and is considered the mainline. } 4. fxe5 Nxe4 { the only good move for black } 5. Qf3! Nxc3 (5... Nc6! 6. Bb5! { pinning the knight. } { [%csl Ge8,Gc6][%cal Gb5e8] } 6... Nxc3 7. dxc3! { Here is an exception where we take with the d pawn instead of the b pawn. } 7... Qh4+ (7... Bc5 8. Qg3 { [%csl Gg7,Ge5][%cal Gg3g7,Gg3e5] } 8... O-O?? { The most common move! } 9. Bh6 { [%csl Gf8,Rg7][%cal Gh6f8,Yg3g8,Rg7h6] } 9... g6 10. Bxf8 Bxf8 11. Bxc6 bxc6 { White enjoys being up the exchange. } { [%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Be1c1,Bg1f3] }) 8. g3 Qe4+ { Black forces a queen trade } 9. Qxe4 dxe4 10. Ne2 { Preparing to put the knight to d4 or f4 } { [%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Ge2d4,Ge2f4] } 10... Bc5 (10... Bd7 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Rf1! { Getting out of the way from the dangerous diagonal of the bishop. } 12... Bc5 13. Nd4! $10 { It's equal. The next step is to develop the bishop and castle queenside, and try to put pressure on f7. } { [%cal Bc1f4,Bf4g5,Be1c1] }) (10... a6 11. Bxc6+! { We double black's c pawns } 11... bxc6 12. Bf4 $10 { [%csl Bc1,Bd4][%cal Be1c1,Be2d4] }) 11. b4! { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb4c5] } 11... Bb6?! (11... Be7 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. a4 $10 { It's 100% equal, enjoy! } { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Re4,Re5,Rc3,Rc2] }) 12. c4! { White threatens to trap the bishop with c5. The knight cannot capture b4 because it's pinned. } 12... a5 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. c5 Ba7 15. a3! $16 { White's knight can hop on over to d4 or f4 anytime, white's ready to castle, and the bishop can be developed very easily. Also black's DSB is trapped until black can prove otherwise. } { [%csl Gb4,Gc5,Ga3,Rc6,Rc7,Ra7][%cal Ga3b4,Gb4c5,Be2d4,Be2f4,Bc1b2,Be1g1] }) (5... f5 6. d3 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] } 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 d4 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Qg3 Be6 10. c4 { [%csl Gd3,Gc4,Gc2][%cal Gc2d3,Gd3c4] } 10... Bb4+ 11. Kd1 O-O 12. Nh3 { [%cal Bh3f4,Bh3g5,Bh1f1] } 12... Qd7 13. Rb1 { making the rook more active } { [%cal Gb1b8] } 13... Rae8 14. Bf3 a5 15. a3 Bc3 16. Rxb7 Rb8? 17. Nf4!! { A brilliant idea.. } 17... Rxb7 18. Nxe6! Qxe6 { Now the queen steps into the same diagonal from the king } 19. Bd5 { Pinning the queen } { [%csl Gg8,Ge6][%cal Gd5g8] } 19... Qxd5 20. cxd5 $16) 6. bxc3! { always capture toward the center! } 6... Be7 7. d4 { building up a strong pawn chain in the center. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gc3d4,Gd4e5] } 7... O-O 8. Bd3 c5 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O Be6 11. Rb1 Rb8 (11... b6? 12. Nf4 cxd4 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qh3 { [%csl Ge6,Bh7][%cal Gh3e6,Gh3h7,Yd3h7] } 14... Rxf1+ 15. Kxf1 Kf8 16. Qxe6 Qe8 17. Bb5 Rc8 18. cxd4 Nxd4 19. Bxe8 Nxe6 20. Bd7 Rxc2 21. Bxe6) 12. Be3 { This is the type of position we want to achieve.
here white has a beautiful position
1. a strong center
2. both rooks have half-open files
3. both bishops are aiming at the kingside
4. the queen can slip over to g3, h3, or h5 anytime
5. the knight can join the attack anytime with either Nf4 or Ng3
With perfect play this is probably still a draw, but in a game between humans, I don't see black surviving this.
The next few moves will be an example of how white can brutally punish a natural looking move, which is a blunder. } { [%csl Yf8,Gb1,Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Ge2][%cal Yf1f8,Rd3h7,Re3h6,Bf3h3,Bf3h5,Gb1b8,Gc3d4,Gd4e5] } 12... Bg5?? { black wants to exchange pieces, because you can't attack without any pieces! } (12... cxd4 13. cxd4 { we want to keep our pieces on the board! }) 13. Bxh7+!! { a brutal punch! most of our pieces are on the kingside, so we just have to open up black's kingside to expose the poor black king. } 13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+! { [%csl Gh7,Gg5][%cal Gh5h7,Ge3g5,Gh5g5] } 14... Bh6 (14... Kg8 15. Bxg5 f6 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Qg6+ Kh8 18. Bxf6+ { [%csl Gg8,Gg7,Gh7][%cal Gg6g8,Gg6h7] } 18... Rxf6 19. Rxf6 Qd7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Qg5+ Qg7 22. Rg6 Qxg6 23. Qxg6+ Kf8 24. Qxe6 $18) 15. Bxh6 gxh6 16. Rf6! { attacking h6 and closing down all black's pieces! } 16... Rh8 17. Rxf7+! Bxf7 18. Qxf7# { checkmate! the game: https://lichess.org/eoPeqa0Y in the game white didn't find Rxf7! and played Nf4?? but robc2021 went on to crush his FM opponent anyway in just a few moves. } { [%csl Gh7,Gg8,Gg6,Yh6,Rh8][%cal Gf7h7,Gf7g8,Gf7g6] } *


