1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 Nc6? { A mistake because we can kick these 2 knights after fxe5. This variation is known as the Two Knights Defense Variation, or the Trash Variation :D } 4. fxe5 Nxe5 5. d4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd4e5] } 5... Ng6 (5... Neg4?? { a blunder because the f6 knight is the only piece protecting it. all we have to do is force it away } 6. e5! { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2 d6 8. exf6 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Nxf6 $18 { white enjoys the extra piece }) (5... Nc6 6. e5 Ng8 7. Nf3 $16 { white has a +2.1 advantage! } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gc3,Gf3,Bb5,Bc4,Bd3,Be2,Bg5,Bf4,Be3,Bd2][%cal Gd4e5,Bf1b5,Bc1g5] }) 6. e5 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] } 6... Ng8 (6... Qe7? 7. Qe2 Ng8 8. Nf3! d6 9. Nd5 Qd7 10. Nxc7+ Qxc7 11. exd6+ Be7 12. dxc7 { same thing as we saw in chapter 3 }) 7. Nf3 $16 { white has a nice center, 2 nice horsies, an open f file, and very easy development. Black for the past few moves has just been horsing around :) } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf3,Gc3,Bg5,Bf4,Be3,Bb5,Bc4,Bd3,Bg1,Ra8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rg6,Rd7,Rc7][%cal Gd4e5,Bc1g5,Bf1b5,Be1g1] } *


