1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d6 { black tries to stay solid. White just has to develop normally now. } 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Bc4!? { not Mr. Fish's favorite move, but it's a bit more tricky. } 5... Nc6 6. O-O Nd4 7. fxe5 { there is only 1 good move here for black, which is Bxf3, but it is only played 12% of the time :) } 7... dxe5? (7... Nxf3+? 8. gxf3 { black can't save the horse and the bishop at the same time! } { [%csl Gf6,Gg4][%cal Ge5f6,Gf3g4] }) (7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 dxe5 9. d3 Bc5 10. Na4 Nxc2+? (10... Be7 11. f4 b5 12. fxe5 bxc4 13. exf6 $10) 11. Nxc5 Qd4+ 12. Rf2 Nxa1 13. b4 a5 14. Bb2 Qe3 15. Qd2 { forcing a queen trade, the knight will get trapped. } 15... Qxd2 16. Rxd2 axb4 17. Bxa1 $13 { still unclear, stockfish gives white a +4.3 advantage though. } { [%csl Rb4,Re5,Rc7,Rb7,Gc4,Ga1] }) 8. Bxf7+! Kxf7 (8... Ke7 9. Bc4 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 Bh3 11. Rf2 Qd4 12. Bf1 $16 { white is better (Stockfish gives white a +2.2 advantage) Bf1 avoids any attacks. }) 9. Nxe5+ Kg8 10. Nxg4 Nxg4 11. Qxg4 $16 { white is up two pawns! after Nxc2 (which is the most popular move), Qe6# is mate in 1 :) } *


