1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 exf4 4. e5 Ng8 5. Nf3 d6 { my recommendation is to play d4 (covered in chapter 4) but, I came across this line that is pretty interesting } 6. Qe2! { d4 and Qe2 are equally good! } 6... dxe5 7. Qxe5+ Qe7 8. d4 Qxe5+ 9. Nxe5 f6 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] } 10. Nf3 g5 11. h4 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gh4g5] } 11... g4 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gg4f3] } 12. Bxf4!! { Lc0's recommendation! all other moves will just make the position be easier to play as black. The point of this move is that after black takes the knight, we play Nd5 and there is no way for black to save the rook.
NOTE: this is still equal though, but in my opinion it is so much easier to play as White, and Black can mess up very easily. } 12... gxf3 13. Nd5! { There is no way to stop white from winning the rook } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gd5c7] } 13... Na6 (13... Bd6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Nc7+ Kd7 16. Nxa8 $16 { stockfish gives white a +1.4 advantage. saving the knight is going to be a challenge, but also it will take black some time to attack it. }) (13... fxg2? 14. Nxc7+ Kd8 15. Bxg2 Bh6 16. Bh2 Ne7 17. Nxa8 $16 Na6 18. O-O) 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Nxc7+ Kd7 16. Nxa8 fxg2 17. Rg1 Ne7 18. Nc7 $10 *


