{ Hello! welcome to this study. This study will be about traps in the Alekhine Defense, they will be for white and black. Let's start! }
1. e4 Nf6 { This is the Alekhine Defense } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6e4] } 2. e5 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] } 2... Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 d6 { in this position white can develop very easily. } { [%csl Gc4,Gf3,Gf4,Gb3][%cal Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Gc1f4,Gd1b3] } 7. Bg5 { the bishop pins the e6 pawn } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gg5d8,Re7e6] } 7... dxe5?! (7... dxc5? 8. Qb3 Nc6 (8... h6 { [%cal Gc4f7] } 9. Bc4 { [%csl Gf7] } 9... Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6 hxg5 12. Qg6+ Kd7 13. O-O-O+ Kc8 14. Rxd8+ Kxd8 { [%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rf8,Bd1][%cal Bh1d1,Bg1f3,Be5e6] }) 9. Rd1 Bd7 10. e6 { the engine give white a +3.7 advantage }) 8. Qb3 { white has two threats, bringing the rook to d1 and Bc4.
The only move that survives for black is Queen d7. White already has a 76% winrate. } { [%csl Gd1,Gf7][%cal Ga1d1,Gf1c4,Gc4f7] } 8... Nc6?? (8... a6 9. Rd1 { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gd1d8] } 9... Nd7 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } (9... Bd7 { [%cal Gc4f7] } 10. Bc4 { [%csl Gf7] } 10... Qc8 11. Bxf7+ Kd8) 10. Bc4 { white cannot stop checkmate unless he sacrifices the queen } 10... e6 11. Bxd8) (8... f6 9. Rd1 Nd7 10. Qe6 fxg5 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } 11. Bc4 e4 12. Qf7#) (8... c6 9. Bc4 Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxb7 Nd7 12. O-O-O) 9. Bc4 { [%csl Gf7,Gc4,Gb3,Gd8,Re6][%cal Gc4f7,Gb3f7,Re7e6,Gg5d8] } 9... Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxb7 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gb7c6] } 11... Na5 12. Qa6 c6 13. b4 { white has an +7.8 advantage } { [%csl Ga5,Re7,Re6,Re5,Rf8,Re8][%cal Gb4a5] } *


