1. d4 { Hello, welcome to this study! I haven't made a study for a while, so I decided to make one. This study will be about traps (for black and white) in the Kings Indian Defense, also known as the KID. Lets get started! } 1... Nf6 { first we will be looking at traps for black (go to chapter 5 for traps for white) } 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 { [%csl Gd1,Gf3][%cal Gg4d1] } 7. h3 { white wants to get rid of this bishop, because it is pinning the knight. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rh3g4] } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 (8. gxf3 { [%csl Rf3,Rf2] }) 8... Nc6 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4] } 9. Be3 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ge3d4] } 9... Nd7 { double attack, white has to do something to save his pawn. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7d4,Gc6d4] } 10. Ne2?? { white wanted to protect his pawn but now black can do a very nice move... } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ge2d4,Ge3d4] } (10. d5 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nce5 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Ge5f3] } 12. Qe2 Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Re8) 10... Nde5! { amazing! black temporary sacrifices his knight, but he will win it back later } { [%csl Gf3,Gd3][%cal Ge5f3,Ge5d3] } 11. dxe5 Nxe5 { [%csl Gd3,Gf3][%cal Ge5d3,Ge5f3] } 12. Qg3 Nxd3+ { black has a -4.0 advantage, black is about to be two pawns up, white has lost his castling privileges and white's queen is not on a good square. } { [%csl Gg8,Gb2,Re1,Rg3][%cal Gg7b2,Gd3b2] } *


