1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 { here white goes for a aggressive setup. this is called the four pawns attack } { [%csl Rf4,Re4,Rd4,Rc4] } 5... O-O 6. Nf3 Na6 7. Be2 e5 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. d5 (9. dxe5? { notice: white cannot take the pawn here, because black will end up with a better position. } 9... Qxd1+ 10. Bxd1 Nd7 { [%csl Ga6,Ge5,Rd1,Rc1,Gg8,Re4][%cal Gd7e5,Gg7e5,Gf8e8,Ge8e5,Ba6c5] }) 9... Nc5 10. Qc2? { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4] } 10... Nfxe4! 11. Nxe4 Bf5 { [%csl Gc2,Ge4][%cal Gf5c2] } 12. Nfd2? (12. Bd3 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 f5 14. Bd3 Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 e4 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Ge4d3,Ge4f3] } 16. Qb3 exf3 17. gxf3 Re8+ 18. Kd1 { [%csl Gg8][%cal Ge8e1,Bc7c6,Bd8d6,Ba8d8] }) 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qh4+ { [%cal Gh4e1,Gh4e4] } 14. g3 Bxe4 15. gxh4 Bxc2 $18 { black is a pawn up, and white has a terrible position. black has a -3.1 advantage. } { [%csl Re1,Re2,Rh4,Gg8,Ge5][%cal Bf8e8,Ba8d8,Bf7f5] } *


